<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS CRUSH METS, 9-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The game was about 10 minutes old and Orel Hershiser
could already hear boos floating around Shea Stadium on Monday
night. Four of the first five Dodgers reached base against him, two
scored and the fans who wanted to see the Mets remain in first
place for another night were agitated. Obviously, they were a bit
antsy, too.
</P>
<P>
   These fickle fans refused to give Hershiser or the Mets a free
pass, not even for one inning. So they booed in the first, they
booed again in the third and they waited to see if Hershiser would
relax or if the Mets would respond against Kevin Brown. Forget it
on both questions. Perhaps the fans were prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets wound up succumbing to a dominant Brown and the
Dodgers, 9-2, on what was a seriously forgettable night. Why? Let
the Mets list the reasons. They sputtered to their third straight
loss, they dropped out of first place in the National League East
by a half-game behind the Atlanta Braves and they slipped to a
half-game edge over the Cincinnati Reds for the wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the end of a long, great streak,'' Hershiser said after
the Mets lost three straight for the first time since their
infamous eight-game losing streak two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Mets uncorked a streak of 40 victories in 55
games through Friday, the run did not build a hefty cushion in the
division. So there is cause for concern whenever the Mets lose
three straight, especially to a team that has been as disappointing
and deplorable as the Dodgers have this season.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, when Brown is pumping his hard sinker and barreling
through any tight spots, the Dodgers become quite respectable. That
happened on Monday night as Hershiser dumped the Mets in a hole
with five ineffective innings and then Brown and the Mets' bullpen
kept piling on more dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets essentially had two opportunities to score against
Brown, and the $105 million man stifled them both times. Rey
Ordonez reached on an error in the third inning and made it to
third with two outs, but Edgardo Alfonzo grounded out. John Olerud
began the fourth with a single and Robin Ventura ripped a one-out
single, but Brown retired the next two batters on groundouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets did not manage another base runner off Brown, who
allowed no runs and two hits in seven innings while striking out
three and walking one. As Brown warmed up for the eighth, he tossed
a fastball that soared about 10 feet over catcher Todd Hundley's
head, looked down at his hand and then left because of a blister.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Borbon replaced Brown and Ordonez singled and Shawon
Dunston doubled, giving the Mets as many hits in two at-bats off
Borbon as they had mustered in 25 against Brown. Alfonzo's
sacrifice fly scored the Mets' first run. The second scored on
Dunston's single in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was so inconsistent in the first inning that Dan
Murray, the rookie who was called up from ClassAAA Norfolk to
replace the injured Rick Reed on the roster on Monday, was warming
up and poised to make his major league debut. Mark Grudzielanek
singled, Jose Vizcaino walked and Eric Karros and Devon White
stroked one-out run-scoring singles to put the Dodgers ahead, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser kept himself in the game by getting Adrian Beltre on a
pop-up with the bases loaded to end what could have been an awful
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was apparent that Hershiser was not sharp against his
former team. Singles by Gary Sheffield and White and Hershiser's
third walk of the game to Raul Mondesi loaded the bases in the
third. Hundley smacked a grounder to first base that glanced off
Olerud's glove as he stretched to his right. While Olerud recovered
to nab an out at first, Sheffield eased in with the third run.
After intentionally walking Beltre, Hershiser ended his second of
three innings with the bases loaded by retiring Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser gave up three runs on six hits and four walks, but the
score was only 3-0 when he left. The bullpen did the rest of the
damage. Billy Taylor made his first appearance since botching his
first save opportunity on Saturday and admitting that he was
nervous. Taylor faced four batters and was bruised for Beltre's
double and Grudzielanek's triple, leaving the mound to boos for the
second time in three days.
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell replaced Taylor and allowed a two-run double to
Karros that increased the Dodgers' bulge to 6-0, and then Murray
was blitzed for three more runs in a dreary debut. So the game that
started with boos ended in a loss for the Mets, on the field and in
the standing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
