<SLUG> BC-Jesse-Attention-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN A SUBDUED VENTURA GRABS ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ To understand Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, it
helps to remember the life of a professional wrestler. One day,
you're defending justice. The next, you're blindsiding someone with
a folding chair.
</P>
<P>
   Roles change in a heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   This week in St. Louis, Ventura continues to show how
effortlessly he alternates between the larger-than-life style of
wrestler and the reserved style of chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura is the big name at the National Governors' Association
meeting, which ends today. But he has managed to keep a remarkably
low profile.
</P>
<P>
   He ambled into meetings quietly, wearing a crisp suit and
occasionally donning glasses to scan policy documents.
</P>
<P>
   From Ventura's subdued manner, it's hard to believe that he will
be the guest referee Aug. 22 at a wrestling free-for-all called
``SummerSlam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People still get a chuckle out of him, but he wants to be
taken seriously by other governors and his colleagues,'' said David
Erickson, co-publisher of MN-Politics.com, an Internet political
magazine. ``With Ventura, you have to separate his public persona
from his governorship.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from Ventura's first governors' meeting, where
his colleagues' staffers hounded him for autographs and he wore a
buckskin coat while booming bombastic to the Washington media.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, Ventura makes an impression.
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday's plenary session, heads turned as Ventura asked
loudly (for him, a whisper) where he was supposed to sit.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura took his spot next to Gov. Bill Graves of Kansas, whose
eyeglasses made him look even more bookish than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Before the governors could begin their discussion on education,
a couple of preteens shyly asked Ventura for a photo, bypassing
other governors who hadn't starred with Arnold Schwarzenegger or
been depicted as action figures.
</P>
<P>
   In one touching moment, Ventura presented a posthumous award
from the governors' association to Samuel Costa, who ran a dance
company in the Twin Cities. Ventura warmly smiled at Costa's
fiancee, whispering words of encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   When Ventura went to shake hands with Costa's family in the
crowd, a loved one with tears in his eyes clutched Ventura's
forearm for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   From that meeting, Ventura attended a session with the
governors' Natural Resources Committee. He listened intently as
commerce officials discussed the salmon population in Canadian
rivers and other arcane topics.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota officials have praised Ventura's willingness to
educate himself about state government and the issues. He soberly
read his State of the State address with no scowls or one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   But Graves couldn't help laughing when asked about Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse is...he is an interesting person. I like Jesse,'' Graves
said. ``Like a lot of new governors, he spends a lot of time
sitting quietly, listening and absorbing the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He obviously still has a lot of professional wrestler in him,
especially when he's making a point,'' Graves added. ``But whatever
his past, be it wrestling, acting, or as a Navy SEAL, he has a huge
responsibility like all of us. And he appears to be taking his job
very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say Ventura is turning Minnesota into a mockery
with his outlandish appearances on the late-night talk shows and
his embarrassingly frank autobiography, I Ain't Got Time to Bleed.
</P>
<P>
   Even skeptical constituents acknowledge that Ventura has emerged
as a credible political spokesman and leader of the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here has been waiting for him to put his foot in his
mouth once again,'' said Steven Smith, a political science
professor at the University of Minnesota. ``But he's been
reasonably careful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Minnesotans are pleasantly surprised at how he's handled
himself on national television and at various national events. He's
tried to leave the wrestler at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Ventura can't help but attract attention.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton lingered with Ventura as he worked the room
after a midday speech Sunday. Eavesdroppers said the two chatted
about wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Before the day was over, a photo of the two political
personalities had been posted on newspaper Internet sites across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   When the governors visited a St. Louis elementary school, the
local newspaper chose to illustrate the story with a photo of
Ventura mischievously displaying a drawing he made.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's events at the governors' conference featured a meeting
with an information technology task force and a barbecue at Grant's
Farm.
</P>
<P>
   But Ventura planned to skip the barbecue for more pressing
business.
</P>
<P>
   He was scheduled to appear in Chicago on the wrestling program
``Raw'' to hype his referee gig later this month.
</P>
<P>
   As the World Wrestling Federation's Web site breathlessly
proclaimed: ``Jesse promised to lay down the law regarding the
Stone Cold vs. Triple H main event and the question is: Will he
start tonight?''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the responsibilities of a governor never end.
</P>
<P>
   Especially this governor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
