<HEADER>
A1438 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTILITIES-DEREGULATIO     08-10 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITIES-DEREGULATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT WAVE LEAVES SOME QUESTIONING DEREGULATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Leon Daggett could hardly believe what he was
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The general manager of the Board of Public Utilities knew he
would be spending some serious money. It was going to be a hot July
day, and the utility would have to buy wholesale electricity to
replace power from a BPU power plant that was out of commission.
</P>
<P>
   On the telephone was one of Daggett's employees telling him the
price would be $2,000 a megawatt _ nearly 200 times more than if
the BPU plant had generated it. The total bill would be $1.4
million for the day.
</P>
<P>
   It was an astounding figure and one Daggett wished he could
reject. But there was really no choice. He envisioned an elderly
person in some steamy apartment without electricity to run an air
conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough decision and it was an easy decision,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The heat wave is over, and prices for wholesale electricity that
spiked as high as $9,500 a megawatt have dropped back to double
digits. Utilities largely have returned to normal operations.
</P>
<P>
   But emotions still run strong, with some taking the experience
of those hot days as further proof of the pitfalls of deregulation.
There are even a few calls to put price caps back on wholesale
prices, though a reversal of their mid-1990s deregulation is
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   As expensive as they were for some utilities, the July price
spikes and some higher wholesale prices in spring 1998 have already
begun to do their job by sparking the construction of more power
plants. More supply will mean more stable prices, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that despite setting records for electricity
use in late July, the demand for power in the region was met. But
it was close, and many utilities had to issue calls for
conservation.
</P>
<P>
   The persistent heat wave tightened supplies more than expected.
The loss of a big plant or two could have produced a real crisis.
</P>
<P>
   That point was brought home last week when the Wolf Creek
nuclear plant had to shut down because of the failure of a water
valve. Fortunately, the weather was cooler by then, and the plant
was back up in a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system held together, but it was a lot closer than a lot
of us would have thought,'' said Larry Holloway, chief of energy
operations for the Kansas Corporation Commission, which still
regulates retail prices paid by utility customers.
</P>
<P>
   Left behind were some big bills, however. Kansas City Power &AMP;
Light Co. spent an extra $18 million for wholesale power to help
fill the gap caused by the loss of its Hawthorn 5 plant earlier
this year in a explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say it was an economist's dream,'' said Bernie
Beaudoin, president of KCP&AMP;L, which doesn't expect to recover the
money from customers.
</P>
<P>
   With Hawthorn 5, KCP&AMP;L could have profited from wholesale power
sales. Many utilities did this year, including Western Resources
Inc., which had all its plants running and power to spare.
Marketers of power, such as UtiliCorp United subsidiary Aquila
Energy, also are expected to do well financially.
</P>
<P>
   Making the wholesale markets an economist's dream _ or something
approaching that _ has been the goal since the mid-1990s when
federal officials took price controls off wholesale electricity.
The idea was that free markets could do a better job of ensuring
ample supplies of power.
</P>
<P>
   If additional supplies were needed, the wholesale market would
signal the need through higher prices. That would encourage the
construction of more generators.
</P>
<P>
   But the change can be jarring. Some utilities said that last
year when wholesale prices spiked they sold electricity to other
utilities at below market rates. This year, when they had to buy
electricity, the favor wasn't returned, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Miller, a senior manager for Sunflower Electric Power
Corp., which supplies electricity to cooperatives in western
Kansas, said the shift in tone is undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like who can cheat who the most,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such strong words are sparked in part by how important wholesale
electricity has become for the utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale electricity, which basically comes from the surplus
utilities can make available, can be bought directly from a
utility, through brokers or middlemen, and from exchanges that sell
electricity offered by several utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale power also can be bought through long-term contracts,
but quick purchases of the sort needed last month can be made for a
day or even by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   Buying the power is only part of the job. It also has to be
delivered, which can be tricky especially when it's coming from
several states away. The job requires a deft touch, because
transmission lines can become overloaded.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Energy Information Administration says that at least
on paper there appears to be enough capacity to meet demand. But
there have been some close calls, including the heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   And suspicions of manipulation persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a greed factor going on,'' said Keith Querry, business
manager of Local 53 of the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers, which represents some workers at BPU and Independence
Power &AMP; Light.
</P>
<P>
   So what to do? Americans can expect to see more peddling of
products such as one offered by Aquila Energy to hedge electricity
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Sunflower Electric Power in Hays, Kan., took out what is thought
to be one of the first insurance policies in the country to help
pay for wholesale power in case one of its plants was disabled.
</P>
<P>
   There also may be more calls for allowing electric utilities to
automatically pass on to customers those prices for higher electric
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Americans can expect to see more power plants. Dave Penn, deputy
director of the American Public Power Association, which represents
city-owned utilities, said in the end more capacity will come.
</P>
<P>
   But as America goes toward even more deregulation in utilities,
he offers this cautionary note.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something happens to your electricity, you don't call the
stock exchange,'' Penn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
