</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-COWBOYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWNS TOP COWBOYS, 20-17, IN HALL OF FAME GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ The Browns' return to football was more of a
celebration than a game. It featured the glare and spectacle of
``Monday Night Football.'' Loud fighter jets flew overhead before
the game. Fireworks exploded at halftime. Dancers danced and shook
big, colorful stars. Each of the five Hall of Fame inductees from
the Class of 1999 attended, and so did a record crowd of 25,156 at
Fawcett Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But there was football to be played. And the Browns decided they
would cap the evening in style.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland did, winning by 20-17 over the Dallas Cowboys in the
annual Hall of Fame preseason game on Phil Dawson's 20-yard field
goal at 6 minutes 54 seconds of overtime. Cleveland had made it
17-17 on Dawson's 23-yard field goal with 5:49 left in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The first half featured 31 points scored and the debut of Tim
Couch, the Browns' heralded rookie quarterback, the No. 1 overall
pick of the draft. He tossed his first pro touchdown pass, albeit
preseason, on a 24-yard strike to the rookie receiver Kevin Johnson
from Syracuse. (Johnson was the Browns' second-round draft pick
last April.)
</P>
<P>
   Couch was prepared and poised in his debut, passing for 88 yards
in the first half and completing 9 of 10 attempts. He finished 11
of 17 for 137 yards with no interceptions and with a long pass of
31 yards. Ty Detmer was the starter.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas started shakily.
</P>
<P>
   It fumbled a snap in its first possession, allowed a touchdown
on Cleveland's first possession, committed a holding penalty on the
ensuing kickoff and then quickly punted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like to see that many penalties in any game, so that
was something I wasn't pleased with,'' said Chan Gailey, the Dallas
head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Dallas began to mesh.
</P>
<P>
   It scored the final points of the half on a 49-yard field goal
with only 3 seconds remaining. Before that, the Cowboys caught the
Browns on the backup Jason Garrett's touchdown passes of 35 and 24
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas looked quick against the run, hesitant against the pass,
adequate running the ball and solid passing it. Cleveland looked
stout against the run, shaky defending the pass, adequate running
the ball and promising passing it.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the Browns fans inside the stadium and the hundreds
of others outside who came without tickets, the Browns could do no
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Doc Wingerter, along with his brother, Jamie, were among the
fortunate to gain entry. Not so, though, for the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, I had season tickets to the Browns for their
last seven years,'' Wingerter said. ``I was there when they played
their last game in `95, against the Bengals, I think. I don't quite
remember, because I got drunk that day at the game so I could try
to forget the Browns were leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hungry for football here. It's always been a blue-collar
town that's loved its football all the way back to the great
Steelers-Browns games. And it's great the Browns are coming out of
the chute in the regular season against the Steelers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Wingerter said: ``I'd like to see them win their division
and make the playoffs this year. That might not be realistic. I'd
take them winning half their games.''
</P>
<P>
   One man who stood proudly while watching the Browns' return was
Hanford Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon played cornerback for the Browns from 1981 through 1989.
He still lives in Cleveland and watched the Browns come and go. The
old Browns were known for their Dawg Pound _ their tough stadium
and lively crew of fans _ and it was Dixon who started the name.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played, we didn't have a great defensive line,'' Dixon
said. ``We had a strong secondary, though. I started thinking of
something to get the defensive line going. I thought of a dog
chasing a cat. I told the linemen to think of chasing the
quarterback that way. I started barking at them and they barked
back. And then the fans got into it and the whole thing took off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's phenomenal, a great feeling to see the team back now and
to see that new stadium they have. When I played in old Cleveland
Stadium, the facilities were so bad, especially in the visiting
locker room, that I was embarrassed to go over and visit friends
from other teams. They have a state-of-the-art facility now.
Everyone is proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman said, ``It's good to see the Dawg
Pound back in the NFL.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
