<HEADER>
A1444 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-CARDS-2TAKES     08-10 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-CARDS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLUT, GIMMICKRY HIT BASEBALL-CARD INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Baseball cards _ once the province of kids with
shoe-box collections _ have lost their gloss and appeal more today
to future investment bankers than future big leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   That's the word from many industry analysts and Southern
California dealers who say overproduction, an investment mentality
and greed are threatening a hobby that exploded into a
billion-dollar industry in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball cards have become pricier and more high-tech. Companies
now market over 50 varieties of cards a year, and many use gimmicks
such as pieces of jerseys and bats _ even sprinkles of ballfield
dirt _ to drum up interest.
</P>
<P>
   Still, overall sales have plummeted. Total sports card sales hit
$1.2billion in 1991, when baseball had the lion's share of the
collectible cards market; in 1998, total sales were less than half
that.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's home-run race revived interest in the industry, but
while cards for top stars such as Ken Griffey Jr., Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa have gained in value since the lockout, dealers and
analysts say the market remains deeply troubled.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Chesler, owner of Perfect Game in Santa Clarita, north of
Los Angeles, said the aggressive product expansion that companies
had hoped would revive the industry has left dealers, and many
collectors, drowning in cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a ridiculous amount of cards,'' he said. ``This year
is especially bad.''
</P>
<P>
   And analysts say an emerging market called ``grading'' _ a
process that began as a counterfeiting countermeasure _ is now
pushing prices into unhealthy territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is certainly languishing,'' said Bob Lemke,
senior price guide analyst for Krause Publications Inc. in
Wisconsin. ``Major events like the home-run race last year, they
attract attention to those individuals, but they don't seem to have
done anything to pull the rest of the market with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry is no stranger to big swings.
</P>
<P>
   A wave of speculation drove the market into a frenzy in 1991,
with collectors buying box after box of cards on the assumption
that prices could head only one way: up.
</P>
<P>
   When speculation met reality, and thousands tried to dump their
cards onto a saturated market, the market plummeted. The labor
unrest in 1994 accelerated the decline, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   According to Scott Kelnhofer, editor of Card Trade Magazine, the
new sports card market generated about $400 million in retail sales
last year, about one-third of the 1991 peak.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball cards suffered disproportionately, Kelnhofer said,
dropping from about 90 percent of the overall market in 1990 to
roughly 40 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken Jr. started the baseball card recovery with his 1995
quest for the record for the most consecutive games played, and the
Sosa-McGwire home-run contest last year solidified the gains.
</P>
<P>
   But the recovery has been shallow, says Lemke.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the broad-based gains that dealers and collectors saw
in the 1980s, Lemke said players and manufacturers are
concentrating on star players' cards and rookie cards, ignoring the
rest of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Companies also have created a scarcity of certain cards by
releasing limited runs and, in some cases, creating just one card
of a particular kind. These rare, randomly inserted ``chase'' cards
are often far more valuable than the price of a pack of cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the only cards that seem to have good cash value are the
rare inserts, the most high-tech of the cards,'' Lemke said.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers say the emphasis on value has turned some young
collectors into young speculators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids you'd think would be buying them just because they
like the players (instead) buy them and rush to the price guide,''
said Alex Sawchak, manager of Porky's Baseball Cards and Stuff in
North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the kids saving up money for the premium packs
because they know they're worth more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``chase'' card phenomenon, which grew dramatically in the
mid-'90s, has even spurred lawsuits by older collectors and the
parents of younger collectors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most advanced cases, in U.S. District Court in San
Diego, accuses Carlsbad card manufacturer Upper Deck Co. of running
an illegal gambling enterprise that targets children.
</P>
<P>
   But some in the industry say the health of the actual sport of
baseball is more important than the marketing of its cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stronger the game of baseball is, the stronger the hobby
is,'' said Rich Klein, a baseball price guide analyst for
Dallas-based Beckett Publications.
</P>
<P>
   Some collectors agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think McGwire and Sosa last year, and Ken Griffey Jr.,
really brought a lot of people back into the market,'' said Brock
Coleman, a resident of suburban North Hills who has collected cards
for about 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman also has seen how the new market is driving up prices. A
Griffey Jr. card that he had considered putting on layaway earlier
this month already has increased from $150 to $200, Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
