<HEADER>
A1446 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-CARDS-2ndtak     08-10 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-CARDS-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: Coleman said. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the country's card manufacturers also have launched their
own efforts to revive the market.
</P>
<P>
   Besides inserts, companies have created lines of cards with
features such as glossy prints, die cutting, chrome finishing and
foil stamping. Each of the four licensed companies _ Fleer/SkyBox
International, Topps Co., Upper Deck and Pacific Trading Cards
Inc._ now has several product lines, ranging from the base line,
traditional cards to high-end, high-cost premium cards that can
cost upward of $6 a pack.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two months alone companies have released roughly 20
new baseball card products, Klein said. That's nearly twice as many
as were available all of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of cards has made it nearly impossible to collect full
sets, discouraging some traditional collectors.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents say flashier cards and a wider variety have
brought young people into the market and retained them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better now, because cards are nicer and there's more
variety,'' said Don Rollins, 16, a Santa Clarita collector.
``There's a bigger possibility that something's going to meet your
tastes.''
</P>
<P>
   Grading, a process in which a company grades a card's quality on
a scale of 1 to 10 or 1 to 100, also has taken off since the
lockout.
</P>
<P>
   The grading industry's largest firm, Newport-based Professional
Sports Authenticator, now processes more than 100,000 cards a
month. Last year it averaged 40,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The company charges as little as $8 and as much as $100,
depending on a card's value and expected turnaround time.
</P>
<P>
   By inserting a third-party analysis into card buying, grading
has paved the way for another growing trend in the industry:
Internet trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grading gives you a lot of comfort trading on the Internet,''
said Klein, the Beckett analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Grades also have led to a pricing boom for highly rated cards.
For example, a mint condition Griffey Jr. rookie card can sell for
several times more than its price guide value.
</P>
<P>
   Card collector Howard Stevens of suburban Van Nuys said dealers
have taken advantage of the system to exaggerate the scarcity of
cards and inflate prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about authenticity anymore,'' he said. ``It's
basically about greed.''
</P>
<P>
   Other skeptics such as Harry Rinker, a collectibles analyst and
head of the Rinker Enterprises research center, say the sports card
industry _ with grading, enforced scarcity and investment focus _
is creating a price bubble that eventually will burst.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the market maintains its recent price gains, he
said, it threatens the core of the hobby itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody trades anymore, except for cash,'' he said. ``When you
teach kids to look at these as investments, you destroy the joy of
owning them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
