<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WOES OF THE LONG ISLAND RAIL ROAD
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Aug. 10:
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island Rail Road operates the nation's largest suburban
commuter line in a complicated and unforgiving environment. Most of
its nine branches on Long Island converge on one station at
Jamaica, Queens. From there its trains must funnel into and out of
Manhattan through four tunnels, two of them shared with Amtrak, and
can linger only a few minutes at Amtrak's Penn Station before they
must pull out to make room for the next train. These conditions and
bottlenecks cause congestion that defies easy solution. But they
should not be used as an excuse to be lethargic about simpler
problems the LIRR can deal with to head off the growing
disenchantment of riders.
</P>
<P>
   The myriad problems of the LIRR were recently explored in The
Times by David Halbfinger. The most critical problem is a decrepit
fleet of coaches that was ordered more than three decades ago,
during the administration of Gov. Nelson Rockefeller. Most of these
cars have not received adequate overhauls or maintenance. The
result is a high frequency of breakdowns, far worse than on the
LIRR's sister agency, the Metro-North Railroad. These problems
should eventually be mitigated by the acquisition of new coaches,
but the first set of new equipment is not expected to arrive until
March 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile other aggravating problems, such as litter in coaches
and cars without functioning air-conditioning units, can surely be
eased by more aggressive management. There is no good reason that
it should take several days to discover air-conditioning systems
that are not working, and many more days to get around to fixing
them. Nor is the short turnaround time for trains at Penn Station
adequate excuse for failing to clean the cars elsewhere on their
routes. Even the frequency of breakdowns might be eased with
renewed emphasis on preventive maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki ought to bring pressure to bear on the LIRR,
and the railroad's president, Thomas Prendergast, ought to retrain
or replace his line managers when they fail to perform well. New
rolling stock, signals and track, dependent on adequately funded
capital programs, will take years to have an effect on congestion.
But progress on lesser problems is well within the power of
Prendergast and Pataki.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
