<SLUG> BC-TEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENSON VOLLEYS ON OR OFF THE TENNIS COURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Alexandra Stevenson was gaily
recounting her recent sit-down interview with Barbara Walters, the
high priestess of television confessionals.
</P>
<P>
   Being on the receiving end of Walters' questions is akin to
standing on the other side of the net from someone intent on
lobbing you into submission.
</P>
<P>
   Walters can inch the most accomplished, competent people into a
corner without breaking a sweat. She has worn down five-star
generals and Hollywood headliners and heads of state. Kleenex ought
to sponsor her one- and two-hour specials for all the tears shed by
her guests under the guise of intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson, who plays Anke Huber in a first-round match today at
the Acura Classic, hasn't been in celebrity's crosshairs long. No
matter. She had Walters' game down pat.
</P>
<P>
   So before the cameras started rolling, Stevenson fired a
preemptive volley. ``You always make everyone cry after 45
minutes,'' the 18-year-old told Walters as they settled into their
seats. ``Well, you're not going to make me cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Walters drew a lot of giggles out of Stevenson but
not one tear. The newly minted pro didn't get watery eyes when
Walters wondered if Stevenson missed having a dad to share in her
successes or wished to know her biological father, former NBA star
Julius Erving, at least a wee bit better than do his fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. No,'' Stevenson replied in a voice so breezy she could
have been rejecting a diet soda instead of a basic human instinct.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't every little girl try, however subconsciously, to put
the sparkle in her daddy's eye? There must be something to
father-daughter bonding or they wouldn't have invented baby
bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, the metaphysical formula is lost on Stevenson,
who reiterated Monday that she doesn't care if she never sees
Erving again. (He has supported her financially, but their only
meeting came when she was 8 and she joined a long line of fans
waiting for his autograph at a basketball camp.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't reached out to me in 18 years, so why should he
start now?'' Stevenson said.
</P>
<P>
   In the next breath, she complimented a television reporter on
her designer platform sandals.
</P>
<P>
   She might get caught flat-footed on the court more than she'd
like, but Stevenson moves nimbly in the interview room.
</P>
<P>
   Her easy maneuvering around such a piercingly personal matter as
her parentage, in her prime-time interview with Walters and again
on Monday with local reporters, is as impressive in one so young as
her velvety one-handed backhand.
</P>
<P>
   As with that stroke, which she developed under the watchful eye
of Dr. Pete Fischer, her volleys with the media have the polish
that can only come with hours of diligent practice.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear Craig Kardon is not her only coach. Stevenson's
mother Samantha has been a sportswriter for three decades. She has
schooled Alexandra well. Only a journalist's daughter would
volunteer the pearls that writers are constantly diving for.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson was speaking breathlessly about how her life has
changed since she became the first qualifier to advance to the
semifinals at Wimbledon _ and the first child of a sports icon to
be outed at at a Grand Slam event _ when she blurted out, unbidden,
that she had ``a funny story.''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen pens snapped to attention. Was Stevenson going to
divulge a chance meeting with Erving? Did she run into some
Hollywood hunk at the Viper Room? Inquiring minds couldn't wait to
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at a restaurant last night,'' Stevenson said, giggling,
``and this average Joe guy said, `I never watch women's tennis.
You've got me watching women's tennis. I'm coming to your match
(today) so you better play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson isn't naive. She knows her bloodlines are like Anna
Kournikova's beauty: a magnet for the fringe fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people recognize me because of the other subject,''
Stevenson said, alluding to Erving. ``But I wouldn't be here if it
wasn't about tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Stevenson handles the most intrusive questions like a
wily veteran, it's easy to forget she has been a pro for only three
months. Brandi Chastain probably has been wearing the same sports
bra for longer than that.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson deserves time and space to get comfortable in her new
life. Forget about being Julius Erving's daughter. Do you know how
hard it is to be a teen waiting for a dreamy boy to call?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the cell phone happens to ring,'' Stevenson said midway
through her session with the media, ``I have to answer it.''
</P>
<P>
   She was hoping to hear from Collin Smith, a beach volleyball
player she met earlier this month at the Pan American Games in
Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
   When she talked about him, her face lit up.You should know,
Stevenson considers him to be THE discovery of her summer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
