<SLUG> BC-ACTOR-VALLEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTOR'S TV PRODUCTION COMPANY MOVES TO SAN FERNANDO VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The actor best known for portraying mailman Cliff
Clavin on ``Cheers'' has joined the growing parade of Hollywood
players setting up shop in a converted shampoo factory in the west
San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   John Ratzenberger has moved his Fiddlers Bay Entertainment Co.
into Ray-Art Studios, the 2-year-old enterprise owned by veteran
producers Robert Papazian and James Hirsch.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old actor said the move made sense because his
company is developing with Ray-Art a pair of TV series _ ``Fine
Food and Diesel'' and ``V-Cops'' _ and ``Mr. Christmas,'' a
made-for-TV film.
</P>
<P>
   Ratzenberger, who was on ``Cheers'' for all 11 of its seasons,
previously operated his production company in the Chatsworth area.
</P>
<P>
   Ray-Art operates four soundstages with 83,000 square feet and
eight offices in a two-story building on Variel Avenue. It plans to
build two or three more soundstages by next June despite a slowdown
in off-studio production because studios are spending less and
moving some productions to lower-cost Canadian locales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get plenty of inquiries, so we believe there's going to be
demand for new space,'' said manager Sean Papazian. ``People are
always going to want to shoot in Los Angeles with what we offer _ a
fair price and friendly atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ray-Art building originally was owned by Boeing Co., then
sold to Redken Shampoo, which left in 1995. Developer Robert Selan
opened a baseball training academy, then renamed it Variel Studios
and struck lease deals with several producers before selling to
Papazian and Hirsch in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ray-Art is home to Aaron Spelling's sitcom ``Charmed.'' Previous
tenants have included ``Wag the Dog,'' ``Blade'' and sitcoms
``Nothing Sacred,'' ``413 Hope Street'' and ``The New Love Boat.''
Additionally, the studio wrapped production earlier this summer on
``The Storytellers,'' a feature film it co-produced with Da'Lin
Films.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
