<HEADER>
A1468 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLAIR-WITCH-PROFILE-A     08-10 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLAIR-WITCH-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL WILLIAMS TAKE HIS NEW-FOUND FAME IN STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Williams didn't know he was auditioning for a
horror film when he went to the first casting call for ``The Blair
Witch Project,'' this summer's phenomenon, but he did notice that
it was paid work _ $1,000 for being scared to tears, literally, in
a creepy stretch of the Maryland woods.
</P>
<P>
   He was just glad to have the money because there were moments
when he didn't have the $3 round-trip subway fare for another
audition. Even when the film opened in mid-July, Williams was still
making his real living moving furniture.
</P>
<P>
   So never did he imagine that the $35,000 film by two unknown
directors with three unknown actors would earn $80 million, be No.
2 at the box office and land on this week's covers of Time and
Newsweek. Fortunately for Williams, his contract calls for him to
get a small percentage of the net earnings, but, in the manner of
his on-screen character, he is remarkably relaxed about when, and
how much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're going to take care of me, and even if they
don't, I don't care,'' he said last week in his Westchester County,
N.Y., home as happily as if he had won the lottery, which for an
actor he has. ``Because you know what? I'm going to be on Jay Leno
in two weeks!''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 26, plays Mike Williams _ all three actors used their
own names _ the scaredy-cat sound man who disappears in the woods
with two other student film makers while making a documentary on
the legend of the Blair Witch. Heather Donahue, who plays the
student director, acts obsessive and obnoxious, while Joshua
Leonard, the student cameraman, is the brooder who hates Heather.
(It's not hard.) Mike, initially the film's whimpering lump,
emerges as the level-headed peacemaker, the character who often
says what the audience is thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted them to be one step removed from the characters
themselves,'' said Daniel Myrick, one of the two ``Blair Witch''
directors, who auditioned 2,000 actors for the parts. ``Mike was a
good fit for `Everyday Man' that we needed in that role.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week at his childhood home in Westchester County, Everyday
Man sat on his mother's back porch and talked about how scared he
himself became while making the movie. (He asked that his
Westchester town not be identified because some of the film's most
fanatic fans are _ How shall one put it? _ unusual.) Like the other
actors, Williams worked not from a script _ there wasn't one _ but
by improvisation and his wits.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, the directors left the three actors for six
days in a two-and-a-half-square-mile area of a Maryland state park.
The actors had with them camping gear and two cameras that they
used to film themselves, like the documentary makers they were
supposed to be. Each day in a milk crate, the directors left food,
fresh camera batteries and directions for each of the actors,
outlining in the most general terms how the characters should
develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd open it up and it would say: `OK, this is getting out of
hand. You've been hiking for two days, you haven't found the car
yet, does Heather honestly know where she's going?''' Williams
said. Or, for the climactic scene: ``Tonight you will hear Josh's
voice. Get out of the tent and follow it.''
</P>
<P>
   The directors, meanwhile, were lurking out of sight in the
woods, making noises in the middle of the night to scare the three
in their tent. ``Some nights you'd wake up and say, `I know it's
them out there, so I'm just going to lie here a little longer and
let them run around while I muster up some fear,''' Williams said.
But by the climactic scene, when Williams followed directions to
reach an abandoned house in the woods, his fear was real.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know we were coming upon it,'' he said. ``So that
was pretty horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of that scene, after six cold, stressful and hungry
days in the woods (the directors decreased the food allocation each
day, to make the actors as desperate as their characters), Williams
collapsed in tears, he said. ``It all just sort of came flying out
of me,'' he said. It was also, as it happened, Halloween night.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we came out of that emotional wreckness and went to Denny's
and there were all these people dressed up in Halloween costumes
looking like freaks walking on earth,'' Williams said. ``It was the
first sign of civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the eighth of nine children _ his late father was an
Exxon executive and his mother stayed home and ran the show _
played Henry Higgins in ``My Fair Lady'' in high school, graduated
in 1996 from the State University of New York at New Paltz, moved
to Queens to be closer to potential acting work and worked as an
ice-cream scooper in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Now he spends his time being interviewed, posing in trees (to go
with the woodland theme of the movie), meeting with more casting
directors than he ever dreamed of and being recognized on the
street. Not long ago he was sitting on a curb in Santa Monica,
Calif., reading a script before an audition, when a guy walked by
and said, ``Blair Witch, Dude!''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I say, `Yeah,' Williams said. ``And he says, ``Awesome!
Awesome!''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is to be married next month to Toni Batiste, a former
account executive for a Westchester shopper publication, and will
soon move to Santa Monica. So far he has no offers, but last week
he did quit his job as a furniture mover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
