<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLANDSWORTH IN IDLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Todd Hollandsworth's agent, Jeff Moorad, said last
winter his client wanted to be traded, but the Los Angeles Dodgers
didn't budge on the demand because they valued the outfielder's
versatility.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also said they would get Hollandsworth more at-bats
than usual for a backup, but that hasn't happened. It could lead
Hollandsworth down a familiar path when this season expires.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson's grand plan to get Hollandsworth
350 to 400 at-bats won't materialize, and not because of injury.
The reality is that Johnson is finding it difficult to sit a
portion of his $21.5 million outfield in favor of Hollandsworth,
who makes $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can play every day, but I can only do what's being
asked of me to do,'' Hollandsworth said. ``In the offseason we'll
look at it. If the club wants me in their plans, we'll talk about
it. I'm not concerning myself with it now. You get to the offseason
and you worry about it then and see where this is going to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll talk to my family and talk to my agent and see where it
leads us to. We'll address the situation then.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth missed the equivalent of a month with injuries,
but he must average four at-bats over the remaining 50 games to get
to 350. Hollandsworth is hitting .311 in 148 at-bats and is on pace
for a 237 at-bat season.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth has also played six games at first base, but
steady Eric Karros is making $5.5 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Agonizing Adrian: Dodgers third baseman Adrian Beltre spent
most of the season flirting with .300, but his offensive production
has fallen off dramatically since the all-star break.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre is hitting .202 (18 for 89) with one homer and 12 RBI
since the break and is hitting .272 for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be more mentally than physically that he's whupped,''
hitting coach Rick Down said. ``It may be a little different
playing all these games here instead of Double-A and Triple-A. He's
thrown some at-bats away, but when the game gets deeper or on the
line, I'm confident in him. I'd be shocked if he doesn't hit .280
or .290.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Balks, walks and chalk: Lefty Carlos Perez, pitching at
Triple-A Albuquerque, allowed seven earned runs on nine hits in
five innings against Calgary. He walked one and struck out one. . .
. Eric Young went 1 for 3 for Single-A San Bernardino on Sunday and
Johnson said the plan is to activate the second baseman when the
club returns home Friday. ``Unless something happens, we'll see him
Friday,'' Johnson said. Young is set to play the next three days
with the Stampede. . . . Johnson said right-hander Mike Judd will
arrive in Montreal today in preparation for his season debut
against the Expos on Thursday. Judd is 8-7 with a 6.67 ERA at
Albuquerque. It'll be his third stint in three seasons with the
Dodgers. He pitched 22/3 scoreless innings in 1997 and had a 15.09
ERA in seven games last year. . . . Former Dodger Bobby Bonilla, on
the Mets' disabled list since July 3 with tendinitis in his left
knee, is scheduled to begin a rehab assignment Aug. 26 and will be
activated when rosters expand on Sept. 1, Mets general manager
Steve Phillips said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
