<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY LOOKS TO SELL ANGELS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ According to published reports, the Walt
Disney Co. is looking into selling the Anaheim Angels only three
years after purchasing the club from Gene Autry.
</P>
<P>
   Published reports say the club is losing too much money.
According to the New York Times, one baseball official suggested
Disney's decision is based on financial losses in baseball.
However, an executive with another major-league team told the
newspaper the move is linked to Disney's multimillion-dollar
settlement in the lawsuit filed by former studio chief Jeffrey
Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Angels spokesman Tim Mead had the following response to the
published reports: ``We're referring all comment to the unnamed
baseball sources . . . in the New York paper. We don't comment on
rumor and speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney purchased the Angels from Autry in 1996, paying 25
percent _ or about $30 million _ and taking over operation with the
agreement they would pay the remaining 75 percent upon Autry's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Autry died last October and Disney paid the balance.
</P>
<P>
   The team reportedly lost $11 million in 1994 and $12 million in
'95, the last two years Autry ran the club. Part of Disney's
takeover included paying $70 million of the approximate $110
million it cost to renovate the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels signed Mo Vaughn to a six-year, $80 million contract
last November, the biggest contract in club history and the
second-highest average annual salary ($13.3 million) in all of
baseball. The club's $52 million payroll this season ranks as the
13th highest among baseball's 30 teams.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the highest payroll in baseball this year is the
New York Yankees' $85 million. The Dodgers rank No. 2 at $79
million and the Montreal Expos have the smallest payroll at $17
million.
</P>
<P>
   __ Vaughn returns: Mo Vaughn will return to the lineup tonight
against the Indians after missing six games with a staph infection
in his right shin.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn hit in the batting cage for about 10 minutes, ran on a
treadmill and reported feeling no pain or swelling in the shin,
which developed the infection after he was hit by a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know what to think of it,'' Vaughn said of the
injury. ``I've never seen anything like it. I just fouled a ball
off my shin and it turned into this.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he initially felt pain in the shin, but when the
infection took hold, his entire body ached. He took antibiotics to
fight the infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad it's over and I can play again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he didn't know if he'd play first base or DH
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's game against the Indians is essentially meaningless
for the Angels. But for starting pitcher Chuck Finley, there are
things to consider:
</P>
<P>
   1) Finley is facing the Indians, the team that tried to trade
for him just before the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   2) The Indians' starter is Mark Langston, a former teammate of
Finley's and a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   3) Finley will be a free agent at the end of the season and
every start counts, especially considering his struggles earlier in
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, Finley says he's taking it as just another
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to continue what I'm doing,'' said Finley, who
threw seven scoreless innings in his last start, Thursday against
the Red Sox. ``I don't care who it's against or whoever's coming
in. It could be against Kansas City or Milwaukee, it doesn't
matter. I'm not going to read more into it that isn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Released: The Angels made it official Monday, releasing
pitcher and Notre Dame High alum Jack McDowell and replacing him on
the roster with right-handed pitcher Lou Pote. Pote made 23 starts
for Triple-A Edmonton, going 7-9 with a 4.50 ERA and three complete
games. He'll be placed in the bullpen for now but is expected to
start at some point.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell was 0-4 with a 8.50 ERA in four starts, but manager
Terry Collins said releasing a former Cy Young Award winner isn't
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never easy to do, especially with a guy like Jack
McDowell,'' Collins said. ``I've enjoyed having him on my team as
much as any player I've had. He's been a true professional.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Angels in the outfield: The Angels' starting outfield Monday
was Garret Anderson in left, Jim Edmonds in center and Tim Salmon
in right. (Darin Erstad played first base.) It marked the first
time the Angels started that outfield all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the best outfields in the American League for
three straight years,'' said Collins. ``. . . In spring training,
we were asked over and over how we were going to handle having four
outfielders and we said we may need all four. Then we come to find
out we needed one more . . . or two more.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
