<SLUG> BC-HACKER-COURT-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFAMOUS COMPUTER HACKER FACES MORE PRISON TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Mitnick, dubbed the world's most notorious
computer hacker, finally has been brought to justice after nearly
four years in prison. His sentence: a $4,125 fine and more prison
time until January.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of young people filled the courtroom and carried ``Free
Kevin'' signs outside the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he has paid his debt. He has suffered enough,''
said 21-year-old supporter Maryanne DuVall. ``The government has
been way too hard on him.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Mariana R. Pfaelzer rejected the
government's request for a $1.5 million fine to pay restitution for
the estimated $80 million in damage that the Monroe High School
graduate was accused of causing with his hacking exploits.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there is no misunderstanding, Mr. Mitnick, this is a token
restitution. I know it and you know it. ... But the principle is
served,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I understand,'' Mitnick replied.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, Alan Mitnick, said he is relieved and happy the
legal battle finally has ended for his son, now 36, who began
hacking in his early teens when there were few guidelines for
talented amateur computer users.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on the cutting edge ... and he was absolutely
mistreated by the government,'' Alan Mitnick said. ``They made him
a poster boy for their mission to set up guidelines and rules over
hacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he did it out of curiosity,'' he added. ``He never
did it to hurt anyone or make any money.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant U.S. Attorney Christopher Painter said that,
despite the father's views, hacking is a serious crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mitnick is not the only hacker out there ... and I hope this
sends a message that anyone caught hacking risks serious
prosecution,'' Painter said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he was satisfied with the judge's restitution
order because Mitnick has agreed to turn over to his victims any
money he makes in the next seven years on books or movie deals
associated with his crime.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick's attorney Donald C. Randolph said his client's life as
a hacker is over. He asked the judge to allow Mitnick to enroll in
a 12-step program at a halfway house to help him make the
transition from prison life as he completes his 46-month sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The sentencing ended an eight-year hunt, investigation and legal
battle over Mitnick's exploits, which elevated the former San
Fernando Valley resident to hero status among the world's hacking
elite.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney said Mitnick's crimes were at least partially
obsessive-compulsive behavior. Mitnick pleaded guilty in March to
five federal counts of wire fraud and computer fraud for crimes
between 1992 and February 1995, when he was captured as the first
hacker to make the FBI's Most Wanted list.
</P>
<P>
   The prison term was determined in a plea agreement Mitnick
reached with the government in March. With time served, he could be
freed by January.
</P>
<P>
   Pfaelzer explained that, despite the government's request for
more than $1.5 million in restitution, she ordered a much lower
amount that he could realistically be forced to pay without
violating other orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to make a restitution order that is much
higher,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pfaelzer ordered Mitnick to stay away from all computer hardware
and software, cell phones, computer networks, personal information
assistants and televisions that could be used for online access.
</P>
<P>
   He is prohibited from working as a consultant to computer
companies or in any firms with access to computers.
</P>
<P>
   She also specified he may not obtain access codes, encryption
data or any altered telephone equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said the order will be lifted three years after
Mitnick's release if he successfully completes supervised
probation. Meanwhile, Randolph said he will ask that Mitnick be
allowed to use computers to the extent needed for college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Mitnick wants to get a college education ... and I'm
hopeful the judge will allow him to use computers for his
education,'' Randolph said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the hearing, Pfaelzer denied defense motions to
assign a forensic economist to investigate whether the government
inflated loss figures.
</P>
<P>
   Painter said defense accusations that the loss figures were
tainted were preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing but a smoke screen,'' Painter said. ``The judge
denied the motion, so I won't even address the accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   Randolph also urged the judge to let Mitnick remain in the
Metropolitan Detention Center in Los Angeles and not be transferred
to a different federal facility in San Bernardino, where he said
kosher food is not available. Mitnick is on a kosher diet, he said.
The judge left that decision to the jailers.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick's hacking exploits began when he was a student at Monroe
in North Hills and gained unauthorized access to the Los Angeles
Unified School District's computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   He was on probation for other computer crimes when he went on
what government lawyers call a cross-country hacking spree, which
climaxed when he was named as one of the FBI's Most Wanted and
ended when he was arrested in North Carolina in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   During the FBI investigation, agents tied cellular telephone
calls from Mitnick's apartment in Raleigh, N.C., to computer
intrusions in San Jose, San Francisco and San Diego. One entry
resulted in the theft of computer software worth as much as $1
million, according to federal affidavits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Mitnick admitted that he broke into a Pacific Bell
telephone computer in 1992, possessed false identification,
consorted with a convicted hacker, failed to make four required
reports to his probation officer and fled Los Angeles without
permission from the probation officer. He also admitted to being
caught with codes to use cellular telephones without paying.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick's plea and sentencing resolved federal indictments
pending in Los Angeles and San Francisco against the 36-year-old
computer hacker.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, state computer fraud charges against Mitnick were
dismissed after prosecutors said they could prove only a minor
infraction that carries a fine of $50 to $100.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick allegedly pretended to be a Department of Motor Vehicles
employee during a telephone call to get some confidential records
sent to him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
