<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT DODGERS TOPPLE METS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They were the laughingstock of the league coming into
a raucous stadium filled with fans of the hottest team in baseball.
It was the set-up for one of the most horrific road trips in
memory, and the deal was nearly closed a few nights ago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Los Angeles Dodgers sent a shock wave through the
NL East and turned the wild-card situation into disarray by winning
their third straight game against the New York Mets, 9-2 Monday at
Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly two outs from an anticipated four-game sweep on
Saturday at the hands of the Mets, the Dodgers retaliated for one
of the few times this season and knocked the Mets out of first in
the division, and out of first in the wild-card race, by winning
the final three of the four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Who knew when the Dodgers trailed by a run in the ninth in the
second game of the series that this was possible? ``This is a good
place to play, it was good for us,'' Dodgers third baseman Adrian
Beltre said. ``When you win two or three games in a row and play
like we did, we feel we still have a chance. It's different on the
road. You feel you can play like San Diego did a few games ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson said after the Dodgers limped through
three games in Houston that playing in New York could be good for
the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the upbeat Dodgers travel to lowly Montreal, the league's
second-worst team, with a chance to gain back a little more of the
pride they frittered away before they arrived in Gotham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it takes time for new players, a new manager and new
coaches to trust each other,'' Johnson said. ``Sometimes when you
play against some tougher people, it's good for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the Mets' career leader in managerial wins, then said,
``I always like coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers completed their first series win in six attempts and
have a three-game winning streak for the first time since the
All-Star break. They did it by outscoring the Mets 23-5 in the last
two games and 27-6 since Saturday's seventh inning. Eric Karros'
encore to a three-RBI afternoon was two hits and four RBI on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't just go out there and lay down for anybody,''
Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield said. ``We were playing in New
York and that's something that's exciting. I'm sure they didn't
think we were going to lay down.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Dodgers also got dominant pitching. Kevin Brown followed
Darren Dreifort's overpowering performance by allowing two hits in
seven innings before leaving with a blister on his middle finger.
Brown insists he won't miss a start because of the injury and
cautioned the Dodgers not to get crazy about the three-game streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to try to build, to get some positives out of the
situation because it's been a tough year,'' Brown said.
``Hopefully, we'll get on a roll. Right now, we're looking at
trying to play for self-respect. That's all you can look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he could have continued, but Johnson said there was
no point in risking his best starter for a game the Dodgers were
controlling. Bothered by the blister since the second inning, Brown
had it drained between innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made it difficult on some of the pitches to hold on to (the
ball),'' Brown said. ``I could have stayed out there, but it
wouldn't be easy to make pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown (13-6) never gave the impression he was laboring. He
allowed both hits in the fourth inning and retired 21 of the 25
batters he faced. In retiring the last 11 batters, he allowed one
ball out of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   It was reminiscent of Brown's masterful four-hitter five days
earlier in Houston. In fact, Brown is 3-0 in his last four starts
with a 0.85 ERA, and the one game in which he didn't earn a
decision he left with a 5-1 lead in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some pretty good swings on (Brown), but he was able to
keep the ball off the barrel of the bat and weren't able to get
back in the game,'' said Mets catcher Mike Piazza, who went 3 for
15 with one RBI against his old teammates. ``I thought I had really
good swings but obviously nothing to show for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
