<HEADER>
A1490 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS     08-10 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ The only thing certain about Monday's game at Turner
Field is that the Astros lost 5-3 to the Atlanta Braves.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Exactly why or how it happened was subject to debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theme of this game was our players missing signs,'' Astros
manager Larry Dierker said. ``There were quite a few missed signs.
Usually, we get 'em about half of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son's Little League team gets signs easier than we do. I
guess we're going to have to go over it one on one with guys. They
(the signs) haven't changed all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation that seemed to epitomize Monday's confusion
occurred in the eighth inning when shortstop Tim Bogar hit a
two-out single, then was stranded on first base when relief pitcher
Doug Henry struck out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said Bogar ``was supposed to go,'' meaning he expected
Bogar to attempt a stolen base, presumably so the Astros could
bring a pinch hitter to the plate with the potential go-ahead run
in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some confusion,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no confusion on Bogar's part following the game. He
was confident he knew his assignment in the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never told anything,'' said Bogar, who is 3-for-8 in
stolen-base attempts this year. ``Just knowing the game, I guess
I'm supposed to steal second so he can hit for the pitcher. I
didn't miss a sign. If he wants me to run, he should have given me
a `run' sign. Every guy on the team has a green light.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (third-base coach Mike Cubbage) gives you a sign that he
really wants you to get a good jump, and that's what (the sign) I
got. I never got a good jump, and I didn't want to get thrown out.
If they were worried about stealing a base, I'm not the guy. We had
guys on the bench who are better base-stealers than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Craig Biggio seemed to indicate the Astros put on
more plays than usual in Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do a lot of it, and then all of sudden we do it
today,'' Biggio said, adding, ``I don't think missed signs cost us
the game. I don't know about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the frustration was a tough loss, highlighted by the
first hit of rookie catcher Pascual Matos' career. His two-run
single off Henry in the eighth inning was the decisive blow in the
first game of this showdown between two playoff-contending teams.
</P>
<P>
   The loss trimmed the Astros' National League Central Division
lead to two games over Cincinnati, which beat Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros stranded 10 baserunners and left runners in scoring
position in five of the nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   The meager run support was par for the course considering it was
Chris Holt's turn in the rotation. Holt held his own in a matchup
with one-time Cy Young winner John Smoltz, but neither figured in
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have my best stuff, but I felt like I gave us a
chance to win the game, which is what I try to do every time out,''
said Holt, who allowed three runs on eight hits in 6 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Braves reliever Rudy Seanez allowed a run in relief of Smoltz,
who left with a 3-2 lead. Seanez (6-1) qualified for the win
because he was the pitcher of record on Matos' timely hit.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker pitched a scoreless ninth inning for his 23rd save.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett's RBI single gave the Astros a 1-0 lead in the
third, and Atlanta tied the score in the bottom of the inning on
Ryan Klesko's run-producing base hit.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who was 3-for-4 and extended his hitting streak to 11
games, again found himself in the middle of the action in the sixth
inning when he led off with a hit and scored on Bogar's clutch
two-out single.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves chased Holt from the game with two in the seventh.
Gerald Williams brought home one run with a sacrifice fly to center
field, and Chipper Jones' RBI single to left broke a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitch to Chipper was just a get-me-over curveball,'' Holt
said. ``He stayed back and got good wood on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros pulled even in the eighth when Everett led off with a
double, moved to third on Russ Johnson's fly to right and scored on
Paul Bako's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The inning ended, rather strangely, with Henry batting for
himself and striking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was baffled by it,'' said Henry, who has only 15 career
at-bats. ``But I don't make those calls. They called me up there,
and I was just swinging hard just in case I hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the way the bottom of the eighth began was an indication
of how things would unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko led off with a grounder that hit first base and caromed
into right field for a double. After Henry walked Andruw Jones and
struck out Walt Weiss, Matos cracked what seemed to be a three-run
homer down the left-field line.
</P>
<P>
   After a strong protest from Bogar, Dierker and left fielder Bill
Spiers, the umpires uncharacteristically overturned the call _
determining the ball cleared the left-field wall in foul territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely foul,'' Bogar said. ``You have to commend
the umpires for changing the call in that situation. That took a
lot of guts.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a brief letdown for the crowd of 40,072, but the fans
quickly got over it when Matos poked a single through the left
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best I've felt since I've been back from the
disabled list,'' said Henry (1-2), who has allowed five runs and
five hits in his last three outings. ``I'll just have to go back to
the bullpen and figure out what the heck I've been doing wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
