<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1493 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-BROWNS-HN     08-10 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-BROWNS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CANTON, Ohio _ Although it was only a meaningless exhibition, based
on the reception they got it seemed as if the new Cleveland Browns
were involved in a playoff game.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one had to ask the Browns' fans if they were ready for some
football. They had been ready since Art Modell moved his franchise
to Baltimore after the 1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   In a break from tradition, the annual AFC-NFC Hall of Fame Game
was moved from Saturday afternoon to Monday night to take advantage
of the rebirth of the new Browns. The Dallas Cowboys, the most
popular television draw in the NFL, were brought in to participate
in what turned out to be an entertaining game that should
obliterate the preseason television ratings record.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was there a festive atmosphere at Fawcett Stadium, but
the Browns and Cowboys drew a record crowd of 25,156 that saw
Cleveland prevail 20-17 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Dawson, a rookie from Texas, won the game with a 20-yard
field goal. Dawson's 23-yard field goal in the third quarter had
tied the game at 17.
</P>
<P>
   A good time was had by all. Browns fans watched quarterback Tim
Couch, the No. 1 pick in the draft, play like a veteran after
relieving starter Ty Detmer in the second quarter. Couch led the
Browns on two scoring drives and finished 11-of-17 for 137 yards
and a touchdown before leaving after the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim didn't exceed my expectations, because I expect a lot from
him,'' Browns coach Chris Palmer said. ``He functioned well for a
rookie. He handled most of the blitzes. He certainly didn't hurt
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys fans, in the minority but still vocal as usual, went
home happy because none of Dallas' stars was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman completed nine of 11 passes for
85 yards before leaving one play into the second quarter. Emmitt
Smith carried once for no yards before departing. Michael Irvin had
two catches for 15 yards before calling it a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They threw a lot of eight-man fronts and blitzes at us,''
Aikman said. ``I was happy with the way our guys protected. We
didn't spend a lot of time in preparation for that kind of stuff,
so you've got to be pleased with the way we handled it.``
</P>
<P>
   Even Aikman was impressed by the atmosphere and the attitude of
the Browns fans, many of whom spent most of the night barking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to see the Dawg Pound back in the NFL,'' Aikman
said. ``I thought Couch had a nice first half. He hung in the
pocket well, and he did a good job of picking up his secondary
receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey wasn't concerned about such veterans
as Aikman, Smith and Irvin. With his long injury list, Gailey
couldn't afford to see any more players go down. He did get a good
look at a lot of his young players, especially on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what some of our young defensive guys did getting to
the ball,'' Gailey said. ``Especially some of the young guys in the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he signed for so much money and has received so much
attention, Couch was eager to show his coaches and fans what he
could do. Whether throwing or running, Couch was fearless and
rambunctious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach (Palmer) told me after one of my runs that we're going
to have to practice sliding this week,'' Couch said. ``I never slid
in high school or college, but I'll try to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't nervous. I tried to stay on an even keel. I made some
positive plays, but I've got a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd got just what it wanted _ a quick Browns
touchdown to get the preseason off to an ideal start.
</P>
<P>
   On Dallas' first series, Aikman was charged with a fumble, and
Cleveland linebacker John Thierry recovered at the Dallas 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns got a break when Dallas was called for pass
interference in the end zone, giving Cleveland a first down at the
Dallas one. Running back Terry Kirby leaped into the end zone on
his second try, and Dawson kicked the extra point for a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first fumble, I thought we moved the ball well,''
Aikman said. ``I had a lot of time to throw. Chris (Warren) had a
few nice runs, and we moved the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   While Aikman didn't throw a touchdown pass, backup Jason Garrett
threw a pair in the second quarter. Garrett connected with MarTay
Jenkins on a 35-yard score and with Jeff Ogden on a 24-yarder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
