<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1495 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ACURA-LADN     08-10 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ACURA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAZIER UPSETS TAUZIAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Call Amy Frazier self-deprecating or
just plain honest. Regardless, the self-dubbed ``one-dimensional''
player only needed her lone dimension to supply the first upset to
the $520,000 Acura Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier rarely moved off the baseline and ousted fifth-seeded
Nathalie Tauziat 3-6, 7-5, 6-2 Monday in one hour, 54 minutes at
Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Known for her steady ground strokes and love for the baseline,
Frazier quietly has become one of the hottest players on the WTA
Tour. Since Wimbledon, where 18-year-old Alexandra Stevenson
knocked her out in the first round, she is 6-2. That same Frazier
is benefiting from the hardcourts in California as opposed to
Wimbledon's grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game's pretty one dimensional, so there's not really much I
can change with it,'' Frazier said. ``I go out and hit my ground
strokes, and hopefully, they go in.''
</P>
<P>
   They went in Monday, helping the Michigan resident remain more
composed than her opponent. Tauziat questioned calls several times
and twice slammed her racket on the ground. The Frenchwoman finally
appeared to collect herself when she took a 2-0 lead in the third
set, but Frazier then rattled off six games. Dropping that lead in
the final set, however, might not have done in Tauziat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I lost the match before, in the second set,'' Tauziat
said. ``When you're ahead, you have to go out and take advantage of
it. I had a break point. I didn't get it. And that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Frazier eliminated one of the tournament's eight seeded
players, the victory isn't an enormous upset. The two are 4-4
lifetime and Frazier, ranked 24th by the WTA, holds a 3-2 advantage
on hardcourts.
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat, ranked 10th, rated the way she played with an emphatic
thumbs-down. She did say that Frazier is always a tough opponent,
especially on hardcourts. But when asked if Frazier gave her
trouble, she said, ``No, not really, I think I made the trouble
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier said, ``She made some unforced errors and I got a little
lucky. I just could have easily lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier's victory overshadowed the night match in which Spain's
Conchita Martinez beat Austria's Sylvia Plischke 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez took a 5-0 lead in the first set and controlled the
entire match. Her victory could serve as a confidence booster
because she lost in the first round in tournaments at Stanford and
Carlsbad.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez, who won the Acura Classic in 1995, said she didn't
do anything differently than she did in the first-round losses to
Jennifer Capriati and Barbara Schett. She pointed out that the
tour's talent level has risen over the past years to make every
round a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, you knew you were going to get past the first round,''
Martinez said. ``Now, you never know. There are so many, many good
players.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Other matches: Julie Halard-Decugisof France beat Croatia's
Iva Majoli 6-1, 6-4. Majoli, who is 5-10 this year, was one of
tournament's three wild cards with Stevenson and Corina Morariu.
</P>
<P>
   Ai Sugiyamaof Japan beat Nathalie Dechy of France 6-2, 6-3.
Sugiyama's victory gives third-seeded Mary Piercea rematch in the
second round. Sugiyama beat Pierce in the first round of last
week's TIG Classic in Carlsbad.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying matches were completed Monday as Lisa Raymond, Magui
Serna, Ines Gorrochategui and Anne Kremer earned their way into the
tournament. Serna's match was the closest, as she beat Kimberly Po
6-4, 4-6, 6-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1496 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-10 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ Forget about looking at the standings today.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the expressions on the faces in the Astros' clubhouse
after Monday night's game at Turner Field. Look at the way the
Astros walked around, stunned and amazed at the uncharacteristic,
un-Astros effort they had just given.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the Mets, Reds and Diamondbacks. Instead, think
about the way things have been in the National League for the past
decade and how they will continue to be until someone proves
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Braves, and then it's everyone else. Monday night, the
Astros looked like just another everyone-else kind of wannabe.
</P>
<P>
   The usually unwavering and unshakable Astros wavered. They shook
in critical situations. They quaked in game-winning moments and
ultimately coughed up a very winnable game 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw a lot of things you don't characteristically see from
us,'' Astros second baseman Craig Biggio said.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the Braves looking vulnerable and beatable this
season. Forget about the Astros looking practically unbeatable in
spite of so many injuries and setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   This was a night that clearly proved yet again that if you want
to take over the National League, you have to prove it against
Atlanta. The Astros didn't.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, this was a night when the Astros not only didn't
take a bold step forward against the Braves but might have taken a
step backward.
</P>
<P>
   The game began the way Atlanta's night air felt _ sultry and
hot. Both teams came dead-serious set on proving something. The
atmosphere dripped with sweat, tension and critical plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scraped out an early lead as the legend of Carl
Everett only grew. Everett went 3-for-4 and now has hits in 12 of
his last 17 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves quickly responded with a game-tying run on the heels
of maybe the greatest play the league will see this season. On a
long drive to the center-field wall by Bill Spiers in the third
inning, the Braves' Andruw Jones sprinted back full speed, leaped
into the air, planted both feet into the padding and caught the
drive over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best play I've ever seen,'' Spiers said.
</P>
<P>
   It was indeed a say-hey kind of play that set the tone for what
would be an entertaining yet ultimately strange night.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this was the kind of game you wish you could box
up, stow away and open again in October when the nights are cooler
and the stakes are higher. Clearly, both teams wanted to prove
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not by any stretch are we intimidated by them,'' Spiers said.
</P>
<P>
   There were other highlight-reel plays. Biggio turned in a nice
one, and Russ Johnson had a sparkling effort at third base for the
Astros on a high hopper by Jose Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   There were missed opportunities on both sides and situational
pitching moves. There were pivotal moments and controversial calls
_ none more enthralling than the umpiring crew's reversing a home
run down the line by Braves rookie Pascual Matos, calling the ball
foul.
</P>
<P>
   And there was good pitching. Braves starter John Smoltz held the
Astros to two runs for seven innings, but pity Astros starter Chris
Holt. Holt carried a lead into the seventh and pitched well enough
to win most games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just hung a couple of pitches,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said, ``and that cost him.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't most games. This was the Braves showing why they are
the team of the '90s and the Astros showing some cracks in the
machine they haven't shown all year.
</P>
<P>
   After fumbling a pair of hit-and-run signals earlier in the game
_ one likely costing an Astros run _ Astros shortstop Tim Bogar
apparently missed a steal signal from the bench. It was the eighth
inning with two outs and the game tied at three, prompting Dierker
to send reliever Doug Henry to the plate instead of pinch-hitting
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was baffled,'' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said he made the unorthodox move thinking Bogar would
steal. If the steal was successful, Dierker would have pinch-hit
for Henry.
</P>
<P>
   But Bogar never ran, and the Astros never again had a chance in
this one. Afterward, Dierker couldn't believe all the missed signs,
saying his son's Little League team took signs better than the
'Stros.
</P>
<P>
   There was a noticeable tension in the air throughout the Astros'
clubhouse afterward and more than a little finger-pointing. Maybe
it will all be better today, when the three-game set against the
team of the '90s continues. But this was one the Astros could have
had and likely should have had. Instead, the Braves motored along,
and the Astros fumbled and bickered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
