<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1503 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     08-10 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS SHUT OUT ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ If this were an audition, Ken Hill's
performance was a success.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels pitcher could still be traded, and the
Cleveland Indians might be interested, especially after placing
starter Jaret Wright on the disabled list Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, however, didn't need any help Monday, as Bartolo
Colon shut out the Angels on seven hits in the Indians' 4-0 win
before 22,013 at Edison Field. The loss was the Angels' fourth in a
row and dropped them a season-worst 19 games under .500 (46-65).
They are 5-20 since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians pursued Angels pitcher Chuck Finley before the
trading deadline but felt the Angels asked too much. But now with
Wright joining Dwight Gooden on the disabled list, the Indians have
Colon, Dave Burba, Charles Nagy and Mark Langston as their
starters. No one else on their roster has started a game this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Hill would have to clear waivers, but he is under contract for
$5.6 million next year and has had elbow problems the past two
seasons, which should be enough to deter teams from making a claim.
</P>
<P>
   Hill was traded from the Cardinals to the Indians just before
the trading deadline in 1995 and went 4-1 in 11 starts down the
stretch, helping the Indians reach the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Monday he allowed three runs (two earned) and eight hits in six
innings. And if there was any question about his elbow, he made 122
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Holding the Indians to two earned runs in six innings is no
small feat, considering the Indians offense ranks No. 1 in the
American League in 10 categories, including batting average, runs,
hits, slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   He has pitched well in five starts since returning from the
disabled list July 19, even if he has only one win to show for it.
His ERA in those five games is 2.70 and he has allowed 31 hits in
30 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, though, he did get considerable help from his defense,
which threw out two runners at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Jesse Levis tried to score from first on
Omar Vizquel's double to the gap in right-center. Right fielder Tim
Salmon threw to shortstop Gary DiSarcina, whose relay throw on one
hop to catcher Ben Molina nailed Levis.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth inning, Manny Ramirez tried to score from first on
Jim Thome's double to right-center. That relay went center fielder
Jim Edmonds to second baseman Trent Durrington to Molina for the
out.
</P>
<P>
   Molina also threw out one of two baserunners who tried to steal
on him.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians got on the scoreboard early, scoring a run in the
first after leadoff hitter Dave Roberts opened the game with a
single. Roberts stole second, took third on a groundout by Vizquel
and scored on a sacrifice fly by Roberto Alomar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
