<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. DROPS NFL BALL AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, chalk up another stirring debacle perpetuated by the
Coliseum, the Los Angeles Clippers of football stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   As the Cleveland Browns made their re-entrance into the NFL
Monday evening, Los Angeles finds itself once again facing another
autumn in which it must turn to two local universities, USC and
UCLA, for its only football entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   This is a most implausible development, considering L.A. County
happens to be the largest in America and considering as recently as
1993 that this area possessed two NFL franchises.
</P>
<P>
   So how could such a strange scenario unfold?
</P>
<P>
   Blame the Coliseum, or at least those myopic L.A. politicians
who have hitched their NFL hopes on the Coliseum even though (a) it
is a decrepit structure built in 1923 that isn't faintly up to
modern standards, (b) it necessitates massive renovations that
neither the public nor the NFL is willing to subsidize, (c) it
inspires widespread disdain among all NFL owners and (d) it has an
ugly recent history of being spurned by such suitors as the Rams,
Raiders and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   It is now indisputable that the L.A. politicians' obsession with
the Coliseum has prevented the return of pro football to Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time owner of the Los Angeles Dodgers, Peter O'Malley,
was set to build a football stadium at Chavez Ravine a couple of
years ago, but caved in to pressure applied by L.A. politicians and
meekly scuttled his plan.
</P>
<P>
   You might recall in the mid 1980s when Al Davis, whose Raiders
were playing at the Coliseum in those days, had a stadium deal set
in Irwindale, but it, too, was sabotaged by the L.A. politicians
carrying the Coliseum's banner.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as though five years ago that Hollywood Park also
might build a stadium, but the L.A. politicians pleaded the
Coliseum's case with such passion that those administrating
Hollywood Park reluctantly backed off and reverted to concentrating
only on horse racing and card playing.
</P>
<P>
   And, amid the blaring of trumpets, Michael Ovitz recently
claimed to have an edifice called the Hacienda set to be erected in
Carson. But he also couldn't resist the stern blandishments of the
L.A. politicians, coldly abandoning Carson and going over to the
Coliseum's side.
</P>
<P>
   And so, what are we in L.A. left with because Richard Riordan,
Mark Ridley-Thomas and those other visionary L.A. politicians
stubbornly insist on the Coliseum being the only outlet for pro
football in Southern California?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly startling that such a phenomenon has occurred
since the Coliseum's bureaucratic overseer, the Coliseum
Commission, has a long and ignoble history of gross mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   It was this august body in the mid 1960s that got into a beef
with Jack Kent Cooke, then owner of the Lakers and Kings, and dared
him to find a new place for his teams.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Cooke did building the Forum in Inglewood and L.A.
found itself stuck having to meet the bond payments on a facility,
the Sports Arena, that has become a financial liability ever since.
</P>
<P>
   You might recall that the Coliseum Commission also had some
run-ins in the late 1970s with Carroll Rosenbloom, the upshot of
which inspired Rosenbloom to shift his Rams to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders still probably would be playing at the Coliseum had
the Coliseum Commission fulfilled its promise to Al Davis to build
luxury suites, which it failed to do even though it had picked up
$20 million from being co-plaintiffs with the Raiders in the
successful anti-trust suit against the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Why is L.A. so obsessed with going with an entity that keeps
producing flops?
</P>
<P>
   What is it about the Coliseum that has the L.A. politicians so
entranced at a time when new football stadiums have been sprouting
up all over the country?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Coliseum has a sacred heritage, having hosted two
Olympic Games and countless other memorable sporting events across
the decades.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is that it has become an antiquated hovel
compared to its contemporaries, and its price tag for renovation is
simply too steep to lure private entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   And since L.A. won't commit to public money and shouldn't for
the Coliseum, the old stadium has become a burdensome eyesore
creating nothing but frustrations and disappointments for its
advocates, unable to generate the fiscal requisites that the NFL
demands for an expansion franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is too economically shrewd to undercut its newest lodge
member the Browns' Al Lerner turned over $500 million to the league
in expansion franchise fees and in the process diminish the value
of its teams by allowing L.A. into its loving bosom at a cheaper
price.
</P>
<P>
   No way that's going to happen, and that's the reason Houston,
which supposedly has the money in place, is now favored to be the
next city to have an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it's ludicrous that those who want to bring
football back to L.A. ever would have consented to join forces with
the Coliseum and its fierce proponent, Mark Ridley-Thomas, a city
councilman with mayoral ambitions who understandably would like the
NFL back in a stadium that, by the sheerest coincidence, just
happens to be located in his district.
</P>
<P>
   But even more ludicrous is how those in L.A. boast about how
it's shameful that this country's ``sports capital'' doesn't have
an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. a sports capital?
</P>
<P>
   A city earns such a title if two or three of its teams are
fortunate enough to win championships in the same year a quirk that
doesn't happen often and such an appellation is pure blaspheme when
applied to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   We have become an area in which our athletic teams in recent
vintage have set new standards of futility in getting blown out in
the NBA playoffs and yielding points in the Rose Bowl and getting
embarrassed in the Sun Bowl and losing game after game by large
margins in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. can boast all it wants about its matchless weather and its
renowned amusements parks and its movie-making capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   But it should affect a modest pose when it discusses athletics
because the unvarnished truth is that it has an antiquated downtown
football stadium whose greatest claim to fame these days is its
ability to keep pro football out of L.A.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
