u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-KITNA-SP     08-10 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-KITNA-SPI </SLUG>
  
 SAME OLD JON: SUCCESS HASN'T GONE TO KITNA's HEAD  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CALRE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY _ To get a glimpse of the real Jon Kitna, it helps to
watch him interact with his 22-month-old son, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna smiles approvingly as Jordan needs next to no coaxing
before raising his arm and mimicking, ``Touchdown, Seahawks.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna breaks into one of those proud-papa grins as Jordan
exchanges high-fives with Pete Kendall and then sends the
massive-by-comparison guard on his way to the locker room with a
``Later.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna almost comes unglued with laughter as Jordan matches tight
end Deems May's gnarled expressions in an impromptu battle of
facial contortions.
</P>
<P>
   He may be the Seahawks' starting quarterback _ just the latest
chapter in an almost-beyond-belief turn of events that have
transpired since he entered Central Washington University as an
afterthought of a passer seven years ago _ but Jon Kitna is first
and foremost just a guy.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any guy, but just a guy nonetheless. A nice guy. A
husband and father. A son. A brother. A Christian. A natural
leader. A quarterback with a linebacker's mentality. A player who
has grown on the team's new coaching staff, just as he did the
team's former coaching staff. A player and person you find yourself
pulling for.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing fancy, but definitely something special. That's Jon
Kitna.
</P>
<P>
   So how is it that someone can come from as far back in the pack
as Kitna has and not emerge with an inflated ego?
</P>
<P>
   ``As my wife always says, she married a math teacher and ended
up with a football player,'' Kitna said during a break in the
team's training camp at Eastern Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna's wife, Jennifer, tells this story about going to her
10-year high school reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``People where like, `Oh, you married a football player. You
really scored,'' she said. ``I'm like, `Not really.' We both still
call ourselves teachers. That's where we want to get to,
eventually. We still kind of look at this as a little vacation.
Then we'll get back to the real world, eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Kitna is able to enjoy this vacation without all the
baggage that can come with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about one of the most salt-of-the-earth people
I've ever met,'' said Todd Peterson, the Seahawks kicker and one of
Kitna's closest friends on the team. ``He treats everybody the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't think of himself more highly than he ought to,
because he does receive some acclaim. Jon has remained
level-headed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tapestry that is this team, Kitna is the common thread.
He gets along as well with the defensive backs as he does with the
wide receivers. He has earned the respect of the defensive linemen
as well as the offensive linemen. He has the ability to transcend
skin color, social backgrounds and cliques.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon is without a doubt the most transparent person I have ever
met,'' Peterson said. ``By that, I mean he is able to look through
everything else and see someone's heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than terms like arrogant, attitude and aloof, people use
words like humble, humility and grounded to describe Kitna.
</P>
<P>
   Humility? Like Kitna, fullback Mack Strong entered the league as
an undrafted free agent. Like Kitna, he has always had to work for
everything he has gotten. Like Kitna, he is a man with strong
religious beliefs. Maybe that's why Kitna and Strong have become
friends. Strong also offers a clue as to why Kitna has not been
allowed to develop anything close to an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon hasn't changed a bit since the day he first walked into
the locker room as a rookie,'' Strong said. ``He's still losing to
me playing cards, just like he was as a rookie.''
</P>
<P>
   Humble? Jennifer was, well, less than impressed with her husband
the first time they met.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I wasn't attracted to him at all,'' she
said. ``He had the skinniest neck I had ever seen and this skinny
little waist. Everything about him kind of reminded me of Fire
Marshall Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   They finally clicked, or as Jennifer puts it, Jon finally
convinced her he was worth taking a chance on. She put Jon through
school his final two years of college, when they lived on the
$1,200 a month she was making teaching school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of stuff, yeah, it does keep us humble,'' Jon said.
</P>
<P>
   Priorities? Football might be the most time-consuming element of
Kitna's life, especially during training camp. But he does not
allow it to become all consuming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to Jordan on the phone and he says, `Dada, miss you,
love you,' '' Kitna said, a smile washing across his face. ``It
keeps things in perspective for me. It helps me understand that no
matter how things go on the football field ... my son is still my
son and my wife is still my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Grounded? Jon and Jennifer live within their means. He might be
a starting NFL quarterback, but he is scheduled to make just
$325,000 this season.
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing by NFL standards, but it's a lot more than either
of their parents ever made. They live in a modest house and live
modest lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to live so that if we are both teaching someday, we'll
still be able to live the same way,'' Jennifer said. ``That's how
we want it. That's how our families were. That's how Jon and I grew
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna, as everyone knows by now, grew up in Tacoma and played at
Lincoln High School. He quarterbacked Central Washington to the
NAIA national co-championship as a senior and the Barcelona Dragons
to the World League title in 1997. In three NFL seasons, he has
started six games.
</P>
<P>
   To find the back door to NFL stardom, just follow Kitna.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, at the end of my freshman year, this is where I
expected to be,'' he said. ``I felt like this is where I could
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he is here, Kitna won't allow himself to forget what
got him here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody looks at me and says, `Oh, you're a starting
quarterback in the NFL,' like it's an esteemed position,'' Kitna
said. ``But, esteemed in whose eyes?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get Kitna wrong. He has goals and aspirations, and lofty
ones at that _ especially for someone who entered the league as an
undrafted rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a starting quarterback. I want to be the best
quarterback there ever was,'' he said. ``But at the same time, I
just want to go out and play football just like I always have.
There wasn't all this fanfare when I was at Central and in high
school. I'm just playing a game I love to play. I just try to keep
that mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   As Peterson puts it, ``Regardless of what happens to Jon,
whether he's MVP of a Super Bowl or the league or throws for 4,000
yards in a season, he'll never change. He's the kid from Tacoma.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
