<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD `MAD MAX' WON'T STEM SONICS' FREEFALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ain't free agency great?
</P>
<P>
   And don't the Sonics really seem to know how to play the game?
</P>
<P>
   I mean, the Sonics make a big fuss about clearing salary cap
room so they can go sign an impact player and lo and behold,
there's no impact player to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Richmond? No-can-do.
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Ceballos? Word in Sacramento Monday was that the Kings
have the inside track _ as if they need more ammo.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Hardaway? The Sonics took the first deal they could get
with Orlando when they got Horace Grant for a slew of Sonics
castaways on a draft-day deal.
</P>
<P>
   Guess Sonics president Wally Walker did not think the Magic were
in such a charitable mood to basically give away Penny.
</P>
<P>
   But if it's true that Suns owner Jerry Colangelo sealed the deal
to steal Hardaway by presenting him with purple-velvet covered golf
clubs, certainly Walker and Paul Westphal could have made a trip to
Puetz or Nevada Bob's to wow Penny to Seattle, no?
</P>
<P>
   You gotta love this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably going to sign two more guys this week, they
just won't be household names,'' Walker said Monday after it was
announced that the Sonics' big offseason acquisition is Vernon
Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, Mad Max.
</P>
<P>
   What Walker failed to mention is that the biggest reason
Maxwell's name is a household name is because Maxwell's arrest
sheet is about as long as his NBA career stats.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the fact that Maxwell punched out a Blazers fan back in
1995 or that he served jail time for misdemeanor possession of
marijuana does not concern me, mostly because it doesn't concern
Gary Payton, who wanted Maxwell in a Sonics uniform and there lies
the entire story.
</P>
<P>
   Things are so desperate with the Sonics that Payton and his
agents have all but carte blanche to suggest to Walker the players
the Sonics must go after.
</P>
<P>
   And, frankly, after watching the likes of Craig Ehlo and Moochie
Norris get trotted into Sonics camps, why wouldn't Payton try his
hand at assistant general manager?
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell's arrival is part of Payton's desire to have the Sonics
get tougher, or in Payton's vernacular _ a little more ``ghetto'' _
which is not a bad idea, at least when there has been an absence of
good ideas the past three or four years about who the Sonics should
sign to help win Payton (and oh, yes, owner Barry Ackerley) a ring.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Shawn Kemp was a genuis.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, after the 1996 NBA Finals, when the Sonics battled to
Game 6 against the Bulls, the Sonics' power forward could see which
direction the Sonics were heading and decided to bail.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because when it came time in the summer of '96 to negotiate
those bonanza free-agent deals, Kemp knew that Walker had made a
tremendous mistake signing Jim McIlvaine for that $35 million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, the Sonics have been paying for that decision.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, would the Sonics' offseason be reaching near
crisis proportion if the chances of Vin Baker becoming a
championship-caliber player weren't so dicey?
</P>
<P>
   Talk about grasping at straws. The Sonics have no choice but to
re-sign Baker to a whopping $87 million contract and then pray the
big man delivers all he promises _ which is a lot, considering
Baker has yet to demonstrate a championship-caliber caliber inside
game.
</P>
<P>
   But as Payton said, the Sonics didn't trade Kemp to turn around
and lose Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like negotiating from a position of strength.
</P>
<P>
   Walker is over so many barrels, it's a wonder he hasn't booked a
ride over Niagara Falls this summer.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other mistakes that are coming back to haunt the
Sonics, what about the McIlvaine leftovers?
</P>
<P>
   As previously mentioned, it sure looked as if Walker had all but
erased the slate on that disaster back in June when he traded away
Don McLean (among several others) to Orlando for Grant.
</P>
<P>
   But oops, we were wrong about that, it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, clearing off the remaining cap room by dealing
MacLean (the last vestiges of the McIlvaine disaster) and
free-agent bust Billy Owens has netted the Sonics absolutely no
bargaining power.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has been unable to trade Hersey Hawkins, which would have
been necessary to complete a deal with Washington for Richmond. But
again, Hawkins' contract was signed during that summer spending
spree that locked up Payton but also brought in McIlvaine and
alienated Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   There is no other way to spin this. The Sonics are in dissaray.
They have gone from Game 6 of the 1996 NBA Finals to
circle-the-drain desperation faster than the Miss Bud going around
Lake Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Signing Vernon Maxwell is better than nothing, but that isn't
saying very much.
</P>
<P>
   Not when everyone from the Sonics front office down to the bar
stool sitters at Floyds Bar-B-Que in lower Queen Anne understood
that in order for the Sonics to hang with the Suns, Blazers,
Lakers, Spurs, Jazz, Kings, Rockets and Timberwolves, they were
going to have to do a whole lot better than nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 0202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
