<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEFEAT A'S, 12-8 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Before each at-bat, Bernie Williams steps
across the batter's box and practices his geometry: he lays his bat
across the front of the plate, notes the spot where the handle dots
the ground and, from that point, draws a straight line back toward
the umpire. In this way, he knows where to take his stance.
</P>
<P>
   Williams seems to do this subconsciously with the calendar, as
well. When summer creeps toward fall, a line is drawn and Williams
begins to whale the ball. He launched a grand slam on Monday night
in an eight-run second inning, and the Yankees whipped Oakland,
12-8.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, Derek Jeter and Ricky Ledee also hit home runs
for the Yankees in a game affected by the small and consistent
strike zone being called by John Shulock, the home-plate umpire.
Oakland's pitchers walked nine batters, the Yankees' six.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics (60-52) are in the thick of the race for a
post-season berth, having won 9 of their first 10 games on this
homestand. But the Yankees (69-42) issued a reminder of who is atop
the American League, jumping on Oakland early.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Haynes walked the first two batters in the second inning,
Williams and Tino Martinez, and then Chili Davis laced a
run-scoring double. Ledee singled, Scott Brosius later singled, and
Knoblauch drew a walk; with the Yankees ahead, 3-0, Mike Oquist
replaced Haynes.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeter drew a walk, forcing home a fourth run. Paul O'Neill
flied to short left, bringing Williams to the plate, to draw his
line and set his stance. Going into Monday night's game, Williams
had 16 hits in 30 at-bats with runners in scoring position (.533).
</P>
<P>
   He fell behind no balls and two strikes and fouled off two
pitches. He took a ball, and then another, and with a 2-2 count,
Williams took a pitch low, threw his bat down and began jogging to
first. With the crowd laughing and jeering at Williams for his
mistake, he returned to the plate, picked up his bat _ and bashed
the next pitch into the stands, for his 19th home run.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also has 82 runs batted in over all, moving ahead of
Jeter (80) for the team lead. Thirty of those rbi have come in the
25 games since the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' eight-run outburst was reminiscent of their
memorable game here last Aug. 4, when Darryl Strawberry's grand
slam highlighted an eight-run rally in the ninth inning of a 10-5
victory.
</P>
<P>
   But this victory would not be so noteworthy, and the Yankees
struggled to hold their lead as Hideki Irabu was knocked out early.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu has managed to contain the flashes of temper that were his
signature in 1997, those spats with the umpires that left him
kicking angrily at the pitching rubber. Close calls that go against
Irabu do not bother him as much now, the pitching coach Mel
Stottlemyre said the other day; he usually contains his
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday night, Shulock called a strike zone roughly
equivalent to the size of a laptop computer, a strike zone that
often eluded and perturbed Irabu. He came into this game with the
second-best ratio of strikeouts to walks in the American League
(3.96), but on Monday night he walked three and struck out none and
repeatedly fell behind in the count.
</P>
<P>
   He reached a 2-0 count to five consecutive batters in one
stretch, and Irabu appeared to be quite certain that some of his
pitches were strikes, contrary to Shulock's opinion. With the
Yankees ahead, 8-0, Irabu gave up four runs with two outs in the
second inning, including a two-run home run to Tony Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   After throwing a close pitch for a ball to the next batter,
Randy Velarde, Irabu glared at Shulock and twice spread his arms:
What do I have to do to throw a strike, his body language screamed.
Martinez and then Stottlemyre went to the mound and tried to calm
Irabu. The next inning, he fell behind, 2-0, to Scott Spiezio and
walked slowly behind the mound with a ``you've got to be kidding''
grin _ and fired a fastball, which Spiezio belted for a home run.
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth, Irabu appeared resigned to firing fastballs in
frustration, and with the Yankees' lead reduced to 10-6 after four
innings, Manager Joe Torre elected to replace Irabu with Allen
Watson rather than give Irabu a chance to register three more outs
and his 10th victory. Irabu's outing was his shortest since May19.
</P>
<P>
   But Watson walked two of the first three batters he faced, and
after Eric Chavez singled home a run, Ramiro Mendoza relieved,
perhaps the best possible match for Shulock's tiny strike zone.
Mendoza, with outstanding control, got out of the jam and pitched
two and two-thirds innings to run his record to 5-7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
