<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS GET MORE ORNERY BY ADDING GUARD MAXELL  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It would appear the Sonics are stuck on one chore from
their summer to-do list.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, they keep getting tougher and tougher.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of veteran guard Vernon Maxwell Monday virtually
assured the Sonics will be a bit more ornery than last season.
Maxwell, a daring player throughout his 11-year career, signed a
three-year contract believed to be worth roughly $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vernon is the kind of guy we want to set the defensive tone.
We didn't want to lose out on him,'' Sonics president Wally Walker
said. ``We've talked to him all along the free agent process. Based
on playing against him last year, he's always on the floor at the
end of games. Plus, he's always taking big shots and making a lot
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell, 33, is labeled ``Mad Max'' for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-4, Maxwell is a fearless competitor who is quick
enough to play both guard positions. He is known for never biting
his tongue, and does not back down from any challenge _ whether it
be a bigger opponent or crazy shot attempt.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a player with the same attitude as fiery Sonics
point guard Gary Payton, it's Maxwell, who becomes the second new
player on the team's roster.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics acquired hard-nosed forward Horace Grant on draft day
to bolster their front line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very intimidating to see me and Gary in the
backcourt. Everybody knows it,'' said Maxwell, who also considers
Grant a close friend. ``... I know we run our mouth the same, and
we play with the same aggressiveness on defense and offense.''
Maxwell averaged 10.7 points, 1.7 assists and 21.9 minutes in 46
games off the bench for the Sacramento Kings last season. He also
shot a career-high 35 percent from 3-point range. A concern would
be whether Maxwell can play more minutes and stay injury-free in an
82-game season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics probably will play Maxwell mostly alongside Payton,
which would mean a decreased role for Hersey Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have a significant role,'' Walker said of
Maxwell. ``I can't say it means anything for Hawk. It just means
we've bolstered our backcourt.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell sought a three-year $10 million contract from the Kings,
who renounced their rights to him. The Sonics' original offer was a
two-year deal worth $3.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Giving Maxwell a third year _ which he can opt out of _ cinched
the deal. Maxwell turned down Detroit, Toronto and the L.A.
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really wasn't a hard decision because I felt like I had a
better chance to have a good year with established ballplayers,''
Maxwell said. ``I felt like I had a better chance of getting back
to that next level. ... And I wanted some stability. The money is
not that bad. It's not what I expected, but I'll bite the bullet.
It weighs out and it's going to make me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell resurrected his career in Sacramento after a tumultuous
career.
</P>
<P>
   He was a 1988 second-round pick of the Denver Nuggets. But
Maxwell is best known for his title runs with the 1994 and 1995 NBA
champion Houston Rockets. From 1995 through 1998, Maxwell played
for Philadelphia, San Antonio, Orlando and Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   After signing Maxwell, the Sonics remained close to $1.8 million
under the salary cap. Walker said he expects to sign another player
or complete a trade this week.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins is still on the trading block. Unless the Sonics do a
sign-and-trade, they will compete with most teams that can offer
their $2 million exception to free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Walker called a sign-and-trade deal with Washington to get Mitch
Richmond, ``an extreme long shot.'' However, Walker is working on
another sign-and-trade transaction that would land a big-name small
forward.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics still need a center and an athletic player who can
create shots off the dribble. Walker is turning his attention to
small forwards _ possibly Cedric Ceballos (Dallas) or Cedric
Henderson (Cleveland).
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to sign a young slashing guy,'' Walker said. ``We'll
look at some veteran guys. We're looking for guys we think will
benefit from the proposed (defensive) rules changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Maxwell stayed out of trouble in Sacramento last
season, the Sonics latched on to a guy known for playing by his own
rules off the court.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Maxwell was suspended after going into the stands at
Portland and attacked a heckler whom he claimed was making fun of
his stillborn child. During the 1995 playoffs, Maxwell was
suspended by the Rockets after a disagreement with the coaching
staff. He played just one postseason game and was waived that June.
</P>
<P>
   He has been jailed for a misdemeanor marijuana possession charge
and violating his probation for a previous gun arrest. Maxwell also
filed for bankruptcy after he was sued in 1996 for allegedly
knowingly giving a woman herpes during a brief relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done anything in five years. The past is the past.
I've moved ahead,'' Maxwell said. ``I did everything that was said
and written about me. But judge me after meeting me. Don't judge me
for my past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
