<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS FAIL TO IGNITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Sparks have experienced slow
starts throughout the season but never worse than Monday's critical
home game against the Detroit Shock.
</P>
<P>
   They fell behind by 20 points in the first half, and despite a
brief but spirited second-half surge, never recovered from the
early deficit. The Shock held them to their lowest scoring output
since last season, 84-59, before 6,858 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Sparks' first loss at home in seven games, dropping
them to one game ahead of the Sacramento Monarchs, who host them in
Sacramento tonight. The Sparks are second in the Western Conference
at 17-8; the Monarchs, who were idle Monday, are 17-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like trying to start your car in the middle of a
Chicago winter,'' Sparks coach Orlando Woolridge said about the
slow start. ``We just couldn't get started.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to regroup and get ready for tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, which had lost three of its last four games since
trading Cindy Brown and Korie Hlede for Utah's Wendy Palmer and
Olympia Scott-Richardson, finally got the game they were looking
for from the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, who was a reserve for Utah, is a starter for the Shock
and played like one with 15 points and 12 rebounds in just 26
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was the worst game for Sparks center Lisa Leslie since the
All-Star game. The All-Star MVP was 2 for 11 from the field and had
only four rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks, who trailed 42-26 at the half, trimmed the deficit
to nine points (51-42) with a 9-0 run led by La'Kiesha Frett (12
points) and DeLisha Milton (16 points, eight rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   But the Shock, who are 12-14 and third in the Eastern
Conference, outscored the Sparks 19-8 to finish the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fighting for our playoff lives and everybody stepped
up,'' Detroit coach Nancy Lieberman-Cline said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
