<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG SWING BY BUHNER RAISES SPIRIT, SINKS WHITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When he dropped a popup in the third inning Monday
night, Jay Buhner thought back to the 1995 playoffs in Cleveland,
when he misjudged a fly bll but ended up the hero when he won the
game with a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's misplay was embarrassing _ ``I just flat clanked it,''
he said _ but Buhner simply picked up the ball and threw to second
for a force out. This would be one of the good nights, with Buhner
the good guy again.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner's first grand slam in more than three years sent the
Mariners to a 6-4 victory over the Chicago White Sox at Safeco
Field. It was a two-way starring role for the veteran right
fielder, who bloodied his left forearm when he dove to catch Frank
Thomas' foul fly for the second out of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game, it does wonders,'' Buhner said. ``I just love the
way one minute you feel like you're a goat and the next minute you
can be a hero. I'm just fortunate to have an opportunity where I'm
in the lineup every day and I'm able to go out there and redeem
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Since July 15, when Buhner came back after nearly two months on
the disabled list because of a strained hamstring, the Mariners
have lost ground in the standings and Buhner has struggled to find
his timing. When he came to bat in the sixth inning Monday, he was
hitting .196 with three homers and four RBIs in 21 games since
returning.
</P>
<P>
   But in the sixth, the Mariners loaded the bases on a walk by Ken
Griffey Jr. and infield singles by Alex Rodriguez and Edgar
Martinez. Buhner took four of John Snyder's pitches, three of which
were close but only one called a strike, then tore into a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   He slowed into a trot just a step or two out of the batter's
box. This was a 411-foot rocket that not even Safeco could fizzle.
``I knew (BEGIN ITAL) that (END ITAL) one was out,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   It was something to savor, not only because it gave the M's a
6-3 lead but because it put Buhner at peace with himself. After the
game, he brought up Saturday's 1-0 loss to the Yankees, when he
doubled twice but failed in a crucial bases-loaded situation.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night was redemtion for that, and for the last several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starting to get a little perturbed at myself at the way
things were going, and I had a lot of negative things going through
my head, a lot of things that have been stressing me out over the
last couple of weeks since I've come back,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to go out and be able to do that. Just when you
think you're down in the dumps, one little swing of the bat can
totally change it. I went up there my next at-bat and felt like I
was completely locked in. Maybe that can be the one at-bat that
gets things going.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's won for the first time since last Tuesday, snapping a
five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   They scored their first two runs in the first inning, when
Martinez doubled off the wall in left-center, scoring John Mabry
and Rodriguez, who had singled.
</P>
<P>
   Given the lead, M's starter Gil Meche promptly gave it away.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old right-hander retired the first White Sox batter
he faced, then walked Paul Konerko. The next batter, Greg Norton,
golfed Meche's only changeup of the game deep into the right-field
seats.
</P>
<P>
   A four-pitch walk came next, then a visit from pitching coach
Stan Williams followed by another four-pitch walk. The bullpen was
stirring, and with good reason: Meche lasted only 12/3 innings in
his previous start, and it seemed he might end another at the same
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never walked two batters in a row on eight pitches in my
life,'' Meche said. ``It's a tough situation to get through.
There's so many things running through your mind out there. The
first thing that comes up is, I don't want to get taken out of this
game, so I've got to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   He dueled Ray Durham on a tough at-bat, finally retiring the
second baseman on a fly to center. The White Sox took a 3-2 lead
before the first out of the third, but Meche allowed no more hits
after Frank Thomas' RBI single. He improved to 3-2 but was
unsatisifed with the six-inning performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wild for sure,'' Meche said. ``I wasn't walking as many
guys the last four innings, but those guys were missing some
pitches that were mistakes. I got away with a lot of bad pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   After two innings from Jose Paniagua, the M's survived in the
ninth after Jose Mesa allowed a leadoff single and a four-pitch
walk. Chris Singleton popped up a bunt attempt, then Buhner put on
his cape to rob Thomas. One out later, the ovations of the 42,978
fans were loudest for Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the favorites here, no question,'' manager Lou
Piniella said. ``And tonight, he responded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
