<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 04:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1536 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAIPAN-SWEATSHOPS-SFC     08-10 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIPAN-SWEATSHOPS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   APPAREL FIRMS SETTLE LAWSUIT OVER SAIPAN SWEATSHOPSBy ROBERT 
 COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Four large apparel corporations settled out of court Monday in
a landmark class-action lawsuit aimed at ending sweatshop labor
conditions on the U.S. island territory of Saipan. Four other firms
signed a preliminary agreement stating their willingness to do the
same.
<P>
   Together, the concessions mark the first step by American
companies to address a growing controversy over accusations of
illegal labor abuses on Saipan, which has become a major site for
clothes manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Three class-action lawsuits filed in January sought $1 billion
in damages, describing the Saipan factories as ``America's worst
sweatshop,'' where 50,000 indentured laborers from China, the
Philippines and Bangladesh _ mostly young women _ have been
mistreated and cheated of wages.
</P>
<P>
   Under settlements filed in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles,
Nordstrom, J. Crew, Cutter &AMP; Buck and Gymboree agreed to pay $1.25
million to reimburse workers for the ``recruitment fees'' that they
were charged in exchange for being hired. The money also will set
up a program of independent monitoring of factories operated by the
companies' contractors on the island.
</P>
<P>
   The fees _ which are charged by labor recruiters and average
$5,000 _ will be banned under the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Four firms that were about to be included in the lawsuits _ Polo
Ralph Lauren, Phillips-Van Heusen, Donna Karan and Chadwick's of
Boston _ signed an agreement in principle to join Monday's
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen other firms named in the suits, including Gap, Tommy
Hilfiger, Sears and J.C. Penney, did not take part in the
settlement and remain defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Saipan is one of the Northern Mariana Islands, a U.S.
commonwealth in the western Pacific that is exempt from American
labor, immigration and customs laws. As a result of these
exemptions, Saipan's billion-dollar-per-year garment industry is
allowed to stamp its clothing with ``Made in the USA'' tags.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Congress, led by Rep. George Miller, D-Calif.,
charge that the exemptions allow violations of international human
rights on U.S. soil. But reform legislation has been repeatedly
blocked by House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who praises
Saipan as a success story of free-market capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits were filed on behalf of the Saipan workers by the
Union of Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees and by
three nonprofit groups: Global Exchange and Asian Law Caucus of San
Francisco, and Sweatshop Watch of Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the lawsuits say the monitoring program, which will
be carried out by Verite, a nonprofit group based in Amherst,
Mass., will set a precedent because it will make unannounced visits
to factories and will carry out private interviews with workers in
their own languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement establishes a monitoring program with teeth,''
said Lora Jo Foo, president of Sweatshop Watch. ``It will make an
important difference in the lives of thousands of Saipan garment
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Bad Publicity Behind Move
</P>
<P>
   The companies that settled Monday did not accept liability in
the lawsuits. Company executives indicated that the negative
publicity surrounding the controversy was a big motive for
settling.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long, drawn-out legal battle didn't make good sense to us
even though we remain confident about our ability to successfully
defend ourselves in these lawsuits,'' said Erik Nordstrom,
co-president of Nordstrom. ``We feel these resources are better
spent elsewhere and could be used toward making a good-faith effort
to furthering our commitment to using vendors who comply with the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Gymboree CEO Gary White sought to downplay the importance of the
settlement. ``We have checked and double-checked our own monitoring
of vendors to assure ourselves that our manufacturing partners were
treating workers well. While we are comfortable with the processes
we had in place, we are pleased to support the greater safeguards
embodied in this agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Meyerhoff, a lawyer for the plaintiffs, said the
settlement will add pressure on Gap, the largest of the 13
remaining defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first domino for Saipan sweatshops,'' he said.
``There's no reason why the others could not agree to the same
terms. They now have a difficult choice _ whether to solve Saipan's
problems or be obstructionist and spend millions upon millions in
litigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
