 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2564 -- August 10, 1999  NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2564 - August 10, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
</P>
<P>
   us for availability in your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. IF WE ARE SERIOUS, WE DO SOMETHING ABOUT POVERTY
</P>
<P>
   By Eveline Herfkens, Hilde F. Johnson, Clare Short and
Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul
</P>
<P>
   From The International Herald Tribune
</P>
<P>
   The writers are, respectively, the Dutch minister for
development cooperation, the Norwegian minister for international
development and human rights, the British secretary of state for
international development and the German minister for development
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   2. WHY THE UNITED STATES SUPPORTS THE WAR ON DRUGS IN COLOMBIA
</P>
<P>
   by Madeleine K. Albright - New York Times Op-Ed
</P>
<P>
   Madeleine K. Albright, the U.S. Secretary of State, explains the
U.S. Policy in favor of helping the governemnt of Colombia fight
its war against drugs.
</P>
<P>
   3. KREMLIN GAMBLES ON PUTIN
</P>
<P>
   by Yevgeny Krasnikov - from The Moscow News Although Moscow's
latest Monday massacre - the firing of Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin and the entire Cabinet - was a shock in the West, for
several weeks now in Russia, the media have been citing the name of
Vladimir V. Putin, 46, as a new political favorite. Since Yevgeny
Primakov was abruptly dismissed as prime minister three months ago,
top Kremlin officials have been saying that Stepashin was destined
to become Yeltsin's successor. But Naina Yeltsin, the president's
wife, among others, has been actively trying to persuade Yeltsin to
choose Putin. Yevgeny Krasnikov is political correspondent for
Moscow News.
</P>
<P>
   4. ARSENIC for DESSERT? By Tamara Zlotnikova from The Moscow
News
</P>
<P>
   In six months, Russia is supposed to begin full-scale
destruction of its chemical weapons, according to the Treaty on the
Prohibition of the Development, Production, Stockpiling and Use of
Chemical Weapons and Their Destruction. But there is no money in
the treasury to do so. It was claimed that without the treaty,
Russia's international prestige would suffer and economic sanctions
would be slapped on us. If, however, it was ratified, supposedly
the international community would pick up much of the tab for the
destruction of our chemical weapons. That is not happening. Tamara
Zlotnikova is head of the Committee for Ecology in the State Duma
of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   5. EYE OF THE STORM
</P>
<P>
   by Jonathan S. Landreth and J.S. Greenberg from The New York
Times Magazine
</P>
<P>
   As the Chinese Government calls for his arrest, Li Hongzhi, the
exiled leader of the massive Falun Gong movement talks about living
in New York and watching politics and belief collide back home in
China.
</P>
<P>
   6. WHO KNOWS BEST ? -- THE EXPERTS OR THE PUBLIC ?
</P>
<P>
   by Timothy Noah from The New York Times Magazine
</P>
<P>
   The general populace is too fickle and too easily manipulated to
decide weighty public questions - that's what Walter Lippmann wrote
in `` Public Opinion, `` his 1922 book, when he was well on his way
to establish himself as journalism's pre-eminent mandarin. These
big questions ought to be handled instead by `` a specialized class
`` of experts working closely with top government officials,
Lippmann wrote. (Full-length article - 3,300 words - available on
request)
</P>
<P>
   7. DOWNSIZING THE POPE - WHY IS THIS POPE DIFFERENT FROM OTHER
POPES ?
</P>
<P>
   by Michael McGough from Slate
</P>
<P>
   In the early evening of Oct. 16, 1978, the newly elected Pope
John Paul II appeared on the balcony of St. Peter's Basilica and
told the crowd that he had accepted election even though `` I was
afraid in receiving the nomination. `` (Michael McGough is
editorial page editor of the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette)
</P>
<P>
   8. INCLUSIVE AMERICA, UNDER ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   by Gerald R. Ford - frtom The New York Times Op-Ed
</P>
<P>
   Of all the triumphs that have marked this as America's century -
breathtaking advances in science and technology, the
democratization of wealth and dispersal of political power in ways
hardly imaginable in 1899 - none is more inspiring, if incomplete,
than our pursuit of racial justice.
</P>
