<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYT clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; It was only 16 months ago that President Clinton toured Africa,
calling it ripe for renaissance. Since then, the number of Africa's
refugees has swollen by more than 5 million, to 8.1 million people.
Contributing heavily to that figure has been the conflict between
Eritrea and Ethiopia, where in three days alone more people died
than in the entire NATO operation in Kosovo. In a two-part series,
written by diplomatic correspondent John Connelly and photographed
by Dominic Chavez, the Globe explores the situation. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ERITREA-WAR-I (Tsorona, Eritrea) _ Welcome to the world's
biggest, bloodiest war, one rarely covered by the press. Welcome to
a place with deadlier fallout than Kosovo, where the world's aid
has dried up. By John Donnelly. (2 takes) PHOTOS: NYT101-103.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   ERITREA-WAR-II (Asmara, Eritrea) _ The war has ravaged an entire
nation, even far from the front. Almost every family can describe
the loss. By John Donnelly. 1600 words. PHOTOS: NYT104-106.
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS
designator and move under the International (i) category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1663 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ERITREA-WAR-I-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     08-10 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERITREA-WAR-I-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 TSORONA, Eritrea: ... a new nation.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Western diplomat based in Eritrea said expectations of many
African countries should be lowered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a new leadership in Africa who are fundamentally
different than the old leadership. They don't have their hands out
as much as the old did for aid, they're smarter, full of ideas of
where to take their countries,'' the diplomat said. ``But maybe
President Clinton comparing them to Michelangelo was a little far.
There needs to be a real maturation process that these new leaders
go through.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the diplomat said, ``it's not time to give up on the
`New Africa,' but there should be more critical thinking because
the challenges are incredible: epidemiologically, politically, with
nature, and providing food. We should put realistic time frames on
the goals.''
</P>
<P>
   But peace comes first.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, some progress has been made. Shaky peace
deals were struck in Sierra Leone, where, in one week in January,
rebels killed an estimated 3,000 to 4,000 civilians in the capital
of Freetown and sliced off the arms and legs of thousands more; and
in the Democratic Republic of Congo, where 10 countries and rebel
groups have taken the side of the government or the main rebel
faction, drawing in most of central Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, solutions remain elusive. The United States and
United Nations have both largely left it to African countries to
resolve neighborhood conflicts, but few leaders have effectively
filled the void.
</P>
<P>
   In Sudan, rebels just broke off peace negotiations with the
government, prolonging a war that has spanned two decades and
killed 2 million people. War has resumed in Angola, where 1.6
million people are displaced, and the United Nations has responded
by announcing a pullout of its peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   In Angola, combatants are laying new mine fields, after spending
years and tens of millions of dollars to clear them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia and Eritrea are another story. Here, the United States
has played an active role, at least compared to its involvement in
other African conflicts. Late last month, former national security
adviser Anthony Lake made his fourth trip in one year to the
capitals of both nations.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides took a small step toward settling the border issue in
late July, by agreeing in principle to pull back to positions held
prior to May 6, 1998. US officials say this round of diplomacy
represents the best chance for peace, which they hope will result
in the deployment of international peacekeepers and a negotiated
settlement on the border demarcation.
</P>
<P>
   American officials are especially eager to seal an agreement not
only to stop the killing, but also to prevent the conflict from
spreading. Already, Ethiopian troops are battling with Somalia
rebel fighters to the east, but more worrisome is that the
Ethiopian-Eritrean war could exacerbate the threat of famine in
north-central Ethiopia. Some 5 million Ethiopians are at risk, say
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Ending the war won't come easily, say analysts and people on the
front such as Abraham Ghebreab, a Tsarona-area commander for half
of his 39 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choice to end this is not ours,'' said Abraham, who
offered visitors a snack of popcorn and coffee in his hillside
lean-to during a late afternoon downpour. ``We are just waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he commands thousands of troops, Abraham bridles at a
suggestion that the front has become his second home. ``It doesn't
feel like home life,'' said Ghebreab, whose wife and three children
live in Asmara. ``I saw them last in January and I wish that
weren't so.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the war bears the attributes of a family feud with
a poisonous past. In the mid-1970s, the Eritrean People's
Liberation Front, led by Isaias, and Ethiopia's Tigray People's
Liberation Front, led by Meles, tried to overlook border and
ideological concerns in joining to overthrow the Menguistu regime
in Ethiopia in 1991. But along the way, they often had political
difficulties, especially when one side began critiquing the other's
vision of a state.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ethiopia's new leader, Meles, granted Eritrea
independence. In 1993, Isaias became president of the new Eritrean
nation, which had endured rule by Italy, Britain, and then Ethiopia
over the past century.
</P>
<P>
   Relations soured not long after Meles and Isaias took power. In
a series of border incidents in mid-1997, Ethiopian troops took a
small village in southwestern Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the skirmishes were kept quiet by both sides.
Unpublicized negotiations failed. The breaking point was reached
almost a year later, in May 1998, when Ethiopian forces killed at
least four Eritrean soldiers in the border town of Badme, a tiny
town that both countries claim.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea responded by sending a mechanized force into the
disputed town. Ethiopia and Western diplomats said that response
prompted the broader conflict. Ethiopia declared war, labeling
Eritrea the aggressor. Eritrea, trying to sway international
opinion, belatedly said that Ethiopia had been the aggressor back
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, the war exploded into the deadly border
battles. If the war continues, analysts expect additional huge
losses of life with the trading of only the tiniest clumps of land
from one army to the other. Eritrea, with only about 3.5 million
people, has sent an estimated 200,000 on or near the front lines,
where they have dug long trenches.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia, a country of 55 million, has sent an estimated 250,000
to 300,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   While both sides have spent tens of millions of dollars on
warplanes, heavy equipment, and small arms, any future fighting
will probably also involve Ethiopia's human wave attacks, which
were first used by the government's ancestors in 1896 to break
through Italian lines in what is now northern Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is war in the family,'' said Salih Booker, an Africa
specialist at the Council on Foreign Relations in Washington.
``Both sides misjudged the other side, and they are taking it out
harder on each other than they would anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eritrea-based Western diplomat used less diplomatic
language: ``They blundered into a stupid war over nothing and they
couldn't get out of it because of pigheadedness and history.''
</P>
<P>
   In Asmara, Yemina Gebreab, a senior political adviser to Isaias,
acknowledged in hindsight that the government's decision to keep
quiet Ethiopia's 1997 border incursions ``did hurt Eritrea. We
preferred to solve this problem among ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea's expectation, he said, was that Ethiopia would do the
same in May 1998, when Eritrean forces conducted the offensive.
``Going public was a breach of trust from the Ethiopian side; their
statement is what led to the war. Eritrea was behaving in a
responsible way by not publicizing the problem. You know, you can
publicize a problem and make it worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Yemina said he was guardedly optimistic about the prospects of
peace, largely because of the intensified international efforts.
``The United States is very seriously engaged, and for the first
time they are willing to be very forceful in their approach,'' he
said. Diplomats say US envoy Lake has made vague threats of
sanctions if warfare does not cease.
</P>
<P>
   But in Addis Ababa, government spokeswoman Selome Tadesse
expressed doubt on whether Eritrea wanted peace. ``The Eritrean
government has repeatedly worked to thwart and impede the peace
process in the past, and it cannot be expected to have suddenly had
a change of heart and be sincerely committed to peace,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the front line, Eritrean soldiers expressed a keen desire for
a settlement, as long as their Pennsylvania-size country doesn't
give up its land. It wasn't possible to hear the views of Ethiopian
soldiers, as Ethiopia declined to allow the Globe access to its
front line. While Eritrea recently reopened the border areas to
reporters, Ethiopia has allowed only a single group of Addis
Ababa-based journalists to go to the front lines since the war
began, saying the danger is too great.
</P>
<P>
   Now, much of the front is quiet, with the exception of periodic
mortar fire around the hilly Badme region.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides seem reluctant to fight during the rainy season,
which lasts through October, because of the difficulty of moving in
the mud.
</P>
<P>
   At Tsorona, that gives them time to think, about the war and
about that horrible battle in March. And about the graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any human being would feel sad about this situation, living on
a graveyard,'' said Jonas Mahari, 30, of Adikiey, in southern
Eritrea. ``But there's no other place to stay, because we must
defend our country.''
</P>
<P>
   As the rains keep gushing down, there is talk on the front line
about collecting more dirt to put over the exposed bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must rebury them,'' Jonas said. ``We can't live like
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ERITREA-WAR-II-ART-BO     08-10 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERITREA-WAR-II-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERITREA'S FUTURE MIRED IN BLOODSHED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos (NYT104-106) are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ASMARA, Eritrea _ From the American Bar, a sidewalk cafe on
Independence Avenue in this capital of lime-washed stucco and
bougainvillea gardens, the war front with Ethiopia is only 55 miles
away. It could be halfway around the world from the looks of things
on a recent night, as hundreds of people strolled the boulevard and
packed cafes to drink the delicious 25-cent Asmara Beer.
</P>
<P>
   But the bitter taste of war wasn't far. It was on everyone's
lips.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk about work in war factories, where people rebuilt
the tanks and heavy artillery the Ethiopians left behind in 1991,
at the end of a 30-year war. There were conversations about the
impossibility of planning a future with so much unresolved. And
there were those speaking about postwar life, and how Eritrea would
find it difficult to cope with the aftermath of what has become the
world's bloodiest war.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea, population 3.5 million, independent for less than a
decade, a country that is no larger than Pennsylvania, dearly wants
an end to its 15-month war with Ethiopia. For this embattled,
tightly stitched society, which some say bears similarities to the
nascent Israel of the 1950s, war has hurt every family. Peace, too,
is likely to usher in painful change.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the war gets over, there won't be the euphoria that there
was the last time, with independence,'' said Wayne Kessler, a
California native who worked here for the Peace Corps in the 1960s
and returned in 1995 to work on development projects. ``There will
be a sigh of relief, and there will be a taking stock of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Peace, said Kessler as he leaned forward at the American Bar,
could create a new group of leaders. ``The young people, this new
generation of fighters, will want to have more of a say in the
government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two years ago, no one would have predicted this.
Eritrea was a bright light in the Horn of Africa, a country just
stretching its legs, a tale so inspirational that National
Geographic in 1996 touted Eritrea's infancy.
</P>
<P>
   Now the hope for Eritrea is limited to ending the bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   The next few weeks will tell much about the future of the war,
and of the two countries. An Algerian envoy is expected to present
ideas on a cease-fire. Among diplomats, there are high expectations
that peace is close. Among Eritreans and Ethiopians, there is great
skepticism. Distrust reigns.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Associated Press reported that the Eritrean
government accepted the Organization of African Unity's plan for
ending the war, a government statement said. Eritrea pledged ``full
cooperation with the OAU and the United States in implementing the
. . . agreements,'' which include a framework agreement,
procedures, and technical arrangements, the AP reported.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, there is an air of sadness that hangs over
Asmara and throughout Eritrea, which a Western diplomat described
as a ``place so different from the rest of Africa.'' It was
difficult to gauge views from the Ethiopian side, as Ethiopia
declined to allow the Globe access to its front line.
</P>
<P>
   Eritreans, the Western diplomat said, ``were the Spartans of
Africa. Nobody really loves them. They are kind of aggressive, but
kind of puritanical as well. You can see that when you realize that
there's the complete absence of corruption here, that there's very
little crime as well. Eritrea as a nation really means something to
the people here. There's a strong sense of community values.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense is particularly strong during war, prompting Eritreans
of all stripes, for example, to switch greetings from a traditional
handshake to exchanging three taps on the right shoulder. Soldiers
started the salutation because they were carrying their guns and
did not want them to accidentally discharge during a handshake.
</P>
<P>
   About 200,000 people are deployed near the front, the percentage
equivalent of about 16 million Americans. Late last month, men age
41 to 50 were called in for military training. The government has
given no casualty figures, but diplomats and analysts estimate
between 7,000 and 15,000 dead. Ethiopia's casualties, say Western
diplomats, are probably about four times as large, from 30,000 to
60,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of common purpose is seen in how the country deals
with those who die during war. No one will express sympathy to the
families of the dead until the war is over. That was what they did
during the 30-year war with Ethiopia, and that is what they will do
now. No one interviewed questioned this. All said it was a matter
of not allowing the mourning to deter the country's purpose; the
country would mourn together later in one giant funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my obligation, not to say anything,'' said Natan
Gebremicael, 20, a medic who suffered shrapnel injuries in a border
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Natan and other soldiers said the battles have been ferocious,
with waves of Ethiopian troops charging at the Eritreans, a World
War I tactic that essentially guaranteed high casualties for a
chance at breaking through trenches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible actually,'' he said. ``An enemy is coming. You
have to defend. You're killing people, Ethiopians, who are not well
trained. Actually, it was terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he was anxious to get back to the war.
</P>
<P>
   His father, a 57-year-old English teacher, understood. He said
Eritreans must fight for their land as Israelis fought for theirs.
``Whenever the Arabs came to fight, the Israelis didn't hesitate.
They understand a lot about war, and Israel stands strong now. It
will be the same for Eritrea.''
</P>
<P>
   Independence came after more than a century of occupation. The
Italians ruled for a half-century, relinquishing the land after its
losses in World War II. The British took over for a decade and then
the Ethiopians assumed control. From 1961 to 1991, guerrilla
fighters battled the Ethiopians in a war that claimed 450,000
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, too soon, war runs Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the war is over, you cannot talk about the future. The
war is what is holding us up,'' said Massimo Guiseppe, 27, at the
American Bar on a recent night.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last seven or eight years, we have had a lot of change
economically and socially,'' said Medehanie Tarke, who works with
Massimo at a military base rebuilding old Ethiopian artillery.
``But now everyone is participating in the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Road projects have stopped. Eritrea's three Red Sea ports have
not been refurbished. New factories remain unopened. Foreign
investment has dried up. Tourists have stayed away.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, arms dealers flock to Asmara. Russian pilots have flown
in tons of weapons in unmarked planes. Cargo ships carry loads of
artillery into the port of Assab. And the government spent between
$120 million and $150 million on six fighter jets. Diplomats wonder
how one of the poorest countries in the world found the money. The
government says a portion, about $50 million in the past year, came
from expatriates' donations.
</P>
<P>
   While President Isaias Afwerki, the only president Eritrea has
known, retains great popularity, some Eritreans and Western
observers find fault with how his government operates with little
outside input. There is a high degree of secrecy here, with the
government expecting the country's new media voices to exercise
restraint in their criticisms. So far, they have.
</P>
<P>
   But when the war ends, questions are likely to emerge, analysts
say. There will be questions about how Eritrea and Ethiopia started
this war, which on the surface has been over land of little use.
Other questions concern the economy and whether the 200,000
fighters will have jobs upon their return. Another 200,000 people
were displaced by the war, and room will have to be made in Eritrea
for 60,000 people deported from Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists wonder about post-traumatic stress disorders for
soldiers who fought in battles that claimed thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is once the dust settles, how are they going to
deal with this?'' asked Dr. Tesfay Aradom, a Medford psychologist
and associate professor of social sciences at Roxbury Community
College. Tesfay traveled to the war front to talk with soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are conflicted by the situation,'' he said. ``I was
flabbergasted by the level of political sophistication that these
youngsters had. They all asked how this problem can be solved
politically. They know this war was partly unnecessary. At times,
they even hesitated to keep shooting. This was just killing people
like flies.''
</P>
<P>
   At the American Bar, the biggest fear that remains is of a war
without end.
</P>
<P>
   No one stated a belief that Ethiopia, with its 55 million
people, will win the war outright. But those at the cafe said
Ethiopians could fight for much longer, delaying Eritrea's bright
dreams and perhaps extinguishing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a time when people can't tolerate it anymore,''
said one young man, who asked not be identified. ``If we keep on
defending, defending, defending, the country collapses, more people
die, and what is there to come back for?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
