u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ERITREA-WAR-I-ART-2TA     08-10 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERITREA-WAR-I-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERITREA AND ETHIOPIA FIGHT A DEADLY FAMILY FEUD 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Photos (NYT101-103) are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TSORONA, Eritrea _ Hard summer rains fall every afternoon here
on the border with Ethiopia, turning terra cotta earth into mud and
eroding a mile-long embankment. The dirt washes away little by
little, and nature gives a glimpse of hell.
</P>
<P>
   There, in the 7-foot-high mound, a boot has emerged.
</P>
<P>
   There, fingers.
</P>
<P>
   There, a face without eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The unspeakable happened here.
</P>
<P>
   It was a battle with tactics resurrected from World War I, as
wave upon wave of Ethiopian soldiers charged the trenches of their
Eritrean neighbors, only to die in mid-stride.
</P>
<P>
   Along this 1-mile stretch, more people were killed in three days
in March than in 78 days of fighting throughall of Kosovo. The
fallen formed a mass grave here that dwarfs any unearthed in the
Balkans over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   This, sadly, symbolizes the state of Africa at the end of the
millennium, a continent full of aspirations, new leadership, and
emerging democracies, but one that remains trigger-happy and that
tumbles into conflicts at frightening speed, often with the West
unable, or too disengaged, to broker a truce.
</P>
<P>
   It was only 16 months ago that President Clinton toured Africa
and called it ripe for renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Since that visit, the number of Africa's refugees has swollen by
more than 5 million, to 8.1 million people. Africa has more armed
conflicts than any other continent, with 11 large wars raging.
</P>
<P>
   The war here, in many ways a simple family feud between two
historically interlinked groups contesting a sparsely populated
620-mile frontier, has nonetheless claimed tens of thousands of
lives over the past 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   There is some hope for a negotiated cease-fire in the coming
weeks, as a US-backed initiative is being presented to both sides.
But both Eritrea and Ethiopia believe the process will be drawn
out, leaving ample time for new difficulties that could lead again
to violence.
</P>
<P>
   As the envoys shuttled between Addis Ababa and Asmara recently,
Birikhti Weldegergish, a slender 21-year-old Eritrean soldier
wearing a long cotton skirt and a camouflage shirt, stood near the
mass grave on the Tsorona front and quietly spoke about what had
happened in the epic battle.
</P>
<P>
   For three days and nights beginning March 14, she and other
soldiers said, the Ethiopians charged at Eritrean positions on the
disputed border, first from behind the cover of tanks and then in
the open when missiles disabled the tanks. Eritrean mortars then
blew up hundreds of soldiers, land mines sent hundreds more flying
in the air like stunt actors and Birikhti and her fellow soldiers
shot many of the rest from their trenches.
</P>
<P>
   It was disorientingly easy to kill, she recalled, like a target
practice that wouldn't end. They shot until their Kalishnikov
rifles and machine guns grew scorchingly hot, burning skin off
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't understand the way the Ethiopians came in at us,'' she
said, the muscles under her left eye twitching nervously as she
spoke. ``They were coming like ants.''
</P>
<P>
   When the shooting was over, Birikhti looked at the field.
</P>
<P>
   Only there was no field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no land to step on,'' she said. ``It was all dead
bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the battle, Eritrean soldiers removed identity
papers from the dead, collected rifles and ammunition, piled the
bodies behind the trenches and bulldozed dirt over them. Eritrea
says 10,000 soldiers were killed. Ethiopia scoffs at the number,
suggesting hundreds were killed. Western diplomats in both nations
and military analysts in Washington lean toward the higher,
Eritrean figure.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the only sure fact is the Eritrean soldiers eat, sleep,
talk and play checkers with Coca-Cola bottletops along this front
line, a front that's a mass grave, a grave that opens further with
each day's rain, a rain that unlocks the scent of old death. The
scent is inhaled with every breath of the living, the living living
in hell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the world's bloodiest war.
</P>
<P>
   It is a war senseless to most outsiders. Analysts argue over why
it began: Some say it's over land that is of little value; others
call it a fight for sovereignty; still others point to
long-simmering problems between the countries' governments and the
two leaders, distant cousins who each owe the other for being in
power in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   It is often called the world's forgotten war, waged in obscurity
because reporters have had little access to the fighting, diplomats
have been forbidden to go to the front lines, and, for at least a
portion of it, the West was obsessed with Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Geography and racism are also to blame. ``We sadly accept a
level of violence in Africa,'' said former US Agency for
International Development chief J. Brian Atwood, ``that we wouldn't
accept in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The fatigues-clad soldiers here on the front, baking flatbread
amid the gunfire, have a blunter explanation. ``The international
organizations have forgotten us. There has been incredible
bloodshed and destruction here . . . someone should have
interfered,'' said Tsegaye Teame, 28.
</P>
<P>
   World leaders, much like Rip van Winkle in their reawakening to
a world beyond Pristina, have recently begun to focus on the
multiple wars and crises in Africa, although still not promising
much.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, in a speech on Africa
last month, acknowledged that the West has been ``able to do far
more to end conflicts in Europe than in Africa.'' She said it was a
partly a matter of stronger regional organizations in Europe, but
added, ``That is no excuse for disengaging or giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the world's tragically late response to the genocide
in Rwanda in 1994, a slaughter that killed more than 500,000
people, Albright said, ``We must do all we can now to see that such
a nightmare is never repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Washington has faced new hurdles in the region in the
year since US embassies in Kenya and Tanzania were bombed by an
Islamic extremist. Africa has borne the brunt of the 70 US
diplomatic missions closed temporarily in the past 12 months
because of security concerns, an issue that was heightened on
Thursday when the State Department warned all Americans abroad of
possible attacks related to the anniversary of the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   In recent reports, the United Nations and the State Department
highlighted the enormity of the problems on the continent: the 11
major conflicts; the threat of famine for millions in Ethiopia,
Somalia, and Sudan; the millions of refugees; and the frenzy of
small weapons sales, with some AK-47s selling for as little as $6
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   All that doesn't even touch the epidemic of AIDS in Sub-Saharan
Africa, including Zimbabwe, where 4 out of every 10 adults are
reportedly infected with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   From the US perspective, the explosion of conflict in Africa is
especially troubling as it follows Washington's effort last year to
link the continent with the global economy and promote emerging
democracies.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his 11-day trip to Africa, his longest ever outside
the United States as president, Clinton told Africans that he
wanted to introduce America to a ``new Africa _ an Africa whose
political and economic accomplishments grow more impressive each
month.''
</P>
<P>
   He spotlighted a region with impressive mineral resources, labor
possibilities, and huge economic potential.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited several African leaders as part of the continent's
new hope, including Isaias Afwerki of Eritrea, Meles Zenawi of
Ethiopia, Yoweri Museveni of Uganda, and Paul Kagame of Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Today all four nations are involved in war. Eritrea and Ethiopia
are shooting at each other, and Uganda and Rwanda are sending arms
and troops to rebel groups in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   The conflicts each have their own complex roots, but diplomats
and analysts say one common theme is that independence movements
filled the vacuum of receding superpowers after the Cold War.
Several analysts said many of the ascendant leaders believe the
only way to resolve certain political or economic problems is
through force.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the end of the Cold War, the lid has come off on a lot of
the instability,'' speeding up moves to sort through new
leadership, said a longtime Africa watcher, Dan Connell, a
Gloucester resident and author of ``Against All Odds: A Chronicle
of the Eritrean Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Connell said, ``African countries are making decisions
on their own immediate needs rather than their colonial masters. It
makes for really chaotic politics sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Connell compared Africa today with Europe in its bloody 16th and
17th centuries. Others compare the current Ethiopian-Eritrean
battle to the War of 1812 between the United States and Britain, a
war fought partly because a colonial master never fully reconciled
itself to the ceding of territory to a new nation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
