<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; It was only 16 months ago that President Clinton toured Africa,
calling it ripe for renaissance. Since then, the number of Africa's
refugees has swollen by more than 5 million, to 8.1 million people.
Contributing heavily to that figure has been the conflict between
Eritrea and Ethiopia, where in three days alone more people died
than in the entire NATO operation in Kosovo. In a two-part series,
written by diplomatic correspondent John Connelly and photographed
by Dominic Chavez, the Globe explores the situation. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ERITREA-WAR-I (Tsorona, Eritrea) _ Welcome to the world's
biggest, bloodiest war, one rarely covered by the press. Welcome to
a place with deadlier fallout than Kosovo, where the world's aid
has dried up. By John Donnelly. (2 takes) PHOTOS: NYT101-103.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   ERITREA-WAR-II (Asmara, Eritrea) _ The war has ravaged an entire
nation, even far from the front. Almost every family can describe
the loss. By John Donnelly. 1600 words. PHOTOS: NYT104-106.
