<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawn beauty is in the eye of the neighbor
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ A 51-year-old artist who shapes colorful
sculptures from
</P>
<P>
   discarded materials such as furniture, lamps, and kitchenware,
has raised the
</P>
<P>
   hackles of her less creative neighbors in an upscale bedroom
community outside
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland by painting an old clawfoot bathtub green, planting it
with red poppies, yellow and peach day lilies and mountain sage _
and putting it in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   The horrified neighbors set up a grumble that was heard in City
Hall. In response to duty's call, the mayor made the following
statement: ``I maintain that you have to have certain standards.
Today it's a bathtub. Tomorrow it could be toilets.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice mayor agreed: ``I don't want a bathtub in the front
yard. I just don't think it looks great.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, in a daring move to protect the aesthetics of the
surrounding
</P>
<P>
   high-dollar landscape as well as the delicate sensibilities of
the neighbors, the City Council has amended a section of the
building code now making it unlawful to put out-of-use stuff like
bathtubs and toilets in front yards.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining about the folks we live next door to, or across the
street from is, of course, an inalienable right that can probably
be traced back to our cave dwelling days. Norman Neanderthal comes
home from work and listens to his wife Buffy complain because the
cavetrash across the gulch have just painted their cavern purple.
And bought an ugly dog. Buffy worries about property values. Norman
is afraid the undesirable's son will want to marry his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   And there you have it. Neighborhood unrest in the Pleistocene
age.
</P>
<P>
   It happened where I lived once, when I was a little girl. My
mother started it.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the '40s, south Florida was awash in flamingoes. Folks
had them everywhere _ standing on one leg next to the jasmine,
guarding a mildewed
</P>
<P>
   birdbath. Mr. Morton, our across-the-street neighbor and my
father's fishing
</P>
<P>
   buddy, had one on his screen door. It was a brightly-painted
metal thing that
</P>
<P>
   covered most of the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tacky,'' my mother decreed. ``Ugly bird,'' Daddy agreed. A
couple of weeks
</P>
<P>
   after the bird went up my mother cracked down. The bird had to
go. My father
</P>
<P>
   told her is was not their business what people hung on their
screen doors and she was to get over it. Mother insisted it hurt
her eyes. Daddy told her not to look at it.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, just before her Sunday school group was to meet in
our living room, Mother dispatched my father to tell his old friend
to ditch the bird. Daddy ambled across the street, had a talk with
Mort, and reported a successful mission to my mother. Told her not
to worry.
</P>
<P>
   By morning the flamingo had flown and Mr. Mort was working in
his front yard lily pond. Mother sighed her relief. Daddy said
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Early evening, just moments before the ladies were due to
arrive, Daddy excused himself and went outside. Mother fussed with
the teacups and issued an
</P>
<P>
   ultimatum _ either I bathed and put on a clean dress or I was
banished to my room for the duration. Since neither idea appealed
to me, I sneaked out the back door while Mother was busy pouring
cashews in a cut-glass bowl. I found my
</P>
<P>
   father and Mr. Mort in lawn chairs beside the lily pond. They
looked a little sheepish. It didn't take long to see why.
</P>
<P>
   Not 20 yards from where the Sunday school ladies would be
parking their Packards, Mr. Mort had installed a stone cherub
incessantly relieving itself in his lily pond.
</P>
<P>
   The ladies were not amused and Mother had a sinking spell that
lasted 14 years until Mr. Mort moved to Kissimmee and took his
``obscene trash'' (my mother's label) with him. Daddy missed his
fishing buddy and the neighborhood kids missed Sprinkles, which is
what we had dubbed the leaky babe.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's hope for the artist's bathtub. Maybe they'll plumb
it, hang a shower curtain around it and make it legal by putting it
``back in use.'' Maybe later they could add a toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail:320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
