<HEADER>
A1676 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAMB-COLUMN11-COX     08-10 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMB-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Discussion should replace dispute in health care debate
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ On both ends of the political spectrum, people
are saying the problem with the health care debate is that it's
about how to regulate managed care instead of how to replace it.
Lawmakers are arguing over whether HMOs should be liable in
lawsuits when they ought to be asking whether managed care should
be viable.
</P>
<P>
   The left and the right each have better ideas. They even have a
lot in common, but our Crossfire culture sadly encourages them to
get in each other's faces instead of putting their heads together.
</P>
<P>
   One premise they share is that employers should not buy most of
the private health care in this country, using their money and
other people's. The government finances health care by not taxing
the money employers spend on it. Patients finance health care not
only by paying premiums, deductibles and coinsurance, but also by
subsidizing managed care when they pay list price for, say,
prescriptions that HMO members get at discount.
</P>
<P>
   And employers, patients and the government all pay for the
nearly one in every five Americans younger than 65 without health
coverage _ 44 million and growing.
</P>
<P>
   In the liberal national health care proposals, the government
would control that money and guarantee every American basic
coverage for preventive and emergency care and treatment for
illness or injury. As in Germany, the coverage could be
administered by private insurers, says Vernellia Randall, a
University of Dayton law professor who was a nurse for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only two developed nations in the world _ the United States
and South Africa _ do not provide some sort of national health care
system,'' says Randall, who began studying the issue on a White
House advisory group in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In the conservative proposals, government tax breaks would
divert all the money now spent on health care to the patients, who
then would set up medical savings accounts (MSAs) to pay for
ordinary health care and insurance against catastrophic costs. They
could buy a basic plan or the health care equivalent of all the
premium channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is control,'' says Dr. David Westbrock, who has
run for Congress twice as a Montgomery County Republican. ``I've
had a lot of HMO executives tell me, `The patients need us
controlling their health care to tell them how to judge quality.'
``
</P>
<P>
   The left wants universal coverage. The right wants patients to
choose their own health care. These are not mutually exclusive
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals have significant conflicts, certainly. Liberals
question the wisdom of giving poor people the chance to spend
dollars meant for health care on other things, whether it's food or
street drugs. Conservatives are put off by another arm of
paternalistic government.
</P>
<P>
   But they agree on taking employers out of the system and taking
medical decisions away from insurers. They agree the current system
wastes money because it's expensive both to manage health care and
to treat the uninsured in emergency rooms and surgical suites
instead of preventing their crises. They agree that health care is
now rationed to people with the most money and the largest
employers in the most populous counties.
</P>
<P>
   They also agree on the need to remove both the old economic
incentives for too many tests and procedures and managed care's
incentives for too few.
</P>
<P>
   Randall isn't suggesting Clintonesque health reform that would
confine everyone to an HMO. Far from it, she says, ``When you have
a system run by private enterprises whose ultimate responsibility
is to the stockholder, at some point they have to cut into
necessary services in order to increase stockholders' profits.''
</P>
<P>
   If patients had the money to buy their own health care,
Westbrock says the free market would also tilt that responsibility
toward the patients. But he's not suggesting a market so unfettered
that it would abandon the sickest and poorest. He says it's
terrible that his diabetic patients can't get health coverage
unless they work for big employers. He says those fortunate enough
to be healthy should be happy to subsidize the sicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would put a surcharge on the healthy,'' he says. ``Those
numbers have been worked out and they're very attainable.''
</P>
<P>
   Both ideas would improve health care at lower costs. Too bad the
parties can't discuss them instead of merely disputing them.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
