<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    College lessons: Set good spending habits now
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Spending is easy.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part is managing your spending. That takes both
education and maturity. If truth were known, I'm still working on
both.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, I understand why money management raises problems for
college students, especially freshmen who are on their own for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   For their families, the challenge is turning potential problems
into part of the learning experience. The process is nothing fancy.
Mainly it deals with budgeting, controlling credit card spending
and _ most important _ building a one-adult-to-another dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing is talk to your students about money,'' says
Nancy McDuff, the University of Georgia's undergraduate admissions
director. ``You don't make it a taboo topic, so a student comes to
you only when there's a crisis. Let them know you're helping them
but that you expect them to act as adults.''
</P>
<P>
   For this year's freshmen, the time is now. If you want to teach,
jump in before the adventures of college start and while you can
still get your youngster's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Budgeting is the first big step. Parents need to sit down with
their child to draw up a realistic spending plan.
</P>
<P>
   You want your freshman to know how much he or she will have to
spend and what responsibilities go with it.
</P>
<P>
   It's best to make up a detailed budget, with spending targets
both for necessities _ laundry and school supplies, for instance _
and for amenities such as movies and pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, it's easier to control your spending if you know the
limits for each category.
</P>
<P>
   Parents may know the total they can put out for personal
spending. Even so, it's better to work it out item by item, rather
than starting with the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Many colleges provide helpful estimates of the year's expenses,
including personal spending as well as tuition, fees and room and
board. At UGA, the recommendation is $1,800 for the school year, or
$200 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet there are students who can do it cheaper, and lots of
students who can do it more expensively,'' McDuff said. ``But it's
a good starting point.''
</P>
<P>
   You're not through yet. At your budget meeting, the family needs
to schedule a budget review. Make it a month or more into the
school year, perhaps a part of your student's first trip home.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, urge your freshman to keep a spending diary. A
detailed record of actual spending will make it possible to see if
your spending limits are realistic. Make it clear the review is
neither snoopy nor punitive.
</P>
<P>
   Credit management is the second major step.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and credit card companies want to be the first to issue
their credit cards to your children. The companies hope those new
customers will stick with them for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   But easy credit is a tremendous temptation to all of us. Buying
stuff with plastic doesn't seem real. It's more like play money.
</P>
<P>
   One way to inculcate responsibility is to sanction your
freshman's first credit card. Setting up a joint account allows
parents to monitor the use of the card and lets the student know
that he or she really is answerable to somebody.
</P>
<P>
   The family should establish in advance what the card can be used
for. Your list might include textbooks and airfare to come home at
Christmas, for example, but not restaurant meals or spring break.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide the card can be used in emergencies, take time to
define what an emergency is. Another possibility is to use a debit
card. Parents or students can deposit a given amount in the bank.
The user can't charge any more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, keep your lines of communication open and try to
help your student along. ``College is all about education,'' McDuff
pointed out. ``Students spend about 25 percent of their time in the
classroom, but they learn all the time. Parents should be part of
that process.''
</P>
<P>
   DOING IT RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't plunk down a full semester's spending money at one time.
It's too hard to stretch that out over several months.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you fear your student will scrimp on things like textbooks
or calling home, put them in a separate budget category. Let your
student know you will cover or reimburse those expenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ If this is your student's first checking account, make sure he
or she knows how to write checks and balance a checkbook. Don't
forget the part about recording ATM withdrawals in your checkbook.
If you get a balance from the ATM, be sure to take into account
outstanding checks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put aside some money to set up your student's first dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stay cool. You made mistakes, and so will your children. As
you work them out, go for learning rather than discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
