A1678 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLIO-PEOPLE11-COX     08-10 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLIO-PEOPLE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conference aims to educate `polio people' on overcoming health
challenges
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When she started falling down unexpectedly as an
adult, Shirlee Sussman wrote it off to the unsteady way she walked
on the side of her foot. She had, after all, come down with polio
when she was 2. Her left leg never grew to the size of her right
leg, and she always limped.
</P>
<P>
   She had no idea that polio, tragic enough when the virus
strikes, often comes back to cripple its victims again later in
life. Neither did the doctors she saw in the 1960s and '70s, even
as her pain level gradually grew and her fatigue threshold
gradually fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to the doctor and they tell you, 'There's no reason for
you to be falling. Maybe you need to go see a psychiatrist,' ''
Sussman says. ``That's very prevalent in the post-polio community,
being told you're a nut case.''
</P>
<P>
   The mystery was unraveled in the early 1980s by Dr. Lauro
Halstead, himself a polio survivor whose coordination seemed to be
deteriorating. ``I thought of myself as cured,'' Halstead said, but
his research showed the experiences of polio people 30 to 40 years
after their infection was neither imaginary nor coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   Halstead coined the term post-polio syndrome, characterized by
progressive muscle weakness, debilitating fatigue and pain,
especially in joints and muscles. To Sussman, her diagnosis at 49
was a relief, finally explaining all those symptoms and identifying
her new challenge to overcome. But even now, she says, many people
who've had polio still don't understand what's happening to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary purpose of this conference is to educate them,
teach them exactly what did happen when they got polio,'' says
Sussman, now 65 and chairwoman of the Ohio Polio Network's biannual
post-polio conference Aug. 21 in Dayton. The conference is for
anyone who has had polio, whether or not they have been diagnosed
with post-polio syndrome, and their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers will talk about the syndrome, aging, exercise, massage
and anger management. ``There's a lot of anger involved,'' Sussman
says, ``because there's grief any time you have to give up
something, whether it's a loved one or part of your being.'' There
also is a lot of denial, she says, recalling many calls ``from
people who really don't want to admit that this is in fact what's
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Polio people are an unusually driven population, says
Halstead, who directs the post-polio program at the National
Rehabilitation Hospital in Washington. His data shows they average
more education than the general population, marry and raise
families at the same rate and have an employment rate four times
greater than that of other disabled people. Generally reluctant to
admit any weakness, they call themselves simply ``polio people'' or
``polios'' instead of using the word victim or survivor.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Most of us overused our muscles and kind of pretended we
never had any limitations,'' Sussman says. ``We were so determined
to be just like everybody else, to our detriment later on.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The cause of post-polio syndrome is not known for sure, but
the accepted theory is that people overcoming paralytic polio
simply wear themselves out in compensating for their disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sussman, for example, was paralyzed below the waist, but after
she reached her maximum recovery at the age of 8, she thought
nothing of walking the mile and a half each way to school with all
her friends. But however robust she acted, polio had destroyed many
of her motor neurons, and the remaining ones had to work much
harder to operate her muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neighboring nerve cells that took over for those killed by
the virus are now wearing out,'' says Dr. Jane Wootton, who directs
a nationally renowned polio clinic in Richmond, Va., and will speak
at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Sussman compares the pain with that of an amputee who still
feels the limb he has lost, because polio has killed the nerves
where she is hurting. ``My hips are always in pain,'' she says, as
are her shoulders and neck and the muscles that control both her
feet and ankles, from below the knee on down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned to pace myself. That is super-important,'' says
Sussman, who still runs her business brokering materials for paper
manufacturers from home with her husband. ``If you do too much
today, for the next three or four days you're going to pay for it
dearly because you'll have more pain and be so tired.''
</P>
<P>
   There's little treatment for PPS besides rest and light
exercise, although Wootton says symptoms can be eased by a variety
of professionals including therapists, orthotists, counselors,
nutritionists and clergy. Many post-polios diagnose themselves, but
Sussman says it's important to get a physician's diagnosis in order
to establish the patient's need for exercise and other help.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is there are so few doctors with dedicated polio
specialties. She knows of none in the Dayton area but one in
Cincinnati. Without that specialty, she says, ``There's really a
lack of understanding and knowledge of what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Sussman could never run and play with other kids and was sad
that she couldn't wear high heels, but she learned to dance and
could excel with the best of them in academics and music.
Successful in business, the Northmont Rotarian became the first
woman to lead the Ohio Chamber of Commerce's small business
council. ``Whenever I talk to anybody I went to high school with,
they say, `We just didn't notice.' ''
</P>
<P>
   People with polio learned it had to be that way. It's never been
easy for the disabled to fit in, and polio in particular was a
national nightmare until the Sabin and Salk vaccines in 1955 and
1961 all but ended it in this country. It struck 50,000 Americans
in 1952 alone, killing nearly one in eight, and estimates range
from 640,000 to 1.6 million living Americans who have had polio.
Between 40 percent and 75 percent of them develop PPS, which is
more than 250,000 at the low end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's made me very different than my three brothers,'' Sussman
says. ``Much more accepting of the things in my life, and I don't
take them as obstacles. They're challenges to be overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason polio people have higher rates of high blood
pressure, for example, is even just walking is stressful. Sussman
wasn't aware until a post-polio doctor pointed it out that she
always clenched her fist when she walked. ``It takes total
concentration,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She can't walk for long anymore, but she uses a scooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes me as mobile as anybody else,'' Sussman says. ``I'm
still more active than many of my friends the same age who never
had polio.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
