<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-SAAB11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pet safety takes front seat at Saab
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not even Saabophiles, loyalist lot that they are, can
resist the temptation to pun when talking about the Swedish
automaker's latest step in auto safety: They're dogging it.
</P>
<P>
   That's right _ safety belts, restraints and other accessories
designed to provide safer and more comfortable travel for dogs and
their masters who own the '99 Saab 9-5 front-wheel-drive wagon.
</P>
<P>
   They work, too. Or at least they restrained the frequently
rambunctious Bud and Charlie, a mutually devoted pair of mostly Lab
companions, during testing of a 9-5 wagon. Bud, the older, seemed
happily restrained in the cargo area, while Charles, a hyper
class-clown type, actually remained sedately tethered to a
rear-seat safety belt. Neither was slipping and sliding the way
dogs frequently do during starts, turns and stops.
</P>
<P>
   As for the wagon itself, a nimble 3,700-pounder that can handle
five humans and 37 cubic feet of cargo in the rear, it's a very
nonwagon sort of vehicle to drive. Between its turbocharged
170-horsepower engine and sporting suspension, it accelerates
quickly, is responsive at speed and rides quite nicely.
</P>
<P>
   With the only options _ excluding the doggie equipment _ being
the four-speed automatic transmission and several seat choices, the
9-5 wagon's standard equipment seems to justify the base price of
$31,850 (it totaled $36,170, plus about $250 for dog accessories).
</P>
<P>
   Saab, which seems to stage a test crash every other business day
in the interest of safety, could hardly have picked a more
opportune time to introduce the dog safety items. Author Stephen
King's injuries, suffered earlier this year when an unruly
Rottweiler caused its owner/driver to swerve and strike the
strolling King, set off a flurry of interest in protecting pets and
pedestrians, too.
</P>
<P>
   Saab's catalog, which offers clothing and sports gear as well as
auto accessories, devotes four pages to the dogs. For safety,
there's a $24.95 harness, a $19.95 belt for seat-riding dogs, a
$49.95 leash that restrains dogs in the rear, and a $69.95 carrier
for smaller dogs and cats that will also fit under airplane seats.
</P>
<P>
   That, as usual, is not the only mention of aircraft in analyzing
Saab vehicles. Its early involvement with aviation helps account
for the true cockpit styling of the 9-3 and 9-5 vehicles. The
dual-cockpit front gives a secure feeling, while the instruments
and controls are readily available.
</P>
<P>
   Saab contends that its console-mounted ignition switch makes
sense because operating it leaves the driver's hand close to the
shift selector. Logical, yes, but that doesn't mean it's easy to
reprogram drivers used to traditionally located ignitions.
</P>
<P>
   Get behind the wheel, and Saab's thoughtfulness is readily
apparent in, among other things, convenient drink holders, a
wide-angle mirror on the passenger side, a clip on the lower left
windshield to hold parking permits or other documents, and an
optional sliding rear floor that facilitates tailgating.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom-liners will find it difficult to fault Saab for the
interior, despite the forever-quirky exterior styling. But how can
anyone possibly fault an automaker that wants to make a dog's life
even better and safer?
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Saab 9-5 front-wheel-drive wagon
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $36,170 (base: $31,850)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 2.3-liter turbocharged four-cylinder engine (170
horsepower), optional four-speed automatic transmission with
normal, sport and winter modes
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual-front air bags, driver and front passenger
side/head air bags, spring-loaded anti-whiplash front seats, power
anti-lock disc brakes, three-point belts at all seats,
semiautomatic height adjustment for outboard seats, wide-angle
passenger side mirror, daytime running lights
</P>
<P>
   Other options on test vehicle: leather interior, $1,350; heated
and fan-ventilated front seats and heated rear seats, $520;
integrated child booster seat, $300;dealer-installed sliding load
floor, $425
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 19 mpg city; 26 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
