r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAPPY11-COX     08-10 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAPPY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    She's happy as a clam _ and some say half-baked
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ During the past year of abuse, derision and
mockery, Pam Johnson has heard it all: That she's an agent of the
religious right or, worse, Hallmark cards. That's she's delusional,
or starting a cult. Ann Landers and comedian Richard Lewis, who
would seem to have nothing whatsoever in common, have in Johnson a
shared enemy.
</P>
<P>
   All this happened because a year ago Sunday _ on 8/8/98 _ Pam
Johnson of suburban Dallas came out of the happiness closet after
33 years.
</P>
<P>
   No more fear, no more denial, no more secrets. She proclaimed
herself aggressively, unapologetically happy and hoped you were the
same. And if you were, she hoped you would talk about it, that you
would not keep your happiness under a basket.
</P>
<P>
   She started the Secret Society of Happy People, mounted a
campaign to declare Aug. 8 National Admit You're Happy Day and soon
found herself the most despised woman in America.
</P>
<P>
   Because really, deep down, don't you hate happy people? Isn't it
time to rewrite that children's song? Stop clapping your hands. If
you're happy and you know it, KEEP IT TO YOURSELF.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say that, in this age of global media and
``woundology'' (Johnson's term) in which recovery is not a process
but an industry, this sales rep from Coppell hit a nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people call and yell and hang up on you,'' she said.
``You say the word 'happy' to them, and they get antagonistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's an antagonistic July 26 posting from www.sohp.com, the
society's Web site. The subject line says, ``YOU PEOPLE NEED TO GET
A LIFE,'' but with a very bad, very descriptive word between ``a''
and ``life'':
</P>
<P>
   ``GET REAL NO PERSON IN THEIR RIGHT MIND IS GOING TO MAKE A
HAPPY DAY IF THEY DO THEY SHOULD BE SENT TO WORK IN A REAL JOB,
WHERE EVERYTHING DOESN'T GO THE WAY YOU WANT IT TO. HAPPY DAY IS
THE STUPIDEST IDEA EVER.''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, you're much more likely to find subject lines that
say things like, ``I LOVE KITTY CATS!!!!!!!'' But the vehemence of
the posting is noteworthy, even in the frequently overheated medium
of of Web message boards.
</P>
<P>
   The real trouble began around last Thanksgiving, when Johnson
went to war in the name of happiness against no less than Landers.
The advice columnist ran a reader's letter (followed by her own
supportive response) begging friends and family to spare them their
``ghastly'' holiday letters about how happy and well they were.
Johnson fired off a response and courted print and broadcast
coverage of the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   In March, aiming to spread the word about her proposed happy
day, Johnson went on the ABC chat show ``Politically Incorrect,''
only to get a verbal thumping from comedian Lewis and guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Maher and the guests were pretty much vicious,'' said
John Propst, a card-carrying happy person from Early, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   From there, things got more and more surreal. Johnson's efforts
to get each of the nation's governors to endorse happiness as a
lifestyle choice produced mixed results. Eighteen have issued
official proclamations. New York Gov. George Pataki has no official
position on happiness, Johnson gleefully reported.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, on the other hand, came out swinging
for happiness. In his official proclamation, Bush notes everything
from the state's ``robust and dynamic economy'' (for which he can
implicitly take credit) to Lance Armstrong's win in the Tour de
France (in which his contribution was more vague) as reasons for
Texans to be happy. ``I urge all Texans to acknowledge the effects
of positive communications and to talk about the happy events and
moments in their lives,'' Bush wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps getting ahead of himself just a bit, Bush proclaimed
Sunday ``National Admit You Are Happy'' day.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spoilsport brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, declined to
issue a similar proclamation, but he may be less happy since his
wife, Columba, was caught for not declaring $19,000 worth of
Parisian loot to U.S. Customs recently.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reasons for playing along or not, the way Johnson sees
it, the Zeitgeist has made it politically correct to have wounds
and plain rude to be happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't meant to be this big emotional debate, like the
governors not knowing if they should sign the proclamation or
not,'' she said. ``I couldn't have scripted that; I couldn't have
scripted the funny things that have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny things like being accused of being a front for Jerry
Falwell or his like. Yes, there is a spiritual element to some of
the message board's postings, but Johnson says members range from
Christian to Wiccan.
</P>
<P>
   As for being a tool of the greeting card industry: ``Hallmark
won't even talk to me.''
</P>
<P>
   About 800 happy soldiers have joined the cause, waging a
grass-roots happy revolution. The Web site has had more than
140,000 hits, and Johnson feels as though she's done at least that
many interviews.
</P>
<P>
   She is tired. Tired, but happy.
</P>
<P>
   And she has interviews beginning at 7 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, happy day.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Beach writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: pbeach(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
