<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1689 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-MECHANIC11-COX     08-10 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Always warm up car before emissions test
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's time I answered some of your letters, which have
been accumulating over the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   First, I receive many requests for copies of past articles, many
of them accompanied by stamped, self-addressed envelopes. I'm not
ignoring you.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, when I want to read my column, I have to buy
a Friday paper just like everyone else. I don't have a copy machine
or fax, thus I have no way to forward the published columns myself.
However, the AJC provides this service to readers for a nominal
fee. Please call 404-526-5668 and save your stamps.
</P>
<P>
   On to the mailbag:
</P>
<P>
   John Schiereck and Mary Sherman e-mailed questions and comments
pertaining to emissions tests.
</P>
<P>
   John writes, ``I have a 1987 Buick that failed the emissions
test. COCarbon monoxide was twice the acceptable level. I always
use 93 octane fuel because the poor old girl knocks and pings with
anything less. Anyway, I put about $2 of cheap gas (87 octane) in
an empty tank and had it retested. She passes with flying colors.
The carbon monoxide was one-tenth of the acceptable level. Can you
explain why?''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Sherman writes, ``You failed to mention that if the engine
is cold, it will fail the emission test no matter the age or
condition of the car. You should have advised: Drive the car for 30
or more minutes and have it retested before you spend another dime
on a book or mechanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary is absolutely right. As I've advised in several previous
emissions columns, your vehicle should be driven, preferably at
highway speed, before getting in the test lane. This ensures that
the vehicle's engine computer _ assuming the rest of the system is
working correctly _ has had ample time to take control of things.
</P>
<P>
   A cold engine, especially with older vehicles, is a prime
candidate for a carbon monoxide failure. This could be the reason
for John's first failure.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect this more than the change in fuel octane. That alone
would not have resulted in such a major improvement in exhaust gas
readings.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Junius writes: ``My '85 S10 pickup's wipers will not park
when turned off. It is a regular two-speed wiper. Is the problem in
the wiper motor itself, or is there another part that parks the
wipers?''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that the truck has not been recently painted, and the
ground circuit for the wipers has not been disturbed, the parking
circuit for the windshield wipers is contained in the cover, which
is part of the motor assembly but not part of the actual motor
itself. (Some parts stores sell only the motor assembly with the
cover as a unit, and some sell the cover with the circuit board
separately.)
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tod Rieger writes: ``Thanks for the recommendation to
retrofit an air-conditioning system only when the situation is
extreme. I have a 1985 system that hasn't had any R-12 added since
1993, and it seems to need some more. If that is all it needs, I'll
skip the retrofit. You also mentioned `other refrigerants.' Is
FR-12 one of those?''
</P>
<P>
   I would strongly recommend steering clear of any refrigerants
other than R-12 and R134A.
</P>
<P>
   Although the other refrigerants, FR-12 included, may perform
well when the air-conditioning system is retrofitted to use them,
it could prove to be a nightmare should you need service down the
road. FR-12 is a blend refrigerant and cannot be recycled. Most
shops are not equipped to service these systems and dispose of the
refrigerant.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter is an automotive instructor. She writes about autos
for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
