<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   POLIO-PEOPLE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ When she started falling down
unexpectedly as an adult, Shirlee Sussman wrote it off to the
unsteady way she walked on the side of her foot. She had, after
all, come down with polio when she was 2. She had no idea that
polio often comes back to cripple its victims again later in life.
Neither did the doctors she saw in the 1960s and '70s, even as her
pain level gradually grew and her fatigue threshold gradually fell.
The mystery was unraveled in the early 1980s by Dr. Lauro Halstead,
himself a polio survivor. ``I thought of myself as cured,''
Halstead said, but his research showed the experiences of polio
people 30 to 40 years after their infection was neither imaginary
nor coincidental. Halstead coined the term post-polio syndrome,
characterized by progressive muscle weakness, debilitating fatigue
and pain, especially in joints and muscles. (Lamb, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ During the past year of abuse, derision
and mockery, Pam Johnson has heard it all: That she's an agent of
the religious right or, worse, Hallmark cards. That's she's
delusional, or starting a cult. Ann Landers and comedian Richard
Lewis, who would seem to have nothing whatsoever in common, have in
Johnson a shared enemy. All this happened because a year ago Sunday
_ on 8/8/98 _ Pam Johnson of suburban Dallas came out of the
happiness closet after 33 years. No more fear, no more denial, no
more secrets. She proclaimed herself aggressively, unapologetically
happy and hoped you were the same. And if you were, she hoped you
would talk about it, that you would not keep your happiness under a
basket. She started the Secret Society of Happy People, mounted a
campaign to declare Aug. 8 National Admit You're Happy Day and soon
found herself the most despised woman in America. (Beach, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MEETING-OF-MINDS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Here they are, sitting in
front of you, tucked into a corner at The Tavern _ a bar with
televisions, cheap nachos and frosty mugs of beer _ and they're
looking like they don't belong. Not in Austin. Not at the Tavern.
They are three of the greatest writing minds chronicling the new
technology age, trusted arbiters privy to the inner workings of
that mystical place where all things are ``point and click'':
Silicon Valley. And you can ask them anything, so you ask them
about the future because that's why they're here. These three
soothsayers, these oracles, are here huddled over a basket of chips
to unravel it for you. Rather, they are here _ a half-mile from the
bookstore where they would, an hour later, shamelessly hawk their
respective books to the bright-eyed geeks of Austin _ to unravel
the Internet. Because the Internet, in all its gnarled knottedness,
IS the future. The Internet is what we will eventually and, in
totality, live on, love on, work on and relax on. They are here to
explain how the Internet will be everything. But first, you should
meet them. (Kallenberg, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ Lee May's gardening column is not available
this week.
</P>
<P>
   FAUX-FINISH _ The thought of selecting one decorative wall
finish from the array of options these days can be enough to send
some homeowners running to the comfort of a gallon of white latex.
Fear of faux _ that broad category of paint and textural finishes,
from sponging to ragging to trompe l'oeil _ may discourage many
from experimenting with a look that is timeless and original, but
Bobby Sikes, Atlanta artist and muralist, explains the recent
trends in faux finishes and how they have moved away from the bold
colors of the '80s to the tone-on-tone neutrals of the '90s.
(Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) With Photos.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Aug.12.
</P>
<P>
   w/FAUX-FINISHTIPS _ Hiring artists to create decorative
finishes, whether it's faux painting a chair, texturizing a wall or
creating a trompe l'oeil mural, requires a certain amount of trust.
Yet there are steps consumers can take to ensure their choice in
painting techniques lives up to what they envisioned. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Aug.12.
</P>
