<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1692 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEETING-OF-MINDS11-CO     08-10 1808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEETING-OF-MINDS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Have a beer with the Net prophets
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Here they are, sitting in front of you, tucked
into a corner at The Tavern _ a bar with televisions, cheap nachos
and frosty mugs of beer _ and they're looking like they don't
belong. Not in Austin. Not at the Tavern.
</P>
<P>
   They are three of the greatest writing minds chronicling the new
technology age, trusted arbiters privy to the inner workings of
that mystical place where all things are ``point and click'':
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   And you can ask them anything, so you ask them about the future
because that's why they're here. These three soothsayers, these
oracles, are here huddled over a basket of chips to unravel it for
you. Rather, they are here _ a half-mile from the bookstore where
they would, an hour later, shamelessly hawk their respective books
to the bright-eyed geeks of Austin _ to unravel the Internet.
Because the Internet, in all its gnarled knottedness, IS the
future. The Internet is what we will eventually and, in totality,
live on, love on, work on and relax on. They are here to explain
how the Internet will be everything. Everything.
</P>
<P>
   But first, you should meet them.
</P>
<P>
   Over there, on the cell phone (again), is Kara Swisher. She
writes for the Wall Street Journal, was named ``most influential
writer on the Internet economy'' by the Industry Standard magazine,
and is the author of ``AOL.com.'' She wears sunglasses indoors like
a rock star because, to the tech world, she is one. Munching on the
limp salad and sipping the Sprite is the bespectacled Gary Rivlin.
He is the award-winning author of ``The Plot to Get Bill Gates''
and is the Cassandra who sees the negative side of technology. Then
there's Po Bronson, uber-journalist and author of ``The Nudist on
the Late Shift.'' He is so on the cutting edge, he even looks
futuristic, with a ``Logan's Run'' angulation of the jaw and alien
blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   So they're all here, and they are all qualified. Overqualified.
Because even if they're wrong about the future, they will be right.
These three are so mighty with the pen that what they write, what
they say, manifests itself as truth. You can trust them. And you
ask: (ital) What will be? (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   They are just starting to untangle your query when the skeptic
appears. The waiter, the one with the backward baseball cap and the
scraggly goatee, the one who brings the tortilla chips and the
Shiner for Bronson, questions that the Internet is the future. His
future is colonies in space and total Y2K-inspired pandemonium. The
waiter sees an end to the overnight millionaire and an end to the
over-hyped medium we call the Internet. He says the boom time is
over. It can't go on. He knows, the waiter explains, because he's a
business major.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't know. He isn't the one who can see the future. He
isn't Kara Swisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should it end?'' snaps Swisher. (Swisher snaps a lot.)
``Why should this end? People talk about the Internet being on a
precipice, the Internet being overvalued, but what's overvalued? Is
real estate in California overvalued? What if buying Yahoo! is like
buying ABC in 1940? Then, you would definitely say it was worth it.
Right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about the Internet and the economy driving it
is that everyone will have the opportunity to be successful,''
Bronson says, stopping to sip his beer. ``Think about it. You have
a better chance of starting an Internet company and being
successful than starting a television network or even writing a
teleplay and getting it produced.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronson knows. He has seen the Internet successes up close. It's
what his book is about. His world is filled with the dreamers who
are shaping an electronic place that our virtual selves will
eventually live in.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us see the Internet through the filters of the press and
through the eyes of Hollywood. He has broken through those filters
and sees a future we can barely comprehend. Our Internet has Sandra
Bullock chasing the evil Jeremy Northam through a Web of E-commerce
sites. Bronson's Internet is a place where we can live in digital
harmony, work anywhere we wish and all exist in a common electronic
space.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, he spends time with the people who are building
this space. He is well-acquainted with the architects of the
future. Bronson knows the New World is coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this new opportunity isn't all good,'' the man from
``Logan's Run'' continues. ``No matter how successful you are in
the Internet, you will still feel the brunt of competition against
your fellow humans. Moderation and being able to downshift will be
prized commodities, and the people who figure out how to do the
downshifting will be celebrated. But it's fantastic. Despite the
Internet's high social cost, it allows opportunity for everyone,
the possibility of financial success for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, the future and the Internet scare me,'' chimes in
Rivlin as he plays with his salad. ``I see lots of interesting
businesses, lots of people making money. Then again, there are a
lot of people not making money. I also see a widening gap between
the digital haves and the have-nots. This new age is going to leave
a lot of people behind. I also feel this linking of people through
computers is going to cut us off from our history. The Internet is
not good for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivlin's future, his Internet, is a world where people are
detached from one another. For him, there will be no common space.
Because we will have less actual contact with other humans, we will
separate ourselves from our pasts and each other. Rivlin cites a
Carnegie-Mellon study of Internet use. The study concluded that the
more time you spend on the Internet, the more lonely and depressed
you are.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, oracles don't agree. And Swisher doesn't. She is
upset at this notion of detachment. In her writing, she has seen
the joining together of people up close. She has seen the good the
Internet can do. Her book, ``AOL.com,'' shows how America Online
started as a way for people to talk dirty to each other and became
a global communications device to exchange ideas, opinions and meet
really neat people. After witnessing the birth of an Internet
company from nothing, and seeing its growth into a communications
giant and NASDAQ star, how can you be anything but excited about
the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability for the Internet to change people's lives is
vast,'' states Swisher. ``Everyone in the world can and will have
access to it. It's a giant idea. Think about it, just the ability
to reach everyone in the world is very powerful. What you can do
with the Internet, you can't do with any other medium. And its
power will only grow.''
</P>
<P>
   This leads Bronson to think about the kids. He wonders aloud
what the generation of children will be like who grow up thinking
there was never a time when there wasn't an Internet. He takes a
another sip from his Shiner and states his affection for the native
brew.
</P>
<P>
   He half-jokes about how parents and kids won't see eye-to-eye on
the Internet. How we, as parents, will recount how things used to
be different before the Net. We'll tell our children how we used to
go outside to play and, to contact friends, we used to actually
call them on the phone. For entertainment, we mindlessly (and
noninteractively) watched television for hours and hours. Our kids
will laugh and call us relics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have an Internet generation where it's all
about sitting and staring instead of going out to play,'' states
Rivlin defensively. (By now, he knows it is only a matter of time
before Swisher will respond.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have an impact,'' Rivlin continues. ``These kids will
grow up not knowing the reality that existed before the Internet
and, therefore, will have no problem entrenching themselves on
their computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivlin's views aren't unfounded. He has spent years examining
the darker side of the technology age. He has seen the greed, the
ulterior motives and the Genghis Khan mentality of Bill Gates and
his rivals. These technology leaders, and those who aspire to be
them, aren't all in it for the charity. They're not in business to
build a global village and make our world a better place. They're
in it for the money and the power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is much more creative than television ever could
be,'' Swisher immediately volleys back. ``At least the Internet is
interactive. It's not just sitting and watching Pokemon do some
weird-ass thing. Besides, when was it that everyone went out and
played? I watched television.''
</P>
<P>
   The future that began as one vision has mysteriously divided
itself into three separate futures _ Bronson's is dreamy and Ray
Bradbury-ish, Swisher's is polished, flawless and Utopian, and,
Rivlin's is dark and exclusionary _ as the tortilla chips are
swapped out once, Rivlin's salad is taken away and Bronson finishes
his beer.
</P>
<P>
   Swisher looks at her watch and decides it is time for all three
to go. She wants to buy a book for beach reading before her
signing. After tonight, Swisher explains, she is off to Mexico to
sun herself at some tropical, totally solar-powered, resort. She
boasts how she found her vacation spot on the Internet. Rivlin and
Bronson, much more concerned about the here and now, wonder if any
good bands are playing nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Talk sways back to the matter at hand one final time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world will demand that the Internet gets easier,'' says
Rivlin as the bill is delivered by a still unconvinced waiter.
``The future will be an Internet like a telephone. When you're on,
you're on. Unfortunately, the Internet of the future is an Internet
where there won't be a choice. If you want to make it financially
or succeed career-wise, you'll have to learn it. There will be no
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like saying in the future, it will be discriminatory
not hiring a field goal kicker who never kicked field goals,''
jokes Bronson. ``Of course, you'll have to learn it.''
</P>
<P>
   True to form, Swisher commands the last word.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, you had monks doing inscriptions and only a few people
see them,'' she says before dialing up her messages on the cell
phone. ``Then you have the printing press. A few more people are
reached. Next you have the radio, the telephone and television and
even more people get reached. The Internet takes it that much
further. How can this be anything but wonderful? The more people
who have access to the Internet, the better the world will be. And
how can an Internet that will eventually reach everyone be a bad
thing?''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Kallenberg writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. E-mail: gkallenberg(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
