<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ To listen to talk radio shows from around the
country in the days after the Atlanta massacre was to be very
afraid for the future of this country. For while there were
individual exceptions and no doubt some exceptional shows, too, the
overwhelming cry was for more guns. What this country needs is a
citizenry armed and cocked to shoot. (Teepen, Cox Newspapers) MOVED
MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ This column will not move today.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ Complaining about the folks we live next door
to, or across the street from is, of course, an inalienable right
that can probably be traced back to our cave dwelling days. Norman
Neanderthal comes home from work and listens to his wife Buffy
complain because the cavetrash across the gulch have just painted
their cavern purple. And bought an ugly dog. Buffy worries about
property values. Norman is afraid the undesirable's son will want
to marry his daughter. And there you have it. Neighborhood unrest
in the Pleistocene age. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ In ``Liar, Liar,'' Jim Carrey portrays
an attorney cursed with a spell that renders him unable to lie.
Coming soon to theaters near you: ``Oh, God, What a Bunch of Liars.
`` Carrey stars as Pat Robertson. George Burns returns as God. All
right, that's not true. It's a lie. But you'd need a full-length
motion picture to do justice to the way Robertson's Christian
Coalition mutilates No. 9 of the 10 Commandments it would post on
public school walls. That's the shalt-not against bearing false
witness. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
