<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1712 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-SURPRISE     08-10 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-SURPRISE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 KREMLIN GAMBLES on PUTIN  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By Yevgeny Krasnikov  
 c.1999 Moscow News  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Once again Boris Yeltsin has played a difficult and
dangerous game _ sacking our country's prime minister. And now our
best analytical minds are considering what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, as everybody knows here, a career is often made
in Russia by those who do nothing to make it. For instance, it is
known for certain that Yevgeny M. Primakov, our second-to-the-last
prime minister, had never wanted the post. In 1996, when spoken to
about running in the national elections, he flatly refused.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was precisely his several months of premiership, at the
forceful behest of Yeltsin, that led Russia to trust him. Or maybe
it was Primakov's special talent to lull Russia into a sense of
security?
</P>
<P>
   Oh well, that's history. We've been through three prime
ministers in the last year and a half _ and now the fourth. We've
seen the firing of Primakov, the ascendancy of Sergei V. Stepashin,
and now, three months later, yet a new move on the chess board. It
must have come as a nasty surprise to Stepashin, 47, who has been
loyal to Yeltsin _ the news was only announced to him in the
Kremlin very early in the morning on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Let this be said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's next president will take over a free but semi-bankrupt
state, overburdened by its social obligations to the people. This
is a constant. Yeltsin cannot wave away the problems on the streets
of Moscow and St. Petersburg as he can wave his hand and make a
prime minister _ or even a whole State Duma _ disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the buzzing in the Kremlin halls had already begun.
Those insiders were saying that a decision was about to be made as
to which would be better _ to start yet another difficult and
perilous move to remove the prime minister, who was being seen as
weak, or to call an all-Russia referendum simultaneously with
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose? A rescue operation to keep Yeltsin in control of
the next presidential race. A mission to control who succeeds him.
A major effort to keep a Yeltsin-backed candidate from being
trounced by the strengthening opposition force, which is an
alliance of several regional leaders, now led by Primakov and
Moscow Mayor Yuri M. Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve this ``rescue,'' a tough scenario was already
emerging behind the scenes. It was being presumed that the post of
head of government would be offered to someone outside the Russian
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Although this new Monday massacre is a shock in the West, for
several weeks now in Russia, the media have been citing the name of
a rising candidate: Vladimir V. Putin, 46, the man who last week
was director of the domestic security service (FSB), an arm of the
Cold War-era KGB, and secretary of the president's Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, this is a reverse. Since Primakov was abruptly
dismissed three months ago, top Kremlin officials have been saying
all but openly that Stepashin was destined to become Yeltsin's
successor.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to our sources, Naina Yeltsin, the president's
wife, and Pavel Borodin, the influential head of the presidential
Property Management Administration, were actively trying to
persuade Yeltsin to choose Putin. Their arguments: Putin is more
decisive than Stepashin and, moreover, as a former deputy Kremlin
administrator in charge of relations with Russia's regional
governments, Putin enjoys the support of the very power structure
now lining up in support of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the sack-Stepashin, elevate-Putin scenario is that
Yeltsin will dissolve the Duma, if in fact, it takes the requisite
three votes and turns Putin down every time. The members may well
vote no _ out of obstinacy, rebellion against Yeltsin, frustration
at the line of prime ministers or just because they don't like
Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Should Putin fail three times, Yeltsin might very well resign,
leaving Putin, appointed by his decree, constitutionally the legal
acting president. Thus, despite the Duma, Putin would have what
Yeltsin really wants for him: an excellent jumping-off ground for
the July 2000 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   This scenario, however, could well be little more than a
``Kremlin horror story'' designed to strike terror into the Kremlin
opponents. Then again, as the world is now aware, step one _ the
sacking of Stepashin _ has already occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Russia, the Communists, led by Gennadi Zyuganov, who
would favor the Primakov option, are already shaking in their
boots. Party members were seriously assuring your correspondent
last week that the Moscow police already had held an exercise in
the outlying suburb of Mitino, in full riot gear, ready for the
worst, a public rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring President Alexander Lukashenko of Belarus also
apparently promised Yeltsin to send in his own republic's police
force, should violence erupt, because at this point the Moscow
police are find of Luzhkov, the populist mayor.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kremlin is indeed considering a scenario based on the use
of force, it would only be as a kind of last resort exotica. No
doubt, Yeltsin is pinning far greater hopes on a peaceful shift,
hoping that the Russian people will, once again, remain stalwart
and passive.
</P>
<P>
   Either a forceful or a peaceful option would have the same
objective, however: to get a man such as Putin in, and in a
position strong enough to defeat a Primakov-Luzhkov ticket.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Yevgeny Krasnikov is political correspondent for Moscow News.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
