<HEADER>
A1722 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     08-10 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SINGING-BUSDRIVER (Houston) _ Travelers fortunate enough to
hitch a ride with airport shuttle driver Ellen Trevathan are having
their lucky day, and she won't hesitate to tell them. Trevathan
entertains passengers from the City Economy Lot to Bush
Intercontinental Airport singing country songs for cowboys, gospel
songs for preachers, gambling songs for gamblers and love songs for
honeymooners. By LISA DAVIS.
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-HOSPITAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ First Sgt. Frances Phelan took a
red-eye flight from Seattle to make it to Sunday's 364th Army
Reserve Field Hospital Inactivation Ceremony here. ``I wouldn't
have missed this for the world,'' said Phelan, who now is a ROTC
medical coordinator at Fort Lewis in Tacoma, Wash. Dwindling
numbers have forced the Army to inactivate the 364th and 15 other
Army hospitals. By MIKE FRICANO.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-RABBI-TALMUD (Houston) _ Rabbi Judith Abrams has been
recognized for establishing an Internet-based Talmud study program
for adults. The award-winning program is four years old and has a
worldwide audience. Abrams will receive an award and a $20,000
prize from the New York-based Covenant Foundation on Nov. 16 in
Atlanta. By RICHARD VARA. (Photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   LOSING-WEIGHT (Albany, N.Y.) _ After struggling to lose weight,
a colleague finally decided to consult a specialist. ``You know
what you need to do,'' he recalled the doctor saying. ``Eat less
and move more.'' If that sounds unbelievably simple, it is. But
it's also a strategy that works, and doesn't require any special
diet, supplement or gimmick. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WELLS-CEO (San Francisco) _ Dick Kovacevich is busy piloting a
very big firm. Last year, the Stanford MBA and his former bank,
Norwest, bought San Francisco- based Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. for $32
billion in one of the last great bank mergers of the decade. By
EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   SAIPAN-CLOTHES (San Francisco) _ Four retailers, including
Gymboree and Nordstrom, have agreed to settle claims in a federal
class-action lawsuit accusing the companies of allowing sweatshop
conditions in the U.S. territory of Saipan. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   SALON-REPORT (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco-based Salon.com
online publishing company recently experienced a surge in visitors
and a jump in revenue _ as well as a swell of red ink. By MATT
BEER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BALLPARK-TOURISTS (San Francisco) _ With the money Glenn
Brakefield of San Francisco, Linda Countryman of Kentucky and Ann
and George Elwood of New York have spent on vacations recently,
they could have gone to Paris for a week. Yet they have opted for
Detroit, Milwaukee and Cleveland. There are neither azure seas in
those cities nor the Arc de Triomphe. They do, however, have
ballparks. Increasing numbers of tourists are forfeiting more
glamorous summer vacations and choosing to visit ballparks around
the country. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-ADDICTIONS (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ A racecourse
backstretch can foster an unhealthy reliance on gambling, drugs or
alcohol, racing veterans say. ``The backstretch, for an addictive
personality, is paradise,'' says Rudy Rios, a certified alcoholism
and substance abuse counselor who runs an employee assistance
program for the New York Racing Association. By LINDA TRISCHITTA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ The many fans of Jeffrey
Deaver's thrillers will be disappointed to learn that ``The Devil's
Teardrop'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25, 396 pages) does not feature the
brilliant quadriplegic criminalist Lincoln Rhyme (he does make a
cameo appearance). But that is the only disappointment that Deaver
serves. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ There's all sorts of talk about
global warming and changes in our climate. Yes, something might be
happening with our climate. After all, something has happened many
times in the past, and it's not illogical to presume that it could
happen again. But to presume, as so many people do, that a few hot
summers and mild winters constitute proof that it's definitely
happening doesn't make sense. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A series of killer earthquakes
that began in Assisi, Italy, on Sept. 26, 1997, damaged St.
Francis' basilica there. From that catastrophe, a wonderful
opportunity has been given to the citizens of and visitors to
Milan, Paris, New York and San Francisco. As part of a $60 million
restoration project, scores of surviving works of art and
reliquaries from the basilica are out of their damaged home and on
tour. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-COCAINE (San Francisco) _ As Texas Gov. George W. Bush
should know from his experience with alcohol, drug use is no game.
He has talked openly about how, at age 40, he realized booze was
taking a toll on his life and how he decided to stop drinking for
the good of himself and his family. Bush should be equally
forthcoming about what he did or didn't put up his nose during what
he has called his ``young and irresponsible'' years. By DARREN
RICHARDSON.
</P>
<P>
   HOOVER-BIRTHDAY (Danville, Calif.) _ Tuesday was the birthday of
one of the most popular presidents ever elected _ the tough-minded,
straight-shooting winner of what at the time was the biggest
landslide in American history. It is also the birthday of a
president who, by the end of his term, had become one of the
nation's least popular leaders and loser of the second most
one-sided presidential election. Happy birthday, Herbert Hoover. By
CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
<P>
   HIDDEN-FEES (San Francisco) _ An amazing turn of events has
occurred since the last time I made a major purchase. Stores, which
formerly raised prices to make up for customers who steal from
them, have apparently decided to eliminate the middleman and now
are stealing directly from you. By RUTH SHERMAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
