<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGING-BUSDRIVER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON BUS DRIVER IN TUNE WITH AIRPORT-GOERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA DAVIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Travelers fortunate enough to hitch a ride with
airport shuttle driver Ellen Trevathan are having their lucky day,
and she won't hesitate to tell them, either.
</P>
<P>
   Trevathan, known to passengers as The Singing Bus Lady,
entertains passengers from the City Economy Lot to Bush
Intercontinental Airport singing country songs for cowboys, gospel
songs for preachers, gambling songs for gamblers and love songs for
honeymooners.
</P>
<P>
   ``My singing can make this the longest or the shortest trip in
your life,'' Trevathan tells a van load of passengers. ``But a
girl's got to do what a girl's got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Her program begins with the jingle ``City Economy Lot is the
place for you,'' which is an advertiser's dream. Trevathan, 52,
continues with throaty renditions of Hank Williams' ``I Saw the
Light,'' Kenny Rogers' ``The Gambler'' and then ``Faded Love,''
which she introduces as ``an old Patsy Cline tune, or a new tune
from Monica Lewinsky to the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Trevathan admits that not every rider is a fan, but the extra
$50 in tips each week, and the ovations, are signs that many enjoy
their five-minute shuttle, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just like the idea that someone's paying attention to
them after a long trip,'' said Steve Howard, vice president of
All-Right Parking, which operates the shuttle buses for the City
Economy Lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have the elevator syndrome when they get on a bus, and
she's certainly the opposite of that. She's just not going to let
that happen,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harmond, a businessman from nearby Katy who rode with
Trevathan recently, said, ``If my wife were here, she'd probably
want to go around for another trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Leroy Traylor, a parking monitor for the City Economy Lot, said
people who've ridden with Trevathan often ``ask when that Singing
Bus Lady will come by.'' But it's not always easy to find her among
the more than 20 buses serving the nearly 10,000 parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Trevathan of suburban Humble is pure Texas, complete with a
butterfly clip nestled in her gray bouffant. She greets everyone
who happens on her charter with a friendly ``Hi, Darlin'.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my job,'' she said. ``I get to look at all the handsome
men in Houston, fantasize about them for five minutes, and I don't
have to wash their socks in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do this until I retire or die, whichever comes
first.''
</P>
<P>
   She's been at the City Economy Lot for 10 months, but she's been
a driver for other All-Right Parking lots for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Trevathan was married to a preacher for the 16 years before
that, and she said she views her job and performing as her personal
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to meet people wherever they are at the time,'' she
said. ``A lot of people are frustrated or worried about the time
when they get on, but humor takes their mind off their anxieties
for a moment.''
</P>
<P>
   She also has been known to put the show on hold for a grieving
family or if someone's really belligerent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to play it cool and let them have a solemn ride,''
Trevathan said. ``I do know how to read people and shut up, even
though I'm an extrovert.''
</P>
<P>
   When traffic is light on her Monday-through-Friday 3 p.m. to 11
p.m. shift, she loves to have single passengers ride with her and
chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like being a bartender,'' Trevathan said.
``People tell me their troubles because they think they'll never
see me again.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she enjoys being a bucket-seat psychiatrist, Trevathan
does have some entertainment aspirations. She's never wanted to
make it to Nashville, Tenn., where singing bus drivers are
abundant, but she wouldn't mind an appearance on a late-night show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to take my jingle as far as it will take me,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
