<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, August 11. If you have any questions, please call The
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   PARTY _ In 1992, Ross Perot led an impassioned following of
angry, disaffected voters that caused fits for the campaigns of
President Bush and then-Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton. His independent
candidacy won almost 20 percent of the vote, the best showing for
an independent or third-party presidential candidate in more than
half a century. And it sparked a debate that continues today about
whether he might have sealed Bush's defeat, even though exit polls
show that he probably drew almost equally from Democrats and
Republicans. Flash forward to 2000. Could a third-party candidate
wield that kind of political clout again? 36. David Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   FAIR: The Missouri state fair opens Thursday in Sedalia. We
profile three groups that will be participating: Kansas City area
kids raising chickens, a family that makes potato doughnuts and a
man who trains jumping mules. Lee Hill Kavanaugh. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   COOK: Steven Cook had been dead so long that his body had begun
to stink. Another heat victim, authorities said, when his body was
discovered July 21 in his sweltering midtown apartment. But local
mental health officials say it was a needless death. They're
outraged because Cook was only 40, and no one had checked on him at
the Campbell Street group home where he lived. Bavley. Photo of
Cook and of Campbell Street group home. 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   VFW: A Platte City, Mo., VFW post is calling for a boycott of
the veteran's organization's convention this weekend because that
draft dodging President Bill Clinton has been invited as a speaker.
Staffer TBA.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIN: Local school districts have long offered early
retirement programs to save money by purging payrolls of teachers
at the top of the salary scale. Now, with a teacher shortage
starting to bloom, districts are coming up with creative ways to
convince teachers to keep working. Jennifer Taylor. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   LIB: The McLouth (Kan.) public library had been closed for 20
years because of a lack of funds to buy books and a lack of
volunteer librarians. Then 14-year-old Kalila Dalton decided to
change things. She began gathering books and now folks there credit
her with single-handedly getting the library back open. Trisha
Howard. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   EVOL. Public comment sessions on compromise science standards
for Kansas schools (the latest in the evolution vs. creationism
struggle) is expected to draw a crowd. Diane Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE (analysis) _ Deutsche Telekom keeps popping up as the
company most likely to buy Sprint. But could it pull off such a
deal? If so, that actually could be good for Kansas City, since
Deutsche is a global player without much U.S. business, so it
probably would let Sprint stay in Kansas City. Ted Sickinger
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Boston at Kansas City, 7:05 p.m. Dick Kaegel. 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   HRGUYS. Amazing as it seems, Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa are on
pace to again captivate baseball fans with another fall home-run
chase. In this sequel, both are playing to packed houses and rave
reviews, and McGwire seems destined to keep the leading role. Steve
Rock. 22-25.
</P>
<P>
   TONY. Tony Richardson, a special-teams terror for the past few
years, gets his chance of a lifetime: starting at fullback. Randy
Covitz. 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   WHITLOCK. Jason Whitlock column from Chiefs training camp.
</P>
<P>
   THEPGA. Daily story from the PGA Championship. Howard Richman.
16-18.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   Fashion-quiz: Back in the old, old days of designer dictates,
fashion protocol tended to follow a single party line. People
mostly dressed in the same styles of clothing. Differences were
distinguished by cost, quality and subtle nuance. The major fashion
folks have finally caught on to reality. Instead of dancing to a
single beat going into the new millennium, they offer a wide range
of styles in keeping with customers' tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Where do you fit in the midst of such diversity? Do you
characterize your own wardrobe preferences as round-the-clock
casual, conventional or designer-obsessed? Are you the earth mother
or the unpredictable dresser? Jackie White. 650 words.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion-answers: Compare your fashion-quiz results with the
categories below. Some answers may appear in more than one group.
The highest number of answers in one group indicates how you see
your sartorial image. Jackie White. 950 words.
</P>
<P>
   Women-childless: Loring Leifer is one of a growing number of
women nationwide who are choosing not to have children. Some decide
to take that path fairly early in life, experts say, a choice that
takes a healthy amount of maturity and self-knowledge. Many others
make the decision gradually as ambivalence turns to certainty.
Having children of their own is not for them. Edward M. Eveld.
1,400 words. Has art. List of support groups attached.
</P>
