<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-HOSPITAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY SLOWLY RETIRING FIELD HOSPITAL UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE FRICANO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ First Sgt. Frances Phelan took a red-eye flight
from Seattle to make it to the 364th Army Reserve Field Hospital
Inactivation Ceremony on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And all the fatigue and travails of predawn air travel were
worth it. As one of the first six women to serve with the
76-year-old Army outfit in Albany, she had to be present for the
retiring of the unit's flag and honoring of her extended family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have missed this for the world,'' said Phelan, who
now is a ROTC medical coordinator at Fort Lewis in Tacoma, Wash.
``This group stays together, because we do far more than bigger
units.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the 260 men and women of the 364th, dwindling
numbers have forced the Army to inactivate the unit, which operates
out of tents. According to public affairs officer Maj. Linda
Taylor, 16 Army hospitals are being inactivated during the next six
years, leaving 25 hospitals throughout the country. Almost all the
members of the 364th have been reassigned to the 348th General
Hospital, which is based in Pedricktown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``The morale is somewhat sad ... we worked very hard under that
flag,'' Taylor said. ``But morale here is very good, because we're
a very close-knit, family-oriented unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. Duane May, commander of the 8th Medical Brigade, of
which the 364th was a part spoke very highly of the unit, which has
provided medical assistance in every conflict since and including
World War II and more recently has been involved in humanitarian
endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't retire the character of the 364th,'' May said in his
speech to several hundred in the audience. He said that the unit
exemplified the army values of loyalty, duty and respect among
others. ``I love a unit that acts like soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   The unit's commanding officer, Col. James M. Veazey Jr., who was
honored with a commendation medal for his exceptional meritorious
service, could not help but boast about the people with whom he had
served for the past 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today even the heavens weep in recognition of the impact of
the 364th,'' Veazey said under cloudy skies that earlier in the day
had given way to showers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pleasure and a great privilege to be base commander
for the last four years,'' Veazey said. ``God bless you and
Godspeed.''
</P>
<P>
   After the formal ceremony, the soldiers and their families
gathered at the Army Reserve Training Center.
</P>
<P>
   When Phelan saw retired Col. Edmund Purdy, who had traveled from
Nova Scotia for the event, they compared travel distances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where'd you come fly from?'' Purdy asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tacoma,'' replied Phelan, who later added that she remembers
when Purdy was a major at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tacoma,'' Purdy said, ``Well, then you win (for distance).''
</P>
<P>
   Purdy, 76, was assigned to the 364th in 1964 as a dentist
specializing in prosthetics.
</P>
<P>
   Initially saddened when he learned of his former unit's fate,
Purdy was overjoyed when he learned of the unit's absorption into
the 348th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1752 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOSING-WEIGHT-HNS &LR;      08-10 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOSING-WEIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST DIET BEGINS WITH SMALLER SERVINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ After struggling to lose weight, a colleague
finally decided to consult a specialist. ``You know what you need
to do,'' he recalled the doctor saying. ``Eat less and move more.''
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds unbelievably simple, it is.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also a strategy that works, and doesn't require any
special diet, supplement or gimmick. Over the past six months, my
co-worker has slimmed down almost three pant sizes by doing nothing
more than walking at little longer every day and keeping an eye on
the portions on his plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that with pasta, which was my favorite because it
was easy and fast, I was probably eating servings for three or
four,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   My colleague now takes a more measured approach, writing down
everything he eats and always leaving a restaurant with a doggy
bag. ``The portions are too big,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But portion control as a dieting strategy doesn't sell books or
make for catchy late-night infomercials, which may explain why
Americans continue getting fatter despite a billion-dollar
obsession with weight loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really become a nation of gluttons and we're not even
aware of it,'' said Karen Miller-Kovach, the lead scientist and
nutritionist at Weight Watchers. ``If you want to learn about
portion sizes, go on a European vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand how out of proportion we've become, think
supersize at McDonald's or all-you-can-eat at the country buffet.
Even bagels and muffins have gotten bigger, and many restaurants no
longer use plates, they use platters.
</P>
<P>
   For people who don't want to join Weight Watchers, there are
other strategies to help figure portion sizes.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, pay attention to the USDA Food Pyramid, and its
list of recommended servings. Remember, a serving size is a
standardized unit of measure and not a serving on your plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest areas of confusion I see with people is
serving size,'' Miller-Kovach said. ``It's not `whatever I eat at a
given time.''' So the six to 11 recommended servings of bread,
rice, cereal and pasta aren't as much as you think and probably
much less.
</P>
<P>
   Eat two slices of toast for breakfast and you've had two
servings. Have a sandwich for lunch, and your running total is now
four. Eat a cup of cooked pasta for dinner and you've gotten two
more (1/2 cup cooked pasta, cereal or rice equals one serving).
</P>
<P>
   ``When people start keeping track of what they're eating, they
often realize they're eating more than they thought,'' said Cindy
Moore, a spokeswoman for the American Dietetic Foundation and
director of nutrition therapy at the Cleveland Clinic Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Losing weight becomes a matter of cutting back on the total
amount of food. To lose a pound a week, you'll need to cut back on
500 calories a day, roughly the equivalent of 4 1/2 tablespoons of
oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is the total number of calories at the end of
the day,'' said Nan Windmueller, an Albany nutritionist. ``Nothing
needs to be eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   Windmueller counsels her patients to get most of their calories
from fruits, vegetables and whole grains. Not only are those foods
healthy, but they pack more bulk per calorie, which leaves you
feeling fuller and more satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   She also reminds them that portion control can leave room for
favorite foods, whether it's chocolate or ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people need is a strategy for eating, not for depriving
themselves,'' Windmueller said. ``I have a client who eats a Ring
Ding every afternoon. She has to and she's losing weight
beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
