<SLUG> BC-BALLPARK-TOURISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S GO OUT TO THE BALLPARK (RATHER THAN PARIS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With the money Glenn Brakefield of San
Francisco, Linda Countryman of Kentucky and Ann and George Elwood
of New York have spent on vacations recently, they could have gone
to Paris for a week, splurged on a condominium in Maui or taken a
cruise to the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they have opted for Detroit, Milwaukee and Cleveland. There
are neither azure seas in those cities nor the Arc de Triomphe.
They do, however, have ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing numbers of tourists are forfeiting more glamorous
summer vacations and choosing to visit ballparks around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   They are swinging through San Francisco this year to be part of
Candlestick Park's final season as the home of the San Francisco
Giants, and even more are likely in the coming years to see the
team's new downtown home, Pacific Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us cares anything about Hawaii,'' said Countryman, 50,
who visits different ballparks every year with her 76-year-old
mother and sister. Earlier this month, they toured Yankee Stadium
and the baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y., to see the
induction ceremonies for pitcher Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   The ballpark-tour boom has capitalized on the trend in major
league baseball to build new downtown stadiums with an
old-fashioned feel, popular since the opening of Oriole Park at
Camden Yards in Baltimore in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been to Europe, and I wouldn't go if someone paid
me,'' said A.G. Thomas of San Diego, a retired engineer who has
seen about 20 of the nation's 30 major league ballparks on nine
tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ride boats. I don't like to dance. This is what I
like. This is what I go for,'' said Brakefield, who has been on
five tours. ``I haven't found a stadium I didn't like. I haven't
found a hot dog I didn't like.''
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, fans say, these buildings are not the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking stadiums with hot dogs as cuisine. Stadiums with
smelly bathrooms. Stadiums with home teams in the cellar, and
stadiums fans can't wait to see closed.
</P>
<P>
   But there are ballparks serving fresh strawberries and whipped
cream, ballparks steeped in history and spanking new ballparks with
retractable roofs.
</P>
<P>
   Tour operators _ such as Sports Travel Inc. of Hatfield, Mass.,
and Jay Buckley Tours of La Crosse, Wis. _ have seen business
double in the past two years alone say the ballpark boom may in
part grow out of a wave of nostalgia. Four ballparks close this
year: Tiger Stadium in Detroit, County Stadium in Milwaukee, the
Astrodome in Houston and Candlestick Park in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the history of it, I like to think about what it was
like back then,'' said Dan Wall, a 39-year-old Pittsburg
merchandiser who enjoyed his $3,000 tour to the Midwest so much he
uses his vacation time to be a host on many of the trips. ``The
guys on these trips can tell you the starting lineup of teams in
the 20s. But ask them who Dirty Harry is, and they'll say, `Who's
he?' They're watching baseball every minute of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that a wave of new stadiums _ including Safeco Field,
which opened last month to replace the Kingdome in Seattle _ and
baseball lovers say there's plenty of reason to base a vacation on
ballpark visits.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when these 7,000 Americans consumed with America's
favorite pastime stadium-hop, trips can include long bus rides,
teams they don't normally root for, and nights in cities known more
for urban blight than beautiful landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Tour-goers pay separately to fly to the original destination and
to fly home from the last stop. The tour price does not include
meals or entertainment outside the ball games. Fans can spend up to
$3,000 for a trip.
</P>
<P>
   The tour price, which runs about $1,000, includes transportation
to and from the games, hotel accommodations and, of course,
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Fans say the trips include more than baseball. Often the games
are in cities like Chicago or New York, where fans say they enjoy
the jazz clubs, great restaurants and shopping. The oft-teased
Cleveland boasts the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Carrillo, a firefighter from Redwood City, Calif., said
Cleveland normally would not have been on his vacation wish list.
</P>
<P>
   But because Jacobs Field, built in 1994, was part of a stadium
package that included Tiger Stadium in Detroit and Oriole Park at
Camden Yards, he visited and discovered Cleveland was ``the most
fun of all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are great,'' said Carrillo, 42, who is planning a
second stadium tour at the end of August. ``The area known as the
Flats on the water (near the stadium) is like a big party area. It
was packed.''
</P>
<P>
   These fans say a ballpark tour also is about Americana and
history.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who visit historic Wrigley Field in Chicago and Fenway Park
in Boston recall a time when major league baseball seemed like less
a business than a national pastime, and the places where players
stepped up to bat were in the middle of neighborhoods, instead of
the middle of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Stadium, which is getting more than its fair share of
visitors this year, is also a sentimental favorite. With Fenway
Park, which opened on the same day in 1912, Tiger Stadium is the
oldest ballpark in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very small and old, and you're sitting on top of the
field,'' Wall said. ``Ty Cobb was there, Hank Greenberg was there,
and a lot of Hall of Famers.''
</P>
<P>
   But he conceded that certain ballparks are ``destination
stadiums,'' a polite way of saying the ballpark is the point of the
trip, not the city.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, ``it's more like you run in, go to the game and get
the hell out of there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Few who take the trips don't consider the vacation expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You usually stay where the players stay,'' said Thomas, 65, of
San Diego, who has seen about 20 stadiums with Sports Travel Inc.
``They're better tickets than you could get walking up yourself.
You meet with the umpires and visit the city, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Foth, 48, and his 10-year-old son, Dalen, were part of a
28-person tour that saw an Oakland A's game this past week at the
Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum. They heard American League umpire
Tim Welke regale them with ``insider'' stories of his 16 years in
the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would make me feel more comfortable, if on the count of
three, you could all boo me,'' Welke joked.
</P>
<P>
   Foth, of Beulah, N.D., said the trip would cost him about
$4,500, but ``I guess I'm just a baseball fan. ... It's a good way
to spend some good time together.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Buckley, who runs Jay Buckley Tours, caters to less affluent
fans who take buses from city to city, while Jay Smith of Sports
Travel places fans in finer hotels and provides air travel between
cities separated more than four hours by car.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies say fans are of all ages and come from many
spectrums of life. At least a third of ballpark visitors are women,
who actually outnumbered men on such tours in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley says his single largest chunk _ 20 percent _ comes from
California, the vast majority from the San Francisco Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Smith says Californians also make up the largest portion of his
clientele.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them could get sucked into the Sports Travel's
Millennium Tour, which for $5,000, will take clients to every major
league ballpark in America next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Ann and George Elwood of Hancock, N.Y., are close to that goal _
with just four stadiums to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
