<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1756 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-ADDICTIONS-HNS &LR;      08-10 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ADDICTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINER HONORED FOR HELPING WITH RACING ADDICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LINDA TRISCHITTA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ A racecourse backstretch can foster an
unhealthy reliance on gambling, drugs or alcohol, racing veterans
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The backstretch, for an addictive personality, is paradise,''
said Rudy Rios, a certified alcoholism and substance abuse
counselor who runs an employee assistance program for the New York
Racing Association (NYRA) and has a caseload of 38 people at the
Saratoga Race Course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an equal opportunity sickness,'' he said of addiction.
``From grooms to trainers to owners and officers, we counsel a lot
of people to try to better their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   One man who donates his time to help backstretch workers was
honored by 60 prominent racing figures as a humanitarian and unsung
hero last week at the Reading Room, a private club at the track.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Perlsweig, the trainer who led Lord Avie to an Eclipse
Award in 1980, received the seventh annual Dogwood Dominion Award
for his volunteer efforts on behalf of backstretch workers at
Monmouth Park and Gulfstream Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tracks can't run without them,'' Perlsweig said of the
workers for whom he has presented a Backstretch Appreciation Day at
Monmouth Park since 1991. ``They're the people that make the game
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who nominated Perlsweig said his support of
workers struggling with addictions to alcohol, drugs and gambling
in the transitory racing business was another reason for his
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've helped a lot of them try to get off the hook, and give an
ear for them to talk,'' said Perlsweig, who was joined by his wife,
Patricia, son Mark and daughter Jude Stomel.
</P>
<P>
   Rios said that backstretch workers often come from very poor
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of these people are single, or come from other
countries to progress,'' Rios said. But instead, ``they become
desperate, lonely and unloved. Sometimes they are isolated if they
don't speak the language.''
</P>
<P>
   Rios said following the thoroughbreds from track to track, as
many workers do each year on the New York circuit, does not promote
health for the addict.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have lost their families,'' he said. ``We also try to
bond them with other people who are sober enough to care for them.
They don't have to be alone, and don't have to live only the
racetrack life.''
</P>
<P>
   After backstretch workers complete detoxification and
rehabilitation, Rios tries to help them return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the program opened up in 1989, we've helped 373 people
keep their jobs,'' he said. ``It's modeled after Alcoholics
Anonymous. We have group therapy on dark days. I also do random
Breathalyzer and urine tests, and we have recovery houses for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Montemarano, who worked for Perlsweig for 15 years at
Monmouth Park and nominated him for the award, said it was the
unknown acts of kindness that defined a person's character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny totally changed my life,'' Montemarano said. ``He sets a
tremendous example as a positive role model.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famers jockey Pat Day and trainer Mack Miller were
judges, with Anne Campbell, the award sponsor with her husband,
Wade ``Cot'' Campbell, of Dogwood Stable in Aiken, S.C. They had to
decide among 35 nominees for the worthy candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny is so deserving for the work he does,'' said Day before
dashing to dress for the second race, when he rode Surfside to a
win. ``It's too bad we can only give one away. Choosing the winner
doesn't get any easier.'' Perlsweig's award included a $5,000 check
and a bronze sculpture of the Campbell's stallion, Dominion, a
horse called workmanlike, dependable and intelligent by his owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny is one of the best known and best liked characters in
all of racing, east of the Mississippi River,'' Cot Campbell said.
``If it's the right thing to do, Danny does it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
