<HEADER>
A1770 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-RABBI-TALMUD     08-10 1726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-RABBI-TALMUD-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HUNGER FOR HOLINESS: RABBI PURSUES INTEREST IN TALMUD ON THE
INTERNET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
(Attn.: Ohio) 
 
By RICHARD VARA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Rabbi judith Abrams likes to fantasize about getting a
phone call one day from director Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   Then the play she is co-writing about the Talmud might become
``Talmud: The Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The daydream amuses Abrams, a Reform rabbi with a growing
national reputation as an expert on the Talmud, a voluminous
collection of ancient Jewish oral law and commentary. It is second
only to the Torah in influence among Jews. Once the lonely preserve
of religious-minded scholars, the Talmud is gaining students. Many
find it on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams is founder and director of Maqom, an award-winning
cyber-school for adult Talmud study. ``Maqom'' is Hebrew for
``place'' and is another name for God.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talmud is the most spectacular, wonderful work of Jewish
literary and spiritual creativity, bar none,'' said Abrams, who
studied the Talmud for her Jewish studies doctorate from Baltimore
Hebrew University. ``It is amazing and enriching for a person's
intellect, soul and emotional life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Talmud is considered rabbinic literature and sometimes
called the Oral Torah. Jews believe that Moses received both the
written Torah (the first five books of the Bible) and the oral law
on Mount Sinai. ``It was put into his ear,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Moses came down from Sinai, he passed it on to the elders
and so on,'' Abrams said.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish law is known as ``Halakah`` (Aramaic for path or way).
Jews believe that being holy consists of obeying God's commands as
revealed in the Torah, both written and oral.
</P>
<P>
   In the second century A.D., Judah Ha-Nasi made the first
compilation of Jewish law (known as the Mishnah). Later rabbis
added their interpretations, which came to be known as the Gemara.
The Gemara, completed by A.D. 500, also includes Jewish history,
customs and folk tales.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the Mishnah and Gemara constitute the Talmud.
``Talmud'' is the Hebrew word for learning or instruction.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, devout rabbis and sages delved into Torah and
Mishnah passages to glean insightful spiritual truths for
practical, everyday application, Abrams said.
</P>
<P>
   They often engaged in detailed arguments on sometimes esoteric
topics (such as the proper way to light Hannukah candles). They
would cite Scripture and teachings of revered rabbis to bolster
their positions. Every aspect of life _ from prayer to sex to
business _ was considered in light of the Torah as part of an
unceasing search for godly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   While the Talmud is more than 15 centuries old, it applies to
modern life, Abrams said. The Talmud deals with vital spiritual and
secular issues such as the family, death, grief, child-rearing and
other evergreen topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has everything to say about modern life particularly when
you face difficult times,'' she said. ``It is a real tower of
strength to fall back on.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams shows how that holds true at her Internet site,
maqom.com. The site includes lessons exploring Jewish law and
tradition as they apply to such issues as parenting, death and
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   For generations Jews have turned to the Talmud for guidance,
Abrams said. For example, the ancients regarded physical disability
as defined by the state of the mind rather than the state of the
body, Abrams said. ``A person with no legs or a person who is blind
is considered hardly disabled at all,'' she said. They could still
learn, think and communicate, abilities that far outweighed their
disabilities, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In another portion of the Talmud, one sage visits another
bed-ridden sage. ``Aren't your sufferings precious to you?'' he
said to the suffering friend. ``Neither they nor their reward,'' he
replies. The first sage lifts his friend from the bed and cures
him. The story demonstrates that sufferings need not be welcomed or
tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to like suffering,'' Abrams said. Sufferers are
encouraged to look for cures or remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jews today know virtually nothing of the Talmud, Abrams
said. Until recently, the study of the Talmud was considered the
province of rabbinical students and devout Orthodox Jews. Usually
written in Hebrew, it was regarded as intimidatingly complicated
and arcane. The stories often require extensive background study
and invite reflection and discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talmudic study method requires looking at a problem from
all aspects,'' said Rabbi Joseph Radinsky of United Orthodox
Synagogues. It was Radinsky who introduced Abrams to the Talmud.
Talmudic study is best done in a study group, since topics need
discussion, arguments pro and con, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is almost axiomatic that adult Jews know nothing about the
Talmud, but I am trying to change that,'' said Abrams. ``(Jews)
have a feeling that it belongs to only somebody with a long beard
and a black hat,'' she said. ``What I am trying to show them is
that it belongs to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But Abrams acknowledges that the Talmud is sexist in some areas.
It was written by men for men, she admits, and she urges people:
``Just get over it.'' The Talmud's spiritual power overshadows its
faults, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her message is falling on receptive ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are recognizing they are missing out on something,''
Abrams said. ``They have achieved what they wanted to achieve: the
house, the boat, the car, the clothes. They are finding that it is
not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   They find they are missing the spiritual dimension in their
lives. ``Talmud is the great feeder of spiritual seekers,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Talmud) is beautiful,'' said recently retired Houston Jewish
educator Shirley Barish. ``There have been a number of us ready to
study the Talmud but you get a little afraid of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been the rabbis who studied the Talmud,'' Barish
said. ``And women didn't study the Talmud.'' But she joined Abrams'
Monday evening class four years ago and she is glad she did. She is
amazed at how wise the ancient sages really were.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn there is a time and a place for everything,'' she
said. Talmud studies have enriched her Jewish life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judaism is not a children's religion,'' said Marsha Schneider,
a Houston Jewish educator. ``There are no easy answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider began studying the Talmud with Abrams three years ago
as she was undergoing a divorce. Her study group became her support
group and helped her grow spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Houston classes, Abrams travels extensively
across the nation lecturing on the Talmud. In 1995, she launched
her cyber-school (http://www.maqom.com/). The Web site provides a
short Talmud lesson with discussion questions. Students can
participate in e-mail discussions. ``I teach from 100 to 200 people
here in Houston,'' she said. ``I teach thousands of people when I
lecture. And we get 60 hits a day on the Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   The cyber-school earned Abrams a 1999 Covenant Award for Jewish
Educators for contributing to the transmission of Jewish values,
knowledge and identity. The New York-based Covenant Foundation
selected three educators, including Abrams, from more than 400
nominees. The award, which carries a $20,000 prize, will be given
to Abrams on Nov. 16 at an awards ceremony in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams began her love affair with the Talmud in Houston while
serving as an assistant rabbi at Congregation Emanu El from 1985 to
1988, right after ordination. She attended a Talmud class taught by
Radinsky. ``He was the one who taught me to love it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Steven, moved to Washington, D.C., and
lived there for three years. It was during that time she began
doctoral studies and was a part-time rabbi for a Virginia Jewish
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Abrams, who now has three school age children, returned
to Houston as the part-time rabbi for Congregation Beth El in
nearby Missouri City.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, she resigned and the congregation hired a full-time
rabbi while launched Maqom.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Illinois, Abrams never expected to become a
Talmud-teaching rabbi. ``I thought I was going to be a DJ,'' she
said. She worked for radio stations doing newscasts and learned the
art of compressing a lot of information in brief reports. It is a
skill that comes in handy when writing lessons for her Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams attended Oberlin College in Ohio, majoring in
anthropology and Russian, giving up her DJ dreams. Her Christian
friends introduced her to daily prayer. Prayer became increasingly
important in her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in that way that I started developing a relationship
with God,'' said Abrams, whose parents were professors in medical
schools.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, her junior year, Abrams listed all the things she
enjoyed. They included: singing, teaching, praying, writing and
organizing. Only a rabbi could do all of that, she decided. She
graduated from Oberlin in 1980 and attended Hebrew Union College in
Cincinnati. She was ordained in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams hopes to finish her Talmud play over the next year. A
Talmudic musical is ``something that has been tickling my head for
a couple of years,'' Abrams said in the small den-office-library of
her southwest Houston home. She has been co-writing the script with
a New York playwright for a year and they are ready to compose the
lyrics and music.
</P>
<P>
   The musical is a natural outgrowth of Abrams' passion for the
Talmud, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She shares that passion with a growing national audience. She
frequently does guest lectures on the Talmud from Los Angeles to
New York. She has authored nine books on the Talmud, including a
three-volume work for beginners. She has also written six
children's books on Jewish tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of her Talmud play is a revered sage, Rabbi Baer Ben
Joseph Akiba, and his wife, Rachel. Rachel refused to marry Akiba,
then an illiterate shepherd, unless he went to a religious studies
school. He spent a total of 24 years studying and became a
legendary rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams intends to have the ancient sage and his wife appear on
stage to assist a modern couple, through song. She has high hopes
the musical will draw yet another audience to the Talmud.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
