<HEADER>
A1777 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEWS-MYSTERIE     08-10 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEWS-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEARDROP' IS A DEVIL OF A THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The many fans of Jeffrey Deaver's thrillers will be disappointed
to learn that ``The Devil's Teardrop'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25, 396
pages) does not feature the brilliant quadriplegic criminologist
Lincoln Rhyme (he does make a cameo appearance). But that is the
only disappointment that Deaver serves.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 a.m. on New Year's Eve, a lone gunman stands at the top of
the escalator at the Dupont Circle subway station in Washington,
D.C., fires 100 rounds from a concealed automatic weapon, and slips
away.
</P>
<P>
   A man calls the security desk at City Hall and says there is a
note about the subway killings under the Washington Post vending
machine outside the building. It reads: ``Mayor Kennedy _ The end
is night. The Digger is loose and their is no way to stop him. He
will kill again _ at four, 8 and midnight if you don't pay. I am
wanting $20 million dollars in cash ... Only I am knowing how to
stop The Digger. If you apprehend me, he will keep killing. If you
kill me, he will keep killing. ... Some of The Digger's bullets
were painted black. Only I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the FBI does find black bullets at the scene. Despite
objections, Mayor Gerald Kennedy decides to pay the ransom. The
FBI, led by Acting Special Agent in Charge Margaret Lukas, takes
the money to the designated field and waits for the terrorist, who
never shows. Eventually, Lukas and her colleagues learn the
terrorist was killed by a hit-and-run driver near City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The only clue is the ransom note, so Lukas asks Parker Kincaid,
the country's best expert in forensic document analysis, to help. A
single parent of two, Kincaid refuses until he learns a child was
killed in the subway carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Examining the note, he decides that the writer has planted red
herrings _ misspellings, bad grammar, etc. _ to make the FBI
believe its is not dealing with a brilliant criminal. The key clue
is the dotting of the i's _ a flourish known as the devil's
teardrop.
</P>
<P>
   With no way to contact the Digger, the FBI and Parker decide the
4 p.m. shooting scene most likely will be in D.C. Checking on what
large events are scheduled, Parker notices that a ``Nutcracker''
performance will be finishing just before 4. Lukas agrees to send
all her backup to the theater.
</P>
<P>
   The ending of this well-paced but truly deceptive thriller
caught me off guard. The analysis of the ransom note could have
been over-technical and boring, but Deaver makes it fascinating.
Full of good characters and dialogue, Deaver's writing is one of
the year's best thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don Winslow's arson thriller ``California Fire and Life''
(Alfred A. Knopf, $23, 337 pages) is a sure-fire, beach-book
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Nicky Vale is a power in Southern California real estate and the
local branch of the Russian mafia. When his wife dies in a fire at
their multimillion-dollar home, Los Angeles County Sheriff's
Department arson investigator Brian (``Accidentally'') Bentley
rules the cause is accidental because Pamela Vale had been drinking
and smoking in bed.
</P>
<P>
   The California Fire and Life Mutual Insurance Company holds the
policy on the Vale home. Crack arson investigator Jack Wade is
assigned to check out the fire before the policies are paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Bentley is sloppy, Wade discovers that the fire was
not accidental and begins a personal mission to prove that Vale
killed his wife to stop her from divorcing him _ and to collect
millions in fire insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Wade will run into Vietnamese chop shops, local
arsonists, Russian gangsters and his old love, Letita del Rio,
whose stepsister was Pamela Vale.
</P>
<P>
   ``California Fire and Life'' moves at a brisk pace. The
descriptions of Wade working the arson scene are engaging and
thought provoking. Good title. Good book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Spring brings a fresh eye to her second murder mystery,
``Nights in White Satin'' (Ballantine Books, $23, 276 pages),
featuring private investigator Laura Principal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball had taken place as May Balls should always do, on a
warm night in the middle of June _ a champagne-and-oysters kind of
night, following a strawberries-and-cream kind of day. By early
evening, even a stranger to the city could sense that something
extraordinary was about to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Principal's firm had been hired to provide security at Cambridge
University's annual ball marking the end of exams.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of young people arrived in swarms and ate and drank too
much. But little damage was done and Principal felt good about the
assignment until the next day when she is told that Katie
Arkwright, who wore white satin, has disappeared. Although Katie
wasn't a student at Cambridge, the university authorities ask
Principal to find out what happened to the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Principal learns of an upper-crust old boys' network
``conspiracy of silence'' to cover up a drunken assault months
before that involved Katie. Things grow more sinister when a
university dean is murdered in his office.
</P>
<P>
   The skeleton of a baby is found hidden in a student's room. And
Principal learns of a very dark side of the missing girl's past.
</P>
<P>
   Spring deftly has captured the essence of Cambridge and the
British upper class. Pert dialogue propels a well-paced plot line.
Perfect English cozy for a foggy weekend afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
