<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1785 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEYLAND-CONSTRUCTI     08-10 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEYLAND-CONSTRUCTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEYLAND MESSY OUTSIDE, STILL MAGIC INSIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
RUNS WITH DISNELAND-GO BOX and DISNEYLAND-PASSES 
Has art 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The signs of the times at Disneyland are bright
orange and bear messages that are inconsistent with the happiest
place on this or any planet: Uneven Pavement. Lane Closed. Detour.
Open Trench. Bump Ahead.
</P>
<P>
   There are other signs, purple ones, put up by the park itself.
They read: Great Things Are Happening! Pardon Our Progress! We're
Making Improvements!
</P>
<P>
   The latter ones seem to be strategically placed _ at locations
where visitors are most likely to be ensnarled in traffic, engulfed
in dust, assaulted by the beep-beep-beep of heavy equipment in
reverse gear. In the exclamation points on all those signs, you can
almost hear the high-pitched squeak of perpetual optimism and good
cheer.
</P>
<P>
   These are times of great upheaval for Disneyland and its
surrounding neighborhood in Anaheim, such that regular visitors
from Southern California should prepare for a test of their
patience. Three major construction projects are being conducted
simultaneously, and getting to, into and out of the popular theme
park can be a challenge _ particularly in the park's busy summer
season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; A 10-mile stretch of Interstate 5 is being widened to
accommodate the crush of traffic that passes daily through this
area of Orange County. New off-ramps that will funnel traffic
directly into Disneyland's parking areas are being constructed,
too. Currently, the construction mess begins around Beach Boulevard
on the I-5 south, about six miles from Disneyland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Several major side streets are being widened, improved,
beautified. Most of that work is nearing completion, but
negotiating such major thoroughfares as Harbor Boulevard, Katella
Avenue and Ball Road is still hectic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; That massive parking lot in front of Disneyland? It's all
but gone, plowed under to make room for a $1.4 billion addition _
theme park, hotel, shopping and entertainment area _ scheduled to
be up and running by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   To Disneyland's credit, however, the business of fantasy
continues as usual, with minimal disruption.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the parking has been shifted to grounds around the
Disneyland Hotel, directly west of the park, and high-tech trams,
using special routes that they don't have to share with any other
vehicles, regularly whisk visitors through and around the
construction zones to the ticket booths.
</P>
<P>
   And once you step through the main gates, you're only vaguely
aware of the construction chaos without.
</P>
<P>
   Your little ones can terrorize one of the big, fuzzy characters
walking about. Your teens can swelter in a 90-minute line for the
Rocket Rods _ if you're lucky enough to be there on a day when the
troubled attraction is not broken down. You, meanwhile, can
reminisce about the bygone days when there were mules, motor boats,
flying saucers and a ``house of the future'' built entirely out of
plastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The park is evolving and changing,'' said Disneyland spokesman
Ray Gomez. ``It's moving from a single theme park to a destination
resort, where people will want to come and spend several days,
enjoying both parks as well as shopping, entertainment and
dining.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the changes might cause Disneyland traditionalists to
raise a skeptical eyebrow. The new theme park in the old parking
lot will be titled the California Adventure, designed to tap into
the myth of the Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   One area will seek to re-create the beach amusement parks of old
(think Pacific Ocean Park). There will be a carnival-style midway
and conventional amusement park rides. The superstructure for a
Ferris wheel is already up, as is the framework for a looping
roller coaster _ built of steel, made to look like whitewashed
wood.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, that rumble you just felt was Walt Disney rolling over
in his grave.
</P>
<P>
   When Disney first attempted to launch his theme park in the
early 1950s, he wanted it to be in Burbank, near his movie and
animation studios, but city fathers weren't keen on the idea of
having a carny atmosphere so near. They couldn't know that Disney's
boundless imagination envisioned something entirely different: a
squeaky-clean environment with cleverly designed rides, from flying
elephants to a roller coaster-like attraction that would be
disguised as bobsleds hurtling down a famous Alp.
</P>
<P>
   Disney had no choice but to seek out some cheap orange-grove
land much farther south.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful he would be thrilled with what's on the design
table now, but it's been 33 years since his death in 1966, and
Disneyland, facing strenuous theme-park competition in Southern
California, feels it must broaden its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Braverman, the Walt Disney Imagineering executive
directing the new project, has said in interviews that California
Adventure will be a ``pop-culture'' park, and has invoked such
words as hip, irreverent and contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disneyland Resort will always be a family destination,'' said
Gomez, ``but at the same time, California Adventure will be an
altogether different experience. Disneyland is a place of fantasy.
California Adventure will immerse you in the California experience
_ the California dream, the myth of California.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of it lends itself to being a family experience, but you
can offer different types of experiences at different parks.''
</P>
<P>
   Another feature being built in the old parking lot is Downtown
Disney, an area of shops, restaurants and nightclub entertainment.
Also going in is a 750-room deluxe hotel in craftsman architecture,
which will offer upscale travelers an alternative to the tired '60s
ambience of the Disneyland Hotel complex.
</P>
<P>
   To make up for all the displaced parking spaces, an enormous
multilevel parking structure is being built just north of the
Disneyland Hotel, where a KOA campground used to stand. It's a long
way from the park entrance, which means the days of making the
sleepy-eyed walk from the main gates to the car are gone for good.
</P>
<P>
   While all of this is going up, Disneyland visitors can encounter
a minimum of construction-related inconvenience ... but only if
they plan in advance.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, the situation is much less chaotic than it was
at this time last year, when the detours to the I-5 seemed to be
extraordinarily convoluted.
</P>
<P>
   The most important step should be to obtain driving directions
from one of two Disneyland information outlets. On the Web, visit
www.disney.go.com/disneyland (click on ``Plan Your Visit,'' then on
``Disneyland Today''). You'll be able to indicate which geographic
area you're coming from to get specific directions. Or, if you
prefer to get this information from a person, call (714) 781-4560.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, driving directions are changed as the
construction projects reach different stages, and Disneyland
officials seem to present the most viable options.
</P>
<P>
   On two recent trips to the area, approaches were made from a
variety of directions in an attempt to find a quicker route than
the one officially suggested. All such efforts proved futile. Signs
prohibit left turns into the parking lot from some directions, for
example; it appears the traffic cops at Disney have taken great
pains to foil short-cut artists during the construction work.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site and the folks on the information line also provide
news of daily ride closures. Neither, however, alerts you to the
current disruption of the Monorail ride.
</P>
<P>
   A portion of its track runs right through the construction
project in the parking lot, so although the ride is still running,
it no longer operates in a loop between its Tomorrowland station
and the Disneyland Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, two trains work a one-way stretch of track to the
hotel, unload all passengers, fill up again, then run in reverse
back into the park. Signs warn that one leg of this short trip _
even after you've been let onto the loading platform _ can take a
half hour, and on a visit in mid-July, the journey required exactly
that.
</P>
<P>
   The disrupted Monorail service primarily impacts people staying
at the Disneyland Hotel _ also adults sneaking off to the hotel for
a better grade of food and a beverage that contains something other
than sugar, syrup and carbonated water.
</P>
<P>
   For the return trip to the park, if the Monorail line is
oppressively long, a better option is to jump a hotel tram. It
loads behind the adjacent Disneyland Pacific Hotel; that's a bit of
a walk, but there is no waiting.
</P>
<P>
   When it's time to leave Disneyland for the drive home, confusion
can reign anew. Maybe it's just my imagination, but it seems the
series of signs leading you into the park area is comprehensive and
clear, while the directions for your trip home are ... well, you're
kind of on your own.
</P>
<P>
   One key tip: When you're leaving the Pinocchio and Simba parking
lots at the Disneyland Hotel complex, be advised that the left turn
off Ball Road onto the northbound I-5 is no longer permitted _
because the on-ramp no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, you must turn right off Ball onto Harbor Boulevard
(southbound), then immediately careen left across three lanes of
traffic in hopes of catching the poorly marked and dimly lit
on-ramp for the I-5 north. There is minimal warning for this
maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   And, no, the sign doesn't have an exclamation point. After a day
of navigating the tumult that encircles Disneyland this summer,
that punctuation mark will be in your head. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
