<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-CRENSHAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDINAH'S MAJOR SUBPLOT IS RYDER CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ As he stood on the first tee at Medinah Country
Club Monday, Ben Crenshaw gazed out at the opening yards of a
demanding golf challenge that will no doubt prove too much for his
once-rich talents. The fairways are too tight, the rough too high,
the holes too long for a 47-year-old who has missed the cut in each
of his 12 starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   Having broken 70 just once in 25 rounds this year, Crenshaw
brings very little game into this 81st edition of the PGA
Championship. So why could he possibly be smiling?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because the Ryder Cup is less than two months away and
things couldn't have fallen together any sweeter for the United
States captain. Just a few weeks ago in New York, Crenshaw said,
``The team is shaping up nicely. I like what I'm seeing.'' This was
just after Payne Stewart clinched a spot, but before Justin Leonard
and Tom Lehman made their moves. All three are players he covets.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Crenshaw opted to be a player, not a coach. But it was
not lost on some observers whom he chose to head out onto the
course with: Leonard and Lanny Wadkins.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, like Crenshaw a Texan, figures to be a key member of
this year's team, and Wadkins is a close friend who went through
the rigors of being captain in 1995. Taking a little European hide
had to be the topic of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Championship, which gets under way Thursday at this
historic course outside Chicago, is the last chance for US players
to gather points. The top five (David Duval, Tiger Woods, Stewart,
Davis Love, and Mark O'Meara) have clinched spots. Hal Sutton and
Leonard are next and they appear to be locks.
</P>
<P>
   Those in spots 8-10 (Jim Furyk, Phil Mickelson, Jeff Maggert)
control their own fate, of course, though the mention of
Mickelson's name brings a smile to Crenshaw's face. He has said
that it is difficult for him to picture the team without Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   If Leonard and Mickelson maintain their Top 10 status, it would
give Crenshaw greater flexibility with his two captain's picks. One
good guess is Lehman (assuming he does not finish strongly here and
make the team automatically) and there's always the lurking
presence of Fred Couples. He is 17th, but he's been on the last
five teams and has displayed a fire for the Ryder Cup that isn't
apparent week in and week out. Throw in the fact that Couples is
immensley popular and you can be warned not to bet against Crenshaw
taking him.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Europeans, they have this week and next week's BMW
International Open before the points system comes to a close. And
unlike Crenshaw, captain Mark James has been playing well, though
not smiling. That's because his Top 10 features six rookies _ one
of whom, Jean Van de Velde, will take memories of his British Open
collapse to any match that goes to the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   The next two weeks are key events for Bernhard Langer (11th) and
Sergio Garcia (12th). One of them needs to move up, or else James
will be forced to choose between them for his second captain's
pick. (Jesper Parnevik is an obvious choice.) It would not have
seemed possible a few weeks ago, but the Europeans could come to
Brookline, Mass., without Garcia; he left Carnoustie shell-shocked,
played indifferently at the European Open, then missed the cut at
the Buick Open.
</P>
<P>
   A seasoned veteran such as Langer, some theorize, would be
better-suited for a young European team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Medinah CC will play to 7,401 yards, with only two holes under
400 yards (except for the par 3's, naturally). There is one tiny
par 5 of 530 yards, but the other three measure more than 580, and
three of the four par 3's are at least 206 yards. Which is to say,
the lads had better load up on their titanium.
</P>
<P>
   When Hale Irwin won the 1990 US Open here, the course played to
7,175 yards, though the PGA of America has graciously kept it to a
par 72. It is the longest course for a major championship held at
sea level. CBS commentator David Feherty told reporters that
Medinah has four par 3s, two par 6s, and 12 par 5s.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson was one of the first to get a look, playing the back
nine with Chris DiMarco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an excellent test of golf,'' said Mickelson. ``The golf
course requires a lot of great shot-making.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, see effects of the tough stretch of hot weather
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over half the greens were brown in color,'' said Mickelson.
``It just didn't look like it was healthy. I don't know if that's
going to present a problem or not. They certainly rolled fine; the
ball rolled over it fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
