<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1832 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-10 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED ISN'T IN HIGH GEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Manchester United juggernaut is off to a slow start. United,
which lost to Arsenal in the Charity Shield last week, tied
Everton, 1-1, at Liverpool in their English Premier League opener
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   United was at full strength, with strikers Andy Cole and Dwight
Yorke running rampant at the start of the game. Yorke scored in the
seventh minute, but United seemed vulnerable after that, unable to
outmaneuver 37-year-old central defenders Richard Gough and Dave
Watson. Gough, formerly of the Kansas City Wizards and San Jose
Clash, was named man of the match.
</P>
<P>
   Jaap Stam headed in an own goal in the 87th minute to tie the
score, but Everton deserved at least a draw after pressuring
goalkeeper Mark Bosnich, shaky in his debut as Peter Schmeichel's
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   There will be little time to reflect as United plays its home
opener against Sheffield Wednesday, giving an indication of the
overloaded schedule that prompted United to abandon the FA Cup
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United has already won the Triple Crown _ Premier
League, FA Cup, and Champions League _ and is going for a Grand
Slam against Lazio in the European Super Cup Aug. 27. As long as
superfluous themes are being assigned to its conquests, the
December meeting with Palmeiras in Tokyo for the Toyota Cup could
be labeled the Fifth Wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea showed that it could become United's top challenger
after a 4-0 wipeout of Sunderland that apparently could have been
much worse had striker Chris Sutton and his replacement, Tore Andre
Flo, been in sync with their teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Gianfranco Zola led the way for Chelsea, with strong support
from Frenchman Didier Deschamps and Uruguayan striker Gustavo
Poyet. With Deschamps anchoring the midfield in front of countrymen
Marcel Desailly and Frank Leboeuf, the Blues seem confident of
their chances of a first league title since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finding the range
</P>
<P>
   The decision of US national team coach Bruce Arena to allow
Claudio Reyna to remain with Rangers during the Confederations Cup
seems to be paying off for Reyna. Rangers took a 4-0 victory over
Hearts, and Reyna scored twice, giving him three goals in two
games. Reyna combined well with Dutchman Michael Mols, who set up
Reyna for a tap-in, then converted the second goal in first-half
injury time, and again set up German Jorge Albertz for the third.
But Parma, Rangers' opponent in the Champions Cup Tuesday in
Glasgow, will provide a tougher test . . . Bayern Munich is still
recovering from its stunning last-second loss to Manchester United
in the Champions League and German Cup final defeat. But Bayern
will be the favorite as it begins the Bundesliga season against
Hamburg Saturday. Stefan Effenberg, goalkeeper Oliver Kahn,
Ghanaian Sammy Kuffour, and Brazilian Paulo Sergio will miss the
game with injuries. And Paraguayan striker Roque Santa Cruz has
been barred from playing because he has not yet turned 18.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Troubling signs
</P>
<P>
   Martin Palermo missed another penalty kick, this time for Boca
Juniors. But Palermo, who had three failed penalties for Argentina
against Colombia in the Copa America last month, converted twice
and Diego Cagna once as Boca Juniors took a 3-0 victory over
Independiente. But Boca Juniors has other problems. President
Mauricio Macri announced that bonuses to players will be reduced
this season, despite the team's success. This placed doubt on Boca
Juniors' visit to Barcelona to play in the Trofeo de los Campeones
tournament this week, as the players threatened to rebel. ``We
aren't in a war but this already seems like Sarajevo,'' Jose
Basualdo told the Buenos Aires daily Clarin. Questions also have
been raised about Macri's refusal to pay expenses for a proposed
Diego Maradona farewell game. Maradona, 39, has yet to be honored
with the traditional sendoff match, despite assurances from Julio
Grondona, president of the Asociacion del Futbol Argentino. Last
week, a crowd of more than 70,000 packed River Plate's Estadio
Monumental for a testimonial game for Uruguayan midfielder Enzo
``El Principe'' Francescoli. Maradona's goodbye should be more on
the scale of a world tour than a single game . . . England,
Morocco, and South Africa led off proposals to organize the 2006
World Cup during meetings at FIFA headquarters in Zurich. The
English delegation was led by Bobby Charlton and Geoff Hurst.
Brazil sent Carlos Alberto, Dunga, Ronaldo, and Zico for Tuesday's
presentation. But Pele has called the Brazilian effort unrealistic
and refused to participate. In fact, Brazil has no chance of
winning. Germany, which had the approval of UEFA before England
entered the picture after the 1996 European Championships, also
will make its bid Tuesday, led by Franz Beckenbauer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just another gimmick
</P>
<P>
   MLS is considering a two-referee, two-linesman system for next
season. This is neither the right place nor time for such an
experiment. FIFA is attempting to evaluate the system, and Italy
will try it during its Coppa Italia competition starting this
month. How it functions in Italy should provide reliable data for
possible future use, since the Italian game has evolved over
decades and its referees are considered among the best in the
world. But MLS has so many weaknesses and wrinkles as to render
such an experiment worthless. No reliable conclusions can be made
until the league solves its other major problems, or at least until
it has evolved past an embryonic stage. If the system were tried in
Mexico, at least some relevant data could be compiled. The Mexican
league is mature, a rich and secure enterprise with a distinct
playing style, plus consistency in administration, coaching, and
refereeing. The two-referee, two-linesman system would be wasted on
MLS. It will be perceived as a gimmick by casual observers and
anyone with an elementary understanding of experimentation.
Gimmicks already seem to be a priority in MLS, and until quality
and substance become paramount, the league will not make progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
