<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE ALMOST HAD A SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the story of how America came within a hair trigger of
imposing realistic restrictions on the ownership of personal
arsenals. We didn't get so close because we got fed up with the
senseless slaughter on our streets. Nor was it because we grew
emotionally exhausted from the repeated episodes of 6-year-olds
accidentally gunning down their younger siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how it went:
</P>
<P>
   It began with a down day on Wall Street. The Dow plunged 180
points and a securities trader resorted to that peculiarly American
tonic for a bad day: a couple of handguns and a stroll through the
day-trading offices where he had lost his money. Afterward, nine
people lay on the carpet dead. We'd seen it before. We've had guns
massacre the innocent in our schoolyards, our restaurants, and our
homes. And nothing had ever been done.
</P>
<P>
   But this was different. This dangerous brew of falling stocks
and flying bullets was quick to spread. A month after its 180-point
drop, the Dow dipped 60 points and three people were mowed down at
a brokerage in Fort Lauderdale. The following week, when Martha
Stewart's IPO failed to measure up to expectations, blood gushed
through Cedar Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after that, Alan Greenspan, who had had bratwurst for
dinner the previous night, accidentally burped during his testimony
before Congress, and someone mistook the ``Urp'' for ``Up,'' which
was immediately misinterpreted as a forecast on the direction of
interest rates. The news flashed on Bloomberg screens across
America, stock prices swooned, and 16 people fell in a hail of
gunfire on the sidewalk in front of a Charles Schwab office in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Soon blood poured into the gutters with every quiver in the
market. No man woman or child was safe from the fluctuations of
Yahoo's stock price. Life expectancy dropped precipitiously for
employees of Merrill Lynch, Paine Webber, and Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   But then something else happened _ something far more chilling
than the wanton loss of life. As the blood rose above our hips,
climbing faster than Amazon.com once did, we lost our will to drive
the stock market higher. We knew that the slightest rise risked
another decline, and more spattering of our blood on walls and
windows and doors from Rochester to Eureka. Before we knew it true
horror struck: We had waded into the depths of the first bear
market in a generation. America had shot the market to death.
</P>
<P>
   After the market's demise, it wasn't long before the wheels of
commerce and industry ground to a halt. With blood in our hair,
blood on our shoes, blood beneath our fingernails, we had lost that
good old American spirit of buying and selling and buying and
buying and buying, and a long, brutal downturn ensued. Our magical
era of prosperity had collapsed before the barrel of a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Then _ and only then _ were voices raised in the corridors of
power to end the mayhem and the malaise. It was not warm and fuzzy
sentiment but cold economic reality that finally got Congress to
stand together behind a fearless leader and a promise to sweep up
the arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   The people were stirred. Hope filled the land. The guns were to
be seized, melted into a heap, and America was to get back to the
business of business.
</P>
<P>
   As momentum built for revolutionary change in America, the
fearless leader took the podium to proclaim a return to civilized
life, and a gunshot rang out, followed by another, and another _ so
many gunshots so fast it was impossible to count them _ and the
fearless leader fell fearlessly to his death.
</P>
<P>
   And no one stood up in his place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at
dollarsnonsense(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
