<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1839 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-YORKS-ART-BOS &LR;      08-10 1527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-YORKS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE`S A LOT OF MAINE TO ENJOY IN THE YORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   YORK, Maine _ A hot sun beats down on the crowded sands of York
Beach, where the air is fragrant with summer-at-the-seaside smells:
suntan lotion, the briny ocean, hot dogs with everything.
</P>
<P>
   Then another timeless summer scent comes through. It's saltwater
taffy, as it has been made for more than a century at the
Goldenrod, a seaside restaurant and candy shop that opened its
doors in 1896. Staff at the Goldenrod make ``Goldenrod Kisses'' in
front of a large plate-glass window _ boiling, pulling, rolling,
and cutting the taffy in full view of the street.
</P>
<P>
   As is invariably the case, this day a couple of little kids in
sandy bathing suits are pressing sunburned noses against the glass
chanting, ``Mommy, that smells good! I want some!'' They might not
realize it, but they are storing away a sensory memory of Maine
that may well bring them back, summer after summer, for the rest of
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Only a little over an hour's drive from Boston, York contains
all the attributes of coastal Maine that tourists often drive
another five hours or more _ to Bar Harbor and beyond _ to savor:
miles of sandy beaches and stretches of rocky cliff, lighthouses,
boat-filled coves and harbors, lobster pounds and seafood
restaurants, beachside amusement arcades, artists and galleries,
turreted grand hotels and ma-and-pa campgrounds, ship captains'
mansions and grand summer homes. And, of course, saltwater taffy
like the one your grandparents shared on their first visit to
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   In packing all this in, it helps that there is a lot of York.
The town, in fact, is divided into an almost bewildering number of
distinct villages and sections, including York Corners, York
Village, York Harbor, York Beach, and Cape Neddick. Samuel Clemens
(better known as Mark Twain) who frequently summered in southern
Maine, once observed that in York, ``It is difficult to throw a
brick in any one direction without danger of disabling a
postmaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Locals refer to this confederation of villages and hamlets
simply as ``The Yorks.'' That's also how it's marked by signposts
from Interstate 95 and Route 1. In summer, an open-sided trolley
circles the town, making several stops in each village. (A local
ride is $1.50, an hourlong narrated tour $3.)
</P>
<P>
   York insists that it's the oldest town in Maine, a claim
fiercely disputed by neighboring Kittery. Whatever the merits of
the rival claims, York Village or Old York was founded in 1630 and,
with its 17th-century burial ground and early colonial buildings,
certainly looks the part.
</P>
<P>
   The Old York Historical Society (207-363-4974) maintains seven
restored buildings in the heart of the village. The society's
visitors' center is in Jefferds Tavern (1759), just off York Street
(Route 1A). Nearby is the Old Gaol (1719), supposedly the oldest
remaining public building in the former English colonies.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibits in the Old Gaol, or jail, tell the dramatic story of
York's early years, in which numerous Native American attacks and a
massacre in which several hundred settlers died. The historical
society runs a gift shop on York Street and also organizes frequent
walking tours and special events. A ticket good for admission to
all the society's properties is $7 for adults and $3 for children.
</P>
<P>
   If you enjoy a good fright of an evening, Ghostly Tours
(207-363-0000) offers candlelit walks through the village led by a
hooded storyteller ($6 per person). There's also a candlelit ``Jail
Break'' tour of the Old Gaol's dungeons and cells, complete with
stories about escapes from them ($4 adults, $2 children).
</P>
<P>
   A mile-long walking trail, ``The Fisherman's Path,'' runs from
behind the George Marshall Store, a former ship chandler's in York
Village, to York Harbor. The trail follows the York River, passing
through Steedman Woods and crossing ``The Wiggly Bridge,'' an
engagingly shaky suspension bridge.
</P>
<P>
   York Harbor's heyday was in the last decades of the 19th
century, when yachtsmen and other well-to-do city folk began
flocking to the Maine coast, building ``cottages'' ranging from
unpretentious to imposing or spending weeks ``rusticating'' in
rambling resort hotels. Today, it still looks much as it did then
with old wooden boats at anchor in the harbor and dignified summer
homes lining narrow lanes. Some of the old cottages are now B &AMP; Bs,
however, and the Stage Neck Inn resort stands on the site of
Marshall House, York Harbor's pioneer hotel.
</P>
<P>
   A fine example of a ship owner's antique-filled 18th-century
mansion is the Sayward-Wheeler House on Barrell Lane in York
Harbor, maintained by the Society for the Preservation of New
England Antiquities (603-436-3205). Admission is $4 for adults, $2
for children.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to get out on the water and learn about lobsterin',
Captain Tom Harmon (a retired high school science teacher) takes up
to six people with him on his lobster boat as he checks traps and
hauls in crustaceans. Harmon departs from the Town Dock in York
Harbor hourly from 10 a.m. to 2 p.m. Monday through Friday. The
charge is $7.50 per person. (For information or reservations, call
207-363-3234).
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary working folk discovered Maine in the last century, too,
and York Beach _ a so-called streetcar resort _ was developed to
accommodate them. In contrast to adjacent York Harbor, the cottages
here are mostly small, modest, and close together; there are also
two tent and trailer parks. York Beach isn't fancy, but it's
friendly and still looks and feels like a Victorian family resort.
</P>
<P>
   There are actually two beaches, Long Beach and Short Sands, both
broad, sandy, and facing the open Atlantic. Long Beach is
particularly noted for its surfing. The York Parks and Recreation
Department (207-363-1040) rents kayaks at the beach for $10 an hour
or $25 for a full day.
</P>
<P>
   In between the beaches is Nubble Point and just off the point,
on its own little island, is Nubble Light. This lighthouse, which
has a red-roofed keeper's house attached, is arguably the most
photographed in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   At the tip of Nubble Point is a small public park with a parking
area, restrooms, and an information center. Here, too, is Fox's
Lobster House, which serves lobsters every way from basic boiled to
baked stuffed and deep fried, and has a great view of both the
ocean and the lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Another gustatory attraction on Nubble Point is Brown's Old
Fashioned Ice Cream, a small stand with a large parking lot for the
hordes of ice cream lovers it attracts. A perennially popular
flavor is wild blueberry; the newest offering is Y2K _ French
vanilla, with chocolate, peanut butter, and malted milk balls mixed
in .
</P>
<P>
   York Beach's dining and entertainment hub is at Short Sands.
It's an old-fashioned scene, featuring a boardwalk lined with
arcades, souvenir shops, beachware boutiques, and hot dog stands.
Like the Goldenrod, most of the buildings date from around the turn
of the century.
</P>
<P>
   A block from the beach is York's Wild Kingdom (207-363-4911),
the largest zoo and amusement park in southern Maine and home to
the state's only white Bengal tiger. Other attractions include
elephant rides, an 18-hole miniature golf course, a carousel, and a
petting zoo. A combination zoo admission and amusement park ticket
is $13.75 for adults, $9.75 for children age 4 to 10, and $3.75 for
children 3 and under.
</P>
<P>
   The village of Cape Neddick, just north of York Beach along
Shore Road (Route 1A), clusters around a small, sheltered cove
where lobster boats anchor. The Cape Neddick Lobster Pound has an
attractive dining room and an outside deck, both looking out on the
water.
</P>
<P>
   Besides beaches and coastline, York also has its own mountain:
Mount Agamenticus, the name of the original Native American
settlement. Agamenticus is only 580 feet high but locals boast that
it's the highest hill on the Atlantic seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   A ski slope at one time, Mount Agamenticus is now a town park,
with both a paved road and a hiking trail leading to the summit.
The park and recreation department rents mountain bikes from its
office on Church Street in York Beach, $15 for a half day, $20 for
a full day. Agamenticus Riding Stables (207-361-2840), located at
the summit, charges $25 for a one-hour trail ride, $40 for a
two-hour one.
</P>
<P>
   There is a fine view down the coast in both directions from the
summit of Agamenticus. It may not be quite as spectacular as that
from the Bar Harbor area's Cadillac Mountain, but it's not bad. And
it's only about an hour away.
</P>
<P>
   To reach The Yorks from Boston, take Interstate 95 north to Exit
4 and follow signs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yorks Chamber of Commerce visitors center, attractively
housed in a replica of a classic York Harbor cottage, is on Route
1, directly across from the entrance to the I-95 connector. For
information about the area stop by, call 207-363-7320, or visit
www.yorkme.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
