<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1842 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENNOCH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-10 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING FOR THE GOLD AT THE COUNTRY CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A businessman gushed recently over breakfast about the
``exuberance of corporate spending.'' He wasn't talking about the
thrill of eating an egg-white-only omelette on someone else's
expense account. He was talking about the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In its narrowest definition, the Ryder Cup is about golf. What
golfers, from hackers to pros, consider the sport's premiere
tournament will be played at The Country Club in Brookline, Mass.
in September.
</P>
<P>
   But don't let the narrow definition blind you to a larger
reality. The Ryder Cup is about much more than poking little white
balls onto perfectly groomed greens. It's a prime illustration of
the exclusionary power of the corporate elite and how it chooses to
spend its money. It also vividly depicts today's sports-driven
culture and value system. Does that sound overly dramatic? Consider
this:
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup could generate as much as $150 million in direct
and indirect spending, according to Patrick B. Moscaritolo,
president and CEO of the Greater Boston Convention and Visitors
Bureau. If it does, it won't beat the 100th running of the Boston
Marathon in 1996, which generated close to $170 million. But here's
a key distinction. The 1996 marathon was a true people's event.
There were 38,000 runners, 10,000 from outside the United States.
One million men, women, and children lined the route. As individual
participants and fans, they spent millions on food, hotels,
souvenirs, and other items.
</P>
<P>
   Money generated by the Ryder Cup is almost exclusively the
product of high-end corporate spending. The Massachusetts Port
Authority is worried about running out of landing space for all the
corporate jets due to fly into town for the event. Golf courses
within a 40- to 50-mile radius of Boston will be leased by
corporations who want to provide their clients with the best
possible golf experience during their Ryder Cup stay.
</P>
<P>
   From tables to tents, the pricetag for claiming a slice of
coveted turf on The Country Club course ranges from $50,000 to
$500,000. Clients who receive treasured tickets will watch the
tournament in air-conditioned comfort. For $275 more, they'll have
butler service. As they watch the best in golf drive, chip, and
putt, the lucky can order smoked salmon platters, iced micro brews,
``first tier'' Chardonnay, shrimp, and sushi. Gross revenue will be
about $63 million. The PGA will net an estimated $16.5 million. The
Country Club should net $5 million to $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   To state the obvious, the sports world is a big-money world, and
corporations are eager to participate. But how exuberant are they
when it comes to sharing their wealth with those outside their
circle?
</P>
<P>
   Basically, it is up to the local host to force the sports
industry and its corporate support base to reach out to the
community and the ordinary fan. Mayor Thomas M. Menino, for
example, seized the moment during the recent Major League Baseball
All-Star Game with the staging of a City Hall Plaza celebration
that drew a crowd of 30,000. The John Hancock Fanfest drew 110,000
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sending the message out to professional sports that
there has to be a side for the general public,'' says Menino.
They're the ones out there supporting it, day in and day out. Their
allegiance doesn't depend on the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   The Country Club is donating 300 Ryder Cup tickets to the City
of Boston. The city, in turn, is looking to sell what it calls
``Franklin Park Corporate Packages'' to create a $1 million
endowment for sports programs for city youth. One table costs
$55,000. Ten of 30 tables remain to be sold.
</P>
<P>
   The Town of Brookline is also getting $3 million from The
Country Club. But Brookline's effort to stage a 10-day ``golf
experience'' similar to the Hancock Fanfest has so far been
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   A Southborough, Mass. company, Corporate Communications Inc.,
won a bid in May to stage the event. But it could not raise the
$500,000 it needed from corporate underwriters, according to
company spokesman Bob Dobinski. The corporate money was already
committed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town is committed to providing a community celebration for
the Ryder Cup,'' says Dobinski, who is now looking for corporate
backing for a scaled-down, one-day event.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball and golf are very different sports with appeals to very
different audiences. Still, golf is increasing in popularity.
Especially for baby boomers, it's a good way to do business. The
knees are going fast, ruling out pickup basketball games and
tennis. Besides, it's hard to close a deal when you are on the
gallop and gasping for air. A golf course offers fresh air, a
modicum of exercise, and a civilized way to entertain clients.
</P>
<P>
   The world of golf is expanding, but it has a long way to go
before it has the kind of critical mass to force change and a
broader social conscience onto privately run tournaments like the
Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime _ smoked salmon, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
