<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1845 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMUSEMENT-ACCIDENTS-A     08-10 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMUSEMENT-ACCIDENTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMAND FOR RISKY RIDES PRODUCING DEATHS, INJURY AT PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Rebudgeting as feature with graphics.)  
 (ART ADV.: Two graphics are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGAWAM, Mass. _ As authorities investigate a weekend water-ride
accident at Riverside Amusement Park, a digital-age drive for the
fastest, tallest, longest, or roughest ride is feeding competition
for the ultimate attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it's pretty much an all-out war between the parks
to try to build the highest and most intense rides,'' said David
Escalante of American Coaster Enthusiasts, a Kansas-based
hobbyists' group. ``That's the number one thing that is attracting
their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   While strongly defending its safety record, Riverside Park's
operator said Monday it has closed 17 water-rafting rides in its
parks nationwide in response to Saturday's accident on a thrill
ride here. Eight people were hurt, one man critically.
</P>
<P>
   The US Consumer Product Safety Commission, in a report last
month, said injuries on amusement park rides are rising sharply,
sending 9,200 people to emergency rooms for treatment last year, up
from 7,400 in 1994 _ a 24 percent spike that outpaces increased
park attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'd be naive to say they're not competing for a group
of people who want to try out everything,'' said Lowell Gratigny, a
senior vice president at American Specialty Insurance Services, an
amusement park risk management firm based in Indiana. ``They want
the quickest or the highest. They're in the entertainment business
and that's what makes the folks come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for those thrills turned to instant terror around
9:30 Saturday night when the 2-month-old Blizzard River ride,
touted by the park as ``more than 1,400 feet of bends and
bottlenecks,'' plunged its patrons into the water in a capsized
raft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like we were lost forever,'' said Kimberly Pescaro, 27.
``As we bumped along the bottom every now and then we would hit
little air pockets and I would be able to stretch my head back and
grab a breath of air ... We were strapped in our seats, upside-down
in the water. All I could think of was that I would never see my
8-month-old son again.''
</P>
<P>
   Pescaro, of Shrewsbury, suffered a concussion on the ride in
which passengers float down the shallow, artificial river in large
round rafts propelled by the force of the churning water. Her
husband, Jerry, needed several stitches for a cut in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Six other rafters were taken to Baystate Medical Center in
Springfield. John Pascone of Dayville, Conn., was in critical
condition Monday. His 9-year-old daughter, Angelica, and 4-year-old
son, Jonathan, were in fair condition. His wife, Kimberly was
treated and released on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Messier, 27, of Coventry, R.I., was in serious condition
Monday at Baystate. Her husband, Ernest, 32, was treated and
released. John and Jonathan Pascone and Susan Messier were admitted
for near-drowning. Angelica Pascone was admitted with a right
shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   Park operators called the accident ``unfortunate'' and promised
a rigorous review.
</P>
<P>
   While local building officials are responsible for checking the
safety of amusement park rides, inspectors from the state
Department of Public Safety are assisting local police and
engineers hired by the park to determine what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be very deliberate in our approach to this
examination therefore there is not a timetable for us to arrive at
the conclusion,'' said Brent Gooden, a spokesman for Premier Parks,
which owns and operates Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden said the 17 rides ordered shut down nationwide by the
company were made by various manufacturers. The company operates
parks from California to Georgia, New Jersey to Colorado, including
all of the Six Flags parks.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's accident was the second this year involving a
water raft ride at a Premier-operated park.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a woman was killed and 10 people were hurt when a
similar raft carrying 12 people capsized on the Roaring Rapids ride
at Premier's Six Flags Over Texas park. In that case, an
investigation found that five of the 12 inflatable ``bladders'' had
lost air pressure, causing them to ride low in the water _ one in a
series of ``extraordinary'' events that park officials said caused
the fatal mishap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six Flags delivers 1.5 billion safe rides a year and our
roller coasters will travel the equivalent of 70 orbits around the
Earth in a season and carry roughly 140 million riders,'' said
Gooden, who called amusement parks safer than water skiing or a
swim in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But William J. Buckley, the US editor of First Drop, a
London-based magazine that focuses on thrill rides and new
technologies, said the race for the big thrill is pushing some
parks too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really surprised to see this happen,'' said Buckley,
who is based in Maynard. ``There have been other instances of this
accident just this year. I think you're going to see sweeping
changes in the industry in regard to the design and fabrication of
this ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley believes competition from other nearby water rides was
among the factors that contributed to Riverside Park's decision to
add the Blizzard River ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend in the industry is to make these wetter rides with
taller, wetter waves,'' Buckley said. ``A good river rapid ride is
judged on just how completely soaked you can get its guests.
Basically, it's not even healthy competition. It's rabid
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Malman, a Denver attorney representing a Colorado woman
who said she lost her memory on a roller coaster at Six Flags
Elitch Gardens park, said today's amusement parks are simply
misnomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're raising the stakes by making them more and more
dangerous,'' Malman said. ``Everyone's going after that dollar and
therefore they have to make them more thrilling. They argue that
there's a very small minority of people who get hurt so there's
nothing they can do about it. And, unfortunately, juries tend to
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Graff, president of the International Association of
Amusement Parks and Attractions, an Alexandria, Va.-based trade
group, blamed the recent US Consumer Product Safety Commission
statistics showing a jump in accidents on a change in reporting
methods that his group is working to correct.
</P>
<P>
   Graff said it's natural that parks promote the superlatives of
their rides.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's certainly the way to market, sure,'' he said. ``You say
you've got the tallest roller coaster in the world or something.
But you usually only get to claim that for about a month before
somebody else puts in another loop or goes you one better.''
</P>
<P>
   And at Riverside Park Monday, the search for a thrilling ride
was still ringing the cash registers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love 'em. The more danger the better,'' said Bob Rouillier,
a charter bus driver from Pawtucket, R.I. ``It takes you to the
peak ... you know that thrill, that peak of the rush. I don't feel
like I'm going to be harmed. One accident out of how many rides?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Correspondents Marcia Stamell and Ryan Davis contributed to
this report. Wire service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
