<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1853 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART     08-10 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL EXTENSION MAY BE TOO MUCH OF A STRETCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My name is Pete Carroll. I am the head coach of the New England
Patriots. I am not worried about being fired this season. Fired?
Please. What I really want to know is this: When do I get my
contract extended?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that's what I was thinking before we began this
conversation. Lately I've been contemplating an ultimatum meeting
with my boss, Bob Kraft, at his office. (He likes me to call him
``Robert,'' but he's Bob today with me. I'm in that kind of mood.
Don't mess with me.)
</P>
<P>
   His secretary will ask if I have an appointment. I'll say I
don't need one. I'll walk into the office and sit in the boss's
favorite chair. I'll boldly take a sip of his coffee, prop my feet
on his desk, and tell him to have a seat and listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extend my original five-year contract or fire me now,'' I'll
say. I'll feel good when I say it. I've been quiet too long.
</P>
<P>
   I've had this job for two seasons and for two seasons I've had
no true job security, despite my contract. You could call me ``Head
Man Sulking.'' I'm the Ron Mercer of football coaches, always
rumored to be going somewhere else. I've been a coach for three
seasons and been in the playoffs two of them. When my team makes
the playoffs this year, I will become the first coach in Patriots
history to lead a team to the postseason three consecutive seasons.
Bill Parcells never did that, OK?
</P>
<P>
   ``You heard me correctly, Bob-o,'' I'll say. ``Extend or
dismiss.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be my third straight season with a different starting
running back. My middle linebacker, Ted Johnson, had a right biceps
injury in '98; he has a left biceps injury in '99. I've got guys on
my team who still look to Parcells for approval after they make a
play against the Jets. You want to talk about fired? I wish I could
fire those guys. I went into the last two games of '98 with Scott
Zolak as my starting quarterback. Hey, I know you're not a coach.
But let's say you were. Would you have Zolak as your starter if you
needed to win one of two games to get you to the playoffs? I love
Zo, but come on.
</P>
<P>
   My team was humiliated by the Jets in the last game of '98. In
the first game of '99, we were crushed by the Jaguars in the
playoffs. That's when I discovered that my office is not really
based in Foxborough; it's more like Alcatraz. My bosses left me on
an island for weeks before saying that my job was safe. I heard
they were fascinated by Jets assistant Bill Belichick. Why would
you want to hire a guy who publicly admits to being a Jon Bon Jovi
fan?
</P>
<P>
   I have some different assistants this year because some were
fired. And it's going to be hard for me to recruit others when they
don't know what my job status is. That's why I'm going to visit the
boss. I want to make things clear. I am tired of hearing about The
Tuna and his transcendent talks with the media. I am tired of
writers and fans speaking in puns about me, saying things like,
``Carroll will be going bye-bye in the Patriots' bye week.'' I am
tired of the mixed messages. I am criticized for not being tough
with the players, but at one point last season players were able to
go to management and evaluate me.
</P>
<P>
   I'm an angry man right now. I've been too good of a company man.
So much so that people forget that Pete Carroll was an exceptional
defensive coordinator in his day (I always wanted to be like an
athlete and speak in the third person).
</P>
<P>
   And let's say my team does go 7-9 this year. Does that make me a
bad coach? A 7-9 season would give me a career record of 33-33.
Parcells, one of the greatest coaches of all time, was 36-27-1 in
his first four years. He also won a Super Bowl in his fourth year,
but remember that he was 3-12-1 in his first season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting ridiculous around here,'' I'll say, borrowing a
quote from Lawyer Milloy. I'll finish the coffee and tell Bob to
get me a refill, no cream. ``I demand to be given an extra year on
my deal, just to compensate for all my aggravation.''
</P>
<P>
   You think I am foolish. But I've got leverage. No way Kraft
fires me now. It is Aug. 10. He knows firing me before the first
preseason game would distract from the season. How can you fire a
coach during training camp? Plus, if he did fire me now, he would
have a hard time getting a big-time coach in here. They would all
wonder about him, not me. I've got leverage, baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I want our extension to be in writing. In clear English,''
I'll say. ``None of this `Memorandum of Understanding' stuff that
John Rowland signed for Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   I can see Kraft looking with increased interest now. The mention
of Rowland has reminded him of his new stadium in Foxborough. He
already has some trailer park residents giving him resistance. He
doesn't need resistance right now from anyone. He will give in. He
will give me my new deal. I deserve it. He knows Pete Carroll goes
out there and gets the job done and gives 110 percent because Pete
Carroll loves the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Pete,'' he'll say to me after a long pause, ``why didn't
you tell me you felt this way? I would have done something a long
time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes. Peace of mind and a new contract. Finally.
</P>
<P>
   I can see Kraft reaching into his desk to pull out a slip of
paper with my name already on it. The slip is pink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, Robert?'' I'll say, taking my feet down from the desk.
``Now that I've had time to think about it, contract extensions are
overrated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
