<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATINGS IN SUMMER AREN'T SO HOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no wonder television executives resort to
pay-for-television events to boost ratings during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend offered ample evidence. With the exception of the
Red Sox, not one event captured significant ratings numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA? Saturday's game pulled a .39, Sunday's a .82. That's a
little more than 1 ratings point combined, or a total of 22,000
households.
</P>
<P>
   The Major League Soccer match between the Mutiny and United
Sunday earned a .7.
</P>
<P>
   Yippee.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox pulled a 6.2 on Channel 25 Saturday, and considering
the great weather that day, it is a considerable achievement.
</P>
<P>
   But not all reliable sports can put up the numbers all the time.
The American Bowl, a football game featuring the Denver Broncos
against the San Diego Chargers Saturday night, netted only a 2.69
rating on Channel 25, just about what the Brickyard 400 auto race
got on Channel 5 that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out of sight
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's Red Sox game against the Anaheim Angels was not
televised because of the exclusive deal between ESPN and Major
League Baseball that prohibits broadcasts of any game on Sunday
nights except the one on ESPN. The Angels could have moved the
start time up to allow television coverage but chose not to.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Famous last words
</P>
<P>
   CNN/SI interviewed two of the most maligned and misunderstood
players talking about their induction into the Pro Football Hall of
Fame. ``I am in the Hall of Fame regardless,'' Lawrence Taylor said
on CNN/SI's ``Page One.'' ``Whether you like me or not, every time
you visit that place you are going to see my face inside that
building.'' It's not a pretty face. George Martin, who played with
LT, said, ``A transformation would take place when he'd put on his
uniform. He would be transformed into this homicidal maniac.''
Taylor's former coach, Bill Parcells, was able to handle the
transformation. ``He's the greatest player I ever coached,''
Parcells told CNN/SI. ``I really love him with all of my heart. I
really do. And it's just like he's like one of my own kids. When he
starts with his hands, he's lying. If he talks straight, he's
telling the truth. If you see him when he starts to emphasize
something, he's not telling you the truth. See, that's something I
know about him, that he doesn't even know that I know.'' Eric
Dickerson's thoughts on the Hall of Fame were similar to Taylor's.
``No matter what people or the media think,'' Dickerson said, ``I
didn't do it perfect, but I did do it right.'' . . . CNN/SI will
have nightly highlight shows from the 81st PGA Championship nightly
at 8:30 and 11:30. It starts coverage with a preview special
Wednesday hosted by Johnny Phelps and Bobby Clampett. The
late-night shows will not air on Saturday and Sunday . . . CBS and
TNT will share coverage of golf's fourth major, a combined 28 hours
worth. TNT provides early-round coverage Thursday and Friday from
1-7 p.m. and picks up play Saturday and Sunday from 10:30 a.m.-1
p.m. CBS has the final two rounds on Saturday and Sunday from
1:30-6:30 p.m. Jim Nantz and Ken Venturi host CBS's coverage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox is jumping
</P>
<P>
   Ratings for Fox's ``Game of the Week'' baseball telecasts have
jumped 10 percent from last year. The Saturday afternoon games are
averaging a 3 rating, up from 2.7. Fox Sports Net's ratings for
Thursday night games also have jumped 18 percent, to a .91 average
. . . The NBA has signed a deal with Viewer's Choice to allow
viewers to subscribe to NBA League Pass, a digital television
package featuring as many as 40 games per week from outside a
subscriber's local viewing area. Early birds get the $169 package
for $149.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
