<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1856 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      08-10 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Developments: President Yeltsin and Putin, his
new prime minister, meet in the Kremlin on the crisis in Dagestan,
where on Tuesday an Islamic council proclaimed the republic's
independence. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi) _ India shoots down a Pakistani naval
reconnaissance plane, killing the 16 people on board. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS (Belgrade) _ Political developments from the
Yugoslav capital. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-PEACEKEEPERS (United Nations) _ Holding out against the
opposition of troop-contributing countries and legal challenges,
Secretary General Kofi Annan decides to impose, by what amounts to
executive order, a code of behavior on U.N. peacekeepers that is in
line with the Geneva conventions. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ATTACK (Jerusalem) _ A Palestinian rams his car into
hitchhiking Israeli soldiers _ twice _ injuring 12 before he's shot
to death. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   EICHMANN-MEMOIR (Jerusalem) _ Israel announced Tuesday that it
would release Adolf Eichmann's jailhouse memoirs, which have been
kept under wraps in Israel's national archives since his execution
in 1962. The Justice Ministry said the 1,300 pages, in which
Eichmann tries to portray himself as a mid-level official who only
followed Hitler's orders, would be released at the ``earliest
opportunity'' in a scholarly fashion, with background and
commentary. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GORE (Washington) _ President Clinton to appear at a
fund-raiser for Al Gore. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-POLITICS (Washington) _ The statements of George W. Bush,
Elizabeth Dole and John McCain about homosexuals signals a
softening of the Republican positions on this subject, but alarming
some conservatives in the party. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-SECURITY (Atlanta) _ As they prepare for the fall
semester, schools institute security measures in response to
shootings around the country, even as the government reports that
fewer guns were found in schools last year. While metal detectors
and more secure entry systems have been installed in many places,
officials in other schools feel that reaching out to students and
coordination with law-enforcement officials will be more effective
than new hardware. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JACKSON-DEATH (Undated) _ Flash -- Doctors Cleared in
Presidential Murder Case! Studying Andrew Jackson's hair clippings,
scientists conclude that his doctors did not poison him after all.
The so-called ``plumbism'' he died of was from lead leaking out of
bullets that remained in his body, not treatments the docs gave him
for whatever else was ailing him. By Abigail Zuger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ALUMINUM-MERGER (Rome) _ Pechiney of France, Alsuisse Lonza of
Switzerland and Alcan Aluminium Ltd. of Canada say they are in
talks to form the world's largest aluminum production and packaging
company. A merger would create a smelting, packaging and chemicals
company with more than $20 billion revenue, overtaking Alcoa Inc.
as the world's biggest aluminum maker. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The government and Microsoft
lay out their presentations of what they regard as the facts in the
antitrust case _ their legal effort to sway the judge's ultimate
findings. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks are down in mid-afternoon. The Dow
Jones industrial average was down 102 points, the Nasdaq composite
index is down 62 points. The 30-year bond was at 6.25 percent.
European markets were also lower, with London down 1.72 percent and
Frankfurt down 2.07 percent. Japan's Nikkei closed up 0.07 percent,
while the Hong Kong Hang Seng index fell 2.69 percent. By Kenneth
N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-EXTORT (Tokyo) _ Kaoru Ogawa is the most prominent of the
remaining survivors of the government's war on the sokaiya, as
Japan's oddly high-profile corporate extortionists are known. At a
recent shareholder's meeting, he proudly introduced himself as the
famous sokaiya who was recently released from jail. But now even he
is turning to other lines of business and seeking to soften his
racketeering image. The crackdown on sokaiya has resulted in a
remarkable forced retrenchment among a group that was formerly so
sharp- elbowed that corporations paid large sums of money to keep
them at bay. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT-ACQUIRE (Undated) _ Lucent Technologies Inc. agrees to
buy computer network integrator International Network Services for
$54 a share, or $3.7 billion, to move further into data networking.
By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   SOROS-APPOINT (Undated) _ Soros Fund Management, whose flagship
$6.7 billion Quantum Fund has declined about 11 percent this year,
goes outside its ranks to recruit Duncan Hennes, Bankers Trust's
former treasurer, as the hedge fund firm's first-ever chief
executive. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   WALMART-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Wal-Mart Stores Inc. reports a 21
percent gain in second-quarter earnings, better than expectations.
By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   GM-ECOMMERCE (Detroit) _ General Motors forms a new business
group focused on e-commerce. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly travel column. By Edwin
McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
