<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DATA GENERAL SALE ENDS ERA OF HIGH-TECH GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And then there were none.
</P>
<P>
   Data General Corp., the last high-tech titan from the glory days
of the Massachusetts Miracle, agreed to be sold Monday for $1.05
billion to EMC Corp., a bigger and better focused competitor in the
dull but booming business of computer data storage.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wang Laboratories Inc., Digital Equipment Corp., and Prime
Computer Inc. before it, Data General struggled and ultimately
failed to pull off one of high technology's most demanding feats:
reinventing itself.
</P>
<P>
   Those four thrived on the high-tech edge when minicomputers used
by businesses were the hot new machines of the early 1980s. When
technology moved on to embrace the personal computer, they were
unable to come up with a compelling second act.
</P>
<P>
   Prime gave up the ghost a decade ago, selling out to a venture
capital firm to avoid a hostile suitor. Digital and Wang tried to
embrace the service economy, building maintenance and consulting
businesses that catered to customers that already owned computer
systems. They have both been sold in the last 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   Data General, the company and creative culture featured in Tracy
Kidder's Pulitzer Prize-winning book ``The Soul of a New Machine,''
stuck to hardware and tried to build a place in a new high-tech
niche.
</P>
<P>
   It found neither success nor outright failure making computer
network servers and storage devices. The company's sales remained
stubbornly stuck at about $1 billion a year for more than a decade.
Data General wouldn't die but couldn't seem to grow. Finally,
Monday, it was time to cash in and sell the business to a new
generation technology leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, they could never get away from that billion-dollar
level,'' said Barry Fidelman, once a Data General executive in the
company's heyday and now a venture capitalist based in Boston.
``This is the way the story somehow had to end.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the way the story often ends. For an industry shaken so
regularly by revolutionary change, high technology produces
strikingly few adaptable companies.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and computer industry veterans say companies don't
change for a handful of reasons. First, there are only so many
great new ideas unspoiled by established competition.
</P>
<P>
   And companies that have made a name for themselves in one field
simply resist moves into a new business. The best talent, and a
company's resources, remain glued to the corporate bread and
butter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're doing well they feel they don't need to reinvent
themselves, and when they're doing poorly they feel they can't
afford to,'' said David Hill of the Aberdeen Group, a high-tech
consulting firm in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Computer revolutions also have a habit of crushing the
profitability of old business models, grinding down the percentage
of every sales dollar a company keeps after expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The minicomputers designed by Data General, Digital Equipment,
and Prime were once a dramatically cheaper and more flexible
alternative to big mainframe computers.
</P>
<P>
   Then something even more flexible and inexpensive arrived _ the
PC. And it practically ran the minicomputer out of business. Now,
the Internet poses similar threats to software companies whose
products run on personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   There is no end to the list of companies that made a name and a
fortune on one generation of technology and didn't want to let go
of the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Digital, once the world's second-largest computer maker, tried
its own line of personal computers in 1984 and failed miserably.
Digital was initially reluctant to give its own personal computers
full support from the very top in 1984 and the high-tech world
raced by. The ultimate irony: Digital was purchased last year by a
leading personal computer maker, Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts argue that Data General missed opportunities to
exploit early technical advantages and own early leadership roles
in products like laptop computers and electronic messaging.
</P>
<P>
   But it did develop computer storage technology that was widely
respected, and data storage has become a fast-growing industry. The
problem was that Data General didn't get there first.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that have to compete against an established leader
face an uphill battle. They often must persuade big clients to dump
the equipment and systems already purchased from the industry
leader to make headway, dislodging the so-called ``installed
base.''
</P>
<P>
   EMC is the leader in storage, and it is getting more competition
from very big competitors like IBM Corp. Data General didn't have
the firepower to compete on their level.
</P>
<P>
   Rare as they are, a few technology companies have made
successful leaps to new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp. was locked in hopeless price competition for
computer memory years ago when it evolved into the world leader of
processing microchips, the ``Intel inside'' personal computer
microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. was another minicomputer manufacturer in the
1980s, but it moved successfully into computer printers and other
products. The company could adapt because it was a more diversified
business from the start, organized and culturally atuned to change
with the times.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe Microsoft Corp.'s abrupt move into the
Internet in the late 1990s will be seen one day as an astute
business decision. Money generated by Microsoft's Internet ventures
are a drop in the bucket compared to the profits from its Windows
computer operating software, but that could change.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is taking precisely the path many declining companies
failed to choose years ago: moving seriously into a new technology
with paltry profit margins compared to those of its very fat cash
cow.
</P>
<P>
   EMC is another technology company at the very cutting edge of
its field, just like Data General, Digital, Prime Computer, and
Wang years before.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be able to change when the time comes?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
