<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1858 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-10 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP GROUP NOW A TRIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be a perfecta, with trainers D. Wayne Lukas, who was
inducted into the Hall of Fame Monday, and Bob Baffert dominating
the national scene. But after the last two weekends, it has become
a trifecta, as Elliott Walden joined the list.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 1, Walden saddled 4-year-old Victory Gallop to a triumph
in the Whitney Handicap at Saratoga, and Victory Gallop now has a
legitimate chance to be handicap champion and Horse of the Year.
Last Sunday, Walden went over the top with his 3-year-olds, as
first Ecton Park won the Jim Dandy at The Spa, and then Menifee
captured the $1 million Haskell Invitational at Monmouth. Many
observers think Menifee, who was second to Charismatic in both the
Kentucky Derby and Preakness before running a poor eighth in the
Belmont Stakes, is the best of the sophomores. Menifee may go on to
prove them right.
</P>
<P>
   Walden, 36, was born in Lexington, Ky. His late father, Ben Sr.,
was a consummate horseman, and his brother, Ben Jr., is also in the
business. Walden, who started as a groom, worked for LeRoy Jolley,
Dennis Ebert, and John Gosden before taking out his own license in
1985. Walden was long known as a top trainer at Churchill Downs,
but emerged into the spotlight only when Victory Gallop ran second
to Real Quiet in the Kentucky Derby and Preakness in 1998, then
took the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   In the Haskell, Menifee defeated Cat Thief, trained by Lukas, by
a half-length, and Cat Thief was, in turn, a half-length in front
of Forestry, trained by Baffert. A son of Harlon, out of a Never
Bend mare, Menifee sports a career record of 9-5-3-0, and has more
than $1.5 million in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the true Menifee who showed up today,'' said Walden.
``It's great to see him back in top form after the disappointing
Belmont. If he comes back well, we'll go to Saratoga for the
Travers (Aug. 28).''
</P>
<P>
   Ecton Park is one heck of a second-stringer. The son of Forty
Niner, out of a Danzig mare, enjoys outstanding breeding for a wet
track, and he relished the slop at Saratoga, beating Belmont Stakes
winner Lemon Drop Kid by more than 6 lengths. Ecton Park finished
12th in the Derby, and Walden pulled him off the Triple Crown
trail. He has a lifetime mark of 10-4-3-2, and has won nearly
$500,000 in purses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been hoping to win a graded stakes with him,'' said
owner Mark Stanley. ``I had no idea how he would run over the mud.
He had never run over it. It seems like he liked it. I think he
might go next in the Pennsylvania Derby (Sept. 6 at Philadelphia
Park), and then the Super Derby (Oct. 2 at Louisiana Downs).''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens in the future, Elliott Walden's name
can now be found on the national map.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Honor roll
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The vote for the Hall of Fame was announced April 27, and Lukas
was joined by jockey Russell Baze in Monday's ceremonies at
Saratoga. Lukas, 63, has won 3,794 races, and his stable is the
first to earn more than $200 million. He has trained 19 Eclipse
Award winners, won 13 Breeders' Cup events, and taken 12 Triple
Crown races. Baze, 41, has 6,666 victories, and his mounts have
earned $94.5 million. He is the only jockey to have ridden 400 or
more winners for seven consecutive years. The horses inducted were
Exceller, who beat Triple Crown winners Seattle Slew and Affirmed
in the 1978 Jockey Club Gold Cup, and Miesque, the turf filly who
was never out of the money (16-12-3-1), and became the first to win
two Breeders' Cup races (1987 and '88 Mile). Gun Bow, who staged
some legendary battles with Kelso in 1964 and '65, was inducted as
Horse of Yesteryear . . . The next assignment for Victory Gallop
will be the $1 million Pacific Classic at Del Mar Aug. 29, in which
he will meet Real Quiet for the first time since last year's
Belmont. Victory Gallop was going to fly to California last Friday,
but will now go out Tuesday. ``He coughed a couple of times Friday
morning,'' said Walden. ``I decided I didn't want to take a chance
on shipping him. When you're dealing with the best horse in the
country, you don't want to take any unnecessary chances.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A flying filly
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chilukki, the 2-year-old filly trained by Baffert, ran another
hole in the wind while winning the Sorrento Stakes at Del Mar
Saturday, scoring by 6 lengths. The daughter of Cherokee Run, out
of a Damascus mare, is 4 for 4, and she's been alone at the wire
every time, winning her races, including one against males, by a
combined 25 1/4 lengths. ``When you have a brilliant one like her,
you just have to manage them correctly,'' said Baffert. ``She went
:21 4/5 for the opening quarter, and she was just galloping down
the backside. She's the kind of filly that's so good that if
anybody tries to go with her, she just puts them away.'' Chilukki's
sire was a miler, at best, and the question she must eventually
answer is one of distance. Next on the agenda for Chilukki is the
Del Mar Debutante, on the Pacific Classic undercard . . . Stephen
Got Even, considered a key contender during the Triple Crown
season, was only 5-1 in the Derby before finishing 14th. He then
ran a decent fourth in the Preakness, and fifth in the Belmont. But
the son of A.P. Indy has gone so sour that trainer Nick Zito
wouldn't even enter him in the Jim Dandy, as originally planned.
``He's still feeling the effects of the Triple Crown,'' said Zito.
``We'll train him every day until he gets a speeding ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks and from
the Daily Racing Form was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
