<HEADLINE>
LONG ISLAND: FULL OF SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD KINDLEBERGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENPORT, N.Y. _ At Orient State Park, on the northeastern tip
of Long Island, an evening breeze blew in from the Atlantic, an
osprey rested atop a tall nest in the marsh, and a turtle paused,
with legs and head retracted, in its labored journey across the
road.
</P>
<P>
   The deer and red-tailed fox that also inhabit the park were not
in view during my brief stop. But in the next two days I saw both
species at other locations on a Long Island I found surprisingly
rural and beautiful _ and a lot easier to get to than many New
Englanders might think.
</P>
<P>
   The eastern end of Long Island _ as opposed to the densely
populated section closer to New York City _ has sleepy villages,
roadside stands, lots of farmland, and enough vineyards to supply a
small European fiefdom. It also has considerable variety, with its
rural tranquillity offset by the Hamptons, the resorts favored by
New York's rich and famous. And it has the stark beauty of Montauk
Point and, to the west, Fire Island.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there is a snap. Two hours out of Boston I was buying a
$63 round-trip ticket at the ferry terminal in New London, Conn.
After a pleasant 90-minute ride across Long Island Sound, the ferry
nudged into the dock at Orient Point.
</P>
<P>
   There was room to spare for cars on that weekday afternoon
crossing in late June. That would be almost unheard of on a ferry
to Martha's Vineyard or Nantucket at that time of year. High season
for tourists is expanding on Long Island's North Fork, but in this
old whaling port, 8 miles west of the ferry landing, some cafes
still don't open until July.
</P>
<P>
   The proprietor of a small bed-and-breakfast whose ad I came
across on the ferry seemed nonplused when I approached him for a
room. None of his rooms was made up and available for my unexpected
midweek business, he said.
</P>
<P>
   I ended up at the Townsend Manor Inn, paying a few dollars extra
for a view of the marina and pool. The $95 room had its limitations
_ a burnt-out bulb over the bed, a barely functional air
conditioner, and a clogged drain in the sink.
</P>
<P>
   At least the woman behind the desk gave me a little flavor of
life in Greenport. Asked to name the favored local pastimes, she
listed two: fishing and drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner at Claudio's Restaurant on the waterfront offered up the
first of several Long Island superlatives I happened on. Founded in
1870 by an immigrant Portuguese whaling hand who grew tired of the
sea, Claudio's claims to be the oldest same-family-owned restaurant
in the United States. (Later I added the nation's oldest cattle
ranch, in Montauk, which I visited, and the world's largest outlet
mall, in Riverhead, which I did not.)
</P>
<P>
   The quiet, leafy enclave of Greenport has an air of still
waiting to be discovered by the tourism boom. The village is in
sharp contrast with the upscale Hamptons that I would pass through
the next day. But if many of Greenport's past economic engines have
dried up, tourism is coming on strong, boosted by the area's
expanding vineyards and wineries.
</P>
<P>
   At one time Greenport was the port of embarcation for Long
Island Railroad passengers traveling to New England. The extension
of the railroad to Greenport in 1844 made it the fastest route
between New York and Boston, I learned at the local library. That
distinction was short-lived. Only a few years later new bridges
over rivers along the Connecticut coast opened up a faster rail
route between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
   The area got another economic boost in the 1920s when
Prohibition made eastern Long Island a favorite dropoff point for
rum runners. Its many bays and inlets made it particularly
advantageous to the smugglers. Business thrived at the local
shipyards, where repair work on speedboats fast enough to outrun
the Coast Guard was happily paid for in advance, according to a
Greenport history compiled by the local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, maybe it was understandable that not
everyone thought rum running was such a bad thing. Local lore has
it that the municipal power supply in those times would
occasionally suffer an unexplained hourlong blackout, enough time
to move a new shipment of contraband liquor through town in the
dark of night.
</P>
<P>
   Claudio's cheerfully confesses on the back of its menu that its
upstairs ``became a lively place for imbibing the illegal spirits''
that passed through the waterfront during Prohibition. The
restaurant, then on stilts, arranged for shipments bound for New
York to be offloaded through a trapdoor under the building.
</P>
<P>
   Driving west the next day took me as far as Sayville, self-
described as America's friendliest city. Maybe that explained the
pet parade it was planning for early July and was advertising
downtown. Sayville, on South Bay across from Fire Island, was the
closest I would get to New York City, but still miles from the
Nassau County boundary.
</P>
<P>
   Easternmost Suffolk County is three times bigger than Nassau in
area but registered a population of roughly the same size, 1.3
million, in the last census. (Strictly speaking, Long Island
includes Brooklyn and Queens, although as boroughs of New York City
they are usually thought of separately.)
</P>
<P>
   The New York end of Long Island was settled by the Dutch in the
early 17th century. A little later, New Englanders crossed Long
Island Sound to put down roots on the eastern end.
</P>
<P>
   The island was heavily wooded until cleared for agriculture.
Farming has prospered to the point that Suffolk is reported to be
the most productive county in New York on the basis of wholesale
farm revenues. The region's increasingly respected wines have
proved such a success that grapes may one day rival potatoes and
cauliflower as Long Island's biggest crop.
</P>
<P>
   A hazy, overcast day almost persuaded me to give up on my visit
to Fire Island. But after I decided to chance it, a stiff breeze,
which almost took my hat with it on the 20-minute passenger ferry
ride from Sayville, soon brought out the sun.
</P>
<P>
   My destination was the Sunken Forest, a thicket of 250-year-old
holly trees managed by the National Park Service. It contains an
elevated wood walkway that steers visitors through thick woods with
charming twists and turns. Screened from the ocean by a barrier of
sand dunes, the woods are not so isolated as to blot out the roar
of the surf, the twittering of birds, and the sigh of wind blowing
through the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the Sunken Forest, I had a quick ocean swim. Walking
east, I soon came to the hamlet of Cherry Grove. Cars are banned on
most of Fire Island, a 30-mile barrier beach. So places like Cherry
Grove, which like some other Fire Island vacation spots has been a
longtime gay destination, are served by crisscrossing boardwalks
instead of streets. I ordered the Tuesday pasta special at
Michael's, on the wharf on the bay side, before catching the ferry
back to Sayville.
</P>
<P>
   The high life in the Hamptons occurs in East Hampton and
Southampton (not Bridgehampton or Hampton Bays). Sag Harbor, a few
miles to the north, is another enclave prized by rich New Yorkers.
A tourism official gave me a sense of their contrasting images:
East Hampton is known for movie people, Southampton for ``old
blood,'' and Sag Harbor for writers.
</P>
<P>
   East Hampton and Southampton are loaded with expensive
boutiques. Both have their multimillion-dollar houses with sweeping
manicured lawns and ocean views. Driving through, I found East
Hampton, with its towering old trees forming a canopy over the main
street, the more striking of the two.
</P>
<P>
   If being ready for polite society means knowing which fork to
use, South Fork is definitely the proper choice. A remark I
overheard, actually on Fire Island, could sum up the attitude of
people found summering well in the glitzier corners of Long Island,
if not across the nation: ``I just don't know how anyone survives
on less than a six-figure income.''
</P>
<P>
   One answer might be to skip the Hamptons and spend the night on
Montauk, at the easternmost tip of the island. Montauk has its
historic lighthouse, cattle ranch, and great views and beaches. Its
60 motels and other accommodations make their pitch more to
families and budget-minded singles.
</P>
<P>
   This was a different world from the private club with 30 grass
tennis courts that I heard about in the Hamptons. The office door
of one Montauk motel I stopped at directed prospective guests to
the bartender next door. (At another motel a similar sign said,
``Ask at the mini golf.'') I instead chose the Sands, where I had
to pay in advance and was told I would need to put down a $20
deposit to make calls from my room.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving South Fork the next day, I passed a gift shop shaped
like a 20-foot duck. A Long Island landmark listed on the National
Register of Historic Places, it is a leading example of a style of
roadside architecture. It was built as a tribute to the dozens of
duck farms Long Island once boasted.
</P>
<P>
   The duck might seem hard to miss, but the previous day I had
gone by it before realizing my mistake and turning back. After all
the hype I had read, it was smaller than I expected. And to me, its
narrow yellow bill made it look more like a gull.
</P>
<P>
   After three days on eastern Long Island, you could call me a
convert. A return visit looks like a must. After all, I've only
been to one of two dozen vineyards for the free tour and tasting. I
have yet to visit the Riverhead water park, even if it isn't the
world's biggest. And at Deep Hollow Ranch in Montauk, Buffalo Bill
and his Wild West Show await me still.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
