<HEADLINE>
A MILLENNIUM FOR STAY-AT HOMES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will traveling for the millennium celebration be a bust?
</P>
<P>
   According to a Travel Weekly survey, 80 percent of consumers
will not travel this New Year's. The survey, however, found 8
percent have firm plans to travel and another 9 percent are
exploring holiday travel plans. Only 9 percent of those surveyed
said they were concerned about the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   Travel Weekly, a trade publication for the industry, noted the
reasons for not traveling: 63 percent said they plan to stay home;
50 percent found plenty to do where they live; 43 percent said the
millennium means nothing; 42 percent do not like traveling over the
holidays, and 23 percent felt millennium products were too
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Staying close to home does appear to be popular. At the Brown
Palace Hotel in Denver, most guests booked for their New Year's Eve
package ($1,799 to $1,999; call 800-321-2599) are from the Colorado
area. That night the Brown Palace will unveil a new clock sculpted
by Boston artist Robert Shure. Couples attending will receive a
limited-edition replica of the clock, which will chime for the
first time at midnight. The souvenir clock will be a millennium
collectors' item.
</P>
<P>
   If the thought of traveling over New Year's bothers you,
consider the Basin Harbor Club in Vergennes, Vt., where they're
planning a Millennium Beach Ball on Oct. 17. This seasonal family
resort will be closed in December. For details, call 802-475-2311.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ryder Cup rooms &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup, one of the premier golf tournaments in the world,
takes over the Boston area Sept. 20-26 when it is played at The
Country Club in Brookline, Mass. Despite the demand for tickets and
unprecedented interest in the Ryder Cup, rooms are still available
in the Boston area during the event. The Greater Boston Convention
&AMP; Visitors Bureau is offering a special hotel hot line for the
event: call 800-777-6001 (available daily 8:45 a.m. to 8 p.m.,
Saturday 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., and Sunday 11 a.m. to 4 p.m.) or, on
the Web, visit www.bostonusa.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foliage trains &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Bay Railroad Enthusiasts will be running the
Berkshires Foliage Flyer Oct. 2. The train leaves South Station at
7:45 a.m. with stops along the way to Springfield, then on to
Albany where passengers can choose from optional activities such as
a Hudson River cruise, lunch, a tour of the USS Slater, or Albany
sightseeing. Tickets are $75 for adults and $40 for children 12 and
under. For information, call 617-489-5277. For those wishing to
travel first class, the private observation car Caritas will be
available. Tickets on the Caritas are $295 a person and include
meals.
</P>
<P>
   A luxurious way to catch the foliage is aboard one of the Great
Train Escapes' eight-day New England Foliage Express tours. Tickets
are $1,999 a person and space is available on the Sept. 18, 25, and
Oct. 16 departures. Travel is aboard the North American Explorer
with eight luxuriously restored vintage cars; where train service
is not available, passengers travel by motorcoach. The rail portion
is from Portland, Maine, into New Hampshire, Stowe, Vt., to Mystic,
Conn., and Cape Cod to Boston. The package includes many meals,
accommodations, transportation, and sightseeing. For information,
call 888-544-RAIL.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flying toddler's seat &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   British Airways has unveiled the world's first airline seat for
children under 2. The new seat allows toddlers to travel in safety
and style in their own infant seat at no extra charge (while the
seat is free, the infant fare is 10 percent of the seat rate). A
maximum of 12 seats will be available on 747 aircraft in all
classes and bookable on a first-come basis. Carrycots will still be
available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire Music Festival's season finale will be Aug.
12-14 with performances at Plymouth State College in Plymouth and
Middle High School in Gilford. Tickets are $17-$40; call
603-524-1000.
</P>
<P>
   A special HOBO Railroad trip will be held Aug. 21 to benefit the
Flying Yankee restoration. The round trip from Lincoln, N.H.,
includes scenic White Mountain vistas and a turkey dinner. The
Flying Yankee is a 200-foot streamliner built in 1935 and is now
under restoration. Tickets for the benefit trip are $100 a person;
call 603-745-2135.
</P>
<P>
   A haunting walking tour of New York's Midtown area will be held
Aug. 15. The Adventure on a Shoestring walk is $5 a person (a real
bargain _ the tours have not changed price in 36 years). For
information, call 212-265-2663.
</P>
<P>
   The Mohonk Mountain House will celebrate its 64th Annual Garden
Holiday program Aug. 29-Sept. 1. Mohonk's gardens are in their
111th year and are the focal point of the weekend. There will be
guided walks, plant talks, classes in drawing, and workshops by
specialists. For information on the program and resort packages,
call 800-772-6646.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest Irish festival takes place in Milwaukee Aug.
19-22. More than 50 performers will be featured, including Tommy
Makem, the Trinity Irish Dancers, and Gaelic Storm, the group that
performed in the festive steerage class scene in the movie
``Titanic.'' In addition there will be plays, a tug of war, and a
children's area. For information, call 414-229-5879.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smart card &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Museum of Fine Arts now offers a Smart Card good
for admission to exhibitions and purchases in the museum shop or
its cafe. And,the card has become a collector's item. Each card is
produced in limited quantity and illustrated with a work from the
current exhibition, ``Cosmos: From Romanticism to the
Avant-garde,'' which celebrates the discovery and search for new
horizons through art. Another card, illustrated with the ``Crown of
Flowers'' by Cilliam Bouguereau, has replaced the museum's gift
certificate. In Europe, Smart Cards rank second after stamps among
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bermuda dreams &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever wanted to visit Bermuda? Better still, with your
company paying all the bills? That's what happened recently for the
people who work for Jordan's Furniture stores in the Boston area.
All 1,300 employees were flown to the island for a day of fun and
sun. It's a great idea, and now Steve Belkin, president of TNT
Vacations, which arranged the outing, is out to market it to other
companies in the New England area. Belkin, no surprise,thinks it's
a great idea. And to back this up, he's been closing up shop and
taking his employees to Bermuda every five years for the last 20.
In case your employer needs a reason to do a similar outing, Belkin
notes that a trip like this helps team building, is a morale
booster, reduces turnover, helps in hiring, and offers great
publicity. Add to this that it's a great value for companies.
Belkin notes it costs about 1 percent of the payroll, about $400 a
person for Bermuda. ``Do something good, and it comes back,'' said
Belkin. Employees like working for a company that does such things.
Bermuda likes the idea, too. Tourism people there feel if people
come for one day, they'll come back. Interestingly, TNT discovered
that 70 percent of Jordan's employees had never been out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stay cool &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first exhibition to explore the transformative power of air
conditioning, ``Stay Cool! Air Conditioning in America,'' is on
view through Jan. 2 at the National Building Museum in Washington.
Through photos, artifacts, television commercials, and interactive
displays, the exhibit will explore the history of ``air
conditioning,'' beginning with pioneering experiments in the late
1800s. Manufacturers at the turn of the century were learning that
by filtering air and stabilizing temperature, mechanical systems
improved the environment for products . . . and people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   World peace &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A conference, ``Building Bridges of Peace, Culture, and
Prosperity through Sustainable Tourism,'' will be held in Glasgow
in October. An estimated 800 participants from more than 70
countries are expected for the conference, which will include
real-life case studies on the theme. The event is being organized
by the International Institute for Peace Through Tourism, founded
in 1986 in Montreal to harness the power of the tourism industry as
the world's first global peace industry. IIPT is now headquartered
in Stowe, Vt. For information, call 802-253-2658 or visit
www.iipt.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
