<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERING THE REAL NOTTING HILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For weeks, ``Notting Hill'' has been giving moviegoers the warm
fuzzies. But it's also giving some of them the urge to see the real
Notting Hill in West London. Here, from George Murray, concierge
manager of London's luxurious Four Seasons Hotel, are some
suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   --Stop for coffee or tea at any number of coffee shops and
cafes. ``They're all lively and friendly,'' says Murray, but you
might head for those on Portobello Road, around which the movie was
filmed.
</P>
<P>
   --Visit antiquarian shops such as the Antique Clothing Shop at
282 Portobello Road, Antique Medical Instruments at 286 Westbourne
Grove, the Real Poster Galley at 72 Westbourne Grove, and Adrian
Harrington antiquarian bookseller at 64a Kensington Church St.
</P>
<P>
   --Take a lunch break. Pharmacy on Notting Hill Gate and
Kensington Place, around the corner from Notting Hill tube, are
modern and bustling. Choices for ethnic food include Khan's at
13-15 Westbourne Grove for Indian cuisine, Four Seasons (no
relation to the hotel) at 84 Queensway for Chinese, and Assaggi at
39 Cheapstow Place for Italian.
</P>
<P>
   --Go shopping. Christine Bec at 72 Westborne Park Road has hats
and designer clothes, Cath Kidston at 8 Clarendon Cross offers bed
linen and tableware, and Aime features French products ranging from
designer clothes to books to household accessories.
</P>
<P>
   --Heading away from Notting Hill, visit Kensington Church
Street, with its marvelous mix of pubs, cafes, restaurants, and
elegant antiques shops. You might try Clarke's at 124 Kensington
Church St. for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   --And don't forget Portobello Market every Saturday. It's the
world's largest antiques market. And it's something to see. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of Notting Hill: We learn from another chief
concierge, Simon Thomas of the Royal Garden Hotel, that the
much-photographed blue door to Hugh Grant's flat in the movie is
actually the front door of a house owned by Richard Curtis, who
wrote the movie script. The house is for sale _ for about $2
million. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Scotland Yard is in London. So why is it called
Scotland Yard? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: The new roller coaster at Six Flags Astroworld in
Houston is called the Serial Thriller. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``I've been to the bottom of the ocean, and I think
Hollywood is stranger.'' _ James Cameron, director of ``Titanic.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's contest time (for kiddies): In connection with its new family
travel section, MSN Expedia is sponsoring an ``Ultimate Family
Vacation'' contest. Youngsters 7-13 can submit brief essays on
their ultimate family travel idea to Expedia at
www.expedia.com/daily/family/. The first 500 entrants will receive
a Fuji disposable camera. Weekly winners will get a variety of
prizes, including Fuji digital cameras, and have their essay
published on the Web site. And they'll have a chance at the grand
prize, an adventure family vacation. The contest runs now through
Sept. 1; details and rules can be found at www.expedia.com/.
Expedia, incidentally, has added several new features and made its
site easier to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's fractured English lesson: A description seen on one
manufacturer's bras in Japan: ``These Underwears Fit Like a
Globe.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Oldies at sea: The years have gone by, but in his heart Harvey
Robbins is still a teenager in love with rock 'n' roll. For Harvey,
it's still a summer evening in the 1950s on Blue Hill Avenue in
Boston's Dorchester neighborhood, with the radio tuned to Symphony
Sid in his booth at the Hi-Hat, broadcasting the doo-wop sounds of
the Penguins and the Harptones and the Cleftones. And soon buddies
Gil, Bobby, and Ron will be by to join Harvey in some do-wopping of
their own, in a group called the Interludes. Those were the days,
my friend. Today Robbins is one of the fortunate few who has
transformed what he has always loved into a career _ he's a concert
producer who presents doo-wop shows on land and sea. From May
21-28, 2000, there will be good rockin' every night as Robbins
presents his Royalty of Rock 'n' Roll All-Stars in a multi-concert
Boston-to-Bermuda cruise on the Norwegian Majesty. The cruise will
be spiced with a variety of oldies shows on board and in St.
George's, Bermuda, where the ship will be docked for 3 1/2 days.
For more information or to make reservations, call Robbins at
978-256-6472. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? The London Metropolitan Police, which began in
1829, had its original headquarters at 4 Whitehall Place _ next
door to buildings that used to house kings and other important
visitors from Scotland. The surrounding area came to be known as
Scotland Yard and the name stuck to the police facility, even after
the police moved to new offices. Today, the facility is in the
Westminster section of London. (With thanks to the World Book
Encyclopedia and faithful contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough,
Mass.)
</P>
<P>
