<HEADLINE>
GORE'S TWO STEPS FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- A very good buddy of Al Gore's observed the other
night that a good presidential candidate should never be shy about
poking a low-and-outside pitch the opposite way for a solid single.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting singles, he said, is rarely a thrill, but singles add up
in politics.
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit, it's worth taking a peek at two clean hits the
vice president has made in the last 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a speech at a community college in Minnesota,
during which Gore made a set of tax-reduction proposals that
focused on the middle-class and working poor, was out in front of
the Clinton administration, and required a ``he's on his own''
response from the less venturesome Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that a once-famous tax-reformer from the mid-'80s
named Bill Bradley has yet to opine on this topic.
</P>
<P>
   The second was an appearance on Capitol Hill here last week, in
which Gore cast his lot with the Senate Democrats trying for the
most ambitious of several possible ways of helping smaller farmers
cope with drought emergencies and hideously low prices.
</P>
<P>
   This act, too, put him in front of his administration and
outside its current policy arc. As the Senate worked its will, in
fact, the White House never did get around to taking a position,
but Gore's Iowa supporters were most anxious that this not deter
him for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that a self-proclaimed product of small-town
Missouri, just south of the Iowa border, named Bradley hasn't
weighed in on this one, either.
</P>
<P>
   Put the two together, and you have something a bit different
from the steady stream of recent policy positions from Gore that
appear to have taxed the dilligence of political reporters and gone
largely without mass media notice.
</P>
<P>
   As the vice president's top-heavy campaign slowly reorganizes,
its most important function _ supplying a message _ is closer to
achieving results. And the option reflected in Gore's last two
moves _ aiming at working families for whom government is not a
dirty word _ is the one holding the most promise.
</P>
<P>
   In tougher economic times, the ``forgotten middle class'' was a
Godsend for Governor Bill Clinton eight years ago. And for those
with longer memories, the message that Mike Dukakis belatedly and
with results turned to in the final days of '88 _ ``I'm on your
side, He's on their side'' _ is even more to the point. It's not
angry, but it is pointed, and while it fits Gore's record as well
as Clinton's, it's not confined by the latter.
</P>
<P>
   On taxes, for example, Gore regularly talks up administration
positions on everything from the R&AMP;D tax credit to incentives for
middle-class retirement accounts outside Social Security, and
stresses the greater importance of conserving most of any future
budget surpluses to help stretch the lives of the retirement trust
funds.
</P>
<P>
   But in Minnesota, he also stressed the portion of the so-called
marriage penalty that affects families of modest and low incomes.
</P>
<P>
   For the former, he would give joint filers the same standard
deduction as two individual filers; and for the working poor, he
would have additional provision for families benefiting from the
Earned Income Tax Credit.
</P>
<P>
   And he emphasized the value of an education proposal he made two
months ago _ providing a dollar in tax credit aid for every two
dollars workers and employers put in a new savings account for
college expenses.
</P>
<P>
   And what goes for ordinary taxpayers goes double for small
farmers. Gore was not merely supporting a higher aid figure in the
Senate's tussle over emergency legislation that for a change was
about a real emergency, he was supporting Democrats who not only
understand the havoc low prices have wreaked, but also understand
that the ``reform'' of 1996 that is designed to gradually wean all
farmers from government assistance is not working well.
</P>
<P>
   In supporting the most hard-pressed small farmers, Gore is
recognizing that what is at issue is not agriculture policy per se,
but rather the future of rural America _ a way of life that
encompasses small businesses, schools, and health clinics as well
as farms where the owning family does the bulk of the work.
</P>
<P>
   It's good people policy as well as good politics, and the more
of it Gore does, the better he'll do in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
