<HEADLINE>
EXCLUSIVE SPA EXPERIENCING GROWING PAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ Settling into one of the salon's raised thrones,
clad in an impossibly soft terry cloth robe, Melissa Black had one
day left and 10 toenails to paint. Departure time from Canyon
Ranch, the luxurious spa nestled in the Berkshire hills, had come
too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But Black, originally from Needham and now living in Maryland,
had yet to use the $100 voucher that came with her package for the
spa's legendary ``health and healing'' services _ bio-magnetic
acupuncture, stress reduction counseling, or herbal medicine
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come for the workouts,'' said Black, undecided if she would
cash in the voucher or skip it. An Allure magazine is passed to her
for inspection. ``I've been to one other spa and my girlfriends
have been to a lot of other spas, and everyone says this place is
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Canyon Ranch, which opened 10 years ago as a high-end, New Age
spa, is one of the hottest resorts in the nation. It is wildly
popular not just with the New York clientele it first cultivated
but with a growing cadre of Bostonians. It is booked solid for the
rest of the year; there's no advertising budget to speak of and no
particular need for one.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as beneficiaries of the booming economy flock to Lenox and
queue up to pay $600 a night, some believe the spa's roots as a
holistic healing center are in danger of being forgotten. Many
people now seem as drawn by the exclusivity and Lexus-dotted, regal
grounds _ and to be pampered, with a 3-to-1 staff-guest ratio _ as
by the lessons in lifestyle changes through diet and meditation _
the basic philosophy that spa founders Enid and Mel Zuckerman
espouse.
</P>
<P>
   Among the herbal treatment consultations and pre-breakfast Tai
Chi sessions, cultures can clash. Some guests are annoyed by the
no-alcohol rule, and must struggle to keep their cell phones shut
off. Some harried newcomers come expecting instant relaxation. They
don't want to hear about art therapy and biofeedback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't care less,'' was the response of one woman who
poured herself a generous cup of steaming black coffee after
stretch class, when asked if she should be drinking organic green
tea instead of ingesting straight caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   Vivien Li, executive director of the Boston Harbor Association
and one of many Boston professional women who make the two-hour
pilgrimage down the Massachusetts Turnpike to Canyon Ranch, said it
invariably takes one or two days to unwind and conform to the
rhythms of the place. Few people wear flashy jewelry or dress up
much, she said, recalling running into Mary Tyler Moore on the
walking trails on one visit, clad in a distinctly unglamorous
sweatsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Li also recalls a game of ``wallyball,' a kind of indoor
volleyball, that quickly became fiercely competitive. On another
visit, Bob Frazier, a partner at the law firm of Goodwin, Proctor &AMP;
Hoar in Boston, paraded around the grounds wearing a T-shirt that
read: ``Born to Lead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `No, Bob, that's not how it works here,' '' Li said.
</P>
<P>
   And as much as the spa emphasizes its low-key, introspective
philosophy, the common experience of going to Canyon Ranch has
become a lingua franca for powerful women in Boston's business,
political, and and academic circles.
</P>
<P>
   Those who consider Canyon Ranch a mecca include Jacqueline
O'Neill, vice president at Harvard; venture capitalists Martha
Crowninshield and Cheryl Marshall; Diane Capstaff, vice president
at John Hancock and head of the Massachusetts Women's Forum;
Margaret McKinnon, president of Lesley College; and Kitty Dukakis,
wife of the former Massachusetts governor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Li said, networking while on the grounds is frowned on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to fly, but it's remote enough you leave your
business behind,'' said Jennifer Lau, chief executive of Lau
Technologies of Littleton, a high-tech defense contractor. Lau said
Canyon Ranch is a gem, relatively accessible for busy Massachusetts
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for others, the resort itself has become too much like work
_ part of the unwinnable competition to have the classiest
vacation. It can be a place to see and be seen, with sightings of
the rich and famous reported back to peers.
</P>
<P>
   All of that is a long drift from Canyon Ranch's original
health-and-healing moorings, said Elizabeth Cook, head of cultural
affairs under Mayor Kevin H. White and former president of the
Advertising Club of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, who attends macrobiotic summer camp and is training to be
an arts therapist, said lately she prefers going to Kripalu Center
for Yoga and Health in nearby Stockbridge. ``I don't have to think
about what I pack when I go there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That image isn't helped by the opening of a third Canyon Ranch
in Las Vegas this year. The 126-room ranch in Lenox, set on 120
acres including a renovated 1897 mansion known as Bellefontaine,
opened in 1989 and followed in the footsteps of the first resort,
in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Joanna E. Roche, communications director for Canyon Ranch and
president of the local chamber of commerce, said it's all a matter
of educating guests. Some come expecting only plush luxuries, she
said, but soon realize ``this is a learning institution, a place to
change your lifestyle. We get men who are turning 50 and are
freaking out, who drink and eat red meat and have high cholesterol.
We have people who have lost spouses, changed jobs, or who've gone
through a divorce. For them, and for baby boomers who want to live
longer and live better, this is a cocoon that's safe, private, and
nurturing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some want instant gratification _ they just say, give me some
techniques. And some do complain if it doesn't work,'' said Marcia
Bernstein, a transplanted New York social worker who holds
stress-reduction consultations _ fitness for the mind and spirit
after guests have toned their abs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all run around like the Energizer bunny. We don't nap. We
don't take Mediterranean three-hour lunches. We have to be
multi-tasking all the time,'' she said. Most guests are eager for
help in managing the stresses of living in 1999, and seek to be a
more confident, serene, ``whole'' person, Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   There are inherent tensions in running a spa that promotes
healthy living, of course. The stately grounds, the plush rooms,
and the attentive staff can promote a sense of indulgence; yet much
of what Canyon Ranch teaches is about discipline if not denial.
</P>
<P>
   Bryn Zeckhauser, 27, a student at Harvard Business School, said
the health and healing programs aren't for everyone. ``I took a
breathing-stress class once and I think I started
hyperventilating,'' she said. But her mother used the center after
a bout with illness and her 83-year-old grandmother takes classes
on osteoporosis. The trio have been coming for seven years
</P>
<P>
   The salon, the pool, and the lush setting may be the main
attractions for an increasing number of guests. Even men, who are
coming in modestly greater numbers, are signing up for such
services as pedicures (the better to patrol the lawn at Tanglewood
in open-toed sandals, so de rigeur this summer).
</P>
<P>
   But ``that's the great thing about it,'' said Zeckhauser. ``They
have the option. Everyone does whatever they want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
