<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCIPALS-CHALLENGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKSHOP PREPARES PRINCIPALS FOR A NEW ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Jeffrey Howard is about to make a school
principal cry.
</P>
<P>
   It's only day three of the summer institute sponsored by the
Principal Center at the Harvard Graduate School in Education.
Already some of the principals in this crowded lecture hall are
showing signs of strain.
</P>
<P>
   They shift in their seats as Howard hammers at the dismal
academic track record of US public schools. They grit their teeth
as he rattles off a list of the ways schools destroy student
initiative. Too many educators, he says, have accepted the
destructive assumption that some students are meant to excel while
others have limited potential.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Cheryl Smith, a principal from Austin, Texas, reaches a
boiling point. Tears flowing, she complains that Howard appears to
be ``damning a lot of caring educational professionals who are
working their hearts out for their kids.'' But Harvard's Principal
Center isn't about to accept this soft approach. The center's
recent nine-day workshop on accountability is dedicated to
preparing principals for the hard new reality of American schools:
the days when empathy and hard work were enough are gone.
</P>
<P>
   The monopoly that public schools enjoyed and that insulated them
from serious reform is being broken by such recent innovations as
competition, as school choice, vouchers, and charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   Today, schools must demonstrate that their hard work is yielding
results in the form of improved test scores. And when those scores
don't improve, principals find themselves on the hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy time to be a principal ,'' said Betty
McNally, assistant director of the Harvard Principal's Center.
``Public reporting on test scores is feeding public scrutiny, and
states are demanding more for their education dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   States and cities are rushing to implement testing programs that
reward or sanction administrators if test scores exceed or fall
below the state's expectations. In Newark, half of the city's 82
principals were replaced during the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the job of principal is becoming so difficult
that people are opting out. Urban school districts across the state
estimate that they will see vacancies reach 30 to 35 percent for
school administrators in the next seven years as retirements hit an
all-time high and replacements become hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1993 education reform law, principals are not only
responsible for running the building and dealing with parents, they
also must hire and fire staff and redesign curriculums. And as the
state begins to grade schools based on specialized general
knowledge tests, called MCAS, principals are beginning to be held
accountable for their students' scores. Principals, unlike
teachers, do not have strong unions, so they can be hired and fired
more easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't met an individual who isn't concerned about the
accountability topic,'' said Jane O'Connor, the principal of
Cunniff Elementary school in Watertown, who is one of the about 70
principals and administrators who attended last week's institute.
``It's shaken people up on every level, creating a rich discussion
about what should be happening in schools.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year that the Harvard Principal's Center has
offered a summer institute on accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Dead-wooders, maintenance-mavens, and central-office-wannabes
need not apply to the summer institute, which is geared toward
experienced ``instructional leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   The faculty is also high-powered. Courses are taught by such
educational leaders as Rudy Crew, New York City Board of Education
chancellor, and Hartford School Superintendent Anthony Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Amato, who in his last job as Community School District 6
superintendent in New York City, was credited with helping to
significantly raise reading scores, says principals can view the
accountability movement as a monster or a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either you're going to control it or it's going to control
you,'' Amato says.
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief obstacles to school reform has traditionally
been bureaucratic inertia. ``You can change schools the same way
you change the direction of an ocean liner,'' says Howard, who
heads the nonprofit Efficacy Institute: ``Slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   New reforms are intended to speed the process, and one of the
latest trends is an attempt to hold individual teachers as well as
principals accountable for student performance. Several states are
starting to hold teachers' feet to the fire. Amato's new home
state, Connecticut, for example, now evaluates new teachers with
videotapes and peer reviews for their first three years in the
classroom. In Florida, starting this year, scores will play a part
in teacher raises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come for principals to say, ``I'm not going to be
the only one held accountable in schools,'' Amato says. ``The
principal must shift accountability to everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
