<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1872 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      08-10 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIM OF NEW BROOKS ALBUM NOT `SOUL,' BUT `SELL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seen the new Garth Brooks video yet?
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you've watched the clip for ``Lost in You'' without
realizing it was Brooks, the country music megastar. That's because
he's traded his cowboy hat for a shaggy black wig and inky soul
patch, and shed his twangy high lonesome for a falsetto pop-soul
croon. Suddenly, the man credited with mainstreaming country music
has morphed into a Backstreet Boy.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. This wouldn't have anything to do with the fact that those
very same Backstreet Boys' sophomore CD ``Millennium'' recently
shattered the single-week sales record Brooks set with ``Double
Live'' last year, now would it?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, The Artist Formerly Known as Garth Brooks
is now calling himself Chris Gaines, at least for his upcoming
album. Stripped of his Wranglers and guitar, he's pushing
milquetoast pseudo-soul in the warbly vein of all those
cookie-cutter boy groups breeding like rabbits these days. He's all
moony eyes, droopy bangs, and melismatic curlicues, a tender
loverboy who wants all the ladies out there to know that he, too,
wants it that way.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not enough for Brooks simply to sound and look like the
Backstreet Boys _ OK, so he looks more like their older cousin with
a lapsed gym membership. He's created an entire persona for this
Gaines character, complete with father-son angst, an album that
spent 18 weeks at No. 1, and a disfiguring car crash that made ol'
Chris something of a recluse, until he decided to release his
greatest-hits CD. (Brooks will play Gaines in next year's film
``The Lamb.'') Leave it to Brooks to create a character who already
has several hit records.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Master P transforming into a patchouli-loving
Lilith Fair performer, or Andrea Bocelli switching it up to go
ghetto fabulous?
</P>
<P>
   Don't think for a moment that Brooks is abandoning all those
CD-buying friends in low places who've made him an obscenely rich
man. The album's title, after all, is ``Garth Brooks in . . . the
Life of Chris Gaines.'' This is about duping unsuspecting new
listeners _ especially those snapping up all those copies of
``Millennium,'' who would rather eat raw eggs than buy anything by
Brooks. And ``Lost in You'' is as hopelessly sappy as anything
Kevin, Brian, A.J., Nick, and Howie could make.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, if you can't beat them, become them.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is scheduled to explain all of this Tuesday night during
a VH1 Web chat, but save your time. If you know anything about
Brooks, you already know what ol' Garth is up to.
</P>
<P>
   A decent singer and performer, Brooks has always been as much
about world domination as music. He wants to be the biggest
recording artist ever, and it if takes hokum and gimmicks, well,
that's all right with him. Remember the publicity-grabbing
``sabbatical'' from music, so that he could try out with the San
Diego Padres? Then there was last year's ``Double Live'' album,
which was nothing more than a shameless, calculated ploy to sell a
million CDs in one week, and inflate his overall sales totals. In
the weird math of the music world, a double CD counts as two albums
even though they are sold as a single unit. As Entertainment
Weekly's music critic David Browne said when the CD was released,
``It's Brooks' bid to fulfill his obsessively demented goal of
selling more records than the Beatles.'' As of last year, Brooks,
already the best-selling solo artist in history, was in second
place with 67 million, to the Fab Four's 105 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's also common knowledge that behind his good ol' boy, ``aw
shucks'' persona, Brooks is ruthlessly single-minded about his
career, and woe to anyone who gets in his way. It's industry legend
that Scott Hendricks was booted out as president of Capitol
Records-Nashville, Brooks's label, in 1997 after the singer
complained that his CD ``Fresh Horses'' undersold because of
Hendricks's mismanagement. Even though the album sold 4 million
copies, Hendricks was shown the door _ especially when Brooks
refused to turn in his next album, ``Sevens,'' unless changes were
made, including the implementation of his marketing plan, which
increased the budget more than threefold. (Brooks was an
advertising major at Oklahoma State University. How convenient.)
</P>
<P>
   So now a label that has bent and nearly broken with the whims of
the man called ``Garth Vader'' and ``Garthzilla'' behind his back
has to figure out how to market Garth Brooks as Chris Gaines.
Still, it's similar to all-purpose discount store Target trying to
remake itself as hip and trendy. Can a leopard change its spots?
Sure. But even when a snake sheds its skin, it's still a snake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
