<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-GUNS (Washington) _ With schools reopening this month in
many districts, Education Secretary Richard Riley reported
significant progress in reducing the threat of violent incidents
such as the one at Columbine High School in Littleton Colo. ``We
are starting to move in the right direction,'' he said, citing a
report showing a 31 percent drop in school expulsions for bringing
weapons to school. However, school security officials said there is
no way to guarantee that deadly rampages won't happen again. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington )_ Christian Coalition President Pat
Robertson, the preacher and former GOP presidential candidate, this
week urged the federal government to drop its anti-assassination
policy and ``send a squad in to take out somebody like (accused
terrorist) Osama bin Laden....'' He added, ``I don't see anything
unChristian about it.'' Well, a lot of others do. Besides, we
adopted that policy decades ago partly out of self-preservation; if
we set out to assassinate foreign leaders we don't like, they may
want to assassinate our's first. By MARIANNE MEANS,
</P>
<P>
   (Note: Marianne Means will be on vacation until Thursday, Aug.
19.)
