   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-SHELL-CRABS (Urbanna, Va.) _ The sun was a blood-orange
disk pinned to the horizon as Thomas Lee Walton eased his 24-foot
Carolina skiff and headed toward the Rappahannock River. It was
6:05 A.M. We were going crabbing. Our quarry was the Atlantic blue
crab _ callinectes sapidus to marine biologists, which means
``savory beautiful swimmer'' in Latin. But not the run-of-the-mill
fellows. Walton fishes for ``busters'' or ``peelers,'' which are
crabs that have already begun to shed their shells, or are about
to, prior to growing new ones. If you catch them at the right
moment, and pull them from the water, the process of growth stops
and you have a soft-shell crab, one of summer's most prized treats
not only here on the rim of the Chesapeake Bay but also,
increasingly, in other cities across the United States. By R.W.
Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With 2 recipes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
