   AIRLINE-COMPLAINTS _ WASHINGTON _ More than 5,000 service
complaints against the major airlines have been received in the
first half of 1999, double last year's
</P>
<P>
   number, the U.S. Department of Transportation said Tuesday. The
complaints, to be detailed in a department report this week,
include stories of being ``imprisoned in the airplane on the
runway'' for three hours and being told to ``shut up'' after
protesting damaged property. What's behind the increase, and
prospects for relief. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN _ WASHINGTON _ While most of his rivals have hopscotched
the country in search of votes, Sen. John McCain has set his sights
almost exclusively on New Hampshire and South Carolina. Hoping to
repeat the success of Bob Dole in 1996, who stumbled in New
Hampshire but came back strong in South Carolina, McCain is looking
for a strong second or third place finish up North and first prize
down South. While McCain's war-time record is a big plus, McCain is
most closely associated with campaign finance and tobacco, two
issues that even his South Carolina supporters acknowledge are not
big sellers in the Palmetto state. McCain plans a New Hampshire
address June 30 on campaign finance to help make that issue more
relevant to GOP primary voters. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
