<HEADLINE>
MERGER IS FLYING NICELY FOR WELLS FARGO CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last year, under the leadership of Richard M.
Kovacevich, the Norwest Corp. bought San Francisco-based Wells
Fargo &AMP; Co. for $32 billion in one of the last great bank mergers
of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kovacevich has inherited a behemoth as the president and
chief executive of the heftier Wells Fargo. The new bank is the
nation's seventh largest with more than $200 billion in assets,
102,000 employees, 15 million customers, and 6,000 branches,
mortgage offices and other outlets in every state.
</P>
<P>
   While many mergers stumble, Kovacevich has done a good job of
fusing the San Francisco bank with Norwest Corp. of Minneapolis and
steering Wells Fargo into a new era, according to Wall Street
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   How? Kovacevich and his lieutenants have brought Norwest's
successful sales techniques to Wells Fargo, cross-selling many
products and services to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The old Norwest was a marketing wizard, selling customers an
average of four products each, from checking accounts to home loans
_ far more than other banking rivals. The old Norwest also was the
nation's leading mortgage lender, lending $60 billion last year to
homebuyers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Kovacevich is taking advantage of Wells
Fargo's sleek technology and business models, including supermarket
branches and on-line banking. Most analysts regard Wells Fargo as
the leading commercial bank on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management is genuinely committed to leveraging the strengths
of both companies,'' said Joseph Morford, a banking industry
analyst at Dain Rauscher Inc. in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the bank has dodged the problems that plagued Wells
Fargo's 1996 super-merger with First Interstate Bancorp. That
business marriage was troubled by computer and telephone foul-ups,
lost customers and a decline in loans and deposits.
</P>
<P>
   According to analysts, a patient Kovacevich plans to blend Wells
Fargo and Norwest at a steady pace over a period of two to three
years.
</P>
<P>
   To the relief of employees, Wells Fargo also has avoided the
mass layoffs that have haunted other mergers. A retraining program
and in-house networking also have helped out-of-work employees land
new jobs at Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   Executives had said in March they would cut about 5 percent of
the bank's 102,000-employee work force, or 4,000 to 5,000 people,
over the next two years. So far, 1,000 people have lost their old
jobs, but nearly all found new positions at the larger Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that Wells Fargo is on target to meet its
cost-cutting goals of $650 million within three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd give them a B-plus,'' said Tim Witt, a financial industry
analyst at Olde Discount Corp. in Detroit who gives Wells Fargo a
``buy'' rating. ``We applaud their successful merger. They've done
almost everything right when compared to other (failed) mergers.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would you assess the handling of the merger over
the past year, Kovacevich said in a telephone interview from
Minneapolis: ``The quick answer is it's gone very well, given what
a big change it is when you put together two companies of this
size.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask analysts who've had the opportunity to study other
deals, I think they would also conclude that our merger is going
far better than other ones.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
