<SLUG> BC-SAIPAN-CLOTHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAILERS AGREE TO MONITOR CONDITIONS IN GARMENT FACTORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Four retailers have agreed to settle claims
contained in a class-action lawsuit accusing the companies of
allowing sweatshop conditions in garment factories in the U.S.
Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement reached Monday, the retailers say future
contracts will require independent monitoring of their contracts in
the Western Pacific island commonwealth. The settlement also
prohibits recruitment fees, or fees charged to workers to go to the
commonwealth for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a watershed agreement,'' said San Francisco attorney
Michael Rubin, a partner in a law firm representing the workers and
human rights groups. ``We've established a model code of conduct
and monitoring program that will be used as a model in cases all
over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers are mainly young women from China, the Philippines,
Thailand and Bangladesh who speak little or no English.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement resolves a federal lawsuit filed in U.S. District
Court in Los Angeles and a state lawsuit filed in San Francisco
Superior Court, both on Jan. 13, concerning the four retailers:
Gymboree Corp., Nordstrom Inc., J. Crew Group Inc. and Cutter &AMP;
Buck Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The cases continue with 14 other retailers named, including Gap
Inc.; Wal-Mart Corp.; J.C. Penney Co.; Sears, Roebuck and Co.; the
Limited; and Dayton Hudson Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, four additional retailers _ Ralph Lauren, Phillips
Van Heusen, Donna Karan and Chadwick's of Boston _ filed a letter
of intent for a similar agreement. Those retailers were about to be
named in the original suits, said Al Meyerhoff, a lawyer for the
plantiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the garment factories in question are located on the
main island of Saipan, the capital of the Northern Marianas, which
became a U.S. commonwealth in 1976. The commonwealth is
self-governing with control over labor, immigration and customs.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, the four retailers will set up a $1.25
million fund to pay for the independent monitoring program and to
cover partial damages to the workers. The lawsuit claimed the
workers, who were attracted to Saipan jobs for the opportunity of
working on U.S. soil, endured 12-hour days, beatings and deplorable
living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the retailers named in the lawsuit had said they would
not have knowingly contracted with substandard factories on Saipan.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long, drawn-out battle didn't make good sense to us even
though we remain confident about our ability to successfully defend
ourselves in these lawsuits,'' Erik Nordstrom, the co-president of
Nordstrom's department store, said in a statement released Monday.
``We believe the settlement is a positive step toward our goal of
ensuring that the goods we contract to manufacture in Saipan are
made in compliance with law.''
</P>
<P>
   Gymboree, in a statement from its chief executive, denied having
liability under the lawsuits but said the agreement increased
protection for its workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now pleased to take another step to ensure we do an
even better job protecting the people who work for us so hard,''
said Gary White, Gymboree's chief executive. ``We believe the new
arrangement will take the protection right to the factory floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for Veriti, an Amherst, Mass.-based
nonprofit organization, to handle the monitoring process through
unannounced visits and private interviews with workers in their
native languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been case before in which retailers have agreed
to a monitor they haven't picked themselves,'' said Media Benjamin,
co- founder of Global Exchange, a San Francisco human rights group
that was a plaintiff in the class-action lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
