<HEADLINE>
SALON.COM REPORTS CONTINUE LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Salon.com on-line publishing venture saw
revenue jump while the amount of red ink continued to grow, the
company reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Salon's latest earnings report, its first since its
June 22 stock market debut, the edgy cultural Web site reported 1.3
million visitors to its various on-line departments in the second
quarter ended June 30. That compares to 567,000 visitors during the
same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But along with those new users came financial losses. The
company reported a net loss of $4.6 million ($10.10 per diluted
share) for the second quarter, compared with a loss of $1.4 million
($3.75 per diluted share) for the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue increased, however, from $408,000 during the second
quarter of 1998 to just over $1 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a land grab out there,'' said Michael O'Donnell, the
chief executive of the company, attributing the losses to staff
buildup and advertising. ``You have to spend to build a brand.''
</P>
<P>
   David Card, an analyst with New York-based Jupiter
Communications, an Internet market research firm, said Internet
users increasingly are turning to a ``handful of Web sites'' on a
regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's very much a land grab and very logical for Salon to be
spending big to grab those limited number of people,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
