<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMUEL BUTLER WAS AHEAD OF HIS TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Samuel Butler, a 20th-century man whose misfortune was to live
in the 19th century, is staging a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Butler was a renowned thinker who died when the 20th century was
still in diapers. His autobiographical ``The Way of All Flesh'' is
among the ``100 best novels of the century written in English'' as
selected by board members of the Modern Library. As with all other
cited titles, it is issued in a new Modern Library edition. It's
selling well, causing talk, and touching off a minibarrage of
essays _ some about the novel, more about its fascinating author.
</P>
<P>
   England's Samuel Butler (1835-1902) was a strange one. He was a
Homeric scholar who theorized that the ``Odyssey'' was composed by
a woman. Butler was a successful sheep farmer during a voluntary
exile in New Zealand, an early supporter of Charles Darwin and,
later, an articulate critic of the latter's ``On the Origin of
Species.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler was an all-around man of letters, an impassioned social
critic whose essays on matters philosophical, theological and
scientific still have freshness. He was best known during his
lifetime for ``Erewhon'' (an anagram of ``Nowhere''), the most
famous and arguably the best of all Utopian satires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way of All Flesh'' was no 20th-century novel after all.
True, it qualified for the Modern Library list by having been
published in 1903, but it was written between 1875 and 1888. Butler
specified that its appearance be deferred until after his death. He
had his reasons. In ``The Way of All Flesh,'' the somewhat
misanthropic Butler related the story of his own family. The novel
is a valid damning of Victorian society but is more powerfully an
indictment of parental cruelty and insensitivity. Ernest Pontifex,
the wayward hero, attributes all of his life's miseries to the
tyranny of Theobald, his father, and to the whining ineffectuality
of Cynthia, his mother.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that a fair number of the English literati read ``The
Way of All Flesh'' in manuscript and accepted all of it as truth.
Surely Butler exaggerated many of his book's particulars,
incorporated events that never occurred, and drew characters
without models from life. In semiautobiographical fiction, mystery
abides in the ``semi.''
</P>
<P>
   What was real and what was invented? ``The Way of All Flesh''
may be no more autobiographical than, say, Charles Dickens' ``David
Copperfield.'' It is surely less autobiographical than ``The Story
of a Bad Boy'' by Thomas Bailey Aldrich, an American and Butler's
exact contemporary. Aldrich's strong novel was intended for adult
readers but became, ironically, a semiclassic for young readers,
because its protagonist was an adolescent over much of the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   The premium American example of autobiographical fiction may
still be Thomas Wolfe's ``Look Homeward, Angel.'' ``The Way of All
Flesh'' has been more widely imitated by confessional authors, yet
it remains somehow singular.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas ``Copperfield'' begins with David's birth, Butler's work
considers three generations of the Pontifex family before Ernest
comes into their world. The distended text touches on every aspect
of Ernest's life, from infancy to the middle years; but in the way
that most autobiographical novels are meant to be instructive, the
teacher in this instance is not Ernest Pontifex. He is the
observed, not the observer. It's a first-person report, but Ernest
is conveyed in the third person by Edward Overton, the narrator,
who is Ernest's godfather.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest's misadventures never fail to interest, but the dominant
personage is Theobald, the monster of a father who also personifies
religious hypocrisy. Bullied by his father into the ministry,
Theobald in turn browbeats Ernest into theological pursuit. Like
Butler, Ernest attends Cambridge but does not take holy orders.
Before he makes a complete break from his parents, Ernest rides a
yo-yo of religious belief and disbelief. Samuel Butler was himself
the embodiment of struggle between faith and doubt that
characterized the late Victorian period.
</P>
<P>
   The novel is stylistically modern, closer to C.P. Snow than to
Dickens or Thackeray in both texture and spirit. No less a critic
than Bernard Shaw saluted ``The Way of All Flesh'' as the greatest
novel ever written.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is retired books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
