<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-COCAINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH W. BUSH: A SLICK WILLIE IN GOP CLOTHES? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DARREN RICHARDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Judging from the early polls and his campaign's
fund-raising prowess, Texas Gov. George W. Bush has a very good
chance to become our next president.
</P>
<P>
   And, judging from his slippery responses to questions about past
cocaine use, Bush understands he can get a lot of mileage by
emulating the verbal evasiveness practiced so fluently by President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stands alone among 12 major-party candidates in refusing to
deny ever using cocaine, stating through spokeswoman Mindy Tucker,
``He's not going to get into the game of personal destruction.''
Election Day 2000 is still 15 months away. That's a long time to
dodge questions about drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is playing a game by saying he's not playing games; it's
sort of like Clinton's ``I didn't inhale'' marijuana qualifier,
just not as clever.
</P>
<P>
   His approach is to take the high ground, no pun intended.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with his strategy of hollow platitudes instead of
substantive policy proposals, Bush now says he ``elevates politics
to a new level'' by refusing to say whether or not he broke drug
laws in the not-so-distant past.
</P>
<P>
   If this is what Bush means by elevating politics, then he's
nothing more than a Republican version of Clinton Lite, pandering
to our cynicism with linguistic dances. Clinton got away with it
because he's Clinton, pure and simple, a freakish, once-in-an-era
manifestation of our worst assumptions about politicians embodied
in the person of a slick-talking Southerner with a heart of
papier-mache and the convictions of the latest tracking poll.
</P>
<P>
   Slick's act is tired now. And it was tired even before he
questioned, under oath, the relative meanings of the word ``is.''
The last thing the country wants or needs is another deceptive
pretty boy pretending not to understand what is expected of him as
leader of the free world.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush should know from his experience with alcohol, drug use
is no game. He has talked openly about how, at age 40, he realized
booze was taking a toll on his life and how he decided to stop
drinking for the good of himself and his family. Bush knows honesty
is crucial to any recovery; and where alcohol is concerned, he
seems to have put that knowledge into practice.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the good of the country he hopes to lead _ not to
mention a campaign that has been heretofore treated deferentially
by most of the news media _ Bush should be equally forthcoming
about what he did or didn't put up his nose during what he has
called his ``young and irresponsible'' years.
</P>
<P>
   If he has never used cocaine, he should say so. Case closed, end
of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   If he has used cocaine, he should deliver a major speech on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   He should also speak out if he may have used cocaine but cannot
remember because of an alcoholic blackout or some other reason. If
that's the case, responsible behavior demands that he tell America
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Voters should not dismiss Bush if he speaks frankly about his
past. He has made mistakes, like all humans, and he has displayed
impressive courage in turning his life around.
</P>
<P>
   What is not acceptable is silence about drug use, especially
when so many prison cells are filled with people who violated drug
laws, ridiculous and severe as some of these laws may be.
</P>
<P>
   To confront a potentially explosive issue directly would mark a
major departure from the head-in-the-sand, ``don't ask, don't
tell'' mentality that has eroded the credibility of the Clinton
administration. Such a speech would also offer hope to cocaine
users who continue to struggle with their own private demons.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, when he was running in 1988 for the Democratic
presidential nomination as a senator from Tennessee, admitted using
marijuana _ and inhaling _ in the wake of President Ronald Reagan's
ill-fated nomination of Douglas Ginsburg to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg, it seemed, had enjoyed a puff now and then while
teaching at Harvard University in the 1970s. When this became
public knowledge, Ginsburg, rather than hypocritically assert he
could impartially uphold the law after willfully breaking it many
times, simply withdrew his name from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that using marijuana in the '60s and early '70s was
akin to drinking moonshine during Prohibition. He admitted getting
stoned as a student while in college, as a soldier in Vietnam and
as a reporter in Nashville. Gore met the potential crisis head on,
defused it, and it wasn't even an issue in 1992 when Clinton tabbed
him as the vice presidential pick.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is taking his cue from the wrong half of the Clinton-Gore
team. And perhaps, if Bush can raise $37 million in campaign cash
before a single primary vote has been cast, a brave speech about
cocaine might persuade Americans to donate to drug rehabilitation
centers, or at the very least acknowledge that cocaine abuse is a
serious problem that crosses all socioeconomic and ethnic lines.
</P>
<P>
   The president that Bush hopes to succeed, sadly, hasn't been
able or willing to speak frankly about so many things, personal as
well as political. To distinguish himself from that pathetic
legacy, all George W. Bush has to do is tell the truth about
cocaine _ or tell us it's none of our business. Just spare us a GOP
version of Dances with Words.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not he's capable of coming clean will tell voters all
we need to know about the ``character issue'' in regard to this
particular candidate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Darren Richardson, a copy editor for the San Francisco
Examiner, says he used cocaine once, in 1987, and liked it so much
he realized the responsible course of action was never using it
again.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
