Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMUSEMENT-ACCIDENTS (Agawam, Mass.) _ As probers investigate the
latest serious accident at an amusement park, specialists say Baby
Boomers who crave life on the edge are driving competition among
park owners to offer the craziest ride. Accidents at theme parks
and carnivals have jumped 24 percent since 1994. By Thomas
Farragher. 1300 words. GRAPHICS: 10 picas x 2.5 inches, ``Dangerous
rides''; 12 picas x 3 inches, ``Ride deaths.'' (Rebudgeting as
feature with graphics.)
</P>
<P>
   CORPS-ENGINEERS (Undated) _ Hobbled by Congressional budget cuts
and fearful of drawing unwanted political attention, the US Army
Corps of Engineers is rapidly retreating from tough protection of
the nation's wetlands. By Scott Allen. 1600 words. GRAPHIC: 36
picas x 4 inches, ``Protecting wetlands.''
</P>
<P>
   FEMALE-INMATES (Framingham, Mass.) _ Women currently comprise
the fastest-growing prison population, with unintended consequenses
that ripple past those serving time. By Zachary Dowdy. 1500 words.
PHOTO; GRAPHIC, 37 picas x 3 inches, ``Stricter laws sending more
women to prison.''
</P>
<P>
   PRINCIPALS-CHALLENGE (Cambridge, Mass.) _ The nationwide push to
demand higher standards _ and better test scores _ from public
schools has put one profession in particular under the gun:
principals. By James Bandler. 870 words.
</P>
<P>
   NEWAGE-RESORT (Lenox, Mass.) _ Canyon Ranch, which started 10
years ago as a somewhat quirky New Age resort in the Berkshire
hills, has become one of the hottest spas in the nation, wildly
popular with the beneficiaries of the booming economy. By Anthony
Flint. 1270 words.
</P>
