</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XIT RANCH REUNION REQUIRES TEXAS-SIZE BARBECUE PIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas writer Jerry Flemmons once wrote: ``Of the world's four
great cuisines _ French, Italian, Chinese and Texan _ only the
latter has a recipe beginning, `First, dig a 3-foot-deep hole.
...'''
</P>
<P>
   Flemmons was speaking of a skimpy, Texas backyard barbecue, of
course, not a cookout like the one in Dalhart this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It is there, high in the Texas Panhandle, that the XIT Rodeo and
Reunion takes place each August. This was the 63rd reunion and, as
usual, more than 20,000 free barbecue meals were handed out.
</P>
<P>
   The XIT was once the largest ranch in Texas, somewhere around 3
million acres _ land exchanged for construction of the state
Capitol. The ranch was eventually parceled off and it no longer
exists. But an XIT organization sponsors the barbecue each year,
financed through ticket sales to a rodeo and dances.
</P>
<P>
   The first reunion was part of the 1936 Texas Centennial and was
celebrated in Fort Worth. The following year, it was moved to
Dalhart where it remains.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch was big, and so is the reunion barbecue. It calls for
two pits (one extra in case it rains) 4 feet deep, 4 feet wide, and
75 feet long. Volunteers work all winter collecting wood for the
fire. They prefer mesquite, but when you need that much wood, you
take what you can get. On Thursday, workers stacked the wood in the
pit until it was piled 5 feet above ground.
</P>
<P>
   It took about 25 truckloads.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was set ablaze before dawn Friday and allowed to burn
for about 12 hours. In the interim, the meat was prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say this is the procedure: Take about 11,000 pounds
of meat in the form of roasts (topside round) weighing about 15
pounds, cut each in half and roll it in special seasoning. Put the
roast in a special paper sack, and then in a burlap bag and tie it
with wire. Soak it in water and put it in a truck. Just before
placing the meat on the coals about 2 p.m. Friday, the Fire
Department soaks the bags of meat again.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the really special and unique touches.
</P>
<P>
   Grader blades (from a road grader) are laid across the pit on
top of the meat and covered with tin, and then with dirt. Then the
meat cooks for 24 hours. Afterward, scrape away the dirt, pull away
the tin, remove the grader blades, open the bags and eat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever driven down a Texas back road and envied the
slow-paced, leisurely lifestyle of the grazing cattle?
</P>
<P>
   Have you wondered what it would be like to be a proud English
aristocrat like a Hereford, or a durable Scotsman like an Angus?
How about something exotic like an African Watusi or purely
American like a Santa Gertrudis? Anything from a milk cow to a
Texas longhorn?
</P>
<P>
   If you have entertained such thoughts, you should probably seek
professional help. But before you do, write to Howard Payne
University professor Frank Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp is working on a doctoral dissertation about cattle. He is
studying their history, but he also wants to know how you feel
about them _ which ones do you like the best? The least? What
images do the different breeds evoke? Essentially, he wants to know
what kind of cow or bull you would be if you could be one at all.
</P>
<P>
   Send your comments to Sharp at 20 Country Club Drive, Brownwood
76801. Or e-mail him at fsharp(at)hputx.edu.
</P>
<P>
   He'll get back to us with the results. He promises the
information will be published in a scholarly article and again in a
subsequent book.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
