<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1943 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWN-SFCHRON &LR;      08-10 1826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWN-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: This story is made up of a main bar, short
pieces  about lawn care (and lawn mower racing!) and a resource
box.   Living by the Blades: Turf experts inch toward cutting-edge 
 lawns  
   
   
 By Holly Ocasio Rizzo 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; New lawns face a tough test: Ali Harivandi's test.
For 20 years, the environmental horticulturist has planted,
nurtured and coaxed grass seeds to sprout at trial plots in Santa
Clara. Then he has examined and cross-examined them to judge the
best grasses for Bay Area lawns.  &LR; The U.S. Department of
Agriculture compiles the results.
<P>
   &LR;  Turf experts such as Harivandi, who works for the University
of California Cooperative Extension Service in Hayward, are
responsible for an explosion of new varieties of grasses that can
withstand kids, dogs, heat and drought. And, as grass becomes
stronger, it is also acquiring a new aesthetic _ still the green
frame around a house, but also studded with low-growing wildflowers
and mowed in naturalistic patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``As new varieties come to market, we plant them and evaluate
them monthly for color, texture, weed activity _ all the factors
about a lawn that concern people,'' Harivandi says. ``At least once
a week we gat a call from somebody who has a new variety for us to
test.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; What's New
</P>
<P>
   The testers here and elsewhere look for an ideal lawn, one that
is dark green, soft, dense, disease resistant _ and doesn't require
much sprinkling or mowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're recommending tall fescues for the Bay Area,''
Harivandi says. A fescue lawn tolerates drought, requiring 20
percent less water than other lawns.
</P>
<P>
   But it can't be just any fescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``What works well in Nevada under irrigation is not what works
in San Francisco or Santa Clara or Lafayette,'' says Paul Albright,
owner of Albright Seed Co., a supplier based in Martinez and
Camarillo.
</P>
<P>
   How can you find out if the fescue you like will like you and
your microclimate? ``Local extension agents' recommendations are
reliable,'' Albright says.
</P>
<P>
   University extension staff also can tell you the pros and cons
of the other high performers for the Bay Area _ bluegrass,
perennial rye grass and hybrid Bermuda grass. They can tell you
about some of the hundreds of new varieties that withstand little
feet, paws and other family traffic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In Bloom &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You can even go one better and include some color in your lawn.
Albright's company is one of several selling seed mixtures
containing wildflowers. One of Albright's, North Berkeley Low Fuel
Concoction, is a mix of fescue, poppy, lupine and clover intended
for quick coverage of slopes scorched by wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   The flower trend developed in Oregon, a state that calls itself
the grass seed capital of the world. At the University of Oregon, a
horticulturist sought a blend of grass and flowers that would look
pretty but require minimal water or mowing.
</P>
<P>
   The result, called Northern Ecology Lawn Mix, is created mixed
 &LR; and sold by Nichols Garden Nursery of Albany, Ore. ``It grows 8
inches high at most,'' says Betty Walker of Nichols. ``We mow ours
about every three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Park in Your Yard &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Even the plainest yards get dressed up nowadays with specialty
mowing. The new aesthetic is mowing higher under trees than in open
areas for a parklike appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Even ordinary lawns acquire sophistication when they're mowed in
patterns. And pattern mowing offers more than superficial benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like in the old days of cattle trains, if you mow the same way
all the time, you could wear paths in the grass,'' says Bill Lowe,
product manager for Snapper Power Equipment in McDonough, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``You especially have the potential of mowing ruts into your
yard when the ground is slightly damp. If you change directions,
the chance decreases.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross mowing _ creating a plaid effect _ helps lift grass
blades, ensuring a more even cut and chopping the clippings into
fine mulch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have a healthier, better-looking yard if you mow in
different directions,'' Lowe says.
</P>
<P>
   The next turf frontier: creating a no-mow grass. ``If someone
comes along and says, `Here's a lawn you only need to mow once
every two weeks,' but once a week isn't enough for the lawn I have
now, I'm going to buy it,'' Harivandi says.
</P>
<P>
   As long as you have to mow, here are some tips for choosing,
caring for and enjoying your lawn. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Meet Your Grass &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Grass comes in two varieties _ sod forming, which grows secondary
shoots along horizontal stems, and bunching, which expands from
clumps. Here are the most common grasses of both varieties for Bay
Area lawns:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KENTUCKY BLUEGRASS  &LR; (Poa pratensis)cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Relatives: &LR;  Sod-forming grass, more than 100 varieties.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Characteristics: &LR;  Fine texture; rich blue-green color; heat-,
wear- and drought-tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Likes: &LR;  Fertilizer; lots of water when weather is hot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dislikes: &LR;  Shade or lots of moisture (some varieties); growing
from seed (some varieties).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TALL FESCUE &LR;  (Festuca elatior)cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Relatives: &LR;  Bunching-type grass; most widely grown lawn grass
in Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Characteristics: &LR;  Coarse texture; new varieties have fine
blades; deepest-rooted among cool-season grasses, so it tolerates
drought as well as heat, wear and shade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Likes: &LR;  Less water than other varieties; growing to 4 inches
between mowings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dislikes: &LR;  Extremely low temperature.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERENNIAL RYEGRASS &LR;  (Lolium perenne)cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Relatives: &LR;  Bunching types; more than 180 varieties (compared
with seven in 1970).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Characteristics: &LR;  Germinates quickly; tolerates drought and
wear; may mow unevenly because of tendency to lie flat under mower.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Likes: &LR;  Growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dislikes: &LR;  Hot and cold extremes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HYBRID BERMUDA GRASS &LR;  (Cynodon dactylon)cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Relatives:  &LR; Sod-forming grasses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Characteristics: &LR;  Fine texture; pest and disease resistant;
invasive root system leads to its reputation as a weed outside the
lawn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Likes: &LR;  Inland heat, drought, poor soil, rapid growth requiring
frequent mowing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dislikes: &LR;  Shade, winter (some varieties turn brown in cool
weather). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Rogues' Gallery &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lawns face many menaces. Here are some ways to discourage the
biggest and baddest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weeds: &LR;  Dandelions, crabgrass and their unsightly ilk that
crowd grass for nutrients and water; dig or pull out, including
roots, or apply a weed killer-fertilizer or pre-emergent control
product.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cutworms: &LR;  Moth caterpillars that chew off blades at ground
level under cover of night, causing holes and ragged appearance;
control with natural predators, such as beneficial soil nematodes,
or earthworms, or with insecticide containing diazinon or carbaryl
and labeled for lawn use.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sod webworms: &LR;  Moth caterpillars that build web-lined tunnels
underground and eat grass blades, causing turf to turn patchy
brown; control with beneficial soil nematodes, or earthworms, or
insecticides containing diazinon or chlorpyrifos labeled for lawn
use.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Brown patch: &LR;  Fungi-caused disease causing irregularly shaped
or circular brown areas in lawn; prevent by planting resistant
grass varieties, avoiding excess fertilizer, watering only in
morning, mowing higher in summer and raking up grass clippings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Red thread: &LR;  Fungus that skulks into lawns from late fall
through early spring, most often in coastal areas, its red
jellylike strands seeming to mat perennial ryegrass blades
together; prevent by planting resistant varieties, aerating lawn if
soil is compacted, fertilizing to build up lawn's resistance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Thatch: &LR;  Buildup of dead roots, stems and debris below grass
blades that stops air, fertilizer and water from reaching roots;
prevent by raking lawn regularly. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Gentlemen, Start Your Mowers &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The stock models reach top speeds of 10 mph; modified drags, 70
mph. We're talking about power here. We're talking about racing
ride-on lawn mowers.
</P>
<P>
   You may see racers live and up close soon at the Cow Palace,
which has begun talks with the U.S. Lawn Mower Racing Association
about competing in San Francisco. ``This is a bigger sport that we
thought,'' says Bill Mendez, operations director at the Cow Palace.
</P>
<P>
   For a preview, watch racing in November on TNN. The cable
broadcaster plans Sunday evening broadcasts of six competitions in
the USLMRA-sanctioned Sta-Bil National Lawn Mower Racing Series.
</P>
<P>
   The circuit starts each April 1, stopping at festivals and
fairs, though it hasn't come to California in recent years. It
involves no purse money. Racers ages 16 to 82 compete for trophies,
bragging rights and fun, says Bruce Kaufman, USLMRA president.
</P>
<P>
   Most races are held on road-style tracks, preferably on grass.
Drag races are held on 150-foot strips. Racers with comparable
mowing equipment compete against each other. Some have pit crews
and sponsors. A few, like big-time wrestlers, have powerful names:
Blades of Thunder or the Iron Maiden. For safety, none of the
mowers has blades.
</P>
<P>
   Tap  &LR; www.letsmow.com  &LR; into your Web browser for information
about becoming a racer or spectator. ``Once you've seen a race,
you'll never look at the weekend chore of mowing quite the same way
again,'' Kaufman says. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GRASS FACTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A lawn of 625 square feet provides enough oxygen for one person
for a day. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turf absorbs carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide, converting them
to oxygen. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well-maintained lawns and landscapes add 5 percent to 15 percent
to a property's value. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 1,000-square-foot lawn contains 850,000 grass plants. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A single grass plant can have up to 300 miles of roots. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans own more than 50 million lawn mowers. &QL; 
 &UR; TO LEARN MORE &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Scotts Co., McDonough, Ga. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Helpline: (800) 543-8873; experts answer grass and lawn
questions, and offer a free lawn care booklet.
</P>
<P>
   Web site:  &LR; www.scottscompany.com &LR; ; information on identifying
and solving lawn problems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ortho Lawn &AMP; Garden Products, San Ramon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Web site:  &LR; www.ortho.com &LR; ; information on basic lawn care.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; University of California Cooperative Extension Service &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Information about basic lawn care, best Bay Area grasses.
</P>
<P>
   Alameda County: (510) 567-6812.
</P>
<P>
   Contra Costa County: (925) 646-6540.
</P>
<P>
   Marin County: (415) 499-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Napa County: (707) 253-4221.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco and San Mateo counties: (650) 871-7559.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara County: (408) 299-2635.
</P>
<P>
   Solano County: (707) 421-6790.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma County: (707) 565-2608. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ON THE SHELF &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``Lawn Care for Dummies,'' &LR;  by Lance Walheim (IDG Books Worldwide,
1998, $16.99).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to a Beautiful Lawn,'' &LR;  by Maureen
Gilmer (Alpha Books, 1999, $18.95).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Western Garden Problem Solver'' &LR;  (Sunset Books Inc., 1998,
$24.95). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ON THE TRACK &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; U.S. Lawn Mower Racing Association, Glenview, Ill.  &LR; Information
about mower safety. Phone: (847) 729-7363; Web site:
 &LR; www.letsmow.com &LR; . &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
