<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1989 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-10 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MIRACLE FROM ASSISI 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If only by virtue of the fact that cinema bad
boy Mickey Rourke once played him in a movie, we can conclude that
St. Francis of Assisi appeals to a broader spectrum of folks than
your average saint.
</P>
<P>
   Even people who don't believe in God have been drawn over the
past 900 years to the nature-loving, peace-preaching Italian monk.
During that time the basilica that honors him in his home region
has been a magnet for pilgrims of all spiritual bent (and twist).
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for a series of killer earthquakes that began in
Assisi Sept. 26, 1997, St. Francis' basilica would currently be
doing business as usual _ which is to say booming. But the quakes
destroyed about 2,000 square feet of one of the 13th-century
structure's two churches. Part of the upper church's roof
collapsed, and priceless frescoes by such Italian masters, as
Giotto and Cimabue were reduced to fingernail-sized chips and
masonry dust.
</P>
<P>
   From that catastrophe, a wonderful opportunity has been given to
the citizens of and visitors to Milan, Paris, New York and San
Francisco. As part of a $60 million restoration project, scores of
surviving works of art and reliquaries from the basilica are out of
their damaged home and on tour.
</P>
<P>
   Through Nov. 14, they will rest here, in a city named after
Francesco di Assisi, in the Palace of the Legion of Honor in
Lincoln Park. A dollar from each admission ticket will go toward
the basilica's restoration.
</P>
<P>
   For at least a dozen reasons, I plan to visit _ to be near St.
Francis' ``things'' _ as often as I can manage. During a deeply
moving visit I made to Assisi in 1989, I realized the power of
proximity to all those beautiful devotional tributes to a man of
simple but perfect spiritual philosophy. It's as close as I can
ever come to feeling the saint's breath upon me.
</P>
<P>
   When I say ''things,'' I don't mean Francesco's hairbrush or
rough brown monk's robe or even his prayerbook. He was buried the
day after he died (in 1226) and _ thanks to a vow of poverty and
perpetual giving _ didn't exactly leave a warehouse of possessions
and memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   The basilica grew up over the centuries around his sacred bones.
All sorts of people who felt moved by and connected to St. Francis
_ from King Henry III of England to the now-nameless artists who
painted the monk's likeness on wood _ contributed to the devotional
decorating.
</P>
<P>
   The trappings of their reverence, honor, awe and love constitute
St. Francis' ``things.'' And you don't have to be Catholic to
imagine that those trappings exude what New Agers might call ``a
lot of great energy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the traveling exhibit, one of the most touching and
representative examples of what I mean is a late 15th century
triptych with a carved gilt frame that pictures the Virgin Mary
with baby Jesus and two angels as its centerpiece. Depicted on the
side panels are Christ tied to a column and John the Baptist on a
journey.
</P>
<P>
   Almost unheard of for that era, the artist actually signed the
piece, infusing it with an animate intimacy: ``Franciscus Gentilis
me pinxit'' _ ``Francisco of Gentile painted me.''
</P>
<P>
   A portrait of Christ, painted in the early 1460s and attributed
to Fra Angelico's star pupil, Benozzo Gozzoli, is heartbreaking.
Entitled, ``The Holy Face,'' it shows an exhausted, profoundly sad,
almost bewildered Jesus wearing his crown of thorns. Blood trickles
from his head wounds and pools in his eye sockets, turning the
whites to pink. His lips are slightly parted, as if he starts to
say something _ ``Why?'' _ but decides it's useless.
</P>
<P>
   As I moved about the two-room exhibit, it occurred to me that,
in a way, the great slow earthquake of time itself has re-fashioned
so many of St. Francis' things.
</P>
<P>
   A portrait of a woman in a vibrant orange tunic could be of St.
Cecilia or St. Margaret. It was created in the mid-1300s; the I.D.
is lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   Several paintings are but pieces from altars that once spanned
huge churches. A panel from the mid-14th century by Sassotta is but
one of a 27-panel giant that was taken from the high altar of an
Italian church and split up. Now the pieces are scattered to the
winds, in 26 separate collections in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The treasures of St. Francis' basilica will be frustrating and
unsatisfying for those among us who find value in a work only when
we know who painted it or when we can view it intact.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of us, it is more than enough to be among some of
St. Francis' things. Gratefully, we join the millions who've come
before us _ kings, peasants and movie stars _ who felt a mysterious
affinity for a rich kid-turned preacher of peace, love and
humility.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
