<HEADLINE>
TOO MUCH HOT AIR ABOUT GLOBAL WARMING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It was late on a Friday afternoon. I was on the
New York Thruway, headed west in blistering heat in a car without
air conditioning. I was drenched in sweat _ something we've all
seen a lot of lately.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the skies darkened, and a monsoon swept over the
highway. It was like driving under Niagara Falls. I pulled off at a
rest area and ducked into the restaurant until the rain lifted.
When I came out, the temperature had dipped about 20 degrees. As I
got back into my car, the guy who'd parked next to me said, ``Hey,
this global warming is getting mean, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, sitting on the deck at my little summer place
on what was becoming a chilly summer evening, I pondered that
stranger's casual, offhand remark. It was one of only dozens I've
heard during this sultry summer of drought and intense, daily heat.
</P>
<P>
   Global warming? Well, what else could be happening here? After
all, wasn't last year the hottest on record worldwide? Haven't the
red-hot 1990s been history's warmest decade?
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that the world is growing warmer because of an
increase in what scientists call greenhouse gases, mainly methane
and carbon dioxide. The theory also is that the increase in
greenhouse gases is largely the result of human activity _ auto
emissions, burning fossil fuels and so on.
</P>
<P>
   There's a problem with the theory, though. Despite what so many
people seem to believe, it could all be hot air.
</P>
<P>
   Weather is what happens this week. Climate is what happens this
millennium. They're related, but hardly the same. Our temperature
records go back only a bit more than a century. The really reliable
records on temperature, the stuff scientists get from satellites,
go back only 25 years or so.
</P>
<P>
   The point is this: we might be in the midst of global warming;
then again, it might merely have been hot lately. In the 1970s, by
the way, it was cold. The winter of 1977 was the coldest on record
_ not that the record is all that extensive.
</P>
<P>
   The other problem is that naturally occurring carbon emissions
outnumber all the emissions caused by humanity by about 30 to one.
In short, if the world's temperature really is rising, can humanity
be playing such a towering, decisive role in that process?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, OK, but if it's really getting warmer, then people must be
having some impact, right? What else could be causing it?
</P>
<P>
   As I sat on that deck, turning all this over in my mind, I was
gazing out over a lake that had been created 14,000 years ago. The
lake had been formed by a glacier receding at the end of the last
ice age.
</P>
<P>
   What caused that ice age to begin with? What caused it to end?
Nobody knows. What we do know is that many relatively quick,
convulsive shifts in world climate took place long before humans
began burning coal or natural gas or cruising around with bad
mufflers. I've found fossils of long-dead oceanic creatures in
slabs of slate along that lakeshore, 714 feet above sea level and
hundreds of miles from salt water.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen thousand years ago, 30 feet of ice covered the current
site of the New York Capitol. In geologic time, that's not even an
eyeblink.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, something might be happening. After all, something has
happened many times in the past. It's not illogical to presume that
it could happen again.
</P>
<P>
   But to presume, as so many people do, that a few hot summers and
mild winters constitute proof that it's definitely happening
doesn't make sense. And to presume that puny humanity has the power
to control it one way or the other makes even less sense than that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
