<SLUG> BC-HIDDEN-FEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINKING INSIDE THE BOX 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH SHERMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An amazing turn of events has occurred since the
last time I made a major purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Stores, which formerly raised prices to make up for customers
who steal from them, have apparently decided to eliminate the
middleman and now are stealing directly from you.
</P>
<P>
   In pursuit of a scanner (which I now find I need to do
business), I visited several major electronics and computer stores.
Scanners, used to add pictures, graphics and text to Web sites,
newsletters and other computer-related enterprises, can run
anywhere from around $99 on up to $1,000. In other words, a major
purchase. After strolling around one electronics store, I settled
on a scanner in the $200 range that seemed to have everything I
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   I learned that with the scanner comes a bunch of computer
software and an interface (after all if it doesn't work with your
computer, what you have just purchased is nothing).
</P>
<P>
   I asked mildly intelligent questions about operation and
applications (all those ``-ation'' words that make people think you
know what you're talking about). After breezing through the scant
details on the warranty I suddenly felt my face shoved into a brick
wall as the salesman jovially informed me that if I had to return
the scanner for any reason at all, if it wasn't in an unopened box
they would charge me a 15 percent ``restocking fee.''
</P>
<P>
   What? ``You mean,'' I asked, ``if I go back to my office, try
out the scanner and come back tomorrow to return it because it's
not compatible with my computer, you'll charge me 15 percent?'' (or
$30 on a $200 purchase).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' the man said with a smile. ``How about if I
came back in an hour?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's still 15 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How about a half hour?''
</P>
<P>
   The salesman looked at me as if I were a very small child, with
an extremely limited brain capacity. ``If the package is opened, no
matter when you bring it back or what it is, we still charge you a
15 percent restocking fee.''
</P>
<P>
   My question is, why don't the stores just put their hands
directly in my wallet and pull out what they want NOW (it would
save a lot of time and trouble in the long run).
</P>
<P>
   To me, this is out and out stealing, a real rip-off. Now, I
understand, since this is, after all real life, that there are some
unscrupulous people out there who appear to buy things, but
actually take them home, use them, then return them, in effect
turning a store into a free rental shopping plaza. But I really do
believe that most people are essentially honest, and only return
things back if the do not work.
</P>
<P>
   Every other store I visited in my scanner quest told me that
they, too, have started imposing a restocking fee of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Why do we never read about this? How come these same stores
(which delight in trumpeting their low, low prices) never mention
this little money-taker in their ads?
</P>
<P>
   I know very few people who have ever been able to make a
decision about how well a particular product works without taking
it out of its packaging. But, in the alien world of modern
marketing, this is a talent you must develop, or else the very
bottom line is: You bought it; it's yours forever.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ruth Sherman is a free-lance writer and filmmaker in San
Francisc.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
