<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY THAT BOTTLE COSTS $50 IN A RESTAURANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the so-so cabernet you shelled out $50 for in that
restaurant last week? And how you felt you'd been taken? Well, if
it makes you feel any better, the winemaker didn't do too well on
the deal, either. He or she probably made about $2.
</P>
<P>
   In the wine trade, that's actually not bad money. Take
Ravenswood, a well-known winery in Sonoma, Calif. Ravenswood has
been making superior wines, mostly zinfandels, for almost 20 years.
Last year the winery, which is publicly traded, posted a net profit
of about $1.5 million on sales of $17 million. With some 131,000
cases of wine sold, that translates into a profit of about 95 cents
a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The Robert Mondavi Winery, also a public company, netted $29
million, selling just under 6.8 million cases, or some 81.2 million
bottles of wine. Net profit per bottle: 36 cents. Beringer Wine
Estates did a little better, making $29.5 million on about 6
million cases, or 41 cents a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   No need to send any of these people CARE packages. Volume
clearly makes up for any shortcomings in the per-bottle profits.
Even so, it should be evident that no one, at least no one at the
publicly owned wineries, is making a killing in the wine business.
Privately owned wineries do not release their profit figures.
</P>
<P>
   So where did your $50 go? (Closer to $60 with tax and tip.)
Mostly to the restaurant. The winery would have sold it to a
wholesaler _ called a distributor in the liquor business _ for
about $12.50. The distributor then would have marked it up about a
third, selling it to a retailer or to a restaurant for about
$16.50, plus freight and state taxes. The retailer then would sell
it for about $25, and the restaurant for double that, charging you
around $50.
</P>
<P>
   This is called the three-tiered system. Antiquated and costly,
it's part of the liquor laws of almost every state. And there can
be a fourth tier as well. Many larger wine producers hire marketing
companies to augment the efforts of the distributors. Typically, a
marketer will take a five-figure fee for selling a predetermined
number of cases.
</P>
<P>
   It cost the maker of our $50 bottle about $10.50 to produce it.
Wine-making costs are not difficult to understand. First, there are
the grapes. Some wineries use only grapes they have grown
themselves. Big wineries like Mondavi and Beringer own vineyards
and also buy grapes from other growers. Many smaller wineries, like
Ravenswood, buy all their grapes, currently paying $2,000 and more
a ton for the best cabernet sauvignon. Estate-grown or purchased,
grapes can account for up to 25 percent of production costs.
</P>
<P>
   The bottle, cork, label and the capsule around the bottle's neck
would ordinarily account for little more than $1, except at the E.
&AMP; J. Gallo Winery, which makes its own bottles and prints its own
labels. Accounting for the rest of the wine production costs:
barrels, which can cost $600 each, storage costs while the wine is
aging, taxes, marketing and promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, prices, markups and fees are flexible. If a highly
regarded small-production wine, say a Bruno Giacosa barbera from
Italy or a Silver Oak cabernet from California, is much in demand
and only one distributor carries it in a state or city, he may
increase his markup from a third to 40 percent or more. Retailers
and restaurants will pass this increase on to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Once, restaurants simply added 50 percent to the retail price of
a bottle of wine. More commonly now, they double or triple the
retail price. It's no longer surprising to find wines that sell for
$10 in New York wine shops on restaurant lists for $25 to $35. Most
restaurateurs defend high wine prices as a way to hold down the
cost of food and general overhead. But there are restaurants _
Harry's Hanover Square, Sparks Steakhouse and Union Square Cafe, to
cite three in New York _ that consistently offer lower wine prices
than their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Some price increases are unavoidable. Like many serious
restaurateurs, John Foy at the Sonoma Grill in East Rutherford,
N.J., holds his best Bordeaux and California cabernets for three or
four years before selling them. Since he uses bank loans to buy the
wine, he adjusts his prices periodically to cover his interest
payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be selling my 1994's for another two years, my 1995's
for three,'' he said. ``I've got to finance my inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with periodic adjustments, Foy said, he hews as closely to
the 50 percent over retail principle as he can. ``When I see some
of the prices in New York restaurants, I feel like saying, `If you
want to hold me up, why don't you just take a gun and ask for my
wallet?''' he said. ``It would be less hypocritical.''
</P>
<P>
   Foy's concerns are not necessarily those of all restaurantgoers,
especially in these good economic times. According to the most
recent restaurant poll conducted by Wine &AMP; Spirits, a consumer
magazine, the average price paid in United States restaurants last
year for cabernet sauvignon was $56 a bottle; for pinot noir, about
$47, and for chardonnay and merlot, about $40.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the average price of the most popular wines in 1998
was $43.59, a 24 percent jump in three years, Wine &AMP; Spirits'
editors said: ``It's beyond inflation and beyond most people's
ability to comprehend.''
</P>
<P>
   So be grateful you got that bottle for $50. At the rate we're
going, next year it may be $75.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
