u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      08-10 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RE-CREATING A TASTE OF SUMMER IN LIGURIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pesto has become a staple, especially in late summer when basil
is best, but pasta with pesto does have its limits. The delicious,
strongly flavored sauce must be used in such small quantities that
it adds practically nothing in the way of bulk to the dish. That's
why pasta with pesto is almost always best served as a first
course, the way it is in Italy. It is not substantial enough to
work as a main course.
</P>
<P>
   The Genoese, originators of pesto, must have figured this out
centuries ago, when they created trenette with pesto. Trenette is a
pasta similar to linguine (at one time made with whole-wheat
flour). Trenette with pesto is not as simple as it sounds: the dish
also contains chunks of potatoes and string beans, which make it
more complex, more filling and more interesting than plain pasta
with pesto.
</P>
<P>
   Re-creating the classic dish of Liguria, the region that
includes Genoa, is straightforward and easy. Although most recipes
would have you cook the string beans, potatoes and pasta
separately, this is not only unnecessary, but also a complete waste
of time and energy. If you start the potatoes and pasta
simultaneously, then add the string beans about halfway through
cooking, they will all be finished at the same time and can be
drained and tossed with the sauce in a snap. Admittedly, this
technique is imprecise, but I have had great success with it.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every time I was served this dish in Liguria, the
potatoes were the mealy baking variety, which just about fall apart
as you eat them. I prefer waxier potatoes, like tiny fingerlings
when I can get them or a not especially starchy all-purpose variety
like Yukon gold. Try the dish with whatever you have on hand,
though.
</P>
<P>
   Any kind of string beans will work, although thinner beans, like
delicate, flavorful haricots verts, should be added a minute or two
later than common string beans.
</P>
<P>
   Genoese pesto is very strong. It begins with the local
super-fragrant basil and great-tasting olive oil, goes heavy on
garlic and often includes sharp pecorino cheese in place of the
more common and mellower Parmesan. Any pesto recipe will work with
trenette, though.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, almost every pasta dish in Liguria is served with a
final sprinkling of good olive oil. This one will definitely
benefit from that treatment, especially if the sauce seems dry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRENETTE WITH PESTO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   { cup grated pecorino romano or other hard sheep's-milk cheese
</P>
<P>
   { cup extra virgin olive oil, or more
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   2 medium potatoes, about { pound, peeled and cut into {-inch
cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound trenette or linguine
</P>
<P>
   { pound string beans, trimmed and cut into 1-inch lengths.
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring a large pot of water to a boil, and salt it. Combine
the basil, garlic, salt and cheese in a blender or food processor;
pulse until roughly chopped. Add the olive oil in a steady stream,
and continue to blend until the mixture is fairly creamy, adding a
little more olive oil or some water if necessary. Add the pine
nuts, and pulse a few times to chop them into the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add the potatoes to the boiling water, and stir; then add the
pasta, and cook as usual, stirring frequently, about 10 minutes in
all. When the pasta is about half done _ the strands will bend but
are not yet tender _ add the string beans.
</P>
<P>
   3. When the pasta is done, the potatoes and beans should be
tender. Drain the pasta and vegetables, toss with pesto and more
salt or olive oil if you like, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
