<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIAN-GROCERIES-ART-N     08-10 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-GROCERIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS ON DECIPHERING AN ASIAN GROCERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though many Americans are eager to cook Asian dishes at home,
the thought of navigating an Asian grocery store is a different
story. For a non-Asian it can be bewildering territory full of
pungent aromas, packages with labels in Chinese, Japanese, Thai,
Korean or Vietnamese and odd-looking specimens you don't know
whether to eat or to plant.
</P>
<P>
   At last, there is a book that takes you by the hand and gives a
clear and fascinating tour of these markets. It couldn't have a
better title, ``The Asian Grocery Store Demystified'' (Renaissance
Books, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   The author, Linda Bladholm, begins by describing the layout of
an Asian grocery in her neighborhood in Miami. As she explains,
there is indeed an order to these markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asian markets are generally stocked according to the
principles of balance,'' she writes. ``Hot, spicy, chili sauces and
curry pastes are all in one place; salty items are together in one
row, and bitter, sour, or sweet things are in other sections.''
That explanation changed my entire perspective, making these
markets seem more manageable and interesting.
</P>
<P>
   I took Ms. Bladholm's book with me on an excursion to Chinatown
in Manhattan. The streets were filled with produce vendors,
children squatting on the sidewalk and women carrying bags full of
vibrant greens.
</P>
<P>
   Every vendor I passed sold these greens, which had long pointy
leaves. I paused at one and turned to the vegetable section of the
book. A simple illustration told me the green was water spinach, a
member of the sweet potato family that is also called ong-choy or
kangkong. The book also told me which part is edible, what it
tastes like and how it is used. Ms. Bladholm's descriptions are so
clear that I was able to identify every single one the vendor had
on display, including those without illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   I continued on to a large Asian grocery store. My first visit
there had left me feeling overwhelmed and defeated. This time I
spent two hours, guide in hand, meandering up and down the rows.
</P>
<P>
   As I made my way, I saw, smelled and learned about dried Chinese
yam, dried oysters and fermented bean curd. I spotted sweet
jackfruit, thinking I had found something truly unusual. But there
it was in the index, in three different forms. With many items,
like dried shrimp, won-ton wrappers and sesame oil, Ms. Bladholm
lists brands she likes. Finding them on the shelves gave
credibility to the book and reassured me.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, I had to use my powers of deduction. With a bottle
labeled ``Banana Catsup,'' for instance, I had to assume it was the
banana sauce written about in the condiments sections. In it, she
points out its similarities in taste and use to ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   I ran into problems when foods had impossibly vague labels, like
``dried herb.'' In these cases, no guide could help.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bladholm's book, as slim as a paperback, kept surprising me
with its depth. Consider the noodle section. While describing the
differences between various wheat, rice and egg noodles, she also
helps you understand how each fits into a particular Asian cuisine,
including important cultural information like the fact that noodles
are meant to be slurped and that cutting them is considered to be
bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   In the tea section, she slips in a paragraph about how tea is
made and how it is graded, and another on tea ceremonies. Under
sugar cane, she describes how the juice is served as a drink
throughout Asia, and how the cane is used to tenderize tripe in
Bali. There is also a small but eclectic group of recipes.
</P>
<P>
   If I would change anything about this practical book, it would
be to make it spiral bound so you could flip to sections and not
have the book close shut as you juggle jars and bags, trying to
read the labels.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bladholm not only sorts out the cultural context of an Asian
grocery store, but does it in such a way that makes you hungry to
return.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHILI PEANUTS WITH ANCHOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Asian Grocery Store Demystified'' by Linda
Bladholm &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   { cup dried anchovies or silver fish (ikan bilis), heads removed
</P>
<P>
   4 dried red chilies, soaked in water for 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, finely sliced
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   } cup unsalted roasted peanuts, skin on.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small saute pan, heat 1 tablespoon oil over medium-high
heat. Add anchovies, and fry until crisp but not browned, 1 to 2
minutes. Remove to a small bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. Drain chilies. In a mortar, combine chilies and shallot and
pound together with a pestle.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a wok or medium saute pan, heat remaining oil over medium
heat. Add chili mixture, salt and sugar, and saute for 1 minute.
Increase heat to medium-high, and add peanuts and anchovies. Fry
for 3 minutes, stirring constantly. Remove to a bowl, and serve.
Peanuts can be stored in a tightly closed jar in refrigerator for
up to 3 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 snack-size servings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BALINESE TOMATO AND LEMONGRASS BROTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Asian Grocery Demystified'' by Linda
Bladholm &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   4 stalks lemongrass, chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 large ripe tomatoes, chopped, plus 4 tablespoons diced tomato
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, chopped
</P>
<P>
   10 to 15 large sprigs cilantro, more for garnish
</P>
<P>
   3 slices ginger, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, peeled and crushed
</P>
<P>
   10 kaffir lime leaves
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons fish sauce, more to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons diced cucumber, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Bean sprouts, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1 lime, cut into wedges, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium pot, bring stock to a boil. Add lemongrass,
chopped tomatoes, shallots, cilantro, ginger, garlic and kaffir
lime leaves. Simmer for 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Strain through a fine sieve. Discard solids. Stir in the fish
sauce, adding more if desired. Divide among four serving bowls, and
garnish with cucumber, tomato, bean sprouts and cilantro. Serve
with a lime wedge.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 small servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
