<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT &LR;      08-10 0151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Cetamura Chianti, Badia a Coltibuono 1997, Tuscany, Italy.
About $10. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   So many good wines are coming out of Italy these days that it's
hard to keep up with them. Unfortunately, many have only two of the
three basic requirements for relatively little-known wines: quality
and a reasonable price. The third leg of the stool is availability.
Fortunately, Cetamura, from Badia a Coltibuono, a prominent Chianti
producer, is quite widely distributed. Less impressive than
Coltibuono's better Chiantis, Cetamura is nevertheless a
delightfully rounded everyday red wine with an array of rich
flavors, good concentration and lots of fruit. It's a classic
Chianti, composed of sangiovese and canaiolo, the essential Chianti
grapes. An easygoing, uncomplicated red for late summer and fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1609EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2044 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1S     08-10 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999    
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Chuck Lewis or Tim Spence at
202-298-6920. For questions about Houston Chronicle sports stories,
please call 713-220-7896.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: BRADLEY-2000; DOLE-2000; NASA-MARS; FETUS-FIGHT;
MENTAL-HEALTH; POLICE-PROFILING; and BBN-ASTROS.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-GUNS (Washington) _ With schools reopening this month in
many districts, Education Secretary Richard Riley reported
significant progress in reducing the threat of violent incidents
such as the one at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. ``We
are starting to move in the right direction,'' he said, citing a
report showing a 31 percent drop in school expulsions for bringing
weapons to school. However, school security officials said there is
no way to guarantee that deadly rampages won't happen again. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-2000 (Houston) _ Democratic presidential candidate Bill
Bradley addresses the Urban League and meets with black leaders in
Houston. The former New Jersey senator also campaigns in the South
Texas city of McAllen. By LORI RODRIGUEZ and ALAN BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-2000 (Des Moines, Iowa) _ We chronicle the campaign day of
Republican presidential hopeful Elizabeth Dole in advance of the
Iowa straw poll this weekend. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-MARS (Undated) _ Scientists say the latest pictures of the
Red Planet taken by NASA's orbiting Mars Global Surveyor reveal a
more dynamic atmosphere than previously thought _ dust devils,
winds that sculpt sand dunes, and frost that comes and goes with
the seasons. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   FETUS-FIGHT (Houston) _ Doctors caring for the unborn child of a
woman on life support cannot find a heart beat for the fetus and
believe the child has died in the mother's womb. The parents of the
woman are asking a court to allow them to turn off life-support
machines. The common-law husband who said he fathered the child
successfully argued for guardianship last week to prevent the
machines from being turned off. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL-HEALTH (Austin, Texas) _ A surprising shortfall of $30
million in this year's revenues for the state's mental health
agency could lead to cutbacks in services statewide by Sept. 1. Key
legislators and officials with the Texas Department of Mental
Health and Mental Retardation are scrambling to find a way to avoid
cutting services to the mentally ill. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-PROFILING (Houston) _ Houston Mayor Lee Brown, the
nation's former drug czar, and the Police Department will unveil a
new policy designed to root out ``racial profiling'' in the
country's fourth-largest city. By S.K. BARDWELL
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington )_ Christian Coalition President Pat
Robertson, the preacher and former GOP presidential candidate, this
week urged the federal government to drop its anti-assassination
policy and ``send a squad in to take out somebody like (accused
terrorist) Osama bin Laden....'' He added, ``I don't see anything
unChristian about it.'' Well, a lot of others do. Besides, we
adopted that policy decades ago partly out of self-preservation; if
we set out to assassinate foreign leaders we don't like, they may
want to assassinate our's first. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: Marianne Means will be on vacation until Thursday, Aug.
19.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Atlanta) _ The Houston Astros, 69-45, try to avenge
Monday night's 5-3 loss to the Atlanta Braves with a game tonight
in Atlanta. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
