<HEADER>
A2055 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-PROFILING-HNS &LR;      08-10 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-PROFILING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON SEEKS TO CURB RACIAL PROFILING BY POLICE OFFICERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
(Attn: Calif., N.J., N.Y. and Pa.) 
 
By S.K. BARDWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A new program aimed at ensuring Houston police
officers don't engage in racial profiling will be unveiled
Wednesday by Mayor Lee Brown and Police Chief C.O. Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the announcement, which coincides with visits to
the National Urban League conference by high-profile minority
rights advocates Johnnie Cochran and the Rev. Al Sharpton, has
brought claims from some officers that the program is just
political lip-service to a ``hot'' issue.
</P>
<P>
   Other officers, though, said the plan is farsighted and will be
copied in the coming months by law enforcement agencies all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Racial profiling is the practice of putting people under
criminal suspicion based on their race.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford declined to talk about the new program, saying he
preferred to answer questions about it at Wednesday's news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo last week, Houston Police Department Capt. David F.
Cutler outlined the methods HPD intends to use to eliminate racial
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Self-Initiated Police Contact Database Fact Sheets will be
filled out by officers every time they perform a ``self-initiated
investigative contact/stop,'' the memo states.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if the officer, based on his or her own
judgment, stops to talk to someone either because they appear to
have a problem or because they appear to be a problem, the officer
must fill out the form on a mobile computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   Information that has to be entered on the form includes the
date, time and location of the contact, the reason for the contact,
the disposition of the contact, and the age, race and sex of the
person contacted.
</P>
<P>
   The reports will be used to form a database from which reports
will be generated for review by Bradford, police managers and the
Internal Affairs Division, the memo states. Those reports will be
used to identify officers who may be practicing racial profiling.
The memo did not state what actions would be taken toward officers
suspected of profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Several patrol officers who read the memo and commented on it in
return for anonymity said they believe the new report will have two
effects on patrol officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction, and I think the reaction of a lot of
officers, is going to be, `OK, I'm not going to do these stops
anymore,''' said one officer.
</P>
<P>
   Another officer agreed: ``If I see a guy who maybe looks like
he's lost, or someone who looks like he's lurking somewhere he
shouldn't be, I might not stop and talk to him now, because most of
those turn out to be nothing, and then I'm going to have to fill
out this form for five or 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   A third officer pointed out another problem the forms may
create: ``If I do stop you, and you're black or Hispanic, I'm going
to try real hard to find something to give you a ticket for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise I may have (Internal Affairs) coming around later
saying I must have just stopped you to hassle you because you were
black or Hispanic _ if you'd been doing anything wrong, why didn't
I give you a ticket or arrest you?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Some older officers say the forms are reminiscent of the field
interrogation cards used by many departments, although not HPD, in
the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Those 3-by-5 index cards were used to record the names and
addresses of people officers talked to on the streets, and then
were sometimes used to round up suspects when a crime was committed
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The cards were put aside amid outrage from the minority
community, whose members made up the vast majority of the cards'
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several officers said the new reports are probably the result of
Bradford ``looking down the road,'' as one officer put it.
</P>
<P>
   Although racial profiling has been an issue for years, several
recent events have brought renewed attention to the matter.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation is still under way in the February death of
Amadou Diallo, an unarmed West African immigrant who died when four
New York City police officers, apparently mistaking him for someone
else, fired 41 bullets at him.
</P>
<P>
   Two New York City police officers have been convicted of
sodomizing and torturing Abner Louima, a Haitian immigrant, while
he was being held for questioning in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In December in Riverside, Calif., police shot a black woman in
the back with 12 bullets as she sat in her car.
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh in the same month, a police officer shot a black
man in a chase. The officer said he feared being run over, but his
reasoning was undermined by the finding that the motorist had been
shot through the driver's side window.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Gov. Christine Todd Whitman fired the state
police chief after he said blacks commit more crimes. State police
there were already under attack for allegedly using a racial
profile to stop motorists on the New Jersey Turnpike, a major
drug-trafficking corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Those incidents and others prompted President Clinton in June to
direct federal law enforcement agencies to begin collecting
information on the race, age and sex of people they detain, as a
first step toward determining whether minorities are unfairly
targeted for scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called on state and local police forces, which
operate outside federal jurisdiction, to begin collecting
information about who is being detained and why.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next step is clear,'' said one Houston police officer.
``Departments that don't start collecting this information,
bringing themselves into line with the feds, are going to lose
their asset forfeiture funding.''
</P>
<P>
   When local law enforcement agencies conduct police operations
jointly with federal agencies such as the DEA or FBI, and assets
are seized from a suspect, the local agency receives a portion of
those assets back. In Houston, that funding makes up millions of
dollars per year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
