<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2111 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT11-COX     08-10 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DUELING BRIEFS FILED IN MICROSOFT ANTITRUST TRIAL
 &HT;    500&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial queues.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. and the federal government filed
harshly conflicting accounts Tuesday of what they believed their
76-day antitrust trial had brought to light.
</P>
<P>
   In its 776-page filing, the government branded Microsoft as a
monopolistic predator that is illegally using its dominant Windows
operating system for personal computers to engage in ``a broad
pattern of unlawful conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time now _ and, if Microsoft's actions to maintain
its monopoly are not halted, for well into the future _ personal
computer consumers are locked into a Microsoft world, one in which
a single company essentially controls the configuration of desktop
computing,'' argued the Justice Department, joined by 19 state
attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   In line with its original complaint and much of the trial
testimony, the government's findings focused on Microsoft's
purported efforts to dominate the market for Internet commerce by
destroying its chief enemy in the browser wars, Netscape
Communications Corp., which is now part of America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's lawyers held that the prosecutors had drilled a
dry legal hole in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the government may have scored public relations points
against the company in the initial phase of the trial using
courtroom theatrics and bits of evidence out of context, we are
entering a new phase of the case in which the government must
confront certain critically important facts that are largely or
entirely undisputed,'' the company's lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of its 465-page brief, Microsoft maintained that
should it ``fail to keep an edge in product innovation and quality
and cease to be the preference of both business and individual
consumers, its (Windows) platform business will wither and die.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the software giant said that none of the ``conduct
challenged in this case has been detrimental to consumer welfare.
Indeed, the benefit to consumers and to the nation's economy of the
widespread adoption of Windows as an industry standard has been
enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said the evidence presented at the trial proved it had
broken no now laws but merely ``responded to a competitive
marketplace by keeping prices low, integrating new features into
Windows, and constantly investing in innovation to meet the demands
of consumers and developers.''
</P>
<P>
   With these polar opposite ``findings of fact'' in hand, U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson has given Microsoft and the
Justice Department one month to review each other's documents and
to file rebuttal briefs on Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Two separate sets of final oral arguments in his courtroom are
then scheduled to follow.
</P>
<P>
   The first exchange, set for on Sept. 21, will deal with the
fact-finding phase of the trial that was addressed in Tuesday's
dueling briefs. The second exchange will come after the judge
releases his own set of factual findings, but before he reaches a
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's decision to divide the current ``findings of fact''
phase from the future ``findings of law'' phase has a twin purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The first is to dampen the chances he will be reversed.
Appellate court panels have often been reluctant to reopen the
factual aspects of a non-jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   The second is to encourage the warring parties to cut a deal.
Those negotiations would presumably take place after Jackson tips
his hand with his initial fact-based ruling, thereby heading off a
final verdict that may fail to satisfy either side.
</P>
<P>
   So far, three secret sessions called to explore a compromise at
the judge's insistence have ended in failure. Settlement talks
broke off in early June and have yet to resume.
</P>
<P>
   If a deal cannot be reached and if Microsoft is found liable,
Jackson is likely to hold yet another set of hearings to determine
what remedial action should be taken.
</P>
<P>
   This potential punishment phase of the trial could range from
such relatively mild steps as barring Microsoft from entering into
exclusive licensing agreements with computer makers such as Compaq
and Dell to a Draconian order breaking up the world's most highly
valued corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
