<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLONY-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     08-10 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLONY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE COLONY OF UNREQUITED DREAMS': ECHOES OF HENRY FIELDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Smallwood, who was the first Premier of Newfoundland after
it voted in 1948 to confederate with Canada, probably never
imagined that his relatively small role in world history could
become the stuff of an epic-size novel. But it has. Smallwood is
the narrator and central figure of ``The Colony of Unrequited
Dreams,'' by Wayne Johnston, a novel that transforms the forlorn
territory of Newfoundland into a fabulous terrain of tragicomic
struggle and loss.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's book falters here and there, the tragicomic
disintegrating at times into the farcical. Still, this prodigious,
eventful, character-rich book is a noteworthy achievement: a
biting, entertaining and inventive saga.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably not by accident that the second major character
in ``The Colony of Unrequited Dreams'' is named Sheilagh Fielding,
known to almost everybody simply as Fielding. She is an object of
ruined love for Smallwood as well as a kind of court jester for
Johnston. She drinks and smokes and writes highly sardonic
commentaries about Newfoundland's history and politics, a kind of
satirical accompaniment to Smallwood's own story, even as she is
the guardian of an erotic family secret that is the moral key to
Smallwood's life as suitor and politician.
</P>
<P>
   Fielding's name reminds one, of course, of Henry Fielding,
author of ``Tom Jones'' and other picaresque adventures in which a
sympathetic, common-man hero swims against the currents of adverse
fate even as the truth about his early life is concealed from him.
Smallwood is not Tom Jones. He is a short and scrawny scrambler
whose political ambition taints him and brings him into unsavory
compromises with the forces of greed and hypocrisy. And in general
``The Colony of Unrequited Dreams'' is too saturated in an
absurdist 20th-century sensibility to be seen as an 18th-century
novel.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is something about the comic extravagance of
Johnston's book, and its moral resolution, that links it tightly
with its 18th-century forebear. One senses that if Henry Fielding
had lived now, and if, like Johnston, he had been born and raised
in Newfoundland, this is the kind of story he would have written.
</P>
<P>
   The Joe Smallwood of Johnston's novel is born on Christmas Eve
1900, which makes him obviously a kind of emblem of the century.
His father is a drunken failure and a wonderfully vivid creation
who rails poetically against the surrounding unfairness.
</P>
<P>
   Smallwood is sent to Bishop Feild, the best of the private
schools in St. John's, Newfoundland's seaport capital, and it is
there that he first meets Fielding, who attends the nearby sister
school. The two of them engage in a battle of wits, a remorseless
duel to the figurative death that they will continue for the next
half-century. All the themes that Johnston will later explore in
this novel are introduced in these first two pages.
</P>
<P>
   These themes include love and betrayal but also the remorseless
contest for power that takes place in both the psychic and the
political spheres. Johnston introduces a mystery here in the form
of an anonymous letter written to the Feild headmaster, an
embittered Dickensian failure whose self-hatred turns into an
intense dislike of Smallwood.
</P>
<P>
   The letter changes everything for Smallwood and Fielding and for
those around them. It is the invisible worm that, unbeknownst to
our dramatis personae, eats away at their hearts. Meanwhile,
Fielding disappears for a time while Smallwood sets out to make his
mark on history. His itinerary from this point is what makes
Johnston's book not just picaresquely entertaining but also
powerfully dug into the drear and bitter soil of his locale.
</P>
<P>
   In one especially memorable passage, Smallwood, who had an
earlier career as a reporter, goes on a seal-hunting expedition
aboard the S.S. Newfoundland to write about the venture for his
newspaper. The chapter in which Johnston describes this experience,
which ends in tragedy, is a stunning piece of writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had been transformed by their passion on the ice,'' he
writes when Smallwood sees a group of men who have frozen to death.
``Each had assumed in death some posture emblematic of his life. Or
else they were refined to men that no one knew, as if in each face
and posture was inscrutably depicted the essence of the person they
had been.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, too, Johnston gives us the epic hardship of life in
Newfoundland, a place that seemed to be ``a landlocked country in
the middle of an otherwise empty continent, a country hemmed in and
cored by wilderness.'' It is the very desolate quality of the
landscape and the corresponding affliction of the human soul that
make ``The Colony of Unrequited Dreams'' both a powerful novel and,
in a few places, excessively silly, as if Johnston's penchant for
an extreme sort of satire goes beyond the thematic bounds he has
established.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a minor flaw as we follow Smallwood on his unlikely,
morally compromised rise to political power, a rise that is wittily
and trenchantly satirized by Fielding, who shadows his every move.
After a few poverty-stricken years in New York, Smallwood returns
to Newfoundland, where he becomes a union organizer, once walking
the entire barren length of the cross-island railway to sign up new
members.
</P>
<P>
   He enters politics as a campaign aide to a hilariously venal
prime minister, Richard Squires. But then, in the spirit of the
18th-century novel, there is moral redemption. Smallwood bravely
leads Newfoundland into confederation with Canada, which began as
an unpopular and risky cause.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he achieves a kind of absolution with regard to
Fielding when the convoluted mystery of that fateful letter of
their youths is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life for 40 years was a pair of rivers, the river that
might have been beside the one that was,'' Fielding writes in her
journal at the very end of Johnston's rowdy tale. Parallel to the
rivers of Fielding's life are the rivers of private and political
history in Smallwood's narrative and in Fielding's acidulous
counter-version. It all adds up to a brilliant and bravura literary
performance by Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE COLONY OF UNREQUITED DREAMS'
</P>
<P>
   By Wayne Johnston
</P>
<P>
   562 pages. Doubleday. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
