<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPERA-COST-ART-610(2T     08-10 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-COST-ART-610(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING NEW OPERA PROFITABLE: TRADITIONAL BACKER CHANGES TRADITIONAL
WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos (NYT6,7) have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (Birth of an Opera: This is the second article in a series on the
making of ``A View From the Bridge,'' an opera adapted from Arthur
Miller's 1955 play. Lyric Opera of Chicago is to present the world
premiere on Oct. 9.)  
 (bl)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ When William Mason, the general director of Chicago's
Lyric Opera, visited Sidney Port last year to discuss Port's annual
substantive support of a Lyric production, he had three projects in
need of financing. Two were relatively unadventurous. But Port, an
88-year-old businessman whose own operatic taste tilts toward the
commonplace (Puccini and Verdi are his favorites), this time
departed from his usual practice.
</P>
<P>
   His $125,000 donation went to Lyric's riskiest production of the
coming season, ``A View From the Bridge,'' an adaptation of the
Arthur Miller play by composer William Bolcom and librettist Arnold
Weinstein. Commissioned in 1995 as part of the company's commitment
to enlarging the operatic canon with new American work, it is to
have its world premiere on Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Port's gift was the most unexpected element in the $1.4 million
project's financing, and it was particularly welcome because new
work generally has the same trouble finding financial supporters
that it does audiences. Unlike the production's two other major
benefactors, the National Endowment for the Arts and AT&AMP;T, which
maintain programs to support new work, Port's largess was motivated
by more idiosyncratic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jumped on `View' right away,'' Port recalled in a recent
interview, ``without knowing anything about it because Cathy'' _
Catherine Malfitano, who will sing Beatrice _ ``is my favorite
singer and because Arthur Miller was in on it. I go with people. I
go with the name. To tell you the truth, I really didn't get around
to reading it until last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Opera, with its grand sense of moment, with its orchestra and
chorus salaries, is the priciest of the performing arts. And opera
audiences are the most devoted to the classics. It is notoriously
difficult for new operas to gain a foothold in the canon. Indeed,
though many companies make concerted efforts to stage new works,
that's actually the easy part. What's tough is staging a second
production.
</P>
<P>
   The highest priority for Opera America, an umbrella organization
for opera companies, is Next Stage, a program that subsidizes
second productions of contemporary works. And the dead end that
confronts new operas is an obstacle to financing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a door opener, huh?'' Port said hopefully of his
gift. There isn't an arts institution in the country that wouldn't
kill for a Sid Port, a lifelong Chicagoan and loyal city booster
whose generosity is apparently unmitigated by pretension. A large
man whose heavy features and dour mien suggest a white-haired
Robert Mitchum, he's a former basketball player at the University
of Illinois who made his fortune in the machine parts business,
owns racehorses and is enough of a boxing fan that he once
sponsored a middleweight named Gorilla Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But he's also on the board of the Joffrey Ballet and the Art
Institute of Chicago, and since 1986, when he gave $40,000 to help
underwrite ``Lucia di Lammermoor,'' his support of 14 Lyric
productions has totaled nearly $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Port's latest gift (which includes contributions from the
families of his three children and is in the name of his wife,
Bettie, who died last Christmas), is all the more fortunate for its
allocation to a commissioned work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any other individual who has that kind of record
of support over the years,'' Mason said. ``Now we were going to do
`View' no matter what kind of support we got, but his faith in the
company and the art form and his willingness to support a range of
productions is crucial. Knowing you've got a Sid Port out there,
that's what you call a real blessing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As it happens, Lyric, the nation's third largest opera company
(behind the Metropolitan Opera and the San Francisco Opera), is
perhaps the leader, at least recently, in trying to enlarge the
repertory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think other companies look to Lyric as a model of how to put
on new works,'' said Wayne Brown, the director of music and opera
for the National Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also something of a model of the frustrations inherent
to the enterprise. ``A View From the Bridge'' is Lyric's third
commission in 10 years, but neither of the other two _ Bolcom's
``McTeague,'' and Anthony Davis' ``Amistad'' _ has had a second
production. And even though Lyric is among the most successful of
companies _ it has sold out its season for 11 consecutive years _
new work always calls for its most ardent marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question it's much more difficult to sell a
contemporary piece than something tried and true,'' said Susan
Mathieson, Lyric's director of marketing and communications. She
added that opera tickets were so expensive, often over $100, ``that
people want to be sure they're going to like it before they go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You do a `Tosca,' a `Carmen,''' she added, ``people have an
idea of what that is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of ``View'' tickets have been helped by a season that
includes two Verdi operas (``Falstaff'' and ``Macbeth'') and
``Tristan and Isolde'' and ``Carmen.'' Full subscription sales were
strong, and if partial series subscribers wanted to see the more
popular works, they'd have to take ``View'' as part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless Bizet,'' Ms. Mathieson said, adding that the general
rule is that single tickets to a popular classic sell at four or
five times the rate for a new one. That's one reason Lyric has
scheduled 13 performances of ``Carmen'' and only nine of ``A View
from the Bridge.'' Still, some 4,000 single tickets to ``View''
will remain after all subscriptions are counted. To sell them Lyric
has just sent 750,000 brochures to people on some 50 mailing lists,
including, in hopes of capitalizing on the Arthur Miller
connection, those of several Chicago theater companies.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``By the middle to the end of August, I'll know if I have to do
something else,'' Ms. Mathieson said, adding that the ``something
else'' would probably entail a more focused mailing: say, to
periodic Lyric attendees who have shown a penchant for contemporary
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make this effort,'' she said, ``because we budget
at 100 percent,'' meaning the annual budget for the company
presumes sold-out performances. ``Nobody in the world does that,
and it wasn't my idea, I'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyric's budget for the 1999-2000 season _ 84 performances of
eight operas _ is about $42 million, about $30 million of which
shows up on the stage in the form of scenery, costumes and
performers' salaries. The Civic Opera House, Lyric's home, has
3,600 seats, but even with its stellar attendance figures, the
company's annual earned income is 60 to 65 percent of the total,
meaning that some $15 million to $17 million has to come from
grants, donations and endowment earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A View From the Bridge'' will cost $1.3 million to $1.4
million, not including the salaries of the 75-member orchestra and
48-member chorus, stagehands and operating expenses of the house,
which come out of the annual operating budget. That's on the high
side for a Lyric production, even a new one, but it isn't
egregious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's roughly, on a per opera basis, what it cost to do each of
the four Ring operas,'' Ms. Mathieson said. Of the total cost,
$200,000 to $300,000 went to commissioning costs, e.g., payment for
Bolcom and Weinstein, a fee to Miller and the substantial expense
(perhaps as much as $50,000) of copying all the parts.
</P>
<P>
   Production costs _ scenery, projections (Wendall K. Harrington
is designing large-screen images of Red Hook, Brooklyn, the setting
of ``View''), wigs, costumes, props _ come to about $400,000. The
rest, about $700,000, pays salaries and expenses for the cast, the
conductor (Dennis Russell Davies), the director (Frank Galati), the
designers and the understudies.
</P>
<P>
   To meet the cost, Lyric is drawing $700,000 to $800,000 from a
$4 million fund that was established by a $1 million 3-for-1
challenge grant provided by the National Endowment for the Arts 10
years ago in support of the company's commitment to put on three
new works by the end of the century. The endowment, which devotes
about 20 percent of its grants for opera to new operas and 10
percent to new productions of recently created work, provided an
additional $100,000 specifically for ``A View From the Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, AT&AMP;T provided $150,000 through its philanthropic
arm, the AT&AMP;T Foundation, which was established in 1984 after the
dissolution of the Bell system. The foundation gives away about $50
million annually; slightly more than 10 percent of that goes to the
arts, almost all devoted to support new work in a variety of
disciplines; its annual Onstage program, which supports nonprofit
theaters, has provided money for August Wilson's ``Seven Guitars''
and Christopher Durang's ``Betty's Summer Vacation,'' among dozens
of other new plays.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the focus on new work is that in 1984 the company
was seeking to distance itself from the stodgy-old-phone-company
image that had accrued in the decades before the Bell breakup and
to create a new one that affiliates the company with high-tech
inventiveness, diversity and creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be seen as an innovative company, and so we've
tended to focus not exclusively on premieres, but certainly newer
work,'' said Suzanne Sato, vice president for arts and culture at
the AT&AMP;T Foundation. The foundation has supported all three of
Lyric's most recent commissions, and though neither ``Amistad'' nor
``McTeague'' lingered in the public consciousness, its support of
``View'' was never a question. ``For us in the region, it was
exactly a no-brainer,'' said Ray O'Connell, the corporation's
public relations vice president for the Midwest. ``Most of what the
foundation supports out here we recommend, and this was something
we recommended almost instantaneously.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which casts Port's gift, a very personal one, in some
relief. ``What I do, giving away money, is no big deal,'' he said.
He grew up poor in Chicago in a ``third-rate hotel'' run by his
parents, who still found time for charity work. He started his
machine parts company, Lawson Products, in 1952 with a loan of
$30,000 from his father-in-law. The company went public in 1970,
and the stock has split seven times since then.
</P>
<P>
   He's not particularly a fan of new opera; he did see
``McTeague'' but didn't remember much about it, including the
composer's name, or realize the same man had written ``View.'' His
interest, he said, was in supporting the institutions of the city
where has lived his whole life, in perpetuating a tradition of
cultural philanthropy (which is why he asked his children to join
him in this gift) and in honoring an art form he was introduced to
by his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that an opera might not live beyond its debut
production seemed new to him but not too troubling. He had an
analogy, unusual for the opera world but not for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me,'' he said, ``of something Charlie Whittingham
used to say. You know who he is? A great horse trainer I was in
business with. Charlie used to say, `You never know if a horse is
any good until 10 years after it's dead.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
