<HEADLINE>
URBANWORLD FESTIVAL NAMES FILM WINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Drylongso,'' a drama directed by Cauleen Smith, was
awarded the grand jury prize for best feature on Sunday at the
third annual Urbanworld Film Festival in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, which focuses on films with themes drawn from
minority groups, announced its winners after presenting 62 movies
over five days at the Cineplex Odeon Worldwide Plaza Cinemas.
Nearly 10,000 people attended the screenings, said Stacy Spikes,
the festival's founder and executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith's film, which takes its title from an African-American
term that means ``ordinary,'' ``getting by with very little'' or
``just the same old thing,'' tells the story of an adolescent
photographer's quest to document what she considers an endangered
species: young black men. Armed with a Polaroid camera and charming
savvy, the heroine, Pica, sets out on her mission and encounters a
series of eccentric neighborhood characters who force her to
recognize the value of her own life.
</P>
<P>
   While attending San Francisco State University, Ms. Smith
received attention for her short films ``Daily Rains'' (1991) and
``Chronicles of a Lying Spirit by Kelly Garbon'' (1992).
``Drylongso'' is her first feature.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Williams was named best director for his feature,
``Spark,'' which he described as ``a suspenseful drama about a
young black couple driving across the country from Chicago to Los
Angeles, stranded in a small desert town and pulled into a somewhat
violent web.''
</P>
<P>
   The award is ``very exciting, but what it means for my career
has yet to be determined,'' Williams said. ``Spark'' originated as
a short shown at the 1996 Sundance Film Festival, the New
Directors/New Films series at the Museum of Modern Art and at the
USA Film Festival in Dallas, where it won the Grand Prize. The film
in its expanded version was selected to participate in the 1997
Sundance Filmmaker's Lab.
</P>
<P>
   The prize for best short went to Rod Gailes' ``Twin Cousins,''
about a spirited girl who concocts an ingenious plan to avoid a
summer trip with an unkind aunt. Honorable mention in the category
went to Jim Fleigner's ``From the Top of the Key,'' the story of a
teenage prodigy struggling with his abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Nanette Burstein and Brett Morgan won for best documentary with
``On the Ropes,'' an inside look at the world of boxing, set in the
Brooklyn gym that produced the heavyweight Riddick Bowe. ``Innocent
Until Proven Guilty,'' Kirsten Johnson's examination of the
statistic that one in three black men between the ages of 16 and 35
is under the supervision of the criminal justice system, was
awarded an honorable mention.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Invited Guest,'' directed by Timothy Wayne Folsome, won the
audience award for best feature. In it, a dinner party turns
violent when a seductive escaped convict spends the evening with an
unsuspecting couple, only to fall in love with the wife.
</P>
<P>
   Each winner received $1,000 worth of film stock donated by the
Eastman Kodak Company. The winner for best short also received $500
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   In a screenwriting competition, Tanya Hamilton won best
screenplay with ``Stringbean and Marcus,'' a coming-of-age tale
about two children in a family of former Black Panthers. The prize
included $500 from Bourgeoisie Films, the production company of the
actor Samuel L. Jackson and his wife, LaTanya Richardson Jackson,
who are both on the festival's board. Michael Genet received
honorable mention for ``Pork Pie,'' the story of a jazz competition
sponsored by the Devil's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Citing her ``outstanding body of work as an actress,'' the jury
presented a special award to Nicole Ari Parker. Ms. Parker was a
frequent presence on the screen during the festival, appearing in
the commercial feature ``Blue Streak'' with Martin Lawrence as well
as three competing films, ``Mute Love,'' ``Loving Jezebel'' and
``Spark,'' which received premieres at the festival.
</P>
</TEXT>
