<HEADER>
A2168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAVOE-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      08-10 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAVOE-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIFTING A CULTURAL HERO'S LIFE TO DEFINE PUERTO RICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The singer Hector Lavoe came to New York from Puerto
Rico as a teen-ager in the late 1960s and became a cultural figure,
his high pure-as-air voice riding salsa's drums. Then he dissolved
in a stew of drugs and hard living.
</P>
<P>
   Lavoe died in 1993, and now his life, his musical excellence and
his death at 46 are being mined for meaning and money. ``Quien Mato
a Hector Lavoe?'' (``Who Killed Hector Lavoe?''), which is playing
at the 47th Street Theater through the end of the month, is in one
sense a conventional musical, linking some of his songs with
dramatic interludes that explain his personality.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also an attempt by Puerto Rican intellectuals to
figure out and reassess the image of a cultural hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Puerto Ricans don't have a Jesse Jackson to speak for us,''
said David Maldonado, the producer who conceived the play. ``We're
constantly looking for leaders, for people who show us who we are,
people who have achieved something. We need our property, our
place, and Hector gave that to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Maldonado, who started in the Latin music industry as Lavoe's
roadie, spent years sifting his experiences to find the material
for a play. He turned the writing over to Pablo Cabrera, a teacher,
and brought in the biggest Latin music agents in the United States,
Cardenas/Fernandez &AMP; Associates, as executive producers. They
financed the show, putting up nearly half a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing a show about Hector makes a lot of sense because he has
so many aspects that make him legendary,'' Maldonado said. ``He
died young, which puts him in the category of Malcolm X, JFK and
Marilyn. He was the most gifted singer of his generation, the bad
boy of salsa but a humane guy, like a pacifist. He was the people's
singer, a champion like Muhammad Ali. And he was a hick, coming
from Ponce, Puerto Rico, to Gotham with this incredible gift. Even
though he had tragedies every day in his life, he'd get up on stage
and be the Bruce Lee of our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The musical is one of the highest-grossing Off Off Broadway
shows, but for Cardenas/Fernandez, the smallness of the theater
limits the profit; it can only break even. Still, the company has
invested in something that can go on the road internationally for
years, and there are plans for it to spend four or five months in
Puerto Rico, then go to Colombia, Venezuela, Peru and Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Colombia,'' said Henry Cardenas, the president of
Cardenas/Fernandez, ``and Lavoe was part of our musical experience.
This play has huge potential.''
</P>
<P>
   For the company, the play is part of a larger plan to promote
more Latin theater. So Cardenas/Fernandez is working on a
large-scale musical called ``Salsa, Mambo, Cha-Cha-Cha,'' based on
the glory days of such music in the 1940s and '50s in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Claudio Segovia, the creator of ``Black and Blue'' and
``Tango Argentino,'' is working on an Afro-Cuban musical, and the
Tropicana Review from Havana is being offered for a United States
tour. Latin musicians like the pianist Eddie Palmieri have been
approached to work on musicals.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas said, ``I think `The Capeman' started people thinking
about the possibilities of the Latin musical, given all the music
from all over Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quien Mato a Hector Lavoe'' is a nostalgic work that explores
an extraordinary era in American popular culture, the period of the
late 1960s and '70s. For Caribbean Latinos, the period is often
called Fania Era, after the record label, which recorded their best
musicians, including Lavoe, Willie Colon, Johnny Pacheco, Larry
Harlow and Ismael Miranda. It was in essence a renaissance of
Afro-Latin cultural production.
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco, the show's musical director, was one of the founders of
Fania Records, a great band leader of the time and a producer and
talent scout for the label.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really strange to go back to that era for the play,
putting together all the songs that we had done together,'' said
Pacheco, adding that he had met Lavoe in 1968 when he asked to sing
with Pacheco's band. ``But his story is so sad, finally, because of
his inability to stay clean, to stay off of drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Domingo Quinones, the Puerto Rican singer who plays Lavoe, has
had a few small film roles and a part in a recent production of
``Jesus Christ Superstar.'' The actor studied Lavoe, and his
stillness, his eyes hidden behind brown aviator glasses, evokes
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Domingo scared me,'' said Pacheco. ``He sounds just like
Hector when he wants to, and he has his calm down perfectly, the
way Hector moved his hands. It's really incredible what Domingo's
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinones is one of the reasons the story is reaching its
audience. Indeed, at a recent sold-out show, members of the
audience were so involved they warned Lavoe not to take the drugs
offered to him. Even some of the cast members were surprised at the
reaction to Quinones' eerie realism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I underestimated Lavoe's importance until this
project,'' said Claudette Sierra, who plays Lavoe's sister in the
play. ``The people that are his fans are amazingly passionate about
him. Nobody leaves the theater without having a visceral reaction,
in part because Domingo is so good. Even though Hector's behavior
wasn't particularly good, he stayed humble, he never became a diva,
and people respect that. He had an erratic, confused life, a life
that is so much fodder for drama, but in a down home way. He's like
a Latin Bruce Springsteen, homeboy who makes good but remains true
to his roots. And that he destroys himself is the tragedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
