<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Aug. 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients for heavy thunderstorms to erupt over the upper
Midwest late Wednesday night and early Thursday will begin to come
together. A warm front marking the leading edge of humid air from
the Gulf of Mexico will press north across the Plains Wednesday as
its escort jet stream disturbance emerges from the Rockies. Showers
and thunderstorms, some with heavy rain, will develop over parts of
the northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley. In the wake of
the disturbance, a trough of low pressure will be left from the
western Dakotas to northwest Texas.
</P>
<P>
   With the trough acting as fertile breeding grounds, a
low-pressure system will rapidly develop over the central Plains
around dawn Thursday as a potent jet stream disturbance emerges
from the Rockies. As the rapidly developing low lifts humid Gulf
air in waiting near the surface, clusters of heavy showers and
thunderstorms will flare across the upper Midwest from the northern
Plains across the upper Mississippi Valley to the western Great
Lakes. Some of these storms will produce severe weather, with
tornadoes and hail possible, but the greatest threat will be heavy
rains and flash flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Broken areas of generally light rain will accompany a warm front
across southern and central New England. Farther south, potent
thunderstorms will erupt near the Carolina Coast. Though most
storms will stay over the ocean, a few may develop inland, raising
the risk of severe weather.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hot weather will persist over the interior Gulf
states.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Dark Days
</P>
<P>
   As daytime darkness descends along a narrow corridor from
northwestern Europe to central Asia during Wednesday's total solar
eclipse, the primary meteorological effect will be a temporary
temperature drop that will average about 5 degrees Fahrenheit.
Evening birds will begin to sing. Frogs will break into a husky
nocturnal croaking. Solar eclipses are one obvious cause of the
eerie tales of dark days sprinkled throughout history. Other cases
of extreme darkness during the day are often the result of volcanic
eruptions or soot from distant forest fires that almost totally
block the sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
