<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: NEW GAME SHOW WITH PHILBIN; TEENS ON VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Game Show Wins Regis
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Regis Philbin, who when he enthuses, enthuses from
every pore, is hardly able to contain himself about his forthcoming
project for ABC, a prime-time game show called ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told David Letterman the other night that I am going to be
the savior of the ABC network. I am going to resurrect ABC!''
Philbin said. ``This show totally knocks me out.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, which Philbin will be host of beginning Monday night
at 8:30, certainly promises to be something either very new or very
old. It will certainly be the first game show to be broadcast in
prime time every night (except one) for two straight weeks. But it
is also very consciously aiming to be a throwback to the early days
of television, when the big-money quiz show was a formula for hit
television.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Davies, the executive producer, called the show ``the
perfect 1990s rendering of 1950s television.'' For those who
instantly associate those '50s game shows with Charles Van Doren
and rigged answers, he added, ``And the format does not have to be
fixed for it to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The format, which involves a series of tryouts by contestants,
first by phone and then in the studio, eventually results in a
single player's answering a series of multiple-choice questions
worth ascending amounts of money, all the way up to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   It was created by an independent production company in Britain,
Celador, and the format has spread to more than 50 countries. In
almost all it is a huge success.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, where the show has been broadcast less than a year,
it is a certified phenomenon. Davies noted that in its last
two-week burst the show hit a new high when it reached 72 percent
of the potential audience in a single night.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin said he heard about the show, saw the British version
and was so excited he campaigned to win the host job. ``I just knew
I wanted to be part of this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, which had success last summer with another British format,
``Whose Line Is It Anyway?'' with Drew Carey, which has gone on to
become a weekly entry in ABC's fall lineup, decided to take a
chance on the game show, even though its schedule was totally
unconventional.
</P>
<P>
   It calls for ABC to clear a spot for ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire?'' every night beginning Monday (except for the
following Monday, Aug. 23, when the network previously had
committed to a football game). The show will even expand to a full
hour on the two Sunday nights of the run.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the hope is that the show will become enough of a
success for ABC to bring it back on numerous occasions for further
tournaments. ``Of course we want to keep it going if it's a
success,'' Philbin said. Davies noted that the show was so flexible
it could be scheduled in a number of different ways, from once a
week to seven times a week.
</P>
<P>
   Davies said, ``I honestly think it is flat-out the best format
I've ever seen in television.'' He backed that up with his job,
quitting his post as ABC's vice president for programming to become
the show's executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   What is different about the format is the application process,
which requires would-be contestants to phone a 900 number and take
part in a quick quiz, then move to a second level which involves a
live phone playoff with other daily winners. Finally 10 contestants
are flown to New York, where they engage in an on-camera
all-or-nothing shootout with one question. The winner then plays
the game.
</P>
<P>
   That also has several new angles. The questions are all multiple
choice, and they come in ascending difficulty. The money grows
slowly from $100 to $200 to $300 to $500. Then it starts to double.
If someone somehow got 15 answers right they could win the $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other wrinkles. The contestant can quit at certain
levels and keep the money. If, for instance, a contestant gets to
$16,000 and misses, he would fall back to the $1,000 level. If he
gets to $32,000, he gets to keep that amount if he misses at
another level.
</P>
<P>
   But at say, $125,000, the incentive to quit gets much stronger.
A miss drops the contestant back to $32,000.
</P>
<P>
   The other wrinkle is that the contestant can get help only three
times and in three different ways. He can ask the audience to vote
(and Philbin said that in Britain the audience majority is almost
always right), he can ask for two wrong answers to be eliminated,
leaving a 50-50 chance, or, in the show's most novel innovation, he
can call a friend he thinks might know the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin noted that no one in England has come close to the $1
million prize so far, always quitting for fear of losing a big
payoff, a potential drawback that Davies believes will be reversed
in the United States by the greater willingness of Americans to go
for broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's great about the show is that it takes knowledge and
courage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The show is a virtual tracing of the British version in style,
Philbin said, and that includes all kinds of lighting effects and
music to heighten the drama. It will be taped at the Sony Music
Theater in Manhattan, another overt homage, Davies said. ``The
1950s shows were from New York,'' he said. ``That's where we want
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers on Violence
</P>
<P>
   In the flood of television news magazine stories about
teen-agers and violence that followed the shootings at Columbine
High School in Littleton, Colo., most of the voices came from
parents and childhood experts.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Neal Shapiro, the executive producer of ``Dateline
NBC'' concluded, and he set out to see if there was a way to get
the voices of teen-agers themselves heard.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a special one-hour ``Dateline'' on Wednesday night
at 8 devoted entirely to examining what teen-agers have to say
about issues like parental control and guns in schools.
``Dateline'' made an arrangement with Teen People magazine, using
its publication base of what it calls trend spotters to assemble a
forum of teen-agers who could be brought to New York as a special
focus group.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro then enlisted Katie Couric to interview them after they
viewed several reports the show compiled. ``I came away most
surprised about how many teens said they wanted parents to be
parents and not their friends,'' Shapiro said. ``They wanted rules
and limits. They said they would rebel against them but they want
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that several teen-agers were ``very frank about how
painful high school can be.'' And on the question of how easy it
would be to acquire a gun, ``they all said it would be very easy,''
Shapiro said.
</P>
</TEXT>
