<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORN-OFF-THE-COB-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE COB, USE YOUR IMAGINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK BISHOP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's only so much you can do with a whole ear of corn. How
many flavored butters can one cook devise?
</P>
<P>
   But take the kernels off the cobs, and the possibilities expand
exponentially. Chowders, salsas, salads, griddlecakes, breads,
muffins and savory custards can all begin with fresh corn off the
cob.
</P>
<P>
   True, kernels cut loose don't have quite the glamour of a whole
ear steamed and dripping butter or charred from the grill. And cans
and freezers haven't helped matters: just the thought of those
mushy, flavorless pellets is enough to stop a cook's creativity
cold.
</P>
<P>
   But at a time of year when daily indulgence may be making corn
on the cob taste a little dull, a few knife strokes can open up new
possibilities for making more of the American symbol of summer. The
cooked kernels can even be turned into creamed corn to make a side
dish worlds away from the canned kind.
</P>
<P>
   Whole kernels sliced off the cob _ cooked or raw _ work best in
most dishes, but for baking, grated raw corn has better texture.
The whole ears can be run over the coarse holes on a four-sided
grater to produce a thick and juicy puree that can be added to
batters for griddlecakes, muffins or corn bread.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite summer side dish in my house is savory corn
griddlecakes flavored with Parmesan and chives. They take just 10
minutes to make; the batter is nothing more than grated corn
enriched with an egg and a little flour and then ladled into a hot
skillet. The cooked cakes are golden brown on the outside, creamy
on the inside and full of fresh corn flavor. I serve them with
grilled steak, since they absorb the meat's juices wonderfully, or
tucked under a grilled salmon fillet.
</P>
<P>
   To a novice cook, cutting the kernels off a long, pointed ear of
corn may seem daunting. But there is an easy and safe technique:
snap the ears in the middle to break them in half, then stand each
piece up on its flat end, so it stays steady. Then slide a sharp
chef's knife down the length of the cob on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   With most recipes, the cobs can be tossed into the trash or onto
the compost heap. But they can actually be used to make a quick
corn broth for soup or chowder or to enhance the corn flavor in
dishes with rice. Cover them with cold water in a pot, and simmer
20 minutes to extract the remaining juices from the cobs.
</P>
<P>
   Cooked kernels are even more versatile than raw, especially for
salads. Grill the corn when you want a sweeter, caramelized flavor
that can stand up to strongly flavored ingredients like chilies.
Boil the ears when you want pure corn flavor.
</P>
<P>
   I like to combine boiled corn with diced roasted red peppers,
parsley, olive oil and lemon juice to make a quick relish for fish
or chicken. Lightly caramelized grilled corn makes a classic summer
salad with tomatoes, basil, red onion, olive oil and red wine
vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled or boiled corn can also be turned into chunky salsas.
Corn works especially well with soft, juicy fruits like mangoes or
peaches as well as with chilies and fresh herbs. It can also be
used in a salsa with black beans, tomatoes, lime juice, cilantro,
chilies and a little minced garlic or shallot.
</P>
<P>
   Some people like to eat corn raw, but I prefer to cook it, on or
off the cob. A quick dunk in boiling water _ no more than a minute
or two _ makes corn off the cob much more tender.
</P>
<P>
   Raw corn kernels can also go right into the cooking pot with
almost any green vegetable. I throw some corn into a pan of
simmering green beans just before the beans are tender and let them
both cook another minute or so before draining the pot and tossing
the vegetables with an herb vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   A cup or two of raw corn kernels and a handful of minced fresh
herbs make an excellent last-minute addition to a pot of steamed
white rice or soft polenta. The heat from the grains will soften
the corn in a matter of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to saute corn off the cob. I stir raw corn
kernels into a pan of sauteed wild mushrooms, add a splash or two
of stock, water or cream and cook it just until the corn is tender,
no more than five minutes. You could omit the liquid, but sauteed
corn can be a little tough. The liquid also keeps it from
scorching.
</P>
<P>
   For a creamier, richer dish, I braise kernels in a covered pan
filled with a cup or so of stock or water for every four cups of
corn. The steam coaxes out starch from the corn, which helps to
thicken the liquid into a silky sauce. A little butter can be
swirled in at the end, or a few tablespoons of cream can be added
and simmered until the liquid thickens.
</P>
<P>
   When boiling or grilling corn, I often intentionally cook too
many ears. After dinner, I cut off the kernels and refrigerate them
in airtight containers. (You could keep the corn on the cob; it may
stay a tad juicier. But in most cases, you will be moistening the
kernels anyway, and I would rather just get rid of the cobs.)
</P>
<P>
   Cutting off the cooked kernels is also an ideal solution for
leftovers. An uneaten ear of corn can't be reheated, and is likely
to be left moldering in the refrigerator. But it's hard to resist a
bowlful of kernels, cleaned and ready for anything from muffins to
quesadillas.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FRESH CORN GRIDDLE CAKES WITH PARMESAN AND CHIVES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 medium ears corn, husks and silks removed
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   \ cup flour
</P>
<P>
   \ cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon snipped fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter.
</P>
<P>
   1. Over large bowl, grate corn on large holes of box grater
until cobs are clean; discard cobs. Stir in egg, flour, cheese,
chives, salt and pepper to taste until batter is smooth.
</P>
<P>
   2. Melt butter in a large nonstick skillet. Take \ cup of batter
and scrape it (the batter will be thick) into pan to form a round
cake. Repeat, using all the batter; you should get 6 cakes. Cook
over medium heat, turning once, until griddle cakes turn a rich
golden brown on both sides, about 9 minutes total. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED CORN, TOMATO AND RED ONION SALAD  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 medium ears corn, husks and silks removed
</P>
<P>
   2 medium ripe tomatoes, cored and chopped
</P>
<P>
   { small red onion, minced (about \ cup)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   8 large fresh basil leaves, cut into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Grill corn over medium fire, turning several times, until
kernels are tender and lightly charred, about 10 minutes. Remove
corn from grill. When cool enough to handle, cut ears in half
widthwise with a chef's knife, stand each piece on its cut end and
slice downward several times to remove all kernels. Place corn in a
large serving bowl; discard cobs.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add tomatoes and onion to the bowl with corn, and toss
gently. Drizzle oil and vinegar over vegetables. Add basil, and
salt and pepper to taste. Toss gently, and serve. (This dish can be
set aside at room temperature for up to 1 hour.)
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CREAMED CORN WITH ONION AND CHILI  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 medium jalapeno chili, stemmed, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   3{ cups fresh corn kernels (from 5 to 6 medium ears)
</P>
<P>
   } cup chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   \ cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh cilantro leaves.
</P>
<P>
   1. Melt butter in a medium skillet. Add onion and saute over
medium heat until golden, about 6 minutes. Add chili, and cook
until softened, about 1 minute. Add corn, stock and salt and pepper
to taste. Bring to a boil, reduce heat, cover and simmer gently,
stirring once or twice, until corn is tender, 6 to 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove cover, and add cream to pan. Simmer until liquid in
pan thickens, 1 to 2 minutes. Add cilantro, and adjust seasonings.
Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CORN CHOWDER WITH BACON, LEEKS AND POTATOES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3{ cups fresh corn kernels (from 5 to 6 medium ears), cobs
reserved
</P>
<P>
   4 strips bacon, cut into small dice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 medium leeks, white and light green parts, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   } pound red potatoes, peeled and cut into {-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh parsley leaves.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place corncobs and water to cover (about 4 cups) in a large
saucepan. Bring to boil, reduce heat and simmer for 20 minutes.
Pick out and discard cobs. Reserve 3 cups corn broth; discard
remaining broth.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place bacon and oil in a large saucepan. Turn heat to medium,
and cook, stirring occasionally, until bacon fat is rendered, about
3 minutes. Add leeks, and continue cooking until bacon is crisp and
leeks have softened, about 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add corn broth, milk, potatoes and salt and pepper to taste.
Bring to a boil, reduce heat and simmer gently until potatoes are
almost tender, about 15 minutes. Add corn kernels, and continue to
simmer gently until corn and potatoes are tender, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Puree 2 cups of soup in a blender. Return puree to soup pot,
and reheat gently. Stir in parsley, and adjust seasonings. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
