<HEADER>
A2218 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEBMD-COX     08-10 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WebMD plans major ad blitz
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WebMD Inc. plans to launch a big-ticket, high-stakes
advertising campaign aimed at imprinting the company's name on the
consciousness of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   With brand name considered critical to success on the Internet,
Atlanta-based WebMD _ a company which thus far has only minuscule
revenues and no profits _ plans to spend upwards of $200 million
during the next five years on the campaign, according to Reggie
Bradford, the company's chief marketing officer.
</P>
<P>
   The spending estimates include distribution agreements with the
likes of CNN and Lycos, as well as advertising, research and direct
mail.
</P>
<P>
   To carry out the plan, WebMD has switched advertising agencies,
jumping to Ogilvy &AMP; Mather WorldWide. Building a brand name will be
the core of the campaign, said Shelly Lazarus, Ogilvy &AMP; Mather
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``WebMD is strategically positioned to become one of the
Internet's most powerful brands,'' she said. ``All communications
will be created to bring to life WebMD's vision of improving the
quality of health care for all its constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMD's former agency was New York-based Gotham, which also
represents ETrade and Maybelline. That agency was responsible for
the start of the campaign, including the somewhat offbeat
television ad that conjures the movie ``Thelma and Louise'' _
albeit with two cars and a happy ending. The ad shows patients and
doctors leaping between cars that have bolted off a cliff. The cars
land on the other side of a huge canyon as the passengers smile.
</P>
<P>
   But WebMD has big ambitions, and Gotham was a bit too
``boutique.'' By contrast, Ogilvy is much larger, with offices in
100 countries.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD said the campaign will capitalize on its arrangements with
Excite, Lycos and the Microsoft Network to be the exclusive
provider of health care information. The company also has a deal
with CNN in which reports about health are delivered 32 times a day
under the WebMD logo.
</P>
<P>
   The company faces a near-frenzy of competition for the
potentially huge market in the Internet health care sector. Among
rivals are local companies like adam.com, as well as national
players like OnHealth, DrKoop, Medscape and WebDoctor.
</P>
<P>
   But in the year since its public coming-out, WebMD has soared to
prominence _ if not profits.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans in September to merge with California-based
Healtheon, with the combined company to be headquartered in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   However, the value of the deal has plunged since its
announcement in the spring, when Healtheon stock crested at $105 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   By last week, it had fallen to $41. On Tuesday, the shares
closed at $31.50, down $7.43 1/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
