<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth announces fee cut to attract customers
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth said Tuesday it would cut the cost of its
Fast Access high-speed ADSL Internet and data services for
customers who sign up between Aug. 8 and Sept. 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The move is part of BellSouth's strategy to find a price point
that will attract customers and accelerate the use of high speed
access technology throughout the nine-state BellSouth region. ADSL
competes against other high speed data services offered by cable
television companies and others.
</P>
<P>
   During the enrollment period, BellSouth will waive its $199.95
installation fee for customers who meet the requirements for the
high speed service. Subscribers will still pay a $99.95 activation
fee, followed by a monthly charges that will remain remain at
$59.95. BellSouth's Complete Choice calling plan customers will pay
$50.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth executives won't say if the $199 installation fee will
be reinstated after Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Cunha, vice president of broadband services, said: ``We
are actively looking at ways to make this affordable. Now and over
the long term, we are serious about making Fast Access affordable
for all of our 15 million customers. Cuhna says lowering
installation prices is one way to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single BellSouth subscriber is able to enjoy this
rate,'' says Terry Yarbrough, senior director of product marketing.
``When we come out of this program, we will have a pricing
structure in place people will find attractive,'' he says. ``This
is just the point we are starting at.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth hopes to have five million digital subscriber line
customers before the end of the year across the nine-state region.
Even though not every area in metro-Atlanta is capable of receiving
ADSL service, Yarbrough says that newly-developed technology will
help make the service accessible to more and more BellSouth
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to send a strong message to our customers that we are
committed to providing this service,'' Cunha says. ``Our goal over
time is to make this service accessible to as many people as
possible and to make installing ADSL as easy as plugging in a
toaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers can order FastAccess service by calling 1-888-321-ADSL
or visiting the BellSouth.net's Web site:
www.bellsouth.net/external/adsl
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
