<HEADER>
A2233 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-10 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TOUGH PUTTING A NAME ON THOSE OLD FEELINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memories should not be done in misty watercolors. I like my
memories vivid and distinct, with all the sights, smells and sounds
of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The images of my past are like an art museum in my mind. There
are great works displayed on the canvas of my soul. Some of my
recollections are like landscapes, pastoral scenes of peaceful
days. Others are like muddled blotches of paint splashed on a
painter's coveralls. A visit to this growing gallery is ofttimes
exhilarating, sometimes humiliating, but always interesting.
</P>
<P>
   When relationships end, when circumstances change, our memories
are so frequently all we have left. That is what terrifies me about
Alzheimer's and other diseases that rob you of your past. If I
don't have that reservoir of painful lessons learned and
hard-fought victories to guide me, how do I determine my latitude
and longitude?
</P>
<P>
   I was having this conversation, or rather a conversation like
this one, with my husband recently. Well, I guess it was a
conversation. He nodded while I talked. Technically, that's a
discussion for women like me. Anyway, as we were exchanging
thoughts, I recalled a wonderful moment in our past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey,'' I asked. ``Do you remember that time we went to
Galveston?''
</P>
<P>
   His eyes lit up in recognition and he smiled a mysterious, manly
smile, just like he did in Galveston many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A manly smile is the kind where the guy just kind of turns up
the corner of his lips and leans his head slightly to the side. The
eyes twinkle under the heavy lids, and that quarter-inch of hair on
his face folds into the creases that line his mouth like
parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   You know, that is just amazing, the way hair grows out of men's
chins. I love that! A guy shaves in the morning, leaves for work,
and comes home a few hours later with hair on his face. My husband
says that I should be over this fascination after 14 years of
marriage, but I still love it when he grows that facial hair for
me. It is for me, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I said, ``Wasn't it beautiful that evening? You had a
blanket and that picnic basket filled with fruit, that expensive
kind of cheese, and chocolate-covered strawberries. The sunset was
like a rainbow that God rolled into a ball and tossed onto the
ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   My honey bunny closed his eyes and reveled in the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You even brought along your jam box and all those Luther
Vandross tapes,'' I continued. ``You know how I love Luther.''
</P>
<P>
   Then I closed my eyes and let the memory wash over me like a
sudden downpour in the middle of the family reunion picnic, just
when you were finally beating Cousin Willie at dominoes for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   When I opened my eyes, my husband was staring at me and
frowning.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong?'' I asked. ``Don't you remember all the fun we
had that evening?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you forget that night? That was one of the best
times we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember because that wasn't me with you that night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' was all I said.
</P>
<P>
   Then I remembered that the chin hair that night was on a
different chin.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, I was torn between conflicting advice coming from
my left brain and my right brain. Do I argue with him and swear
that it was him and that he's forgotten? Do I laugh and say that I
made it up just to tease him? Or do I say that I was with my
favorite really old uncle that evening who was trying to cheer me
up because I'd been diagnosed with a rare disorder that makes me
remember things that never happened?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I just said: ``How does lasagna sound for dinner?
That's your favorite, and I haven't cooked it in a while. In fact,
you just let me know whenever you want lasagna, and I'll whip it
right up for you. Just any old time, uh huh, you bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Looks like I won't be touching honey bunny's wonderful chin
hairs for quite some time. Oh well, I'll always have my memories.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
