<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-CZECH-KRATOCHVILO     08-10 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-CZECH-KRATOCHVILOVA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNING DOWN THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANITA VERSCHOTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASLAV, Czech Republic _ In the summer of 1983, in the span of
20 days, Jarmila Kratochvilova of Czechoslovakia lowered the world
record in the 800 meters and the 400 meters and won two gold medals
and one silver at the first world track and field championships in
Helsinki, Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Her extraordinary performances, however, were shrouded in
controversy. Was she really that good, some critics wondered, or
were her amazing times _ 1 minute 53.28 seconds in the 800 and
47.99 in the 400 _ achieved with the help of drugs?
</P>
<P>
   And in perhaps the unkindest cut of all, was she really a woman?
</P>
<P>
   Kratochvilova, then 32 years old, was heavily muscular, with a
stocky frame and a preference for wearing drab warm-up suits. She
never flunked a gender test or a drug test in an era when there was
no out-of-competition testing.
</P>
<P>
   Kratochvilova was aware of the innuendos swirling around her
then, yet today she prefers to remember those days as the happiest
in her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought that I would like to look like other women,
with more in front and a better-looking backside,'' the 48-year-old
Kratochvilova said recently. ``I have an athletic body. I was not
hurt when I heard those remarks. My body has been good to me; it
has kept me healthy. As for drugs, I never 4took any. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   She returns to the world championships Aug. 20-29 in Seville,
Spain, this time as a coach of two female Czech athletes. Anyone
who has not seen Kratochvilova in recent years may be startled by
another transformation: gone are about 18 pounds of muscle.
</P>
<P>
   She is now slender, with her hair fashionably cut and her face
tanned and finely chiseled. Her blue eyes light up when she laughs,
a welcome shift from the shy, often surly ``state professional''
who seldom felt comfortable in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   She earned only 8,000 crowns ($235) for an 800-meter mark that
is the oldest surviving among major events in the sport, for men or
women. No woman has run faster than 1:54.44 in 10 years, and no one
has broken 1:55 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an athlete, I never made $15,000 in my life,''
Kratochvilova said in an interview in this medieval town 50 miles
east of Prague, where she commutes eight miles four times a day
from her home village of Golcuv Jenikov for coaching sessions.
``When I hear today that some runners get $15,000 for a 1:58, I
prefer to keep my mouth shut. That's not sports anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Kratochvilova said today's runners spend too much time traveling
the world for several meets a week and too little time on
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My generation ran in two big championships per year; the rest
of the time it was all concentrated work,'' she said. ``I would not
have minded to get some money for all the work I did.''
</P>
<P>
   And work she did. Her coach, Miroslav Kvac, said that
Kratochvilova's success was the result of intense workouts, not
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Although other Soviet-bloc athletes, most notably in East
Germany, were subjected to sophisticated state-supported sports
programs that included the use of anabolic steroids and other drugs
during training, Kvac said, ``there were never any drugs involved''
in Kratochvilova's regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just supplements such as vitamins, amino acids, protein,''
said the 67-year-old Kvac, who still coaches at the Caslav
Athletics Club.
</P>
<P>
   Initially a sprinter, Kratochvilova went unnoticed until Kvac
shifted her to longer distances. But at 5 feet 7 inches and 152
pounds, she was at first handicapped in the 400 and 800 by her
weight and short body. So Kvac decided to turn her weight into
power, working with hundreds of pounds of weights at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Kvac put her on a program that included take-off jumping and
uphill sprints. She ran 200-meter sprints 20 times, and on a
steeper hill, 60-meter sprints 12 to 16 times. Kratochvilova, who
won a silver medal in the 400 at the 1980 Moscow Olympics, still
remembers the punishing 300-meter interval drills _ 20 of them _ at
a 47-second pace, which she executed with only a two-minute rest
between each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps you cannot imagine what it means to run 300 meters 20
times,'' she said. ``You should try it. Every day of my training
was hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladislav Krnac, a Slovak journalist, who followed
Kratochvilova's career, said recently, ``She was willing to torture
herself.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``There are very few of those around. She didn't need
orders. She knew, `If I suffer, I can get good.'''
</P>
<P>
   American athletes and fans seldom saw Kratochvilova compete. In
January 1984, she made the first of four appearances in the United
States, competing in the Sunkist indoor meet at Los Angeles.
American coaches and officials were stunned at her muscularity, and
one prominent chiropractor, Dr. Leroy Perry, said at the time, ``I
think there is something chemically different about her
physiological makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet-led boycott of the Los Angeles Olympics cost
Kratochvilova an almost certain Olympic gold medal in the 800. An
Achilles' tendon injury put her out of competition a year later,
and she resumed training for the 1987 world championships in Rome,
but finished fifth in 1:57.71.
</P>
<P>
   Kratochvilova now lives with her parents in a spacious two-story
house that was built six years ago. The parents occupy the lower
floor while she has the second floor to herself. Most of her
trophies are on display in her large living room.
</P>
<P>
   From a drawer she pulls out a plastic shopping bag that contains
her medals from international championships. They are in the bag,
she said, because they often have to be taken to schools for
children to look at and perhaps draw inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the apartment are neatly stacked toys awaiting the
next visit of 2-year-old Steppana, the first grandchild of her
sister Maria. There was never time to marry as an athlete,
Kratochvilova said; her sisters' five children, plus her runners
are her family.
</P>
<P>
   Since she began coaching, she has been paid a salary as a high
school physical education teacher, although she coaches mainly
graduates. She also gives clinics in Prague and Bratislava,
Slovakia. Her group is sponsored by Adidas and some local
industries. Her celebrity status is written on the car door of the
silver Skoda she drives.
</P>
<P>
   At the world championships, Kratochvilova's star pupil, Lyudmila
Formanova will be one of the medal favorites in the 800. At the
world indoor championships last March, the 25-year-old Formanova
outran Maria Mutola en route to a winning time of 1:56.90.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there wouldn't be any good results without hard work,''
Formanova said after a recent workout. ``But Jarmila introduced me
to it gradually. There are days when I don't feel like training,
but she teaches me not to give in.''
</P>
<P>
   Kratochvilova recalled: `When I won a race and stood on the
podium, I felt great satisfaction. It was a feeling that is hard to
describe. You feel you have triumphed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often tell my two girls that I hope they too can experience
this satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Hana Benesova, a sprinter, is the other athlete Kratochvilova
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Does Formanova believe she can run a time under 1:54?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, never,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kratochvilova smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't think you could run 1:56 either,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
