<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2240 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEETWATER-REUNION-LA     08-10 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEETWATER-REUNION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VH1 MOVIE BRINGS WOODSTOCK BAND BACK TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The year is 1967: The Age of Aquarius is in full
swing. A funky, photogenic, multiracial band forms in L.A. At a
coffeehouse gig, a beautiful 17-year-old from Glendale, Nansi
Nevins, gets up from the audience and starts singing with the band.
She joins the group and becomes the band's star.
</P>
<P>
   They give free concerts in the park and begin to attract a
following. They open for such legendary acts as the Doors and the
Grateful Dead; they're the first band to play at Woodstock in 1969.
Then, just as they're breaking into the national spotlight on
television shows, including ``The Red Skelton Hour'' and ``American
Bandstand,'' tragedy strikes: Nevins is nearly killed in a car
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, miraculously, she recovers, but one of her vocal cords
has been badly damaged by the tracheotomy that saved her life. The
band soon disappears into the netherworld of ``whatever happened to
...'' trivia questions.
</P>
<P>
   If Sweetwater had never existed, someone would have had to make
up a movie about them _ create a bittersweet tale like ``The
Commitments'' or ``Still Crazy'' about a fictional band, on the
verge of superstardom, that loses it all. But they did exist. Now,
they're back together again, performing, laying plans for a new
album and as the subject of the TV movie ``Sweetwater: A True Rock
Story,'' which debuts Sunday on VH1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really fun. Who could have imagined this?'' said
songwriter/keyboardist Alex Del Zoppo, who has reunited with Nevins
and bassist Fred Herrera. ``We don't even have a press agent. But
you turn on MTV these days, and it's like the all-Sweetwater
channel. It's almost embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweetwater may not have a publicist, but MTV Networks does. This
is the first original movie produced by VH1, sister channel to MTV,
and they are, in fact, promoting the heck out of it. Frequent
messages pop up on-screen reminding you that ``Sweetwater'' is just
days away; ads on the channel link the band to virtually every
significant event of the '60s. Nevins is played by ``Felicity's''
Amy Jo Johnson in her youth and by singer/actress Michelle Phillips
in the present day.
</P>
<P>
   The band's path back from obscurity actually began about four
years ago. Del Zoppo and Herrera had stayed in touch over the years
but had lost contact with the others. One is still around but has
moved on and declined to rejoin the band. Three died, either in
accidents or, in flutist Albert Moore's case, of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Nevins was the missing piece of the puzzle. After her accident,
she'd had a rough time finding her place in the world. After a
long, painful recovery, which left her voice much-changed from the
early days, she recorded a solo album. It bombed.
</P>
<P>
   After that, ``I crashed and burned personally. ... I was
homeless for a period of time,'' Nevins recalls. She abused drugs
and quickly ran through any money she'd made as part of Sweetwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' Nevins said, `` I needed money, so I went back to
school. I figured that was the way to make more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevins earned a teaching credential and went to work at
California State University, Fullerton. ``I like teaching people in
the same place I was in a few years ago,'' she explains about her
love of teaching young college students. The talkative Nevins had
by now shed the stage name Nansi, and reverted to spelling her
first name Nancy (same pronunciation ... hey, she was a teen-age
girl in the '60s).
</P>
<P>
   Though Nevins had taken a new path in life, she admits, ``This
thing would not die inside of me. I always felt like (Sweetwater)
had unfinished business.''
</P>
<P>
   So when she saw a newspaper article about the 25th anniversary
of Woodstock that said Sweetwater was ``missing,'' she felt
compelled to respond. ``(START ITALS)I'm(END ITALS) not missing,''
she wrote, signing her name and city to the letter that ran in the
paper a week later.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Herrera tracked her down. ``We got together in a
coffee shop and talked for four hours,'' Nevins recalls. Soon, the
two got together with Del Zoppo and started doing some informal
jamming for the first time in more than two decades. Around the
same time, Nevins started writing the story of the band and her own
journey in longhand during school breaks in the faculty lounge.
These notes would eventually turn into the basis for the VH1 movie.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera had stayed in the music business, both as a backup
musician and an orchestra manager for such artists as Yanni. He
admits he was surprised and delighted to hear that Nancy's voice
had come back well. ``It's not the same voice,'' Nevins admits,
``but it's strong.'' Actually, her voice, which in her younger days
was compared to the big voice of Grace Slick, today has a slightly
raspy quality that recalls a more willowy Kim Carnes (``Bette Davis
Eyes'').
</P>
<P>
   Del Zoppo had sort of a love-hate affair with music. He made a
living for several years as a session musician with such stars as
the Beach Boys and Eric Burdon but grew tired of the lifestyle. ``I
got kind of burnt out on the business,'' Del Zoppo admits, ``So I
started a construction business. I just kind of wanted to work and
collect a check for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Zoppo was the most hesitant of the three to regroup as a
performing act. ``We'd had all this great hope for our band. We'd
just about made it,'' Del Zoppo says, ``then the bottom fell out
from under us. It really kind of leaves a bitter taste in your
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was won over by the chance to write music and perform
again. Also, Nancy's enthusiasm was contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy is the eternal optimist, and it's paid off for her,''
Herrera says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any dream needs to be pursued,'' says Nevins, who seems to
have achieved a sense of peace after years of hardship. ``I think,
as Winston Churchill said, `Never give up.' Everything brought me
to this moment. I believe in synchronicity, in perfect timing in
the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevins now lives a quiet life in Tujunga, tending to her garden
and her cats. She's taking a break from teaching writing and
literature at Glendale Community College to concentrate on music.
</P>
<P>
   The band now has high hopes for the future. After years of being
out of print, their music is set to hit stores again: Rhino, the
reissue label owned by Warner Bros., is releasing ``Cycles: The
Reprise Collection'' on Monday, the day after the VH1 movie airs.
They're working on a new album, though they don't have a label yet
and are fielding offers to tour based on the publicity for the
movie. Del Zoppo says they've been offered a tour of the House of
Blues chain, for example.
</P>
<P>
   For now, all three are just trying to enjoy the ride _ and get
used to being seen by young people as icons of another era.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're young, you really don't know the implications of
what's going on,'' Herrera says. ``We didn't really appreciate how
rare it was that we made it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Zoppo says he had a moment of realization in a conversation
with Kurt Max Runte, who plays him as a young man. ``He called to
ask me some questions,'' Del Zoppo recalls, ``and at the end of the
conversation, he said, `I'm looking forward to this. I've never
played a historical figure before.' I said, `What?' Then I
realized, I guess he's right,'' Del Zoppo says with a laugh. ``We
ARE historical now.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
The  &LR; show &UR; : &LR;  ``Sweetwater.''  &QL; 
The stars &UR; : &LR;  Amy Jo Johnson, Michelle Phillips, Kelli Williams and
Frederic Forrest. &QL; 
Where &UR; : &LR;  VH1 &QL; 
When &UR; : &LR;  9 p.m. Sunday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
