<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SPORTS-MINORITIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS LEADERS CALL FOR MORE MINORITIES IN TOP MANAGEMENT
POSITIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By LORI RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ More than 52 years after baseball legend Jackie
Robinson cracked the pro sports color line, minorities have barely
penetrated the top ranks of the industry, National League president
Leonard Coleman told blacks meeting Tuesday in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, 2 percent of the jobs in the front office were
held by African-Americans and other minorities. Today, that number
is 21 percent. That's not insignificant progress,'' Coleman said on
a panel at the National Urban League's annual conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we made enough progress? The answer is an emphatic,
`No.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, said Coleman, only Bob Watson, formerly with
the Houston Astros and New York Yankees, had managed to ascend to
the highly visible post of general manager. Seven other minorities
have risen to the rank of assistant general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old boy network has outlived its usefulness, but it's
still entrenched,'' said Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball Commissioner Bud Selig also was scheduled
to appear on the panel discussing sports as a pathway to power but
canceled, citing scheduling conflicts. Coleman, however, said a
recent meeting with Selig and other ``disturbed'' industry leaders
had yielded some action.``
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner has issued a letter to all clubs stating that
no clubs may hire a general manager, an assistant general manager,
a field manager, a head of player development or a head of scouting
without first consulting with the commissioner,'' Coleman said in
the panel at the George R. Brown Convention Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minority candidates must be considered. Can it be done? I
would argue yes, obviously with the backing of the commissioner.''
</P>
<P>
   From the National Football League side of the panel, Michael
Huyghue, a senior vice president for football operations with the
Jacksonville Jaguars, said that while 70 percent of the players are
black, none of the 31 team owners are and only two of the investors
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself in National Football League meetings each year
as the only African-Americans in those boardrooms, which is
striking and unfortunate,`` Huyghue said. ``We shouldn't be at a
stage where someone 37 years old is the only voice of
representation for African-Americans in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Huyghue said NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue was sensitive to
the problem but added that was far from enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until owners in the NFL are African-Americans, I don't believe
we'll truly have the full inclusion and level playing field that we
all seek,'' Huyghue said. ``The commissioner has been behind it,
but the commissioner is an employee of the owners of the NFL so his
edicts, while important, don't carry the weight that ownership must
take on.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond ownership and front-office posts, Coleman said the
vending, supply, construction and professional service side of the
sports industry provided another path for minority inroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Houston, there was a referendum,'' Coleman said of the
vote to build the new ballpark on the east edge of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to get the support of the minority community, 30
percent of the construction contracts and jobs were set aside for
the minority firms,'' Coleman said. ``A new ballpark generates $119
million to $187 million in total spending per year and, also each
year, 2,000 to 3,200 full- and part-time positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Huyghue said he is confident the time will come when he will
look around NFL board meetings and not be the only ``dark face'' he
sees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few years ago, it would have been unthinkable that
Green Bay, Wis. , a team that has a long history in the NFL, can
have a black head coach, a black offensive coordinator and a black
defensive coordinator and a white quarterback who is known as one
of the top quarterbacks in the game,'' said Huyghue, who was
referring to Green Bay Packers' quarterback Brett Favre, a two-time
NFL Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens now without much notoriety.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The meeting concludes Wednesday. A morning town meeting on ``The
Police and People of Color: Can't We All Just Get Along?'' features
12 nationally recognized panelists.
</P>
<P>
   The moderator is Charles J. Ogletree Jr., a Harvard Law School
professor. Panelists include attorney Johnny Cochran, Karen K.
Narasaki, executive director of the National Asian Pacific American
Legal consortium; John F. Timoney, police commissioner of
Philadelphia; and Raul Yzaguirre, president of the National Council
of La Raza. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
