<HEADER>
A2245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAXES-GOP11-COX     08-10 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-GOP11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP HIGHLIGHTS PENSION PROVISIONS IN TAX BILL
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans opened a broad public relations
campaign supporting their $792 billion tax cut bill Tuesday with a
news conference touting the plan's bipartisan measures to expand
retirement savings.
</P>
<P>
   Opening a sales campaign that will occupy much of the August
recess, Rep. Rob Portman, R-Ohio, said provisions such as raising
401(k) contribution limits address the need to encourage greater
savings among Americans.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert , R-Ill., will be
in suburban Chicago hammering away at the same theme in a speech to
workers at an auto parts plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll (also) have a bigger-picture message,'' said Hastert's
spokesman, Pete Jeffries, of ``challenging the president to sign
tax relief into law.''
</P>
<P>
   The underlying point of the Republican effort is to buttress the
tax bill against an anticipated veto by President Clinton, who
favors a smaller tax cut package. The GOP plans to have members of
Congress appear on radio and television talk shows and do
interactive online chats ``frankly, to explain what's in the
bill,'' Portman said.
</P>
<P>
   This week's focus is on retirement savings, next week's will be
about tax cuts and the economy as a whole, and in the final week of
August the GOP plans to focus on how their program benefits
families, women and children.
</P>
<P>
   But every week will be about going up against Clinton, who calls
the GOP plan ``risky'' and ``irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just ask the question,'' Portman said, ``how
irresponsible is it to expand savings plans for people who don't
have retirement programs?''
</P>
<P>
   Among the provisions in the pension reform section:
</P>
<P>
   _ Increasing annual limits on pre-tax contributions to pension
programs such as 401(k) plans from $10,000 to $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increasing tax-deductible IRA contributions from $2,000 to
$5,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   _ Permitting workers over 50 to have higher contribution limits
that would allow them to ``catch up'' for years when either income
or expenses from child rearing didn't allow them to make regular
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Faster vesting that allows workers to become eligible for
matching contributions from their employers in three years rather
than five years.
</P>
<P>
   Portman is co-author of the pension reforms in the bill, which
were offered in stand-alone legislation earlier this year. His
partner, Rep. Ben Cardin, D-Md., helped draw an array of
co-sponsors from across the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the support of both labor unions and the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce for improving the advantages of tax-deferred
retirement accounts, that seems unlikely to draw opponents of the
larger tax-cut bill into the fold.
</P>
<P>
   Cardin himself said Tuesday that while he was thrilled to see
both the House and Senate pass a bill carrying the pension reforms
he and Portman put together, he still disagrees with the bill
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting that (Republicans) are highlight the pension
provisions, because they're such a small part of this big tax
bill,'' Cardin said. ``I'm one of those people who would encourage
the president to veto the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   But Portman and Cardin agree that even if the existing tax bill
is vetoed as expected, the retirement savings element is likely to
be transplanted into a compromise bill simply because it has drawn
so much support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's extremely likely that if we have any significant
tax bill, we'll have pension reform,'' Cardin said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
