<SLUG> BC-ABA-RENO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reno to convention: Funding the court system will help
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno on Tuesday called for
increased funding for the nation's court systems to combat juvenile
crime, domestic violence and child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in my heart and soul that if we give the judges the
tools to do the job, they will do it,'' Reno said in a brief
address to the American Bar Association's annual meeting here.
``Let's give our courts and our judges what it takes to do
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno's comments to the ABA's House of Delegates almost coincided
with the airing of an NBC ``Today'' show interview with Independent
Counsel Ken Starr, who declined to comment on repeated questions as
to whether he believes Reno has conducted herself properly during
his five-year investigation of President Clinton and his wife,
Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Starr said the ``career people at the Justice
Department are honorable, decent people'' and that the independent
counsel's office has had a good relationship with them during the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked whether he could say the same thing about Reno,
Starr answered, ``I'm not going to comment.'' When told he was
leaving the impression that he does not believe Reno has been
honorable and decent throughout the investigation, Starr again
replied, ``I'm simply not going to comment.''
</P>
<P>
   During her speech before the ABA, Reno noted that the nation's
drug courts recently celebrated their 10th anniversary and that
there are now 359 in operation across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The country should draw upon the drug court success and use it
to combat domestic violence and child abuse and neglect, the
attorney general said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us use that experience and show what can be done and let
courts lead the way,'' she said. ``But we can't if we make justice
a hollow, hollow voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno also noted that, over the next five years, more than 2.5
million inmates will be released from prison and returned to
society.
</P>
<P>
   Unless something is done about it, ``they will come back to
their apartments near the open-air drug markets and they'll have no
job,'' Reno said. ``Guess what? They're going to be (committing
crime) again.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno called for the initiation of ``re-entry courts'' that give
the criminal justice system the chance to monitor inmates returning
to society. ``Unless we bring them a chance of success, the
criminal justice system will fail again,'' said Reno, who provided
no specifics about this new brand of court system.
</P>
<P>
   Reno also noted that 16 percent of the inmates in the prison
population have been diagnosed with mental illness. These prisoners
are neglected and need help, she said, calling on the nation's
lawyers to speak up for them and help these inmates as they
continuously return to prisons and jails.Bill Rankin writes for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
