</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAT ROBERTSON'S DEADLY FOREIGN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Marianne Means' column will resume on Thursday, Aug. 19)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Christian Coalition President Pat Robertson, the
preacher and former Republican presidential candidate, recently
urged President Clinton to end the decades-old U.S. policy that
forbids the assassination of foreign leaders we don't like.
</P>
<P>
   Premeditated murder across borders in an exercise of national
revenge is, in Robertson's eyes, a good family value. He assumes
that global moral order is automatically on our side, the end
justifies the means and there will be no destructive consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Good grief. This is not God's plan, it is Machiavelli's.
</P>
<P>
   The political world is a breeding ground for bizarre notions.
But coming from a famous evangelist who is accustomed to giving the
Republican Party fits, a revival of this bloody, unethical and
impractical theory of governing by covert force is exceptionally
alarming.
</P>
<P>
   What is he trying to do? We all know that Robertson's belief in
the gospel is conditioned by his frustrated political ambitions.
Yet surely pronouncements from a theological pulpit should be held
to decent limits.
</P>
<P>
   His 1988 presidential run was disastrous; he fizzled in the
first primary in New Hampshire and never recovered, even in his
Southern home base. He has tried to pick presidents by intimidating
candidates with his bellicose, self-righteous Christian Coalition.
But nowadays his crumbling organization is less influential than in
past elections. He has even sold off his television network.
</P>
<P>
   So Robertson has become something of a political leftover, vying
with fresher conservative voices for attention. Killing off
America's perceived enemies is a familiar Robertson theme. He has
long advocated secret counterterrorism squads to assassinate
kidnappers and killers of Americans abroad.
</P>
<P>
   He raised the subject again this week on his religion-oriented
television program the ``700 Club,'' specifically suggesting we
``send a squad in to take out somebody like (accused terrorist)
Osama bin Laden, or take out the head of North Korea ... take out
(Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic, take out (Iraqi President
Saddam) Hussein. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, he left his much-advertised Biblical principles behind
the studio door when he decided to discuss foreign policy. Unless
the Good Book has been rewritten lately, the Ten Commandments still
insist that we are to love our neighbors, not to kill them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's (assassination) the intelligent thing to
do,'' Robertson said. ``I don't see anything unchristian about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson is not bothered by the traditional moral, legal,
practical and operational objections that have long barred
government-issued orders to gun down some leader in another
sovereign country. He has also predicted the end of the world in
his lifetime, maybe in 2000, so perhaps he doesn't care what our
national standards are in the brief meantime.
</P>
<P>
   The official American policy toward assassination was publicly
settled in the 1960s during President Lyndon Johnson's
administration after a Senate investigation of CIA activities that
exposed inept plots to kill Cuban President Fidel Castro. Johnson
himself once told me he believed Castro's agents encouraged Lee
Harvey Oswald to kill President John F. Kennedy in retaliation for
the CIA plots.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson executive order making it illegal to conspire on
behalf of the U.S. government to assassinate anyone has been the
official policy of subsequent administrations.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of practical reasons for this, in addition to
the fact that state-ordered killing is morally wrong without
judicial due process.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious is self-preservation. If we set out to kill
another country's political leaders, the targeted group is apt to
try to kill our leaders too. Murdering a controversial foreign
official could also lead to a brutal round of atrocities in which
innocent people of that country would needlessly die.
</P>
<P>
   We cannot authorize a cycle of international murder-for-hire.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, it doesn't work anyway. Those who replace the
victims may be even worse. We cannot control foreign succession.
</P>
<P>
   And if we are after terrorists, the odds are the campaign will
fail.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorists are cunning about hiding and resilient as well. After
the attack on Israeli athletes at the 1972 Munich Olympics, Israel
methodically assassinated 11 suspected leaders of Palestinian
terrorist organizations over the next two years. Palestinian
terrorist attacks continued.
</P>
<P>
   Our foreign policy is conducted by diplomacy, not by the end of
a gun or the tip of a poison dart. When it is necessary to wage
war, we will do so. But in the meantime we will be wise not to
tempt the fates with evil deeds masquerading as acceptable public
policy.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
