<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABA-VOTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABA delegates delay vote on partnership ban
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``One-stop shopping'' offering legal work along with
tax preparation and insurance might sound appealing to some
consumers, but the nation's largest group of lawyers Tuesday
determined the time for it may not be right.
</P>
<P>
   Citing serious ethical concerns governing the attorney-client
relationship, the American Bar Association's House of Delegates
delayed a vote whether to abolish a decades-old ban that prevents
lawyers from forming partnerships with non-lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The ABA's annual meeting here, held at the Georgia World
Congress Center and other hotels around the city, ends today.
</P>
<P>
   Votes by members of the House of Delegates, the ABA's
policy-making arm, signaled the winding-down of the meeting, which
attracted 13,000 lawyers, including President Clinton and
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   No issue has more sharply divided the ABA membership that the
proposal to end the ban on profit-sharing between lawyers and
non-lawyers. Supporters said the sharing of professions is
inevitable and allows U.S. firms to compete internationally with
European firms that already allow it. But opponents say it
jeopardizes the ``core values'' of the legal profession: loyalty to
the client, confidentiality and independence of lawyer judgment.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the heated debate over the issue appeared to parallel
fears raised in small-towns where drug and hardware store owners
expressed concern about the new Wal-Mart planned for construction.
</P>
<P>
   A large ``one-stop shop'' that provides legal work, accounting
and insurance will drive the solo practitioners out of business,
Cheryl Niro, a state attorney from Chicago, told the delegation.
``This is an access-to-justice issue for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jamie Gorelick, a former deputy U.S. Attorney General who is
now vice chairwoman of Fannie Mae, urged abolition of the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many, many problems that can benefit from this
approach,'' she said. ``Clients will want to look to one person to
bring a team together that crosses the boundaries between the law
and other business arenas. Whether corporate clients or individual
clients, they need that choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Lamm, a Washington lawyer, said rules can be established
to require lawyers to adhere to ethics codes.
</P>
<P>
   But others said that would be almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you enforce the ethical standards of two professions
when the same person is wearing both hats?'' asked Stephen Zack, a
Miami lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous lawyers cited concerns over how a lawyer could work
with an accountant when the lawyer must give absolute
confidentiality to a client, while accountants have a duty to
report their clients' financial irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm uneasy about it because of the conflicting obligations in
the different professions,'' Georgia Attorney General Thurbert
Baker, a member of the state's ABA delegation, said before the
vote. ``We need to show some caution.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the House of Delegates passed a resolution calling
on legislators to require police to keep statistics to help
determine whether traffic stops and searches are being conducted
for racially discriminatory reasons. It also reaffirmed its support
for the merit selection of judges.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
