<HEADER>
A2259 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-62     08-10 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-625(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS RISE AS INDIA SHOOTS DOWN PAKISTANI PLANE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ An Indian jet fighter on Tuesday shot down a
propeller-driven Pakistani naval aircraft that was flying near the
India-Pakistan border, reportedly killing all 16 people aboard and
heating up the already inflamed situation between the world's
newest nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani plane was hit by a missile in the late morning,
and by late evening each country was still asserting not only that
the aircraft had been flying in its airspace, but also that the
wreckage had fallen within its territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a routine training flight, ruthlessly shot out of the
sky without a single provocation,'' Mushahid Hussain, Pakistan's
information minister, said in a telephone interview. ``The Indians
seem to be in a very provocative and belligerent mood.''
</P>
<P>
   A sharply contradictory version was delivered by India's defense
minister, George Fernandes. He said what when the Pakistani plane,
a French-built Atlantic, was intercepted and commanded to land at
an Indian base, it ``indulged in a hostile act by taking a turn
toward the Indian fighter aircraft and challenging it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indian plane, a MiG-21, then fired a missile into the
Pakistani plane's port engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the area was thick with clouds, the fighter could not
see where the Pakistani plane went down,'' Fernandes said, though
he added that Indian helicopters later found the crash site and
were trying to examine wreckage that rested in a marshy area.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandes said that several Pakistani helicopters had also
ventured near the debris. ``We made it clear that we will not allow
them to be there,'' he said. ``We will fire. We have warned them
that any movement onto our side will be treated as hostile.''
</P>
<P>
   The wreckage rests near the border between the Indian state of
Gujarat and the Pakistani state of Sindh. The area is sometimes
known as Sir Creek, and it is the subject of one of several
boundary disputes between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's events could lead to fearsome consequences. Pakistan's
foreign minister called the incident a ``blatant unprovoked act of
military aggression'' and said, ``Pakistan reserves the right to
make an appropriate response in self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indian military announced that it was in a ``state of
alert.''
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan have already fought three wars in their half
century of existence. The last was in 1972, and, in recent months,
tensions have been at their highest in nearly 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   From mid-May to late July, the Indian military fought ferocious
battles against hundreds of infiltrators who had sneaked into their
territory in the snow-capped mountains of Kashmir. India said that
the intruders were Pakistani soldiers, while Pakistan insisted that
they were Islamic warriors engaged in a holy war.
</P>
<P>
   During this fighting, India lost two fighter jets, both of which
fell in Pakistani-controlled territory. The downed aircraft were
repeatedly shown on Pakistani television. One of the two pilots was
said to have died in the crash, but when his body was returned,
Indian officials contended that an autopsy proved the man had been
tortured and shot dead.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations did manage to apply the brakes at the brink of
yet another all-out war, but since then shelling has remained heavy
across the so-called line of control that separates the parts of
Kashmir that each side controls.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 14 years, both countries have also been fighting a
high-altitude war in some of the world's least habitable terrain in
the western Himalayas near the Siachen Glacier.
</P>
<P>
   There is other fighting as well. In just the past week,
Pakistani-backed insurgents have been unusually audacious,
launching rocket attacks on Indian military bases in Kashmir. On
Sunday, Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee of India said he had
asked the United States to designate Pakistan formally as a
terrorist nation.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic-1 is a twin-engine aircraft that looks similar to a
cargo plane. It is used by many navies for aerial reconnaissance
and anti-submarine combat.
</P>
<P>
   Here in New Delhi, early press accounts referred to it as a
``spy plane,'' highlighting its capacity to fire missiles and sink
submarines with torpedoes.
</P>
<P>
   But Hussain, Pakistan's information minister, said the airplane,
as operated, was ``entirely harmless'' and carried no weapons. He
confirmed that 16 people _ five of them officers _ were on board
and presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a routine flight, frequently repeated, and India was
certainly familiar with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian defense ministry, however, said that the aircraft had
been traced ``intruding'' into its air space eight times from May
to July. In a television interview, Fernandes said that Indian jets
had scrambled to confront those planes but that they ``ran away
before our aircraft could reach them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The United States on Tuesday made note of the ominous events.
``We are concerned about an increase in tensions,'' said David
Leavy, spokesman for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   He said the White House was monitoring all reports of the downed
aircraft, adding that it hoped the two nations would return to
efforts toward peace that began last February when Vajpayee made a
celebrated bus trip to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   That effort, once hailed as the inevitable coming together of
two neighbors with a shared heritage, has in just a few months come
to seem an improbable pipe dream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
