<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-RUSSIA-ART-425&AMP;ADD-     08-10 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-RUSSIA-ART-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PREMIER-DESIGNATE OFFERS PLAN ON DAGESTAN SEPARATISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art slug)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As Russian forces continued to do battle with Islamic
militants in the mountains of the North Caucasus, Vladimir Putin,
the newly designated prime minister, said Tuesday that he had
proposed a ``package of measures'' to bring the volatile situation
under control.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a morning meeting with President Boris Yeltsin,
who Monday anointed him as the Kremlin candidate in presidential
elections next year, Putin, the former head of Russia's domestic
intelligence service, said he hoped that these measures would quell
the Islamic fundamentalist insurrection within weeks. He did not
say what the measures were.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, Islamic militants set off the crisis by crossing
the Chechen border into the neighboring Russian province of
Dagestan and seizing several mountain villages. Tuesday they issued
a statement declaring Dagestan's independence as an Islamic state,
and vowing to drive away ``infidels'' from its territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Dagestani authorities, who recently called in the Russian
army to help them fend off the threat of armed Islamic militants,
dismissed the statement as propaganda, and said it had no support
from the local population.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation in the North Caucasus promises to be the top
issue facing Putin, as he tries to prove to Yeltsin, and the
country, that he has the leadership qualities he needs to make a
serious run for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real test of his ability will be the Caucasus,'' said
Andrei Piontkovsky, head of the Center for Strategic Studies in
Moscow. ``There is no clear-cut strategy now, and it will be
necessary to take very difficult decisions. In the end, it is not a
military problem, but a political problem, the same one every
Muslim state faces with its fundamentalists.''
</P>
<P>
   Unrest and lawlessness in the North Caucasus have been one of
Moscow's major security concerns since the 1994-1996 war in
Chechnya, which ended with the defeat of Russia's undisciplined and
demoralized federal forces.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Chechnya has in effect seceded from Russia, although
its independence has not been formally recognized.
</P>
<P>
   In Dagestan on Tuesday, Russian troops from both the army and
the Interior Ministry continued their attacks on the rebel
strongholds in the southwestern part of the province. Most
civilians had evacuated the villages Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from the remote region were sketchy, and at times
contradictory. According to some reports, militants have been
forced out of some villages, but it is not clear where they went.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday, Lt. Col. Anatoly Kornukov,
commander of the Russian air force, said that three air regiments
were involved in the campaign, and that so far, 78 reconnaissance
and attack sorties had been flown.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Kornukov said the militants have sustained heavy losses
from the air strikes, and that some have retreated, but he gave no
specifics. In the first day of fighting, a Russian airplane
accidentally struck a police station near one of the rebel bases,
killing several Dagestani policemen.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Dagestani interior minister, a Russian air
force officer was killed Monday in a mortar attack, four soldiers
were wounded and two military helicopters were burned.
</P>
<P>
   Kornukov denied charges made Monday by the government of nearby
Georgia that Russian airplanes had bombed a Georgian village.
Kornukov said Russian planes had not violated Georgian air space,
but suggested that bombs dropped along the commandoes' escape route
might have been carried overland into Georgia as a provocation.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts Tuesday, attempting to make sense of Yeltsin's
sudden decision to dump his last prime minister, Sergei Stepashin,
concluded that the president had found Putin to be a tougher, more
resolute leader.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Monday by Yeltsin how his mood was as he took over his new
job, Putin _ who began his career as a KGB officer _ answered
curtly: ``combative.'' Putin's nomination goes to the Parliament's
lower house next Monday, where he is expected to be confirmed by
deputies eager to concentrate on their reelection campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the Federal Security Service, and secretary of the
Kremlin's advisory Security Council, Putin was already deeply
involved in Moscow's campaign in the Caucasus, and it is still not
clear whether his plan of action, presented Tuesday, will differ
from the course taken by the Stepashin government.
</P>
<P>
   In his parting comments to the Cabinet on Monday, Stepashin, who
returned Sunday night from a trip to Dagestan to oversee the
operation, said the coordination between the various forces,
including army and Interior Ministry troops, was poor. ''I had to
fly there and say that I was taking the responsibility myself,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to news reports, the Islamic commandoes _ adherents of
the so-called Wattabi fundamentalist sect which has been gaining
strength across Russia's northern caucasian region _ are led by
Shamil Basayev, a field commander who became a Chechen hero during
the war with Russia, and by Hattab, a shadowy Jordanian-born
guerrilla fighter who has established a military training camp in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The Wattabi sect has already made inroads into Dagestan, a
region made of 33 different, mainly Muslim, ethnic groups, but in
other villages, their presence has been tolerated by authorities.
Even if Russia's latest military operations succeeded in pushing
out the latest wave of militants, the problem of rising Islamic
militancy _ fueled by poverty and local corruption _ will remain,
some experts say.
</P>
<P>
   In the Chechen capital of Grozny, the president, Aslan
Maskhadov, insisted that Chechnya is not involved in the fight
being waged on its border, which he called a ``dirty game''
probably instigated by Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building an independent Chechen state rather than waging new
wars is our most important jihad'' or holy war, at the moment, said
Maskhadov, whose authority at home has been undercut by warlords
like Basayev who have forged links with religious fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
   As Putin tried to bring the complex situation in the Caucasus
under control, politicians in Moscow were scrambling to position
themselves for the political season, officially opened Monday by
Yeltsin. Parliamentary elections are to be held in December and
presidential elections are due next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin _ who until Monday had been seen as a possible Kremlin
favorite in the presidential race _ was being courted Tuesday by
right-wing political parties, headed by the reformers who were once
part of Yeltsin's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepashin has a political future,'' said Sergei Kiriyenko,
another former prime minister. ``Such people must not be wasted. I
consider it right that he lead a center-right bloc.''
</P>
<P>
   The emergence last week of a center-left bloc put together
Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov and several powerful regional governors,
a group perceived as hostile to the Kremlin's interests, is widely
seen as a catalyst for Yeltsin's decision to fire Stepashin and
replace him with someone who will be more forceful in protecting
the Yeltsin legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts Tuesday suggested that by firing Stepashin,
Yeltsin may have freed him to become a presidential candidate in
his own right, one who would not be burdened with an endorsement by
a deeply unpopular president, but who would still be loyal to
Yeltsin's personal interests, as well as his program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
