<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2268 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANCE-ARMSTRONG11-COX     08-10 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANCE-ARMSTRONG11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CYCLIST ARMSTRONG TAKES VICTORY LAP THROUGH CAPITAL
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (s) sports categories.
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tour de France champion Lance Armstrong continued
his victory lap of America Tuesday with a visit to the White House
and a lively question-and-answer session at the National Press
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know why we're celebrating. I hope it's because
of my victory in the Tour de France, which shows that there's life
after cancer,'' said Armstrong, who beat testicular cancer after
three operations and a course of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago I wouldn't have lived six months,'' he said
during a meeting with Vice President Al Gore at the White House.
``I hope that what I did gives inspiration to people all over the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also met with President Clinton for a photo session
and presented Clinton with a bicycle and helmet in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong gave Gore an official cycling jersey signed by his
teammates in the Tour de France, the world's premier bicycle race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some victories have an extra meaning to them,'' Gore said.
``The fact that you even began the race makes you a winner. You
captured the eyes of the nation and the hearts of the entire
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that in the aftermath of Armstrong's victory,
increased focus must be given to cancer research. He announced the
development of ``Insight Awards to Stamp Out Breast Cancer,'' a
research program that will use more than $4 million of the revenue
from the U.S. Postal Service's breast cancer research stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also spoke Tuesday at a National Press Club luncheon,
stopping first outside the club's headquarters to give autographs
to a group of admiring bicycle messengers.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was praised at the lunch as ``a testament to the
courage, determination and triumph of the human spirit.'' Quizzed
on matters ranging from controversial to comical, Armstrong was
alternately passionate and humble in his responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you're probably used to hearing politicians speak, not
necessarily professional cyclists,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong retraced his career highlights and recovery from
cancer before fielding questions from an audience that took him up
on his promise to try to answer every one.
</P>
<P>
   _ On whether his teammates on the U.S. Postal Service cycling
team receive enough credit: ``The work I did was small. It mainly
has to do with the perception of cycling in America. The sport is
really about a team. I never could have won it without this great
team. Nobody (abroad) believed in us. Next year there will be no
doubters. They probably don't get enough credit. They're not only
my teammates but friends.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On the monitoring of drug abuse in global competition: ``It
varies from sport to sport. What can you really do for substances
that aren't detectable? You can encourage athletes to be fair and
honest, but beyond that what can you do? Any time you mix big
sports with big money, you're going to have someone who wants to
cut corners.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On ways to increase cycling's popularity: ``Every sport needs
characters and personalities. Basketball wouldn't be basketball
without Michael Jordan. Fans need someone to follow. You need
events in the States. And you need junior development for the new
generation to keep the personality flow going.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
