<HEADER>
A2275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAWSON-TOURISM-NYTR &LR;      08-10 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAWSON-TOURISM-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 A `DAWSON'S' PEEK: SEE SITES MADE FAMOUS BY TV SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALLISON BALLARD   
 The Morning Star, Wilmington, N.C.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Wilmington has become a tourist attraction.
No, not for the beautiful beaches, challenging golf courses or even
the historic homes. It has become must-see on any trip south
because of its alter ego, the fictional town of Capeside, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Those outside the teen-age and 20-something set might not know
what a grip the hit series, Dawson's Creek, has on the country.
</P>
<P>
   In its first two seasons, the high-school drama, created by
North Carolina native Kevin Williamson, has caught fire and made
stars of James Van Der Beek (Dawson), Katie Holmes (Joey), Joshua
Jackson (Pacey) and Michelle Williams (Jen). The fans have created
a ratings surge for the WB network, started numerous Web sites
devoted to the show, and made the characters a part of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Production for the third season began Monday and the series
premiere is scheduled for the end of September. In an effort to get
as much Creek as possible, though, many fans have made pilgrimages
here in hopes of meeting the stars. And while they are searching
for them, they might as well have a look around town and see some
of the places where Dawson Leery, Joey Potter, Jen Lindley and
Pacey Witter have walked, hung out, even kissed.
</P>
<P>
   Wilmington has seen a boom in teen tourism. The Cape Fear Coast
Convention and Visitors Bureau has even published a brochure
helping fans locate places that have been used for filming. And
while talk of moving Dawson's Creek to the West Coast caused local
concern, producers now say they plan to keep the show here.
</P>
<P>
   A publicist for the series explained the decision to stay was
made because the look is an important part of the show they didn't
feel they could get in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The series is filmed on a closed set that is not open to the
public. visiting fans, however, can hope for a chance sighting of
the stars. Just last week, for example, Joshua Jackson made
national news for his part in a rescue of two girls swimming off
nearby Wrightsville Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a touring guide for fans compiled from information from
the Visitors Bureau and with help from location manager Craig
Rogers. First, visitors should know Dawson's Creek is really
Hewlett's Creek. And although there is a Dawson Street in town, it
has nothing to do with the show.
</P>
<P>
   _ A great place to start is a walking tour of EUE Screen Gems
Studios at 1223 N. 23rd St., the location of the soundstages for
most of the show's interiors. Tours are available on Saturdays and
Sundays at 10 a.m., noon and 2 p.m. and cost $10 per person. The
tours are given by Silver Screen Tours; for information call (910)
675-8479. Fans can purchase Dawson's memorabilia at the Hollywood
Connection Cafe at the studio _ look for the homemade mural of the
stars.
</P>
<P>
   _ All Dawson's fans should recognize the Cape Fear Riverwalk,
which is at the end of Market Street, and Riverfront Park on Water
Street . These sites are frequently featured for smooching scenes
and brooding moments. Bonus points for those who recognize the
Riverfront Information Booth as a hot dog stand in the series.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mollye's Market, 118 Princess St., a cute grocery/eatery is
also frequently used as a hangout and shop. And nearby Island
Passage Elixir at 4 Market St. was a boutique in a recent episode.
</P>
<P>
   _ The real-life video store, Screen Play Video, 212 N. Front
St., doubles as Pacey's after-school workplace on the show. Also,
before the series became a hit, actress Holmes used to live above
the shop. By the way, Van Der Beek and Jackson used to live above
the nearby restaurant, Deluxe.
</P>
<P>
   _ The interior of Thalian Hall Center for the Performing Arts,
310 Chestnut St., served as the Rialto Theater, one of Dawson's
favorite places. Although it was mentioned in the episode when
Dawson and Joey had their first date that the theater was to be
torn down it is, in fact, still standing
</P>
<P>
   _ The IceHouse, 115 S. Water St., was Joey's workplace for the
first two seasons. In the season finale, though, the restaurant
burned. The real reason the site is not being used is because there
is an extensive construction project being completed next door.
</P>
<P>
   _ The University of North Carolina at Wilmington, 601 S. College
Road, plays the role of Capeside High, where Dawson, Joey, Jen and
Pacey go to school. The buildings are often used as a backdrop to
the action and this season the athletic fields will be used for
filming.
</P>
<P>
   _ With its boardwalks and swing sets, Greenfield Lake, 1702
Burnett Boulevard, provides a perfect place for romantic walks. On
Dawson's Creek its name is Burham Lake.
</P>
<P>
   _ Serious fans may want to head down Airlie Road to Airlie
Gardens, which is sometimes used as a romantic spot. Also,
Battleship Park on Eagles Island was the site of the show's Winter
Fair.
</P>
<P>
   _ This season, The Cape Fear Seafood Co., 100 Yacht Basin Drive
in Southport, will be a new hangout for the Capeside gang.
Producers for the show are changing the inside of the building from
a fish house to a marina, said Larry Potter, owner of the shop. The
tentative title for the site on the show is Logan's Marina. Other
places in scenic Southport are likely to been seen in the drama
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scouts have been on the lookout for locales to film football
games and practices this season, perhaps to capitalize on the
success of Van Der Beek's hit sports movie, Varsity Blues. Legion
Stadium on Carolina Beach Road will be one of the locations.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of Dawson's Creek FAQ Sheet are available from the Cape
Fear Coast Convention and Visitors Bureau by calling (800) 222-4757
or by sending e-mail to info(AT)cape-fear.nc.us.
</P>
<P>
   Allison Ballard writes for The Morning Star, Wilmington, N.C., a
member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This article
was distributed by The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
