<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-ACQUIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT TECHNOLOGIES AGREES TO BUY CONSULTING COMPANY FOR $3.7
BILLION IN STOCK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies Inc. said Tuesday that it had agreed to buy
International Network Services Inc., a fast-growing consulting
company, for $3.7 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   For Lucent, North America's biggest maker of communications
equipment, the deal is a bid to move beyond merely making
complicated communications gear and expand its ability to help big
corporate clients install and use it.
</P>
<P>
   International Network, based in Sunnyvale, Calif., is
essentially a temporary-employment agency for network engineers.
Most of the company's 2,200 employees are digital trouble-shooters
who help big companies and communications carriers design and
manage complex networks. The companies' clients have included AT&AMP;T,
Bell Atlantic, First Union, Mastercard International and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   International Network earned $10 million in the last quarter on
revenue of $94.1 million, up sharply from a profit of $5.2 million
on revenue of $52.5 million in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's Netcare operation provides many of the same services
but may have been held back by its identification with Lucent. Even
though Cisco Systems Inc. owns 8 percent of International Network,
one of the company's selling points with potential clients has been
that its independence allows it to suggest the best networking
products without bias. Now that the company is part of Lucent, its
consultants may have to assure clients that they will not become
prejudiced in favor of Lucent's products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convergence of voice and data is driving tremendous demand
for services and support,'' Richard A. McGinn, Lucent's chairman,
said in a statement. ``Together, Lucent and INS will offer
customers the industry's deepest portfolio of network planning,
design, integration, maintenance and management solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cisco, the big data networking player, said it would
invest about $1 billion in KPMG, the consulting company, in a bid
to jointly offer Internet and networking consulting services.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's deal may improve the prospects for the coming initial
public offering of Predictive Systems Inc., which, like
International Network, provides networking consulting services.
Predictive, based in New York, is seeking to raise as much as $52
million. Predictive counts Qwest Communications International Inc.
and Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. among its clients.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of Tuesday's deal, each share of INS will be
exchanged for 0.8473 share of Lucent. Based on Lucent's closing
share price of $63.625 on Monday, the deal is worth about $54 for
each share of International Network. Shares of International
Network closed Monday at $47.4375, giving the deal a premium of
about 13.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent said it would account for the deal as a pooling of
interest, allowing the company to evade goodwill charges against
its future earnings to cover the difference between International
Network's book value and what Lucent is paying.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent said the deal would not affect its earnings in its 2000
fiscal year, which begins in October, but the company's shares fell
$2, to $61.625. Shares of International Network rose $3, to
$50.4375.
</P>
<P>
   John L. Drew, the chief executive of International Network and a
former executive for the Unisys Corp., will become the head of the
expanded Netcare organization, which will include International
Network and have 5,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not the deal's primary beneficiary. Instead, Donald K.
McKinney, the founder of International Network, will become the
latest Silicon Valley billionaire. In the deal, McKinney's roughly
32.1 percent stake in the company will become worth almost $1.2
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
