<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, Aug. 11, Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   LA-SHOOTING _ A man sprayed the lobby of a Jewish community
center with gunfire, injuring five people including three small
boys. Dozens of police officers searched the complex and the
surrounding neighborhood. The suspect was described as a white
male, police Commander David Kalish said. (Summary from wires.) By
James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-OUTLOOK (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ The U.N. mission in
Kosovo is finally moving to establish its authority here as the
province's government, to try to fill the vacuum exploited by the
Kosovo Liberation Army and those acting in its name. Senior U.N.
officials admit that they are now in a period of testing and
challenge with the KLA and its political and military leaders, but
they are also eager not to act like an imperial power or to drive
the KLA into opposition. By Steven Erlanger. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi, India) _ India shoots down a
Pakistani naval reconnaissance plane, killing the 16 people on
board. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   With map. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-POLITICS (Washington) _ The statements of George W. Bush,
Elizabeth Dole and John McCain about homosexuals signals a
softening of the Republican positions on this subject, but alarming
some conservatives in the party. By Katharine Q. Seelye. 1,900
words.
</P>
<P>
   OPEN-AIR-MOVIES (Baltimore) _ After the sun has set and he is
finished watering his rooftop garden, 89-year-old John Pente beams
down upon the fresh life that has come to the aging streets of his
beloved Little Italy: An al fresco specialty from the Old Country,
open-air movies, flash onto the parking lot wall of Da Mimmo's
restaurant, proudly projected from a bedroom window of Pente's row
house. Three stories below in the street, hundreds of people gather
with their lawn chairs for the free showings, engrossed in silence
but for the movie dialogue and the audience's lip-smacking at the
gift cannolis from Vaccaro's bakery. By Francis X. Clines. 1,000
words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PARAGUAY-ARCHIVE (Asuncion, Paraguay) _ When Martin Almada asked
a judge for records of his arrest under the dictatorship of Gen.
Alfredo Stroessner, he hoped merely to learn more about his own
private tragedy: nearly four years of captivity, during which
police telephoned his wife so she would hear his screams under
torture. Instead, the one-time school teacher unearthed a mountain
of records detailing repression among U.S.-backed military regimes
throughout South America during the Cold War. From floor to
ceiling, five tons of reports and photos detailed the arrest,
interrogation and disappearance of thousands of political
prisoners. The documents trace the creation and work of Operation
Condor, a secret plan among security forces in six countries to
crush left-wing political dissent. By Diana Jean Schemo. 2,000
words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-REPUBS (New York) _ Rick Lazio will suspend his plans
for a U.S. Senate campaign while New York City's mayor, Rudy
Giuliani, considers his own bid. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
</TEXT>
