<SLUG> BC-PERU-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LATIN-INDIAN-ROCK SOUND STIRS URBAN PERU  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Japan, N.J.)   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ Whenever there was a good harvest in ancient times,
according to Quechua Indian legend, the Earth Goddess sent
fun-loving dwarfs called Los Shapis to frolic under a giant rainbow
and help the peasants celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   It has been many centuries since Los Shapis were last seen in
the Andes, but they are back now in Lima. In their new form, Los
Shapis play electric guitars and keyboards, pound drums to a Latin
tropical beat and sing about unrequited love and the misery of
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a street vendor, I am a proletarian, I am humble,'' sang
Julio Simeon Salguiaran, 38, the lead singer of the group, his
voice droning one of the group's biggest hits in a sad monotone.
But the 400 youths at a concrete soccer field on Saturday night to
hear Los Shapis danced to the music and appeared anything but
depressed by the words.
</P>
<P>
   Los Shapis are one of many bands that are playing a new form of
Peruvian popular music that has touched a chord among migrant
youths of Indian origin who are trying to retain vestiges of their
Andean cultural heritage even as they adapt to modern urban life.
</P>
<P>
   The genre mixes singing styles and melodies from huayno
(pronounced WHY-no), the traditional music of the central Andean
highlands, with the tropical rhythms of cumbia, the music of
coastal Colombia, and then adds some rock touches from the Beatles,
the Rolling Stones and Santana.
</P>
<P>
   The blending first began in the 1970s in the slums of Lima that
sprouted up along the highways connecting the capital with the
central highlands, as Indian musicians from across Peru came in
contact with one another and lived together for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread misery in the countryside, made worse by a failed
land reform by a leftist military government in the 1970s, pushed
the peasants off the land and into the cities. Lima has nearly
tripled in size, from 2.8 million inhabitants to 8 million, since
1970. The earliest Indian migrants quickly assimilated, giving up
their languages and customs as they sought employment in factories
and as street merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvian anthropologists and sociologists say the new music has
shown that a new cultural quilt is emerging in Lima that combines
Indian and white threads.
</P>
<P>
   The music ``is linked to the process of the Andeanization of
Lima,'' said Raul Romero Cevallos, director of the Center of Andean
Ethnomusicology at the Catholic University of Peru. ``It is a new
cultural style created by Andean migrants to the cities as an
attempt to create a new sense of identity and that is very
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, longtime Lima residents, who were shocked by the waves
of Indian migrants overcrowding the capital, stigmatized the new
genre as lower-class music that appealed only to drifters and
melancholy Indians. But sensing the commercial power of the
migrants, local radio stations began to play it in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, several music and dance shows featuring
the music have cropped up on Peruvian television, which
traditionally appealed only to the wealthier white audience.
Cassettes of the music are now at the top of the Peruvian charts,
but complete sales figures are difficult to come by because pirated
cassettes are so prominent in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   As the great Peruvian migration moved beyond Lima to around
South America, Europe and the United States in recent years, the
new music has gone along with it. It has become a hit on Argentine
cable television, and bands playing it have made appearances in
nightclubs as far away as Paris, Tokyo, Washington, Port Chester,
N.Y., and Paterson, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Even President Alberto Fujimori has declared himself a fan. He
recently appeared in public embracing Rossy War, a star whose
trademarks include high leather boots and miniskirts trimmed with
pearl-white beads. Fujimori was probably trying to appeal to urban
youths as he plans his re-election campaign at a time when some
stars and managers are making increasingly explicit political
statements about unemployment and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, a night listening and dancing to the
music of Los Shapis is just a good time, and an excuse to drink
beer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the swirling lights of a kaleidoscope ball, Salguiaran and
his group strut, kick and dance a neat three-step in unison. They
dress in black and white athletic warm-up suits and their banner is
appropriately a rainbow in honor of the ancient, erotic dwarfs.
</P>
<P>
   Repetitive guitar riffs in high C have something of a hypnotic
effect, and the words of the songs are catchy, even if depressing.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd lights up with smiles as Salguiaran _ a squat, rather
uncharismatic man whose stage name is Chapulin _ sings old
favorites like ``Little Drunk for Love'' and a song called ``El
Aguajal,'' named after the juice of an exotic tropical fruit, that
goes: ``There are lovers. There are objects of affection. They are
all traitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Elena Pancaya, a 20-year-old Los Shapis fan, said the melancholy
music did not bother her at all. ``The songs are sad, but they
remind us of our families and our hopes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Salguiaran said that the music ``is popular
because it speaks to the lives of the people _ the stories of the
street vendors, the drivers, the students.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's about life and love.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted a great future for the genre, one that would put it
right up there with rock and the blues.
</P>
<P>
   The music ``originated in Huancayo,'' he said, referring to a
highland city. ``Then it triumphed in Lima, and in the future it
will triumph all over the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
