<SLUG> BC-CAR-RACIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO WINSTON CUP TEAM MEMBERS SUSPENDED IN RACIAL INCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two NASCAR Winston Cup team members were put on indefinite
suspension by the sanctioning body and subsequently fired from
their jobs as motorcoach drivers for Derrike Cope and Terry Labonte
because of a racially insensitive prank they played on a black crew
member of Jeremy Mayfield's team.
</P>
<P>
   The incident took place July 8 as Winston Cup teams arrived at
New Hampshire International Speedway in Loudon, N.H. for the July
11 Jiffy Lube 300.
</P>
<P>
   According to Chip Williams, a spokesman for the Penske-Kranefuss
Racing team, David Scott, a motorcoach driver for Mayfield's team,
answered a knock at the vehicle's door and was greeted by the two
motorcoach drivers, one of whom wore a pillowcase over his head in
an apparent impersonation of a Ku Klux Klansman.
</P>
<P>
   According to Williams, Scott declined comment on the matter.
However, Michael Kranefuss, the car owner who lodged a complaint
with NASCAR on Scott's behalf, issued a statement applauding
NASCAR's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penske-Kranefuss Racing and Jeremy Mayfield fully support
NASCAR's response to the behavior directed at one of our team
members,'' Kranefuss said. ``We and the team member stand together
and look forward to putting the incident behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to reports that the incident stemmed from an argument,
Williams said there was ``no fight, no argument, no physical
confrontation, or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to reports, the situation was characterized by those
close to the incident as a joke that went too far. But no one at
NASCAR thought it was a laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes down to it, whatever the reason was behind it,
whatever the motivation was, there are certain things that can't be
tolerated in this day and age,'' said Kevin Triplett, NASCAR's
director of operations. ``There's a certain professionalism with
being involved in any occupation, and there's zero tolerance for
anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The team members, whose names were not disclosed by their
employers, were immediately terminated when NASCAR handed down the
suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behavior like this simply cannot be tolerated in today's
society,'' said Cope. ``This was an example of grievous behavior
that I do not condone. It was an ignorant act, and I took the only
course available to me of rectifying the situation by terminating
the employee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
