<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV17-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SHOULD REFLECT LIFE'S DIVERSITY
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday, Aug. 17)  
(yn) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk turned to the good old days when kids came home from school
and watched the Mickey Mouse Club. Everyone started to recall their
favorite Mousketeer and Barbara Love, an African-American, quietly
excused herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I wanted to say was I thought the Mickey Mouse Club was
pretty racist. But if I had, then someone would have said, `Oh
Barbara, don't be such a downer. Is everything about race with
you?' Which would mean, `Can't you sit here and accommodate us and
let us be comfortable?'''
</P>
<P>
   The Mickey Mouse Club made her feel bad when she was a young
girl, because no Mousketeer looked like her or any other
African-American. Annette Funicello came the closest to being a
person of color. And she wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kinds of shows weren't fun for me. I watched through a
much different lens,'' says Barbara, a Headstart administrator in
Santa Rosa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years post-Mickey Mouse Club, the issue comes up again.
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
wants to know where the black faces are on prime-time TV. A
Hispanic advocacy group asks the same, why the ``brownout'' of
Hispanics?
</P>
<P>
   There's an antidote, however, to white bread television, and
that's reality. For a healthy dose of it, try the video ``The Way
Home,'' produced by the World Trust in Oakland, Calif. It's a
compelling, frank discussion about oppression by 64 women who vary
in identity from Arab to Jewish to Afro-American to
European-American.
</P>
<P>
   They relate how they've all felt outside the circle _ and the
divide goes beyond black and white. A group of Jewish women talk
about how Ashkenazi Jews discriminate against Sephardic Jews. A
Vietnamese student in San Francisco says she feels cut out by
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
   Arab women say they're routinely stopped by security guards in
airports. A white waitress admits being surprised that Asians know
so much about wine.
</P>
<P>
   They speak of the self-disgust that comes from racism. An
African-American says, ``I had nappy hair but thank God I had the
lightest skin.'' A Jewish woman confesses that when someone told
her she didn't look Jewish, she said, ``thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Women of mixed blood wonder where they belong. The white
grandparents of a half-black woman won't introduce her to their
friends. An Afro-Cuban is shunned by Latinas.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Love helped work on ``The Way Home'' and is promoting it
in Northern California, starting to take it around to schools,
churches and employee groups. The theme is similar to the popular
``Color of Fear,'' produced a few years back, in which eight men of
different races discuss their resentments and fear of one another.
</P>
<P>
   The mood of the women in ``The Way Home'' is less
confrontational, but it still hits the mark. No one gets to deny
their own prejudice, even if it means sitting silently and wincing,
remembering how your Gidget-style adolescence kept non-whites off
the pajama party list.
</P>
<P>
   The intent of the video is to make a dent in racism _ which most
people agree is bad _ by discussing it, which most people find
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants it to be all right without talking about it,''
says Barbara. ``They want to say, ``That was my ancestor's thing,
not mine.' Or they say, ``We've come a long way.'''
</P>
<P>
   If so, why doesn't everyone get to see faces like theirs on TV _
``someone with my nose, my hair, my lovely eyes,'' asks Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally you'd watch the video with a group of friends and then
afterward admit to those ugly notions that crept in from childhood
and the slurs you let pass at work.
</P>
<P>
   In our culture the white person, who is still entitled, can make
the choice to work on racism or not. If white people desire
diversity, in our communities and on TV, we have to also demand it.
</P>
<P>
   Saying nothing is a different vote. A young European-American
says in the video, ``Keeping silent is how I hold onto my
privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2289 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-10 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS BEATING THE BUSH FOR LINEBACKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ There's only one viable solution: Do not let
the important players play until the season starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are so banged up that Tuesday they were holding
auditions, bringing in veteran linebacker Steven Morrison, formerly
of the Indianapolis Colts, and former Tampa Bay running back and
special teams player Jerry Ellison.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they may take a look at former Cleveland Browns and
New York Jets linebacker Pepper Johnson and are seeking a backup
tight end and a reserve veteran defensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to some teams, we're not doing too badly,'' said vice
president of player personnel Bobby Grier Tuesday. ``We've had the
big injury to Ted (Johnson), and there's no question that's huge,
but we have others that we've held back and others like Willie
McGinest, Chris Slade who have been able to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are certainly acting on the side of caution where
tight end Ben Coates is concerned. Though he has dressed in pads
for a few days, Coates has yet to take part in any hitting after
spraining his knee early in camp. Grier expects the Patriots to go
very slowly with their future Hall-of-Famer; he probably won't play
in Friday night's exhibition opener against the Washington
Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Grier has had to redefine some of his personnel priorities with
the losses of Johnson (likely for the season), defensive tackle
Henry Thomas (for two or three weeks), and defensive end Sterling
Palmer (bruised disk in his back, day-to-day).
</P>
<P>
   Grier also is without the services of Shawn Stuckey, a
linebacker who played on special teams last season. Stuckey is in a
custody battle for his younger brother and needs time to sort
things out.
</P>
<P>
   With the Patriots so thin at middle linebacker, Pepper Johnson
is becoming more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pepper's name came up,'' said Grier. ``We understand he's
working out, so that's something we may consider over the next few
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not steal an ex-Jet? It's usually the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Patriots dumped Lovett Purnell to Baltimore for a
seventh-round pick, they also left themselves thin at tight end.
Rod Rutledge, the team's No. 2 draft pick two years ago, continues
to show he's a superb blocker, but his receiving remains suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Grier is looking for an H-back type. He has one long shot in
camp, Wabash's Jamie Bowers, who appears to catch everything thrown
his way. But Grier and Pete Carroll understand that Bowers comes
from a Division 3 program and is overmatched in certain situations.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive line is full of ends, but there isn't enough brawn
in the middle. Grier is looking for another ``Henry Thomas type,''
and some older defensive linemen are expected into camp soon.
</P>
<P>
   As for the running back situation, Kevin Faulk continues to show
good things, but the team has had few reservations about seeking
more veteran help. They would consider Ellison more for special
teams than running back, and the endless talks with Terry Allen
were still going on as late as Tuesday. Grier feels the Patriots
still have a good shot at Allen because the Falcons, embroiled in
the Jamal Anderson fiasco, have re-signed Harold Green, while the
Detroit Lions seem to be content with Barry Sanders's heir
apparent, Ron Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Grier was unsure why Tyrone Wheatley didn't take the Patriots'
offer rather than sign with Oakland, which already has Napoleon
Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   A trade? A player-for-player trade in the NFL?
</P>
<P>
   Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   It makes too much sense to trade Vincent Brisby to the Dallas
Cowboys for Chris Warren. The Cowboys could use a receiver, the
Patriots a running back. The cap numbers aren't far off, either.
But trades, unless they involve draft picks, are seldom made in the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   So for now, the Patriots are forced to go with what they have
and come up with some veteran backup help if they can find it.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots fans give a collective sigh of relief every time Terry
Glenn, Willie McGinest, and Brisby get through a practice without
getting hurt. The Patriots have paid close attention to McGinest,
making sure they don't overload him, while at the same time trying
to test the groin/hip/stomach area that has been McGinest's weak
spot for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery in the groin area may have eased some pressure, but
McGinest said Tuesday he's about 80-85 percent and feels some
soreness from the operation he had two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest will play Friday, but he said, ``I'm not doing nothing
stupid.'' McGinest wants to test himself, but not at the risk of
injury, in exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to prove anything against the Washington
Redskins,'' said McGinest. ``I've got to be smart. I understand the
team needs me for Sept. 12 against the New York Jets, and that's
what I'm trying to get ready for. I don't need to impress anybody
until that time.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point it's the right attitude to take. Glenn, who has
also been worked hard in camp, could probably step back a bit and
start gearing up for the Jets as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't busted Terry deep yet,'' said Grier. ``We're taking
it slow with that, and when we feel he's ready, we'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there is pressure, on both players and management, to
get injured players back on the field. But in this case, the
Patriots might be best served by using Sean Morey and Nafis Karim a
lot and saving Troy Brown, Glenn, Shawn Jefferson, and Brisby for
when it counts. They'd be better off throwing Greg Spires and
Willie Cohens at defensive end and saving McGinest for the real
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   And why would you play Bruce Armstrong except in the final
exhibition game? He's finally healthy and in the best shape of his
career. Losing him now would be stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Really, is there any reason why Coates or Thomas has to play
more than one exhibition game to be ready for the regular season?
Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons we may never know, the Patriots have become a
fragile team. They may not have any choice but to protect their
players until the bell rings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
