<HEADLINE>
EXPULSIONS INVOLVING STUDENTS CARRYING GUNS TO SCHOOL DECLINING,
REPORT INDICATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although the nation continues to struggle with
deadly classroom violence, an Education Department report indicates
the number of students expelled for bringing weapons to school is
dropping.
</P>
<P>
   That number fell 31 percent nationally during the 1997-98
academic year, the department reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, which led the nation in total number of students
expelled for toting weapons, expulsions dropped 20 percent. Texas
has the second-largest student population in 1997, at 3.97 million,
behind California with 6.29 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Education Department's study, a compilation of state figures
on school expulsions, found that 3,930 students nationwide from
elementary through high school were expelled in 1997-98 for weapons
possession, the most recent year for which statistics are
available. During the prior school year, 1996-97, 5,724 students
were expelled.
</P>
<P>
   The report said 424 Texas students were expelled for weapons in
1997-98. In 1996-97, 532 pupils were expelled.
</P>
<P>
   Of the expelled students, 33 were in elementary school, 136 were
in middle school and 255 were in high school, the Education
Department reported. The federal report is based on disciplinary
action only.
</P>
<P>
   The expulsion requirement is called for under the federal
Gun-Free Schools Act, which required U.S. states and territories to
enact laws calling for expulsion for at least one year whenever a
weapon is carried to school. The Education Department report is
designed to measure the progress of the 1994 act.
</P>
<P>
   The federal report's release follows tragic shootings last
spring at Colorado and Atlanta-area high schools. Local and federal
school safety officials on hand Tuesday in Washington for the
report's release said those tragedies are sobering reminders that
parents and community leaders must pay greater attention to what
children are doing before, during and after school.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Marquis, police chief for the Houston Independent School
District, said too many parents expect schools to be a ``catch
all'' for children, serving not only as places to learn but also to
receive moral guidance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfair to have these expectations of schools,'' said
Marquis, who joined Education Secretary Richard Riley in releasing
the report. The police chief said that moral values should be
taught at home.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-area schools, in the aftermath of the Colorado and
Georgia violence, have taken extraordinary steps to discourage
children from bringing guns to school when classes resume this
month.
</P>
<P>
   For example, HISD prohibits students from carrying firearms,
knives with blades longer than three inches, BB and pellet guns,
replicas of guns, razor blades, utility knives, live ammunition and
laser pens or pointers. Also the HISD police force has created a
Special Response Team of 17 officers who are training in methods to
evacuate schools safely.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby Pasadena Independent School District, students
have 30 days to switch to book bags and backpacks that are
transparent. Pasadena schools will have more and better video
surveillance equipment at all intermediate and high schools; a
standardized dress or uniform policy at all campuses; photo
identification badges at all high schools; and hand-held metal
detectors for use at elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   But safety measures alone are insufficient, Marquis said.
Children disposed to violence must be identified and helped before
they come to school, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to look at this from not just one angle, but all
angles,'' Marquis said. ``It's going to take the community to solve
these problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley praised the federal law for discouraging students from
bringing guns to school but said recent violence on campus
highlights the need for parents and communities to become more
involved in their children's lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that all of us _ parents, educators, students and
all citizens _ can look to this new school year with hope, not with
fear,'' Riley said. ``But more needs to be done and this can only
happen if every community puts its heart and soul into reconnecting
with all of our children. Our schools simply cannot do it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Riley and Marquis at the press conference were school
safety officials from Denver and Atlanta, cities near the suburban
communities of Columbine, Colo., and Conyers, Ga., that were
gripped in school violence this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Ray, security director at Denver Public Schools, and
Karen Hall, a lieutenant at Atlanta Public Schools, echoed the
other officials in calling for greater community involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said the key to preventing school violence is identifying
and treating the ``red-flag'' students prone to violence before
they get to campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes not just law enforcement, but the whole community,''
Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Moments before the Education Department issued its report, an
independent group released a study of student opinions that found a
drop of 7 percent from last year in the number of pupils who said
they always feel safe at school. The group, the Alexandria,
Va-based Horatio Alger Association of Distinguished Americans, also
found an 8 percent decline in the number of students who said they
believe teachers and administrators have taken all necessary steps
to make pupils safe and secure.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials, however, dismissed the group's findings. They
noted that the survey of 1,327 households was conducted between
April 22 and May 25, when the Colorado and Georgia shootings were
fresh in people's minds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
