<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-1500(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POST-COLUMBINE HIGH DRAMAS TAKE ON TEEN ALIENATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ A telling moment in the pilot of the new
series ``Manchester Prep'' involves a handful of pampered
princesses strutting down the middle of the school hallway, bumping
everyone in their path while saying ``move'' in a snooty,
harmonious melody.
</P>
<P>
   Early on in this campy drama, scheduled to premiere this fall on
Fox, it's clear that this is a place of the haves, have-lots and
have-absolutely-everythings. The point: No matter what your social
standing or bank balance, there's always someone perched a rung
higher, looking ``down'' on you _ and snickering.
</P>
<P>
   These are no longer ``Happy Days'' when it comes to high-school
life. Carefree frolicking, easily digestible lessons and mild
sexual banter are passe. ``Manchester Prep'' is just one of a
half-dozen shows coming this fall that are set in high schools and
feature scenes of peer cruelty, psychological torture and
introspective despair. In these shows, the hierarchy of adolescence
is not only well-defined, it takes on a serious, realistic tone.
``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Moesha'' and ``7th Heaven,'' these shows
aren't.
</P>
<P>
   In NBC's new drama ``Freaks and Greeks,'' for instance, a key
character is slammed into the wall while his peers burst into
laughter. In Fox's ``Popular,'' a girl looks at her classmates in
utter disgust, describing them as cattle. ``Look at them. They
dress alike, talk alike, are terrified of having an opinion or
being different because they risk being judged.'' In ``Malcolm in
the Middle,'' also on Fox, a bully trying to flatten his prey
misses, only to hit a boy in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' producer Clyde Phillips is planning an episode in
which a main character's smoke-bomb prank gets out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to pull any punches with this episode,''
Phillips says of the Fox drama. ``We don't mention Columbine
specifically. But there is a line from the principal saying `in
light of recent incidents ...' Just like the title, we want to get
it real.''
</P>
<P>
   How well _ or oddly _ timed.
</P>
<P>
   The world of jocks and nerds, preppies and geeks, artsys and
brainiacs has been under the microscope ever since the murderous
assault in a Colorado high school shed light on the harmful fallout
of cliques, and how teen-age alienation and anger can produce
deadly consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Producers and network executives say the slew of teen-oriented
dramas is their attempt to lure young adults, who have been
successfully courted by the music and movie industries, and by the
WB, with its advertiser-friendly ``Dawson's Creek'' and
``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   With this focus on youth, perhaps it was inevitable that the
Columbine High School tragedy would reverberate through prime time.
But is this a good thing? Can shows be ``too'' realistic?
</P>
<P>
   Whether by economic design or merely by attempting to explore
difficult situations, television now finds itself dramatizing some
of the very issues that were at the core not only of the killings
at Columbine but of shootings in Pearl, Miss.; West Paducah, Ky,;
Jonesboro, Ark.; and Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   The WB Entertainment President Susanne Daniels said the other
day that producer Brenda Hampton is planning several episodes next
season that deal with teen alienation for both ``7th Heaven'' and
her new family series, ``Safe Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our producers are really thinking about this issue,''
Daniels said. ``And I feel we're in the forefront of this with a
series like `Popular.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, ``Popular.'' It's an hourlong drama that explores
acceptance within the teen caste system. It stars Carly Pope
(''Disturbing Behavior'') as Sam, who is navigating the corridors
of the ``in'' crowd. Geeky but pretty under the frizzy hair and
baggy Salvation Army clothes, she's also something of a confused
bird: She wants in but doesn't quite know how to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the gorgeous, tight-sweater-wearing Brooke (Leslie
Bibb), who feels crushed by the pressure to be, well, perfect.
</P>
<P>
   In narration, the girls express disgust and contempt for each
other. It's clear that they are on a collision course; the
collision happens when Sam's mother gets engaged to Brooke's
father, thrusting each into the other's world literally overnight.
</P>
<P>
   While the broad outlines of the basic high-school drama remain
intact, there are significant changes inside the picture.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   In ``Freaks and Geeks,'' Linda Cardellini plays Lindsay Weir,
whose secure life is jolted by the death of her grandmother.
College and career now seem insignificant, and she's being driven
away from her old ``brainy'' clique into the lives of the
``freaks,'' a band of chain-smoking slackers who spend their days
slumped on school benches cursing the prom, sports and other
high-school traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The slackers could easily be Columbine's so-called trench-coat
mafia, and creator and supervising producer Paul Feig admits that
to ring true, the show must be based in reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything,'' he said, ``it just shows me how necessary a
show like this is now, because to make a high-school show and not
show the cliques, and not show that there is labeling in the school
is to literally stick your head in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``And once again, it goes back to what kids want to see; they
won't see a bunch of the most beautiful people in the school
dealing with their problems of who's sleeping with whom. They're
going to watch and say, `Oh, my God, that's me. That's my group.'
''
</P>
<P>
   ``Manchester Prep'' is based on the movie ``Cruel Intentions,''
which was inspired by the novel ``Dangerous Liaisons,'' in which
sex was used as a means of manipulation and greed. A writer for the
series said that the writers had been given a mandate to stay away
from violence, but that everything else was fair game.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she'd had a difficult time in high school, the writer,
Erin Maher, said, ``Are you kidding me? High school was `hell.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Which suggests that these shows can serve as a kind of revenge
of the nerds. Talks with producers of the new series reveal that
almost all considered themselves ``geeks'' in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a writer, you go, `I'm going to right the wrongs of when I
was a kid in school,' '' said Feig of ``Freaks and Geeks.'' ``So
you write with the feeling that if you knew then what you know now,
you would have ruled. You can now snap your finger and make the
other kids look dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean this show will rethink America's schools of hard
knocks, letting the freaks and geeks and nerds win, giving viewers
from those groups a reason for encouragement?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, let's just say that we're not doing `Dawson's Creek,'
where everyone is gorgeous and talks like 30-year-olds,'' said
Feig. ``We want our kids more verbal, more real, and we want them
to be the kids who were always ignored. Will we help or hinder?
Either way, we're at least setting ourselves apart and taking
risks. Isn't that what it's about?''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at (817) 390-7862 or
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
