<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART TURNS DOWN THE VOLUME FOR SUMMER TOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Right now, Ann and Nancy Wilson could be part of one of those
classic-rock-bands-team-up package deals that are the bread and
butter of the summer concert season.
</P>
<P>
   They could be teaming with, say, Cheap Trick, Foreigner, Styx,
REO Speedwagon, Steve Miller or Journey (or any combination
thereof) and playing a best-of-Heart set to thousands of sunburned,
beer-drinking nostalgia-starved baby boomers. It'd be no problem,
really: Go out there, turn up the amps, play an hour or so, and
walk away with a large paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   But that, says Ann Wilson, now 48, would do nothing artistically
for her and her younger sister, Nancy. Such a tour would be nothing
more than the two of them becoming human jukeboxes for a couple of
months.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Wilson sisters are spending the summer in clubs and
theaters armed with nothing but some acoustic instruments and a
host of songs _ old and new _ they really want to play, the way
they really want to play them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing against the bands that do those tours _ they're
buying new houses and sailboats,'' Ann Wilson says with a laugh.
``The offers are so huge. But Nancy and I aren't there in our
minds.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The small-scale acoustic format ``is just the best. We've found
ourselves the best possible situation. We talk about our songs and
laugh and play the songs. We get to show ourselves as artists. And
it's so much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially dubbed ``An Acoustic Evening With Ann and Nancy
Wilson,'' the tour has been going about six weeks. The Wilson
sisters took their music down to this scale to keep it ``fresh,''
Ann says, and because they wanted a change from the big places
where they had played.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in Seattle in 1974, Heart released its first LP,
``Dreamboat Annie,'' the next year; in 1977 they broke nationally
with ``Crazy on You,'' ``Kick It Out'' and the very Led Zeppelinish
``Barracuda,'' all from the multiplatinum ``Little Queen.'' And for
years after that, it was big sales and big arenas. Which started
out fun but ultimately became a grind, Wilson says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about all we've done until the early '90s,'' she says.
``And it was so numbing. We had to work the real estate, as they
say, jumping around and running and stuff to keep the people in the
back rows interested. For teens and rap people that's appropriate,
but as people get older they want more.''
</P>
<P>
   For this tour, the sisters rearranged their best-known songs for
the acoustic format. Some songs, she said, just wouldn't make the
transition from electric to acoustic, but for many others it was
``an easy slide.'' ``Barracuda'' and ``Crazy on You,'' she says,
are now performed with one acoustic guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ```Barracuda' is shockingly different,'' she says. ``But it
works. And now I don't have to scream out those angst-ridden lyrics
like I used to.''
</P>
<P>
   But new, unrecorded material makes up about one-fourth of the
current live set, Wilson says.
</P>
<P>
   One of her favorites at the moment is ``She Still Believes,''
which she says is a true story about a friend who is ``in love with
a man who is completely Mr. Wrong. For seven or eight years she's
been going through this abusive, angry but highly sexual
relationship, and it's tearing her up, but she just keeps hanging
on.''
</P>
<P>
   She's also very fond of a new song called ``Nothing but Love,''
which the sisters wrote with Burt Bacharach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just bold and called him up,'' she says. ``We thought,
`How great it would be to set his lyrics to music and get a great
synthesis of old and new like he got with Elvis Costello.' It's a
very simple song about taking a walk during the day in a city and
seeing love around you and going home alone. It's very cool.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
