<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ATTACK-ART-NYT     08-10 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ATTACK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN SHOT DEAD AFTER HE INJURES 11 ISRAELI TROOPS WITH CAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A Palestinian apparently on a suicide mission plowed
his car twice into a group of Israeli soldiers early Tuesday,
injuring 11 of them before being shot dead by an Israeli policeman.
</P>
<P>
   The attack, in the town of Beit Shemesh, halfway between
Jerusalem and Tel Aviv, came a week after two Jewish settlers in
the West Bank city of Hebron were lightly injured in a drive-by
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the attacks may signal renewal of armed actions by
militant Palestinian groups opposed to peace with Israel, whose new
prime minister, Ehud Barak, has vowed to step up peace efforts with
the Palestinians and Syria. Hamas, the largest such group, called
in July for such a renewal. But it has not claimed responsibility
for either attack and they may well have been uncoordinated,
freelance actions.
</P>
<P>
   Tension was also raised early Tuesday when the Israeli police
sealed a new opening in the outer wall of Al Aksa, the mosque
compound on the ancient man-made plateau above the Western Wall.
Muslim authorities, who had cleared and widened a window in the
wall earlier in the week, said they were renovating the building.
Israeli officials said they suspected that the Muslims were taking
the first step in creating a new entry to the mosque, which would
violate the two sides' agreements on the holy site.
</P>
<P>
   Fears that the Israeli action would lead to demonstrations or
violence prompted the Israelis to increase security around the
mosque and the Old City of Jerusalem but no trouble occurred.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Israeli and Palestinian officials continued
their negotiations on how to proceed with the next phases of their
land-for-security agreement. Representatives of both sides
refrained from harsh statements about both the attack on the
soldiers and the renovation dispute, indicating that relations at
the official level remained steady.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy held talks with
King Abdullah of Jordan in Amman on Tuesday and urged Syria to come
to the negotiating table, saying the time is ripe for Middle East
peace.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tuesday's attack in Beit Shemesh occurred during the morning
rush hour, when soldiers gather at hitch-hiking posts. The
assailant, Akram Alqam, 22, from the West Bank town of Bethlehem,
had no known ties to Hamas or any other group. Palestinian security
officials said he was released six months ago after a year in jail
for car theft and drug dealing.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Fadwa, told The Associated Press that her had son
called her on a cell phone and told her he was going to carry out a
suicide attack. She said that while he had no known ties to Hamas
or any other group, he had spent the past week reading a biography
of Yehya Ayyash, a Hamas bomb maker killed by the Israelis in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses and army officials said Alqam's red Fiat Uno hit two
soldiers and kept on going. Police were called and a chase ensued.
About 10 minutes later, the car returned to the scene traveling
very quickly. It hit more soldiers and crashed into the truck after
a policeman shot Alqam. Most of the soldiers were lightly hurt but
one was in serious condition with a head injury and two others were
also hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   While Israeli security officials said they were surprised that
no group had claimed responsibility for the attack, the chief of
the army's home front command, Maj. Gen. Gabi Ofir, did not
hesitate to call what happened ``an Arab terrorist attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak and other senior Israeli officials refrained from publicly
pointing their fingers at the Palestinian Authority for not doing
enough to stop such attacks. But security officials, speaking on
the condition of anonymity, said recently that such attacks are
rarely spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are either organized or the product of incitement by the
Palestinian leadership,'' one top military official said last week
after the Hebron shooting. ``The Palestinian Authority behaves like
someone who doesn't want to see stability on the ground and can
create instability in many matters.''
</P>
<P>
   In late July, a leaflet was circulated by Hamas threatening to
renew strikes against Israel after a relatively quiet period of
several months. The flyer said, ``The public will be happy to hear
in the near future good news about our Jihad,'' using the Arabic
word for struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Palestinian Authority as the ``autonomous
entity,'' it added, ``The Zionists and their American allies,
together with the autonomous entity intend to destroy the Hamas
leadership. Hamas will not neglect the path of Jihad, whatever
victims it leaves behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamas' support among Palestinians has declined steadily since
Yasser Arafat returned to Gaza in 1994, and now stands at about 20
percent of the population. Israeli security officials say that
whenever peace prospects improve the risk of attacks goes up.
</P>
</TEXT>
