<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2336 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PICNIC-FOODS-LADN     08-10 2127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICNIC-FOODS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(RUNS WITH PICNIC-SEASON)
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) (Resending for Long Beach Press-Telegram) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; RED PEPPER SPREAD &QL; 
1 package (8 ounces) cream cheese, softened &QL; 
1 cup roasted red bell peppers, rinsed and drained (1/2 of a
15-ounce jar) &QL; 
3/4 teaspoon garlic pepper &QL; 
2 teaspoons dried basil &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon garlic powder &QL; 
2 tablespoons red wine vinegar &QL; 
1 tablespoon whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor fitted with a metal blade, process all
ingredients until almost smooth. Keep refrigerated until serving
time. Serve with crackers, fresh vegetable dippers, Italian or
French bread slices, toasted, if desired. Makes about 1 3/4 cups
spread or dip.  &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
ANTIPASTO SALAD &QL; 
This makes an ideal picnic offering when served on a bed of
shredded fresh spinach or lettuce. It is also good wrapped in a
tortilla or pita bread. &QL; 
1/2 cup bottled Italian salad dressing &QL; 
1 teaspoon Dijon mustard &QL; 
3 tablespoons chopped fresh basil &QL; 
3/4 pound sliced Genoa OR other hard salami, cut into thin strips &QL; 
1/2 pound provolone cheese, cut into 1/2-inch cubes &QL; 
1 can (15 1/2 ounces) garbanzo beans (chick-peas), drained &QL; 
3 medium tomatoes, seeded and chopped &QL; 
4 to 6 sun-dried tomatoes packed in oil, cut up &QL; 
1 medium green bell pepper, cut into thin strips &QL; 
1 bunch green onions, thinly sliced &QL; 
1/2 cup ripe olive pieces &QL; 
8 to 10 cups shredded fresh spinach
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix together Italian dressing, mustard and
basil. Add salami, cheese, beans, fresh and sun-dried tomatoes,
green bell pepper, green onions and olives. Toss to mix well.
Refrigerate several hours for flavors to blend. Toss again before
serving. Serve on a bed of spinach or lettuce. Makes 6 to 8
servings. From ``365 Easy One Dish Meals'' by Natalie Haughton,
Harper &AMP; Row. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
SOUTHERN FRIED CHICKEN &QL; 
1 chicken (3 pounds), cut into 8 to 10 portions, OR 12 chicken
drumsticks &QL; 
Salt and freshly ground black pepper &QL; 
2 tablespoons paprika &QL; 
2 tablespoons celery salt &QL; 
2 tablespoons onion powder &QL; 
1 tablespoon dry mustard &QL; 
1 teaspoon cayenne pepper &QL; 
3 large eggs &QL; 
2 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
Vegetable oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   Rinse chicken and pat dry with paper towels. Place in a large
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Mix salt and black pepper to taste, paprika, celery salt, onion
powder, dry mustard and cayenne. Divide into 3 equal portions and
sprinkle one portion over chicken pieces. Toss pieces together so
that each piece gets coated with some os seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Combine seasonings and chicken in a plastic food bag and shake,
if desired. Cover and let stand 45 minutes to 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs in a bowl until light and fluffy. Add 1/3 of
seasonings and beat to combine. Mix remaining 1/3 with flour.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a large, deep, heavy-bottomed skillet or frying pan.
Dip each piece of chicken into egg, then dredge in seasoned flour.
Fry chicken in batches in hot oil about 12 to 14 minutes, or until
each piece is well cooked and golden.
</P>
<P>
   To see if chicken is properly cooked, prick pieces with a
skewer. If clear liquid comes out, this is a sign it is cooked on
inside. Cook remaining chicken. Drain chicken on paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Serve chicken immediately. Or cool all chicken pieces, and then
refrigerate until cold before packing for a picnic. Makes 4 to 6
servings.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``United Tastes of America'' by Dorinda Hafner,
Ballantine Books.  &QL; 
LEMON CAKE &QL; 
1 package (18.2 ounces) pudding included lemon cake mix &QL; 
1 package (3 ounces) lemon-flavored gelatin &QL; 
3 eggs &QL; 
3/4 cup vegetable oil &QL; 
3/4 cup water &QL; 
Lemon Glaze
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl of an electric mixer, combine cake mix and gelatin.
Add eggs, oil and water. Beat at low speed to combine ingredients,
then increase speed to medium and continue beating another 2
minutes. Turn into a 12-cup greased Bundt pan. Bake in preheated
350-degree oven 45 to 50 minutes or until a toothpick inserted in
cake comes out clean. Cool cake in pan 10 minutes; then invert cake
onto a serving plate. While cake is still warm, use a thin skewer
to poke holes over surface of cake. Spoon warm Lemon Glaze over
cake until it is all absorbed. Cool cake. Makes 1 cake.
</P>
<P>
   LEMON GLAZE: Combine 2 tablespoons melted butter with 1 1/2 cups
sifted powdered sugar and 3 to 4 tablespoons fresh lemon juice,
mixing until smooth. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
CALICO SALAD &QL; 
2 cups fresh raw corn kernels &QL; 
1 small green bell pepper, cored, seeded and sliced &QL; 
1 cup thinly sliced celery &QL; 
1 cup diced tomatoes &QL; 
1 teaspoon dried marjoram, crumbled &QL; 
1/2 cup Cucumber Salad Dressing &QL; 
Romaine lettuce &QL; 
1/2 red onion, sliced into very thin rings &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In a salad bowl, combine corn, bell pepper, celery, tomatoes
and marjoram. Toss with Cucumber Salad Dressing and refrigerate
until chilled.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, line 6 plates with romaine lettuce leaves, divide
salad among them and top with onion rings. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CUCUMBER SALAD DRESSING: Place 2 tablespoons white wine vinegar,
1 tablespoon grapefruit juice, 1 tablespoon sugar, 1 teaspoon
freshly minced ginger, 1/4 teaspoon salt and 1 large peeled and
quartered cucumber in a food processor or blender and process until
cucumber is in small pieces.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Corn'' by Patricia Mack, Record Books. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CREAMY CURRY SLAW &QL; 
DRESSING: &QL; 
1 clove garlic, minced &QL; 
1 cup plain yogurt &QL; 
2 tablespoons sugar &QL; 
2 tablespoons cider vinegar &QL; 
1 tablespoon fresh lime OR lemon juice &QL; 
1 teaspoon curry powder OR to taste &QL; 
SALAD: &QL; 
1 large (about 2 1/2 pounds) cabbage, cored and shredded &QL; 
4 carrots, peeled and grated &QL; 
2 cups golden raisins &QL; 
1 bunch green onions, thinly sliced &QL; 
1/2 cup coarsely chopped fresh cilantro &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   For Dressing, in a small bowl, whisk all dressing ingredients
together.
</P>
<P>
   For Salad, in a large bowl, combine cabbage, carrots, raisins,
green onions, 1/2 of cilantro and 1/2 of parsley. Toss with
dressing. Taste and adjust seasonings. Sprinkle with remaining
cilantro and parsley. Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``A Good Day For Salad'' by Louise Fiszer and Jeannette
Ferrary, Chronicle Books.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PENNE SALAD PROVENCAL &QL; 
SALAD: &QL; 
1 pound penne pasta &QL; 
Water &QL; 
8 ounces green beans, cut into 1-inch pieces &QL; 
1 small red onion, cut into 1/4-inch dice &QL; 
1 small zucchini, cut into 1/4-inch dice &QL; 
1 red bell pepper, seeded and cut into 1/4-inch dice &QL; 
1 large ripe tomato, seeded and diced &QL; 
1 cup Nicoise olives, pitted and halved &QL; 
1/4 cup capers, drained and rinsed &QL; 
BASIL VINAIGRETTE: &QL; 
1 cup fresh basil leaves &QL; 
1/2 cup olive oil &QL; 
1/4 cup white wine vinegar &QL; 
2 cloves garlic, minced &QL; 
Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   For Salad, cook penne in boiling water, according to package
directions. Drain and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Cook green beans in salted, boiling water until crisp-tender,
about 4 minutes. Drain under cold water and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine penne, green beans, red onion,
zucchini, red pepper, tomato, olives and capers.
</P>
<P>
   For Basil Vinaigrette, in a food processor or blender, process
all vinaigrette ingredients until smooth. Pour over pasta and toss
well. Taste for salt and pepper. Let salad stand about 2 hours at
room temperature before serving. Taste and adjust seasonings if
necessary. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``A Good Day For Salad'' by Louise Fiszer and Jeannette
Ferrary, Chronicle Books. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
DESSERT DIP &QL; 
2 cups dairy sour cream &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
3/4 cup apricot OR peach preserves &QL; 
Sugar to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine first 3 ingredients in a medium bowl and blend. Sweeten
with sugar and stir to combine.
</P>
<P>
   Chill. Serve with fresh fruit pieces for dipping. Makes about 3
cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Chips, Dips and Salsas'' by Judy Walker and Kim
MacEachern, Northland Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHICKEN APRICOT WITH DIJON ROSEMARY DRESSING &QL; 
4 medium boneless chicken breast halves, seasoned and grilled, then
skinned and cut into bite-size pieces &QL; 
1 cup dried apricot halves &QL; 
1 cup diced celery &QL; 
2 to 3 green onions, minced &QL; 
1/2 cup sliced almonds &QL; 
1/2 cup mayonnaise &QL; 
1 1/2 tablespoons Dijon mustard &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon sugar &QL; 
Salt and white pepper to taste &QL; 
1/4 cup half-and-half OR whipping cream &QL; 
1 1/2 to 2 tablespoons chopped fresh rosemary &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In a large bowl, combine chicken, apricots, celery, green
onions and almonds.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mix together mayonnaise, mustard, sugar, salt,
pepper, half-and-half and rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   Pour over chicken mixture and toss until well blended.
Refrigerate until serving time. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VEGETABLE SANDWICHES &QL; 
18 (1/4-inch) crosswise slices eggplant, peeled if desired &QL; 
Salt &QL; 
Extra virgin olive oil &QL; 
6 round OR long individual serving size sourdough OR French bread
rolls &QL; 
3/4 or a 15-ounce jar roasted red and yellow peppers, drained &QL; 
6 thin large slices smoked mozzarella cheese &QL; 
12 large fresh basil leaves, rinsed, drained and patted dry
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle eggplant slices on both sides with salt; let stand in a
single layer on paper towels 1/2 hour. Press out excess moisture,
rinse and pat dry.
</P>
<P>
   Brush eggplant slices with olive oil and grill over hot coals on
both sides until tender. Split rolls in half horizontally and grill
over hot coals until lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   On bottom half of each grilled roll, place 3 eggplant slices,
then red and yellow peppers, a cheese slice (folded to fit, if
necessary) and 2 basil leaves. Drizzle top half of roll with a
little olive oil and place on top of basil leaves. Return filled
rolls to grill a few minutes just until cheese starts to melt.
(Rolls can also be warmed quickly in microwave oven to melt
cheese.)
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately or wrap and take to a picnic. Makes 6
sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GREEK SALAD SANDWICH WITH OREGANO VINAIGRETTE &QL; 
1 (10-inch) round bread loaf &QL; 
1/2 cup Oregano Vinaigrette &QL; 
2 cups mixed salad greens &QL; 
1 cup (5 ounces) crumbled feta cheese &QL; 
1 English (hothouse) cucumber, thinly sliced &QL; 
2 large tomatoes, thinly sliced &QL; 
1 small red onion, thinly sliced &QL; 
1 small yellow bell pepper, seeded, deveined and thinly sliced
(optional) &QL; 
1/4 cup oil-cured black olives, pitted and coarsely chopped &QL; 
1/4 cup fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   Cut bread in half and scoop out some of soft center. Brush each
half generously with Oregano Vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   In bottom half of bread, arrange greens, cheese, cucumber,
tomatoes, onion, bell pepper, olives and oregano. Place remaining
bread half on top, wrap in plastic wrap and place on a baking
sheet. Set a plate on top of loaf and top with some canned food or
another weight to compress loaf. Refrigerate 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap and take to a picnic. Cut into 6 wedges to serve. Makes 6
servings.
</P>
<P>
   OREGANO VINAIGRETTE: In a blender or food processor, combine 1
tablespoon chopped fresh oregano; 1/4 cup fresh lemon juice; 1/4
cup lemon-infused olive oil OR extra virgin olive oil; 2 garlic
cloves, chopped; 1 tablespoon drained capers; 1 teaspoon salt and 1
teaspoon ground pepper. Process until smooth. Store in an airtight
food container in refrigerator up to 1 week. Makes 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   From ``San Francisco Flavors,'' favorite recipes from The Junior
League of San Francisco, Chronicle Books &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
SANGRIA &QL; 
4 cups orange juice &QL; 
3 bottles dry red wine, preferably an inexpensive fruity Merlot &QL; 
4 oranges, thinly sliced &QL; 
6 lemons, thinly sliced &QL; 
8 limes, thinly sliced &QL; 
3/4 cup sugar OR more to taste &QL; 
Ice cubes
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine all ingredients except ice cubes.
Refrigerate 4 to 6 hours. Taste for sweetness, then add ice. Makes
12 to 16 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``San Francisco Flavors,'' favorite recipes from The Junior
League of San Francisco, Chronicle Books
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CINNAMON-PEACH CAKE &QL; 
1 cup unbleached all-purpose flour &QL; 
1 teaspoon baking powder &QL; 
1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, softened &QL; 
1/2 cup packed light brown sugar &QL; 
1/2 cup plus 3 tablespoons granulated sugar &QL; 
2 large eggs, at room temperature &QL; 
2 1/2 cups ripe peaches (about 3 peaches), peeled and thinly
sliced &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Lightly butter and flour an 8-inch square baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, whisk together flour and baking powder.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, using an electric mixer on high speed, cream
butter, brown sugar and 1/2 cup granulated sugar about 3 minutes
until light and fluffy.
</P>
<P>
   With mixer running on medium speed, add flour mixture to batter,
a little a a time; do not overmix. Beat in eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape batter into prepared pan. Smooth surface and then arrange
sliced peaches on top of batter.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine remaining 3 tablespoons sugar with
cinnamon and sprinkle mixture over peaches.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven about 1 hour or until cake
begins to pull away from sides of pan and turns golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Remove cake from oven and cool in pan on a wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   When completely cool, serve cake directly from pan. Makes 6 to 8
servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Picnics'' by Barbara Scott-Goodman, Chronicle Books. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
