<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2337 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIAN-ADOPTIONS-SPI     08-10 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-ADOPTIONS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN KIDS COME TO U.S. HOMES WHERE LOVE IS THE FIRST LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VLADIVOSTOK, Russia _ ``Papa, papa, papa,'' says Alexey, 6,
hanging on to the man who just became his father: Lamont Crogh.
</P>
<P>
   Crogh is a shop foreman at a lumber mill, and lives in New
Meadows, Idaho. He had never been in the Russian Far East or, for
that matter, outside of North America. ``I don't really like
getting out of the United States,'' he says. ``I wouldn't have done
it for anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Croghs and a group of Americans are celebrating their new
families in a Chinese restaurant. The food is only so-so, and the
music, a raucous Russian disco, is punctuated by an occasional car
alarm from out in the street. But these Americans don't care.
They're celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Crogh, who works as a physical therapist, looks at the
boy's wobbly gait. ``He's a bit weak,'' she says. ``I think he
needs to run around.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Idaho, the Croghs have 12 acres including woods, an
Australian shepherd dog and a pond full of fish. ``It's a great
place for boys,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Alexey, who knows nothing of this, is basking in the excitement
of this big-city restaurant. He wants to get all the attention he
can from his new dad. And he's not the only one: The Croghs also
have just adopted a 1-year-old, Benjamin, so Alexey will have a
brother.
</P>
<P>
   These children are coming from a world of poverty. They take
nothing when they leave. ``You return the clothes, even the
underwear,'' says Connie Crogh.
</P>
<P>
   But the parents have only good words for the Russians they have
met. The orphanages they saw did not mistreat or grossly neglect
the children, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Lamont Crogh was still thinking about the director of Alexey's
orphanage making just $50 per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people here are trying so hard,'' he says. ``It just
makes you appreciate what you've got.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents have arranged their adoptions through a Seattle
agency, the World Association for Children and Parents. Barbara
Knowles, assistant director, says the agency has found parents for
7,000 children since 1975, and has helped with feeding programs for
hundreds of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The Croghs got their children in about six months. ``Families
that apply to adopt a boy child, or an older child, or a child with
special needs, will wait the shortest amount of time,'' Knowles
says.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilson family applied to adopt all three types. On this day,
Taylor and Jennifer Wilson of American Fork, Utah, have adopted
three children: Ekaterina, 7, her brother Dmitry, 6, and Maxim, 10
months. Maxim, not related to the other two, has a cleft palate, a
birth defect that would not be fixed in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilsons are a child-oriented family: they have five of their
own. Taylor and Jennifer both work at home, he for a 3-D graphics
company and she as a homemaker. They decided at Christmas that they
would adopt from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer, who has relatives who came to Russia as Mormon
missionaries, says, ``When we heard about the conditions the kids
lived in, it really touched our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   The two older kids, nicknamed Katya and Dima, are finishing
their food and have already learned their first English: ``More,
please'' and ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Katya cleans her plate a second time, and Taylor spoons more
food. He says to Jennifer, ``We need to stop asking if they want it
and just give it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinner finished, the parents and kids go outside for group
photos. Nearby, three uniformed soldiers watch curiously, spitting
the shells of watermelon seeds.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Vladivostok seems a dream. Back in Utah, Katya
and Dima ``have learned how to get along with the family,'' says
Taylor Wilson. The most difficult time, he says, was in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Each has made a special friend with the Wilson child closest to
his age. ``You can tell that once the language barrier is gone, it
will be just as if they were born into the family,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilsons have made friends with a couple who speak Russian,
in hopes that Katya and Dima have someone to speak Russian with.
Already they're mixing in words and phrases from English. It is
likely that they will lose their Russian entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The baby, Maxim, ``had a hard time figuring out that being held
is a good thing,'' Taylor Wilson says. He is getting used to it;
and on July 30 he went in for surgery to mend his lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went great,'' says Taylor Wilson. ``He's able to say things
like, `Mama, Mama,' by putting his lips together that he couldn't
do before.'' Surgeons will close the hole in the palate in about
two months.
</P>
<P>
   In Idaho, Alex is squirting water at the dog _ a big step for
him. ``He was panic-stricken when he first saw the dog,'' Connie
Crogh says. ``He was climbing up on the table. He thought his life
was over.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy had never had any experience with pet dogs, or any
similar animals.
</P>
<P>
   Nor with a supermarket. ``Every step it's, `Mama, mama. Look at
this!''' Crogh says. ``He sees a bag of carrots, and he says,
`Ohhhh.'''
</P>
<P>
   Alex won't eat much bread or meat. ``He will inhale any fresh
vegetable or fruit. He likes ice cream,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And as for the wobbly gait, she says, ``That's improving,
definitely. He's getting some muscles in his legs.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his behavior, she says, ``He has tried a few little
naughty things just to see what we'd do, but he backs down right
away. He aims to please.''
</P>
<P>
   And she is pleased. ``I'm having a blast,'' she says. Her
biggest worry is going back to work after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   But, she says, ``It's only half time.''
</P>
<P>
   WACAP, the World Association for Children and Parents, can be
reached at 206-575-4550. Its address is P.O. Box 88948, Seattle WA
98138.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
