<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2353 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROBES-IN-EARTH-NYT     08-10 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROBES-IN-EARTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO HELL AND BACK: FINDING LIFE IN THE DEPTHS OF OUR PLANET  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    FOUR COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 By KEVIN KRAJICK  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Four scientists wearing coveralls and hard hats shuffle warily
into a steel cage the size of a closet, cramming themselves against
a dozen miners.
</P>
<P>
   The doors clang shut, and the group plunges hundreds of stories
down into the darkness _ No. 5 Shaft in South Africa's East
Driefontein gold mine. The goal: to find living microbes living
deep in the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments the air becomes oppressively hot. This is one of
the farthest-reaching excavations in the world, burrowing more than
two miles toward the center of Earth.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of the mine, radioactivity and heat from the
planet's core raise the temperature of the stone in the tunnels to
a searing 120 F, and the atmospheric pressure is double that on the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen rarely exists naturally so far underground, and only a
constant rush of forced air from the surface disperses poisonous
methane and hydrogen seeping from the rock. Pumped-in jets of water
help keep workers from slowly cooking to death.
</P>
<P>
   Geologist T.C. Onstott, a Princeton professor, pulls a water
bottle from his knapsack and takes a swig. To him, the heat and
claustrophobia are merely aggravation. Real worry for the team of
scientists, as well as the miners, centers on ``seismic events'' _
high-pressure cave-ins that kill.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to obtain samples from wells that have not been
contaminated by air or water from the surface. Onstott decided he
had to find a way to visit the microbes himself. The mine he chose
to explore is part of a sprawling manmade underworld started on a
Sunday morning in 1886 when an Australian prospector found a
gold-rich outcrop on the present site of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   Like a nose peeping out of the covers, that outcrop was just the
start. Since then, three-quarters of the gold ever mined has come
out of the region. The most recent shaft at East Driefontein took
15 years to excavate _ and that was just the vertical hole.
</P>
<P>
   For his journey into this biosphere, Onstott rounded up an
all-star crew of microbiologists. They included: Bill Ghiorse, who
led Environmental Protection Agency research into subsurface
bacteria that eat toxic waste; Duane Moser, a lab wizard and avid
spelunker; Svetlana Kotelnikova, a Russian scientist working in
Sweden; Mary DeFlaun of Envirogen, an environmental technology
firm; and Jim Fredrickson, who has isolated many deep-bacteria
cultures while working at the Pacific Northwest National
Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   At East Driefontein, Onstott and his team would spend three
months gathering samples at a depth where no microbe hunters had
ventured before: The No. 5 Shaft bottoms out at 11,222 feet.
</P>
<P>
   On this scouting mission, the elevator slowly comes to a halt at
6,120 feet and the researchers walk through a short tunnel to a
second elevator that takes them to the mine's deepest diggings. At
the bottom, the group boards a miniature train for a half-mile ride
through the dark as a giant air pipe roars overhead.
</P>
<P>
   The train stops at a dark hole in the wall: the stope, or mining
face. The passage dips down at a steep angle; in many sections the
ceiling is only three feet high.
</P>
<P>
   The stope swarms with miners. Drills, saws and jackhammers roar
so loudly that hand signals must be used. Amid the pandemonium, the
scientists find their objective: a black coal-like vein interwoven
with round stones and sparkly filaments.
</P>
<P>
   This mineral-rich seam is dubbed the carbon leader. Often no
more than a finger wide, sandwiched in a mass of ancient quartzite,
the carbon leader is heavily laced with uranium and holds an
extraordinary concentration of gold.
</P>
<P>
   No one is certain how the carbon leader formed. It could be the
remains of either algae that settled on an ancient sea bottom or
oil that shot through a crack underground. In any case, the rock
formation is loaded with carbon compounds potentially nutritious to
microbes.
</P>
<P>
   Strong evidence that microbes could survive in an even more
austere environment was uncovered in 1995, when a team working at
the Department of Energy's Hanford Reservation in Washington found
rock-eating organisms that get their sustenance from elemental
mineral energy sources.
</P>
<P>
   The microbes were taken from groundwater sitting in igneous
basalt 4,500 feet down. In a series of lab experiments,
microbiologist Todd Stevens of Pacific Northwest National
Laboratory showed that basalt may react with groundwater to release
hydrogen.
</P>
<P>
   The microbes combine the hydrogen with carbon dioxide in the
water to make organic compounds. Their main waste product is
methane _ a natural gas long thought to be formed mainly near the
surface by swamp-dwelling microbes, and in the depths of Earth by
nonbiological chemical reactions.
</P>
<P>
   But eating is only half the equation. Like us, many bacteria
must respire _ combine food with some other substance to release
energy. Our respiratory agent is oxygen, a byproduct of plant
photosynthesis.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen is rare below ground, where microbiologists have found
organisms that breathe an astounding variety of alternatives:
ferric iron, sulfate, nitrate, nitrite, uranium and carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   In rocks Onstott gathered on a 1996 visit to another South
African mine, microbiologists Jim Fredrickson and Tom Kieft
discovered a heat-resistant bacterium that inhales iron, nitrate,
manganese, sulfur, chromium, cobalt and oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   At East Driefontein, Onstott planned to gather more samples to
test a hypothesis that some deep bacteria extract energy from
elements released as byproducts of the natural radioactivity of the
rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, crouched before the carbon leader, he reaches out and
touches the seam with a Geiger counter.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a drill starts up somewhere, shaking the place like an
earthquake. Rock fragments bounce off helmets. The group of
researchers moves on, looking for a safer spot.
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred feet down, they come upon a newly blasted section
of tunnel where miners are shoving steel hydraulic jacks called
rock props against the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good!'' Onstott hollers. ``Means it's fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Moser pulls out a ball peen hammer and a sterilized chisel and
pounds at the crumbly ore. When he is done, Onstott _ with precious
samples in hand _ and his fellow scientists finally smile. They
climb slowly down the stope to another railroad tunnel and begin
hiking out.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, Onstott's team were in for a surprise: Some stones
appeared to house between 100,000 and 1 million microbes per gram.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's 100 times what we expected,'' Onstott says.
</P>
<P>
   The team's trove also included mine-water samples containing
rod-shaped microbes six times the size of many surface microbes.
Some of the bugs breathe iron; some live on methane. Others might
eat hydrogen freed when radiation breaks down water molecules.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists even speculate that some of the deep microbes may
have deposited the filigree of gold in the East Driefontein mine.
</P>
<P>
   It's all in a day's work for scientists who search for life that
exists in the world miles below us.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Kevin Krajick is a reporter for Discover magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
