<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2367 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUPFISH-IN-PERIL-NYTS     08-10 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUPFISH-IN-PERIL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUPFISH IN PERIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 By KAREN WRIGHT  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The water is warm and deep and clear. Four scuba divers splash
in, signal the go-ahead, and then slip below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   As they drift down, the sunlight transforms the bright hues of
their gear into a moving palette. Then the swimmers are lost from
sight.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a scene from ``Sea Hunt'' _ except that the divers
have plunged into a bottomless hole in the heart of the Mojave
Desert, more than 200 miles from the nearest ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion is the semiannual pupfish count in Ash Meadows,
Nev., a 24,000-acre oasis of clay dunes, spring-fed pools, and
plants and animals found nowhere else in the world.
</P>
<P>
   On this morning in late March, representatives of the National
Park Service, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and the Nevada
Division of Wildlife have gathered to assay the fortunes of an
animal that lives here, in what is perhaps the most restricted and
isolated environment occupied by any fish anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   That environment is Devils Hole, a limestone cave filled
year-round with warm water that flows up from an underground
aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   It's the pupfish that draw the divers and their retinue twice
yearly. To the untrained eye, the Devils Hole pupfish, Cyprinodon
diabolis, is an unremarkable creature: It looks like a stout, steel
blue minnow.
</P>
<P>
   To knowledgeable observers, the fish is a prime example of
evolution _ and possibly extinction _ in action.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 10,000 years, the Devils Hole pupfish has adapted
to increasingly extreme conditions as post-Ice Age climate changes
have shrunk its habitat from a sizable lake to the ecological
equivalent of a kiddie pool.
</P>
<P>
   With their thermal sources and arid environs, desert springs
have some of the highest temperatures, greatest salt concentrations
and lowest oxygen contents of any fish habitat.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils Hole pupfish and other pupfish species that were
stranded in the Mojave by receding waters have developed unique
physiological mechanisms to cope with these pressures.
</P>
<P>
   But pupfish still need water, however salty, stagnant or hot.
And for the Devils Hole pupfish, that resource has been further
threatened since the late 1960s, when pumping from nearby springs
for farm irrigation began to deplete the underground water supply
that feeds the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, then, that C. diabolis is classified as an
endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, after a contest pitting developers and state
supremacists against federal statutes and conservationists, the
U.S. Supreme Court ruled that protecting the pupfish from an
unnatural extinction also meant protecting its home. In particular,
the court ruled that water levels in Devils Hole must be kept high
enough to top an algae-covered rock shelf at the mouth of the cave
where the fish do most of their feeding and spawning.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the ruling, development in the area was halted,
and in 1984 the Ash Meadows National Wildlife Refuge was
established.
</P>
<P>
   Desert-fish advocates have long felt the need to keep tabs on
the imperiled pupfish population itself. Scuba-diving biologist
Stan Hillyard of the University of Nevada at Las Vegas has been
counting pupfish for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   This year, as in most others, he accompanies his fellow divers
about 80 feet down the hole, to a flat shelf called Anvil Rock,
then begins a slow ascent.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing each other up a staircase of ledges that can't be seen
from the surface, Hillyard and a colleague use waterproof tablets
to tally the fish. The other two members of the group are certified
cave divers who watch over the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Devils Hole is a notoriously dangerous place to dive: Despite
expeditions down 400 feet and more by the U.S. Geological Survey,
no one has ever found the bottom of the cave, and at least two
people have died here during recreational dives (which are no
longer permitted). Their bodies were never found.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, safe on dry land, National Park Service biologist
Doug Threloff supervises the surface count. This involves crouching
over the spawning shelf and staring through half a foot of water
and algae to enumerate fish that look exactly like other fish
you've already counted and which, because they refuse to keep
still, may in fact be other fish you've already counted.
</P>
<P>
   It's an imprecise science. When the divers reappear about 40
minutes later, the surface and submarine counts are added for a
total of 196. A second count in the afternoon, using the same
procedures, yields a sum of just 182.
</P>
<P>
   Threloff is troubled by the numbers, which have been low for the
past two years. The population tends to build over the summer as
fry hatch on the shelf, so fall counts are usually higher.
</P>
<P>
   In good years, more than 500 fish have thrived in a Devils Hole
autumn. But it's not clear just how low the spring count can go
without jeopardizing the pupfish's seasonal rebound and long-term
survival.
</P>
<P>
   Directly or indirectly, almost all of the Ash Meadows endemics
rely on fossil water stored in underground basins since the end of
the last Ice Age. The springwater in Devils Hole is known to be at
least 8,000 years old, and Threloff worries that it may never
return to its pre-pumping level.
</P>
<P>
   Farms and mining operations to the north could still be
depleting the Ash Meadows supply, albeit slowly, as they draw more
water than is replaced by the region's meager rain and snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   The most tangible evidence of that depletion would show up at
Devils Hole, where water levels have in fact been dropping again
since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the pupfish is a kind of canary in a coal mine for all the
plants and animals in Ash Meadows. As such, it has a sorry song to
sing.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the fish repeat the trick by which our ancestors crawled
out of the sea and onto land, they could perish along with their
jewel blue pool.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the edge of that pool, with the spring sun hinting
at summer's heat, it's not hard to imagine how the underground
oasis at Devils Hole might one day become a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Karen Wright is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
