<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2369 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARAGUAY-ARCHIVE-2TAK     08-10 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARAGUAY-ARCHIVE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAGUAY'S `ARCHIVES OF TERROR' DETAIL YEARS OF REPRESSION 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay _ When Martin Almada asked a judge for
records of his arrest under the dictatorship of General Alfredo
Stroessner, he hoped merely to learn more about his own private
tragedy: nearly four years of captivity, during which police
telephoned his wife so she would hear his screams under torture.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Almada, a one-time school teacher, and the judge
unearthed a mountain of records detailing repression among
U.S.-backed military regimes throughout South America during the
Cold War. From floor to ceiling, five tons of reports and photos
detailed the arrest, interrogation and disappearance of thousands
of political prisoners during Stroessner's 35-year dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   The documents trace the creation and work of Operation Condor, a
secret plan among security forces in six countries to crush
left-wing political dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguayans quickly nicknamed the files the ``archives of
terror.'' Though discovered in 1992, the files have gained new
prominence throughout Latin America with the arrest of Chile's
former dictator, Gen. Augusto Pinochet, in London last October. To
this day, they remain the only extensive collection of public
records of a project by the region's military rulers that succeeded
in exterminating thousands of political opponents, many of whom had
sought sanctuary in one another's countries.
</P>
<P>
   The files have given a kind of vindication to survivors, their
families and the families of those dead and missing, by delivering
concrete proof of a secretive era that might otherwise be lost in
the ether of memory and denial.
</P>
<P>
   The archives have also provided fodder for the developing case
against Pinochet, the only one of the region's dictators to face
the prospect of trial. Stroessner remains a fugitive in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Baltazar Garzon, the Spanish magistrate seeking the extradition
of Pinochet from England, has collected more than 1,500 pages of
evidence from the archives. Last December, he requested records on
Bolivia's current President, Hugo Banzer, who ran the military
regime there from 1971 to 1978, and on Stroessner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This documentation might exist in other countries as well, but
it's hidden, while in Paraguay they didn't manage to hide it all,''
Juan Garces, the lawyer who brought the suit against Pinochet, said
in a telephone interview from Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proves that there was an organization with a structure and
discipline that didn't only exchange information but committed
criminal acts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence sharing between Washington's allies in South
America did not begin with Operation Condor, but the plan
formalized and deepened cooperation among police and military
forces that had taken power in six countries _ Brazil, Argentina,
Chile, Paraguay, Uruguay and Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   After Gen. Manuel Contreras of Chile invited security chiefs to
create ``the basis of an excellent coordination and improved
action'' at a meeting in November 1975, police from member
countries began to operate in each others' jurisdictions. Their new
ties allowed security officials to participate in joint
interrogations, to pursue nationals across borders and to order
surveillance on citizens who sought asylum in other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Trained during the Cold War at the School of the Americas in
Panama, the officials viewed their enemy as Communism, backed by
Moscow in a subversive war without frontiers. To prevail,
governments, too, would have to work across borders, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The security threats were not entirely imagined. Armed rebels
like the Montoneros in Argentina did aim to destabilize some
governments. But in other countries there were no rebel movements,
and military regimes used the club of anti-Communism to snuff out
any calls for democracy or labor rights.
</P>
<P>
   In Chile, Pinochet had overthrown the democratically elected
president, Salvador Allende Gossens, a Socialist, and hunted down
his Cabinet officials and supporters. Among them was Orlando
Letelier, the Chilean ambassador to the United States who was
killed when his car exploded on a street in Washington; his
American aide, Ronni Moffitt, also was killed.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1979 Senate Foreign Relations Report, which
remains classified, the killings in Argentina of Gen. Carlos Prats
of Chile and Gen. Juan Jose Torres of Bolivia were also reportedly
the work of Operation Condor, as was the attempted assassination of
a Chilean senator, Bernardo Leighton, in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In Paraguay, the targets of Stroessner included members of a
rival faction in the governing Colorado Party, doctors who refused
to cover up torture and Almada, who had criticized the educational
system in his doctoral dissertation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I was an intellectual terrorist,'' Almada said. He
blames Paraguayan police for the death of his 33-year-old wife, who
suffered a heart attack and died after hearing his screams over the
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Two of the thousands of cases contained in the archives are
those of Gladys Sannemann and Augustin Goiburu, physicians in
Asuncion who refused to falsify an autopsy to show that a man
beaten to death under police custody in 1958 had died of natural
causes. Instead, Sannemann took the cadaver to her medical school
in Asuncion and performed a proper autopsy before her students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practically from that moment it began,'' said Sannemann, an
immunologist who is now 69 and practicing here in Asuncion. The
challenge marked her out for the Stroessner regime.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking safety, Sannemann and her husband, Rodolfo Jorge, fled
to Brazil in 1963, a year before the military seized power there,
and then moved to Argentina. But in March 1976, the military took
power in Argentina as well, making Sannemann and other exiles
targets of the new regime.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the coup, Argentine police abducted Sannemann and
tortured her at the Escuela Mecanica in Buenos Aires. Sannemann
said she was bound and plunged into a bathtub of vomit and
excrement, in a torture nicknamed ``the submarine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They accused me of killing a patient in my office,'' Sannemann
said, calling the charge ``a total lie.'' Then police falsely
accused her of selling drugs, she recalled. ``They said anything
that occurred to them,'' she said. A week later, Sannemann's
husband was abducted and tortured as well.
</P>
<P>
   Sannemann landed at the Emboscada camp for political prisoners
in Paraguay, where she treated more than 400 fellow prisoners from
several South American countries, including widows whose husbands
had been executed _ to silence them _ and their children .
</P>
<P>
   Sannemann and her husband were eventually given asylum in
Germany in 1997, after the German government pressured Argentina
for their release.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Goiburu, who also refused to whitewash torture,
remained a mystery until the archives were opened. In 1977, Goiburu
was kidnapped from a street in Missiones, an Argentine town where
he had gone to escape the Stroessner regime. The government
steadily denied any knowledge of Goiburu's disappearance to his
wife, ElbaElisa Benitez de Goiburu.
</P>
<P>
   The archives, however, contained surveillance reports and photos
of the doctor's house and office, and showed that eliminating him
had become a priority for Stroessner. In a bitterly comic twist,
one effort to kidnap Goiburu collapsed after the Paraguayans balked
at the price Argentine agents demanded for the job, according to
documents in the archive.
</P>
<P>
   Stroessner declined repeated requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Goiburu said she has no doubt that it was Condor that had
swooped down to persecute her family and eventually to take her
husband's life, though he has never been found.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The archives do not detail Washington's role in Cold War
repression here. Along with documents surfacing elsewhere, however,
they suggest U.S. officials backed Condor nations not only with
military aid, but with information. Last month, the United States
declassified 20,000 pages of documents from the Cold War era,
mostly involving Chile. Some of them have made their way to Garzon.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The archives here show that a U.S. military official, Col.
Robert Thierry, apparently helped design the apparatus of the
police state, as he trained police for the Technical Section soon
after Stroessner seized power here in 1954. A relative, Margaret
Van Skike, located in Galveston, Texas, said that Thierry died
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the FBI released a document confirming that
it had provided the Pinochet regime with information about Jorge
Isaac Fuentes de Alarcon, the leader of a leftist movement in Chile
who, the archives here show, was first seized and interrogated by
Paraguayan agents. FBI officers checked addresses in the United
States found in Fuentes' personal phone book, and gave the results
and information on Fuentes' questioning in Paraguay to the Pinochet
regime. Fuentes later disappeared under Chilean custody.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The archives here include friendly letters, law enforcement
magazines and books from the FBI to Paraguayan police officials
whose human rights records had come under fire even then.
</P>
<P>
   In one letter, FBI Director Clarence Kelley wishes Pastor
Coronel, the long-time head of the Department of Investigations who
is now serving a 25-year sentence for torture, ``a truly joyous
Christmas and a New Year filled with all the good things you so
richly deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley died two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The archives also shed light on the killing of Letelier, the
ambassador, in Washington. Two weeks before the assassination,
Contreras, the Chilean colonel, requested $600,000 from the
Pinochet government for ``the neutralization of the governing
junta's principal adversaries overseas, especially in Mexico,
Argentina, Costa Rica, the United States, France and Italy'' in a
memo.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the FBI defended the information sharing with
Chile as standard practice among law enforcement agencies of
governments friendly to Washington. A State Department spokesman
declined to comment on the record of U.S. cooperation with the
South American dictatorships, saying it was ``ancient history.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the archives in 1992, coming as Paraguayans
tackled their first democratic presidential elections, brought
euphoria at first.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the trove spread, victims of the dictatorship flocked
to the police station at Lambare, some 15 miles outside the
capital. Mrs. Goiburu sought word about her husband. Sannemann came
in disbelief. Gloria Estrago, a former political prisoner, felt as
if she had stumbled onto ``the Vatican's secret treasures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like finding our comrades alive again, like
something from science fiction,'' said Ms. Estrago, who is now a
judge.
</P>
<P>
   When she saw the files, Ms. Estrago said she imagined an old
friend who had vanished in police custody, Mario Sher Prono,
calling out to her now, saying, ``Here's proof of what happened to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many activists, early exhilaration has given way to
disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   Upon discovery of the archives, they complain, journalists,
police, and even victims like Almada hauled away cartons of
records. Key documents published in newspapers days after their
discovery vanished from the archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt they have been sanitized,'' Ms. Palau said.
</P>
<P>
   The archives, at least now, contain no direct accounts of
tortures or deaths, only of prisoners who police arrested but never
released, and formulaic confessions that say nothing about the
methods used to obtain them. Gaps in the sequences of numbered
letters from the FBI suggest missing correspondence. And the
archives do not address the military's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Only five officials here have been convicted for torturing and
killing Paraguayans who challenged the Stroessner dictatorship.
None have apologized for their acts or broken the security forces'
code of silence. Nobody has said where the bodies are buried.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Goiburu said the present government has pressured her to
drop efforts to find her husband's killer, as well as a lawsuit
against Stroessner for her husband's disappearance. Recently,
Paraguay's new president, Luis Gonzalez Macchi, dismissed her from
her job representing the Ministry of Education and Culture in a
national professional association, and Mrs. Goiburu said she has
been warned not to challenge the move.
</P>
<P>
   The dictatorship is over, the widow said, but the reflexes of
terror linger on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
