<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: To bolster your coverage of the latest upheaval in
Russia's political world, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
these timely articles from Moscow News:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KREMLIN GAMBLES on PUTIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Yevgeny Krasnikov &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Although Moscow's latest Monday massacre _ the firing of Prime
Minister Sergei Stepashin and the entire Cabinet _ was a shock in
the West, for several weeks now in Russia, the media have been
citing the name of Vladimir V. Putin, 46, as a new political
favorite. Since Yevgeny Primakov was abruptly dismissed as prime
minister three months ago, top Kremlin officials have been saying
that Stepashin was destined to become Yeltsin's successor. But
Naina Yeltsin, the president's wife, among others, has been
actively trying to persuade Yeltsin to choose Putin. Yevgeny
Krasnikov is political correspondent for Moscow News. (slugged:
BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-SURPRISE -NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARSENIC for DESSERT? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Tamara Zlotnikova &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In six months, Russia is supposed to begin full-scale
destruction of its chemical weapons, according to the Treaty on the
Prohibition of the Development, Production, Stockpiling and Use of
Chemical Weapons and Their Destruction. But there is no money in
the treasury to do so. It was claimed that without the treaty,
Russia's international prestige would suffer and economic sanctions
would be slapped on us. If, however, it was ratified, supposedly
the international community would pick up much of the tab for the
destruction of our chemical weapons. That is not happening. Tamara
Zlotnikova is head of the Committee for Ecology in the State Duma
of Russia. (slugged: BC-RUSSIA-CHEMICAL-WEAPONS -NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   ........................
</P>
