<P>
   Much of what the articles had to say I already knew. I've been
writing about my community for years. What I appreciated was that
the Newsweek writers managed to put together a package of articles
designed to inform a wider readership of a significant social and
cultural trend _ that's what the news business is supposed to do _
while speaking directly, and sensitively, to the very community
that the articles were about _ U.S. Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   In the articles, America's so-called mainstream readers learn
that 83 percent of Latinos polled by Newsweek said that ``being
Hispanic was important to their identity''; that ``42 percent go to
church once a week''; and that the community is ``an increasingly
unpredictable political force: 37 percent of 18- to 34-year-old
Latinos say they are independent, about twice as many as their
Hispanic elders.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being pithy and polished, these are facts that are
relevant to the community at large.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek readers also are told that ``Hispanics are clustered in
11 states, with a total of 217 out of the 270 Electoral College
votes'' needed to win the presidency. That explains the ``Me llamo
Al'' (my name is Al) and ``Me llamo Jorge'' (my name is George)
speeches we've been hearing lately on the campaign trail from Al
Gore and George W. Bush, the respective Democrat and Republican
front-runners for their presidential nomination of their parties.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the article also does a respectable job of balancing these
celebratory factoids against the sobering reality that many
Hispanics face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Latinos are assimilated into cycles of urban blight; 40
percent of Latino children now live in poverty, the highest rate
ever'' Newsweek reported. And the magazine reminds us that ``not
everybody has been eager to give Latinos a big abrazo''
(affectionate hug). (The sprinkling of a few Spanglish phrases was
a nice touch.)
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek also did a good job of explaining the multicultural
makeup of U.S. Latinos by featuring quotes and vignettes about
Cubans, Mexican Americans, Dominicans, Puerto Ricans, Colombians
and other Latino ethnic groups. Until I read the article, for
instance, I did not know that Soledad O'Briens Cuban-born mother is
black, and her father is Irish-Australian.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek, of course, is not perfect. Latino readers,
particularly Latino writers, must have winced when they saw the
word ``illegals'' in print _ even if the paragraph that included it
was meant to condemn such stereotypes. So-called illegal or
undocumented immigrants, in almost all cases, are people accused of
violating civil statutes. They are not criminals. The term
``illegals'' also dehumanizes. It's a lot like calling the mentally
ill ``lunatics.''
</P>
<P>
   As for George magazine's attempt to document the expanding role
of Latinos in American politics, I think I now understand why the
magazine is faltering. While I suspect that John F. Kennedy Jr.'s
heart was in the right place when he and his staff set out to put
together ``Latin Heat!'' I couldn't help but wonder if the
magazine's editors weren't tapping their feet to Los Lobos'
rendition of the catchy folk-turned-pop-rock-standard. ``Para
bailarla bamba. Para bailarla bamba.''
</P>
<P>
   George's saving grace would have been its generally well-written
and insightful profile of the Mexican-born actress Salma Hayak, if
it hadn't been for story's garish headline, ``Mexican
Firecracker.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexy photos of Hayak abound, but we also learn she has a knack
for business, and more than a few choice thoughts about domestic
and foreign politics.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, I think Bob Morris, the writer who penned the Hayak
piece, might have been better off selling the story to Newsweek.
These days, at least, Newsweek seems to have a better accent.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Garcia is editor and publisher of Politico, a national weekly
newsletter on U.S. Latino politics. He can be reached by e-mail at
Politico1(AT)aol.com. The word AT in parentheses has been used in
this E-mail address instead of the symbol, which cannot be
interpreted by many newspaper computer systems.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
