<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-COMEBACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FISH STOCKS OFF NEW ENGLAND REBOUNDING, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The gray sole, a traditionally valued flounder called
witch flounder in the Gulf of Maine, has almost completely
rebounded from near-extinction thanks to strict limits on catching
the species, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   The sole is just one of the many troubled Northeast fish that
appear to be on the mend, according to a report on fisheries
released Tuesday. The independent scientific panel indicates
improvements in a dozen commercially valuable and regulated stock,
including yellowtail flounder and sea scallops.
</P>
<P>
   But the tight fishing restrictions probably won't be lifted
anytime soon, the report said, because the stocks of some fish,
such as the Gulf of Maine cod and white hake, still remain at
record low stock levels.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Fisheries Management Council is scheduled to
discuss the report and its implications for future management at a
public meeting Wednesday in Hyannis.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, there have been a wave of fishing restrictions
imposed by the council to help nature replace the fast depleting
fish populations. In 1994, officials closed nearly 6,000 square
miles of fishing ground on Georges Bank, and a series of closures
for the Gulf of Maine started in 1997. In June a portion of the
banks was reopened for scallop fishing only. Scallop stock is at
its highest level since 1982, according to Andrew Applegate, senior
biologist for the New England Fishery Management Council.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Fisheries Management Council also voted to
increase the size of mesh on groundfishermen's nets, which allowed
smaller, younger fish to escape and grow to reproductive maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Applegate said overall the regulations appear to be working,
with the stock of the troubled fish doubling since 1994. The
council projects that the fish populations should be completely
rebuilt within the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   For two species, the Georges Bank yellowtail flounder and
Southern New England winter flounder, more fishing can be allowed
because the population has recovered so well, with more than 90
percent of the target population for both species, said Applegate.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, cod has not fared as well. The stock Gulf of Maine
cod is near record lows, though officials hope it will improve with
reduced catches this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Additional efforts are needed to promote rebuilding for Gulf
of Maine cod to reach objectives,'' said Applegate, which may
include more restrictions for fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   The cod depletion is still too high, he said, even though the
rate at which they are dying is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Along Georges Bank, Applegate said, cod population has been
increasing every year, even though rebuilding prospects have been
poor because the number of young fish surviving has been low.
Scientists project that it will still take at least seven to eight
years to rebuild the cod population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fishing control for Georges Bank has been more effective than
for the Gulf of Maine,'' said Applegate.
</P>
<P>
   The Georges Bank haddock is showing some promise, Applegate
said. Although haddock has only reached 43 percent of its target
population, the 1998 class appears to be the largest in 20 years,
enabling stock recovery to be more quickly than previously though.
Haddock is at its highest stock levels since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Despite increasing fish populations, the council warns that
restrictions are still necessary to rebuild stocks to long-term
sustainable levels. The council will make final decisions about how
to manage the fisheries in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
