<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2399 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GET-RICH-QUICK-NYTSF &LR;      08-10 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GET-RICH-QUICK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 MARGARET, WILL YOU MARRY ME? (P.S. I'm NOT GREEDY)  
 &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When I was growing up in a nice, relatively safe, lower-middle
class neighborhood of tidy bungalows, concrete porches, one-car
garages and backyard patios half the size of an NBA free-throw
lane, we had very specific definitions of what it meant to be rich.
</P>
<P>
   If your dad bought a new Lincoln Continental or Cadillac Coupe
de Ville every two years, you were rich.
</P>
<P>
   If your family took an airplane on vacations to exotic locales
such as Orlando rather than squeezing everybody sausage-style into
a wood-paneled station wagon for a drive to the Wisconsin Dells,
you were rich.
</P>
<P>
   If people in your family golfed, you were rich.
</P>
<P>
   If you had a color TV with remote control and your driveway was
paved, you were rich.
</P>
<P>
   If each kid in your family had his or her own bedroom, you were
rich.
</P>
<P>
   And if you had a built-in swimming pool in your backyard, well,
you were practically dripping money.
</P>
<P>
   In this tiny corner of the world, the families of dentists and
doctors and lawyers were our Rockefellers and Kennedys and DuPonts.
We didn't know from millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   But almost everybody had a story about how the family could have
been seriously, filthy rich, if only Grandpa or Uncle Freddy or
Great-Aunt Minnie had made the right move in 1893 or 1914 or 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Like my buddy Shemp _ so nicknamed because of the way his hair
always fell across his face, ala Shemp of the Three Stooges. He was
always talking about how his great-grandfather had blown the
opportunity to buy a chunk of a fledgling company that was going to
make a product called Pepsi-Cola. If only!
</P>
<P>
   Who knows if it was true. No doubt great-grandpa passed along
that story as true fact and it traveled through the generations,
just as lots of other relatives from the old days were telling
similar tales. We all had Willy Lomans in our family trees,
lamenting from the grave that they didn't go into the jungle like
brother Ben, who came out a rich man.
</P>
<P>
   I know what my descendants (assuming there are any) are going to
be saying 75 years from now. Something like, ``My family could be
stinkin' rich today, if only my stupid great-grandfather Richard
the First had bought stock in eBay when he had the chance in the
late 1990s!''
</P>
<P>
   Or Amazon, or Yahoo, or America Online. Or Priceline or uBid or
iVillage or DoubleClick, or any of those other darned ``dot-com''
stocks you and I didn't buy when we had the chance, dadgummit!
</P>
<P>
   Too late now. According to people who know these things, most of
the above stocks will probably never reach the value they once
held. And we're certainly well past the point where you could have
bought into one of those companies at a few bucks a share and
watched your investment increase fiftyfold.
</P>
<P>
   The current issue of Time magazine has an article on the
plunging prices of Internet stocks, including a little
picture-chart showing how the heads of some well-known companies
have seen their worths decline greatly in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Jeff Bezos of Amazon.com used to be worth $13
billion, but now he's worth only $5.3 billion. And Margaret Whitman
of eBay has seen her worth decline from $1.6 billion to a mere $569
million.
</P>
<P>
   Yet I'm still willing to say: Margaret, will you marry me?
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to feel sorry for these people with their
``silly money.'' (That's when you have so much money it's just
plain silly.) All you can do is shake your head and be solid in the
knowledge that are other companies out there right now offering
incredible investment opportunities _ and you'll miss out on those
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's not just the kabillionaire founders who have
made silly money over the last few years; a lot of people have
become rich playing the market. Forget about building a company
from the ground up or working your way to the top of a law firm or
laboring for 15 years to invent an ingenious device that improves
the quality of life for millions of people. It's a lot easier to
buy a few thousand shares of an Internet stock that suddenly
explodes and turns you into an instant millionaire at 27.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone who has pulled off the latter trick doesn't
deserve the money. If you make a brilliant and/or lucky investment
and it flowers into an entire meadow of money, God love ya.
</P>
<P>
   But it kind of reminds me of the talented but usually unknown
authors who win the ``Oprah lottery'' and suddenly find themselves
giving interviews about what it's like to see their book catapult
from nowhere to the top of The New York Times' bestseller list.
It's a wonderful windfall, and any writer feeling the tap of
Oprah's sword on their shoulder would have to be insane to decline
her offer of instant riches and fame _ but I wonder if there's
something just slightly bittersweet about the triumph. Wouldn't it
be better if a half-million people bought your book because they
really wanted to, not because a TV talk show host told them to?
</P>
<P>
   And wouldn't it be more satisfying to achieve fabulous wealth
through something more tangible, rewarding and life-affirming than
the wild rise of an Internet stock? Wouldn't anyone prefer to
really and truly earn that hundred million?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it doesn't make a bit of difference. I suppose we'd all
welcome the opportunity to find out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times, a commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
