</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-TERRORIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRORIST ACT BRINGS BENIGN ISRAELI REACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ A Palestinian on a suicide mission rammed his car
into a group of Israeli soldiers Tuesday, wounding 11 people before
being shot to death by other soldiers and police.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials, in a marked change from previous responses to
attacks by Palestinian militants, did not personally blame
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat or threaten to halt the peace
process over the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we can expect that those organizations that
oppose the peace process will try to derail it at a moment when it
starts to gain momentum, which is now,'' said Deputy Defense
Minister Ephraim Sneh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the Palestinian Authority and our security services
will do their most to contain this _ so far, there is no doubt they
(Palestinian security services) are trying their best,'' Sneh told
Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak called the attack ``cowardly'' but
added that Israel would work together with the Palestinian
Authority to ``put an end to terror.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack was the second in as many weeks. The militant group
Hamas claimed responsibility for a shooting Aug. 3 in which two
Jewish settlers were wounded in Hebron, where about 400 Jews live
in a heavily-guarded section of the West Bank town.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's attack began, Israeli police said, when a Palestinian
in a Fiat with Israeli license plates drove into a group of
soldiers waiting beside the highway halfway between Tel Aviv and
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said that 10 minutes after the man drove away, he
returned and again plowed into the soldiers, who had been joined by
police and others assisting those initially wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fled and then the car returned to the site and tried to hit
soldiers again, and police and soldiers at the spot fired at the
car,'' said Linda Menuchin, a police spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Menuchin refused to give the assailant's name, saying police
were still investigating, but Israel Radio and others identified
him as Akram Alkam, 22, from the West Bank town of Bethlehem. Most
of Bethlehem is under Palestinian self-rule.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Fadwa Alkam, said her son had called her from a
mobile phone just before the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `I am at a junction about to carry out a suicide
attack, and I see a lot of soldiers,' '' his mother quoted him as
saying. ``I begged him not to do it, but he wouldn't listen, and
hung up the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   She said he wasn't a militant but had just finished a biography
of Hamas chief Yehiyeh Ayyash, slain in 1996 in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 11 soldiers were wounded but by the end of the day
only four remained in hospital, one in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
   The attack comes at a time when Israel and the Palestinians are
in dispute over the next transfer of West Bank land to Palestinian
rule. Barak has said he will carry out the Wye accords, signed by
his predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu, but he has asked the
Palestinians to accept a delay in the next land transfer and put
off the last until negotiations start on a final peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   His request has raised accusations from Palestinians officials
that Israel is trying to wriggle out of handing over more of the
West Bank _ occupied by Israel in the 1967 war _ to Palestinian
self-rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the more Barak procrastinates _ the more he leaves the
process open to violence from both sides,'' said Hanan Ashrawi, a
member of the Palestinian Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat did reluctantly agree to Barak's proposal that the next
land transfer be carried out around Oct. 1, but he has so far
refused to accept any further delay in the last of the
redeployments mandated by the Wye accords.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between the two leaders already has caused US
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright to delay her planned visit
to the region. The Israeli premier asked her to put off her trip _
originally planned to start Aug. 14 _ until he and Arafat settled
their differences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
