<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2415 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPEN-AIR-MOVIES-ART-7     08-10 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEN-AIR-MOVIES-ART-750(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOOR MOVIES BRING CROWDS BACK TO THE OLD NEIGHBORHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ After the sun has set and he is finished watering
his rooftop garden, 89-year-old John Pente beams down upon the
fresh life that has come to the aging streets of his beloved Little
Italy: An al fresco specialty from the Old Country, an open-air
movie, flashes onto the parking lot wall of Da Mimmo's restaurant,
proudly projected from a bedroom window of Pente's row house.
</P>
<P>
   Three stories below in the street, hundreds of people gather
with their lawn chairs for the free showings, silently engrossed in
the movie but for the occasional crunch of the cannoli distributed
free from Vaccaro's bakery. In sweet escape, they take in ``La
Strada'' and ``Rocky'' and, even more, the old neighborhood
darkness that flashes with fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come out and sit, turn the streets lights off and
everybody gets down to earth,'' Pente said, delighted to see all
the visiting children enlivening the streets once more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ci vediamo al cinema!'' (``See you at the movies!'') has
become the homespun prescription here in Little Italy every Friday
night this summer.
</P>
<P>
   A nettlesome civic issue _ what to do about that blank billboard
wall in the parking lot _ has been turned into a word-of-mouth
triumph, with more than 800 people settling down in the middle of
South High Street every Friday and staring up at the fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of it when I was visiting my sister-in-law in
Palermo last year,'' explained Mary Ann Cricchio, a dynamic young
restaurateur who grew up in Little Italy and still lives there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked and saw the big social event in Sicily,'' she said,
``all these people sitting in the piazza watching movies.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bedroom of Mr. John, as Pente is widely known, the
aluminum storm window is popped out before each showing. But
otherwise things are untouched, from the wall crucifix to the
neatly made twin beds of his two sons, who moved out decades ago.
During those decades, Little Italy has been reduced largely to the
entrenched old people and to the 16 busy Italian restaurants that
still anchor the century-old enclave.
</P>
<P>
   A huge 16-millimeter, 2,000-watt projection machine has been set
up in the bedroom for the duration of the 10-week program, which
ends on Sept. 3 with ``Cinema Paradiso,'' a poetic choice about the
love of movies in a small Italian town.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minutes before the beginning of the latest
offering, ``The Name of the Rose,'' Maria Monaldi Oma, in from the
suburbs with her family, stood exultantly on the streets where she
spent the first 30 of her 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of community _ that's one thing I miss,'' she said,
recalling life as one of seven children in a three-generation row
house. ``The movie idea is great. It brings the old people back out
into the streets, me and my old friends return, and the tourists
come in,'' she said as her brother, Frank, came over after testing
his old finesse in the Stiles Street bocce court.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As they settled under the starry sky, a hurdy-gurdy resurrected
for the occasion spieled old immigrant tunes. ``That's Peggy
O'Neil'' plunked forth lyrically as the late arrivals searched out
their spots in a buzz of family imprecations. (``Angie! Over
here!'')
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A feverishly busy man, Tom Kiefaber, lugged forth two big sacks
of boxed popcorn for curbside distribution. Then Kiefaber,
proprietor of Baltimore's historic Senator Theater, hurried up into
the Pente bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is full circle for my family,'' Kiefaber said, describing
how his grandfather had started the family's movie-theater dynasty
by showing open-air silent films to packs of world-weary
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Doubtful at first about the Little Italy venture, Kiefaber
yielded when he saw the street setting's simple beauty. He put word
out on his web site (www.senator.com), and now he and the Little
Italy Restaurant Association have agreed to underwrite another 10
films next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Up in the bedroom, Ms. Cricchio had a last-minute conference
with Kiefaber about the sensitive subject of prevailing
neighborhood standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sex scene between the monk and the Italian peasant girl?
_ I checked, and Father Mike said it was OK; it was art,'' Ms.
Cricchio said with some doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I already cut that scene,'' Kiefaber announced, wary
about the family-values throng buzzing down in the street and the
respect owed to Mr. John.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. John, a polite, elfin man, seemed far too delighted at
seeing the streets so crowded with real people to care about
full-frontal figments on the parking-lot wall. ``I'd do anything
for the neighborhood,'' he reassured one and all.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mr. John has refused all payment for his help. But the
restaurants, prizing his cooperation, have given him a handsome
heavy sidewalk bench, and they secretly plan to pay his utility
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy life and love to cook,'' he said of his other weekly
pleasure, the repasts he makes on Sundays for a dozen family
visitors. ``My sister Rose, next door, she's 85 and doesn't come
out for the movies. She's traditional. She cooks special dishes at
different times of the year, knocks on my window and passes me the
food.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. John offered a smile of happiness worthy of a Fellini extra.
Then he headed down to his new movie-watching bench in the old
neighborhood. Seated as one of many once more in Little Italy, Mr.
John gazed across at the wall and waited for the movie to shine
forth from his upstairs window.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
