<SLUG> BC-COKE-ACTORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke seeking former commercial actors for residual checks
 &HT;    By Shannon Shelton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Calling all extras!
</P>
<P>
   If you were ever lucky enough to have appeared in a Coca-Cola TV
ad, there might be a check with your name on it.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co. and the Screen Actors Guild are looking for more
than 180 performers who appeared in Coke ads between 1953 and 1995,
and are owed residuals.
</P>
<P>
   Some actors have been easy to find, like football great ``Mean''
Joe Greene, who appeared in a well-known 1985 commercial.
</P>
<P>
   But others who played more minor roles have been more difficult
to track down. Depending on the contract, their checks could range
from $50 to $2,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   The problem arose in 1996 when Coke began running old ads in its
World of Coca-Cola attractions in Atlanta and Las Vegas, and at its
Everything Coca-Cola retail store in New York. An actor complained
to the Screen Actors Guild about not being paid.
</P>
<P>
   The guild stepped in to help work out the current agreement with
Big Red.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's attempts to locate all the performers failed. The
company then handed an undisclosed sum to the guild, which is
leading the search.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to do our best to locate them,'' said Susan
McDermott, a Coke spokeswoman. ``Some of these people could be
living in another country.''
</P>
<P>
   Or some might not be living at all.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, survivors can claim the money if they can prove
their loved one was in one of the TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   If all else fails, the money will revert to a Screen Actors
Guild Foundation fund, said group spokeswoman Jayne Wallace. But
she added the union will do its best to find each person.
</P>
<P>
   If you think you're one of the chosen few, call the guild at
212-827-1540, or e-mail the group at ebates(at)sag.org
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Shelton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
