<HEADLINE>
ROBERT M. VILES, 60; WAS KEY TO LAW SCHOOL'S SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Wife, Bruce Earman Viles, is cq.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Marshall Viles, former dean of Franklin Pierce Law Center
in Concord, N.H., the country's smallest independent law school,
died Mondaywhile vacationing in France.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Viles, a champion of ``community lawyering,'' apparently
drowned while swimming with his wife off the coast of Brittany. He
was 60.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to teaching courses on contract law, poverty law,
and social legislation, he cultivated the law center's growing
reputation in intellectual property law and public interest law,
particularly in underserved communities, which he called
``community lawyering.''
</P>
<P>
   The law school, with little more than 400 students, has been
ranked first in intellectual property law by US News and World
Report for the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be seen as a jewel of a law school,'' Mr. Viles
said in a story published in the Globe on Aug. 24, 1997. ``What is
unique _ as Harry Truman would say _ is that in a small school, the
buck stops here. It doesn't stop somewhere over there in the
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about preparing someone so he or she knows how to
counsel a client, to give advice,'' he said. ``We want our students
to be able to do that . . . Relatively few law schools have devoted
full attention to developing students who are one step from having
professional responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Viles was born in Skowhegan, Maine. He graduated from Bates
College, New York University School of Law, and Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in New Hampshire in 1973 to become associate dean of
the law center at Franklin Pierce College. In 1976, when the law
center severed its ties with the college, Mr. Viles became its
dean. He held the post for the next 20 years and, in 1992, also
became the school's president. Last month, he became vice chairman
of the school's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Douglas J. Wood, a former student and current chairman
of the school's board of trustees, said of Viles: ``His vision,
creativity, hard work, and caring for faculty and students alike
brought this school from its infancy to its current national, and
even international reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Bruce Earman Viles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
