<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONKEY-DANCE-THEATER-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BUMP IN A MIDSUMMER NIGHT: IS IT A DREAM?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 William Harris' most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about
the dancer-choreographer John Jasperse.  
 By WILLIAM HARRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every Thursday night since January, cognoscenti have
been flocking to a sassy dance-theater performance at the Pyramid
Club in Manhattan's East Village. ``The Donkey Show,'' conceived by
Randy Weiner and directed by Weiner and his wife, Diane Paulus, is
an adaptation of Shakespeare's ``Midsummer Night's Dream'' as
interpreted through the lyrics of disco music and the dances these
catchy tunes inspired, including the hustle, the bump and the
freak.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography was created by the company under the
supervision of Ms. Paulus, who danced with the New York City Ballet
as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Now this production is transferring to El Flamingo, a larger
club in Manhattan, with the help of Jordan Roth, 23, the son of the
veteran impresario Daryl Roth (currently represented by ``De la
Guarda'' and ``Wit'') and MAC Cosmetics, in its first theatrical
venture.
</P>
<P>
   The show is to open on Wednesday, with previews through the
previous week. Six days a week audiences can join the dancing, both
before and after the 55-minute performance, as well as sip
cocktails throughout. Tickets are $25.
</P>
<P>
   There is no dialogue in the show, but lots of cross-dressing,
lip-synching and polyester. In other words, something for everyone.
People who know the play will be struck by the way vintage disco
hits like ``Don't Leave Me This Way'' (sung by Thelma Houston,
1977), ``Enough Is Enough'' (Barbra Streisand and Donna Summer,
1979) or ``You Sexy Thing'' (Hot Chocolate, 1975) are used to
amplify the story of two couples unhappy in love and caught in the
cross hairs of the feuding Oberon and Titania, the king and queen
of the fairies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Shakespeare is all about passion and sex and drugs, just
like disco in the late 1970s,'' said Weiner, who has previously
re-examined ``Twelfth Night'' through the filter of pop music. ``I
love the metaphor in `Midsummer' of putting a drop of something in
someone's eyes and it instantly changes the world. It also dawned
on me that this is really a story about bestiality. I'm interested
in the tension between the hot music and the play's darker
images.'' Weiner, 34, and Ms. Paulus, 33, Manhattan natives, met in
a high school production of ``Wonderful Town'' 17 years ago. They
subsequently attended Harvard University, where they frequently
sneaked into the American Repertory Theater to see productions by
experimental directors like Robert Wilson, JoAnne Akalaitis and
Andrei Serban.
</P>
<P>
   However, both cite the comic actor-playwright-director Charles
Ludlam, founder of the Ridiculous Theatrical Company, as their
principal influence. In 1993, they founded the Project 400 Theater
Group, a populist New York troupe devoted to musical- and
community-based performance.
</P>
<P>
   Two more people have been added to the original 11-member cast
of ``The Donkey Show,'' and the design elements have been
sharpened.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the underground mentality of the event and the sense that
the show happens out of the organic life of a club is untouched,''
Ms. Paulus said. ``People came to us wanting to work on the show,
which is how this company was assembled. They are all highly
physical, but I would not call any of them dancers. I also think
anyone who wants to be a performer can be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
