<HEADER>
A2429 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAUX-FINISH12-COX     08-10 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAUX-FINISH12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Artist's condo captures mood and style one layer at a time
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Aug. 12.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    Photos by Joey Ivansco
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When friends see Bobby Sikes' renovated condo for the
first time, their first reaction, he says, is ``Where's your
artwork?''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta artist and interior designer has made a name for
himself with his paintings, murals and faux wall finishes, so they
expect to see far more than the couple of pieces gracing its walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want this place to feel decorated, but like a home,''
he says of the simple yet elegant approach he's taken to the
Midtown unit he bought last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a closer look reveals subtle touches of Sikes' brush. He
finished the walls in an aged plaster texture in warm shades of
light gold and gray. He marbleized a pair of columns in similar
neutral tones yet made them pop with metallic gold accents. He used
the columns to draw the eye to the ceiling where he created a mural
of pale blue sky and white wispy clouds. (He even faux painted its
ceiling fan in the same parchment finish he created on other
ceilings in the unit). And in the foyer, he painted an arched mural
with a beckoning view of neighboring Piedmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of selecting one decorative wall finish, let alone
several, from the array of options these days can be enough to send
some homeowners running to the comfort of a gallon of white latex.
Fear of faux _ that broad category of paint and textural finishes,
from sponging to ragging to trompe l'oeil _ and its ``permanent''
nature discourage many from experimenting with a look that, unlike
paint or wallpaper, is timeless and original.
</P>
<P>
   ``On average, people are afraid of color, and with textured
finishes, it's pretty much there to stay so they need to be sure
they select the color they want,'' said Atlanta artist and author
Phillip Myer of PCM Studios, a decorative painting business. ``It's
hard to get people over the hurdle that color shouldn't be
frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason recent trends in faux finishes have moved away
from the bold colors of the '80s to the tone-on-tone neutrals of
the '90s. Busy sponged effects have evolved into stuccoed and
distressed surfaces that offer the high contrast that variations in
color had provided. The result is subtle refinement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at walls as the backdrops for artwork or for playing up
fabrics _ not as a statement in themselves,'' Sikes says. ``I also
think of things in a timeless sense, instead of finishes that are
trendy and will look dated in a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Both views are evident inside his own place.
</P>
<P>
   All in the details
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old, known for his traditional oil paintings, had
been living in a colonial home in metro Atlanta near his studio and
fine art print business, Bobby Sikes Fine Art &AMP; Design, when he
decided to move closer in. Ironically, the two-bedroom unit, at
Piedmont Road and 13th Street, had been owned twice by artists.
</P>
<P>
   Renovation was nothing new for Sikes, who with sister Susan
Davis, also co-owns a Lawrenceville (Ga.) design business founded
by their mother, the late Faye Sikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never done a project like this before,'' he says of the
84-year-old building. ``I do it for clients all the time, but doing
it for yourself is another story. But it was a good renovation for
me because it involved no exterior.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-floor unit is among 12 in the gray brick building
nestled among sought-after high-rise condos near the park entrance.
Because of the long, narrow layout, Sikes added vertical elements
to offset the design _ the columns separating the living room from
a small sun room overlooking the park, the living room's sky mural
painted inside a tray ceiling, the foyer's tall trompe l'oeil
surrounded by faux stone walls. He replaced standard hallway doors
with French ones containing panes of beveled mirrors, which,
because of their reflections, make the space appear wider.
</P>
<P>
   Sikes gutted a cold kitchen of pale blue walls and simple white
cabinets to create a warm European setting of earthy granite
countertops and limestone tile, new cabinets in a distressed,
oatmeal finish and walls in more of the Venetian texture, a mix of
paint and plaster.
</P>
<P>
   The two bathrooms also were gutted and now contain one of the
home's most interesting accents. Set into the marble wall tile
above the tubs are plaster friezes the artists painted look aged,
creating a patina to match the tile.
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of detail, combined with the murals and textured
walls, that gives homes a unique sense of character, says the
artist, whose current projects include the Fayetteville home of
boxer Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   But Sikes cautions: Just don't overdo it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do every room faux,'' he says, ``but I look at it like
a wardrobe in that everybody needs to strike a balance between
solids and patterns. I tend to do a lot more solid and in one
color.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating something unique
</P>
<P>
   The artist, who began painting professionally only seven years
ago after managing his father's car dealership, has done murals and
wall finishes for everything from banks and office buildings to
funeral homes and apartments. But Sikes, who studied both art and
marketing at the University of Georgia, says his most exciting
project has been his condo, a renovation that took about seven
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the fact that I didn't have anyone else to answer to
but myself,'' he says. ``The most exciting things to do _ and the
ones that bring the best results _ are ones in which the client
gives me the freedom to create and doesn't dictate something they
may have seen elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Though many faux artists first create sample boards of the
finishes they plan to use, Sikes prefers to start with the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's developed such a reputation for doing color so well he
doesn't need to do the boards,'' says Alpharetta resident Paul
Maggard, for whom Sikes is doing painting several rooms. ``He can
do something to a wall, and if you want him to modify it he can.''
</P>
<P>
   The look's random quality is what appeals to Maggard most about
paint and textural finishes. ``It's just so much more dramatic than
wallpaper, a real art form that gives you something timeless,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   And, as eclectic European interiors continue to influence
American decor, consumers are drawn to the juxtaposition of fine
surfaces with rough ones, contemporary art with antique furniture,
the new with the old. When it comes to walls, Myer says, ``it's the
imperfection they're after.''
</P>
<P>
   Faux finishes also give homeowners something unique _ a
large-scale work of art. ``I like something in our home that you
don't walk down the block and see in someone else's place,''
Maggard says.
</P>
<P>
   Not even in Sikes'.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
