<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPANISH-ONLY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BUSINESS IN SPANISH ONLY FOR TEXAS TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL CENIZO, Texas _ Leaders of this rugged town on the banks of
the Rio Grande on Tuesday defended an ordinance that requires all
local government business to be transacted in Spanish, and another
law that calls for firing any municipal employee who helps the
Border Patrol apprehend illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial ordinances are rooted in El Cenizo's Mexican
immigrant heritage, even though it has not been part of Mexico for
150 years.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said that while there are no plans to
challenge the new ordinances, they note a 1996 federal law
prohibits cities from stopping their employees from assisting
immigration authorities.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to find a non-Spanish speaker in this town of about
1,500 people, located in Webb County 10 miles south of Laredo.
Nearly everyone has either come from Mexico, is married to an
immigrant or is the child of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and one of two city commissioners came to the United
States from Nuevo Laredo, Mexico, as illegal immigrants. They are
now U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President (Al) Gore and Governor (George W.) Bush are
campaigning in Spanish because they know it is important. They want
the vote,'' Mayor Rafael Rodriguez said Tuesday as American and
Mexican flags hung behind him on the wall at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them to come here and learn Spanish,'' said Rodriguez,
who speaks no English.
</P>
<P>
   He said the push for the two ordinances was prompted by
residents' apathy toward government and the Border Patrol policy of
searching buses linking El Cenizo, with its low-slung shacks and
many unpaved streets, with nearby Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Schultz, spokesman for the Washington-based U.S. English, a
group that wants to make English the official language of the
United States, said El Cenizo's stance flies in the face of a
common language holding together the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We essentially predicted we would have a dropping out _ a
linguistic ghettoization of the country,'' Schultz said. ``We did
not know it would happen this soon.''
</P>
<P>
   But Israel M. Reyna, the lead attorney for Texas Rural Legal Aid
in Laredo, said city leaders are doing what they can in a place
where many people have limited English skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a developing democracy opening government's doors to the
people,'' Reyna said of the language ordinance. ``Getting people
involved is the primary mission.''
</P>
<P>
   El Cenizo, which started as a housing development without water
or electricity, was incorporated in 1989, but it still faces many
conditions reminiscent of a developing nation.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders _ the two commissioners and the mayor _ approved
the two controversial ordinances last week.
</P>
<P>
   One ordinance requires that City Council sessions and other
official functions be conducted in Spanish and that notices will be
posted in Spanish. English translations will be provided with 48
hours' notice.
</P>
<P>
   To conform with state and federal regulations, ordinances will
be created in English but will be translated into Spanish,
according to city documents.
</P>
<P>
   The second ordinance declares El Cenizo a ``safe haven'' for
undocumented immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   As such, all town employees and elected officials are forbidden
under the penalty of dismissal, from assisting the Border Patrol,
according to the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not fighting the government; we are expressing our
feelings,'' City Commissioner Gloria Romo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it is their job to go after illegals, but it is not
right to bother people who are legal,'' Romo said.
</P>
<P>
   Romo, who has taught English as a second language at the
community center here, said more people can participate in
government if they understand what is happening.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities are keeping an eye on El Cenizo's
ordinances, but there are no plans to challenge them in court, said
Tomas Zuniga, spokesman for the Immigration and Naturalization
Service regional headquarters in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think we have seen it taken this far,'' Zuniga said
of the ordinance on immigrants. ``We are going to sit back and see
how it unfolds.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Strassberger, an INS spokesman in Los Angeles, said the
1996 Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act
prohibits state and federal governments from restricting employees
from sharing information with the INS.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court in May struck down a New York City
ordinance that put limits on the sharing of information, but it was
not as harsh as what El Cenizo has done.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In El Cenizo, residents supported the ordinances.
</P>
<P>
   Lorenzo De La Cruz, a welder, complained that people are often
detained by the Border Patrol based on what they look like, rather
than their immigration status.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not all illegal,'' Cruz said as he stood in Los
Compadres, a grocery store near City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``How you look is how they treat you,'' he said of patrol
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Guadalupe Gomez, 54, welcomed what she perceived as new access
to local government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, they speak more Spanish than English,'' Gomez said as an
American flag billowed in front of her husband's tire shop. ``They
should keep speaking Spanish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
