<SLUG> BC-REM11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Electric R.E.M. kicks off U.S. tour in top form
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's been a California dream the last few days for
R.E.M., the Athens supergroup kicking off its first American tour
in four years with two soldout shows here.
</P>
<P>
   They've dedicated songs to Beach Boy Brian Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Their entourage is spread out in a series of Hollywood hotels,
from the John Belushi deathpad _ the Chateau Marmont _ to the
chi-chi Beverly Hills Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Conducting some Hollywood business, band members went to Warner
Brothers to hear the soundtrack for the upcoming Jim Carrey movie
about Andy Kaufman, a film that takes its title from ``Man on the
Moon,'' R.E.M.'s irresistible hit about the over-the-top comedian.
(In concert, Stipe dedicated the song ``Man On the Moon'' to ``my
friend Milos,'' referring to the movie's director, Milos Forman.)
</P>
<P>
   They've even had an audition, of sorts. Kathy Wetherell, a
producer with MTV's ``Road Rules,'' was at Monday's concert
checking out the music and hoping to convince the band to
participate in the show when it visits Atlanta in October.
</P>
<P>
   After months of playing European dates, R.E.M. is touring
America for the first time since 1995, heading for three soldout
shows at Chastain Park Aug. 29-31 in Atlanta. Judging from their
riveting performances here, the band has survived its midlife
crisis _ slowing album sales, the retirement of drummer Bill Berry
_ not only intact, but with a lively sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's show at the Greek Theater, lead singer Michael Stipe
poked fun at their latest image _ 40-year-old icons who are
sometimes criticized as being out of step with today's,
rage-oriented rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're probably the last band in the universe to have a
website,'' Stipe laughed as a bright blue URL address flashed on a
screen above his shaven head (www.remhq.com).
</P>
<P>
   Stipe also mocked his Rock God status a bit by halting the
encore performance of ``It's the End of the World As We Know It''
to break into a rambling, lyrically quirky version of Elvis
Presley's ``Suspicious Minds.''
</P>
<P>
   This superb musicianship and carefree has been casting a spell
on concertgoers, too. From the time fans began pulling their cars
into the dusty parking lots in the hills overlooking Hollywood to
the first chords of the opening song ``Lotus,'' R.E.M.'s shows have
had the look and feel of a school reunion. The crowds have been
mostly 30-something, dressed in the casual hip of off-duty
professionals ready to let down their guard. For the most part,
they've done just that, liberated by an energizing, 22-song set in
which R.E.M. ripped through 20 years of hits and new material with
the enthusiasm of teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   The shows are literally electric. The stage of the 5,000-seat,
outdoor amphitheater _ it looks much like Chastain Park with
bleachers _ was draped with intricate scaffolding holding hundreds
of brightly lighted, kitschy icons (coffee cup, smiling whale,
revolving video camera, big banana and giant yellow lotus) that
blinked on cue with the music. The band itself, back by three
supporting musicians, was in tight veteran form, with Stipe's
rubbery dancing and Mike Mills' ethereal backing vocals often
recalling the group's party days in Athens. Even guitarist Peter
Buck let fly some air kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, R.E.M. has opted not to deliver a walk-through
performance of greatest hits. The band is playing plenty of
material off less commercially successful albums, such as 1996's
``New Adventures in Hi-Fi'' and this year's ``Up.'' Stipe
introduced the Dylan-esque ``E-Bow the Letter'' as his ``favorite
song ever.'' And, in a gesture that underscored a mood of ``we
ain't done yet,'' the band even unveiled the new tune ``Great
Beyond,'' which they wrote for the ``Man On the Moon'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the most poignant moment during the shows, Stipe
introduced the 1986 hit ``Fall on Me'' with a sweet nod of
nostalgia: ``This song is older than time,'' he said, raising his
arms up into the spotlight while pouring out the lyric ``lift your
arms up to the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Concertgoers, too, have noted R.E.M.'s efforts to remain vital
in a hip-hop universe, where relevant rock is a scarce musical
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't dug the last couple of albums all that much
because they were too mellow. I like my R.E.M. a little more
uptempo,'' said longtime fan Gary Poole, a 38-year-old music
industry exec. ``But, sure, they should always keep going. You can
still drink beer and rock at 40.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen-year-old Jonathan Yaffe drove from San Diego to see the
band because ``they offer so much more variety than other music of
today. They haven't sold out. They haven't altered their sound to
be on the radio. They aren't a fast flurry like Korn. They are more
about music than money.''
</P>
<P>
   Clutching his R.E.M. poster, Yaffe added, ``My advice to them
would be to keep touring. I mean, look at this place _ it's
packed.''
</P>
<P>
   SET LIST
</P>
<P>
   The songs being played (and the albums they're from):
</P>
<P>
   ``Lotus'' (``Up'')
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the Frequency, Kenneth'' (``Monster'')
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wake-Up Bomb'' (``New Adventures in Hi-Fi''
</P>
<P>
   ``Suspicion'' (``Up'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Fall On Me'' (``Life's Rich Pageant'')
</P>
<P>
   ``E-bow the Letter'' (``New Adventures in Hi-Fi'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Low Desert'' (``New Adventures in Hi-Fi'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Hurts'' (``Automatic'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Daysleeper'' (``Up'')
</P>
<P>
   ``The One I Love'' (``Document'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweetness Follows'' (``Automatic'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Great Beyond'' (``Man on the Moon'' soundtrack)
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing My Religion'' (``Out of Time'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Find the River'' (``Automatic'')
</P>
<P>
   ``At My Most Beautiful'' (``Up'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Finest Worksong'' (``Document'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Walk Unafraid'' (``Up'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Man on the Moon'' (``Automatic'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Crush With Eyeliner'' (``Monster'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Tongue'' (``Monster'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuyahoga'' (``Life's Rich Pageant'')
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the End of the World As We Know It'' (``Document'')
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
