<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2433 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAUX-FINISHTIPS12-COX     08-10 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAUX-FINISHTIPS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    5 things to know when considering faux finishes
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Aug. 12
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cynthia Potter has to admit she was a little antsy about having
someone ``beat up'' her kitchen cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   But she and her husband, Peter Lasser, wanted to give the room a
Southwest look, and Atlanta artists Phillip Myer and Andy Jones
recommended refinishing the cabinets in an aged distressed look.
``We were leery about using the old cabinets, but they just beat
them and painted them,'' Potter says. ``We couldn't be more
pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiring artists to create decorative finishes, whether it's faux
painting a chair, texturizing a wall or creating trompe l'oeil,
requires a certain amount of trust. When you ask your hair stylist
to do ``something different,'' you're placing your head in someone
else's hands, aren't you?
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are steps consumers can take to ensure their choice in
painting techniques lives up to what they envisioned:
</P>
<P>
   Learn to speak the language: Get familiar with the dozens of
painting and texturizing techniques that make up decorative
painting. Most of the terms describe the look the artists try to
replicate, such as marbleizing, woodgraining and tortoiseshell. But
others, such as trompe l'oeil (the French term for ``fooling the
eye'' into believing that life-size painted objects are real), are
less obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, look at magazines and tear out pictures of things that
interest you,'' says Myer, who co-owns PCM Studios, a decorative
painting business, with Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have a feel for what you want, be warned: Decorative
painting has become a highly competitive field.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully select the artist: Ask friends and co-workers for
referrals. Then make sure your personality clicks with the
artist's; communication is key to a successful project.
</P>
<P>
   Ask to see the artist's portfolio to get a feel for his work.
``Ask to go and look at what they've done previously, too,'' Potter
says.
</P>
<P>
   Ask for sample boards or sketches: Once you narrow your choices
of finishes, most artists will create a sample board illustrating
the technique. If it's a mural you're commissioning, the artist
should provide sketches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spend a good bit of time in this process because you can
really prevent problems down the road with color and technique,''
Myer says. ``Pin the sample boards up in the room and look at them
at different times of day to see how they look under different
amounts of light.''
</P>
<P>
   (If you're building a new home, most artists prefer to get
involved early in the process to advise clients on selecting base
paints for
</P>
<P>
   finishes.)
</P>
<P>
   Expect the expense of something handmade: Charges for murals run
across the board, depending on size, subject matter and intricacy.
For paint and textural finishes, some artists charge by the hour,
others by the room or square footage. Atlanta artist Bobby Sikes'
fee is based on the technique and room size. The cost for painting
a parchment finish on the walls of a 12-foot-by-12-foot
dining-room, for example, range from about $750 to $950. (The fees
for creating sample boards are applied toward the cost.)
</P>
<P>
   ``On the whole, painting costs a little more than wallpaper, but
if a finish gets scuffed or scratched it can be touched up,'' Sikes
says.
</P>
<P>
   Wallpaper manufacturers have jumped on the faux bandwagon with
patterns that mimic finishes, providing a more affordable
alternative. ``If you want a look that's letter perfect, a
faux-finish wallpaper may be for you,'' Myer says. ``But if you
have imperfect walls that don't lend themselves to wallpaper, a
painted finish is the better option because it can hide those
imperfections.''
</P>
<P>
   The unique imperfection of paint is what draws most to faux
finishes. Like any other artwork, no two fauxed walls _ or rooms _
are exactly alike.
</P>
<P>
   Keep an open mind _ you can always change it later: Years from
now, what if you grow tired of the finish and want to make a
change? Walls done in a simple painting technique, such as
sponging, can be painted over, Myer says. But ones texturized with
heavier, three-dimensional finishes will need to be scraped and
sanded, or covered with a wallpaper liner, to be made smooth for
painting. (Or if it's just the color you want to change, textured
walls that have been glazed can be painted over.)
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, Potter says, is be willing to experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're open to new ideas, even though these finishes have
been around for a long time, the artist can take it from there,''
she says. ``At some point, you just have to trust them.''
</P>
<P>
   _Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
