<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2434 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAINT-TERMS12-COX     08-10 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAINT-TERMS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An A to W list of paint terms
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Aug. 12.
 &HT;    By Danny Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Decorative finishes include dozens of painting and texturing
techniques, so it helps to know the language when selecting one.
Here are some terms as defined by Atlanta artist Phillip Myer of
PCM Studios in ``Creative Paint Finishes for the Home'' (North
Light Books, F&AMP;W Publications, $27.99):
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Antiquing: The application of a very thin brown or black
coating over a surface to make an object look older that it is.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Crackled: A surface of random separations in a paint or
varnish finish, making it appear older than it is.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Decorative painting: An ornamental art form used to decorate
surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Distressed: A battered or beaten surface, created with
abrasive materials to create an aged appearance.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gilding: A layer of gold or silver leaf applied over a
surface.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Glaze: A transparent mixture of color plus painting medium.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Granite: The appearance of a hard, natural stone formation of
quartz, feldspar and mica.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Malachite: The appearance of a green to nearly black mineral
that is a basic carbonate of copper, with an intensive pattern of
irregular, wavy half-arch shapes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Marbleizing: A marbled pattern reproduced through the use of
paint, applied with a brush and/or feathers on a surface.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Plaster: A mixture of lime, sand and water, molded and formed
into various architectural or decorative shapes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ragging: A painted finish in which a mottled texture is
created by patting a crumpled rag on a wet paint glaze.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sponging: The application of paint loaded on a sponge to
create a textural pattern.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stenciling: The application of design work achieved by
brushing paint through a cut design opening.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Strie: Irregular linear streaks in a wet paint glaze made with
a flogger brush.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Texturizing: A pattern similar to alligator skin, created by
pressing crumpled plastic wrap into a wet paint glaze.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tortoiseshell: A finish that duplicates the texture of a
turtle shell.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Trompe l'oeil: The French ``fool-the-eye'' painting style that
renders objects in life-size proportions, fooling the viewer into
believing they are real objects.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Woodgraining: A painted finish that duplicates a wood type
through the use of a wet paint glaze, brushes and special woodgrain
tools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
