<HEADLINE>
HE KNEW HIM WELL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York magazine asked an array of New Yorkers who knew  &UR; JFK &LR; 
 &UR; Jr. &LR;  for their recollections of the fallen idol. Among the
respondents was  &UR; Venard Garvin &LR; , who was, according to a profile
describing his connection with the deceased, ``convicted of drug
possession in 1992 and sentenced to two to six years; his
prosecutor was John Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him in the courtroom,'' begins the reminiscence.
``Even though his job was to put me away, I liked the guy.'' The
account includes Garvin's recollection that the judge, annoyed by
all the attention the prosecutor was getting, scolded everyone in
court for staring.
</P>
<P>
   At recess, recalls the former defendant, ``I spoke to him. I
remember I said, `It's the job _ it's not you.' Even though he was
a D.A., he didn't have the killing instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAKING BABIES IN SPACE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The necessity of sex in space was emphasized by  &UR; Jerry Brown &LR; 
(not Oakland's) of the U.S. Space Foundation, at the University of
Montana's ``space camp.'' ``If it's going to take 10,000 years for
us to get to the next place, we need to have children in space,''
he said, in remarks quoted by the Billings (Mont.) Gazette and
forwarded by  &UR; Dwain Hanson &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult,'' said one unidentified astronaut who had
traveled in space with his significant other. ``Maybe it's
impossible. It's hard to keep in one place, and you keep floating
off in different directions.'' A harness invented in 1985 has been
patented, but not tried out in space, said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the different daily cycle _ in space, the sun rises
and sets every 45 minutes _ destroys the natural rhythms of
testosterone surges. The lack of gravity means that eggs don't drop
and sperm don't swim up; nor is a baby likely to drop through the
birth canal.
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts typically develop ``fat face chicken leg syndrome,''
as a result of body fluids being pumped upward. ``If we go to
space,'' asked Brown, ``will we remain the same species? If we go
and stay, the children will be born in microgravity, and we better
figure out what that would look like. ... They may not look human,
they may not survive and they may not be able to return to Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Publishers Weekly warns of the coming of ``Whose Death in the
Tunnel'' (Robert D. Reed; $25),  &UR; Aaron Becker &LR; 's novel based on the
premise that  &UR; Princess Diana  &LR; faked her death.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you were worth $225,000 and you were to lose 47 cents in
your couch, says Wired magazine, that would be like  &UR; Bill Gates &LR; ,
whose worth is likely to be a trillion dollars in his lifetime,
losing $2.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wise guys: Eyewitness  &UR; Steve Finacom &LR;  says the masks worn by
Merola Opera performers in ``The Italian Girl in Algiers'' at Stern
Grove last Sunday, the 25th anniversary of  &UR; Richard Nixon &LR; 's
resignation announcement, were  &UR; Nixon  &LR; masks. Furthermore,  &UR; Tom &LR; 
 &UR; Ammiano &LR;  is wondering whether the closing of the Mustang Ranch is a
strike against ``live-work'' arrangements; and if you're wistful
about missing Wednesday's,  &UR; Mike Harris &LR;  suggests you mark the
occasion with a dim sun dinner.
</P>
<P>
   _ Among the prominent legal eagles California Lawyer asked to
name their favorite books is San Francisco District Attorney
 &UR; Terence Hallinan &LR; . Unsurprisingly, for a man nicknamed  &UR; Kayo &LR; 
(K.O.), it's  &UR; David Remnick &LR; 's ``King of the World,'' about
 &UR; Muhammad Ali &LR; , ``so much more than a sports figure,'' says
Hallinan. ``He is a people's hero. Plus, of course, he was a great,
great boxer, the champion of all champions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Omega submitted a watch, along with several other watchmakers.
Theirs was picked. Neil (Armstrong) and I both had the watches. ...
I chose to wear mine on the moon. ... I agreed to send the watch to
the Smithsonian Institution (but) it never reached the Smithsonian.
... I didn't end up with anything. No insurance. It never turned
up, this piece of equipment that's very valuable symbolically. And
then later on, when it became an accepted thing that you compensate
someone for using a picture of them for commercial purposes, that's
when I got stiffed by Omega. ... Eventually, I disallowed them the
use of that photograph. Now they show other pictures, including
Cindy Crawford _ who is compensated rather handsomely, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Buzz Aldrin, in Icon magazine, about one of the
disappointments of his career as a moon-walking astronaut.
</P>
