<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2443 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-MILITANTS-BOS &LR;      08-10 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MILITANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITANTS DECLARE DAGESTAN INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Islamic militants greeted Russia's new acting prime
minister Vladimir Putin Tuesday by declaring independence for the
southern Russian republic of Dagestan, escalating the largest armed
uprising the Kremlin has faced since it lost a war against
separatists in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, appointed Monday after President Boris N. Yeltsin
abruptly dismissed the government of Sergei Stepashin, responded to
the insurgents' challenge by promising that Russian troops would
bring order to the Caucasus region ``in the shortest time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Putin's confident prediction was dimmed by the shadow of
Russia's failed two-year campaign against separatists in Chechnya,
where the Kremlin and the military repeatedly claimed success
against rebel fighters until the day in 1996 when federal troops
withdrew from the region in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Russian military reported success against the
militants in Dagestan Tuesday, signs appeared that the rebels have
no intention of leaving soon. Dagestani officials said that the
militants, estimated at several hundred to more than 1,000, were
well-trained and receiving supplies and reinforcement from across
the virtually unguarded frontier with Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military said Tuesday federal troops had succeeded
in pushing the rebels out of two villages on Dagestan's mountainous
border with Chechnya that the gunmen had occupied since Saturday.
The chairman of Russia's general staff, General Anatoly Kvashnin,
called the situation in Dagestan ``manageable.''
</P>
<P>
   But other reports said the guerrillas had taken control of
another village, this one a mile from Botlikh, the main town in the
mountain valley where fighting has raged. The reports said the
militants also shot down two helicopters, killing four Russian
pilots, including a colonel who had won the service's highest
military honor.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians also have been blamed for killing four Dagestani
police and wounding 17 in friendly fire (they have denied it) and
accidentally bombing a village in Georgia on the other side of the
Caucasus (also denied). On Monday, Kvashnin reportedly narrowly
escaped death himself when his helicopter came under mortar attack
as it was landing (the military denied this, too).
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994-96 Chechen war, Russia and the rebels often seemed
to be fighting two separate conflicts. The Russians would take
villages, while the guerrillas would move around at night, taking a
toll with quick attacks. Initial military reports here echoed the
optimistic Russian approach publicized throughout the war in
Chechnya, with accounts of the enemy being surrounded and villages
swiftly retaken by Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, who visited Dagestan the day before his firing, said
Russia would not repeat the mistakes of Chechnya and that no
soldiers or civilians would die. But local Dagestan officials urged
Moscow to use overwhelming force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are faced with a very dangerous and clever enemy that will
do anything to meet their objective,'' said Mukho Aliyev, the
speaker of Dagestan's parliament. ``The goal of the militants is to
rip Dagestan out of the Russian Federation and set up an Islamic
Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the message of a statement issued by a council of
Muslim leaders, or Shura, that declared an independent Muslim state
of Dagestan governed by Islamic rule. The council called on all
Dagestani Muslims to ``fight until all the infidels are ousted from
the Muslim territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Dagestani leaders quickly denied that the Shura existed, and
blamed the statement on the rebels' Chechen backers. Aliyev said
that despite the povery and unemployment plaguing Dagestan, most
people, aware that Chechnya is even more lawless, violent and
impoverished, do not want to ally with the breakaway region. But he
added that Dagestan is vulnerable and seconded outgoing premier
Stepashin's remark Monday that Russia ``could lose Dagestan.''
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Putin emerged from a meeting with Yeltsin and said
Moscow had a plan to ``normalize the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin opened yesteray's meeting with Putin by asking about his
mood. ``Combative,'' Putin responded in his usual terse style.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, who is in the last year of his term, announced Monday
that he sees Putin, a former KGB agent who before his appointment
headed Russia's security service, as his favored successor in
presidential elections set for the middle of next year. But first
he has to be approved by parliament next Monday, a vote that
analysts and politicians said could go either way.
</P>
<P>
   How Putin handles the situation in the Caucasus may decide his
fate. Television showed Putin being greeted by Yeltsin, who asked
about his mood. ``Ready for battle,'' Putin replied tersely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation there is normalizing, but the situation is still
complicated,'' Putin said. ``The job can be fulfilled and will be
fulfilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting with this image of unity and decisiveness were
contradictory reports from the ground in Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   Since the rebels entered the region four days ago, Russian
officials have said their troops were preparing a full-scale
operation to push out the fighters. But as of Tuesday, only two
motor rifle brigades had been sent to the area of the fighting, the
newspaper Kommersant reported. At the moment, the insurgents were
faced by Dagestani police covered by military helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Special forces commandos should be fighting against these
well-trained militants, not police officers,'' said Aslanbekh
Aslakhanov, a former senior police official who now heads the
Russian Islamic Congress.
</P>
<P>
   General Viktor Kazantsev, arriving to take command of Russian
forces in Dagestan, said Russia was being cautious to avoid harming
civilians he said the militants were using as ``human shields.''
But Aliyev, the local parliament speaker, said the guerrillas had
no hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior Russian military officer, General Nikolai
Mikhailov, told the Interfax news agency that the situation in
Dagestan is different than the war in Chechnya because in the
current conflict, ``the people don't support'' the militants.
</P>
<P>
   But most Chechens in 1994 were against a war with Russia. Some
observers worry that the Dagestan conflict, handled the wrong way,
might lead to a new war.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this situation the biggest fear is a repeat of the
escalation that preceded the Chechen war, when the military, unable
to force the militants out of villages, launched massive airtrikes
against them, which led to numerous victims among the civilian
population,'' journalist Mirlad Fatullayev wrote in Nezavisimaya
Gazeta from Dagestan. ``Then the people joined the ranks of the
separatists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
