<SLUG> BC-ICUBE-RAZORFISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE-KNOWN 'NET CONSULTANTS TO MERGE IN $600 MILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rap on electronic-commerce is that profits are rare. But at
least one group of companies has already begun to earn big money
on-line: the consultants who help others set up shop on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   More evidence came Tuesday when I-Cube of Cambridge, Mass.
agreed to be sold to Razorfish Inc. of New York, for stock worth
about $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big price tag for I-Cube, a seven-year-old company known
to few even under under its previous name, International
Integration Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But I-Cube has earned more than $13 million since 1996, profits
Razorfish chief executive Jeff Dachis attributes to an
old-fashioned business model both his company and I-Cube have
pursued: selling consulting services for more than it costs to pay
a staff to provide them.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many pure Internet companies with unproven profit
sources, ``We're able to quantify this into basic mechanics,''
Dachis said.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two companies earned about $1.1 million during the
second quarter, or $3.3 million excluding certain charges, on
combined revenue of $33.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's in contrast to Amazon.com, one of the best-known
electronic-commerce companies, which reported a loss of $138
million for the same period on revenue of $314 million.
</P>
<P>
   Such losses may be unavoidable as big retailers build out their
brand names in cyberspace. But much of their spending is reflected
on the bottom lines of local players like I-Cube or its Cambridge
neighbor Sapient Corp., or the big Wellesley, Mass. office of
Anderson Consulting LLP.
</P>
<P>
   All are benefiting from the rush to offer electronic-commerce
services, said Judith Hurwitz, a consultant who serves the same
market. ``All businesses are facing electronic competition and they
have to play in this environment to compete,'' Hurwitz said. ``But
you have to clean up your house before you invite the neighbors in.
You have to make sure your model works and you're not going to do
an eBay.''
</P>
<P>
   The reference is to the San Jose, Calif-based Internet auction
service, which was forced off-line for nearly a full day in June by
a computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   Clients are anxious to avoid that outcome, but they also want to
move on-line quickly, said Meredith McCarty, senior analyst at
International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   She expects the market for Internet consulting and system
integration services to increase to $78.6 billion in 2003 from $7.8
billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of I-Cube, the company said it agreed to be acquired
by Razorfish in order to provide a fuller service line.
</P>
<P>
   I-Cube is best-known for its work connecting back-office
operations like databases with the Internet, for clients including
American Express and Shell International.
</P>
<P>
   Razorfish, meanwhile, develops what are termed ``front-end
solutions'' for the likes of Bank One and Charles Schwab, to allow
their clients to view their accounts on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   I-Cube employs about 400 people including about 200 at its
office in Cambridge, while Razorfish has about 600 workers.
</P>
<P>
   I-Cube chief executive Michael Pehl said the merger would not
lead to layoffs and suggested Razorfish will likely expand its
local presence instead.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for each of I-Cube's roughly 27.4 million
total shares to be exchanged for 0.875 shares of Razorfish.
</P>
<P>
   The New York firm's stock fell 3 1/4 in Nasdaq trading Tuesday
to close at 25, valuing each share of I-Cube at 21.88 apiece_a
slight premium over I-Cube's closing price of 19.875 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase is expected to be completed later this year pending
approvals from shareholders and regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Dachis will remain president and chief executive of the company.
I-Cube's Pehl will become chief operating officer of Razorfish,
effectively its second-in-command, and will join its board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Other I-Cube executives will also become board members, Dachis
said, though he declined to say how many seats I-Cube would
receive. I-Cube chief financial officer, Larry Begley, will take a
similar post at Razorfish.
</P>
<P>
   The company's current CFO, Sue Black, will become executive
vice-president for mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The companies declined to discuss specific impacts on earnings
expectations. Dachis said there would be an unspecified charge
against earnings related to acquisition costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
