<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2448 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DANDRIDGE-ART-2TAK     08-10 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DANDRIDGE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD'S FIRST BLACK GODDESS AND CASUALTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15)  
 (af)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ For a brief moment in the 1950s, Dorothy Dandridge
was a movie star who rivaled Marilyn Monroe and Ava Gardner. But
Dandridge's film career sputtered and she fell victim to personal
demons, tragedy and, perhaps most of all, bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   The first black woman ever nominated for an Academy Award as
best actress died penniless _ but still beautiful _ at the age of
42 in 1965. It's still unclear whether Dandridge took her own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw `Carmen Jones' when I was 18,'' recalled Halle Berry,
the star and an executive producer of HBO's ``Introducing Dorothy
Dandridge,'' which has its premiere on Saturday at 9 p.m. ``I was
home in Cleveland and I was watching a UHF station one afternoon
and I was mesmerized. I remember thinking, Wow! I had never seen a
black woman quite like that in a film.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berry said she went to the local library to research the
actress-singer and has never since stopped trying to assess,
understand and, yes, identify with Dorothy Dandridge.
</P>
<P>
   One result of that is a project that had been rejected over the
years by almost every movie studio in town. ``The answer was no,
no, no, and the very reason that I wanted to make the movie was the
very reason they didn't want to make it _ and that's because nobody
knew who she was,'' said Ms. Berry, 33, who is, even by Hollywood
standards, extraordinarily beautiful but whose career in films like
``Jungle Fever,'' ``Losing Isaiah'' and ``Bulworth'' has not been
an especially easy one.
</P>
<P>
   HBO welcomed the project. ``Halle's passion for it, her
commitment, was extraordinary from the outset,'' said Jeff Bewkes,
chairman of HBO. ``For us, it was the story of a groundbreaking
performer who lived a very interesting life in the larger cultural
context of what it was like to be a black entertainer. She couldn't
swim in the hotel she was performing at in Las Vegas. She was
refused access to restrooms at the very hotels at which she was
drawing large crowds. It was shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   So are the facts of Ms. Dandridge's life that serve as the basis
of the film, which was directed by Martha Coolidge and adapted by
Shonda Rhimes and Scott Abbott from the 1970 book ``Dorothy
Dandridge,'' by Earl Mills. Mills, her longtime manager, was, like
many men, admittedly infatuated with her.
</P>
<P>
   As depicted in the film, Dandridge was reared as a performer by
her mother, Ruby, an actress who appeared on the ``Amos 'n' Andy''
television series.
</P>
<P>
   Although the child blossomed into a charismatic, sexy singer and
dancer, her life was horrific almost from the outset. As a young
girl, she was abused by her mother's violent lesbian lover. Her
later love affairs were unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   While performing at the Cotton Club, she met the suave tap
dancer Harold Nicholas. Their marriage was strained and produced a
severely retarded daughter, whose condition left Dandridge
guilt-ridden for the rest of her life. Dandridge felt that she _
and her husband _ were somehow responsible for the child's
retardation because when Dandridge was in labor they got to the
hospital late.
</P>
<P>
   At a Hollywood party, Dandridge was discovered by Mills. He
secured an audition for her in 1954 for ``Carmen Jones,'' an
all-black musical melodrama based on the Bizet opera. She won the
leading role and began a five-year love affair with the film's
director, Otto Preminger.
</P>
<P>
   But as extraordinary as she was in the film, the roles that
followed were often tepid, because studios had no idea how to deal
with a black female star as opposed to Gardner or Monroe, who were
her friends in Hollywood (Dandridge was the first person Monroe
called when Joe DiMaggio left her). Preminger, who felt his career
would be destroyed if he married a black woman, walked out on her.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the affair with Preminger shattered her. ``He
abandoned her at a time when it really had a profound effect on
her,'' said Ms. Berry. ``He wasn't strong enough to stand up and
confess his love for her because of the racism of the time, and
says in the movie that neither of them would work again if it came
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he never really acknowledged her, and that devastated her.
When people are telling you that you're beautiful and great, but
the man you love is saying, `You're not good enough for me,' what
does that do to your psyche?''
</P>
<P>
   The career and personal troubles Dandridge endured hardly
diminished her charisma: she was a blend of elegance, beauty and
sexuality in films like ``Porgy and Bess'' and ``Island in the
Sun,'' a drama about racial strife in the West Indies, and in her
nightclub appearances. (Time magazine said that at a club
performance she ``came wriggling out of the wings like a
caterpillar on a hot rock.'')
</P>
<P>
   She was the first black woman to appear on the cover of Life
magazine and the first to appear at the Academy Awards as a
presenter. She was said to have had affairs with several men,
including Peter Lawford.
</P>
<P>
   She also defiantly fought the bigotry she found in clubs in
Miami Beach and Las Vegas and struggled vainly for Hollywood roles
that went beyond, as Ms. Berry put it, ``girls in banana hats and
curled slippers.'' (By contrast, Lena Horne, another black star,
appeared in MGM musicals but only as, say, a nightclub performer
and not as an actress with relationships to white characters.) But
Dandridge fought a losing battle.
</P>
<P>
   Her final years were deeply troubled. She had a brief marriage
to an abusive nightclub owner and was forced to pay off his debts
in a divorce settlement that left her bankrupt. Distraught and
without money, she had to hand over her daughter to the state to be
institutionalized.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dandridge became addicted to prescription drugs. On the eve of
leaving on a national nightclub tour in an effort to revive her
career, she was found dead in her home. The Los Angeles coroner's
office classified the death as an overdose of a prescription
antidepressant, Tofranil, but declined to rule it a suicide or an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   The team that made the film are not of a single mind on the
cause of death. Ms. Berry said: ``It is a mystery, but I am
inclined to believe, especially after playing her and looking at
some things that have happened in my life, that was she so
discouraged that she killed herself. Even though she had packed her
bags, I think, somehow, she had reached the end. She was just
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Coolidge, the director, disagrees. ``She was on the
upswing; she was about to leave for New York,'' she said. ``We will
never know the truth, but had she lived I think she would have had
a career.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rhimes, the screenwriter, who believes Dandridge did commit
suicide because she was just too weary to start her life all over
again, said, however: ``Until the end of her life she was a person
who never gave up. She was also a lady in the classic sense of the
word. The way she dealt with racism on the road _ always smiling,
very sweet, very calm. She never raised her voice, but in the end
she was as tough as nails.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berry, seated on the patio of a quiet Italian restaurant
near Beverly Hills, admitted that her longtime yearning to play
Dandridge was not merely a desire to make a statement about the
hardships of being a black actress. It was also a first-rate role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not really been able to be a leading lady in a film,''
she said. ``And it gave me a chance to do that.'' She shrugged.
``It's hard enough being an actress, but being a black actress __
'' The words drifted off. ``Now I've played Dorothy Dandridge, so
there's no other role for me to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berry grew up in Cleveland and dropped out of college after
a year to pursue a modeling career. That led her to New York, where
she took acting lessons. Her first acting role _ in ``Living
Dolls,'' a short-lived ABC series about fashion models _ began a
career that has been successful but not quite satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Her next role will be in a splashy, big-budget 20th Century Fox
film, ``X-Men,'' based on the comic book. ``I play a character
who's black in the comic book,'' said Ms. Berry, ``so it's not a
stretch for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how she, unlike Dorothy Dandridge, can refrain from going
over the edge, partly because of the frequent rejection for roles
solely because she's black, Ms. Berry said simply: ``I can't go
crazy. I can't. It's not even an option.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I value my life too much,'' she continued. ``And when I read
stories in history about the people before me, people who got up
every day and some of them had shackles on their feet and they
fought the fight, how could I even consider not fighting the fight?
I have a charmed life. How could I be so tired that I would go mad?
I have an opportunity to incite change and carry the ball. It's
almost a responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the film about Dandridge, which has consumed her for the
last few years, has, Ms. Berry said, lessened the frustrations of
trying to succeed as a black actress. One day, she said, there will
be a black female movie star who will equal the success of, say,
Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that I may not break through but I have to carry
the ball that I have, just like Dorothy, in her way, never broke
through but she carried the ball, too, and she made it possible for
me to be here,'' said Ms. Berry quietly. ``So I have to do my part.
And if I don't see my breakthrough, if it doesn't happen in my
lifetime, somebody else down the road will break through. And
perhaps I'll be able to play a part in that too, just like Dorothy
played a part in my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
