<HEADLINE>
STRIDE RITE TO CUT ADMINISTRATIVE JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A month after its new chief executive abruptly resigned, Stride
Rite Corp. said Tuesday it will cut about 125 positions from its
administrative staff in a bid to save $9 million annually and to
give its footwear business a sharper focus.
</P>
<P>
   Because some of the positions eliminated were already unfilled,
only about 70 people will lose their jobs, Stride Rite said.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 of the people losing their jobs work at Stride Rite's
headquarters in Lexington, Mass., which had employed 450 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Staff reductions are always difficult,'' said Myles J.
Slosberg, Stride Rite's interim chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Stride Rite has operated as several nearly
autonomous divisions putting out such footwear lines as Keds,
Sperry Top-Siders, and its namesake children's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Streamlining'' its administrative and sales staff by a 13
percent work force reduction should help the company to better
integrate and centralize various operations, Stride Rite said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes will bring more focus on integrating strategic
initiatives,'' said Diane M. Sullivan, recently promoted to Stride
Rite president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are important steps toward building earnings leverage
for the company going forward,'' said analyst Steven A. Richter of
Tucker Anthony Cleary Gull, who added ``This is very positive for
the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Stride Rite said it expected to record a third-quarter pretax
charge of $3 million for severance and other costs related to the
initiatives announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several years, Stride Rite has looked to lessen its
dependency on Keds, a brand subject to the whims of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   To this end, Stride Rite has entered agreements to market
footwear under such brand names as Tommy Hilfiger and Nine West
Kids.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Stride Rite hired James A. Eskridge to be its
chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Eskridge told Wall Street his mission was to make brand
acquisitions for the company.
</P>
<P>
   But Eskridge and Stride Rite's board apparently clashed, and
Slosberg, a member of the family that founded the company 80 years
ago, was brought in as interim chairman and chief.
</P>
<P>
   Stride Rite declined to comment on the progress of its search
for Eskridge's permanent replacement, though it said its long-term
strategy still includes ``prudent business acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   After Eskridge quit, Stride Rite re-examined its business, and
Tuesday's announcement was a result of that re-examination, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite management turnover, Stride Rite's business fundamentals
remain sound, analyst Richter said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to job cuts, Stride Rite announced plans to
repurchase an additional 2 million shares of its stock as it looks
to increase shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, company shares rose 1/16 Tuesday
to close at 8 7/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
