<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROKERAGES-MARKETPLAC     08-10 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKERAGES-MARKETPLACE-1050&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: REGULATORS PUT BROKERAGES ON NOTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Actions by state and national securities regulators
in recent weeks have brought increased and scrutiny to some
once-obscure corners of Wall Street. Although the cases are very
different, a common theme runs through them: Executives of
brokerage firms both large and small have to take more
responsibility for protecting the individual investor.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage firms that may have looked the other way as investors
were hurt either by fraudulent practices or by risky trading
strategies are being put on notice that such practices will no
longer be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the report on Monday from state securities
regulators on daytrading firms is a shot across the bow to
brokerage firms in the growing business of electronic stock
trading. Deceptive marketing practices, the downplaying of risks
associated with rapid-fire stock trading and other misconduct will
not be tolerated, the regulators made clear.
</P>
<P>
   And in a settlement last week with Bear Stearns Securities
Corp., which processes more investor trades than any other firm on
Wall Street, the Securities and Exchange Commission sent a message
to the nation's 185 clearing firms that they must be vigilant
against fraudulent practices at the smaller firms whose trades they
handle. This is a big change; clearing firms have escaped
responsibility for such activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our markets will remain strong only as long as people
recognize that their responsibilities extend beyond their narrow
self-interest,'' said Richard H. Walker, director of enforcement at
the SEC. ``And when their view becomes clouded, we will not
hesitate to remind them of their broader responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Central to the regulatory position is something known as
suitability, Wall Street terminology for the matching up of an
investor's needs or objectives with the appropriate investment to
help meet those needs. Internet stocks, for example, would not be
considered a suitable investment for an 80-year-old widow seeking
preservation of capital.
</P>
<P>
   A brokerage firm is required to make sure that an investment or
strategy is suitable to the client it is being recommended to. But
advances in technology have broken down some methods that brokerage
firms used in the past to ensure investments were suitable. Now,
anyone with access to a computer modem can trade stocks without
ever meeting a broker. Furthermore, investors executing those
trades electronically do not have the help of a responsible broker,
who might well ask an 80-year-old widow placing an order if buying
an Internet stock is such a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many online brokerage firms have argued that they
cannot possibly monitor the suitability of the investments their
clients are choosing in cyberspace. Furthermore, why should they
have to enforce suitability rules when their customers make their
own investment decisions?
</P>
<P>
   Suitability questions about daytrading are especially worrisome
to regulators. Although the marketing materials for day-trading
firms often say that the strategy is not appropriate for all
investors, many firms play down the risks.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators in Massachusetts, for example, filed an action
against All-Tech Investment Group, one of the nation's largest
daytrading firms, last December. A major part of the regulators'
case against the firm was that it essentially claimed in its
advertising that daytrading was suitable for just about anyone,
that the technique was easy and profitable. Without admitting or
denying the allegations, All-Tech agreed to stop doing business in
the state for two years and returned $228,000 to some of its
customers there.
</P>
<P>
   Some firms have even argued to regulators that they do not have
to meet the same suitability standards required of full-service
brokerage firms like Merrill Lynch and Paine Webber because as
daytrading firms they are not peddling stocks, but selling
computerized access to the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear to us that there is a large sector of the
daytrading community that has acted as though the suitability rule
does not apply to them,'' said Matthew Nestor, director of the
Massachusetts Securities Division. ``They hide behind the fact that
they are teaching a trading system. Too many daytrading firms have
created a legal fiction that these rules do not apply to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as improved technology brought daytrading into being, so
too did technology bring considerable growth to the nation's
securities clearing businesses. In recent years, these firms, which
process trades for small brokerage firms and administer their
customers' paperwork, were able to take on more and more smaller
firms as clients. Bear Stearns, the leader in the clearing
business, has 2,700 customer firms and says it clears trades in
over 70 countries, accounting for more than 10 percent of New York
Stock Exchange volume daily.
</P>
<P>
   By contracting with a larger firm that provides clearing
services and much-needed capital, thousands of small firms, also
known as correspondent firms, were able to set up shop. Some of
them committed huge frauds against the investing public, stealing
hundreds of millions of dollars through stock manipulation and
other securities law violations.
</P>
<P>
   Even as these frauds were being committed by the small firms,
some big firms in the clearing business argued that they bore no
responsibility for the activities of the correspondent firms'
employees. They were, after all, once removed from the practices
and only served as administrators or bankers to the firms. How
could they police hundreds of firms trading thousands of shares
each day? It was a dream combination: an exceedingly lucrative
business with virtually no strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, in the wake of the SEC's settlement with Bear
Stearns, clearing firms can no longer turn a blind eye to
fraudulent or other problem practices taking place at the firms
whose trades they process.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators say that most clearing firms already police their
correspondent firms' operations closely and well, so increased
scrutiny from the SEC is unlikely to have much of an impact on
them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   James M. Walsh, managing director of S.G. Cowen Securities
Corp., said that his firm already scrutinizes his clearing
customers carefully. Nevertheless, the SEC case will tie the
correspondent firm much more closely to the clearing firm. ``A
clearing firm must get into the mind of the correspondent firm,''
he said, ``not just to keep people from breaking the law, but in
large part to keep people from unknowingly doing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis D. Lowenfels, a lawyer at Tolins &AMP; Lowenfels in New York,
and Alan R. Bromberg, professor of law at Southern Methodist
University in Dallas, have written an article entitled
``Suitability in Securities Transactions'' to be published in the
August issue of The Business Lawyer, a publication of the American
Bar Association. A theme of the article is that in recent years,
advancements in technology have outpaced certain areas of
securities regulation. Now, that may be changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convergence of new technology, a hot stock market,
daytrading and microcap fraud have stimulated regulators to
re-examine the whole suitability doctrine,'' Lowenfels said, ``and
refashion it to meet the needs of today's marketplace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
