s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLA-BAFF-DANCE-2TAKE     08-10 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLA-BAFF-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT JACOB'S PILLOW, SCANT PATIENCE WITH THE PIETIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't ask Ella Baff, the newish executive director of the
Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival, to speak about ballet, modern dance
and ethnic dance. These are labels, in her opinion, that do not
evoke dance's ``variety and texture'' (two of her favorite words).
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the first season she has programmed at the famed
festival in the Berkshires, offers a hint of what she has in mind
for its future: namely, an ever-expanding view of dance that is
also increasingly international.
</P>
<P>
   The Bolshoi ballerina Nina Ananiashvili and her touring group
from Moscow, which open on Aug. 25, may have little in common with
the performers on today's programs: Hugo and Ines, experimental
mimes and puppeteers, and the Afro-Cuban group of dancers and
musicians Los Munequitos de Matanzas.
</P>
<P>
   Nor &UR;  &LR; is there any evident connection between Paul Taylor, whose
choreography was seen earlier this summer at the Pillow, and Batoto
Yetu, the acclaimed children's African-dance troupe from Harlem
that opens on Wednesday with young Portuguese guest artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each thing is very different from another at this festival:
that's the idea,'' Ms. Baff said recently in a telephone interview.
``If you try to offer a new and broad international palette, then
you have an expanding repertoire in dance that the audience might
find interesting. I'm looking for the best of what there is in the
whole world, from the Bronx to Burundi.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Pillow's eighth director since the death of its founder,
Ted Shawn, in 1972, Ms. Baff, 45, is less concerned with living in
the past than in dealing with a changing arts scene. Shawn
established the festival, in Becket, Mass., in 1933 as a home for
his company, Men Dancers.
</P>
<P>
   He later presented a relatively wide range of performers in
different idioms. But he had strong opinions about those who
followed him as a modern-dance pioneer; he was not interested in an
avant-garde reputation for the Pillow and its summer dance school.
</P>
<P>
   A major change came under Liz Thompson's leadership, from 1980
to 1990. Ms. Thompson built a second theater and expanded the
grounds and buildings. She also introduced performances and
residencies with cutting-edge choreographers, a policy continued by
her successors, Samuel A. Miller, Sali Ann Kriegsman and Ms. Baff,
who was appointed in 1997, oversaw the 1998 season planned by Ms.
Kriegsman. The Pillow, also under Ms. Kriegsman, retired a $4.8
million cumulative deficit in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Working today with an annual budget of $3.6 million, Ms. Baff
admitted to some ``Europe envy'' in that European festivals, thanks
to state subsidies, have greater choices in programming. But
box-office pressures should not come first at the Pillow, she
declared as she returned to her main theme of presenting ``dance in
all its definitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Warming to her subject, she went on, ``I like to travel, and
most people, when they travel, open up.'' Presenters, as some arts
producers call themselves, should have ``a healthy relationship
with the audience that encourages the kind of curiosity you have
when you travel,'' Ms. Baff said. ``You might feel vulnerable in a
strange town with no reference point. But the more you explore, the
more things look alive to you. It's a great state to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugo and Ines, for instance, use knees and other parts of their
bodies to create different characters and thus ``broaden an
audience's sense of movement,'' Ms. Baff said. Similarly, she would
like audiences to be aware of a variety of styles in African dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a specific repertoire,'' she added. ``I would like to
expose people to a wide range of dance. Much of it has been
presented in a limited way.''
</P>
<P>
   Music suggests how definitions can be extended. ``When I was a
child, the repertoire available to us is not what it is now. Think
of the early-music recordings alone. I'm concerned with what is
brokered to us, culturally. Dance is a little behind.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This may surprise audiences that are familiar not only with the
boundary-shifting esthetics of American experimental choreographers
but also with forms that range from Baroque dance to clearly
distinct styles from India.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one suspects Ms. Baff's enthusiasm lies in her belief that
there is always something over the horizon to be explored. The
audience, she also believes, can be enriched on this journey
through the kind of multiple activities that are part of the total
Pillow experience: pre- and post-performance talks (often with the
choreographers involved), opportunities to view films and videos,
and free performances and events on an outdoor stage in the
festival's ``Inside/Out'' series. At one event, Taylor read from a
novel he is writing.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what were the benefits of all this information
channeled, if not stuffed, down a spectator's eager throat, Ms.
Baff replied, &UR;  &LR; ``Knowledge and interaction &UR; . &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe in patronizing audiences,'' she continued.
``There are hazards, as we've learned from hyper-academe. You can
intellectualize out the authentic experience. But I want people to
be engaged in an art form. It stimulates discussion when people
talk to each other about art. We should never get so jaded that we
lose that impulse to share.''
</P>
<P>
   As in past years, the Pillow has acted as a service organization
to the public and artists alike. Ms. Baff, who lives in nearby Otis
with her husband, John Badanes, a clinical pharmacist, is involved
in the festival's year-round activities, which include programs in
local schools and at Mass MOCA (the Massachusetts Museum for
Contemporary Art) in North Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Support to selected choreographers at various stages of their
careers is a prime goal. This summer, residencies (studio space,
housing, meals) have been provided to the New York-based
choreographers Wally Cardona and Ben Munisteri as well as Kota
Yamazaki from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The festival school occasionally integrates its sessions into
the performance series. Students in a three-week workshop were
taught choreography from different stagings of ``The Rite of
Spring.'' Taylor's version was performed by his company and Ms.
Baff invited the pianist Peter Serkin to coach the two fellowship
students from Tanglewood who played for Taylor. ``I want more live
music in the theater,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baff's own introduction to theater, music and dance came
early. Her older sister, Regina Baff, became an actress. As a child
in New York City, Ms. Baff studied piano, violin and harp. She
attended the Martha Graham school and continued in ballet and
modern dance with other teachers before graduating from the
University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   At Cal Performances, the arts presenting organization there, she
was director of education and community programs and then program
director. Among her other activities was teaching dance and theater
in juvenile prisons. ``It was a really remarkable experience that
is deep within me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The same faith in exposure to the arts can be sensed in her view
of the Pillow experience. ``You get to be in close proximity to
artists who are working here,'' she said. ``This is where dance
lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
