<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-GUNS (Washington) _ Education Secretary Richard Riley
says efforts to counter violence in schools are paying off and
students are getting the message that guns have no place in school.
He cited a new Education Department report showing that 3,390
students were expelled for taking firearms to school during the
1997-1998 school year, the most recent year available. The number
was 31 percent lower than the previous school year, when 5,724
students were expelled. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-2000 (Houston) _ Democratic presidential candidate Bill
Bradley addresses the Urban League and meets with black leaders in
Houston. The former New Jersey senator also campaigns in the South
Texas city of McAllen. By LORI RODRIGUEZ and ALAN BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-2000 (Des Moines, Iowa) _ We chronicle the campaign day of
Republican presidential hopeful Elizabeth Dole in advance of the
Iowa straw poll this weekend. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-MARS (Undated) _ Scientists say the latest pictures of the
Red Planet taken by NASA's orbiting Mars Global Surveyor reveal a
more dynamic atmosphere than previously thought _ dust devils,
winds that sculpt sand dunes, and frost that comes and goes with
the seasons. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   FETUS-FIGHT (Houston) _ Doctors caring for the unborn child of a
woman on life support cannot find a heart beat for the fetus and
believe the child has died in the mother's womb. The parents of the
woman are asking a court to allow them to turn off life-support
machines. The common-law husband who said he fathered the child
successfully argued for guardianship last week to prevent the
machines from being turned off. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   SPANISH-ONLY (El Cenizo, Texas) _ Leaders of this town on the
banks of the Rio Grande defend an ordinance that requires all local
government business to be transacted in Spanish, and another law
that calls for firing any municipal employee who helps the Border
Patrol apprehend illegal immigrants. By DANE SCHILLER. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL-HEALTH (Austin, Texas) _ A surprising shortfall of $30
million in this year's revenues for the state's mental health
agency could lead to cutbacks in services statewide by Sept. 1. Key
legislators and officials with the Texas Department of Mental
Health and Mental Retardation are scrambling to find a way to avoid
cutting services to the mentally ill. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-PROFILING (Houston) _ Mayor Lee Brown and the Houston
Police Department plan to unveil Wednesday a new policy designed to
root out ``racial profiling'' in the country's fourth-largest city.
Some officers say the plan is farsighted and will be copied by law
enforcement agencies across the country. By S.K. BARDWELL. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington )_ Christian Coalition President Pat
Robertson, the preacher and former GOP presidential candidate, this
week urged the federal government to drop its anti-assassination
policy and ``send a squad in to take out somebody like (accused
terrorist) Osama bin Laden....'' He added, ``I don't see anything
unchristian about it.'' Well, a lot of others do. Besides, we
adopted that policy decades ago partly out of self-preservation; if
we set out to assassinate foreign leaders we don't like, they may
want to assassinate our's first. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   (Note: Marianne Means will be on vacation until Thursday, Aug.
19.)
</P>
