<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela: Military Leader Ousted
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to further consolidate his control over the
military, President Hugo Chavez has fired the commander of the
army, Gen. Noel Martinez Ochoa, and replaced him with the
presidential chief of staff, Gen. Lucas Rincon Romero. Chavez, a
former army colonel, gave no reason for the change other than to
say that some of Martinez's activities were being investigated, but
news reports said the army commander has been implicated in tapping
the telephones of other military officers.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia: American Security Mission
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. delegation including senior State and Defense Department
officials has arrived in Bogota to discuss the worsening political
and military situation with President Andres Pastrana and Colombian
security officials. The two-day visit of the delegation, led by
Undersecretary of State for Political Affairs Thomas Pickering,
follows visits to Colombia in the past two weeks by President
Clinton's top anti-drug official and the chief of the U.S. Southern
Command, as well as proposals that American military and anti-drug
aid to Colombia be quadrupled to $1 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone: Final Hostages are Freed
</P>
<P>
   Anti-government forces released all of the remaining hostages
who were taken last Wednesday about 40 miles east of Freetown,
including U.N. employees, aid agency workers and West African
peacekeepers. The kidnappers were former government soldiers who
had been allied with Foday Sankoh's Revolutionary United Front, but
said that they felt they had been forgotten in the recent agreement
to end the country's eight-year war.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   South, North Korea: Bodies to be Returned
</P>
<P>
   North Korea agreed to accept the bodies of two North Korean
flood victims that washed into the South during heavy floods last
week, South Korea said. They were the first bodies of drowned
citizens that North Korea agreed to accept since 1996. The bodies
of eight flood victims that had washed into South Korea since then
were cremated and buried in the south.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
