<HEADER>
A2459 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERITAGE-COX     08-10 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERITAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heritage students want return to routine
 &HT;    By Will Anderson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKDALE COUNTY, Ga. _ Heritage High School students return to
class today, nearly three months after a troubled teen opened fire
on his classmates, wounding six.
</P>
<P>
   But students, including some of those injured during the May 20
melee, said they are ready to get on with their education, and
don't want to focus on what happened months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally fine with it,'' said Brian Barnhardt, a junior who
was injured during the shooting. ``I went back the Monday after the
shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Barhardt, who testified in a court hearing Monday to determine
whether Anthony ``T.J.'' Solomon should be tried as an adult or a
juvenile for the shootings, said he remains angry at the
15-year-old Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't plan to forgive him,'' he said. ``He needs to go to
jail for the rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Barnhardt, Brian's father, said his son is apprehensive
about returning to the 1,400-student school, even though he may not
admit to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's nervous about going back. It's inevitable, but you have
to do it,'' Barnhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   School officials held an open house for new students Monday,
which was closed to news media. Media also will be kept off the
campus today, said Heritage High Principal Lowell T. Biddy. Biddy
said he wants the first day back to be a regular school day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the majority of the people feel good about being
here,'' Biddy said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents say they are ready for things to return to normal, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a good day if everybody would leave the kids
alone,'' said Mike Cheek, whose son, Jason, was one of the injured
students.
</P>
<P>
   Cheek, who sat through two days of testimony in juvenile court,
said the Heritage shooting was in part a copycat of the Colorado
school massacre on April 20. And he's tired of all the attention
that the shootings have gained.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the type of exposure these young people don't need,''
Cheek said. ``Unless everybody works together, we're going to keep
seeing this. And every time we do, we relive it.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Anderson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
