<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2460 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AVIGNON-FESTIVAL-$ADV     08-10 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVIGNON-FESTIVAL-$ADV15-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVIGNON FESTIVAL RINGS WITH INTERNATIONAL FLAIR, STUMBLES WITH
LOCAL OFFERINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Aug. 15)  
(yn) 
 By ANNE MIDGETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVIGNON, France _ Within the medieval walls of Avignon, the Rue
Republique cuts through the tangle of streets to the central Place
de l'Horloge and the broad white square in front of the Papal
Palace. Now, street and squares are a solid mass of people.
</P>
<P>
   Among the throngs are actors with outlandishly painted faces,
jugglers, men twisting balloons into animal shapes, mimes standing
motionless on soapboxes. A group of African drummers weaves
through, passing out fliers and singing.
</P>
<P>
   As a backdrop, every available surface is plastered with posters
advertising theater events, from Marguerite Duras plays to
circuses. The bright logos and graphics blend into a colorful
wallpaper or, hanging from lampposts in sheaths of plastic, flap
like the flags of unknown countries in the wailing gusts of the
mistral.
</P>
<P>
   ``For three weeks,'' says Alain Leonard, the director of the
Festival Off, Avignon's answer to the Edinburgh Fringe, ``the whole
city of Avignon becomes one big theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avignon Festival itself is the largest theater festival in
France. In its 53rd season this year, from July 9 to 31, it
presented more than 50 works of theater and dance in 23 spaces in
and around the city, from an old quarry eight miles out of town to
the traditional open-air stage of the Cour d'Honneur in the Papal
Palace.
</P>
<P>
   While French-language theater still accounts for more than half
of the program, this year's festival included a special focus on
South America, as well as works from Bulgaria, Italy and Germany.
Companies not invited to the main festival come at their own
expense to the Festival Off, and this year 550 did.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since it began in 1947 with Shakespeare's ``Richard II,''
Paul Claudel's ``L'Histoire de Tobie et Sara'' and a brand-new work
by a young author named Maurice Clavel, the Avignon Festival has
walked a fine line between old and new, provocative and popular
and, more recently, between focusing on France and moving into the
international arena.
</P>
<P>
   This year's season opener was ``Henry V,'' which had never been
performed in France perhaps because it shows the English triumphing
over the French. The critics were reserved; the public
enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum was ``Voyage au bout de la
nuit'' (``Voyage to the End of Night''), an adaptation of Celine's
novel by an Italian company, Societas Raffaello Sanzio. The
production focused on, among other things, the cadaver of a dead
horse, prompting both catcalls and bravos on its opening night.
``Avignon has had its scandal,'' Le Monde and other papers reported
with satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two audiences,'' said Bernard Faivre d'Arcier, who
has directed the festival since 1992 and led it from 1980 to 1984
as well. ``There is a more popular audience, which isn't much of a
connoisseur, which likes theater but is a little scared of the
critics and the Parisians. Then there is an audience composed of
real connoisseurs. So one has to bring these two together, combine
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the start of the festival,'' he continued, ``the audience
is more regional, so you have a production like `Henry V.' After
July 14, Bastille Day, when everyone goes on vacation'' _ heads
south, that is, from Paris to Avignon _ ``we do more divisive, more
provocative things: Angelin Preljocaj'' _ the contemporary ballet
choreographer _ ``or Raffaello Sanzio with Celine. And at the end
of the festival, we do a piece that brings everyone together.'' The
final work of the season was ``Tango, vals y tango'' by an
Argentinian choreographer, Ana Maria Stekelman.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, theater at the Avignon Festival was secondary.
The main event in 1947 was an exhibit of contemporary art in the
Papal Palace, and there was heated debate about placing work by the
likes of Bonnard and Picasso within those venerable walls. As an
added attraction, the popular actor and director Jean Vilar was
invited to stage one of his signature pieces, ``Murder in the
Cathedral.'' He proposed Shakespeare, Claudel and Clavel instead. A
welcome move toward decentralization _ transporting culture to
areas outside Paris _ the event was a success. ``Thanks to Jean
Vilar, Avignon may be able to give us a festival of theater the way
we have festivals of film,'' said the newspaper Le Figaro.
</P>
<P>
   In more than two decades as the festival's founder and director,
Vilar sought to bring new life to French theater and at the same
time create a dialogue with the distinctive architecture of the
medieval city. Today, however, festivals are less local than
international, and Avignon is no exception. The increasing number
of companies from abroad reflects a general trend, but it is also
an invitation for additional foreign spectators. While foreigners
accounted for only about 10 percent of the 115,000 tickets sold
this year, the exoticism of special programs devoted to Asia (last
year) or South America could attract wider audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The tango seems to be a trend these days, from California to
Switzerland. And in ``Pernambouc,'' Antonio Nobrega presented a
history of northern Brazilian popular music with the help of a
band, a clown and even a woman in a monkey suit, until the
audience's rhythmic clapping echoed off the cliff walls of the old
quarry, luminous in the moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   An even better synthesis of the popular and the highbrow was
``Auto da Paixao'' (``Mystery of the Passion''), also from Brazil
and performed in the gardens of the cathedral at midnight. Carrying
candles, the audience followed a group of dancing, folk-singing,
torch-bearing women up the dark paths, stopping at shrines by the
sculptor Romero de Andrade Lima, as if they were a new
interpretation of the Stations of the Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Every critic singled out for praise the director Thomas
Ostermeier, a rising star in Berlin, who brought three pieces,
including Mark Ravenhill's English morality tale, ``Shopping and .
. . ''
</P>
<P>
   Also strong was ``Maistora i Margarita,'' the Bulgarian Stefan
(Teddy) Moskov's adaptation of the classic Bulgakov novel. Moskov
used video clips, screens and well-timed slapstick to turn the
actors into cartoon-like figures who somersaulted through the air
or stood against a screen like sketches on a sheet of paper that
could be scribbled on or torn in two, as the author, seated at his
typewriter to one side of the stage, pondered what to do with them
next.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The festival makes a less convincing case for French theater.
Faivre d'Arcier has been faithful to a cadre of artists who return
to Avignon time and again: the young director and author Olivier
Py; the formidable and complex playwright Valere Novarina, or
Preljocaj. The latter's new work, ``Personne n'epouse pas les
meduses'' (``One Shouldn't Marry the Medusas''), was filled with
interesting ideas but lacked a compelling artistic flow, like an
elaborate new dish in a restaurant that boasts a wide range of
ingredients but no particular flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``To know a painter or an author well,'' said Faivre d'Arcier,
``it takes time, it takes years. You have to follow an author,
accompany him. In my opinion, Novarina is a great French author,
but it takes a number of years to explain his work and create a
loyal public.'' The impenetrability of Novarina's text in
``L'Operetta Imaginaire'' illustrated some of the differences
audiences could have with him, although the piece, with its
accordion accompaniment and send-ups of stock characters, was also
very funny.
</P>
<P>
   Py is a particular pet of Faivre d'Arcier's, but from Py's work
at this year's festival, it was hard to tell what the fuss was
about. ``Requiem for Srebrenica,'' true, was a thoughtful
presentation of a collage of journalistic pieces about the war in
Bosnia and eyewitness reports enacted by three woman on a floor of
echoing metal. But in the autobiographical ``Theatres'' that Py
wrote but did not direct, the protagonist (called simply Myself)
concluded with a long narration about the difficulties of his
generation and the artist's lot that was self-aggrandizing rather
than convincing.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Avignon Festival and the Centres Dramatiques, France's
national theaters like the one that Py now directs in Orleans, are
mainly financed by the French government. Py's success could
therefore be seen as relating to his approval from a certain circle
of state administrators as much as to widespread recognition of his
merits as an artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit as if university professors were to write novels
and books and then make sure everyone read only the novels and
books they wrote,'' said the author and actor Andre Benedetto about
the country's cultural administration in general. ``Like an army
corps, we also have a culture corps, a group of people out to
administer art _ `art' being what they say it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Benedetto, whose Theatre des Carmes is one of three in Avignon
that is active year round, was also one of the initiators of the
Festival Off, in which he participates every year. In the late
1960s, when theater troupes began coming unbidden to perform in
Avignon during the official festival, the Off (the term was adopted
to echo Off Broadway) was ``a challenge to the festival,
esthetically and politically,'' Leonard said. As the director of
the Festival Off, he created a more formal structure in 1982.
``Today,'' he said ``it is more a chance for companies to present
themselves than a political statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Off doesn't turn anyone away, be it Korean actors,
Shakespeare in a Gypsy caravan, or Benedetto performing the
monologue ``San Jorgi Roc,'' a miner's moving soliloquy to his dead
brother about their shared heritage. It was rendered all the more
poignant through its unintelligibility to a good part of the
audience, since it is not in French but in Provencal.
</P>
<P>
   ``My principal goal,'' said Faivre d'Arcier, ``is that the
festival produce its own projects, more and more.'' He would like
to have more works like ``Le Cid'' of last year, by the Anglo-Irish
director Declan Donnellan, which the festival produced and then
toured around the world, with well-received performances at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music in April.
</P>
<P>
   Faivre d'Arcier is a reminder that festival administrators today
are increasingly like chefs: not artists themselves, but with more
and more pressure on them to bring together the right combinations
of ingredients _ pop singers and actors, film directors and operas
_ to create the requisite buzz of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Avignon has all the ingredients for a successful
millennial season next year: Eastern Europeans, a production of
``Medea'' with Isabelle Huppert, and the ubiquitous equestrian
troupe Zingaro. Such combinations are generally guarantors of good
ticket sales. But this year's festival also demonstrated that,
however safe your bets, however generally good your shows, there is
no guarantee that the ingredients in your recipe will combine into
that rarity: true artistic excellence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
