<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2468 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARASZTY-DESIGNER-ART     08-10 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARASZTY-DESIGNER-ART-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSICAL FURNITURE UPSTAGED BY FLOWER POWER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Mitchell Owens is the senior interior design editor of Traditional
Home magazine.  
 By MITCHELL OWENS 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Necessity may be the mother of invention, but surely boredom is
part of the equation, too. What else but idle hands would drive an
otherwise sensible person to transform an icon of modernist
restraint into a giddy evocation of pure hippie chic?
</P>
<P>
   ``Eszter Haraszty had no respect for this stuff,'' said Liz
O'Brien, a leading Manhattan dealer of 20th-century furniture. In
her move last week from her Soho gallery to an eponymous new space
at 800-A Fifth Ave., Ms. O'Brien brought along one of Haraszty's
homemade reinventions _ a bentwood Thonet settee, painted shining
white and dressed in white linen embroidered with voluptuous
Iceland poppies.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much stitchery over stitchery, in fact, that each
flower is about an inch thick. Though the effect is entirely unlike
that intended by its Victorian manufacturer, Michael Thonet, the
settee, which is priced at $5,250, has a happy-face joie de vivre
that Ms. O'Brien called ``a perfect statement of its time.''
</P>
<P>
   Make that the 1960s, not the 1860s, when the steam-bent wood
furniture manufactured by the company Gebruder Thonet came into
international vogue. With her blond Twiggy-style crop,
Gabor-sisters accent, thigh-high skirts and bug-eye sunglasses,
Eszter Haraszty was an Age of Aquarius heroine, one part Carnaby
Street to two parts Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   Though her name is unknown today, the Hungarian-born Haraszty,
who died in 1995 at 74, was an American design guru in the late
1940s and early 1950s, thanks to the ebullient color sense and
swashbuckling patterns she championed as the director of
KnollTextiles, the fabric division of the modern furniture
comeditedpany started in 1937 by Hans G. Knoll.
</P>
<P>
   Just as quickly as she made her mark there, however, Haraszty
resigned. First, she married a television producer, and then she
abandoned Manhattan for Los Angeles, where Haraszty set to work
revamping an unprepossessing house in Coldwater Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   The cottage was recast as a paean to flower power. Fireplaces
were encased in yellow-and-white flowered tiles, thickly flowered
rugs paved the floors, and giant red poppies, Haraszty's favorite
flower, were painted on the cobalt-blue garage door. Out in the
garden, the designer and her husband built a petal-shape altar to
sunworshipping: six scarlet vinyl mattresses set atop individual
brick platforms, all radiating from a Chinese paper parasol painted
with giant red and pink blooms.
</P>
<P>
   The provocateur couturier Rudi Gernreich, he of the breastbaring
monokini, was enthralled by what he enthusiastically called her
``dreamflowernatureartenchantedgardenhouseworld.'' Equally stunned,
House Beautiful devoted 10 pages to the 56-year-old designer's
hippie haven in its May 1966 issue, celebrating what the article's
writer, Elizabeth Sverbeyeff, described as Haszarty's ``blithesome,
blossoming world.''
</P>
<P>
   The cover was a closeup color photograph of a bouquet of orange
and red poppies bursting from a white pitcher that Haraszty
handpainted to match.
</P>
<P>
   The Iceland poppy was the designer's talisman (she also painted
them on her toenails): simple in shape and brilliant in color, its
petals as delicate as silk gauze and as bright as Kool-Aid. They
were, she wrote in her book ``Needlepainting: A Garden of
Stitches'' (Liveright, 1974), ``the purest, the most brilliant and
translucent colors I've found in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she had dismissed embroidery as a peasant's craft when
she was a child in Budapest, Haraszty took up her needles and yarn
again in 1960. Her first project was daunting in scale but a
triumph, after six months of work: embroidering a 10-foot-square
piece of white Belgian linen to create a cushion cover for a Thonet
chaise longue.
</P>
<P>
   Her next project, a sleeveless tunic, was less successful.
Weighing in at eight pounds, it proved unwearable. Chastened,
Haraszty framed the tunic and returned to her furniture, and soon,
every piece in the house _ old, new, antique, modern _ was
transformed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chrome and beige wicker, no matter how magnificent the lines,
seemed rather out of place in what might kindly be described as a
country house in search of a facade,'' she wrote. And, after all,
she reasoned, since the Bauhaus brigade, not to mention the Knolls,
had intended their furniture to be functional, and Haraszty could
only function surrounded by eyepopping colors, then reupholstering
the classic designs was entirely appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Stripped of its ponyskin upholstery, a Corbusier chaise longue
was dressed in needlework depicting purple and blue pansies.
Poppies bloomed on Brno chairs designed by her friend and fellow
Hungarian Marcel Breuer. Fist-size primroses covered the seat of a
Provencal side chair, poppies the size of bowling balls decorated
Sheraton arm chairs, and petunias erupted on the headboard of her
kingsize bed. And the settee exploded with poppies: orange, pink
and red, each petal executed in satin stitches and each stamens in
pert French knots.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Thonet settee is a turn-of-the-century original or a
reproduction purchased in the 1960s is unknown. In any case,
Haszarty did not care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faithful Thonet reproductions are on sale everywhere at very
reasonable prices,'' the designer wrote, echoing the practical
beliefs of the early modernist movement. ``In short, if you like
the atmosphere of our living room and find it out of the ordinary,
the look is one which all can afford.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
