<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR SAYS HE HAD NO VENDETTA AGAINST CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In one of his most candid discussions about his
lengthy inquiry, Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr on Tuesday
insisted that he was never motivated by a personal or political
vendetta against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense that this was a match between two
individuals; it wasn't,'' Starr said in an interview broadcast
Tuesday on NBC's ``Today'' program. ``It should not have been
viewed that way. It should not have been portrayed that way. It was
a professional process, and it was done professionally.''
</P>
<P>
   That process, of course, led to the impeachment of Clinton, but
Starr said there were no winners in the deeply bitter and divisive
battle that his prosecutors waged with the White House. Instead, he
called it ``a very sad chapter in our recent history'' that had
``cost the country terribly.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time, Starr was highly critical of Monica
Lewinsky, saying she was oblivious to the profound consequences of
her affair with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very immature,'' Starr said, ``and I think failed to,
in any way, appreciate the gravity of what she was doing,
including, frankly, assisting in the process of putting our leader,
who has to accept his own responsibility, in the most unfortunate
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr refused to characterize his view of Attorney General Janet
Reno. After lavishing praise on the ``honorable, decent people''
who work as career prosecutors at the Justice Department, Starr
declined to say anything about his opinion of Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you won't say the same thing about the attorney general?''
Lisa Myers, a correspondent for NBC News, asked Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to comment,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   `You leave the impression that you do not believe that she's
been honorable and decent throughout this,'' Ms. Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm simply not going to comment,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr may have simply believed it was inappropriate to discuss
Reno because the Justice Department has told Starr's office that it
plans to investigate the ethics of his office's Lewinsky
investigation, including prosecutors' questioning of Ms. Lewinsky
at the outset of the inquiry. The Justice Department is also
examining whether Starr failed to disclose possible conflicts of
interest in January 1998 when he asked Reno to expand his
jurisdiction to investigate the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Starr refused to comment about whether he would seek indictments
of anyone before he concludes his inquiry, which he estimated would
be concluded, with the filing of a final report, before the
November 2000 elections. That report, Starr said, would not
criticize anyone, including Hillary Rodham Clinton. ``There will be
no trashing of anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could rule out any future indictments, Starr said,
``I think what I need to do is assiduously say, I can't comment.
And there should be no inference one way or the other drawn from my
inability to comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr also spoke candidly about his own personal and
professional regrets, saying that his office ``made a number of
miscalculations with respect to public appearances.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think in the process of remaining silent, we allowed a
sense to develop that there were other motivations at work,'' Starr
said. ``And I think that's most _ most unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   And he added that the inquiry had taken a deep personal toll.
``Many times I thought, good grief, this whole mechanism of the
independent counsel statute is fraught with potential for mischief,
all kinds of defects,'' said Starr, who added that he hopes to
return for private law practice and continue to teach a law school
class.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Starr testified before a Senate committee that the
independent counsel law should not be renewed. It expired June 30,
just one day after Starr's office announced a plea agreement with
its last remaining defendant, Webster Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   Starr was asked if he believed there were ``any winners'' in his
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't,'' he said. ``But I do know this _ it cost the
country terribly. It caused my colleagues, my friends, a lot of
distress. And it's just a very sad chapter in our recent history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
