<HEADER>
A2492 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACID-HOUSE-FILM-2TAKE     08-10 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACID-HOUSE-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER `TRAINSPOTTING,' A TRUER, DARKER COMIC VISION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 David Bahr is an arts and culture writer based in New York.  
 By DAVID BAHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its savvy soundtrack, cypnotic direction and a charismatic
cast of heroin-hooked hooligans, the 1996 film ``Trainspotting''
made substance abuse look like exhilarating fun. Based on the
Scottish writer Irvine Welsh's novel of sex, drugs and rock `n'
roll, the film was a seductive tour through life's skids.
</P>
<P>
   From its rapid-fire opening scene following a pack of fleeing
thieves (accompanied by Iggy Pop's ``Lust for Life'') to its
lulling evocation of an overdose (to the tune of Lou Reed's
``Perfect Day''), ``Trainspotting'' transformed Welsh's bleakly
comic narrative into a toe-tapping head trip worthy of MTV. Yet it
was precisely that slick sensibility that Welsh intended to avoid
when asked to write the screenplay for ``The Acid House,'' his
second work to be brought to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think commercially,'' said Welsh. ``I wanted to
do a movie that was a bit more hard-core. I wanted to make less of
a stylized pop video and more of a rock `n' roll art film where
everyone was a bit dotty, badly dressed and on the out.''
</P>
<P>
   What he wanted to make was a film more faithful to his fiction,
where being ``on the out'' is a way of life and black humor remains
the only respite. ``The Acid House,'' which opened on Aug. 6, is a
triptych of three short films _ and certainly truer to Welsh's work
in terms of tone and setting than Danny Boyle's ``Trainspotting,''
written by John Hodge.
</P>
<P>
   The language is coarser, with salty Scottish slang and
accompanying subtitles. The humor is darker, and, certainly in the
first two shorts, there's a fuller, albeit gloomier, sense of
working-class Edinburgh. And while the soundtrack boasts a rich
roster of contemporary British rock acts (Oasis, Beth Orton and
Belle &AMP; Sebastian all contribute tracks), the music doesn't drive
the narratives as much as it enhances them.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three shorts, the first, ``The Granton Star Cause,''
about a hapless young man who loses his home, girlfriend and job
before being transformed into a fly by God, and the third, ``The
Acid House,'' a hallucinatory tale of a man who switches identities
with an infant, are closer to the movie ``Trainspotting'' in their
use of Kafkaesque visuals. (That movie's more fantastical elements
included a character who dives through a dirty toilet into an
underwater netherworld and a head-spinning, wall-climbing baby.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``The Acid House'' centerpiece, ``A Soft Touch,'' about a
gullible galoot and his sadistic wife, is cinematic realism in the
vein of Mike Leigh or Ken Loach. Stark and moody, its
character-driven script and strong ensemble performances offset the
other two shorts' fantastical elements.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the three films provide a vivid showcase of the
40-year-old Welsh's imaginative breadth, even if they don't
necessarily cohere within a thematic framework.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Usborne, a co-producer of the film along with David Muir,
said he chose the three stories for their distinct strengths, not
because of any related subject matter. Having been ``blown away''
after reading Welsh in 1994, Usborne said, he tried to obtain the
film rights to ``Trainspotting,'' but Boyle beat him to it by a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Usborne then quickly optioned ``The Acid House,'' a collection
of short stories. ``I wanted to make a film 100 percent pure to
Irvine's vision,'' he said. ``With every rude word and a strong
sense of place.''
</P>
<P>
   A producer of documentaries before coming to Welsh's fiction,
Usborne chose the documentarian and Glasgow native Paul McGuigan to
direct ``The Acid House,'' even though McGuigan had never worked on
a drama before. ``I wanted the director to be Scottish and have a
good feeling for the place,'' Usborne said. ``Paul did some strong
documentary films, and I think that making documentaries is as good
a training as you can get. You get a lot of information and have to
hew it out, make it really sharp. You develop a smell for the
real.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At first McGuigan was signed to direct only ``The Granton Star
Cause.'' The goal was to make that film and use it to raise money
for rest of the project. A year after its completion, and some
positive film festival feedback, Usborne got Britain's Channel 4 to
finance ``A Soft Touch'' and ``The Acid House,'' with McGuigan
returning as director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only expected to make the first one,'' said McGuigan, who
previously shot three installments of Channel 4's documentary
series ``Walk on the Wild Side,'' about youth on British society's
edge. ``So I made it as mad and wild as I could, with no fear of
letting anyone down.'' It was after he was asked to direct the next
two films that his apprehension grew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first and third films were easier to do,'' he said. ``But
`A Soft Touch' required me to represent working class life in a
very true way. It actually suited my style, which comes from doing
documentaries, but my expectations were greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the same vision of authenticity with the screenwriter
and producer, McGuigan was given free rein. ``They just let me
go,'' he said. ``Irvine was fantastic. I'd say, `Can we change
something?' And he'd be `yeah, yeah no bother.'''
</P>
<P>
   Welsh said: ``I'm pretty easygoing. Some people think a little
too easygoing. But I can let someone else do the film because I see
it as their project. My thing is the books. And I get my stories
from where I live and the people I grew up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the three films, both Welsh and McGuigan prefer ``A Soft
Touch,'' viewing it as a maturer, more layered work that best
reflects the hard-knock life they knew while growing up in
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   The story stars an affecting Kevin McKidd as Johnny, a
child-like lug who marries Catriona (the captivatingly baleful
Michelle Gomez), a cruel part-time prostitute with an even more
pugnacious bunch of brothers. Soon after the couple's shotgun
wedding (where half the male guests are suspected of impregnating
the bride), Catriona starts sleeping with a neighbor, Larry (an
elastic-faced Gary McCormack), a crazed bleach blond with a
penchant for practicing martial arts naked in front of the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Johnny is really a bit of a masochist,'' said Welsh.
``He gets off on the powerlessness of the situation. At the same
time, he wants to be one of the boys. There's a definite macho
culture in Scotland. There are a lot of Larrys.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath its pitch-black humor, Welsh sees his work as a
testament of human tenacity. ``People get beat up and knocked down
and they just go on,'' he said. ``There is a real will to
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Released in Britain in January, ``The Acid House'' may have
proved too darkly comic to rouse ``Trainspotting'' fans. According
to Usborne, its accumulated gross in Britain was only $500,000 as
compared to the $5 million earned by ``Trainspotting.''
</P>
<P>
   Welsh cites the weather. ``It opened the day after New Year's,''
he said. ``It was cold and damp and everyone was hung over. I found
the movie really depressing. I remember seeing it at a summer
festival and the audience really went wild over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Usborne concurred. ``Irvine believes his work plays best when
people have a little sunshine in their bones,'' he said. ``I'm
inclined to believe him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
