<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2504 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COPLEY-TEVA-BOS &LR;      08-10 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPLEY-TEVA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEVA BUYS COPLEY IN $220M DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Copley Pharmaceuticals Inc., still recovering from a
drug-manufacturing scandal in which it paid millions in fines and
settled several class-action lawsuits, Tuesday said it will be
acquired by Teva Pharmaceutical Industries Ltd., Israel's largest
drug maker, for $220 milion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The sale ends the Canton, Mass. generic drug maker's
relationship with Hoechst A.G., which paid $546 million for a 52
percent ownership stake nearly six years ago. The German
pharmaceutical giant has been trying to sell Copley for more than
two years and recently shed another American generic drug company
in an effort to exit from the generic drug business.
</P>
<P>
   Teva said it is paying $11 a share for Copley, or one-fifth of
the $55 per share paid in 1993 by Hoechst. Teva is also buying a
more stable company that recently strengthened its management team
and its product line, which includes 52 generic products ranging
from skin lotions to prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (Copley) is pretty much a bargain,'' said Peter Terreri,
chief financial officer of Teva's US operations in Sellersville,
Pa. ``As the industry has changed a lot, prices for generic drug
companies have come down and we are getting a company that is now
prepared for growth,''
</P>
<P>
   Copley shares closed Tuesday at 10 13/16, up 1 15/16. About 1.18
million shares were traded, 30 times the company's normal volume of
36,000. Teva's American depositary receipts, each representing one
share, closed at 48 1/8, up 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Teva, which had $430 milion in revenues from its US operations
last year, said the acquisition of Copley, which reported $133
million in revenues in 1998, will help it create the country's
largest generic drug maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the US, Teva products will fill one out of every 16
prescriptions at retail pharmacies,'' said William A. Fletcher,
president of Teva USA, based in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Both Copley and Teva officials declined to discuss possible
layoffs or management changes. Terreri said he expects Copley,
which employs 460 people, will lose its corporate name. He said the
deal will probably close in October or November, following a
required review by the Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst still faces a series of legal challenges in connection
with its stake in Copley. Last May, two Copley shareholders accused
the German company of mismanaging Copley, causing the company's
shares to fall. Copley sales in the past three years have shrunk 6
percent, falling to $133.5 million last year. Last summer, two
Copley directors resigned, and one of them, Agnes Varis, blamed
Hoechst for causing a ``steady decline'' in Copley stock.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did Hoechst acquire its majority stake in Copley in
1993 than the company issued a recall of its albuterol drug, used
to treat asthma, after bacteria contamination caused by
manufacturing problems was found in some bottles.
</P>
<P>
   The firm was found negligent for not reporting the problem
sooner to the FDA and in 1997 paid a $10.65 million fine for
failing to tell the FDA about changes it made in drug production.
The fine is the largest ever paid by a generic drug maker. In 1995,
Copley settled a series of class-action lawsuits with users of the
asthma drug for $65 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Copley today is a very different company,'' said David F.
Saks, senior drug analyst and managing director of Gruntal &AMP; Co., a
New York investment firm. ``And looking back, Hoechst paid an
obscene price, and they are glad to get rid of it. But Copley has
only been rejuvenated in the last two years and that's what
probably appealed to Teva.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
