<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC HUDDLES WITH PARTY AS CHURCH BACKS OPPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ President Slobodan Milosevic attended a
rare strategy meeting of his Socialist Party here Tuesday
afternoon, apparently in response to the growing opposition
movement against him. A government reshuffle may be in the offing,
although Radio Television Serbia's report on the meeting revealed
no significant developments.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav president has found himself under increasing
pressure, as the notoriously divided Serbian opposition parties and
leaders have begun to show a new will to unite to remove him from
power. The Serbian Orthodox Church has added its weight, bringing
key opposition leaders together Monday and giving its backing to
their plans for democratic change in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Holy Synod, the highest body of the church, convened Tuesday
to discuss the church's role in political developments. Pushed by
outspoken members of the church in Kosovo, who have denounced
Milosevic's disastrous and cruel policies in the southern province,
the church is poised to take a prominent role in the move for
change in the country. The synod is expected to issue a statement
Wednesday on the results of its meeting.
</P>
<P>
   State media have been quick to criticize the opposition's
attempts to win the backing of the church. The state news agency,
Tanjug, and the main government newspaper Politika, denounced the
meeting, saying the opposition leaders ``are practically inducing
the church to violate the constitution,'' which they said
stipulates that the church is forbidden to engage in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The Socialist Party repeated its standard criticism of the
opposition politicians at its meeting Tuesday, calling them
``NATO's lackeys'' who are trying to bring down the government and
so achieve what NATO failed with its bombing campaign, RTS
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the party apparently intends to continue business as usual.
It appointed two new members to its executive council but otherwise
announced no changes in tactics or its program.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition groups meanwhile announced after Monday's meeting
that they will join forces for a mass rally planned for Aug. 19 in
Belgrade, and they pressed Patriarch Pavle, the head of the Serbian
Orthodox Church, to take part in a demonstration of unity with the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Holy Synod was considering Tuesday whether the patriarch
should attend the rally in person, and whether to meet another
request, to attempt to mediate between the government and the
opposition to find a political settlement, the Beta news agency
said, quoting opposition members.
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 19 rally is being organized by independent economists,
Mladjan Dinkic and Predrag Markovic, the creators of the Stability
Pact for Serbia, and is intended to unify the opposition movement
and channel the mood for change in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Patriarch Pavle chaired the meeting Monday of the key opposition
leaders, including Democratic Party leader, Zoran Djindjic, and Vuk
Draskovic, the head of the Serbian Renewal Movement. It will be the
first time in over two years that the two men will share a platform
together. Their bitter personal rivalry was blamed for the collapse
of the democratic movement in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders are united in calling for a peaceful demonstration,
and for the need for a transition government. Yet they remain
divided on how to bring it about and on the form of that
government. The authors of the Stability Pact for Serbia, and
others, in a plan that has the backing of the United States, insist
Milosevic must step down before any transition government can take
over.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party leader Zoran Djindjic is hoping the rally
itself will build a momentum of its own, describing it as ``a kind
of a referendum where people will have a chance to say whether they
are for changes.'' He warned that no compromise was possible with
Milosevic. ``After the 19th, Milosevic will have to realize that he
is out of time, it is the day when the countdown begins,'' he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But Draskovic questions how Milosevic's removal will come about.
He is arguing for a transitional government that includes some sort
of power-sharing deal with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Patriarch Pavle I oppose a government which would be
formed on the streets. We will not support such a government,
because it would deepen the agony and the divisions among the
Serbian people,'' he told reporters after Monday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The patriarch also met separately Monday with former Yugoslav
army chief of staff, Gen. Momcilo Perisic, who has founded his own
political party, the Movement for Democratic Serbia. Perisic, who
was dismissed from his post eight months ago, has called for
democratic change and for Milosevic to step down.
</P>
<P>
   The general has been criticized for not joining one of the
myriad existing democratic parties, but he could prove a potent
political figure amid the swelling ranks of the opposition
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition rallies have continued daily around the country
although attendance at some is only in the hundreds. The Aug. 19
rally, expected to draw thousands, will be watched as a measure of
the urgency of public discontent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
