<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS' ADVENTURE ENDS IN STABBING DEATH IN N.M. DESERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM AND CARLOS MONJE JR.  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Coughlin and Raffi Kodikian were on the adventure of a
lifetime, traveling cross-country together like characters in a
Jack Kerouac novel, a big carefree trip before new responsibilities
set in.
</P>
<P>
   But the adventure ended Massachusetts pair last week when their
travels took them to a remote corner of southeastern New Mexico. In
the scorching Carlsbad Caverns National Park, Kodikian, 25, stabbed
Coughlin, 26, twice in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian told police that after killing his friend he buried his
body and stayed close to the shallow grave until rangers found him
on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian said he and his friend had gotten lost, believed they
were dying of thirst, and that Coughlin, in unbearable pain, had
begged Kodikian to put him out of his misery.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian, a former Boston Globe editorial assistant, was charged
with an open count of murder Monday because authorities have not
determined how serious the charge against him should be.
</P>
<P>
   Following his arraignment on the open count Tuesday, Kodikian
was released on $50,000 bail and ordered not to leave the county.
</P>
<P>
   When rangers found Kodikian in a lean-to on Sunday evening, he
was suffering from dehydration and exposure.
</P>
<P>
   According to his mother Doris Kodikian who spoke with Kodikian
after his arrest, he asked rangers: ``What took you so long?''
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian led park rangers to his friend's buried body and told
them he had killed Coughlin after they both becane convinced they
were going to die.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin died from two knife wounds to the chest, one of which
pierced his heart, said Albuquerque medical examiner Tim Stepetic.
There were no signs of a struggle, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not determined what condition Coughlin was in
before Kodikian stabbed him. That will not be determined for a few
days, if ever, Stepetic said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Wellesley, Mass. Tuesday, a half-dozen cars stood
outside the home of Coughlin's parents, Robert and Joyce Coughlin.
``My family is grieving,'' said a male family member who declined
to give his name. ``We'd like some privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said the couple had three grown children _ David, his
brother and a sister.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Coughlin quit his job at Wellesley Town Hall and
was moving to California where he planned to study for a master's
degree in environmental science at the University of California at
Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   The road trip was to be a last hurrah before Coughlin began
dealing with the pressures of graduate studies, said Sandy Hobson,
who worked with Coughlin at Wellesley Town Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was looking forward to that trip,'' she said. ``All the
places he was going to stop and see. He had been born in Wellesley
and he just wanted to spread his wings and see the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The sandy haired, freckled, blue-eyed Coughlin, Hobson added,
was handsome, funny and popular at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all still in shock. We're trying to rationalize it but
it's impossible,'' said chief Wellesley assessor Donna McCabe. ``He
touched all of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin began working for the town four years ago while
studying resource economics at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst. After graduating in 1996, he worked in the selectmen's
office as a liaison between residents and town planners.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a wonderful sense of humor,'' said Planning Director
Richard H. Brown. ``There was a free and easy-going sense about
him, yet he was still very serious about his work.''
</P>
<P>
   So well-liked was Coughlin that a couple of weeks ago town
officials held a party to wish the former employee good luck on his
cross-country trip.
</P>
<P>
   His admitted killer was equally well-liked, impressing
co-workers at the Boston Globe where we worked as an editorial
assistant for about two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed happy, energetic, eager to please,'' said Linda
Matchan, a Globe reporter who edited his writing in 1996.``He had a
sweet nature, laughed a lot, and was very conscientious.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the Globe, Kodikian wrote a first person account
of a cross-country trip he had taken alone in 1997 after graduating
with honors from Northeastern University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid the excitement of the road had been run down,
paved over, washed away,'' he wrote. ``Still, I knew I had to
travel that road to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote an article for the Globe on the virtues of snakes
as pets; he owned a red tail boa. Matchan said he took editing
suggestions well and his writing improved.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, Kodikian played drums in a band that appeared in
clubs around Boston, but he gave up music when the opportunity came
to go on his first road trip, said Jonathan Pape, a fellow
bandmember.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a friend of Kerouac,'' Pape said. ``He loved the road,
that was nirvana for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pape, who also worked with Kodikian at the Globe as an editorial
assistant, said Kodikian could ``fly off the handle if things
didn't go the way he wanted at times, but a day later he'd turn
around and help you move. He went out of the way to be helpful. He
was the consummate sidekick.''
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian was known as much for his trademark thick ponytail as
for his personality. Lately, Pape said Kodikian had spoken of
cutting off that ponytail _ a symbol of youthful rebellion _ and
entering a new, mature stage in his life. He was going to send it
to his father to show him he was now growing up. His hair was short
at his arraignment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian worked in the correspondence department at
Massachusetts Financial Services a Boston investment firm, Pape
said. Another friend, Colin Hesketh, who works for the Globe web
site Boston.Com, said Kodikian was considering leaving his job and
moving to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin's co-workers said he delayed his trip so that his good
friend, Kodikian, could join him.
</P>
<P>
   The two arrived at Carlsbad Aug. 4, setting up camp in
Rattlesnake Canyon, in the Chihuahuan Desert. Park rangers say they
were scheduled to leave the park Aug. 6 and a search was begun
Sunday. They found Kodikian a mile from the nearest road and two
miles from the park's visitor center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlsbad does get hotter than hell down there,'' said
Stepetic. ``It seems they weren't prepared for that heat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
