<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANCE MEETING MAY HAVE LED TO TREASURY PLUNDER, PAPERS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was a chance meeting of two old Malden school
friends at a Frankie Valle concert on the Esplanade two years ago
that eventually led to a multimillion-dollar scheme to plunder the
state Treasury, according to an affidavit released in Boston
Municipal Court Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   John P. Trischitta, the supervisor in the Treasury's Unpaid
Check Fund, told investigators from Attorney General Thomas F.
Reilly's office last February that after meeting his chum, Martin
Robbins, again after about 30 years apart they worked out a scheme
to plunder the fund, the affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
   That scheme resulted in Trischitta in November 1998 steering
$6.5 million in funds due to a defunct Cambridge economic
development agency to Robbins on the basis of forged documents that
contended he represented the agency, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   On Trischitta's recommendation, Robbins had started an heir
finders' business in early 1998 that sought to locate missing state
revenue for companies and individuals. However, investigators have
found that Robbins gained the release of several of the checks on
the basis of fraudulent documents and, according to Trischitta,
shared some of the stolen money with him.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta and Robbins were arrested last February in connection
with the scheme. In early March, Reilly's investigators arrested
Deputy State Treasurer Robert Foley and a second heir finder,
Thomas Ciliberto, for carrying out a similar scheme, in gaining the
release of more than $2 million in checks from the Unpaid Checks
Fund on the basis of fraudulent documents.
</P>
<P>
   While the arrest warrants were dropped two months ago, a grand
jury continues to sit on the investigation in Suffolk County and,
according to informed sources, indictments are expected in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme began to unravel last Feb. 10 when a BankBoston
teller became curious about Robbins' attempt to withdraw the $6.5
million he had deposited in his account at the bank in November.
Within 48 hours, Trischitta provided State Police investigators
with the details of his alleged scheme with Robbins as well as his
knowledge of Foley's dealings. The details also provided the basis
for four State Police affidavits, one of which was released
Tuesday, which were used to search for evidence in Robbins'
condominium in New Hampshire and Trischitta's home in Stoneham.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta said that he had been an acquaintance of Robbins'
when the two were in separate high schools in Malden. Both were
interested in sports and Trischitta arranged for sports figures to
appear on a cable television station Robbins ran in Malden.
</P>
<P>
   After not seeing each other for decades, Trischitta said, he ran
into Robbins at the Frankie Valle and the Four Seasons performance.
A few months later, in January 1998, Trischitta said, Robbins
called him while he was at work and the two began talking about the
heir finder business.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, Trischitta was funneling to Robbins lists of the
names of companies and individuals who were owed money by the
state, and Robbins was submitting claims on the behalf of many of
them, according to the affidavit. In return, Trischitta said
Robbins paid him about $50,000 in ``kickbacks'' and had promised
him a one-third of the $6.5 million stolen with the Cambridge
Economic Development checks.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that Trischitta approved Robbins' claim for the
$6.5 million owed to the Cambridge agency, he also approved claims
for payment of far smaller checks which were due to Data General,
Brigham &AMP; Women's Hospital, and a group called High School/High
Skills. The investigators have been poring through those claims as
well as others submitted by Robbins to determine if they may have
been forged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
