<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK FALL BROADLY, BUT RECOUP SOME LOSSES LATE IN SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices staged a broad retreat Tuesday on
continued worries about rising interest rates. A late recovery
brought major market averages up from their lows for the session,
preventing what was a bad day from being even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Selling was broad-based, and the pace of business was fairly
brisk for a Tuesday in August, conditions that traders and analysts
said do not bode well for the market in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are probably in a very oversold condition,'' said Ned
Collins, head equity trader at Daiwa Securities America. ``But that
doesn't mean we can't be further oversold. This is not necessarily
a great time to think about markets rallying.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for a time Tuesday, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index was technically in a correction, having fallen 10 percent
from its July 16 high of 1418.18.
</P>
<P>
   But the index, which fell as low as 1,267.73 during the day,
bounced, and closed at 1,281.43, down 16.37 points, or 1.3 percent.
So far this year, the S&AMP;P 500 is up 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Weakness in IBM and J.P. Morgan were instrumental in driving
down the Dow Jones industrial average, which closed at 10,655.15,
down 52.55 points, or 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A late rebound in Internet stocks helped to limit the decline in
the NASDAQ composite index. Still, at the close the index was down
28.87 points, or 1.2 percent, to 2,490.11. Earlier in the day the
composite index had traded as low as 2,442.22.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the late swing in some stocks, there were plenty of
signs of weakness.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small-capitalization companies fell
3.07 points, or 0.7 percent, to 422.82. And the combination of
higher interest rates and rising energy prices hammered
transportation stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones transportation average fell 82.91 points, or 2.6
percent, to 3,137.54. The average peaked May 12 and has now fallen
more than 17 percent from its all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   Airline stocks were hard-hit. AMR, the parent of American
Airlines, fell 2 1/16, to 59 5/16. UAL, the parent of United
Airlines, dropped 15/16, to 59. Delta Airlines shed 2|, to 53|.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies, a high-flying component of the S&AMP;P 500
index, helped to drag the index down after it announced it had
agreed to buy International Network, a computer network integrator,
for $3.7 billion. Lucent fell 2[, to 61.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, which is Lucent's main competitor in data
networking, was the most actively traded stock Tuesday. It fell 1
1/16, to 58}, only to rebound in after-hours trading after
releasing healthy second-quarter profit numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in interest rates hammered financial service company
stocks. J.P. Morgan led the Dow index down, falling 3, to 121
15/16. Chase Manhattan dropped 1 5/16, to 74 5/16. And Merrill
Lynch fell 13/16, to 63 11/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 2029EDT &QL; 
