<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS11-COX     08-10 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons camp: No Anderson, no meeting
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves and general manager
Harold Richardson hope to meet today with holdout Jamal Anderson
and his agent in an attempt to get the All-Pro running back in
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   But as of late Tuesday afternoon, neither Reeves nor Richardson
had heard anything specific from Jim Sims, who represents Anderson
in his attempt to gain a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Sims called team officials Monday and said he wants to sit down
with Anderson, Reeves and Richardson. Sims, whose office is in
Oakland, said he could not make it to Greenville until Wednesday.
However, he and Anderson arrived in Atlanta about 5:30 a.m. Monday,
according to the flight records of Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   With a larger-than-usual media contingent around the Falcons'
training camp on the Furman University campus, Reeves seemed irked
with Anderson's agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to have had this done a month ago, so,
hopefully, we'll get something done,'' Reeves said. ``If they want
more publicity, we're doing a good job of giving it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves noted that Anderson is not the only player entering the
final year of his contract. Fifteen veterans back from last year's
team stand to become unrestricted free agents after this season; 10
of them are starters. All of those players are in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, quarterback Chris Chandler was in camp while his
agent worked to complete a five-year, $27 million contract with a
$6 million signing bonus. The deal was signed two days before the
season opened.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has accumulated nearly $70,000 in fines for
missing training camp and a mini-camp last month, has said he will
ask to be traded if he is not satisfied with the Falcons' offer.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has said repeatedly that Anderson won't be dealt. ``We'll
meet with them, and (Anderson) won't get traded,'' he said again
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
