<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALUMINUM-MERGER-ART-7     08-10 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALUMINUM-MERGER-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 ALUMINUM COMPANIES IN MERGER TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics showing the price of aluminum and the partners
in the possible three-way merger are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Alcan Aluminium of Canada, Pechiney of France and the
Alsuisse Lonza Group of Switzerland confirmed Tuesday that they are
in merger talks that could create the biggest company in the
aluminum industry, a business plagued for nearly a decade by
oversupply and depressed prices.
</P>
<P>
   The potential combination may be a signal of other big
cross-border deals and could lead to stable or higher prices for
aluminum, a basic industrial metal.
</P>
<P>
   Although executives of the companies said they were still in
discussions and an agreement was not certain, their talks were a
vivid illustration of how corporate consolidation is occurring on a
global scale.
</P>
<P>
   The three-way combination under consideration would create an
aluminum and packaging giant with more than $26 billion in annual
revenue, easily eclipsing the $15.5 billion in revenue of the
current No. 1, Alcoa of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies make aluminum used in products ranging from
aircraft bodies to cooking foil, as well as packaging for drugs and
food. In addition, the Swiss company, informally known as Algroup,
has a profitable specialty chemicals division, which probably would
be sold if the merger talks succeed.
</P>
<P>
   The aluminum business has been badly depressed since the early
'90s, when the collapse of the Soviet Union, one of the biggest
producers of aluminum, led to undisciplined selling by Russian
exporters in a quest for foreign currency. Aluminum supplies
surged, and prices fell. The supply glut was aggravated during the
last two years by severe economic problems in Asia, Russia and
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, mergers in the automotive and aircraft industries
have created huge global customers with the buying power to keep
prices low.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, world aluminum prices have fallen about 30 percent since
the late '80s and touched a five-year low in March, hurting the
earnings of big producers and raising pressure on them to find
partners.
</P>
<P>
   In brief identical statements, Alcan Aluminium, Pechiney and
Algroup would only say that they were in discussions regarding a
``potential business combination.'' News of their discussions was
reported Tuesday in The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are talks, there have been talks, but there's no deal
yet,'' said Marcel Barthe, a spokesman for Alcan Aluminium, at the
company's headquarters in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The talks come against a backdrop of mergers in other metals
industries, which have all been hurt in varying degrees by low
prices. In June, British Steel agreed to acquire the Dutch
steelmaker Royal Hoogovens for $2.3 billion, and last year two of
Germany's biggest steelmakers joined to form Thyssen Krupp AG.
</P>
<P>
   But announced deals have unraveled, too. Indeed, Algroup last
year announced year an $8.7 billion deal to merge with Viag AG, the
German utility and aluminum maker, but the deal collapsed. Earlier,
two big Swiss chemical producers, Ciba Specialty Chemicals AG and
Clariant AG, canceled an agreed-upon stock swap.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the deals that succeeded reflect a new-found
attention to shareholder value among European corporations, many of
which number among their major shareholders large American and
British pension funds, keen on returns. But many deals simply
reflect the volatility of commodity prices, and the need to gain
scale and reduce costs to inject a measure of stability into the
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see the potential to unlock value, so that everyone comes
away a winner,'' said Peter Davey, an analyst at Societe Generale
Securities. Through the companies' mixture of primary aluminum
production, packaging and other activities varied, he said, there
was sufficient overlap to justify consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   Rene Weber, an analyst at Bank Vontobel in Zurich, Switzerland,
agreed. ``Pechiney and Alusuisse have food, pharmaceutical and
cosmetic packaging operations that overlap, and both Alusuisse and
Alcan have aluminum plants in eastern Switzerland,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, officials for both Alcoa and the Aluminum
Association trade group declined to comment on such a merger's
impact.
</P>
<P>
   But investors clearly thought a merger represented good news,
with the creation of a huge global manufacturer that would not
necessarily have to cut prices to thrive. That would inject some
stability into the market and perhaps lead to higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very big positive for the entire aluminum
industry,'' said Daniel A. Roling, an analyst with Merrill Lynch
Global Securities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Paris, shares in Pechiney rose by 4.8 percent to 54.20 euros,
or $58.19, while Algroup's shares rose 4.8 percent to 1,828 Swiss
francs, or $1,226, on the Zurich bourse. In Toronto, shares in
Alcan rose 6.2 percent to 50.50 Canadian dollars or $33.43.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa shares rose 81.25 cents to $66.4375 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Though such a deal could face formidable obstacles, including
possible anti-monopoly challenges by European Union regulators, who
said Tuesday that they had been informed of the talks last week, it
is expected to set off a scramble for partners among smaller
aluminum producers, like Hoogovens of the Netherlands, Norsk Hydro
of Norway, and the VAW Aluminum subsidiary of Germany's Viag.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal that the companies are looking at,
Pechiney and Algroup shareholders are expected to receive shares of
Alcan in exchange for their stock. The planned combination would
have its headquarters in Montreal and would be headed by Alcan's
president and chief executive, Jacques Bougie. Jean-Pierre Rodi,
Pechiney's chief executive, is expected to be named chief operating
officer.
</P>
<P>
   All three companies have similar activities, producing primary
aluminum from basic raw materials and then turning it into such
products as rolled aluminum and ingots from which aluminum products
are made. But Alcan, which hired Morgan Stanley Dean Witter as its
adviser in the discussions, is by far the most profitable of the
three, yielding pretax profits equivalent to 10.5 percent of
revenues, compared to 9.6 percent at Algroup and 6.6 percent at
Pechiney. Pechiney has been using Credit Suisse First Boston and
Algroup Goldman Sachs as advisers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
