<HEADER>
A2535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-ECOMMERCE-NYT &LR;      08-10 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-ECOMMERCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM DOUBTS IT WILL GAIN AUTO MARKET SHARE SOON; PLANS WEB UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors Corp. executives conceded Tuesday that
the company would be unable to increase its share of the booming
auto market soon. They also announced that the company would bundle
its Internet-related assets together in a single unit called e-GM.
</P>
<P>
   The giant automaker has watched its market share slide for
decades, but as recently as July executives had vowed to regain the
30 percent level. Instead, its share of the market sank to 28.4
percent in July. Tuesday, executives said that GM's factories were
running flat out to build as many cars and trucks as possible and
that GM could not produce enough vehicles to increase its market
share as long as customers continued to buy them at a pace of 17
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is so strong it is impossible to produce more
vehicles at the moment,'' said GM chairman and chief executive John
Smith at a new conference.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Zarrella, president of GM's North American operations,
said, ``We're making absolutely every product we can make at every
plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Some on Wall Street expressed skepticism about Zarrella's
assertion, saying that GM simply did not have enough factories
devoted to building its most popular models _ sport utility
vehicles, pickup trucks and minivans _ though it had excess
capacity for building cars. ``Its truck plants are indeed running
full out,'' said John Casesa, an analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``It
still has too much capacity devoted to products that are not
selling well.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, GM has earned substantial profits recently. In the
second quarter alone, it earned $1.73 billion from continuing
operations, up from $306 million in the corresponding period last
year, when a strike nearly shut the company.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference was called to announce the new business
group, e-GM, comprising all GM Internet initiatives worldwide,
including Web sites and a program called Onstar, which uses
satellites to link motorists to GM staff members 24 hours a day for
assistance in the event of accidents or just to locate nearby gas
stations or restaurants. The Internet unit will also lead efforts
to integrate electronic commerce through all the company's business
lines and back-office functions.
</P>
<P>
   GM president and chief operating officer G. Richard Wagoner Jr.
said that issuing a separate tracking stock for the unit or
spinning it off in a public offering was ``not on the radar screen
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-GM unit will join with technology companies to provide
more products and services to GM customers, executives said.
``We're talking to all the big players,'' Zarrella said. ``We bring
a huge customer base.''
</P>
<P>
   GM named Mark Hogan, who was vice president of small-car
operations, to lead the unit. He has kept a low profile since
enraging the United Automobile Workers union this spring by pushing
for streamlined assembly processes in new GM factories. The union
feared that this approach, called modular assembly, would cost
jobs, and UAW president Stephen Yokich publicly called for Hogan to
be dismissed for advocating the moves.
</P>
<P>
   The e-GM initiative is similar to moves under way at other
automakers. At DaimlerChrysler AG, for example, a $500 million
technology program called Customer Connect is meant to link
customers and dealers worldwide through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 61, who has made few high-profile public appearances
lately, sat in the audience Tuesday for the e-GM announcement by
Wagoner and Zarrella. He took questions afterward, however, and
among other topics fended off rumors that he might soon retire,
saying he had no plans to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
