<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-RAGE-BOS &LR;      08-10 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-RAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR PASSENGER'S EXPLETIVE LANDS HER IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a courthouse this morning, Miami resident Patricia
Lemerise will defend herself on criminal charges that stem, she
believes, from one key fact: that she used a one-word expletive to
a flight attendant.
</P>
<P>
   Her case, of course, is more complex than that. It's a tale of
in-flight tension between passenger and airline crew that started
with grumbling, escalated into swearing, and reached a crescendo
when Massachusetts state troopers met her at the airplane door.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, her travel agent informed her that American Airlines
had banned her for life from their flights.
</P>
<P>
   They wouldn't even refund her ticket back to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But the curse word _ and the treatment, by airline employees,
that Lemerise says provoked it _ is at the heart of the conflict
that landed her in jail last Thursday, charged with disorderly
conduct and interfering with a flight crew.
</P>
<P>
   Lemerise, who will be represented by a public defender in East
Boston District Court, said she can't believe she could go to jail
``for being in a bad mood'' during a flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't threaten anybody,'' she said. ``I didn't beat anybody
up. . . . I didn't put my hands on anybody's person.''
</P>
<P>
   But her story comes at a time of increased tension in air
travel, when passengers are lodging more complaints about the
airlines, and airline employees are citing a rise in unruly _ and
threatening _ behavior.
</P>
<P>
   After a few vivid examples of passenger violence, many carriers
have established ``zero tolerance'' policies, promising to
prosecute disruptive fliers. But passengers complain of being
herded like cattle, crammed into shrinking seats, snapped at, lied
to, and subjected to treatment that makes frustration boil into
anger.
</P>
<P>
   So the events that unfolded on American Airlines Flight 2040,
nonstop from Miami to Logan International Airport last Thursday,
could be viewed as yet another tale from the battle front.
</P>
<P>
   Lemerise, 28, an art dealer, said she had already had a lousy
day by the time she boarded the plane in Miami at around 11 a.m.
Her wallet had been stolen that morning. She was tired. She wasn't
in the mood for a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Midway into the 2 1/2-hour flight, when she rose from her window
seat in row 25 and stepped into the aisle to roll up some artwork
that had become crumpled during transport. At the time, the flight
attendants were about to push the meal cart to the front of the
plane, and Lemerise was blocking their path.
</P>
<P>
   A nearby passenger, Michele Haft Hudson, said she overheard one
attendant tell another that Lemerise ``had better get her butt back
in her seat, because if she gets stuck, that's her problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemerise said a flight attendant told her to move to an empty
aisle seat. But by the time she got there, the occupant had
returned from the restroom, so she walked to the first-class
section and stood between the cockpit and the kitchen, waiting for
the meal cart to pass her row.
</P>
<P>
   Three times, Lemerise said, she walked down the aisle to try to
slip past the meal cart. Each time, she said, the flight attendant
wouldn't let her through.
</P>
<P>
   After her third attempt, Lemerise recalled, she turned to the
flight attendant in first class and said, ``I guess you're stuck
with me for another (expletive) 20 minutes, because it seems that
I'm under punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendant curtly told Lemerise that the word she used
_ the f-word _ was forbidden on an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Lemerise answered that she was exercising her First Amendment
rights. The flight attendant then reported her to the captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked in construction for the last nine years,''
Lemerise said in an interview this week. The ephithet ``is not such
a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, Lemerise, who said she felt like a chastened
schoolgirl, was arguing with the attendants. Then, an off-duty
pilot, who was sitting in first class, joined the verbal fray,
defending the flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Lemerise said the pilot jabbed his finger at her. She said she
used the word again, in a sentence that went about like this:
``Tell the (expletive) stewardess to get out of my way and I will
gladly go back to my seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemerise said she demanded the name of the pilot; a flight
attendant refused to give it. So when another flight attendant
asked for her name, Lemerise would not tell her.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the plane landed at Logan, several passengers had
offered their names and phone numbers to flight attendants,
pledging to support them as witnesses. Hudson _ who was incensed by
the crew's nasty behavior towards her own family that day _ said
she'd support Lemerise, and told the attendants that they were
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were so rude,'' Hudson said, ``that they deserved a
passenger response.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached Tuesday, American Airlines spokesman Mark Slitt said he
could not comment on the airline's side of the story. But while
American might not have a specific policy against swearing, he
said, the airline is tough on passenger misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it gets to a point where passenger language makes a flight
attendant feel threatened in some way, or abused in some way . . .
that's something we would find intolerable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants are expected to be polite, but courtesy is a
two-way street, he said. Passengers with complaints should call the
airline's customer relations department and file a report.
</P>
<P>
   Lemerise said she's considering a lawsuit instead.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane landed at Logan, and state troopers hauled her to
the airport barracks in handcuffs, Lemerise said, she was in tears.
But by the time she was released on $50 bond five hours later, she
was angry again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry that promotes this behavior of lying and deceit
and bullying _ they're going on the wrong approach,'' she said.
``You're asking for what you get. you're really asking for what you
get.''
</P>
<P>
   Slitt said Lemerise's barred-for-life status from the airline
``may be as much myth as reality.'' American Airlines has no master
list of forbidden fliers, he said, but when passengers behave
extremely badly, ``we make it very clear to them that we don't want
their business.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, Lemerise said, the feeling is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even drive and I'm going to buy a car right now and
drive back to Miami,'' she said. ``I don't even want to go back in
an airport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
