<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-EXTORT-ART-2TAK     08-10 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-EXTORT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOKAIYA, JAPAN'S CORPORATE EXTORTIONISTS, ARE LOSING THEIR
EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Kaoru Ogawa is among the last of a dying breed.
</P>
<P>
   Ogawa is the most prominent of the survivors of the Japanese
government's war on the sokaiya, as Japan's oddly high-profile
corporate extortionists are known.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent shareholders meeting, he proudly introduced himself
as the famous sokaiya who was recently released from jail. But now
even he is turning to other lines of business and seeking to soften
his image. For one thing, he has encouraged shareholders of Japan
Airlines to boycott the company until it gets its business in
order. He even urged executives of Honda Motor to emulate a foreign
auto maker, Daimler-Chrysler, by developing more exciting designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the Japanese Ralph Nader,'' he told the directors of Mazda
Motors during that company's annual meeting in July, when he tried
to make a case for himself as a rather benign ombudsman for
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   That's a stretch. But, in fact, the government's crackdown on
sokaiya (pronounced so-kaiyah) has resulted in a remarkable forced
retrenchment among a group that was formerly so sharp-elbowed that
major corporations paid large sums of money to keep them at bay and
avoid disruptions to their public meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been reduced to a level we can almost ignore,'' said
Hideaki Kubori, a lawyer who helps companies design policies to
keep the sokaiya and other threats away. ``The sokaiya have
operated with an eye toward balancing how much money they get
versus the penalty they might get. These days they've decided
there's no profit in it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   There is resistance, and desperation has forced some sokaiya to
move closer to their criminal cousins, the yakuza. Even Ogawa was
not afraid to warn Japan Airlines that risks remain. ``If
management doesn't improve, then bang, bang, there will be more
shootings,'' he said at the recent meeting, referring to a
mysterious incident at the home of a former airline executive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sokaiya's numbers are shrinking fast, their demise
further evidence of Japan's increasing if grudging embrace of the
global economy, and the premium it places on transparency and sound
corporate governance.
</P>
<P>
   Kubori estimates that 350 to 500 sokaiya remain formally
operating in Japan, somewhat fewer than half the number in 1997.
That was when the government decided to end the business _
technically illegal since 1982 but infrequently prosecuted _ once
and for all by attacking not only the sokaiya but also their hidden
corporate patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the fall of 1977, the police arrested executives from
Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank and the four major securities firms here. They
also prosecuted Ryuichi Koike, whom authorities describe as Japan's
leading sokaiya, and succeeded in putting him in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, the sokaiya participated in a variety of
activities, from publishing and other seemingly legitimate
businesses to outright extortion and stock-market manipulation.
Using their ties to the yakuza, Japan's underworld, the sokaiya
gathered damaging information about companies and their executives
and traded on it.
</P>
<P>
   By purchasing a subscription to a poorly written, erratically
published ``newsletter,'' corporations could guarantee themselves
and their directors a harmonious, embarrassment-free shareholders'
meeting, courtesy of sokaiya like Ogawa. Corporate managers were
invited to attend affairs arranged by the sokaiya, where cash was
handed over to guarantee peace.
</P>
<P>
   If a company failed to pay, its shareholders meetings could
degenerate into violent melees and shouting matches, where
directors' sexual and other peccadillos were aired. In
image-conscious Japan, such disturbances could permanently stain a
career and disgust customers.
</P>
<P>
   Today's remaining sokaiya are far more well-behaved. Reporters,
who were allowed to attend Japanese shareholders' meetings this
year in far greater numbers than ever before, were surprised to
discover that Mamoru Tamura, a particularly outspoken shareholder
who had berated the managements of Nissan and Mitsubishi Motor as
well as several financial services companies, is a well-known if
somewhat small-time sokaiya.
</P>
<P>
   To their ears, Tamura sounded a lot like Evelyn Y. Davis or the
Gilbert brothers _ the outspoken, if slightly eccentric, American
shareholder advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Tamura's command of the microphone and his harsh, fact-packed
diatribes, however, were tell-tale clues to his sokaiya status: The
typical Japanese shareholder prefers to hold his tongue, and if he
does speak, is likely to couch his criticism or question in profuse
apology.
</P>
<P>
   That is changing, and police officials credit far-reaching
changes in Japanese society as much as their own efforts for
bringing the sokaiya to their knees. More ordinary shareholders are
speaking out, not necessarily with loud voices and angry invective
but in a critical manner nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Management, too, seems determined to severe its ties to the
sokaiya. ``Ten years ago, presidents of companies were very much
afraid of a sokaiya's performance at their shareholders'
meetings,'' said Makoto Ota, chief of the investigative unit of
Metropolitan Police Department's Organized Crime Control Division.
``It was regarded as a big mistake by the corporate staff and an
embarrassment, but it's not like that so much now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the line between sokaiya and shareholder advocate is
becoming so blurred that many praise the sokaiya for their efforts
to give shareholders in Japanese companies a voice. ``What I'm
doing is confronting companies and fighting against them,'' Ogawa
said. ``Japanese companies are very bad to their shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubori, the lawyer who helps companies defend themselves against
sokaiya, said appraisals like those, along with rather romanticized
portrayals of the sokaiya in both the Japanese and foreign press,
are helping them recast themselves as a new breed of Japanese-style
shareholder advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters ``now have the impression that Japanese shareholders'
meetings and the sokaiya who attend them are the same as American
shareholders' meetings and the shareholders who attend them,'' he
said. ``They're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Kubori said, the growing pressure is increasingly
pushing them into outright extortion and other criminal acts. ``It
used to be that the shareholder's meeting was the arena for the
battle between corporate Japan and the sokaiya,'' he said. ``Now
the confrontation is spreading throughout the year and going into
different areas of harassment.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The police, for instance, are investigating a mysterious
shooting at the Tokyo home of Matsuo Toshimitsu, a former president
of Japan Airlines, which has long been one of the sokaiya's
favorite targets. Several days before the company's shareholders'
meeting this year, a bullet was fired into the wall near the
entrance of Toshimitsu's house, and traces of another bullet were
found on a window sill.
</P>
<P>
   The police are also looking into a call about the incident from
Eitaro Itoyama, Japan Airlines' biggest individual shareholder.
Even before Toshimitsu had informed the company of the shooting,
Itoyama called executives, demanding to know why the airline was
covering it up. Itoyama, through his secretary, said that he heard
about the shooting from friends in the neighborhood and he only
called the company after failing to see any news reports about it.
</P>
<P>
   Itoyama, a former politician whose career was marred by
financial scandals, has never called himself a sokaiya, though many
of his activities are similar to theirs. His wife is the niece of
Ryoichi Sasakawa, a well-known gangster who died not long ago, and
Itoyama told Bloomberg News this spring that he had relied on the
yakuza for support in elections.
</P>
<P>
   Ogawa, the self-proclaimed Ralph Nader of Japan, is miffed at
the attention Itoyama and Koike, who got his start as one of
Ogawa's lieutenants, have snared in the last two years. Koike, in
particular, has become something of a celebrity since his arrest
and imprisonment in 1997, shortly after the police adopted a
scorched-earth policy toward the sokaiya.
</P>
<P>
   In his own bid for the spotlight after serving jail time on
corporate-racketeering charges, Ogawa posed for pictures astride
the motorcycle he used to navigate Tokyo's perpetually snarled
streets on June 29, the day when the bulk of Japanese companies
held their shareholders' meetings this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese police are portraying the capture of Koike as a
big deal,'' he said when the subject of his rivals came up. ``They
are exaggerating his importance to make themselves look good.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, Ogawa said, in a good year, a prominent sokaiya
could earn up to 150 million yen, or about $1.3 million _ much of
which was tax-free. Times are harder than when he owned three homes
in Hawaii and was the backer for Pink Lady, a teen-aged singing duo
that was wildly popular here in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time leader of the biggest group of sokaiya in Japan,
Ogawa said he plans to start a new company that offers information
and stock tips to ordinary investors via the Internet for an annual
membership fee of 1,000 yen ($87) or so.
</P>
<P>
   He also sees a role for himself as a champion of small and
mid-sized construction companies, which, he said, often have to pay
a ``commission'' to get a piece of the action in the lucrative
public-works contracts that are controlled by the big general
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the small and medium-sized companies cannot pay the
commission, they get a bullet in their house,'' courtesy of the
yakuza who work on behalf of the general contractors, Ogawa said.
He thinks he can offer the smaller contractors protection from the
fees.
</P>
<P>
   He also writes a gossipy column about Japanese companies and
sokaiya for a sports newspaper. Ogawa is an inveterate gambler,
betting on boats, horses and baseball. It was gambling, or rather
gambling losses, that propelled him into the sokaiya business when
he was a young man.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he sees what was for him a proud career ending with a
whimper, not a bang. ``In Japan now, even ordinary shareholders who
speak out at shareholders meetings are now called sokaiya, so who's
really a sokaiya any more?'' he lamented. ``The sokaiya is dead,
there's just no benefit in it any more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
