<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. FREEZES ASSETS OF AFHAN AIRLINE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States froze the American assets of the
Afghan national airline on Tuesday, calling it a link in the chain
of support for Osama bin Laden, the suspected terrorist leader now
living in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier, Ariana Afghan Airlines, ``has supported, or is
linked to, the bin Laden network,'' David Leavy, a National
Security Council spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, President Clinton imposed financial and commercial
sanctions against the Taliban, the armed religious group that rules
most of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The government on Tuesday also blocked American business
transactions with Ariania, along with freezing its assets in the
United States, about half a million dollars. The tiny airline has
the only planes with scheduled flights to and from Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Although the impact of the actions may be more symbolic than
real, they are aimed at strangling the Taliban, and cutting off all
means of support to bin Laden, who is charged with masterminding
the bombings of two American embassies in Africa a year ago,
disasters that killed 224 people, including 12 Americans, and
wounded about 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden remains in Afghanistan, reportedly outside Jalalabad,
about 40 miles from the Pakistani border.
</P>
<P>
   The first anniversary of the embassy attacks passed peacefully
on Saturday. But on Tuesday, the State Department issued a warning
that ``extremists based in Afghanistan'' might soon ``attack U.S.
interests in Pakistan,'' urging Americans there to take
precautions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
