<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLORADO-POLITICS-NYT     08-10 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLORADO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VULNERABLE COLORADO DISTRICT INSPIRES DEMOCRATS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Touring a United Airlines training center Tuesday
during the congressional summer recess, Rep. Tom Tancredo, a
Republican freshman from the Denver suburb of Littleton, took
special delight in recounting a story of his return to Washington
on United last January, when he said several flight attendants
praised him for refusing to attend President Clinton's State of the
Union Message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be in the same room with the gentleman making
that speech,'' Tancredo, who is 53, told a group of employees,
recalling a presidential appearance that followed the House
impeachment vote and the start of the Senate trial. One flight
attendant, he said, even waived the charge for the movie headset.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tancredo earned widespread attention for his boycott,
it was fully in keeping with his conservative bearings and disdain
for Clinton that helped him win an open seat held for 16 years by
Don Schaefer, a less controversial Republican, who retired. Since
then, Tancredo has distinguished himself in other high-profile ways
that left no doubt about his conservative bent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it is precisely such dramatic acts that are fueling a
growing belief among many Democrats across the country that voters
are tiring of conservative Republicans as too far removed from the
political center and that by defeating just a few like Tancredo,
Democrats can retake control of the House next year.
</P>
<P>
   The gulf between Republicans and Democrats, reflected by
opposing views on such issues as gun control and tax cuts, is also
one reason officials of both parties say fund-raising efforts for a
House election still 15 months away are proceeding at a dazzling
pace in Tancredo' district and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, which helps
raise money for Democratic House candidates, says that 17
challengers in districts where party leaders views the incumbent
Republican as vulnerable each passed $100,000 in fund raising by
June 30, including 6 who passed $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   By the same date, the National Republican Congressional
Committee said fund raising for the 2000 campaign had exceeded 1998
efforts by 66 percent, with 18 challengers and candidates for open
seats already above $100,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are huge amounts for this early in the cycle,'' said Don
Simon, executive vice president of Common Cause, a group that works
for government reform. ``But it's a leading indicator of the stakes
in play for control of the House. It used to be rare that a
candidate would spend $1 million in a House race. After the last
two cycles, it is becoming more common, and I think we're going to
see a lot more this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Republicans hold a margin of 222-211 in the
House, with one independent who generally votes with the Democrats.
The recent death of Rep. George E. Brown Jr., D-Calif., has left
one seat vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Rocky Mountain states, Colorado is largely
represented in high office by Republicans, including the governor,
Bill Owens; both senators, Ben Nighthorse Campbell and Wayne
Allard, and four of the six House members.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Toltz, 42, a Democratic businessman from Englewood who began
raising money to challenge Tancredo just four weeks after the 1998
election, is one of the challengers who enjoyed early fund-raising
success, with $104,675 by the June 30 reporting period, compared
with about $165,000 for Tancredo.
</P>
<P>
   Using Tancredo's brand of conservatism as a major fund-raising
tool, Toltz contended in a recent interview that the incumbent's
views no longer match district tastes, calling him `'a polarizing
force and a master at pulling people apart.''
</P>
<P>
   As examples, Toltz cited several of Tancredo's other
controversial acts. In addition to skipping the State of the Union,
Tancredo was the only freshman House member of either party to
refuse an invitation to visit the White House. Also, he joined 16
other House members, all but a few of them Republicans, in a
lawsuit against Clinton in May, charging that the involvement of
American troops in Kosovo without Congressional approval was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Five years before he won his House seat, as president of the
Independence Institute, a conservative research organization in
Golden, Colo., Tancredo advocated no government support of public
education, a position he said he no longer holds as a congressman.
</P>
<P>
   While Toltz argued that the district can ill afford a
representative that holds such unusual views, Tancredo said Tuesday
that he stood by everything else he did, calling each a principled
stand that reflects his activist nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I end up this experience,'' Tancredo said, ``I want to be
able to think to myself that it mattered. If a majority disagrees
with me, then I should be out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   One subject Toltz declined to criticize Tancredo on was gun
control. Even though the House failed to pass any meaningful
measures this year, Tancredo was the only member of the Colorado
delegation that voted for the failed House legislation that
included modest reform.
</P>
<P>
   For Tancredo, it was more than a symbolic vote: He lives six
blocks from Columbine High School where two students last spring
shot and killed 12 students and a teacher before turning their guns
on themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 2056EDT &QL; 
