<HEADER>
A2549 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEDERALISM-MEETING-CO     08-10 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDERALISM-MEETING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meeting of Senate, governors proposed for 'federalism'
discussions
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ All 50 governors and the 100 members of the U.S.
Senate are invited to convene in Washington in February for what
Utah Gov. Michael Leavitt called a ``landmark'' session to discuss
the evolving relationship between the federal government and the
states.
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt, the new chairman of the National Governors'
Association, said Tuesday they will discuss what he called the
``new frontier of federalism,'' a world in which the boundaries
separating states and even countries have become blurred by
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democratic U.S. Senate leaders have agreed to the
meeting, said Leavitt, who was named chairman as the governors
wrapped up their four-day summer meeting.
</P>
<P>
   For state governments to continue to play an important role in a
technology-driven global economy, they must devise new models of
governing that emphasize central coordination but local control,
Leavitt said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, states should join forces to create a central spot
on the Internet where financial services companies could go to be
licensed to do business in each of the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   If the states don't act to preserve their traditional role in
areas such as regulating businesses, the federal government will
step in and take over, he said. This would create an undesirable
``one size fits all'' approach, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue that needs to be addressed is the sales tax
revenue that states have been losing because mail-order and
Internet sales are not taxed, Leavitt and other governors meeting
here have said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be required to rethink the (state-federal)
partnership. . . . A partnership that is not devoid of healthy
tension,'' Leavitt said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes this would be the first such meeting
involving all 50 governors and the 100 U.S. Senators. It will occur
during the winter meeting of the governors' group in Washington,
next Feb. 26, 29.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, governors will be encouraged to meet with the
U.S. House members from their states, Leavitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting between the senators and governors is key because
both groups of officeholders represent entire states, said Leavitt,
48, a Republican serving his second term as Utah's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The ``healthy tension'' Leavitt mentioned has been apparent
here. Some of the uneasiness with Washington subsided after U.S.
Sen. Don Nickles, R-0kla., told the governors he would do all he
could to stop efforts to force states to return surplus welfare
dollars to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the dispute over the surplus welfare money, the governors
also have criticized what appears to be an effort by Congress to
reduce spending in areas critical to the states such as health and
human service programs. The proposed cuts are part of the effort by
Congress to meet spending limitations it imposed on itself under
the 1997 Balanced Budget Act.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark welfare reform act passed by Congress in 1996
signified the most visible change that has resulted from this shift
_ moving much of the control of welfare programs from the federal
government to the states. The February session between the
governors and the senators represents the newest effort to better
define a relationship that has been shifting power from Washington
to the states for nearly two decades, dating at least to 1981 when
President Ronald Reagan began the first of his two terms.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
