<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALMART-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALMART REPORTS BIG GAINS IN QUARTERLY RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing on its juggernaut sales pace, Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
said Tuesday that its second-quarter sales had jumped 15 percent as
its profit rose 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Net income rose to $1.25 billion, or 28 cents a diluted share,
compared with $1.03 billion, or 23 cents a share, in the quarter a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding a charge of 3 cents a share for a legal settlement
with Valores Corp., a Mexican grocery wholesaler, the company made
31 cents a share. Analysts had expected the company to earn 28
cents a share, according to First Call Corp., which tracks company
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The results sent shares of Wal-Mart up $2.6875, to $42.875.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest retailer, based in Bentonville, Ark., has
been setting records all year as it races toward greater expansion.
Last week, Wal-Mart had the fourth-largest bond issue in U.S.
history, raising $5.75 billion to buy ASDA Group PLC, a British
grocery chain. The company also had robust sales in July, posting
growth of 9.6 percent in stores open at least a year compared with
figures in year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were impressed with the quarter's $5 billion increase
in sales, to $38.5 billion. ``The numbers were very strong and
broad based,'' said Jeff Feiner, a retail analyst with Lehman
Brothers, who has raised his estimates for earnings for the year to
$1.25 a share from $1.21.
</P>
<P>
   The company said both increased sales and cost cutting
contributed to the gains. Its cost of sales fell to 78.3 percent of
revenue from 78.8 percent in the quarter a year earlier. In
particular, the retailer held domestic inventory growth to 2
percent while sales rose 14 percent, said Les Copeland, a company
spokesman. Average consumer purchases rose as shoppers showed
strong interest in clothing, household goods and groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart offers a limited selection of groceries at some of its
regular discount stores and a full grocery selection at its giant
supercenters, which have performed particularly well. ``The food
increases measured in the double digits,'' Copeland said.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart will not break out figures for supercenter sales from
its total store revenues, but analysts estimate that those sales
this year will be nearly $58 billion, up from $150 million 10 years
ago. Wal Mart's total sales last year were $138 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company already has 622 supercenters and has said it plans
to open 150 new ones this year. Wal-Mart's success in that area has
possibly dire implications for competitors in the food and drug
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty percent of the retail growth in the food channel is
going directly to Wal-Mart, which means that by January 2003 their
supercenter sales will be greater than their No. 1, 2 and 3
competitors, food and drug combined,'' said Burt Flickinger III,
who has been studying regional retail patterns for three decades
and is now managing director of Reach Marketing, a retail and
marketing consulting agency in Westport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Wal-Mart opens against a big regional leader _ like
Jitney-Jungle in Louisiana _ they lose 50 percent of volume
overnight and the competitor never recovers,'' Flickinger added.
</P>
<P>
   Despite robust sales growth recently, other retailers have seen
their shares decline because of fears that the Federal Reserve will
raise interest rates and that consumer spending may slow later this
year. Wal-Mart seems mostly immune to such concerns, however.
``Even if the consumer environment does slow down, we still think
Wal-Mart is extremely well positioned,'' Feiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Flickinger went one step further. ``A consumer downturn is the
best possible thing that can happen to Wal-Mart and the worst thing
that could happen to every major competitor,'' he said. He argues
that a slowdown would only highlight Wal-Mart's pricing advantages.
``Wal-Mart's prices are 20 to 30 percent lower than competitors on
the fastest-selling items in the store like laundry detergent and
toothpaste.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
