r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-PARENTS-LADN     08-10 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-PARENTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS LOOK FOR THEIR CHILDREN AFTER SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY AND PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Aviva Baraza was watching CNN Tuesday when she
heard the horrible news: a shooting rampage at the North Valley
Jewish Community Center _ the day-care center her 7-year-old son
attends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I panicked,'' the woman said as she stood anxiously behind
police lines with a crowd of parents waiting to be reunited with
their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came straight to the school and have been waiting to find
out what happened to my son. This is bad. I don't know why anyone
would do this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Baraza and dozens of other frantic parents sped to the center in
the Granada Hills community of Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley to
learn the fate of their children, to find them and take them home.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers and fathers, some weeping, many in work clothes, ran
down Rinaldi Street straining to get as close as they could to the
center, which operates a day-care center, day camp and preschool
for 300 children.
</P>
<P>
   When they spotted parents they knew, they hugged and exchanged
information. Others yelled urgently into cell phones, relaying
whatever bits of news they had learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where he is,'' one mother yelled into a cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is horrible. Why would somebody do this to these kids?''
asked Debbie Simon, as she searched for her 7-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   One little boy, tucked safely inside his father's arms, could
only say, ``There was a bad guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Once parents reached the police line around the facility, they
were directed next door to a church shared by Temple Beth Torah, a
command post where police and day-care workers had led children
after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Sareet Kleiner, 33, of Granada Hills nervously dodged knots of
people until she spotted her 2-year-old twins, Dan and Tamar, being
ushered into Temple Beth Torah along with several other children.
</P>
<P>
   Kleiner said her husband called her and told her the news. She
turned on the radio and raced toward the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to see my kids are OK,'' Kleiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Randi Tobin of Granada Hills scoured the growing crowd searching
for her 5-year-old son, Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God, I just don't know what to think. My husband called me
and told me and I rushed down here. My mom was killed in a car
crash 30 years ago on this day. Another relative died three weeks
ago. And today is my son's birthday. I don't need any more of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Goldberg, whose 5-year-old son was at the center at the
time of the shooting, was trembling so violently she could barely
use her cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old resident of the San Fernando Valley's West Hills
community said she had had concerns about security when she first
signed her children up at the center but quickly dismissed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think there was a high enough level of security,''
said Goldberg, who has an 8-year-old child who was on a field trip
during the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen plenty of violence take place, and I was afraid. I
can't believe this happened. Those poor kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Macales, whose two young sons attend the center, said he
is considering moving his family back to Israel, where he believes
it's safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just talked to my wife and mother about moving the family
back to Israel,'' said Macales, a public relations officer for the
University of California, Los Angeles, who lives in the Northridge
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel there's not much of a future for Jews in the United
States. It's not an issue of anti-Semitism, but there's a moral
eclipse in America which leads to moral unaccountability in this
country. I dream to move back.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Nissenbaum, who was picking up her 4{-year-old daughter,
couldn't make sense of the tragedy either.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do so much to protect your child. I don't know how much
more we can do,'' said Nissenbaum, who lives north of Los Angeles
in Valencia, one of the country's safest cities. ``It's frightening
and random. And it's scary to think that you can't always keep your
kid safe.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Pianko, who was reunited with son and daughter, said no
place is safe any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been quite aware of violence at schools, and the only
thing I can think of is to go to some remote island and deal with
your own,'' said Pianko, a Northridge resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to do. This school violence is such a new
dimension to society that I don't know if anybody knows how to
react.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
