<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 11
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-TAIWAN-INDEPENDENCE-NYT (moved on Sunday, Aug. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Aug. 8,
about people in Taiwan who do not want the island to be part of
China misstated the title of a United States diplomat, Stanley
Roth, who has been involved with China-Taiwan issues. He is an
Assistant Secretary of State, not the Deputy Assistant Secretary.
The article also misstated his recent diplomatic travels. According
to the State Department, he has not been to Taiwan since assuming
his current post in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PAINKILLER-PROTECTION-NYT (moved on Sunday, Aug. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Aug. 8,
about trends in the use of medication for intractable pain
partially misstated the view of Dr. June L. Dahl of the University
of Wisconsin Medical School. She said that even patients with a
history of drug abuse could properly be treated with painkillers,
but that their doctors would have to use special care to avoid
readdiction.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCHWEPPES-BOTTLING-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Aug. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Aug. 4,
about the soft-drink business of Cadbury Schweppes P.L.C. misstated
the percentage of Cadbury brands acquired by the Coca-Cola Company
that would be handled at least temporarily by Pepsi-Cola bottlers
as part of the deal. About 20 percent of the volume, not 60
percent, will be bottled by Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-MUSIC-HISTORY-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Aug. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Aug. 4,
about Country.com's Century of Country, a country-music
encyclopedia on CD-ROM, misstated the title of a 1997 song by the
group Alabama. It is ``Sad Lookin' Moon,'' not ``Sad Lookin'
Mama.''
</P>
</TEXT>
