<HEADER>
A2555 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-TEX     08-10 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINOR MAJOR IS A MAJOR STEPPING STONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Davis Love III stood on the threshold of his first major
championship. Yet none of the questions being lofted at Winged Foot
Golf Club had anything to do with the 1997 PGA Championship, an
event Love would win four days later.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, inquiring minds sought insight on Love's thoughts about
his position as a fence straddler in the race to secure a spot on
the Ryder Cup team. Finally, Love had heard enough. He cut off a
questioner in mid-sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a minute, guys,'' Love said. ``This is a major
championship. This is not the qualifying school for the Ryder
Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's both. But in odd-numbered years, the season's
least-celebrated major championship is best known as the official
cutoff date for accumulating Ryder Cup points in quest of a berth
on the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life at the PGA Championship, the Rodney Dangerfield of
golf's major championships.
</P>
<P>
   The most-anticipated news conference this week at Medinah (Ill.)
Country Club will not be with Sunday's winner. It will be Monday
morning, when U.S. Ryder Cup captain Ben Crenshaw announces his two
at-large picks for the 1999 team that will compete Sept. 24-26 at
The Country Club in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, for a second, the Masters being viewed as a springboard
to the Diners Club Matches. Or golfers at the U.S. Open playing to
position themselves for a spot in the Skins Game. Both scenarios
are laughable. Those majors stand alone and command attention, even
with fans who don't know a sand wedge from a sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   But the PGA does not. Every year, it's No. 4 chronologically in
terms of golf's major championships and No. 4 in the hearts of golf
fans. Heck, it's even a clear No. 4 to the participants.
</P>
<P>
   Want proof? Check the 1999 player guide distributed by
Cornerstone Sports, a Dallas-based agency whose clients include
professional golfers Mark Brooks, Phil Mickelson, Corey Pavin, Paul
Stankowski, Bob Tway and Brian Watts.
</P>
<P>
   As part of each player profile, golfers are asked which
tournament they would most like to win. Of the 14 PGA Tour
participants who specified a favorite, seven picked the U.S. Open.
Five opted for the Masters. Two selected the British Open. No one
named the PGA. And two of the respondents (Brooks and Tway) are
past PGA champions.
</P>
<P>
   For longtime golf observers, the PGA's place in the sport's
pecking order is far from breaking news. Its location on the
professional sports calendar is less than ideal, sentenced to the
dog days of August and overshadowed by the upcoming football season
and the onset of pennant races in major-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the event has suffered an identity crisis since 1958, when
the playing format was switched from match play to stroke play to
appease television executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt the PGA should go back to match play. That's
its roots. That's what made it special,'' said Tom Watson, 49, who
lacks only a PGA title to complete a personal sweep of golf's four
major championships.
</P>
<P>
   For the 27th consecutive year, Watson will chase that elusive
triumph, this time at Medinah. During his career, Watson has seen
the PGA contested at some of the nation's most prestigious courses:
Pebble Beach Golf Links, Congressional Country Club, Oakland Hills
Country Club. He has seen it played in more humble surroundings,
like Tanglewood Golf Club in Clemmons, N.C., and Shoal Creek
Country Club in Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Some years, tournament organizers lay out a menacing test, with
heavy rough and narrow fairways. That is the game plan for Medinah,
where even par could be the winning score. Other years, the layout
includes little rough, wide fairways and minimal challenge. John
Daly capitalized on a forgiving layout at Crooked Stick Golf Club
in Carmel, Ind., in 1991, shooting 12 under par for 72 holes
without the benefit of a practice round.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Colin Montgomerie shot 17 under ... and lost to Steve
Elkington in a playoff at Riviera Country Club in Pacific
Palisades, Calif. In 1976, Dave Stockton failed to break par (1
over) yet won by a stroke over Raymond Floyd at Congressional
Country Club in Bethesda, Md. You won't find that kind of disparity
in winning scores at other majors. The PGA's prestige is hurt
because its layouts often are not challenging enough to weed out
lesser players.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the past 11 PGA winners made the event their first major
championship. The extended run of long shot winners will not help
pull the PGA out of its spot as No. 4 among golf's major
championships any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still a major. And, through its symbiotic relationship
with the Ryder Cup, it might be starting to gain some prestige.
</P>
<P>
   Because the PGA of America runs both events, organizers are
willing to tolerate the PGA's perception as a Ryder Cup qualifying
tournament. And, by linking the two events in its bidding process
for future sites, officials have gained entry into a class facility
such as Medinah, which also will play host to the 2011 Ryder Cup
and the 2006 PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Awtrey, chief executive officer of the PGA of America,
described the double-dipping as ``part of our long-term strategic
plan we've formulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, officials hope playing enough PGA Championships at
recognized Ryder Cup sites will lift their annual event to
something other than No. 4 in the pecking order for major
championships. For this week, however, another Ryder Cup qualifying
school is set to commence. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-DUVAL-COX     08-10 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-DUVAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duval squirms in fame's spotlight
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ While on their Irish golf trip before last
month's British Open, David Duval and Tiger Woods found themselves
hitting practice balls one day in a remote field, playing the
equivalent of a Michael Jordan-Larry Bird game of ``horse.''
</P>
<P>
   During the friendly competition, the conversation got around to
dealing with the fame that accompanies the position they hold in
their sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell him what I've gone through, the mistakes I've made,
but he still has to experience it for David Duval,'' Woods was
saying Tuesday at the 81st PGA Championship. ``I've found a way to
handle it best for Tiger Woods. . . . I think he needs to make his
own mistakes and learn from them.''
</P>
<P>
   It looks like it might take a few more sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months after Duval seemingly had evolved into an
engaging, energized personality, he has returned to viewing at
least some of the media as a nagging, never-take-a-break presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not comfortable with the fame,'' Duval, 27, conceded
Tuesday, two days before the start of the PGA Championship at
Medinah Country Club. ``I don't think that the golfing public or
the writers have a right to know everything about me. . . . If that
seems standoffish, well, I apologize. . . . There are some things
that I think are for me to know and for you not to. . . . Everybody
wants me to talk about what happened to my brother, what happened
to the divorce of my folks. . . . Well, I just don't really want
to. I've done some of that, but I just don't like to talk about
it.'' Duval added to the media attention through his comments in a
recent Golf Digest story, in which he advocated some form of
compensation for Ryder Cup players and suggested a possible boycott
over the issue in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Candid to a fault, Duval sometimes ignores the timing of his
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he has labored to get used to his quotes becoming
headlines, Duval said, ``Maybe so. There may be a bit of a
transition just in that more people are listening. I don't have to
think about, when I leave here or somewhere else, which untruth did
I tell or what did I sugarcoat. I say what I think and I answer
honestly. . . . As a player, you don't change because you went to
No. 1. I try to let people know that, but they don't seem to want
to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizeable pressure already existed on the former Georgia Tech
player for his lack of a major championship, despite 11 PGA Tour
victories since the fall of 1997 and acquisition of the world's No.
1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of concerning himself with whatever intangible might
push him to a major title, Duval is wrestling with his critics. At
the British Open, he got in the face of an American reporter. On
Tuesday, he ripped the British media for inaccuracies at
Carnoustie, then was seen discussing a beef with a Golf Channel
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Other players ripped Carnoustie, but their words weren't
inspected quite as much. ``They made up words and quotes,'' Duval
said, ``and people ran with it.''
</P>
<P>
   This week should be fun for Duval. He has returned to Medinah,
where he played a U.S. Open as a 19-year-old and managed to make
the cut. He is striking the ball crisply, certainly better than in
the Woods match, where he said, ``I didn't swing well.'' He has
ironed out an alignment problem with his putting.
</P>
<P>
   Duval contended in both the Masters and U.S. Open, finishing in
a tie for 6th and 7th, respectively, before the tie for 62nd at
Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you could rate my performance much above
mediocre,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Duval can push himself toward more pleasing headlines with a low
number in Thursday's first round. Medinah, 7,401 yards and fairly
straightforward, is a course that should fit his game. Duval's best
PGA finish was a tie for 7th at Winged Foot in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my golf game is very good,'' Duval said. ``If I can
just put it all together, I would hope to be talking to you all, or
at least have a chance, on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
