<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON APPEALS TO TOP FUND-RAISERS TO SUPPORT GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton brought together some of his most
adept money-raisers on Tuesday night and tried to make the case
that they should support Vice President Al Gore to take his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record of this administration is his record,'' Clinton
told two dozen top fund-raisers in a small, mahogany-paneled room
at the Hay-Adams Hotel here before turning over the microphone to
Gore and melting back into the mostly male, dark-suited gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've built a foundation,'' Gore said of the Clinton
administration. ``Now it's time to reach for the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Tuesday night's events, which consisted of two
dinners with 25 people at each one, were not fund-raisers. The
well-heeled guests, who ranged from Harvey Weinstein, head of
Miramax, to Edgar Bronfman Jr., president of Seagrams Co. Ltd., did
not pay for their exclusive sit-down dinners.
</P>
<P>
   But they are noted for their ability to raise money and Tuesday
night's events were intended to woo them to the Gore camp. Some of
them have already helped raise substantial amounts for the vice
president and have committed to do more, and the clubby dinners
were viewed as added incentives to keep going.
</P>
<P>
   Among the attendees were Terry McAuliff, who has helped Clinton
raise record amounts of cash for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is trying to persuade McAuliff to become chairman of the
Democratic National Committee to oversee fund-raising for the 2000
elections. But friends say McAuliff already feels overcommitted,
since he has signed on to raise money for Hillary Rodham Clinton's
Senate campaign, Clinton's library, the Clintons' legal defense
fund and their millennium bash in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Other guests on Tuesday night included Dennis Archer Jr., a
businessman and son of the mayor of Detroit; Alan Solomont, former
treasurer of the Democratic National Committee; Alfonso Fanjul, one
of Florida's top sugar magnates; Sumner Redstone, chairman of
Viacom, and Julie Johnson and Kay Van Wey, partners in a Dallas law
firm and key fund-raisers in the gay community.
</P>
<P>
   There were numerous lawyers from across the country, including
Tom Leonard from Philadelphia, Oscar Holt from Westbury, N.Y., and
Isaac Byrd from Jackson, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Also present was Jayson Williams, center for the New Jersey Nets
and a particularly hot catch for Gore, since his rival for the
nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley, is from New Jersey and is a
former basketball star himself, for the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night marked the second time that Clinton has held a
campaign event for Gore. The first was in Little Rock on Saturday.
They plan two more events next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
