<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2558 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WATKINS-PHOTOGS-2TAKE     08-10 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATKINS-PHOTOGS-2TAKES-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WONDER OF IT: THE WEST JUST SO  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (af) 
 Richard B. Woodward is photography editor-at-large for DoubleTake
magazine.  
 By RICHARD B. WOODWARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Carleton Watkins would rank among the great
enigmas of late 19th-century American art even if his life weren't
so mysterious and sad. The pictures he made of scenic glories in
the West during the 1860s and '70s have been the sublime standard
for generations of landscape photographers. Ansel Adams, for one,
worked in his long shadow.
</P>
<P>
   A fine Watkins photograph is about as fine as a photograph gets.
There is nothing hit or miss about where he chose to aim his
camera. His so-called mammoth prints, developed from 18-by-22-inch
glass plates, often combine an eerie clarity with a bold massing of
shapes that verges on analytic geometry.
</P>
<P>
   As the rigor of his compositions is startling for the time, so
are his later studies of domesticated trees and fruits. A
romantic's sense of wonder was matched by a classicist's restraint.
Contrary to the practice of many painters in the West, then and
since, Watkins surveyed nature without trumpery. By printing the
facts he didn't need to elaborate myths.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition of his work at the San Francisco Museum of Modern
Art (through Sept. 7, then moving to the Metropolitan Museum of Art
on Oct. 12) offers pristine examples of Watkins the magnificent.
His prints of Yosemite Valley are front and center.
</P>
<P>
   The power of persuasion in these images was such that Congress
preserved the valley as a sanctuary in 1864; and for a while print
sales to the public gave Watkins a comfortable living.
</P>
<P>
   But the show's curator, Douglas R. Nickel, also highlights many
lesser-known pictures in order to ask questions about the puzzling
maturity of the work. Nothing in the Watkins biography _ what
little we know of it, anyway _ explains how a former carpenter and
bookstore clerk, born in 1829 in Oneonta, N.Y., came to possess
such expressive gifts. How did a bumpkin who spent his adult life
in the northern California backwater produce some of the most
forward-looking pictures of the 19th century?
</P>
<P>
   In looking for clues, Nickel examines the innovative ways of
seeing pioneered by the Victorians, specifically the invention of
stereography. An early form of 3-D that became a craze in the
1850s, it was, in Nickel's judgment, the most important and
pervasive visual technology the 19th century produced, excepting
photography itself.
</P>
<P>
   A series of booths at the end of the show lets viewers
experience _ with the aid of computer software coupled to wireless
goggles, both courtesy of StereoGraphics _ what the thrill was all
about. The show and catalog (which has been published by Abrams)
are rightfully subtitled ``The Art of Perception.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most field photographers of his time, Watkins also made
stereographs for the home market, some 6,500. Mass marketed as
cards that fit into a binocular hand viewer, they heightened the
drama of perception. A street scene could become a stage in a
stereograph, with sharp divisions between foregrounds and
backgrounds, and figures cut out from both like silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins exploited the stereograph's displacing qualities with
glee. In a shot of San Francisco, the streetcars look like toys in
a child's pop-up book. In another, of a ferry and its passengers,
he has arranged the people in layers, like ducks in a shooting
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   An 1878 image of lily pads on water reflecting a grid of windows
in the background offers the viewer no clear way to resolve a
pictorial riddle. Both the subject and its reflection seem to exist
in the same plane. As a study in flattened perspective, it rivals a
Degas.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins was clearly involved with the theatrics of space. He put
together multipanel photographs of cities, or of mountaintops, that
look down and across from high cliffs. Not only do these cinematic
panoramas convey the appropriate awe at the width of the horizon;
they can also bring on a dose of vertigo.
</P>
<P>
   Even the mesmerizing detail in some of Watkins' enormous plates,
as Nickel says, force the viewer's eyes to spiral around the print
and study it, rather than take it in at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Watkins was also making careful documents of
his time. His pictures of the Columbia River in 1867 show how the
Northwest was really won _ not on any battlefield, but in mining
camps and lumber mills, where the day-to-day harvesting of minerals
and timber produced the raw materials for exportable wealth.
</P>
<P>
   However much he may have manipulated space with his triptychs
and wide-angle lenses, Watkins stayed grounded in the economic
reality of his employers, primarily mine owners and the railroads.
A respect for the material world can be found throughout his work.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All his life he photographed trees as if he knew they were
essential for both life and culture. It is possible to examine a
dozen Watkins prints and, except for the train tracks and rare
steam engine, find little or no metal parts. The houses in a
panorama of Portland, Ore., appear to be entirely built of wood,
with stumps of felled trees prominent in the foreground. Even the
dams at this time were hewed out of timber.
</P>
<P>
   People hardly figure in Watkins' work, except as puny yardsticks
for measuring the loftier stature of nature. The five men standing
shoulder-to-shoulder in front of Grizzly Giant, the wizened sequoia
in Yosemite's Mariposa Grove, are barely visible beside the massive
base of its trunk. Almost no one in his pictures exhibits traits of
personality other than endurance in the face of vaster forces.
</P>
<P>
   The less grandiose trees he photographed in the 1870s may be his
most intimate work. They are like character studies. The buckeye
tree in a California front yard shades a cabin like a floppy hat.
His 1878 view of a house in a larch grove is as plain and mournful
as a Willa Cather novel.
</P>
<P>
   Seven detached figures stand in the shadows. The subject of the
picture appears to be neither the people nor the trees, but the
uneasy struggle to establish a home. A photograph of a box of
peaches on its side from 1887-88 is shocking in its simplicity. In
arranging the fruits so that their cleavage is unmistakable,
Watkins even seems to be telling a harmless dirty joke.
</P>
<P>
   That Watkins produced this majestic and diverse body of work
with little or no formal esthetic training is still hard to fathom,
as is his rapid and tragic decline in popularity. The Yosemite
pictures made him famous and employable. He was praised by Emerson
and Oliver Wendell Holmes. By 1871 his studio in San Francisco was
the grandest in the West.
</P>
<P>
   But in the late 1870s his fortunes reversed like a train rolling
backward down a mountain, and he never really found the brake. He
was a wretched businessman. In 1874 he lost a studio he had opened
in Yosemite, as well as the copyright on his plates of the park, to
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   At 50 he married a woman 28 years younger, only to find that he
could barely support her. The market for stereographs dried up
through saturation. Watkins' meticulous skills were less and less
in demand. He suffered from arthritis and blindness.
</P>
<P>
   In 1895-96 he lived with his family in a boxcar _ they couldn't
afford a house _ until his childhood friend, the railroad baron
Collis Huntington, deeded him a ranch. As a final blow, the 1906
San Francisco earthquake and fire destroyed the glass-plate
negatives in Watkins' main studio and, in effect, wiped out a
life's work. In 1910 he was committed to the Napa Hospital for the
Insane, where, six years later, he died. He is buried on the
grounds in an unmarked grave.
</P>
<P>
   The strangest puzzle may be how late recognition for Watkins has
been in coming. Beaumont Newhall's standard history of photography
didn't include a Watkins photograph in its first four editions.
Finally, in 1982, Watkins made the grade.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the last 25 years, thanks in part to the advocacy of
scholars like Peter Palmquist, has Watkins been considered the
finest American photographer of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   His contemporaries didn't regard him as anything special,
either. They never saw him as unusually modern in his picture
making but rather as an exceptional craftsman. That also seems to
be how Watkins saw himself.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few remarks we have from him is second-hand _ he left
no diary or articles, and gave no interviews _ from the
photographer John Hillers, who had brought him prints to review.
``I have little advice to offer,'' said Watkins. ``You are a clean
worker in which lies the great secret of photography.''
</P>
<P>
   Although scholars have found that there is a great more to it _
and to him _ than that, the bedrock of Watkins' remarkable
artistry, even after as excellent a show and catalog as this, can
still seem more submerged than exposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
