<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PATERSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JENNIFER PATERSON, TV COOK FROM `FAT LADIES,' DIES AT 71  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Uganda, Britain)   By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jennifer Paterson, the over-the-top co-star of the quirky
television cooking show ``Two Fat Ladies,'' died Tuesday at a
hospital in London, where she lived. She was 71.
</P>
<P>
   Lung cancer had been diagnosed last month after Ms. Paterson
fell ill while filming installments of the cooking series with her
partner, Clarissa Dickson Wright.
</P>
<P>
   The show, featuring the two unashamedly corpulent and
opinionated eccentrics, is a hit in Britain and the United States
and has been syndicated in other countries following its debut on
the British Broadcasting Corporation in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Paterson and Ms. Dickson Wright were unknown to each other
until they were brought together by a BBC producer in what was
described as a match made in ratings heaven. One fan who apparently
contributed to the ratings was Prince Charles, who sent a gift of
homemade organic tomato soup and vanilla ice cream to Ms. Paterson
after she disclosed her illness last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Paterson and Ms. Dickson Wright offered their viewers
cholesterol-soaked dishes that they favored in their own homes. One
show, called ``Meat,'' featured meatloaf draped with strips of
bacon, lamb stew, fillet of beef and, perhaps as a nod to health
fanatics, a pan-fried chicken dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame Americans for this fear of red meat and fat that's
spread all over England,'' Ms. Paterson told an interviewer last
year while taking a sip of vodka in a restaurant before heading to
the sidewalk for a pre-lunch cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dickson Wright agreed, although she credited the success of
the show to a backlash against what she called the health police.
``Our show seems to say to Americans that it's OK to eat red meat
and cook with butter,'' she said in the same article. ``I don't
know why they feel they need permission.''
</P>
<P>
   Each episode of ``The Two Fat Ladies'' was recorded at a
different location. Every show began with Ms. Paterson astride a
motorcycle with her partner squeezed into a sidecar, zooming toward
their destination. When they did their ``Meat'' show, for example,
they cooked for a girls' lacrosse team in the kitchen of a boarding
school.
</P>
<P>
   They each cooked two dishes per show, working in tandem and
punctuating their culinary advice with a raucous sense of humor on
any subject that took their fancy. They delighted in skewering the
pretensions of haute cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ms. Paterson said she was in fine shape for her age.
``Lots of meat, drink and cigarettes and not giving in to things,''
she said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   She was born into an army family and was unconventional even as
a child. At 15, she was expelled from convent school for being
disruptive; she later became a matron at a girls' boarding school
near Reading.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Paterson went on from there to become a professional chef.
She was the cook for the Ugandan legation in London and later
provided weekly lunches for celebrities, including Prince Charles.
She was a food columnist for The Spectator when she met Ms. Dickson
Wright, a former barrister who wrote a column for Decanter magazine
and owned a cookbook store in Edinburgh, where she lives.
</P>
<P>
   The pair was characterized by Suzanne Hamlin in a 1998 article
in The New York Times as being ``as appealing as someone else's
dotty aunts.'' But Ms. Hamlin, in reviewing their cookbook
``Cooking With the Two Fat Ladies'' (Clarkson Potter), reported
that all six of six recipes she tested did not work as described
and that eccentricities and farce failed to be compelling in a
cookbook that purported to be useful.
</P>
<P>
   Following its instructions, she said, one dish ended up looking
as though ``it had barely survived a brush fire'' and a pudding
that was touted as thick and creamy turned out ``wan and thin as a
sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is their rapid rise here, of course, that makes this
careless effort at a cookbook so regrettable,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Food Network began broadcasting the shows in the United
States in 1997 and, as Ms. Hamlin noted, ``in the blink of an eye,
they developed a cult following among those who have an innate
fondness for British eccentrics.'' American Public Television also
distributes ``Two Fat Women'' to stations all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Food Network is planning a two-hour tribute to Ms. Paterson,
who is survived by an uncle and two brothers, on Sunday night at 9.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dickson Wright told the BBC that she had last seen Ms.
Paterson 10 days ago, although they had spoken each day on the
telephone. She had intended to visit her Wednesday to drop off a
tin of caviar, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't see the point of flowers,'' Ms. Dickson Wright
said. ``She'd rather have caviar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
