<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2561 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-30S-FILM-SERIES-2TAKE     08-10 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-30S-FILM-SERIES-2TAKES-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE SPICE OF CHOICE WAS SIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 J. Hoberman is senior film critic for The Village Voice.  
 By J. HOBERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wish to join the Legion of Decency, which condemns vile and
unwholesome moving pictures. I unite with all who protest against
them as a grave menace to youth, to home life, to country and to
religion.'' So began a pledge written in the spring of 1934 by the
Archbishop of Cincinnati, John T. McNicholas.
</P>
<P>
   Distributed in Roman Catholic churches across America, the
petition garnered some four million signatures within a month.
</P>
<P>
   Racy and insolent, populated by dynamic, street-smart criminals
and glamorous ``fallen women'' in scanty lingerie, set in Art Deco
penthouses and skid row dives, predicated on breezy wisecracks and
slangy double-entendres that confounded censors and offended less
cosmopolitan audiences, the Hollywood movies of the early 1930s
were a different world. Or were they?
</P>
<P>
   ``I condemn absolutely those salacious motion pictures which,
with other degrading agencies, are corrupting public morals and
promoting sex mania in our land,'' the Legion of Decency pledge
continued.
</P>
<P>
   Adopted four years before the legion began its crusade, the
Motion Picture Producers and Distributors of America Production
Code had proscribed undue exposure, indecent dancing, lustful
kissing, obscenity and explicit adultery, seduction or rape, not to
mention ``sex perversion,'' ``white slavery'' and
``miscegenation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Code was not truly in force, having gone into effect
just as the movie industry was stunned by two surprise
developments, one technological, the other economic. Movies became
``talkies'' even as hard times battered a business previously
imagined depression-proof.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the stock market crash, Warner Brothers and Fox
were suffering heavy losses. Universal had discharged hundreds of
its employees. RKO was already in receivership. Paramount, which
would declare bankruptcy the following year, was selling off its
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Weekly movie attendance was 60 percent of what it had been
before the Depression began. By the summer of 1932, a third of
American moviehouses had gone dark, and exhibitors were
experimenting with exploitation angles ranging from double bills to
dish giveaways to bingo games. Producers were desperate and, as
demonstrated by ``The Joy of Pre-Code: Sex, Booze and Red Hot Jazz,
1930-33,'' a 44-film series starting on Friday at Film Forum 2,
they pushed the weakly enforced Code to its limits and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone brought up on the movies of the 1940s and 1950s,
those of the early '30s can be a revelation. Sinners escape
punishment and virtue is not necessarily rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Crime sometimes pays and marriage vows are frequently flouted.
Self-interest is a near-universal principle. Fast-talking,
tough-acting James Cagney became Warner Brothers' top star by
hustling his way up from the streets, but he was scarcely the only
tiger in the urban jungle. The now-forgotten Warren William,
oiliest of alpha males and caddish personification of ruthless
capitalism, abused the men and seduced the women lucky enough to be
working but unfortunate enough to be working for him.
</P>
<P>
   Women acted out as well. If the former factory worker Joan
Crawford was kept by the Park Avenue lawyer Clark Gable in MGM's
enormously successful ``Possessed'' (1931), the more proactive Jean
Harlow wrecked her boss' home, then married and betrayed him in the
1932 comedy ``Red-Headed Woman.'' In ``Female'' (1933), Warner
Brothers' biggest female star, Ruth Chatterton, ran an automobile
plant and satisfied her sex drive with a succession of handsome
young employees.
</P>
<P>
   Marlene Dietrich sold her body to support her sick husband in
``Blonde Venus'' (1932). That movie lost money for Paramount, but
the studio struck gold with Mae West _ even if Will Hays, the
mostly ineffectual head of the producers' and directors' Code, did
manage to keep them from titling her second vehicle ``It Ain't No
Sin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Face'' (1933), which opens the series on a bill with the
luridly expressionist Edward G. Robinson vehicle ``Two Seconds''
(1932), is a crude, still-powerful morality play in which Barbara
Stanwyck systematically sleeps her way to the pinnacle of economic
power. Dreamed up by the Warner production boss Darryl Zanuck in
the wake of MGM's ``Red-Headed Woman,'' the movie single-mindedly
tracks Stanwyck's climb from a gritty Pennsylvania steel town,
where she is pimped by her father in his speakeasy, to control of a
New York bank.
</P>
<P>
   Each new conquest celebrated by a honkytonk chorus from ``St.
Louis Blues,'' Stanwyck is a femme fatal as inexorable as the
Depression itself: her discarded men lose their jobs, their
fortunes and, in two cases, their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Goldstein, the director of repertory programming at Film
Forum 2, calls ``Baby Face'' the quintessential pre-Code movie,
although he singles out the moment in the 1932 ``Call Her Savage''
when an amorous Great Dane jumps Clara Bow as ``the most
astonishing pre-Code shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein organized his first pre-Code series 11 years ago. ``I
don't think anyone had ever done one before,'' he says. ``The
period was completely overlooked. They never showed these films on
television when I was growing up. Not one of them is a `classic'
and that's why it was a discovery for most people.'' Film Forum's
``Hollywood Before the Code'' not only clicked at the box office
but also received national publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Within the year, Goldstein said, revival houses in Boston,
Chicago, Los Angeles and San Francisco ran similar programs, while
MGM Home Video issued a collection of pre-Code movies. The
forthcoming series is Film Forum's fourth, and interest in the
period continues to grow. Two books are scheduled for publication
this fall, Thomas Doherty's scholarly history, ``Pre-Code
Hollywood: Sex, Immorality and Insurrection in American Cinema,
1930-34'' (Columbia University), and Mark A. Vieira's lavish
coffee-table volume, ``Sin in Soft Focus'' (Abrams).
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the pre-Code movies were attacked for their amoral
violence. The 1931-32 gangster cycle drew most of the heat _ even
Al Capone professed to disapprove, telling reporters that movies
like ``Public Enemy'' and ``Little Caesar'' were ``doing nothing
but harm to the younger element of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1932, the studios were cranking out ``bad girl'' movies.
Variety, which attributed their popularity to the female audience,
would estimate that 80 percent of the 440 pictures released during
the 1932-33 season had some sort of ``sex slant.'' Nevertheless,
some movies were more scarlet than others, and ``Red-Headed Woman''
in particular sent studios stampeding down the primrose path.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An Irving Thalberg project, written by Anita Loos to relaunch
Harlow at her new studio, ``Red-Headed Woman'' was as much
throwback as innovation. The irresistible vamp who haunted the
American screen 15 years earlier in the exotic form of Theda Bara
was resurrected as a gum-chewing stenographer.
</P>
<P>
   Sound brought silent movies down to earth, and Harlow embodied
the triumph of the vulgar, seducing her married prey on his living
room sofa with his photograph pinned to her garter. As comic as she
is steamy, Harlow's two-timing golddigger maintains audience
sympathy even when she petulantly shoots her estranged husband. Nor
does the movie see fit to punish her. The bad girl winds up in
Paris, mistress to a marquis, with a handsome chauffeur in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red-Headed Woman'' inspired Warner Brothers to make ``Baby
Face'' and Fox to adapt Tiffany Thayer's risque ``Call Her Savage''
as the comeback vehicle for the erstwhile ``It Girl,'' Clara Bow,
after sound and scandal short-circuited her career. (Plodding as
cinema and racist in its implications, this sordid saga of a half
American Indian vixen is best known today for its often
anthologized scene of two men dressed as French maids entertaining
the patrons of a Greenwich Village speakeasy.)
</P>
<P>
   Paramount adapted William Faulkner's sensational ``Sanctuary''
in 1933 for the ``The Story of Temple Drake'' (thrill-seeking
Southern belle slips into degradation after she is raped by a
gangster and dumped in a New Orleans brothel), while embarking on a
protracted struggle to bring Broadway's bawdy sensation, Mae West,
to Hollywood. Hays managed to delay West's screen debut but failed
to prevent it. Released in early 1933, ``She Done Him Wrong''
grossed $2 million in less than two months, returning 10 times its
production costs in North America alone.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, pre-Code advertising promised more sex than the
movies themselves delivered. (For ``Baby Face'' _ ``She Had IT and
Made IT Pay.'') The strategy ultimately backfired. It was a movie
billboard that so offended Denis Cardinal Dougherty of Philadelphia
that he called for a boycott of all movies. The first selective
boycotts had been organized by the Detroit diocese during the
summer of 1933.
</P>
<P>
   With the Legion of Decency pledge promoted from the pulpit and
Mae West pilloried in the Hearst press, the crusade gathered
momentum over the next 10 months. ``Hollywood is in the most
serious crisis of its history,'' The Los Angeles Times reported in
June 1934. With the creation of President Franklin D. Roosevelt's
National Recovery Administration, which sought to regulate film
exhibition practices, the studios were worried that the federal
government might then try to police movie content as well.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Bank of America's chairman, A.H. Giannini, threatened
to link continued financing to Production Code Administration
approval, the industry buckled.
</P>
<P>
   That summer, Hays had appointed the hard-nosed and
well-connected Catholic journalist Joseph Breen to enforce the
Code. (As Doherty points out, pre-Code is a misnomer; the correct
term should be pre-Breen.) From then on, as the screenwriter Herman
Mankiewicz paraphrased the Code for his peers, the hero and heroine
have to be virgins, while the villain can have sex with anybody he
wants, ``cheating and stealing, getting rich and whipping the
servants.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``But you have to shoot him in the end.'' By 1935,
Hollywood had passed from inspired disorder into the golden age of
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Code improve American movies as well as morals? Doherty
concludes his detailed and fascinating study by stating the
``inconvenient truth'' that Hollywood's ``most vivid and compelling
motion pictures'' were produced ``under the most severe and
narrow-minded censorship.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet the early, free-wheeling '30s churned up a remarkable
number of enduring celluloid archetypes, ranging from gangsters and
gold diggers through Dracula and King Kong, to such pop icons as
W.C. Fields, Mae West, the Marx Brothers, Betty Boop and even
Mickey Mouse. Moreover, individual filmmakers as distinguished as
Ernst Lubitsch, Josef von Sternberg and Busby Berkeley produced
their finest work during the pre-Code period.
</P>
<P>
   There is something to be said for crisis as a stimulus to
popular art. Similarly, the transformation of movies to talkies
served to break existing rules for narrative filmmaking, even as
the Depression pushed producers towards wild experimentation. Taken
as a whole, the movies of the early '30s constitute a distinctive
American idiom.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest pre-Code movies are as rowdy, pungent and oddball
as the Sunday funnies or the country blues. Tawdry gems like the
electric-chair flashback ``Two Seconds,'' the declasse daisy-chain
``Blood Money'' _ a madam loves a bail bondsman who loves a
masochistic debutante who loves a bank robber _ or the tropical,
``No Exit''-like nightmare ``Safe in Hell'' are hard-boiled beyond
belief and almost kabuki in their economy of means.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to their Depression-induced frugality and the exigencies
of the double feature, pre-Code movies are admirably terse. Perhaps
even more wondrous than their convoluted, down-and-dirty narratives
is the seemingly lost art of squeezing such shenanigans into a
highly satisfying 70 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
