<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-REPUBS-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO SUSPENDS SENATE CAMPAIGN; LEAVES FIELD CLEAR FOR GIULIANI 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bowing to an emerging consensus among state
Republican Party leaders, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island has
decided to suspend his primary campaign for the U.S. Senate,
clearing the way for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to become the party's
uncontested choice for 2000, party officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who has scheduled a news conference Wednesday to announce
his plans, reached his decision reluctantly and after a secluded
weekend of consultation with supporters and advisers, an aide to
Lazio said. He decided to suspend his campaign only after Gov.
George Pataki _ who had been tacitly nudging him to challenge
Giuliani _ announced on Friday that he thought Giuliani was the
best candidate the Republicans had to send up against Hillary
Rodham Clinton, and urged Lazio to defer an announcement tour he
had scheduled for next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and his aides did not return telephone calls seeking
comment Tuesday. His press secretary, Mollie Conkey, said Lazio
would detail his decision at a news conference on Long Island
today. She declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, neither Giuliani nor Mrs. Clinton, who was
campaigning in New York again Tuesday, meeting with political
leaders in Queens and the Bronx and holding a forum with union
members in Queens, has formally announced a Senate candidacy. But
with each passing day, both have given increasingly stronger
indications that they are in the race to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's reported agreement to back off would produce a highly
unusual scenario for New York politics: a contest for an open seat
in the U.S. Senate between two candidates who have been spared the
rigors and expense of a party primary. That dynamic, assuming it
holds up, means that Giuliani and Mrs. Clinton will be able to
focus without distraction on a general election campaign that seems
likely be a constant presence in New York between now and November
2000.
</P>
<P>
   A primary between Lazio and Giuliani would have been a
particular problem for the mayor, because it probably would have
forced him to stress some of his more conservative positions in an
effort to counter Lazio with a Republican primary electorate. That
would have inevitably complicated a general election campaign
against Mrs. Clinton, assuming he won the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Lazio's advisers described him as unhappy with Pataki
and startled by the governor's announcement on Friday. They said
that he had given serious consideration over the weekend to
following the advice of some associates, notably Michael Long, the
state Conservative Party leader, and staying in the race.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Lazio reportedly concluded that it would be
impossible to stage a realistic run with explicit opposition from
Pataki and Alfonse D'Amato, the former senator and Pataki's
political ally.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Pataki and D'Amato to support Giuliani, no
matter how reluctantly, would have complicated Lazio's candidacy
every step of the way: from raising money to finding party leaders
to host political events. Most important, it would have made it
nearly impossible to win enough organized support from the state
party, 25 percent of the votes at the party convention, to
guarantee him a spot on a primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how he had any choice,'' said an associate to
Pataki, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In deferring his plans rather than dropping out entirely, Lazio
was following the script suggested by Pataki. That would allow
Lazio to enter the race if Giuliani ended up deciding to skip it,
an unlikely though not impossible occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   In making that suggestion, Pataki called on Giuliani to firm up
his political plans quickly to allow the party to prepare for the
contest to replace Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the Democrat who is
retiring. At City Hall, Giuliani, asked about Lazio's decision,
seemed in no hurry to rush his own schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have got my own decisions to make, campaign to put together,
money to raise, political support to gather,'' Giuliani said, ``and
you know I am not going to pay attention to anybody else's campaign
until sometime a year from now when this election really gets
started. Everybody has escalated this election way too fast. People
are going to be really bored with it in about three months if we
don't slow it down a little.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, appearing at another ``listening forum,'' this one
with union members in Queens, also declined to comment on
developments among her prospective opponents. ``I try not to think
about issues that I have no control over,'' she said. ``And you
know what the other party decides to do is strictly their
business.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the evolution of a contest in which both major party
candidates for statewide office might win their party's support
without a nomination battle _ an almost unprecedented event in
modern New York politics _ is the latest sign of just how
profoundly the prospective candidacy of a first lady has changed
the dynamics of the race.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Democrats, other prospective candidates
cleared the field as soon as Mrs. Clinton said she was interested.
In the case of Republicans, party leaders across the nation had
been urging the state party to back Giuliani as the strongest
candidate the party could offer to assure the removal of the
Clintons from public life after President Clinton leaves the White
House in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, Lazio's prospective exit from the race was good,
if less than surprising, news for Giuliani. Given the importance
the national party had attached to the race, most Republicans had
assumed that Pataki would eventually advise Lazio to pull out and
allow Giuliani to proceed unencumbered.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are political complications ahead for Giuliani
involving the state's Conservative Party, which typically
cross-endorses Republican candidates for statewide office. Long,
the Conservative Party leader, said that Giuliani called him on
Saturday morning and asked for a meeting to discuss the possibility
of winning a spot on the Conservative Party line.
</P>
<P>
   Long has left little question both about his inclination to
support Lazio and his suspicions about Giuliani's ideological
credentials. He said Tuesday that he could not imagine the
Conservative Party supporting Giuliani unless the mayor made two
major concessions: abandoning his connection to the Liberal Party,
which endorsed him in his race for mayor, and dropping his
opposition to measures to ban a form of late-term abortion, which
opponents describe as partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look to run a candidate on our line,'' Long said. ``We
weren't formed just to pick winners. I don't need to send someone
to Washington who winds up voting against cutting taxes, or not to
shrink the size of government, or sending someone to Washington who
doesn't want to vote to stop partial-birth abortions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
