<SLUG> BC-AGENCIES-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: SIGNS OF STRAIN BETWEEN AGENCIES AND CLIENTS
CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Relations between agencies and advertisers are
showing signs of strain for a second consecutive year, according to
an annual survey.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the survey, which asked executives at agencies
and client companies to assess the nature of their dealings with
each other, indicate that efforts to narrow the gap between them
have fallen short, as they did last year. The two years of
deterioration follow surveys in 1996 and 1997 that had indicated
improvement in relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an industry, we're not doing great,'' said Nancy L. Salz,
president of Nancy L. Salz Consulting in New York, who offered a
preview of the findings of the 1999 Salz Survey of
Advertiser-Agency Relations. ``Our numbers are absolutely
confirming what the AAF found.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salz's reference was to a much-publicized survey released in
June by the American Advertising Federation. That study showed
surprising skepticism among top corporate executives about the
effectiveness of advertising in helping their companies grow as
well as a reluctance to declare themselves more than merely
satisfied with advertising on behalf of their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers who responded to the Salz Consulting survey also
judged advertising to be less important to their sales growth than
before.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when asked how much sales could improve if their
agencies were always able to do the best possible work, the mean
figure the respondents gave was 21.4 percent. That was the lowest
since a mean of 21.1 percent in the recession year of 1991 and a
sharp decline from 31.4 percent as recently as 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And when asked to rate the quality of work from their agencies
on a scale of 1 to 10, with 10 highest, the mean rating from
advertisers for 1999 was 7.0. That was the lowest since the same
rating in 1992 and 1993 and a significant decrease from 7.5 as
recently as 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about accountability,'' Ms. Salz said.
``Advertising as a tool has got to be accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't `Show me the money,''' she added. ``It's `Show me the
results.'''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, this year's answers to the survey, which has
been conducted for the last 14 years, point to a results-oriented
way to dissipate tensions between Madison Avenue and clients: the
practice known as performance-based compensation. That's when
clients switch from traditional methods of paying their agencies,
like a 15 percent commission or a flat fee, to basing payments on
predetermined, measurable goals like increases in sales of
products. Among the well-known marketers using or experimenting
with performance-based compensation is the Procter &AMP; Gamble Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Performance-based compensation has an effect for the good,''
Ms. Salz said, reviewing survey tables showing that advertisers
using it reported smoother relationships with their agencies than
those that did not: more teamwork, more respect, more focus on the
work.
</P>
<P>
   Performance-based compensation is no cure-all, Ms. Salz
acknowledged; otherwise ``you'd see more people using it'' than the
39 percent of advertisers who reported they did. Agency executives
who responded said that 22.9 percent of their clients were
compensating them based on performance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Salz said, performance-based compensation ``offers a
foundation for better advertising,'' primarily because it
encourages agencies and clients to collaborate more, by ``focusing
on common goals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's putting agencies in the same boat as clients,'' she
added. ``They are rowing or not rowing together.''
</P>
<P>
   For agencies, the survey indicated a potential bump in the road
to more performance-based compensation: clients using it said they
were likely to go beyond their agency rosters in assigning tasks in
realms like strategy and marketing. Of course, the struggle to keep
clients from seeking advice elsewhere has been one of the most
pressing recent concerns among agency leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The three reasons most often cited by advertisers for delegating
tasks were expertise, wanting a new perspective and cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``With more on the line under performance-based compensation,''
Ms. Salz said, ``advertisers are paying a lot more attention to how
they're spending their money.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted in March and May for Salz Consulting by
Thurm Marketing and Consulting Inc. in Princeton, N.J. Salz
Consulting sponsors training seminars in agency relations and
advertising development for marketers like Clorox, GTE and
Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
