u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-500&AMP;ADD-NY     08-10 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ EXECUTIVE WILL BE KNICKS' NEW GENERAL MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying it was time to grow up and blaze his own
trail, Scott Layden, the longtime executive of the Utah Jazz,
announced Tuesday that he will become the next general manager of
the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will officially announce the hiring at a news
conference Wednesday at Madison Square Garden. Dave Checketts,
Madison Square Garden president, was not available for comment
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Layden, who made his announcement at a news conference at the
Delta Center, worked for the Jazz for the past 18 years. He joined
the franchise as an assistant coach in 1981 while his father,
Frank, now the president of the Jazz, was the team's head coach. He
has been Utah's vice president of basketball operations since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   To come to New York, Layden, 42, will receive a multiyear
contract believed to be worth more than $1.5 million annually from
the Knicks. He was paid less than $400,000 last season by the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes as a really tough decision to move on, but it just
feels like the right thing to do,'' said Layden, who has also
served as Utah's head scout and director of player personnel. ``I
need to move on and grow up a little bit. I've really felt like
I've been on the coat tails of some brilliant people _ coaches,
players, owners and the people who work in this organization.''
While Layden has no family ties to the Knicks, he does have more
than a working relationship with Checketts, who was a member of
Utah's front office from 1983 to 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping build the Jazz into a Western Conference
contender, Checketts and Layden became close friends. Though
Layden's credentials are impressive, his strong relationship with
Checketts is believed to have been a major factor in his hiring.
Despite giving Jeff Van Gundy a two-year, $10 million contract
extension last month, tension still exists between Checketts and
the Knicks' head coach because of Checketts' awkward courtship of
Phil Jackson near the end of last season, according to people
within the Knicks organization. Realizing that he and Van Gundy
could butt heads in the future, Checketts wanted to bring an ally
into the organization, which is why he is willing to give Layden a
contract worth nearly twice as much as that of his predecessor,
Ernie Grunfeld, who made $800,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy, who is scheduled to return Wednesday from a vacation
in California, could not be reached for comment, but his agent, Rob
Ades, said his client would not be paranoid about the hiring of
Layden. ``I am happy for Frank Layden that his son got the job
because Frank is my friend and I've known him for 35 years,'' Ades
said. ``I am sorry that Ed Tapscott did not get the job because he
is my friend and I've known him for 20 years. I've never met Scott,
but if he's anything like his father, he's a great guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapscott, the Knicks' vice president of player personnel for the
past two seasons, had been serving as the club's interim general
manager since Grunfeld was unceremoniously removed from that post
on April 21.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The prevailing assumption for months was that Tapscott, who has
more than enough qualifications to fill the position, would receive
the job. Tapscott has been with the Knicks since 1991 and refused
to comment when reached Tuesday by telephone. Had Tapscott been
promoted, he would have become only the fifth African-American
general manager in the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed as an outstanding judge of talent, Layden has been the
key decision-maker concerning Utah's player personnel moves since
1992. While the future Hall of Famers, Karl Malone and John
Stockton, were already playing for the Jazz, Layden put together
the complementary cast that helped Utah reach the NBA Finals in
1997 and 1998. In 1994, he orchestrated a trade that brought the
shooting guard, Jeff Hornacek, to the Jazz, and a year later, he
discovered the now reputable backup point guard, Howard Eisley, in
the Continental Basketball Association. Some of Layden's finest
work was accomplished in the draft, where plucked two gems late in
the second round. In 1993, he used the 45th pick to select Bryon
Russell, who has developed into a solid small forward, and three
years later, he acquired the versatile Shandon Anderson with the
54th pick. ``He has picked some outstanding players in the second
round,'' said Wally Walker, the Seattle Sonics general manager.
``That's a team that has been good for a long time, and he's done a
great job despite always having a low position in the draft.''
Though New York will provide a much different atmosphere than Salt
Lake City, Layden will not be totally out of his element. His
father grew up in Brooklyn, and Scott developed into a top-notch
high school athlete in upstate New York. After playing collegiate
basketball at St. Francis of Pennsylvania, he landed his first
coaching job at Fairleigh Dickinson University in New Jersey. At
Tuesday's farewell conference in Utah, Layden added that one of his
main reasons for making the move was that his wife, Marsha, and
four daughters are excited about tackling New York City. ``He said
his family really liked New York,'' said Evan Silverman, a Jazz
spokesman. ``And that they thought it was time to move on, time to
make a change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
