<HEADLINE>
REPORT NOTES SAFETY FLAWS IN MANY COMMERCIAL NUCLEAR REACTORS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: This story was budgeted earlier as RADIOACTIVE-NICKEL) 
(sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly all the operators of commercial nuclear
reactors in the country have told the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
that their systems might not work as required in an emergency, an
analysis of government data by a nuclear safety group showed on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The group, Critical Mass, based its analysis on reports over the
last three years made by operators who found that plant equipment
or procedures differed from what engineers specified in the safety
analyses required for the plants to be licensed.
</P>
<P>
   Of 111 reactors licensed for operation from October 1996 to May
1999, 102 reported over 500 instances of operating outside their
``design basis,'' or the conditions on which they were licensed,
the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The utility reports varied from ones about a fire door failing
to close during a test to others about the discovery of wiring
problems that would have prevented a safety system from working.
Many of the reports were made when a system broke down, though the
system was often the second of two redundant systems, which
nonetheless required that the plant be shut down.
</P>
<P>
   In one case employees at a Connecticut plant, Millstone 1, near
New London, pointed out that the company was moving hot nuclear
fuel faster than its license allowed. The Nuclear Regulatory
Commission ordered all reactors to examine their licenses, their
equipment and their operations, and report back on whether the
three matched.
</P>
<P>
   The report's author, James P. Riccio, wrote that the lapses had
created situations where ``a single event or condition could have
prevented the functioning of safety systems needed to shut down the
reactor.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Nuclear Energy Institute, the industry's trade
association, took the opposite tack. ``One has to note you do have
defense in depth built into the facility,'' a spokesman, Steve
Kerekes, said. ``That's the whole engineering principle.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, William F. Kane, the
associate director for inspection and programs, said all such
reports were carefully analyzed by the commission staff. He said
that there were more such reports in the last few years but that it
could be ``a function of how hard things are being looked at''
after the discovery of discrepancies at Millstone 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
