<SLUG> BC-SILICON-GRAPHICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILICON GRAPHICS EXPECTS LAYOFFS AND REVAMPING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Minn., Wis.)   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Silicon Graphics Inc., which has been mired in
losses and dwindling market share for much of the last four years,
plans to lay off 1,000 to 1,500 people, or up to 15 percent of its
work force, and sell or spin off several businesses, including the
Cray Research line of supercomputers.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said Tuesday that it would record a charge of
$100 million to $200 million in connection with the revamping.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Belluzzo, who became Silicon Graphics' chairman and
chief executive 18 months ago, has been working to turn the company
around. And, Silicon Graphics did surprise analysts with a profit
for its fourth quarter, which ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Tuesday's announcement indicates that the company
still faces major strategic and structural problems, which may or
may not be solved by this latest effort to sharpen its focus.
</P>
<P>
   Best known for building the computers used to create such
memorable special effects as the dinosaurs in the movies ``Jurassic
Park'' and ``The Lost World,'' Silicon Graphics enjoyed phenomenal
growth through the late 1980s and early 1990s. But growth slowed
late in 1995, and management has erred and new products have
fumbled, hurting the company's financial performance ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Silicon Graphics, which is based in Mountain View,
Calif., fell $3.75, or 23 percent, to $12.4375, on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Graphics said that it had formed a separate business
unit for Cray, which is based in Chippewa Falls, Wis., and Eagan,
Minn., and that it was in discussions with several companies
regarding a possible sale or partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it would spin off its Media Base media
streaming application, engineering team and technology to a newly
formed company with venture capital backing. It has previously
discussed finding a buyer for its Wavefront and Alias software
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Graphics also said it had reached a preliminary
understanding with a potential joint venture partner to take over
its Visual Workstation line of products based on Intel
microprocessors and Microsoft's Windows NT operating system.
Executives said terms of the deal had not been finalized and it is
not clear if Silicon Graphics would retain a major stake in the
joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced amid great fanfare in January, the NT machines were
supposed to broaden the company's reach to the low end of the
graphics market, but they were late to market, and have been
further plagued by production problems.
</P>
<P>
   If every aspect of the revamping is carried out, Silicon
Graphics will emerge as a smaller company focused primarily on
midsize high performance servers aimed at the Internet market. The
company will continue to produce its graphics work stations, which
use its own Irix version of the Unix operating system and MIPS
microprocessors, and will also develop products using the Linux
variant of Unix.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it is not clear Silicon Graphics would find buyers
or viable partners for the pieces of the business it wants to sell,
and noted that the entire company had effectively been for sale for
some time without takers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has been on the block for two years and nobody has
done anything,'' said Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Belluzzo said that Silicon Graphics expected a loss from the
Windows NT work station business in its first fiscal quarter, but
that the other parts of the business remained profitable, and the
company should report a profit over all in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
