<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS PITCHES SCORELESS GAME FOR 5 INNINGS, THEN ... OAKLAND WINS
6-1  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ At the moment Roger Clemens knew he was going
to be relieved Tuesday, when he saw Manager Joe Torre headed toward
the mound, Clemens stared downward. His catcher Jorge Posada walked
up and reassuringly tapped his glove on Clemens' side, and so did
first baseman Tino Martinez. But Clemens only glanced up a couple
of times before departing.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens wants to do better. He knows more is expected of him. He
knows he is expected to be the staff leader, the ace, the guy who
makes everybody else feel as if there is absolutely no chance the
Yankees will lose on the day he pitches. He knows he's not meeting
those expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Engaged in a scoreless game Tuesday, Clemens pitched himself
into trouble in the sixth inning, allowed four runs and the Yankees
went on to lose to the Athletics, 6-1. Omar Olivares, one of the
pitchers acquired by Oakland before the trade deadline 10 days ago,
pitched into the seventh inning and allowed just one run.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had won six straight games and 17 of their last 23;
they are playing better and building momentum during the last third
of the regular season. But Clemens - the most crucial Yankees'
puzzle in need of solving - remains an enigma. He allowed nine
hits, five walks and five runs in 6 1/3 innings Tuesday, raising
his ERA to 4.92. His record is 10-5, but Torre is sure Clemens'
desire to pitch better chafes at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a lot tougher if Roger is not pitching the
way Roger can pitch, and we need him very desperately, and I think
sometimes he is a little too analytical and he puts a little bit
too much on himself,'' said Torre, ``as opposed to going out there
and letting it happen. He may try to make it happen a little too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure Clemens places on himself, Torre said, ``is going
to relax here sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it is,'' the manager added. ``It gets to a point where
he's going to find it.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he thought that maybe Clemens had found himself in
the last four innings of work in Seattle last week, when he shut
out the Mariners. But Clemens was unable to develop a second pitch
Tuesday to complement his fastball - a decent split-fingered
fastball or a consistent breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite possible for a pitcher to win a game throwing just
one type of pitch for strikes; Clemens probably has done so dozen
of times in his career. To offset the lack of a secondary pitch,
Clemens needed to throw strikes early in the ball-strike count.
With a count of no balls and one strike, or 1-2, a hitter cannot
anticipate just one particular pitch; he must be on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens fell behind in the count over and over Tuesday. He
pitched himself into situations in which he needed to throw
strikes, and the Oakland hitters were well aware of the fact that
Clemens' fastball was really the only pitch he could rely on. When
Clemens fell behind in the count, he might as well have shouted to
the world that he was going to throw a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw hard today,'' said Torre, ``but the darn count got
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all great pitchers, Clemens managed to escape a few times.
The Athletics had two runners on and one out in the first and did
not score; they had runners at first and third and two out in the
third and did not score; they had a runner at second and one out in
the fifth and did not score.
</P>
<P>
   Twice the Athletics hit into double plays; Clemens has generated
a total of 12 double-play grounders this year, half coming in his
last four starts.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the sixth inning that Clemens' one-dimensional
stuff finally hurt him. Randy Velarde reached a 3-ball, 2-strike
count leading off. With the game scoreless and the middle of the
Oakland lineup ready to follow Velarde, Clemens had to throw a
strike; he had to throw his fastball. Velarde lined a single to
right field.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens walked Jason Giambi on seven pitches. First and second
and nobody out. Clemens tried to vary his pattern, throwing a
first-pitch slider to Matt Stairs, but it spun low for ball one.
Clemens threw ball two, and Stairs, assuming Clemens had to throw
fastballs, began to swing like a slugger in a lumberjack's
slow-pitch softball league. He fouled off one pitch, then hit into
a forceout.
</P>
<P>
   One out, first and third.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens threw three straight balls to Scott Spiezio, then a
strike, before he fouled off two pitches. Clemens had to throw a
strike. He had to throw a fastball. Spiezio was ready: He drove a
liner over the head of Bernie Williams in center, scoring Velarde,
and because Stairs quickly realized Williams could not catch the
ball, he scored, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Grieve followed, and again, Clemens pitched himself into a
corner, throwing three straight balls. He fired a strike, and
Grieve, too, correctly anticipated Clemens would throw a fastball.
When he did, Grieve crushed it, maybe 12-15 rows deep in the right
field stands. Oakland led, 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt tremendous out there today,'' said Clemens. ``I made
two mistakes, and both mistakes they hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens wants to be better. He wants to get on that Clemens-type
roll, and he's got about 8 or 9 starts left before the playoffs to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter has always been known as an inside-out hitter,
driving inside pitches and swatting them to right field for
singles. But in his current slump - his average has dropped from
.376 on July 20 to .350 - he has been pulling the ball to the left
side. Jeter has not made an out to the right side of the field
since his first at-bat in a game against Toronto Aug. 2, and
opposing pitchers have taken to pounding him with inside
fastballs... Outfielder Chad Curtis left the Yankees team to be
with Candace Curtis, his wife, for the birth of their third child. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
