u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SECURITY-GUNS-     08-10 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SECURITY-GUNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SCHOOLS REPORT FEWER GUN EXPULSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(gm) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Far fewer students are being expelled for bringing
guns to school, the U.S. Department of Education reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a new state-by-state survey comparing the academic year
1997-1998 to the previous year, the department found that
expulsions for carrying firearms onto school property dropped by
nearly a third, from 5,724 students to 3,930.
</P>
<P>
   The study is the second examination of how schools around the
country are implementing the Gun-Free School Act, a federal law
passed in 1994 requiring that school districts expel any student
who brings a weapon to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot compromise the safety of the millions of students
who do obey the rules by allowing those who do not to remain in the
same classrooms,'' said Secretary of Education Richard W. Riley at
a news conference here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Based on reports submitted by the states, the survey found that
62 percent of the expulsions were for handguns; 31 percent for
other types of firearms, including bombs, grenades and starter
pistols; and 7 percent for rifles or shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than half the cases were at high schools.
Thirty-three percent were at junior high schools and 10 percent at
elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   California and Texas reported the most incidents, with more than
300 expulsions, though the number declined for both states, by 47
percent and 20 percent, respectively. New York state registered
about a 30 percent drop, from 128 to 91. Wyoming has not expelled
any students for firearm violations in the two years surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the overall percentage declined, 20 states reported
increases, including Oklahoma (0 to 17), Delaware (7 to 29) and
Tennessee (98 to 192).
</P>
<P>
   The quality of data collection varied widely, researchers
warned, with some states making no distinction for type of weapon
or for school level. Researchers also cautioned that the data does
not provide insight into how many students carry guns to school,
but rather whether they are being disciplined for violations.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are in line with other youth violence studies. The
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, in a study released
last week, found that violence committed by teen-agers has declined
this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of high school students carrying a weapon dropped
from 26 percent in 1991 to 19 percent in 1997, according to that
report, published in the Journal of the American Medical
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new and promising data, coupled with last week's findings
from the Centers for Disease Control, shows that fewer young people
are carrying guns or taking them into schools,'' Riley said. ``This
is good news coupled with the fact that the overall rate of school
violence is down. But communities need to continue to use
comprehensive approaches to keeping schools, students and educators
safe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
