<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2585 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-SECURITY-LAD     08-10 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-SECURITY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY TIGHTENED AT L.A. DAY-CARE CENTERS, PARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Staff writers Phillip W. Browne, Robert Monroe, Rick Orlov and
Krystn Shrieve contributed to this story 
BY TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Just moments after the shooting at the day camp
in Los Angeles' north San Fernando Valley, frantic parents deluged
day-care centers across the San Fernando Valley with calls while
the centers locked their doors and arranged to send children home.
</P>
<P>
   City park and recreation programs near the shooting also took
emergency measures to ensure the safety of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some lunatic is loose, who knows if somebody could come
here,'' said Sandy Tandler as she picked up her daughter Tuesday at
the Bernard Milken Jewish Community Center in the West Hills
community. ``We have no idea what this guy could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Rouss, executive vice president of Jewish Community Centers
of Los Angeles, said officials have stepped up security at their
other 12 sites in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Unsure whether the gunman was targeting Jewish centers, the
Bernard Milken campus, a sister faclity of the North Hills Jewish
Community Center, asked the Los Angeles police to send officers and
called parents to pick up children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are horrified. We are saddened by this,'' said Jack Mayer,
executive director of The Jewish Federation/Valley Alliance in West
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   At Children's Wonderland in the Warner Center in the Woodland
Hills community of the Valley, a secular day-care center, officials
canceled parent tours of the facility, locked all doors that led
onto the street and kept children indoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not allowing anybody inside the premises who doesn't
belong here,'' said Mary Willoughby, assistant director of the
center, which received dozens of calls from alarmed parents.
</P>
<P>
   Willoughby said it will take a long time to recover from the
emotional fallout. ``The teachers are a little uneasy; the parents
are uneasy; we're all emotionally upset,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Soboroff, president of the city's Recreation and Parks
Commission, said all nearby parks and recreation centers
immediately went into an emergency operation after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it's no in-no out,'' Soboroff said. ``Any kids who
are in a program are immediately taken care of, and we don't let
any people in the buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Steve Tucker of Temple Ramat Zion in Northridge said
children in day care were moved to a locked area and parents called
to take them home.
</P>
<P>
   At Temple B'Nai Hayim Children's Center in Sherman Oaks,
officials hustled their 20 charges indoors as soon as they heard
the news. ``We took children inside right away, and we stayed away
from the windows,'' said Tatyana Ingel, head teacher of the
temple's preschool.
</P>
<P>
   At Temple Beth Hillel, a reform congregation in North Hollywood,
officials considered hiring a security guard.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish temples and preschools in the Simi Valley and Thousand
Oaks areas north of Los Angeles opted to stay open following
Tuesday's shooting.
</P>
<P>
   A police officer was stationed at Congregation B'Nai Emet in
Simi Valley until the 18 children at the Reform temple's summer day
camp went home for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no threat, no reason to believe there will be any
problems,'' police Sgt. Bob Gardner ``They were just feeling a
little uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
