<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PURE-POP-THEATER-ART-3TAKES-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK AFTER QUIRK IN SIDE-BY-SIDE FESTIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15)  
 (af)  
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the fractious world of Off Off Broadway, it was
bound to happen. The Fringe has developed a fringe.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Wednesday, the downtown theater scene will be witness
to the opening of two simultaneous festivals, each based on the
Lower East Side and each purporting to represent the rich variety
among the city's littlest and least-known theater troupes.
</P>
<P>
   This year's newcomer is the Pure Pop Theater Festival, which
will kick off just hours after the first show of the New York
International Fringe Festival, now in its third summer.
</P>
<P>
   Pure Pop's organizers promise to match the Fringe quirk for
quirk, with programming that includes a rarely seen temperance play
(``Ten Nights in a Barroom'' by William Pratt), an 18th-century
Japanese epic (``The Battles of Coxinga'' by Chikamatsu Monzaemon)
and several shows with titles not suitable for a family newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Pure Pop promises to stage nearly 60 productions
over seven weeks (through Oct. 3), at sites ranging from the Queens
Theater in the Park to Theater 4S, a 15-seater in an East Village
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Fringe will present some 150 productions in 12
days, through Aug. 29, an ambitious schedule that includes theater,
dance and performance art. Here, too, some of the titles suggest a
deep immersion in the odd: ``Urinetown,'' an original musical, and
``Jinkies,'' a series of Scooby Doo episodes based on the
television cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a revival of the Robert Wilson-Tom Waits-William
S. Burroughs rock opera ``The Black Rider,'' which was staged at
the Brooklyn Academy of Music in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Does downtown really need all this? Aaron Beall, the founder of
Pure Pop, answers: ``Nobody's saying to Lincoln Center, `Hey, too
many festivals, guys! Too much creativity! You've got to stop it!
Why do you need the Mozart? You just did Schubert! Enough with the
Mendelssohn!'''
</P>
<P>
   Pure Pop and the Fringe have a shared history. Beall (pronounced
Bell) was a founder of the Fringe, but earlier this year he had a
falling out with a co-founder, John Clancy, and left to start Pure
Pop. ( Beall is also the founder of Todo Con Nada, a storefront
theater on Ludlow Street, and Clancy is also the artistic director
of the downtown theater group Present Company).
</P>
<P>
   Beall's departure led to rumors _ and news reports _ of a
vitriolic crisis in the heart of the city's Off Off Broadway
community. But Clancy and Beall, who are both 35, say there is
little animus between them. They ascribe the fight to personality
differences and some grumbling over dividing box office receipts.
Each man's company lost money on the two previous Fringe festivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When times are tight, a little bit of money gets to be very
important,'' Clancy said at the Theatorium, the Fringe's
headquarters and mainstage on Stanton Street. ``But Aaron and I are
getting along.''
</P>
<P>
   What the two men can also agree on is that their festivals
represent only a part of what is going on Off Off Broadway, which
many on the scene say is in the midst of a period of remarkable
popularity, economic growth and structural change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's an influx of extraordinary people working in
the scene right now,'' said the playwright Mac Wellman, a stalwart
of downtown theater. ``And a lot of them don't want to make it in
the traditional way.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many in the new generation of theater artists and
downtown producers have begun to exhibit the professional trappings
of larger institutions: press agents, marketing plans and
six-figure annual budgets.
</P>
<P>
   The Fringe and Pure Pop are no exception: the Fringe has a
budget of $180,000; Pure Pop about a third of that. Beall, in
particular, is something of a media hound, talking up his festival
with the showy optimism of a circus barker. ``It's the beginning of
festival season,'' he said recently, smiling over a plate of sushi
near Todo Con Nada. ``You got to make the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   While Beall was with the Fringe, he aggressively promoted the
festival in radio and television interviews; with Pure Pop, he has
taken to dyeing his hair _ blue, most recently _ for effect. He is
also pushing Pure Pop in interviews and on the Internet as the
first season in a ``99-year plan'' to save Off Off Broadway from
what he complains is invasive real estate development.
</P>
<P>
   Beall's fears aside, much of downtown theater is blooming
Critical praise has begun to follow young companies like Elevator
Repair Service and playwrights like Richard Maxwell, the author of
``House.'' That play toured Europe this summer after good reviews
in New York; Elevator Repair Service's ``Total Fictional Lie'' will
tour five American cities this fall and winter.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Target Margin's acclaimed 1998 production of ``Mamba's
Daughters'' was the headliner at the Spoleto Festival in
Charleston, S.C., in May. The chamber musical ``Running Man,'' a
March production at HERE in SoHo, was a finalist for the Pulitzer
Prize, while the winner, ``Wit,'' had its New York premiere at the
99-seat MCC Theater on West 28th Street.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Commercial success stories have been more hit and miss. Downtown
shows like ``Shakespeare's R&AMP;J,'' which began at the tiny Expanded
Arts theater on Ludlow Street, had a long commercial Off Broadway
run, as did ``Gross Indecency: The Three Trials of Oscar Wilde,''
which began Off Off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, last season's commercial transfers of the
Adobe Theater Company's ``Duet!'' and Premium Bob's ``Manhunt''
were not successful in larger auditoriums.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown theater isn't even always downtown anymore. ``Three
Virgins,'' developed by the experimental company Collapsable
Giraffe, reclaimed Show World, a former sex superstore on Eighth
Avenue near 42d Street, as a theatrical space.
</P>
<P>
   Such activity has jumped the rivers, too, spreading to hot
neighborhoods like Dumbo in Brooklyn, where the experimental troupe
Gale Gates et al. has its own 40,000-square-foot performance space.
An additional large performance space and gallery, Smack Mellon,
has opened in an old spice factory.
</P>
<P>
   While the technical definition of Off Off Broadway is any
theater with less than 100 seats, the term is also emblematic of
the artistic standards of a movement that was born in the early
1960s. Those criteria _ being noncommercial, experimental and, in
the words of the director Richard Caliban, ``off the radar'' _ are
still embraced by a majority of downtown theater artists. But the
term has also had its less flattering associations.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, when I started, it seemed Off Off Broadway was
synonymous with bad,'' said Jeremy Dobrish, the artistic director
of the Adobe Theater. ``It was like, `I'm going to go, it's going
to be hot, it's going to be cramped, the people won't know what
they're doing, it will be pretentious and alienating, and I'm not
going to have a good time.'' But, he said, downtown theater in New
York is ``different now,'' more like ``the independent film
scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversations with some 20 downtown theater artists supported
the notion that changes were afoot, though some said the reasons
might be more personal than professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were all just sick of playing for our friends,''
said Jim Findlay, the co-artistic director of Collapsable Giraffe.
``I'd rather have an audience of 25 people I don't know than 40
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that has had an effect is dwindling government
support. ``This generation of artists came up not expecting to get
a grant,'' said Mark Russell, the executive director of Performance
Space 122 in the East Village. ``All these guys came of age after
the N.E.A. Four and the Karen Finley episode. You say Karen Finley,
and they have a blank look on their faces. It's like Kennedy
getting shot. They don't remember it.''
</P>
<P>
   (In 1990, Ms. Finley and three other performance artists had
their federal grants revoked by the National Endowment for the Arts
after conservative Congressmen objected to using government money
for what was deemed by some to be obscene art.)
</P>
<P>
   The new climate, Clancy said, has made Off Off Broadway more
self-sufficient: ``The 1990s are really a time when people started
thinking in a businesslike fashion _ if you're going to keep your
doors open, you're going to have to earn money. And part of that is
understanding that you're in the service industry. and that that
goes not only for the art but also the conditions.'' In short,
cramped basements and creaky folding chairs are out;
air-conditioning and comfortable seating are in.
</P>
<P>
   But does all this spit and polish mean that downtown theater has
lost its edge? One elder statesman said he had found indications of
trouble. ``I haven't seen anyone walking out angrily like they did
from my work,'' said Richard Foreman, the experimental director.
``That's a bad sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Young downtown types scoff at the thought that they have gone
soft. And, to be sure, gratuitous nudity, violence and simulated
kinky sex can still be found in a number of shows. Some say,
though, that the content of downtown theater work has become more
populist _ more easily accessible and less cynical. But part of
that, said David Latham of the Premium Bob troupe, has to do with
``shock fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who hasn't seen someone urinate onstage?'' asked Latham.
</P>
<P>
   Even without a Finley-style controversy, directors agree that
government grants for small companies have diminished during the
1990s, while private support has improved and corporate support has
dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   David Herskovits, the artistic director of Target Margin, said
the losses in corporate support have been ``particularly
disgraceful,'' considering the money being made in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But what of the boom? Has there been a trickle down?
</P>
<P>
   Off Off Broadway producers are divided. Some say that New York's
economic resurgence has caused nothing but headaches, raising rents
and production costs. Dixon Place, a performance space on the
Bowery, recently announced it would have to move because its rent
had been increased; other theater spaces and companies are still
operating hand-to-mouth.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``What Off Off Broadway means,'' said Jeff Sugg, a lighting
designer, ``is you still (italics)ask(end italics) if you're
getting paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say the boom has made downtown fashionable and safe
again, a comfortable place for monied audiences and producers to
seek out new work.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the peripheral benefits. ``There are literally
175 new condos being built next door to us and they were
(italics)expensive,''(end italics) said Michelle Stern, a
co-founder of Gale Gates. ``So we have an audience literally right
next door that walks by every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The influx of young people into the city is also being felt.
``Broadway is always talking about trying to get a young audience,
but I go to see one of these shows at HERE, or the Ontological, or
the Flea, and I feel like I'm clubbing,'' said Stephen Nunns, a
director and an editor for American Theater magazine. ``It's the
most beautiful audience I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The roster of popular downtown theater spaces has expanded in
the last few years. Newer ones like Access Theater in TriBeCa and
the Present Company's Theatorium on the Lower East Side are home to
a steady stream of work of their own as well as that of renters.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of theaters like HERE, the SoHo Rep and the
Workhouse Theater (now known as the Flea Theater). Of the older
performance spaces, P.S. 122 on First Avenue and Ninth Street, the
Ontological at St. Mark's Church and Second Avenue, the Ohio
Theater and the Performing Garage, both on Wooster Street in SoHo,
are still vibrant breeding grounds for young artists.
</P>
<P>
   And look at them come. ``More and more training schools churn
out more and more actors who arrive in New York City,'' said Beall
of the Pure Pop Festival. ``And it becomes harder and harder for
younger theater artists to carve out a spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is where, ironically, the Fringe Festival comes in. The
Fringe's role is to ``provide access and opportunity to talent
without reputation and without resources and without cash and
without experience,'' said Clancy. But some larger companies, he
added, have also begun to look at the Fringe as a place to present
work in its early stages.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clancy acknowledged, most of the
better-established companies have little motivation to perform at
his festival, where several companies share the same theater and
where turnaround time between different shows can be as little as
15 minutes. ``For a company like Elevator Repair Service,'' he
said, ``is this going to serve them? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   John Collins, the artistic director of Elevator Repair Service,
said: ``All these festivals are working at the very basic level,
and though I probably shouldn't say this, some of it can be really
awful stuff. But that's a great kind of evidence that companies are
still generating raw material, and the festivals keep trying to
give the work a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, those involved in downtown theater seem to
respect the Fringe. ``I asked someone about the Fringe and they
said, `It's cheap, and we get a venue for our play,''' Herskovits
said. ``And I said, ``Fantastic. That's all you need.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not, of course, that they don't have a few suggestions: more
international programming for one, and oh, yes, more good stuff.
Clancy said he's working on it.
</P>
<P>
   New York International Fringe Festival tickets are $11.
Information and tickets: (212) 420-8877. Also: www.FringeNYC.org.
Most Pure Pop Theater Festival tickets are $9. Information and
reservations: (877) 932-4222. Also: www.purepop.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
