<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-10 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS HEAR RUMBLING FROM FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The tide comes up twice every 24 hours in Flushing
Bay, just north of Shea Stadium. But inside the ball park, the
moods swing spasmodically.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have one of the best records in baseball, but the boos
have been coming early and often as the Mets took a three-game
losing streak into Tuesday night's game with San Diego. Kenny
Rogers was performing in front of the same genre of screamers who
once filled his ears in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perplexing,'' is the way the manager puts it.
</P>
<P>
   The fans jeered bad pitching during the three losses, starting
Saturday night when the bullpen blew a lead and the Mets could not
deliver the tying run from third base with nobody out in the ninth.
The players are aware of the quick booing, Manager Bobby Valentine
said, ``particularly if it's the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``No one likes it, to be certain.''
</P>
<P>
   In such an environment, even the totally defensible tactic of
using a position player like Matt Franco to pitch an inning in a
blowout, as Valentine did Sunday, suddenly becomes suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to do it, but it just makes sense to save your
staff,'' said the manager, perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   In much of the world _ even the hangin'-jury world of baseball
fans _ three losses would constitute a vexing but normal little
slump. In New York, it brings out the werewolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans are great,'' Valentine said Tuesday night, ``but
sometimes you get a vocal minority that gives a bad name to the
majority.''
</P>
<P>
   All this negativity comes from otherwise sweet and positive New
Yorkers who Hillary Clinton wants to join. The amazing thing is
that the Mets had been rolling since Valentine suggested he had
only 55 games to turn the team around or he would be gone. He is
still here, his team in contention for the playoffs, and his mental
gears are still whirring away, quite often productively.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the manager even took a shot from Tom Seaver, no
less, for using Franco in the ninth inning of a 14-3 horror show.
Some of the reaction after the game was as if Valentine were doing
something totally ludicrous and demeaning that had never been done
before.
</P>
<P>
   After Valentine used Franco (for the second time this season)
the other day, I thumbed through a record book and came up with a
highly unofficial and probably incomplete list of more than 100
players who have pitched a game or three, either as a late-season
lark or, more recently in this age of specialization and pitch
counts, to save a weary pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Among the recognizable players who have made cameo appearances
as pitchers were: Cap Anson, Wade Boggs, Hal Chase, Ty Cobb, Rocky
Colavito, Dave Concepcion, Jose Canseco, Rick Cerone, Chili Davis,
Jimmie Foxx, Terry Francona, Mickey Hatcher, Jim Hickman, Harry
Hooper, Tom Hutton, Dave Kingman, Vance Law, Pepper Martin, Gene
Michael, Terry Moore, Stan Musial, Jeff Newman, Paul O'Neill, Jose
Oquendo, Bill Pecota, Tris Speaker, Honus Wagner, Tim Wallach, Mark
Whiten and Glenn Wilson _ as well as the Mets' third-base coach,
Cookie Rojas, who pitched an inning for Gene Mauch in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same situation,'' Rojas was saying Tuesday night. ``We were
losing a doubleheader, and we wanted to save pitchers for the next
game. It made sense to use me for an inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas, who pitched in high school, did not give up a run in his
inning, but his evaluation Tuesday night of his repertory was,
``Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gene Mauch made the move in 1967, it was sound baseball.
When Ralph Houk used his shortstop, Gene Michael, and the aging
strong-armed slugger Rocky Colavito one day in 1968 _ Colavito was
the winning pitcher; you could look it up _ it was a stroke of
genius. When Valentine does it, he is defiling the great game of
baseball. Perplexing, as the man said.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, the Mets' pitching staff is running low, what
with injuries and weariness. Valentine does not absolve himself
from the strain on the staff.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night he brought in the 37-year-old relief pitcher
Billy Taylor, who promptly gave up a home run. Valentine took the
blame, saying he should have been aware that Taylor has been a
closer with Oakland, not used to warming up three and four times
during a game. On Sunday, Rick Reed had to leave the game with a
strained finger, and Masato Yoshii, normally a starter, promptly
gave up a three-run homer to a pitcher, Darren Dreifort. On Monday,
Orel Hershiser, who has been solid, was bombed early.
</P>
<P>
   The fans were right on everybody's case, more capricious than
the tide, but just as relentless. Perplexing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
