<P>
   (NYT102) TSORONA, Eritrea -- Aug.10, 1999 --
ERITREA-WAR-I-2-BOS, 08-10 -- A soldier rests at a camp near the
disputed border between Eritrea and Ethiopia. Behind him is an
embankment that marks a mass grave for soldiers who preceded him on
the war front. Along this one mile strectch, more people were
killed in three days in March that in 78 days of fighting through
out all of Kosovo. The battle here sadly symbolizes the state of
Africa at the end of the millennium. It is a continent full of
aspirations, new leadership and emerging democracies, but one that
tumbles into conflicts at frightening speed. (Dominic Chavez/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT101) TSORONA, Eritrea -- Aug.10, 1999 --
ERITREA-WAR-I-1-BOS, 08-10 -- Following heavy rains, the body of an
Ethiopian soldier, one of thousands buried here in a mass grave, is
exposed. Along this one mile strectch, more people were killed in
three days in March that in 78 days of fighting through all of
Kosovo. This sadly symbolizes the state of Africa at the end of the
millennium, a continent full of aspirations, new leadership and
emerging democracies. But one that tumbles into conflicts at
frightening speed. (Dominic Chavez/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
