<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMESCHOOLING-FEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTINGS INTENSIFY INTEREST IN HOME SCHOOLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Spelling of `Sherie' in 16th graf is correct) 
(yn) 
 By MINDY SINK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Brian Rohrbough remembers the promise he and other
anxious parents made on April 20 as they stood outside Columbine
High School waiting to see if their children had made it out alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were saying, `if my child is OK, he or she will never
set foot in that school again,''' Rohrbough said. Although his
15-year-old son, Daniel, was among the 13 killed in the school that
day, he wants other parents to make good on that promise. ``It's
amazing that people have already forgotten the terror,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To Rohrbough and many others who recently attended ``Education
Options,'' a seminar here sponsored by local home-school groups,
public schools no longer represent a safe haven for their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you going to trust these people who let Eric Harris make
videotapes that showed how he would shoot up the school?''
Rohrbough said, referring to one of the shooters. ``Is that the
type of environment you want your kids in?''
</P>
<P>
   Such thoughts may have been on the minds of parents across the
state in the weeks after the shooting, when inquiries to groups
that work with home-schoolers swelled.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Department of Education, which usually gets about
40 calls a month, saw a 60 percent increase, said Suzy Parker, the
department's home-schooling consultant. ``Some people specifically
mentioned Columbine as their reason for wanting to home-school. One
woman said her son was physically ill at the idea of returning to
school.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Home Educators of Colorado said calls to its small
office quadrupled after the killings, to about 75 a day, and the
Jefferson County school district, where Columbine is located, saw a
flurry as well.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects these inquiries to translate into perceptible
enrollment declines at schools this September, even at Columbine,
which like many schools has yet to complete fall enrollment.
``We're not seeing a great mass exodus from Columbine,'' said Jane
Hammond, the superintendent of schools for Jefferson County.
</P>
<P>
   But by most accounts, fear and safety have become new factors
for those considering schooling at home.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Ray, president of the National Home Education Research
Institute in Salem, Ore., said, ``Traditionally, people chose to
home-school for four reasons: to strengthen family relationships,
to pass on particular beliefs and values, strong academics and
guided social interactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's too early to have hard data on how many families
are home-schooling because of violence,'' he added, ``in the past
couple of years we are seeing more parents concerned with safety at
school, whether it's physical violence or illegal drugs or
psychological and emotional safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of school-age children being taught at home is
estimated at 700,000 to 1.5 million. In Colorado, 8,827 students
were registered to be schooled at home in the fall of 1998, with
699,135 enrolled in public schools. In Jefferson County, 874
children were being taught at home and 88,654 at public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, individuals who put their children in the public
schools seemed to take the `Lake Wobegon' average _ that fictitious
place from the radio show where all the men are strong, the women
are beautiful and the children are above average,'' Ray said. ``But
when something dramatic happens, they think, `this could be us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Experienced home-schoolers are quick to point out that keeping
children out of school is no guarantee of safety. ``I think people
get the wrong perspective that they will stay in their own home all
day long,'' said Janice Quitmeyer of the Christian Home Educators
of Colorado. ``My kids go where I go during the day _ to the post
office, the grocery store. Look at the number of violent crimes,
and a very minor number of those take place in schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while shootings like those at Columbine incite a sense
that the nation's schools are under siege, studies show that youth
violence has been declining for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Sherie Ferguson has decided to pull her 16-year-old
daughter, Brandi, out of Bear Creek High School this fall. ``If you
had told me five months ago that I would be facing this, I would
have shook my head,'' said Ms. Ferguson, a single mother in
Lakewood, also in Jefferson County. ``I had total blind faith in
the schools, but I am not going to play Russian roulette with her
life. I just can't do it. She thinks about where she'd run and how
she'd get out of her school if it happened to her. How do you study
and concentrate like that?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferguson talks with pride about the ``school'' she and
Brandi have set up in their kitchen _ a computer with a printer and
scanner, a science laboratory with a microscope and an anatomically
correct human model, complete with internal organs. Educational
requirements vary from state to state for home schooling, which has
been legal in all 50 states for the past 15 years; Colorado
requires four hours of teaching a day, 172 days a year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferguson admits: ``We're pretty nervous _ this is new to us.
I'm only going to teach the courses I'm comfortable with, like
Spanish and literature, and then she will also do correspondence
and college courses.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandi, who told her mother that she was too afraid to return to
school, said she would stay in touch with friends from school. ``I
will miss the prom and the senior yearbook, but I can still call my
friends,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Kramer is also still deciding how best to educate her
daughter, Jess, 13, so she and her husband attended the seminar
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Jess, a student at Summit Middle School, remembers sitting at a
school lunch table planning escape routes. ``At lunch we would talk
about what we would do if it happened to us _ would we go out this
door and stuff like that,'' she said. ``The idea of someone coming
in with a bomb made us really, really scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kramer said she was horrified at the idea of a group of
eighth graders facing such issues. ``You never know how kids are
going to react to one another, and kids can be cruel,'' she said.
``I don't think any child should have to walk through the doors of
an educational system and think about fear.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Jon DeStefano, the Jefferson County school
board president, met with the school district's safety task force
at its last gathering before school resumes. The district will add
extra video cameras and campus supervisors as and will require
students and staff members to wear visible identification tags.
</P>
<P>
   In thanking the committee for the summer's work, DeStefano
concluded, ``It's going to take some time, as parents and as a
community, to feel safe again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
