A2598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSING-ACTIVIST-BOS &LR;      08-10 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-ACTIVIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL HOUSING ACTIVIST SEALS $3B LOAN DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rebel of affordable housing has done it again.
</P>
<P>
   In a watershed deal that transforms his radical low-income
mortgage program into a national model, self-styled Boston housing
guerrilla Bruce Marks sealed a deal Tuesday for the nation's
largest bank to funnel $3 billion in loans through his
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Under the arrangement, Bank of America will channel the funds
through Neighborhood Assistance Corp. of America, a nonprofit group
that has put thousands of low-income and minority buyers in homes
but drawn criticism for its easy-credit policies.
</P>
<P>
   The eye-opening accord with the Charlotte, N.C.-based bank is
the single largest affordable home loan program ever, and has major
implications for the nation's low-income housing market.
</P>
<P>
   For Marks, an in-your-face activist under new attacks from
skeptics, the 10-year arrangement is nothing short of a coup. The
deal may spur other banks, notably Fleet Financial Group, to
rethink doubts about working with NACA in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found NACA able to produce incredible results,'' said
Bank of America's community development director, Cathy Bessant, in
a statement. She was referring to the bank's first exposure to NACA
through a $500 million loan program launched four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In dramatically expanding the reach of its no-downpayment loan
philosophy, NACA's newest deal underscores a striking
transformation in how banks view high-risk borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   It is a change that is intimately part of NACA's history.
</P>
<P>
   In a decade, NACA has gone from an obscure community group to
the nation's biggest housing services outfit. Created by Marks in
1988 as a housing trust fund for Boston hotel workers, NACA now has
more than 20 offices in 17 states. Known for wringing deals out of
banks after slamming their lending practices, NACA now has banks
knocking at its door.
</P>
<P>
   NACA disburses money provided by banks and other financial
companies to low-income, inner-city and minority home loan
borrowers. Under Tuesday's deal, Bank of America will channel
30,000 no-downpayment mortgages through NACA to borrowers across
the country. NACA has already funneled 5,000 affordable mortgages
through similar arrangements with other banks.
</P>
<P>
   NACA is unique in that it requires little or no downpayment, no
closing costs, and no application fee from borrowers. It accepts
poor or no credit history and counsels applicants on budgets and
the buying process. In doing so, it has challenged the strict
credit requirements and rigid appliction procedures of traditional
lenders.
</P>
<P>
   NACA also charges affordable interest rates _ with Bank of
America, 7.5 percent a year. Most high-risk borrowers have been
limited to nonbank lenders charging rates nearly twice as much _ a
feature Marks says locks poor borrowers out of the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   Far from everyone has praise for NACA and its feisty leader, a
former Federal Reserve staffer and an ex-union activist who grew up
in upper-middle class community of Scarsdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Some housing activists argue that Marks encourages borrowers to
take on more than they can handle. High-risk borrowers not used to
making monthly mortgage payments can fall behind schedule or
default outright. By spurring foreclosures that destabilize urban
neighborhoods, skeptics argue, no-downpayment loans subvert Marks'
goal of creating stable communities
</P>
<P>
   John Anderson, a real estate analyst and housing activist in
Boston's Dorchester neighborhood, received his mortgage from NACA
but questions the nonprofit's ability to do substantial good.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask _ when is the medicine worse than the cure?''
Anderson said, referring to partial data that he says indicates
high foreclosure rates in neighborhoods like Dorchester, Roxbury,
and Mattapan, where NACA has programs with Fleet and BankBoston.
The worry, Anderson said, is that once the booming economy slows
down, high-risk borrowers could be left without jobs and fail to
make mortgage payments, resulting in a wave of NACA foreclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Another Marks critic, Senator Phil Gramm, Republican of Texas,
recently labeled Marks an extortionist. Gramm, chairman of the
Senate Banking Committee, wants to scale back the Community
Reinvestment Act _ the 1977 federal law that requires banks to lend
to the poorer areas they serve.
</P>
<P>
   The CRA law gives banks credit for making affordable loans _ but
does not track the loans' foreclosure and delinquency rates.
</P>
<P>
   That, said Anderson, is one reason why some banks are now
running to Marks. ``The banks just want to generate the volume,''
Anderson said, faulting industry regulators for not scrutinizing
banks' low-income lending records.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the hard-knuckled activist, Marks, 44, deflected the
criticism. Calling Gramm ``the best thing to happen to NACA since
Terry Murray''_ the Fleet chief executive that Marks hounded
earlier this decade over allegedly usurious lending practices _
Marks vowed to expand his fight against ``predatory lenders.'' (He
no longer counts Fleet in that group.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Confrontational tactics are standard operating procedure for
NACA, and they will only get stronger,'' said Marks, who recently
launched a national television campaign against Gramm.
</P>
<P>
   NACA refuses to provide delinquency rates _ a standard barometer
of a success _ for its programs. ``They aren't relevent,'' Marks
said, adding that ``99.75 percent'' of NACA clients are ``in their
homes and making payments'' _ late or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   A bank executive said Tuesday that industry officials believe
NACA's deliquency rates top 10 percent _ above the 7 percent Fleet
sees for its non-NACA housing loans, and far above the 2 to 3
percent common for traditional loans.
</P>
<P>
   Marks is not alone in refusing to provide data on a program that
now has a national scope.
</P>
<P>
   Housing activists like Dorchester's Ada Focer complained that
Fleet and BankBoston, along with community groups like the
Association for Community Reform Now, or ACORN, and the
Massachusetts Affordable Housing Alliance, also refuse to disclose
deliquency and foreclosure rates. ``If these programs are good,
then they should prove it,'' Focer said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Bank of America was concerned about measuring
NACA's success, a company spokeswoman, Lisa Lester, said, ``We just
know that we like what we've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   NACA prides itself on offering counseling and advice to
borrowers, rather than throwing money at them and leaving them to
sink or swim. In a world of second mortgage scams and predatory
lenders, Marks said, the advice is invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   But the nonprofit has unusual conditions for applicants.
</P>
<P>
   It requires borrowers to contribute $50 a month to a
``stabilization fund.'' Those unable to make monthly mortgage
payments can tap into the pool _ a practice that keeps many
borrowers from confronting their financial problems, Focer said.
</P>
<P>
   NACA also requires borrowers to participate in five ``community
activities'' a year _ code for protests and rallies. At a recent
public hearing for Fleet's proposed acquisition of BankBoston,
hundreds of NACA troops stormed the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston,
wearing yellow T-shirts that read ``Stop the Loan Sharks!''
</P>
<P>
   Marks and supporters once showed up uninvited to a Harvard
business breakfast hosted by Fleet's Murray to protest Fleet's
allegedly questionable lending practices. Badgered by Marks and
dogged by lawsuits and regulatory scrutiny of its mortgage lending
unit, Fleet signed a watershed deal with NACA in 1994 to disburse
$140 million in affordable housing loans through the group. That
benchmark deal, now expired, launched NACA's mortgage program and
led several other beleaguered banks, including First Union, to seal
similar arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's deal was different. In a reflection of how eager banks
have become to tap the nonprofit's ability to locate low-income and
minority customers, NACA did not have to hound Bank of America into
a deal. ``Bank of America gets it, and they came to us,'' Marks
said. The bank, with 30 million customers, has a $350 billion
community lending plan, the biggest of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   In a unique arrangement, Fleet paid NACA about $3.85 million for
administrative costs. NACA's newest deal will be even heftier _
Bank of America will pay the nonprofit up to $2,000 for every loan
it processes, or up to $60 million for the entire project. Marks
paid himself $72,308 in 1997, the last year for which data was
available.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet said earlier this year that New England's largest bank
would not renew its no-downpayment program with Marks after it
absorbs BankBoston. But Fleet spokesman James Mahoney said Tuesday
that after NACA finishes disbursing $100 million left over from
previous agreements with the banks, Fleet would consider working
with NACA again. ``We'll wait and see,'' Mahoney said.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after he launched his affordable lending program by
holding Fleet's feet to the fire, Marks sees sweet justice in that
prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did our first deal with Fleet, Fleet's attitude was,
`We'll give you just enough rope to hang yourself,' '' Marks said.
``But we just grew. We got bigger, stronger, and meaner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
