</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: FREQUENT-FLIER MILES; ELECTRONIC CONVENIENCE;
BARGAIN FARES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: Also moving in `t' category) 
(yn) 
 By EDWIN MCDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A week after American Airlines all but eliminated the expiration
date for its frequent-flier miles, United Airlines did much the
same Tuesday. But in a departure from American, United will also
reinstate expired miles from 1998 for members who register and who,
by the end of this year, take either two paid domestic round trips
or one paid international round trip on flights operated by United,
United Shuttle or United Express.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are great moves for frequent fliers,'' said Randy
Petersen, the editor of Inside Flyer magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen said that United and American probably wanted to bring
their frequent-flier programs more in line with those of their
airline code-sharing or alliance partners, whose miles generally do
not expire (Continental Airlines, Northwest Airlines and US
Airways) or expire only after several years of member inactivity
(Delta Air Lines and Trans World Airlines).
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Northwest got a jump on American and United early this
year when, soon after joining an alliance with Continental, it
replaced frequent-flier miles that expire with nonexpiring miles.
</P>
<P>
   Under their new programs, United and American require that
members earn or redeem miles at least every 36 months. But they can
do that by paying for purchases with the airline's affinity credit
card, by making long-distance calls with its telecommunications
partners, by staying at a partner hotel, by renting a car from a
rental partner and so on.
</P>
<P>
   To reinstate 1998 miles on United, however, members must
register and make the specified flights by Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Also under the United program, all miles in a member's account
for 1999 will be valid until Dec. 31, 2002, after which they will
expire unless the member earns or redeems miles between Jan. 1,
2000, and Dec. 31, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Convenience
</P>
<P>
   Airlines may have done little in recent years to enhance
passenger comfort, but they have made substantial improvements in
some other aspects of the air travel experience. For example, code
sharing and alliances, whatever their actual or potential
drawbacks, have made it more convenient for passengers to buy one
ticket for travel on two or more airlines, to check baggage through
to their final, distant destination and to earn free tickets faster
on the partner airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Now another air travel improvement will soon be in the works.
IBM and the International Air Transport Association are scheduled
to announce Wednesday that they plan to develop a service linking
the electronic ticketing systems of their 266-member airlines and
other interested carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The service is expected to begin in the middle of next year and
allow passengers to buy an electronic ticket on one carrier that
will also be valid for other carriers' connecting flights.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain Fares
</P>
<P>
   Friday the 13th is a lucky day for bargain hunters. Most
airlines have extended until this Friday their sale fares valid for
travel this fall and winter. These are the fares that include an
additional 10 percent discount if purchased through an airline's
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Friday is also the last day to purchase discount flights on
Japan Airlines for travel beginning by Sept. 20 and ending no later
than Dec. 16. For example, round-trip fares start at $648 for
travel between Los Angeles or San Francisco and Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia; $945 between Chicago and Beijing; $748 between New York
and Taipei, Taiwan, and $798 between Las Vegas, Nev., and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Air New Zealand is offering more than 25 percent off round-trip
fares this fall from New York, Chicago and Los Angeles to New
Zealand for tickets purchased by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Those who buy tickets by Aug. 31 can fly round trip on Korean
Air Lines to Hong Kong or Beijing from the West Coast from $600, or
from New York, Chicago, Dallas and other cities from $700. Flights
to Bangkok and Singapore start at $620. Travel must be completed by
Sept. 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
