<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNAFUS AT TEXAS AGENCY THREATEN SERVICES FOR MENTALLY ILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A surprising $30 million shortfall in the coming
year's state mental-health budget threatens to slash services by
Sept. 1 for at least 2,000 mentally ill people statewide, officials
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   State auditors are probing the financial woes plaguing the Texas
Department of Mental Health and Mental Retardation and might have
answers by Friday to avoid or minimize a cutback in services.
</P>
<P>
   Key legislators and agency officials began scrambling for
solutions this week after widespread protests followed the
mental-health board's Friday vote to cut programs for the mentally
ill to make up for mistakes in budgetary planning.
</P>
<P>
   The board wants to cut $5 million from $27 million in new state
spending for a ``new generation'' of more effective anti-psychotic
drugs. Even more troubling to some legislators, the board also
slashed $7.2 million from current levels of community services for
the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does have some fairly significant implications at the
community level in terms of services that may not be available,''
said Dr. Steven Schnee, executive director of the Harris County
Mental Health Mental Retardation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that 1,700 psychotic individuals statewide
suffering from schizophrenia, bipolar disorder and major depression
would not get the new drugs as legislators had intended.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks at Houston mental-health centers could weaken case
management, outpatient counseling, housing, employment services and
other supports that help stabilize the mentally ill, said Spencer
McClure, executive director of the Texas Council of Community MHMR
Centers Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 19,000 mentally ill people receive services from the
Harris County community center along with about 3,500 mentally
retarded individuals, according to the state MHMR agency. Harris
County includes most of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how many will be affected statewide and locally by cuts
to the community centers is unclear, but estimates easily exceed
2,000, considering the impact on the drug treatments alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's adult mental-health services that are particularly being
reduced,'' McClure said. ``Without these services and support they
(the mentally ill) would end up either in the streets, the jails or
back in the state institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Also among the scheduled cuts are $2.3 million in services for
those receiving the new drug therapies; a $2.4 million reduction in
state hospital beds, reducing the number by 60; and more than $4
million in administrative spending and information technology
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The problems would presumably be repeated in the fiscal year
2001 as well, meaning that the total shortfall for the two-year
funding cycle could reach $60 million, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Key legislators, frustrated that the agency did not reveal the
funding problem last spring when lawmakers could have fixed it,
asked the agency not to make any cuts while a solution is explored.
MHMR Commissioner Karen Hale said plans for the cuts are in effect
but ``on pause'' for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that it would change. I hope that the funding would go
back into the community centers and in the new generations drugs
and services,'' said Lynn Lasky, public policy director for the
National Alliance for the Mentally Ill of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Lasky added that it is particularly ironic for the agency to cut
funding from the new drug program, which includes support services
for the patients receiving them, since it originally asked for more
than twice that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got about half of what they asked for, and now they're
saying we can do this for less,'' she said. ``When you come back to
the next session how do you knock on the door again and say we need
more money?''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Rob Junell of San Angelo, chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee, said the audit will be key in
understanding the funding problem _ when it developed, why it
wasn't reported and what to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's money they are in the hole, money they
have to pay back for this fiscal year, bills they've got now,''
Junell said. ``If they really went and spent money they're not
going to have, we don't know it, and I'm not sure they know.''
</P>
<P>
   Junell said he doubts Commissioner Hale knew the full extent of
the problem, which she now attributes to a smaller surplus in
federal funds to carry over from previous years and fewer federally
insured Medicaid and Medicare patients at state hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's because they didn't have a clue. That's better
than they intentionally withheld the information. You don't get $60
million behind in just a few months,'' Junell said.
</P>
<P>
   Hale said Tuesday that the agency became aware of the full
extent of the shortfall by the session's end but simply failed to
communicate the problem effectively to legislators. She and the
agency's chief financial officer, Bill Campbell, who came on board
in April, contend that legislators were aware the agency was
expecting $15 million less in surplus money from federal accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Junell said, the current estimated shortfall for the next
two years is four times that. He said committee members thought
that problem had been solved by allowing for an emergency
appropriation if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did everything we could first to try to close the gap
without affecting services,'' Campbell said. ``Then we got down to
the really hard decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said cuts to the community centers represent a 3.2 percent
reduction in services statewide, but plans to allow the centers
flexibility in the use of their money might help.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Garnet Coleman, D-Houston, a legislative champion of the
mentally ill, said the budget snafu is particularly troubling
because the state of Texas has never come close to meeting the
critical needs of the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I'm real concerned is we don't make a lot of
progress in this area,'' he said. ``When the Legislature has no
confidence in the agency, that hurts programs that the agency is
carrying out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
