<SLUG> BC-PAXSON-PARTNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paxson looking to take on partner, CEO says
 &HT;    By Stephanie Smith
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Paxson Communications is interested in
finding a partner, not selling off stations, company Chief
Executive Jeff Sagansky said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson Communications' plans have been the subject of
speculation since a federal ruling last week that allows
broadcasters to own two stations in the same large market. The
Federal Communications Commission decision also allows the company
to sell as much as 32.5 percent of its stock to a TV network.
</P>
<P>
   The company has hired Salomon Smith Barney to explore its
options.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear that (Chairman Lowell ``Bud'' Paxson) is
looking to do a number of deals,'' said Christopher Dixon, an
analyst with PaineWebber in New York. ``He can basically sell off a
number of stations and use the cash to buy programming or enter a
joint venture with CBS or another one of the networks that could
provide content.''
</P>
<P>
   Sagansky ruled out selling any of its large-market stations,
though some small-market stations might be sold.
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that West Palm Beach-based Paxson Communications
has been looking for a financial alliance. The company has
established itself, but could use a financial boost, Sagansky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would help us to get a bigger company behind us,'' Sagansky
said. ``If we find a strategic partner, they would inject money and
probably other kinds of expertise. It would help us continue the
way we are going, but get there faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Allan Roness, an analyst with JWGenesis Capital Markets in Boca
Raton, said he doubts an alliance with a network will mean Paxson
will veer from its format.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Bud Paxson has his foot in it, it has to have a
certain type of programming,'' said Roness. ``Second, if it's a
national network, what would be the point of having the same
programming on two channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Content has been a problem for Pax TV. It has been struggling to
find an audience for its family-friendly fare, often attracting
less than 1 million of the 100 million households with television
sets.
</P>
<P>
   The network has scheduled more original programs this fall, but
past offerings consisted mostly of network reruns. Some of its
highest rated shows have been repeats of ``Bonanza.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts struggled to put a price on what a buyer would have to
pay for 32.5 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Cheen, an analyst at First Union Capital Markets in
Charlotte, N.C., said the Paxson network was worth $2.5 billion
before the federal rule change. Sagansky said he estimates the
ruling has made the company worth as much as 25 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Paxson Communications (Amex: PAX) finished at $15.75
Tuesday, up 63 cents on the day. The company now has a market
capitalization of more than $963 million.Stephanie Smith writes for
the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
