<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BLONDE ON BLONDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I spent the day with two blond icons, women whose faces and
first names are instantly recognizable around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Both paired off in rocky romances with sex-addled young
presidents. And both were painted variously as vulnerable and
stubborn, accomplished and self-defeating, smart and dumb. Misfits,
both, neither quite believable as a Yankees fan or a wannabe Jewish
girl.
</P>
<P>
   One is Camelot, the other Castle Grande. One is Cecil Beaton;
the other Kaki Hockersmith. One is champagne, the other tea and
cookies. One is marabou, the other Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   One is most famous for standing on a New York subway grate in a
billowing white pleated dress; the other is still trying to get her
New York subway lines straight. One lost a famous husband because
she refused to duck into his shadow; the other keeps her famous
husband even as she tries to bolt from his shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary in Queens. Marilyn at Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity-drenched culture that dawned in the glamorous aura
of Marilyn Monroe, JFK and Jackie has now reached nauseating new
depths. We're always wallowing in celebrity lifestyle and
deathstyle.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of her therapy session with Talk magazine, Hillary
Rodham Clinton was trying to shift back to listening. At a union
hall in Queens Tuesday morning, she expressed her ``concern'' about
the problem of too much money in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I'm out there raising money, I'm a zealot about
campaign finance reform,'' she told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be the same Hillary who helped turn the White House
into a pajama party for fat-cat donors? Is this the same political
right hand who urged the return of Dick Morris, the man who fueled
the obscene money race in '96 with phony issue ads?
</P>
<P>
   It's jarring to hear the would-be senator offer beliefs that
ignore the reality of the last eight years of aiding and abetting
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's bid is still rooted in her status as celebrity
and victim. That's a cocktail that Marilyn would have understood
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   The display of Marilyn's personal property that will be
auctioned by Christie's in October is much like Hillary's Talk
interview _ invasive and inviting at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hillary, Marilyn's troubles are what keep her so
compelling. As the actress said in ``Some Like It Hot,'' she always
got stuck with the fuzzy end of the lollipop.
</P>
<P>
   The Christie's galleries were chock-a-block with Ferragamo
stilettos, Maximillian furs, Pucci silks, Norell beaded gowns, lace
bustiers, see-through nighties and marabou capelets and mules.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Marilyn stuff, bequeathed by the star to her acting
teacher, Lee Strasberg, and sold by his widow, Anna, is glamorous.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the gilt lighters from Frank Sinatra's Cal-Neva Lodge,
the gold sandals she wore to entertain the troops in Korea, and the
dog license of the small white pooch the singer gave her. Here are
her scripts with penciled notes to herself, like the scene in
``Some Like It Hot'' when she tells herself to act ``delighted''
when she gets on the yacht with Tony Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   Her ambitious library gets its own room _ Thomas Mann, D.H.
Lawrence, Tennessee Williams, Colette, a first edition of Kerouac's
``On the Road,'' a book on mixing cocktails signed by Dean Martin,
who wrote the introduction, the works of Freud. Stuck inside her
copy of ``The Joy of Cooking'' is a typed diet starting at 8 a.m.
with stewed prunes and ending at 11 p.m. with eggnog.
</P>
<P>
   The ``nudest dress,'' as the designer Jean Louis called it _
that skin-tight, flesh-tone, rhinestone-dotted gown that Marilyn
wore to sing ``Happy Birthday'' to JFK _ is reverently displayed in
a room by itself, lit from above as though it were the Pieta or the
David.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wore no undergarments,'' said an awestruck matron with a
heavy Queens accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cost $12,000!'' her friend chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   But a B-flat mood prevailed. Marilyn's Mexican sombreros, her
certificate of conversion to Judaism when she married Arthur
Miller, her platinum-and-diamond ``eternity band'' from Joe
DiMaggio, her heart-shaped cookie cutters, her poem entitled ``A
Sorry Song'' were sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be alive, they say I'm lucky to be alive,'' she
wrote in pencil, ``it's hard to figure out when everything I feel _
hurts!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
