<HEADLINE>
FATHER OF SAINTS RB WILLIAMS PLEADS GUILTY TO FELONY THEFT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The father of Heisman Trophy winner and New Orleans
Saints running back Ricky Williams pleaded guilty to felony theft
Tuesday and was placed on 10 years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Mark Kent Ellis sent Errick Lynne Williams
Sr., 41, to jail for 90 days as part of his probation and ordered
him to do 350 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   He also must repay Lexington Place Healthcare Center $20,752,
the amount he stole between Oct. 20, 1997, and Oct. 20, 1998, said
prosecutor Terry Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was remorseful, and he was very embarrassed for his son,''
Jennings said after sentencing. ``Obviously, his father's problems
cannot be held against Ricky Williams in any way. If anything, it
shows what he had to overcome to get where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Toby D. Boyer did not return calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings said Errick Williams, who was working as housekeeping
supervisor at the nursing home, created phony documents and
timeslips that showed his wife worked with him. She did not, but
Jennings said Williams collected her checks and cashed them.
</P>
<P>
   There was no evidence that Williams' wife, Patricia Maria
Williams, was involved, and she was not charged.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Williams, Ricky's mother, raised him alone after
divorcing his dad in 1983, raising allegations of child abuse,
according to the May 18 issue of Sports Illustrated. The story also
says Errick Williams denied abusing his children and that he and
his son have become friends in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings said Errick Williams was placed on probation in a
federal court in 1978 in California on a misdemeanor theft charge.
He successfully completed that probation.
</P>
<P>
   If he follows the rules in this case, Ellis will continue to
withhold a finding of guilt and no conviction will be on Errick
Williams' record.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
