u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHERRY-PICKERS-1STLD-     08-10 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERRY-PICKERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRACKDOWN ON HOUSING FOR MIGRANT WORKERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Rewritten 4th graf adds sentence describing crackdown, new
9th graf describes housing standards)   By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WENATCHEE, Wash. _ At the height of cherry-picking season, 12
men were making a patch of woods on Stemilt Hill into a home.
Plastic grocery bags hung from nails in the Ponderosa pine bark:
the pantry. A shard of mirror was wedged into a trunk of another
pine: the bathroom. The kitchen was a Sunbeam propane grill, the
bushes served as toilets, and six cheap tents formed the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meat we have to buy every day, because it spoils,'' said
Nereo Sanchez, who like the others came from Pachuca, Mexico. Last
year, they stayed in an orchard, but this year the owner will no
longer allow it. They said they had looked for campgrounds, but
found no room. They stayed here on public land, until forest
rangers moved them along.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel bad,'' said his coworker Juan Sanchez. ``When we go
pick, we don't know if our tents will still be here'' at the end of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Of the state's 16,000 cherry pickers, said an adviser to Gov.
Gary Locke, 10,000 have not had adequate housing in the brief but
profitable couple of weeks that the fruit ripens. And in a recent
crackdown, the federal Occupational Safety and Health
Administration displaced 2,000 more, said the adviser, Rich
Nafziger, after it threatened to close camps run by fruit growers
that did not meet federal health and safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with fines, many growers stopped letting workers camp in
the orchards.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the state health department created a temporary
licensing program for camps in the orchards with standards which
were supposed to meet federal requirements by next season. Workers
were allowed to stay in tents they bought on their own, which often
leaked and did not provide protection from insects and heat.
Growers had to provide water and toilets but not refrigerators.
Workers used ice-filled coolers to store their food.
</P>
<P>
   ``In hot weather the food ends up floating in water in the ice
chest,'' said Richard Terrill, northwest regional administrator for
the safety and health administration.``You have a lot of people in
close quarters, with the danger of communicable diseases. Some of
the camps didn't have an adequate number of toilets and showers.''
</P>
<P>
   The licensing provisions were intended to give growers an
incentive to supply better, more plentiful shelter for workers, but
they served only to justify the status quo instead of encouraging
growers to meet federal standards, Terrill said.
</P>
<P>
   Those standards include making living quarters at least 7 feet
high, with adequate ventilation and permanent floors to keep out
vermin and moisture. The camps also have to have water and
refrigeration.
</P>
<P>
   With growers showing little progress in meeting the tougher
federal standards, the government stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year when we made our objections known, there were
probably a few farmers who decided they wouldn't even provide what
they had provided before, and that probably meant _ I'll be honest
with you _ that several hundred more workers didn't have a place to
camp, he said. ``And I feel bad about that. I know that pinched
people, but hopefully the outcome will be good, so next year and in
the years after, there will be more housing and better housing.''
</P>
<P>
   Growers are not legally required to provide housing, said Dan
Kelly, assistant manager of the Washington Growers Clearing House
Association, a group of 2,800 tree fruit grower members. Most
growers say they cannot afford to build permanent housing for
pickers during a two-week harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Fox, owner of C&AMP;S Orchard in Wenatchee, had a camp on his
property three years ago, but decided to close it. He employs
between 150 and 600 workers, depending on the size of his harvest
on the arid, irrigated hills above the Columbia River.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was economically feasible, I'd love to have the camp,''
Fox said. But he said meeting licensing standards would cost
$400,000 to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unjustifiable expense,'' he said. ``Talk to any
banker, and a banker will laugh you out of the bank.'' He said
workers are better off in a grower's camp than on the roadside.
``It's safer, better, healthier, for everyone concerned,'' Fox
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Guadalupe Gamboa, the state director for the United
Farmworkers of America, is optimistic that the crackdown will
result in improved conditions.
</P>
<P>
   He said establishing state standards for licensing that were
lower than federal requirements was ``a huge subsidy to the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   If growers want to rely on a migrant work force, he said,
``They've got to find a place for migrants to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Farm worker advocates point out that growers are willing to make
other large investments in a quick crop, like orchard warming
machines that cost $26,000 just to transport, while showers for the
workers are more likely to be considered a luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole issue about short seasons kind of bothers me,'' said
Terrill. ``If you're a grower and you grow a short-season crop, you
still invest in chemicals, tractors, and other equipment. I think
that argument is specious.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherry picking requires special timing and skills; the fruit
must be picked just as soon as it is ripe, and workers must be
careful not to separate the stems from the fruit or damage the
branches where next year's buds will form.
</P>
<P>
   Working from 4 a.m. til noon, when heat can damage the fruit,
pickers can make $4 for filling a 40-pound box, or up to $80 a day.
Many travel for weeks at a time following the ripening from
California to Oregon, then from Washington to Montana. Workers say
living conditions in other states are better, with trailers
available in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   A few solutions are being tried in Washington. About 300 people
found shelter this season through the state's Rent-a-Tent program,
which leased 26 six-person tents for $200 per tent a month to 8
growers during the harvest, with the hope that if enough growers
participate statewide, the tents can move with the workers along
the trail of ripening cherries. In Mattawa, a town on the Columbia,
the state has developed the Esperanza migrant center, a village of
temporary shelters created out of shipping containers. Each
8-by-40-foot structure sleeps six and has windows, air conditioning
and a bathroom with shower.
</P>
<P>
   But such accommodations reach only a small percentage of the
work force. Many of the rest made do in the woods outside of town.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Padilla, 36, of Yakima, Wash., was camping with seven
other people, including three of her six children. Their dinner was
frying on a propane stove. They drink untreated water from a nearby
creek and have no access to indoor plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like a house or a cabin so we could wash dishes and
shower,'' she said. She and her husband, Lupe Padilla, 39, figured
they each were making $40 a day, not enough to support their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not very good,'' Padilla said, surveying the four tents
pitched near the road. ``But what can we do?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
