<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-PSYCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DO YOU SAY TO THE KIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHIL DAVIS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ First the gunshots. Now the questions.
</P>
<P>
   What do you say to a wide-eyed child who wants to know why a
grown-up would gun down children at a day camp, a place that's
supposed to be safe and fun?
</P>
<P>
   It's a question parents across America are facing today. And
it's an even more difficult question for suburban San Fernando
Valley parents because this time the bullets hit close to home.
Tuesday's shooting rampage at a day camp at the North Valley Jewish
Community Center in the Granada Hills area of Los Angeles left
three children, a teen-ager and an adult wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Even the experts shudder at the thought of explaining this to
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm almost at a loss,'' said Dr. Leslie Waxman, a child
psychiatrist who works with Kaiser Permanente Medical Centers in
the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no magic word to reassure your child about something
like this. All you can do is explain to kids that there are some
things we don't have explanations for, but we're going to do our
very best to make sure that they're safe and that they're taken
care of.''
</P>
<P>
   As police hunted the gunman, crisis counselors and clergy
converged on area hospitals and the church near the community
center to treat the psychological wounds of the injured, their
families and about 20 other children at the day camp.
</P>
<P>
   But parents and children across the nation continued to be
assaulted with non-stop television images that included a wounded
boy being wheeled to a waiting emergency helicopter and frightened
children being led to safety by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Feinberg, a child psychiatrist at the University of
California, Los Angeles, said children will react differently to
the shooting, but all benefit from talking about it. It's best to
be honest and direct.
</P>
<P>
   Parents must assess just how much their child can understand.
For example, children can't grasp the concept of death _ that it's
universal, inevitable and irreversible _ until they're 9 or 10
years old.
</P>
<P>
   For the younger children, simplify the situation: ``Some people
get really upset and they don't know what to do when they're upset
so they hurt people and that's terrible,'' Feinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Older children can handle more information, and it's a good
chance to use the incident as an opportunity to talk about violence
and death.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, it's also crucial to point out there's nothing
normal about the violence. Children need to feel safe. ``When you
look at the statistics, violence hasn't increased but the media
coverage of it sure has,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And parents should feel comfortable expressing their own
emotions about what happened. ``You can't expect parents to be
superhuman,'' said Waxman. ``I think it's important to be calm, to
try not to be hysterical, but letting your kids know that you're
sad or that something bad has happened is natural and normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts offer these tips to help children cope with violence:
</P>
<P>
   _ Talk about it. Encourage children to say how they feel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sometimes drawing pictures can help a child express feelings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be honest. It's OK to be sad. It's OK not to understand
everything that happens in the world. And it's OK to tell that to
your child.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turn off the television. Experts disagree on this point, but
all agree that it's best to tailor the information kids get to
their level of understanding.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be alert to any changes in your child's everyday behavior.
Some children may need to do more than simply talk about what
happened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
