<HEADER>
A2611 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ANDRUW-COX     08-10 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDRUW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Andruw Jones: King of the wall
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the typewritten play-by-play that the Braves hand
out in the press box after every game, it wasn't even highlighted
as The Catch. ``Astros 3rd,'' the fifth paragraph reads, ``Biggio
singled to center. Spiers flied out to AJones.''
</P>
<P>
   But a day after Andruw Jones updated his personal highlight film
with an over-the-shoulder, leaping, cleats-in-the-outfield-padding
catch of Bill Spiers' drive to center field, Atlanta was still
abuzz.
</P>
<P>
   It was still the talk of Turner Field, where fans bowed to Jones
Monday night as if royalty were returning to the home dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best catch I've ever seen,'' Spiers said. He wouldn't go
as far as to say he was robbed of an extra-base hit. ``No, I
expected him to make it. He makes a lot of good plays. He has a
chance to be as good a center fielder ever in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many times we've seen Andruw top his previous
catch,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said, ``but this time I think
he's done it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Otis Nixon, whose historic leap against the Pirates
in 1992 had been the most famous catch in recent Braves history
until Jones showed up, had a flashback watching Jones Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded me of that, but he's been doing it all season,''
Nixon said. ``That's probably one of the best he's made since I've
been here. The others? Where do you want me to start, the one over
in the gap, the one over there, which one? He's been making quite a
few this season. He's the best center fielder in the game right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he would rank the catch up there among his three
best. The others: 1998, against Steve Finley of San Diego, and one
this year, he doesn't recall against whom, when he hit his head on
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finley hit the ball off (Tom) Glavine and I made the catch on
a similar play,'' Jones said. ``Those are two that I hang on the
wall. You're off balance, you're in the air and you're catching a
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He was proud of his effort Monday night, mainly because the
Astros did not score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a great catch, especially to save a run,''
Jones said. ``If the ball hit the wall and I didn't try to jump on
the wall, I think Craig Biggio could have scored. Most of the
catches that I think are good are when I save a run, that's what I
think is a great catch. When there's nobody on base and you make a
good catch, it's just a good catch. For me, it's great when you
keep a run from scoring or throw somebody out at home plate. Those
are the good plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's game against Houston, Jones went out to the
center field wall to inspect his cleat marks in the padding. He
knows the sacrifice he makes when he goes after a ball at the wall.
He knows what it's going to feel like the morning after.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to hurt the back of your ankles and most of the
time you hurt your knee, too,'' Jones said. ``I feel those pains,
but sometimes I just tell myself don't put it in your mind. Just
leave it there. If you don't jump right you can get stuck (in the
padding) and hurt yourself. You never know what's going to happen
when you do stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the men who play with Jones and against him have a pretty
good idea. They recognize his speed, that he plays shallow because
he can chase down balls. The most common word heard at Turner
Tuesday about Andruw Jones was ``incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, he's in a defensive class by himself,'' said Carl
Everett, the Astros center fielder. ``I don't see any outfielder
that can actually do what he does. Of all the centerfielders in
baseball, no one would have caught it except him. He has great
wheels and great instincts. But he throws people out because he
takes those chances of playing in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect him to make those plays now,'' said left fielder
Ryan Klesko. ``He makes diving catches and plays that most
centerfielders would never get to. He's awesome, he gets a good
read on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was weak,'' right fielder Brian Jordan said, teasingly.
``Honestly, this guy is amazing. He puts it out there on the line,
he doesn't worry about injury. He makes one great play after
another. He's still learning the game. He's just playing on raw
talent right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Keven McGlintchy saw Jones' play from the bullpen
Monday night and watched in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how in the world he caught that ball,''
McGlintchy said. ``His concentration is amazing. He's just
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Jones is a pitcher's best insurance policy. ``It's good
to know that if we make a bad pitch and they hit it in the gaps,
there's always a chance Andruw will make a nice play,'' McGlintchy
said. ``To him it looks very easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
