<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-RACISM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR ousts crew pair for racial incident
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NASCAR's image was tarnished Tuesday from a month-old
incident that resulted in the governing body suspending two white
race-team members for their part in a racial harassment incident in
New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Two crew members knocked on the door of the motorcoach and one
put a pillowcase over his head in an apparent effort to mimic the
Ku Klux Klan in a prank on David Scott, a black crew member with
Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   One of the two, Mike Culberson, was fired by Winston Cup driver
Derrike Cope. The other, Ray Labbe, was fired by Cup driver Terry
Labonte. Both were terminated within days of the July 8 incident
during practice sessions at the Jiffy Lube 300 in Loudon, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Both were motorcoach drivers, who transport the race cars to
tracks. Labbe also was a crew member for Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's added its ``indefinite suspension'' on Tuesday after
investigating the matter for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their actions were deplorable and will not be tolerated,''
said Kevin Triplett, NASCAR's director of operations. ``We have
zero tolerance for any harassment, whether it's gender, race or
religion.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's actions haven't stopped the concerns of minorities, who
have contended that the organization is racist. The critics point
to limited representation and opportunities in the sport for
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has kept miniorities out of motor sports is actual racism
and perceived racism,'' said Charles Farrell, spokesman for the
Rainbow/PUSH Coalition. ``This incident supports the perceived
racism. Yet, we're very glad NASCAR took the steps to suspend the
two men. There's no room for this type of thing if NASCAR is
serious about bringing blacks into the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Cope and Labonte, two of the sport's top drivers, seemed
embarrassed by the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behavior like this simply cannot be tolerated in today's
society,'' Cope said. ``This is an example of a grievous behavior
that I do not condone. It was an ignorant act, and I took the only
course available to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte, brother of Terry, said during a Tuesday stop in
Atlanta that he was concerned about his brother and the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered Terry; he was very, very upset and torn up about
it,'' Bobby Labonte said. ``It embarrassed him and put him in a bad
situation. It put me in a bad situation, too, because I'm his
brother and people are asking me about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Driver, who drives in the Modified Series and is the first
African-American to finish in the top five of a NASCAR touring
series, said he thinks it was a isolated incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR is already in a situation where they have been getting
beat up for a while here now on the issue of trying to get
minorities to come into the sport,'' Driver said. ``It can put a
dampening on things. You have to oversee two clowns like this and
just look at the positive and end it here, because NASCAR took care
of it immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope the sport isn't held accountable for the actions
of two individuals,'' NASCAR's Triplett said. ``When you have a
town of 60,000 people, you have a couple of individuals who make
gross errors. Is the town held accountable? It's similar to this
situation, with this organization involving 60,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
