<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UPS LOSES TAX RULING THAT COULD COST IT MILLIONS
</P>
<P>
   A judge has ruled that United Parcel Service took inflated
deductions in 1984 and must pay taxes, penalties and interest that
the company said might total nearly $300 million. Its ultimate tax
liability could be much larger because the ruling covers only the
first year of a practice that has continued ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a rare victory for the IRS in its efforts to
prevent companies from taking tax deductions when they move money
to subsidiaries overseas for the sole purpose of avoiding taxes.
</P>
<P>
   3 BIG ALUMINUM COMPANIES IN MERGER TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Alcan Aluminium of Canada, Pechiney of France and the Alsuisse
Lonza Group of Switzerland confirmed Tuesday that they are in
merger talks that could create the biggest company in the aluminum
industry, a business plagued for nearly a decade by oversupply and
depressed prices. The potential combination may be a signal of
other big cross-border deals and could lead to stable or higher
prices for aluminum, a basic industrial metal.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. AND MICROSOFT GIVE THEIR VERSIONS OF FACTS TO COURT
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses have departed, but the paper wars began Tuesday in
the Microsoft antitrust trial as both the company and the federal
government presented the court with book-sized documents detailing
what each camp believes are the facts of the case. Tuesday's
filings more sharply delineate their arguments in painstaking
detail, allegation by allegation, witness by witness, e-mail by
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT TO BUY CONSULTING COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies agreed to buy International Network
Services, a fast-growing consulting company, for $3.7 billion in
stock. For Lucent, North America's biggest maker of communications
equipment, the deal is a bid to move beyond merely making
complicated communications gear and expand its ability to help big
corporate clients install and use it. ``The convergence of voice
and data is driving tremendous demand for services and support,''
said Lucent chairman Richard McGinn.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK PRICES STAGE A BROAD RETREAT
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices continued to slide on sustained worries about
rising interest rates. But a late recovery that brought major
market gauges up prevented what was a bad day from being even
worse. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 52.55 points, to
10,655.15. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index declined 16.37
points, to 1,281.43, and the Nasdaq composite index dropped 28.87
points, to 2,490.11.
</P>
<P>
   SOROS CHOOSES A CHIEF EXECUTIVE
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to turn around dismal performance at his $13 billion
hedge fund family, George Soros has picked Duncan Hennes, the
former treasurer of Bankers Trust, to serve as chief executive with
a mandate to end the personnel turmoil and other problems that have
led to huge investor redemptions over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   WAL-MART PROFIT BEATS FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Continuing on its juggernaut sales pace, Wal-Mart Stores said
that its second-quarter sales jumped 15 percent as its profit rose
21 percent, beating analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   GM SEES NO GAIN IN MARKET SHARE
</P>
<P>
   Executives of General Motors conceded that the company would be
unable to increase its share of the booming auto market soon. They
also announced the bundling of the company's Internet-related
assets into a single unit that has been named e-GM.
</P>
<P>
   SILICON GRAPHICS PLANS TO CUT JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Graphics, which has been mired in losses and dwindling
market share for much of the last four years, plans to lay off
1,000 to 1,500 people, or up to 15 percent of its work force, and
sell or spin off several businesses, including the Cray Research
line of supercomputers. The company also said that it would take a
$100 million to $200 million charge in connection with the
revamping. Shares of Silicon Graphics fell $3.75, to $12.4375.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED AIRLINES EXTENDS FLIER MILES
</P>
<P>
   A week after American Airlines all but eliminated the expiration
date for its frequent-flier miles, United Airlines followed suit.
But in a departure from American, United will also reinstate
expired miles from 1998 in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   SEC TO TOUGHEN ACCOUNTING RULES
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission plans to issue rules that
will make it more difficult for companies to finesse their earnings
results by underplaying or leaving out adjustments in their
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   BP AMOCO OPERATING PROFIT RISES
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco, Europe's second-biggest oil company, said that its
second-quarter operating profit rose 13.6 percent after crude oil
prices surged and savings from the $62 billion purchase of Amoco
began to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   CISCO EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, the maker of telecommunications equipment,
reported a nearly 50 percent gain in fourth-quarter sales and
earnings, beating Wall Street estimates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
