<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAVY-TAILHOOK-1STLD-W     08-10 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVY-TAILHOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY MOVES TO RESUME TIES WITH TAILHOOK ASSOCIATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add 10 grafs at end)  
 (ATTN: Nev., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Navy took its first step Tuesday to restore
official ties with the Tailhook Association, eight years after
sexual assaults and drunken revelry at the group's annual
convention roiled the Navy and led to changes in the military's
treatment of women.
</P>
<P>
   While stopping short of fully embracing the association, the
Navy said it would resume its formal support once it received
assurances that the group's leaders would never again tolerate the
sort of behavior that made the name Tailhook shorthand for
disrespect and mistreatment of women in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The Tailhook Association, which is based in San Diego, has
10,500 members, including retired and active-duty pilots, and acts
as a sort of booster club for carrier-based aviation. Although the
group is private, its members and activities up until 1991 were
closely associated to the Navy and its officer corps, particularly
those who had flown from aircraft carriers.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Tuesday to the group's president, Navy Secretary
Richard Danzig welcomed ``a number of constructive steps'' the
association had taken since ``the shameful events'' of the 1991
convention, where 83 women, some in the Navy, reported being
assaulted or harassed in a Las Vegas hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig said those steps, including the adoption of resolutions
condemning harassment and promoting equality, merited a
reconsideration of its pariah status. He announced he would send
three senior Navy and Marine Corps officials to monitor this year's
convention, which begins Aug. 19 in Sparks, Nev., and after that
make a final decision on restoring ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to assess the extent to which the association lives by
these principles and has the potential to reflect in its membership
the charge and profile of today's _ and the future's _ naval
aviation community,'' said Danzig.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tailhook president Lonny McClung, a retired Navy captain and
pilot, welcomed the decision. In a telephone interview Tuesday,
McClung said the association had worked hard in recent years to
regain official status, the loss of which hurt the prestige and
morale of the group and made it difficult to recruit new members
from the active fleet. The association is named for the steel hook
that enables jets to land on carriers. ``We are thrilled, to say
the least,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tailhook scandal had a profound impact on the Navy and the
Marine Corps. The Pentagon's inspector general implicated more than
100 officers in the assaults or other riotous behavior at the
group's 35th annual convention in September 1991. The worst of the
assaults came when a group of drunken pilots formed a gantlet in a
hotel corridor and molested women as they passed.
</P>
<P>
   To many, the assaults reflected a military culture that condoned
machismo and worse. The public uproar over the assaults ultimately
led to the resignation of Navy Secretary Lawrence Garrett and the
early retirement of the chief of naval operations, Adm. Frank
Kelso, both of whom attended the convention, though they denied
witnessing the worst of the behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Tailhook's most lasting legacy may have been to focus attention
on the role of women in the military, which since 1991 has expanded
greatly, prompted, some have argued, by the furor over the scandal.
Women now make up 13.3 percent of Navy personnel and serve in
virtually every job, from commanding warships to flying fighter
jets off carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has been under pressure, from inside and outside the
service, to renew its ties to Tailhook. The influential chairman of
the Senate Armed Services Committee, Sen. John Warner, R-Va., a
former Navy pilot, led a campaign on behalf of the group, which was
founded in 1956. Tuesday's announcement _ essentially a half-step _
appeared designed in part to gauge public sentiment for restoring
ties.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Danzig cited three criteria he would use to
consider the association's status, including its attention to
professional development and education and its support ``in word
and deed of all the men and women in the carrier aviation
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Danzig wrote, ``the association must be committed to
preventing, and take all reasonable steps to prevent, the type of
misconduct that resulted in the removal of departmental support in
1991.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Navy never prohibited membership or attendance at
the conventions, most officers, especially senior officers, avoid
Tailhook like the plague. In a letter to Danzig in March, Warner
argued that bestowing official recognition would boost morale among
pilots and encourage them to stay in the service.
</P>
<P>
   McClung said the association had got past the scandal, shifting
the focus of the conventions from socializing to informational
seminars and moving the site from Las Vegas to the more subdued
surroundings of Sparks, which is near Reno. He also said the group
now encouraged wives and family members to attend by offering
seminars geared to their interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had color coordination seminars for the wives,'' McClung
said, describing some of the changes. ``We're really trying to
improve our image a bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
