<HEADER>
A2624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-DOT-COM-COX     08-10 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-DOT-COM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Garden.com delays its stock offering
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Reacting to Wall Street's recent icy reception
to Internet initial public offerings, Garden.com Inc. delayed its
IPO on Tuesday, becoming the latest in a number of skittish
technology companies to put a stock issue on hold.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin company, which sells plants and gardening equipment
over its Web site, had hoped to raise more than $45 million in the
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Garden.com officials did not return calls, and the company's
attorney declined to comment. While about 30 IPOs were planned for
this week, many companies are delaying, cance ling or reducing the
size and price of their offerings after demand by investors began
fading last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty apparent the Internet market is tanking fast,''
said Stephen Lacy, managing editor of IPO Reporter, a New
York-based publication that tracks the IPO market.
</P>
<P>
   What's spooking Wall Street are concerns over a possible
interest rate increase, a recent battering in technology stocks _
the tech-heavy Nasdaq index is down about 13 percent from its
52-week high _ and lousy showing by recent tech IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, seven companies that went public watched their stock
fall below their offering prices. In reaction, on Friday, eight
companies that were scheduled to go public postponed their debuts.
</P>
<P>
   For companies such as Garden.com, it's better to postpone an
offering than move forward and bomb, financial analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing you want is to bring a company public when the
market itself is struggling,'' Lacy said. ``If the original
investors pay $10 and it opens at $9 and closes at $8 and a half,
nobody's happy.''
</P>
<P>
   HotJobs.com, the New York-based online recruiter, is a case in
point. The company initially planned to price its stock at $12 to
$14, but slashed it to $8 late Monday. The stock closed Tuesday in
its first day of trading at $7.62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's two most recent IPOs are both trading below their
offering prices. Shares of Hoover's Inc., which provides business
information over the Web, have slid 37 percent since its debut. The
stock began trading at $14 when it went public July 21. Tuesday, it
closed at $8.81 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Perficient Inc., which provides software services to Internet
companies, started trading at $8 on July 29 and closed Tuesday at
$7.93 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts don't expect the market to warm toward Internet IPOs
until the Federal Reserve announces later this month whether it
will increase interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the market psychology right now it's going to be very
hard for Internet IPOs to put together a strong rally until the
fourth quarter,'' said Brian Belski, chief investment strategist at
George K. Baum and Co., a Kansas City investment bank. ``Their poor
performance over the past seven or eight weeks is making investors
very skeptical.'' This isn't the first time the IPO market has
turned cold.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, overall market volatility prevented all but a handful
of deals from getting done between the end of August and
mid-October because investors pulled back from everything but the
safest securities.
</P>
<P>
   And not everyone is backing off. In a bold move, Red Hat
Software, the Durham, N.C., vendor of Linux software, upped the
price range of its IPO by about 18 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it will offer 6 million shares at $12 to $14,
up from $10 to $12, in its $83 million IPO set for today.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Hawkins writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
