<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FARMWORKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: 13 NEEDLESS DEATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial on Wednesday, Aug. 11:
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of 13 farm workers in a vehicle crash in Five Points,
Calif., underscores the need for better enforcement of the laws
that protect farm laborers. The circumstances of Monday's accident
are shocking but not uncommon _ an unlicensed driver ferrying 15
people home just before dawn in an overloaded van. It defies common
sense that vans used for the express purpose of transporting such
laborers are not required to have seat belts. Farm workers often
have no alternative means of transportation to and from the fields.
</P>
<P>
   These accidents are yet another mark of a callous system that
exploits the migrant laborer, allowing growers to shirk
accountability by using farm labor contractors as middlemen to hire
and manage the workers. Although California has relatively tough
laws protecting farm laborers, there are loopholes that place them
at risk. The law requires that drivers of these vans be specially
licensed, but in practice many are not. California already assigns
officers to patrol the highway in the early morning hours to stop
vehicles that violate occupancy and licensing laws. But these and
other efforts to prevent violations need to be increased.
</P>
<P>
   Steps must also be taken to force growers to take more
responsibility for the general safety of their workers. Their
political muscle has allowed them to abuse the system for too long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
