<SLUG> BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA REASSESSES CAUSE OF LAUNCH SHORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New findings on Tuesday prompted NASA to change its mind about
the cause of the electrical short that occurred during last month's
launching of the shuttle Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The short that disrupted the computer-like controllers on two of
the shuttle's three rocket engines was likely caused by a blow to a
wire beneath the payload bay, said James Hartsfield, a NASA shuttle
program spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency said Monday that engineers had determined the
short occurred five seconds after liftoff because insulation from
the wire had been chafed away over time against a screw head.
</P>
<P>
   Experts, however, changed their mind Tuesday after reviewing the
results of an analysis with an electron microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``From looking at it with the electron microscope the
indentations in the wire were a telltale sign that it was really an
impact type of damage,'' Hartsfield said. The short could have
developed at any time since Columbia was manufactured, he said,
adding, ``They really don't know when it could have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of the shuttle orbiters, Columbia first flew in April
1981. The latest mission launched July 22 carrying NASA's $1.55
billion Chandra X-ray telescope, with skipper Eileen Collins, the
first female spacecraft commander, and four others.
</P>
<P>
   Had backup engine controllers not taken over after the
electrical short, Collins and pilot Jeff Ashby would have been
forced to attempt an unprecedented emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Tuesday's finding it was unclear what impact the
electrical short would have on NASA's plans to launch Endeavour on
Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   But shuttle managers delayed for a second day the transport of
Endeavour from its processing hangar at the Kennedy Space Center to
the large assembly facility where it is to be mated with its fuel
tank and twin solid-fuel rocket boosters.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour's wiring cannot be inspected without removing a large
radar device from its payload bay that astronauts will use to map
much of the Earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more research we want to gather to determine if this
is something to be concerned about that would cause us concern
against flying Endeavour,'' Hartsfield said.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is focused on a review of the documents from previous
instances in which technicians had access to the same wiring on
Endeavour, the least flown of the four orbiters. The areas is
seldom accessed, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
