A2630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-INDIA-PAKISTAN-N     08-10 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW TENSIONS ON THE SUBCONTINENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial on Wednesday, Aug. 11: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month after India and Pakistan stepped back from a
military clash in the Himalayan foothills of Kashmir, a new crisis
has erupted in another tense border area. The latest episode
involves the shooting down of a Pakistani military aircraft by an
Indian jet fighter over the marshy region along India's western
boundary with Pakistan. Both countries assert that the plane was
flying in their own air space when it was downed and that the
wreckage is in their territory. The incident shows the urgent need
for the two nations to ease distrust and improve communications.
</P>
<P>
   Now that India and Pakistan have tested nuclear weapons, there
is little margin for miscalculation in their relationship. There is
no guarantee that the presence of nuclear weapons on both sides
will produce the kind of relatively stable balance of terror that
prevailed between the United States and the Soviet Union during the
Cold War. It is essential that India and Pakistan insure that minor
military clashes do not escalate into volatile confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   The Kashmir crisis came to a head this summer after Islamic
militants, backed by Pakistan, seized several Indian positions in
the mountains. Under pressure from the United States, Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan wisely arranged for the
withdrawal of these forces last month. But promises by India and
Pakistan to resume their dialogue have not been fulfilled. Indeed,
tensions remain high.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that India and Pakistan both genuinely believe
they are the aggrieved party in the airplane downing. That would be
all the more reason to take concrete steps to exchange information
on maneuvers, flights near the border and accidental airspace
violations. A hot line between senior military commanders was
established years ago, and India and Pakistan promised earlier this
year to upgrade it. The region, and the world, cannot afford to let
such incidents spin out of control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
