<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DALAI-LAMA-NY-NYT &LR;      08-10 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALAI-LAMA-NY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH HIS 13TH VISIT, DALAI LAMA GOES FROM OBSCURITY TO CELEBRITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the Dalai Lama's first trip to New York in 1979,
he went to see the Statue of Liberty. He and his colleagues went to
Battery Park, and the Dalai Lama stood on the pier and gazed across
the water, apparently not even recognized by passers-by. He gave
talks at various churches and Buddhist centers to a total of 1,000
people, without security guards, police escorts or trailing
photographers.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as the exiled political and spiritual leader of
Tibet begins his 13th visit to New York, his fame and his following
will draw a more traditional reaction to celebrity. His every move
has been mapped out by the State Department. City police officers
are blocking off and stationing guards along his itinerary.
Photographers, television camera operators and reporters from
around the world will be following him. And an estimated 40,000
people are expected at the four major talks he is giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is here not only for the Tibetan people but for everyone in
the city,'' said Tsering Yangzon, 24, of Brooklyn, who was born in
Darjeeling, Tibet. But though Westerners may be familiar with the
Dalai Lama, they often do not understand his spiritual
significance, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference, being Tibetan,'' Ms. Yangzon said. ``He
is so sacred _ if you see his name in the newspaper, you do not
throw it away. He is not just a plaything. It is so politically
right to become Buddhist, like Hollywood does. There are Buddha
T-shirts as a fashion statement. It's not that that is negative.
But it's sad. The Dalai Lama is not a style that will fizzle out.
The Dalai Lama is so sacred to us.''
</P>
<P>
   However staunch or fickle his admirers, the city is full of
them, and the Dalai Lama's days of strolling the city's streets
unattended are long over, banished by the Nobel Peace Prize, the
Beastie Boys, Richard Gere and a host of magazine covers. His name
is invoked at rock concerts, his face stares down from billboards
and the book he wrote with Howard C. Cutler, ``The Art of
Happiness,'' (Riverhead Books, 1999) has been on the best-seller
list for 29 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his free lecture in Central Park at 11 a.m. on
Sunday, the Dalai Lama is making three other public appearances on
this trip, which is sponsored by the Gere Foundation. All three
appearances, at the Beacon Theater, have been sold out.
</P>
<P>
   The approximately 2,500 Tibetans living in the New York
metropolitan area are watching the rapidly growing adulation of
their leader with delight and bemusement.
</P>
<P>
   For people reared to revere the Dalai Lama as the enlightened
embodiment of compassion, the widespread admiration, Nobel Peace
Prize or no, is natural, proper and due. But they hope that the
admiration will spill over into political action that will help
free Tibet from Chinese occupation, bringing independence, or at
least a negotiated settlement that would allow the Tibetans more
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good that everybody knows the Dalai Lama,'' said Tenzing
Ukyab, owner of the two Tibet Arts and Crafts stores in downtown
Manhattan. ``He has compassion for everybody. He talks about peace
for the whole world, not just the Tibetan people. And it is good
that everybody knows the Tibet situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The bemusement among Tibetans stems in part from their deep
connection to their exiled leader. ``He is everything to
Tibetans,'' said Thupten Thokmey, head of the international Tibetan
Youth Congress, a group of 4,000 Tibetan students, and a student at
Baruch College. ``We sleep, we die, we eat, we are happy, we suffer
_ and we think of him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
