<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2640 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UPS-TAX-1STLD-WRITETH     08-10 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-TAX-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX COURT SAYS UPS INFLATED DEDUCTIONS AND MUST BE PENALIZED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 4th, 5th and 6th grafs for additional information and
rewriting; adds 2 new grafs at end)  
 (ATTN: Ga.)   (bl)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A judge has ruled that United Parcel Service took inflated tax
deductions in 1984 and must pay taxes, penalties and interest that
the company said may total nearly $300 million for that year.
</P>
<P>
   But its ultimate tax liability could be much larger _ perhaps
growing into one of the biggest corporate tax cases ever _ because
the Tax Court decision, issued Monday, covers only the first year
of a business practice that has continued ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The 114-page decision, and its withering dissection of testimony
by UPS executives, was a rare victory for the IRS in its efforts to
prevent companies from taking tax deductions when they move money
to subsidiaries overseas for the sole purpose of avoiding taxes.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, United Parcel Service would not estimate its
potential liability. But previously, the company had disclosed that
it could owe $259 million in taxes alone for its returns covering
the years 1985 through 1990, which have been challenged by the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, UPS has continued to claim these deductions on the
same theory that the Tax Court denied, said Kenneth Sternad, the
chief spokesman for the company. It expects the IRS to contest its
tax payments for the subsequent years. Based on the company's past
estimates of tax liability, its total in taxes, interest and
penalties could easily surpass a billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   UPS may appeal Monday's decision, Sternad said. The case would
move to the 11th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in Atlanta, where
UPS is based.
</P>
<P>
   The decision will not affect plans, announced by the company in
July, to sell shares to the public for the first time, Sternad
said.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the civil tax case were deductions that UPS took for
the costs of insuring against damaged or lost parcels worth more
than $100.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS claimed that UPS charged customers three times the
actual cost of the insurance in a scheme to funnel money to an
insurance company it created in 1984 in Bermuda, thereby inflating
its tax deductions. UPS charged customers 25 cents per $100 for
``extra value coverage'' in 1984. It then paid the money over to
National Union Fire Insurance of Pittsburgh and took a deduction
for the expense.
</P>
<P>
   But the transaction was a sham, wrote Judge Robert Ruwe in his
ruling. National Union was merely acting as a front, he said,
because after taking a small fee, it sent the money on to Overseas
Partners Ltd., a Bermuda insurance company owned and controlled by
UPS.
</P>
<P>
   United Parcel argued that its insurance fees were reasonable,
but the judge held that the rates were as much as three times what
UPS would have paid had it bought the insurance in the open market,
instead of through its own insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas Partners counted at least 63 cents of each dollar it
received as profit, Ruwe wrote _ in some years as much as 78 cents
on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   In funneling business to the Bermuda insurer, the judge ruled,
UPS was motivated only to reduce its income taxes in the United
States, and not by any legitimate business purpose. It is legal to
organize business activities in ways that reduce taxes _ but it is
illegal to engage in transactions whose sole purpose is to avoid
taxes, Ruwe noted.
</P>
<P>
   He quoted at length the testimony of Neil Doherty, an expert
witness hired by the company for the Tax Court proceedings. At
trial, an IRS lawyer asked Doherty if the 25-cent-per-$100 fee
would have made sense for UPS if the money were not being paid to
an insurer it controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a rather strange business decision to basically
give off that profit to an outsider,'' testified Doherty, a
professor of insurance and risk management at the Wharton School of
the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The inflated insurance charges allowed UPS to take nearly $65
million in improper deductions, the judge held, while inflating the
profits of Overseas Partners, which is not required to pay United
States income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The judge upheld the IRS's finding that the company owed $64.9
million in tax, a $3.2 million penalty for negligence, an
additional $11.3 million penalty for substantial underpayment of a
tax liability and interest at 50 percent above the usual rates on
$45 million of the underpayment.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to 1984, the judge wrote, UPS collected fees to cover
damage or loss to packages worth more than $100 and treated that
money as part of its regular revenue stream, paying taxes on its
profits.
</P>
<P>
   The company argued that it had created the Bermuda insurance
company not to avoid taxes, but to avoid running afoul of state
insurance regulators, some of which had questioned car rental
companies about charges they added to customer bills to cover
potential damage to vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Johnson, at the time the company's chief insurance
official, acknowledged in his testimony in the case that no state
insurance official had challenged UPS and that he had never asked
any state or federal official if the company was acting improperly
in charging the fees.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also noted that UPS had letters from each state
authorizing its earlier practice of adding charges for high-value
packages.
</P>
<P>
   As a major company, Ruwe wrote, he would have expected UPS to
investigate any such risks and to produce documents showing its
legal and economic analysis of the issue. But during the period it
was considering setting up the Bermuda insurer, he added, UPS
``produced no documentation, such as corporate minutes'' indicating
that it ``had motives other than tax reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Sternad, the company spokesman, said UPS believed the judge was
wrong and that its insurance charges were reasonable. He said the
company was not considering making refunds to customers. The IRS
has fought an uphill battle against a range of practices by
corporations intended to reduce their income taxes in the United
States by taking profits in countries that charge little or no
corporate income tax, such as Bermuda, Luxembourg and the Cayman
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   There are many legitimate reasons for companies to move funds
overseas, tax experts note, so the IRS must prove the sole motive
for the transaction was tax avoidance.
</P>
<P>
   In insurance arrangements like that set up by UPS, it has been
nearly impossible for the IRS ``to draw a bright line around which
payments to captive insurance companies are proper and which are
not,'' said Andrew Pike, a former Treasury official who teaches tax
law at American University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS has lost cases involving captive insurance companies
owned by Gulf Oil; Sears, Roebuck; U-Haul; Humana; and others,
according to Lee Sheppard, a New York lawyer who writes for Tax
Notes magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the IRS lost a $180 million case against National
Westminster Bank PLC a big British bank, over how it allocated
interest expenses between its U.S. and overseas operations.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
