<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2646 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-REACTION-HNS     08-10 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-REACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI ATHLETES SAY SHOOTINGS PART OF EVERYDAY LIFE FOR THEM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
(Attn: Calif.) 
 
By MEGAN DICKSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The shooting rampage at a Los Angeles Jewish community
center Tuesday was shocking to most of the world. But for 10
Israeli girls playing volleyball as part of the Maccabi Games in
Houston, news of violence is part of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really scary; it's more sad than scary,'' said Liat Adiv,
16. ``It's very sad to know that after so many years that people
still want to hurt us. We feel this all the time in Israel, but
it's hard to see that this happens all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Los Angeles continued searching Tuesday for a
gunman who entered a Jewish community center and fired 20 to 30
shots with what police said was a high-powered weapon with a large
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Five people were wounded, including three boys who were
attending camp at the community center, according to The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   The motive was unknown, but police are not ruling out the
possibility it might be a hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County constables informed coaches and directors of the
Israeli team, who are among about 1,600 Jewish teen-agers
participating in the Houston portion of the Maccabi Games, about
the shootings while the group was playing against a team from
Detroit on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was made to keep the Israeli team members together
and step up security with police escorts to and from the venues of
the games, according to Jason Black, communications director for
the Jewish Community Center in southwest Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Cheek, a constable in Harris County, which includes most of
Houston, said more security officers might be added in the wake of
the Los Angeles shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real tragic situation,'' said Cheek, who had met
over a period of several months with Maccabi officials to arrange
security for the games. ``Obviously we'll be more alert, but for
right now we're going to stick with our plan. We'll meet throughout
the night to figure out if there is something more we need to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow, we may have the horse patrol out there for
visibility and to provide a sense of security.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli team captain Anat Matus, 16, was comforted by the extra
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the time in Israel,'' Matus said. ``You go on a bus,
and you never know if it's going to blow or not. It's very scary;
at least now I know we'll be safe. It's very good to have the
escorts.''
</P>
<P>
   JCC officials in Houston released a statement saying their
thoughts and prayers would be with the families victimized by the
shooting in Los Angeles. Organizers declined to make any further
statements until the identity and motivation of the perpetrator was
identified.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bunny Radolff, part of public relations for the Houston JCC, was
unaware that security for the Israel volleyball team had been
increased and refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have absolutely no knowledge of the extra security,'' said
Radolff. ``I don't know anything about that and it's probably just
someone reacting to the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheek said her reaction wasn't unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately on hearing the news we did bring in extra people
but I'm sure not everyone there was totally aware of that,'' said
Cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Adiv said the news of the shooting gives her volleyball team
motivation to finish the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes us believe that we have to win now,'' Adiv said.
``We have to show all the world that we exist and there is nothing
more they can do to us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
