<HEADER>
A2647 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-SHOOTING-2NDLD-WRI     08-10 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-SHOOTING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN WOUNDS 5 AT L.A. COMMUNITY CENTER, THEN FLEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: CORRECTS critical boy's age to 5, sted 8, in 4th and 13th
grafs; also CORRECTS receptionist's age to 68, sted 65, in 13th
graf, bgng, Fire Department ...; subs lede to rephrase intro
clause.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the latest in a string of seemingly
inexplicable shootings, a balding, white, middle-aged man walked
into a Jewish community center in a middle-class suburb Tuesday
morning and fired as many as 30 shots, wounding five people,
including three young boys at a day camp, and then fled.
</P>
<P>
   A 3{-year-old boy who said he was just a few feet from the
shooting _ his mother would only give his name as Eric _ said the
man said nothing before fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad monster ran away,'' said the boy, who clung to his
mother and asked her if any of the wounded children had done
anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   One of the victims, a 5-year-old boy, who had been shot in the
abdomen, was said to be in critical condition after undergoing
surgery, while the other victims were said to be in good condition
and were expected to be released soon from local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Police with dogs cordoned off the area around the North Valley
Jewish Community Center in Granada Hills to search for the gunman,
described as about 40 years old, but by Tuesday evening they had
not found him and believed he was no longer in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they had no idea who he was or why he had opened
fire and that none of the people who saw the shooter at the center
recognized him.
</P>
<P>
   Officials asked residents of the neighborhood to remain indoors
as they conducted their search, but police lines quickly became
jammed with parents waiting anxiously to hear about their children.
</P>
<P>
   Within 30 minutes after the shooting at 10:45 a.m., helicopter
crews from local television stations broadcast images of police
officers leading children out of the center by hand, in strings of
five, six and seven. Firefighters and paramedics at the scene said
the children had been orderly, though upset.
</P>
<P>
   The images of fleeing children, anxious parents and armed
officers searching alleys, sheds and homes in the area were
broadcast for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents who were reunited with their children in the street
then stayed in the area, hugging their children, chatting with
friends and other parents, apparently so stunned by the violence
that they seemed unconcerned that the shooter could still be in the
neighborhood. Around midday, the Fire Department brought a cooler
of drinks for parents, many who were still waiting for word on the
whereabouts of their children.
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Shalometh Golden was quoted by the City News Service as
saying that her mother, Isabelle Shalometh, a receptionist at the
center, had been wounded lightly in the arm and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said a young man, a ruffian, she saw him coming at her and
I guess he just started open firing,'' Ms. Golden said, ``and she
knew enough to quickly duck down and she did.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire Department Capt. Steve Ruda said that in addition to Ms.
Shalometh, who he said was 68, a 16-year-old girl was shot in the
right thigh and shin, a 6-year-old boy was wounded in the left foot
and another 6-year-old boy was shot in the left leg and hip. The
most seriously sounded was the 5-year-old boy hit in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the shooter was between 5 feet 8 and 5 feet 10,
about 170 pounds, and was dressed in green clothing. He fired as
many as 30 shots from a 9-millimeter handgun, then apparently fled
on foot, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the police said that two young men had been
responsible, but later attributed that description to confusion by
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms sent
agents to the residential area, in the San Fernando Valley about 30
miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles, to assist local police.
</P>
<P>
   Police were sifting through a number of clues, whose relation
remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Police Cmdr. David Kalish said they had searched a red van
with Washington state license plates, in an area not far from the
shooting and had found ``an incredible amount of ammunition,'' a
bulletproof vest and ``substantial other evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Police also said that about noon there had been a carjacking in
which a white male who generally matched the description of the
shooter had stolen a dark green 1999 Toyota Corolla. The police
later said that the van's driver was the same man who had stolen
the car at gunpoint, and that they had been led to the van while
investigating the car theft. Later, police found the Toyota several
miles away at a hotel that they barricaded and surrounded.
</P>
<P>
   Because the incident followed a string of school shootings in
recent months, and comes in the middle of an intense debate over
the availability of firearms, it was followed closely by officials
across the state and in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said, ``Once again our nation has been shaken
and our hearts torn'' by what he called ``another senseless act of
gun violence.''
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Gray Davis said, ``Once again, we have been
shocked, saddened and outraged by an act of vicious gun violence
aimed against defenseless children and innocent adults.'' He
offered a $50,000 reward for information leading to an arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The North Valley Jewish Community Center is an educational and
recreation facility where the elderly come to play cards, parents
drop their toddlers off for pre-school, singles play tennis and
children learned to swim in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   There are after-school enrichment classes on gymnastics, karate,
cooking and celebrating the Sabbath. Children learned to make
traditional braided challah bread and how to celebrate the Jewish
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The ``little red schoolhouse,'' a small facility behind the main
building, houses the pre-school for children aged 2 and 3. The
pre-school's security rules required that parents sign children in
and out each day.
</P>
<P>
   Although the neighborhood is generally quiet, several residents
said there have been growing racial tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Trombley, 18, who graduated last year from the local high
school, said Granada Hills is largely white, with a mix of blue
collar and white collar families. But, he said, it borders on one
side a largely Asian neighborhood, and on another side a Latino
neighborhood, and there have been sporadic racial tensions, with
fights involving teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of life around here,'' he said. ``You just accept
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
