<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2652 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-AGAIN-COX     08-10 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-AGAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Oh God, not again!' Atlantans share pain
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After the shootings Tuesday in Los Angeles, cameras
caught a woman scooping up a girl in a pink tie-dyed skirt, hugging
her so tightly that the child's T-shirt rode up over her shoulder
blades and her sneakered feet kicked in midair.
</P>
<P>
   All over Atlanta, parents had the same visceral impulse: to grab
their children. To clutch them close. To feel that they could be
safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You send your child off to an allegedly safe place, a place
with nursery story characters painted on the wall, and something
like this happens,'' Carey Sipp, an Atlanta author and mother of
two, said in disbelief. ``I just don't know what we're going to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been less than two weeks since Mark O. Barton killed 12
people in Stockbridge and Buckhead, including his own two children,
wounded 13 and then ended his own life with a bullet to the head;
less than three months since Anthony ``T.J.'' Solomon shot into a
crowd of 200 Heritage High School students in suburban Rockdale
County, wounding six; and less than four months since Dylan Klebold
and Eric Harris killed a teacher, 12 students and themselves at
Columbine High School in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   In his office at Emory University, gun violence researcher and
father Arthur Kellerman read reports of the L.A. shooting on the
Web. ``Oh, God,'' he said. ``Not again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad enough it was another shooting, another inexplicable
outburst of rage, another attempted mass murder. Much worse that
most of the victims were young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hurt a child _ that's unthinkable for most of us,'' said
Nadine Kaslow, chief psychologist at Grady Memorial Hospital. ``But
for some small group of very troubled, very angry people, that
inhibition isn't there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Atlantans, reactions to the shootings were as poignant and
identifiable as headings on a counselor's chart: disbelief,
outrage, grief, fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that goes through your mind, no matter where
you are, is: Where are my kids?'' said Dr. Philip Shayne, an
emergency physician at Grady, who treated some of Barton's victims
and whose wife is pregnant with their second child.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hamilton Mill Child Development Center in Buford, Ga.,
where an 18-month-old was kidnapped at gunpoint by a parent four
months ago, administrator Faye Miles lamented the precautions she
has to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our world was much safer'' when she started in day care 37
years ago, she said. ``Our communities were much safer. We live in
a world of strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a jaded world as well, adults worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear about things you didn't used to,'' said Lee Leonard,
whose 4-year-old attends Atlanta Cooperative Preschool. ``I hope
I'm not becoming desensitized.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Hannah Miller, a college junior working during the summer
at Inman Park Cooperative Preschool: ``As much as we think we can
protect the children in our care, there are some things we can't
protect against.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is home to some of the country's top researchers into
violence. The idea that the L.A. shootings could be dismissed as
random troubled them almost as much as the shootings themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Columbine, after Heritage High School, after Buckhead,
you wonder what is it going to take for us as a society to get off
our backsides and try to tackle this problem,'' Kellerman said.
``What will it take for us to shake off the fatalistic sense that
there is nothing we can do about this?''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding and preventing violence is Rodney Hammond's
vocation. He is a psychologist who heads the Division of Violence
Prevention at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, and
he has a grown son.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The shootings) make me feel, at a very basic level, worried
about the safety of our communities, and desperately wanting to
know something I can do to predict situations where this kind of
event would affect me or my children,'' he said. ``What nags at you
is, what would deter an incident like this? It underlines that we
need to move the discussion to prevention, to understanding some of
the causes of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houghton family, leaving the Downtown Child Development
Center with their three sons, four hours after the shootings in
L.A., couldn't begin to understand. Both parents are Europeans,
John from England and Christine from Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't see this sort of things as regularly as here,''
John Houghton said. ``The gun part of this country is amazing.
Everyone, just everyone, seems to be allowed to get a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   And so few men have other outlets, his wife added. ``There
doesn't seem to be anyone who helps them resolve their problems.
It's quite sad,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans were just as dismayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being pregnant, I wonder about the society I'm bringing a
child into,'' said Dr. Tammie Quest, a Grady emergency physician.
``There's such a depersonalization. We don't relate to each other
as humans anymore; it's as though people are targets or objects.''
</P>
<P>
   Or bargaining chits, Kaslow said. ``Children are our most
precious commodity. Society pays attention when they are harmed,''
she said. ``I really think that when people are angry and hostile
and hate the world, they know they'll be most heard by attacking
children.''
</P>
<P>
   The more these shootings are televised, the more appealing that
twisted logic may become, Emory's Kellerman contended. ``It would
be hard for anyone not to argue that there's a copycat phenomenon
going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The thought that the recent shootings will continue _ and that
children could be even more at risk _ frightens both parents and
children themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 6 or 7, I didn't have to think about this stuff,
but now I have to deal with it,'' said 13-year-old Brittany
Harrington Pool. ``All this makes me more aware and makes me more
worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Evie Weinreich, who teaches at a Jewish school, was watching TV
reports of the L.A. shootings when her two sons came in from
religious camp. Tzvi, 11, and David, almost 8, knew Allen Charles
Tenenbaum, one of Barton's victims; their mother had taught his
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your heart breaks,'' she said. ``It's a horrible reflection on
society. We have to find a way to do something, or we're going to
destroy ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son asked me, `Can I go outside and play?' '' she said,
``and I hesitated.''
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Diane Lore, Diane Loupe and Jennifer Brett
contributed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
