</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PRESIDENTIAL-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE $2 BILLION ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
   (yn) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Aug. 11:
</P>
<P>
   It is getting more and more expensive to influence politicians.
The Republican Party, looking ahead to next year's presidential and
Congressional elections, has recently established ``Team $1
Million.'' As Don Van Natta Jr. recently reported in The Times,
membership will cost donors a cool $1 million in campaign
contributions. But membership has its privileges. In return for the
money, among other things, donors will be given opportunities to
discuss their concerns with House Speaker Dennis Hastert, the
Senate majority leader, Trent Lott and other Congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   With fund-raising on that scale, the current political season
will almost certainly produce the first $2 billion election. The
amount of unregulated ``soft money'' from corporations, unions and
wealthy individuals is likely to double or even triple the $260
billion hauled in during the last presidential campaign, when
President Clinton opened the White House to sleepovers and coffees,
inviting such abuses as foreign contributions that later had to be
returned. More scandals and evidence of favors in return for
donations are bound to corrupt the system as fund-raising
accelerates in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   A fairly good example of the corruption of campaign money can be
found in the $792 billion tax cut recently approved by Congress.
Republicans know that Clinton will veto this bill. But they are
shopping it around during the August recess to the health care,
real estate, oil and gas, timber and securities industries, all of
which got special tax breaks in the legislation. The argument to
these industries is that they can make a donation now to ensure
that their special deal survives if there is a final tax cut accord
with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder that Hastert and Lott will be fighting once again
to kill campaign finance reform. The latest maneuver occurred last
week, when the House speaker put forward a rule governing debate on
the issue next month. Hastert did keep his promise to Reps.
Christopher Shays of Connecticut and Martin Meehan of Massachusetts
to allow their bill to be considered. But in a tactic reminiscent
of those used last year, Hastert would allow the House first to
vote on a toothless substitute bill. If it passes, there would be
no vote on the Shays-Meehan bill itself. To defeat this maneuver,
House members will have to vote against a measure that
superficially looks attractive so they can vote for the
Shays-Meehan reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Most members are likely to see through the speaker's tactics. If
they do not, they will consign Americans to a system that strangles
democracy and deepens the cynicism of voters. The Shays-Meehan bill
would clean up the system by banning corporate and union donations
to parties and applying strict limits to donations by individuals
and political action committees. It would also extend these curbs
to money raised by independent groups running campaign ads within
60 days of an election.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom in Washington is that this legislation
cannot pass, even though it commands healthy majorities in the
House and Senate. In fact, the Shays-Meehan bill can be approved by
the House in September, and by the Senate in October, if lawmakers
respond to their constituents instead of party cash machines. The
August recess is a fine time for Americans to remind their senators
and congressmen that citizen interests, not special interests,
should rule in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
