<HEADLINE>
FETUS IN LIFE-SUPPORT CASE APPARENTLY DIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A 17-week-old fetus at the center of a fight over
whether a comatose woman should be kept alive by artificial means
has apparently died, lawyers said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors noticed Monday night that the fetus' heart had stopped
beating while preparing the mother, Tammy Martin, for a
tracheotomy, attorney Craig Smyser said during a court hearing
Tuesday. Smyser represents Memorial Hospital Northwest in north
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Smyser told Harris County Probate Judge Rory Olsen that a
radiologist performed sonogram tests, found no fetal movement and
confirmed Tuesday that the fetus had apparently died.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen ordered further tests of the fetus and Martin within 10
days by doctors unconnected to the hospital. Martin, 34, fell into
a coma from a blow to the head July 18, and until Tuesday hospital
officials had reported the fetus had a heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Law, 35, a Houston man who claims to be the biological
father of the child and the common-law husband of Martin, cried
after the hearing and was too distraught to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's destroyed his world. The baby meant everything to him,''
said Law's attorney, Jared Woodfill. ``He got into this battle
because he wanted the child to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Law sued the hospital July 23, claiming it was conspiring with
Martin's family to let her die and that he was being shut out of
the decision-making process. A judge that day ordered the hospital
to not withhold life-support treatment, and July 30 Law was
declared to be Martin's temporary guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's parents, J.D. and Joyce Cox of Bracketville in South
Texas, and her brother, Lonnie Martin of Splendora, have said that
the life support should be removed because doctors told them she is
brain-dead and the fetus had little, if any, chance of being born
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   They said they would fight to remove the life support even if
the fetus' heart kept beating, claiming Law is not Martin's
common-law husband and may not be the father of the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew in our hearts and in our souls the fetus would never
make it,'' Lonnie Martin said from his home after the hearing. ``We
had the feeling that God was going to do God's work. I do believe
God had delivered my sister's wish.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers involved said they expect the court-appointed
doctors to do the tests within 10 days and for another hearing to
held afterward. Olsen scheduled a hearing for Aug. 23 to determine
who should be Martin's guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Woodfill said the court-appointed doctors will not perform an
official test to determine whether Martin is brain-dead. He said
the test, called an apnea test, will presumably be ordered by the
court after the independent doctors report their findings. Apnea
tests measure the ability of the brain to stimulate a breathing
response after ventilators are turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Woodfill said that if Martin is declared brain-dead, he is not
sure Law would want to cut off life support. In court documents
filed last week, Law said he believes Martin is showing increasing
brain activity.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County sheriff's officials confirmed Tuesday that if
Martin is declared brain dead, they plan to ask prosecutors to
consider filing charges of criminally negligent homicide against
Law.
</P>
<P>
   Law, a concrete crew supervisor, has declined to discuss the
blow to Martin's head in detail because he knew he was being
investigated by law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   He has denied any wrongdoing, saying the door of a pickup hit
Martin's head when it jumped out of gear and that she had seemed OK
and went to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   He said she woke up hours later at their home, started throwing
up and fell unconscious. He said doctors told him there was no way
for him to know that a major blood vessel had ruptured.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's parents and brother believe Law was either negligent by
not calling for an ambulance sooner or that he may have assaulted
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one will rest in peace until the story of what happened is
told,'' Lonnie Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Woodfill said Law was stunned by the reported death of the fetus
because doctors had been saying for more than a week that the
heartbeat was getting stronger and the organs were developing
normally.
</P>
<P>
   Woodfill said doctors noticed the heartbeat stopped after Martin
was moved to an operating room for the tracheotomy, a procedure to
enable her to be fed. He said he did not know if the move may have
injured the fetus because he hadn't seen hospital records.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's attorney, Smyser, said he did not know the
details of the fetus' apparent death. Hospital spokeswoman Patty
Riddlebarger said she did not know if doctors had a theory as to
what may have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was facing two years in prison for violating parole after
being convicted of injecting cocaine into the minor daughter of her
former boyfriend, Ben Bruce. Martin's family has described her as
an alcoholic and cocaine addict, and they say doctors told them if
the fetus was born it would likely be retarded or deformed because
of the mother's addictions.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce, who has said he planned to file a petition to be declared
Martin's common-law husband, said Tuesday he would not know until
further proceedings if he would still want to take such a step. He
declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
