<HEADLINE>
CABLEVISION DEAL TO BUY METS IS `REAL CLOSE'
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The public's focus on the Mets this season has been
on their proximity to first place, but off the field they have
moved quietly and steadily closer to a deal for the team's
$400-million sale to Cablevision. How close?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're real close,'' the owner of another team said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting awfully close,'' said another owner, who also
requested anonymity, adding that they're so close ``they're sending
papers back and forth putting in the last details.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wilpon, one of the Mets' co-owners, declined to comment on
those observations. His silence is understandable considering that
George Steinbrenner's negotiations with Cablevision for the sale of
the Yankees collapsed after Steinbrenner talked publicly about a
possible deal. Charles Dolan, the No. 1 man at Cablevision,
conducts his business in total privacy and doesn't like anyone
talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   The other team owners said that under terms of the sale Wilpon
would operate the Mets while Nelson Doubleday, the other Mets
co-owner, would remain with the club in an executive capacity.
Wilson and Doubleday are each supposed to keep a 10 percent
interest in the team.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday, asked if a deal was close, said, ``I don't have a
signed piece of paper,'' adding that he had ``people sniffing
around'' to find out if a deal is close.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the business merger between the Yankees and the Nets
remains incomplete. One team owner said Tuesday that the Nets have
deposited the $225 million they will pay the Yankees to offset the
difference in the value of the two teams but that Steinbrenner
remained undecided on whether to go through with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner denied that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who would be starting that rumor,'' he said.
``There's no truth to that. It's moving along. We're waiting for
baseball's approval, and then NBA approval. That's all I know. We
have no other plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed transaction, unique in professional sports and also
very complex, has created a problem for Major League Baseball.
Commissioner Bud Selig must decide whether the deal creates a
control issue. If he concludes that it does, the deal would have to
go before the ownership committee.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner apparently has argued that there would be no change
in control so it should not have to be voted on by the ownership
committee. If Selig agrees, it would be up to him to approve it.
</P>
</TEXT>
