<SLUG> BC-NY-ATTICA-SURVIVOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTICA: THE PAIN, LIKE THE LAWSUIT, PERSISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAN HOFFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even now, 28 years later, as Frank B.B. Smith sits
talking with his wife, Pearl, on their porch in Queens Village, you
can sense why he had the respect of both the inmates and the guards
when he was doing time at Attica. He is blunt and funny, with a
hustler's charm. He is also intimidating: 6-foot-1, 230 pounds back
then, and his middle initials stand for Big Black. Call him Black,
please! he says warmly.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a former junkie and petty criminal who had been convicted
of holding up a dice game, was the inmates' football coach. The
warden gave him special privileges.
</P>
<P>
   And on that September morning when the rebellion over prison
conditions erupted, the inmates selected Smith to be chief of
security and protect negotiators. Five days later, when troopers
stormed the prison, wounding 88 men and killing 29 inmates and 10
hostages in six minutes, they reserved a vengeful torture for the
man everyone had trusted.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in the latest chess move of a 25-year-old lawsuit, a
federal appeals court overturned the $4 million jury verdict
awarded Smith for what happened to him that endless day. While not
disputing the events, the court said the trial judge had made
significant errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about that decision,'' Smith says. ``I play the
Lotto. It might pop for me that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Laughter. Then he adds quietly, ``I'm a humorous-sounding
person, but inside I'm hurting. I am so sick of the law business.''
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 13, 1971: Guards and troopers made Smith lie naked on a
table, a football under his chin. If it fell, they warned, he would
be killed or castrated. (There was a rumor he had castrated a
guard, who had in fact been shot inadvertently by troopers.) For
several hours, they beat him around the head and testicles,
dropping lighted cigarettes and hot shell casings on his belly.
</P>
<P>
   Then, prodding with batons, they forced Smith, his legs
buckling, toward a corridor from which, witnesses testified, could
be heard the rhythmic thunder of clubs against a wall and voices
chanting, ``We're waiting for you, Frank!'' Barefoot, he stumbled
across the broken glass, strewn for the gantlet.
</P>
<P>
   That night he was dumped, nude and bleeding, wrists broken, in
an isolation cell. As he lay spread-eagled, guards taunted him with
a gun, playing Russian roulette.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has told this story many times, the retellings have
not worn down the rage and incredulity in his voice. Mrs. Smith
leans forward and says that, years later, ``He would have
flashbacks at night, and he'd be on the floor crying like a baby as
if he was reliving the rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Smith, 66, says: ``Attica was my downfall and my
lifesaver.'' For when he was released in 1973, he realized that
however easy it would be to commit more crimes, the last thing he
wanted was a return ticket to Attica. He became a leader for the
Attica Brothers Legal Defense, helping to raise more than $1
million to contest the indictments against himself and 61 others
stemming from the uprising.
</P>
<P>
   After his and most other cases were dismissed, Smith,
articulate, imposing, wrapped in the mantle of the Attica tragedy,
emerged as a sought-after presence at many left-wing events, as
well as at schools, community centers and colleges, where he
continues to speak about preventing future Atticas. He moved
comfortably among groups like the Black Panthers and the Black
Liberation Army: ``Angela Davis, she's my buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as he never sided with one gang, he never allied with
one organization. ``I believe in spreading around and not locking
myself in,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He was also struggling with a cocaine addiction, which had
dogged him since his younger days in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section
of Brooklyn. By 1986, he finally got clean. He became a substance
abuse counselor, and, like Pearl, whom he had married in 1983 and
who works in the Staten Island Family Court, took a special
interest in troubled adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   And though he had only an 11th-grade education, he apprenticed
himself as a paralegal with Elizabeth M. Fink, a lawyer who has
represented him since 1974 and who has pressed the civil suit since
1981. He free-lances for lawyers as a paralegal and an
investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, now 320 pounds, places his hands over his belly, clearly
enjoying the grand joke in which he is working in the court system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to find people, ask questions, get statements,'' he
says. ``I know how to lie to the judge and get something done. The
cops wave and say, `How are you doing, Black?'''
</P>
<P>
   He is doing fine, even became born-again four years ago. It's
just that Attica is unfinished. ``Attica is 28 years of my life,''
he says. ``I sleep with it, I eat with it, it's everything to me.''
He is flabbergasted that the lawsuit which he and other inmates
filed in 1975 seeking reparations from the police shootings and
tortures is still unresolved, following last week's court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   He has been running his mouth for a while. Mrs. Smith again
leans forward. ``He's big and vocal, but underneath it all he's a
really good person,'' she says. She smiles fondly. ``He'll say:
`Pearl, do you have an idea of what you want to wear tomorrow? I'll
iron it for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Smith looks a tad embarrassed. ``I worked in the laundry,'' he
says, ``when I was at Attica.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
