A2660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-RYN-NYT &LR;      08-10 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RYN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNNY VAN RYN, 94, SPECIALIST IN DOUBLES FOR U.S. DAVIS CUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Va., Texas, N.J.)   (bl)  
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnny Van Ryn, whose doubles partnership with Wilmer Allison
proved to be the anchoring force of the U.S. Davis Cup team from
1929 to 1936, died Aug. 7 in Palm Beach, Fla. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Newport News, Va., in 1905, Van Ryn's doubles expertise
first attracted notice during his collegiate stint at Princeton,
where he won the U.S. tates intercollegiate doubles championship in
1927.
</P>
<P>
   Once he teamed up with the scrappy Allison, who won the
collegiate singles title that same year for his alma mater, Texas,
Van Ryn quickly distinguished himself on the Grand Slam front. He
and Allison captured the first of their four career Grand Slam
titles at Wimbledon in 1929, and successfully defended it in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   The duo also reached six U.S. finals, one short of Fred
Alexander and Harold Hackett's record seven, and they won the
national titles in 1931 and 1935.
</P>
<P>
   When Van Ryn paired with an alternate partner, George Lott, and
won the French Open and Wimbledon doubles crowns in 1931, he became
the only American man to prevail in Wimbledon's doubles
championship for three consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   Van Ryn also enjoyed a notable singles career, ranking among the
United States' top 10 from 1927 to 1932 and reaching the world top
10 in 1929 and 1931, but he got no closer to the singles title at
Forest Hills than the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   But it was on the international Davis Cup front where Van Ryn
left his greatest mark. His 14-2 record there alongside Allison was
not eclipsed until John McEnroe and Peter Fleming teamed up decades
later and accumulated a 14-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Van Ryn produced Davis Cup records of 7-1 in singles
and 22-2 in his specialty, doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Van Ryn was a prominent player in the controversial 1932 Davis
Cup showdown between France, the defending champion, and the
Americans. On a heavily watered clay court at Roland Garros, which
was intended to disturb the Americans and fortify the French, Van
Ryn and Allison defeated Henri Cochet and Jacques Brugnon to cut
France's lead to 2-1 in the five-match competition and set up a
pivotal duel between Allison and Jean Borotra.
</P>
<P>
   After losing his surprising two-set lead, Allison again nosed
ahead in the fifth set and, after squandering three match points,
began celebrating a 2-2 Davis Cup deadlock when Borotra served an
apparent double fault on the fourth match point.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the serve was ruled legal, Borotra went on to claim the
match and guarantee France its sixth straight Davis Cup
championship. Van Ryn and the rest of the dumbfounded U.S. squad
boycotted the official Davis Cup dinner that evening under orders
from Dwight Davis himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only ever heard him cuss once,'' Van Ryn said of Davis, who
inaugurated the Davis Cup competition in 1900, ``and it was then.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Ryn's Davis Cup career ended in 1936, and he was inducted
into the International Tennis Hall of Fame in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 62 years, Cornelia Drake Van Ryn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
