<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES WITHDRAW LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the umpires union shut down its lawsuit against the
National and American leagues, the union president opened the door
Tuesday for dissident umpires to return to the fight against
major-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the umpires had become splintered over the
union's mass-resignation strategy, Jerry Crawford, the union
president, appealed to the umpires in a letter asking that they
return to their solidarity position, in which they supported
``those members whose rights and jobs were attacked by baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two umpires, 13 in the National League and nine in the
American League, face the end of their careers three weeks from
Thursday, the effective date of the letters of resignation most of
them signed July 14, then rescinded July 27.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires withdrew their resignations after Judge Edmund
Ludwig of U.S. District Court in Philadelphia failed to grant them
an order protecting their jobs. The union subsequently filed unfair
labor practice charges with the National Labor Relations Board and
announced Tuesday that it had withdrawn the lawsuit on Monday so it
could focus on the labor board charges.
</P>
<P>
   The union announcement also said it withdrew the lawsuit because
the issues had changed since the suit was filed. The union acted
before the leagues filed a motion to dismiss the suit on the
grounds that the issues it raised belong before the labor board or
an arbitrator. The union held out the possibility that it could
refile a lawsuit next week dealing with different issues. But it is
also pressing its case before the labor board.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Phillips, the union chief, said that Susan Davis, the New
York lawyer handling the union's case, submitted a 12-page outline
of the union's case on Monday. ``We all feel that very compelling
arguments were set forth in that outline,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford set forth some strong arguments of his own in his
letter to the umpires, a copy of which was obtained by The New York
Times. As examples of union solidarity, the veteran NL umpire cited
cases involving John Hirschbeck and Joe Brinkman, the AL umpires
considered the leaders of the dissident faction, the 24 umpires who
didn't resign or rescinded their resignations in time to save their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Roberto Alomar spit on one of our members,'' Crawford
wrote, referring to Hirschbeck and a 1996 incident, ``this union
and its membership stood together in support.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Likewise, when baseball considered firing one of our members
last fall,'' Crawford continued, referring to Brinkman, ``we again
were all prepared to do what was necessary to back him.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford noted that Richie Garcia, one of the AL umpires who is
losing his job, ``said that he would walk for the guy's job.''
Later, when the AL took away Brinkman's crew-chief job, ``Garcia
vowed to give his back in support.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is ironic now,'' Crawford wrote, ``that some members who
have received the benefit of our support are now actively working
towards the destruction of this union.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford called major-league baseball ``cruel and
mean-spirited'' in its decision to accept the resignation of 22
umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an immediate purpose,'' he wrote. ``A commitment to
the 22 umpires who baseball has selectively hung out to dry. We
will not leave them hanging out to dry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-10-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GWYNN-NYT &LR;      08-10 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GWYNN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: A NIGHT WHEN GWYNN WOULD NOT STEP UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tony Gwynn was tired. He limped from his locker to
the bathroom and back to his locker in the visitors' clubhouse at
Shea Stadium. Then Gwynn grabbed a soda and his cellular phone and
sought privacy and some reception in the third-base dugout. He
found neither.
</P>
<P>
   The phone did not work, so the chubby man with 3,004 hits sat
down. Rickey Henderson ambled across the field and hugged Gywnn,
and Gwynn told Henderson that he would be the next player to
eclipse 3,000. Bobby Valentine was a couple of steps behind
Henderson, and the Mets manager shook Gwynn's hand and then
actually reached down and kissed it.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after the usually affable Gwynn moved into a rarefied
position in baseball history, he arrived with the San Diego Padres
in the media capital of the world Tuesday. Gwynn obviously knew
that reporters would want to talk to him about his accomplishment,
and the Padres tentatively scheduled a news conference for 4:30
p.m. At 4:11, Gwynn balked. ``I've been talked out,'' Gwynn said.
``I hope you understand. I just need a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the reporters had to understand because two separate
attempts to speak with Gwynn were met with polite yet stern ``no
comments.'' Whatever Gwynn has thought about since getting 3,000
hits, whatever relief or euphoria he has experienced since reaching
what Henderson described as ``every hitter's dream'' and whatever
Gwynn felt about Jim Leyritz's recent criticism of him remained
unanswered. ``I'll do it all tomorrow,'' Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   That is unfortunate. Gwynn is one of the most eloquent and
cooperative players in the major leagues and it is too bad he
selected Tuesday to turn silent. Gwynn received a 60-second
standing ovation from Mets fans before he batted in the first
inning, and dozens of fans stood outside Shea four hours before the
first pitch in pursuit of his autograph. In addition, the New York
chapter of the Baseball Writers Association of America selected
Gwynn as their Good Guy Award winner last year, the first time the
prestigious award was not won by a Met or a Yankee. Someone from
the Padres should have reminded Gwynn, who did not attend the
awards dinner, of that. But, instead, there was a major-league
official standing sentry near Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been interesting to hear what Gwynn thought about
Leyritz's remarks. The day before he was traded back to the Yankees
on July 31, Leyritz criticized the San Diego icon for not working
with younger players and for not staying with the team while he was
injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Tony, there have been good things and there have been bad
things,'' Leyritz told The San Diego Union-Tribune. ``As far as a
hitter, watching him day in and day out and the way he prepares
himself, it is fun to watch. But there are other things you look
for in a player. There may be intangibles that other players have
that I'd like to see in him.''
</P>
<P>
   When Leyritz was asked what sort of intangibles, he said: ``Don
Mattingly was an unselfish player. When he was on the disabled list
for a long time, he was always with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn surmised that Leyritz was perturbed because Gwynn did not
stay with the Padres for a full game while he was disabled and they
were in Anaheim last month. The future Hall of Famer blamed the
remarks on the endless attention he received while the Padres
struggled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kind of been sitting back waiting for somebody to say
something or do something out of frustration,'' Gwynn told the
newspaper. ``I didn't figure on him, but I'm not surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz slightly backpedaled from his comments Tuesday and said
he meant that, for him, comparing Gwynn to Don Mattingly was like
``comparing him to God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony knew how I felt about him not staying for games when he
was on the disabled list and not being around the team,'' Leyritz
said. ``To me, that didn't bother me. That's his personality. We
talked about it as a team. We didn't like it, but that's Tony's
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   The Union-Tribune quoted two players who did want their names
used as saying that Gwynn needed to listen to what Leyritz had
uttered and called Gwynn self-centered. Gwynn should be more upset
with them. At least the candid, though cocky, Leyritz spoke
publicly. But Leyritz's words were poisonous in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife has to go to the grocery store and the bank and all
she hears is: `Why does your husband hate Tony Gywnn? He says bad
things about Tony Gwynn. Why does he do that?''' Leyritz said. ``It
really made me look bad as far as taking a cheap shot going out the
door.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, who played with Gwynn in 1996 and 1997 and who is 241
hits from 3,000, defended him as a ``good teammate'' and speculated
that Gwynn was not with the Padres when he was injured because he
was too frustrated. Before Gwynn made it to 3,000, he occasionally
felt awkward about the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I feel like my teammates don't want to talk to me
because I'm locked into 3,000,'' Gwynn told The Union-Tribune.
``It's a feeling I don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   So Gwynn felt uncomfortable because someone did not want talk to
him? He should have remembered that feeling Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
