</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHESAPEAKE-ENVIRON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHESAPEAKE BAY'S VITAL SIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Aug. 11:
</P>
<P>
   Chesapeake Bay, one of America's most beleaguered estuaries, is
showing signs of better health this summer. Improved water quality
in some tributaries is allowing the regrowth of underwater grasses,
the striped bass have returned and the oyster population, as
recently reported in The New York Times, is on the upswing _ a big
gain for the bay because oysters act as a natural filter for
impurities in the water. Meanwhile last week an environmental group
and a timber company agreed to preserve 76,000 acres of Chesapeake
watershed lands that might otherwise have been developed.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a fragile body of water requiring constant care, and
one of the biggest threats to its health is only now being
addressed. That is the waste runoff from factory farms,
particularly the huge poultry operation in the Chesapeake
watershed. As The Washington Post noted in a series on the problem
last week, the runoff from these farms is devastating to the bay
because such waste is rich in nitrogen and phosphorus, which
encourage algae growth, choke underwater vegetation and rob aquatic
life of necessary oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive nutrients can also lead to outbreaks of toxic microbes
like pfiesteria piscicada, which in 1997 caused serious illness in
fish and humans. Agricultural runoff from the six states in the
Chesapeake Bay watershed is not a new problem, but the growth of
agribusiness has accelerated the flow of waste. The amount of
poultry manure spread over the fields adjacent to the bay in
Delaware, Maryland and Virginia as fertilizer is three times
greater than what the soil can absorb.
</P>
<P>
   The basic federal responsibility for this mess lies with the
Environmental Protection Agency. Last Friday the agency issued a
draft set of guidelines for livestock factory farms. This is a good
step, but the guidelines leave considerable authority to the
states, which vary widely in their eagerness to attack the problem.
Before the EPA puts its regulations into effect, it should devise a
set of minimum standards for phosphorus, nitrogen and other
pollutants to which all states must adhere.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA is also seeking some way to fairly apportion the costs
of waste disposal and other anti-pollution programs among the major
players in the poultry industry. The big food processors have
dumped the problem on the farmers who raise the chickens. But the
farmers do not have the money to dispose of the byproducts
properly. The federal and state governments could help as well,
perhaps by underwriting new disposal techniques and by providing
subsidies to get the waste to other parts of the country where it
could be used more effectively.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration among scientists, private organizations and
the government to restore the oysters, as well as the land
acquisition agreement, could serve as models for the poultry
industry. Unless the farm runoff problem is solved, Chesapeake Bay
could take another step backward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
