<HEADER>
A2664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STRANDED-SHIP-NYT &LR;      08-10 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STRANDED-SHIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANDED FREIGHTER OFF NEW YORK FINALLY GETS ORDERS AND CARGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Ukrainian freighter that had floated in limbo in
New York Harbor for four months, without orders and at times almost
out of provisions, is scheduled to take on cargo Wednesday morning
and head off to the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The ship, the Banner of October, will pick up 260 used cars and
trucks at the Howland Hook Container Terminal on Staten Island and
then transport them to the Dominican Republic and Haiti, said
Vladimir Shamshin, U.S. representative for Azov Shipping
International, a state-owned company based in the Ukrainian port of
Mariupol.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard and the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey, which owns the Howland Hook terminal, confirmed the ship's
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The 458-foot, 3,900-ton vessel arrived in the area on April 13
after its last delivery of cars and trucks to the two countries, a
round trip it had been making every two weeks for two years,
company officials said. But the ship got caught in limbo without
pay and provisions for the 26-member crew because of the shipping
company's bureaucratic procedures and some canceled shipments.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the years I've been in business, I've never seen
something so disarrayed,'' said Louis Spano, owner of Bayway
Shipping International, an export company in Elizabeth, N.J., that
chartered the Banner of October for Wednesday's scheduled shipment.
``They're good people, just everything's got to go back to their
country. If they had a better communications system with their home
country, I think they'd be better off.''
</P>
<P>
   Bohdan Yaremenko, the Ukrainian consul in New York, conceded
that the company's rigid procedures might have contributed to the
ship's scheduling and supply problems. However, Yaremenko insisted
that the ship's problems were not symptomatic of any fundamental
financial problems with the shipping company or his government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to some financial regulations, all money that they receive
from the ship, they transfer to the Ukraine, and then the company
sends the money back, and so on and so on,'' Yaremenko said.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard inspectors who boarded the Banner of October on July
31 deemed it to be in good shape, with the crew in equally
satisfactory condition. But there was only two to three days' worth
of food on board, and the air-conditioning was not working in the
midst of a heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   A charitable group that works closely with the Coast Guard, the
Seamen's Church Institute in New York, was called upon to deliver
emergency provisions.
</P>
<P>
   But others say the ship and the company have long had trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jean R. Smith, managing director of the Seamen's Church
Institute, said Azov had left dozens of ships in dire straits
around the world. Ms. Smith said that she was satisfied that there
was a lasting supply of food on board but that she remain concerned
about the health of the crew's 23 men and three women and hoped to
board the ship Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Taras Szczur, commander of the Ukrainian-American Veterans Post
301 in Yonkers, which has sent hundreds of pounds of meat, rice and
other provisions to the ship since last week, said the post carried
out a similar mission for another Azov ship, the Mikhail Stenko, on
April 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the second time we've done that this year, the same
company, different ship,'' said Szczur, a former Marine Corps
sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Coast Guard, the Seamen's Church Institute and
the Ukrainian Consulate have begun monitoring another Azov ship,
the Viktor Talilikhin, which dropped anchor three miles off shore
on Aug. 2, after Shamshin said it returned from a delivery of cars
and trucks in the Caribbean. The ship has no orders at the moment,
he said. It received provisions on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Spano, the exporter, said he would make sure the Banner of
October was loaded and departed Wednesday. ``I'll pay the
overtime,'' he said. ``This ship has got to get out of here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
