<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boone's 4 RBIs fend off Astros
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the second consecutive game, the Braves found some
late-inning offense and another unlikely hero to beat the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on two Houston errors in the seventh inning, Bret
Boone hit a two-run double down the left field line to break a 4-4
tie. Boone, who sat out the previous game with offensive struggles,
hit a two-run homer in the first inning to help the Braves take a
3-0 lead and finished with four RBIs in the 6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves used their fifth win in six games to keep first place
over the Mets for another day. The Braves moved to 5-1 against the
team with the best pitching numbers in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   They benefited from a pair of defensive breakdowns by the Astros
in the seventh. Shortstop Ricky Gutierrez let a Jose Hernandez
grounder scoot under his glove to start the inning. Hernandez stole
second and took third on an Ozzie Guillen sacrifice attempt. On
that play, third baseman Russ Johnson's throw to first sailed high,
giving the Braves runners at first and third with nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Boone's go-ahead hit made a winner out of Tom Glavine (10-9),
who got above .500 for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine spent the fifth inning wondering what's happening to him
this year. He had given up two singles to start the inning, then
got a double-play ball off the bat of Craig Biggio back to the
mound. But shortstop Jose Hernandez fielded his throw a few steps
from second base, failed to step on the bag and threw to first, but
the throw was late. So the bases were loaded, and Glavine proceeded
to give up three runs. Andruw Jones made another great catch on the
run to hold Derek Bell to a sacrifice fly, but the Astros had their
first lead, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine hadn't lost to the Astros since Aug. 21, 1995, going 6-0
with a 1.60 ERA in eight starts since, including his fourth win
this season on June 15 in Houston. He got a second chance when Ryan
Klesko homered off Reynolds in the bottom of the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
