<SLUG> BC-BAUER-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAUER SAYS BUSH MOCKED TEXAS WOMAN WHO WAS PUT TO DEATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate Gary Bauer criticized Gov.
George W. Bush on Tuesday for making fun of an executed Texas woman
in an interview Bush gave to Talk magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is nothing short of unbelievable that the governor
of a major state running for president thought it was acceptable to
mock a woman he decided to put to death,'' Bauer said of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign aides said the Talk writer ``misread'' Bush and
said the governor never has taken the death penalty lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is portrayed in Talk as ridiculing pickax killer Karla Faye
Tucker of Houston for an interview she did with CNN broadcaster
Larry King shortly before she was executed last year. Just before
her execution date, Tucker appealed for clemency on the grounds
that she had become a born-again Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities, anti-death penalty activists and Christian
activists pressured Bush to ask the state Board of Pardons and
Paroles to grant Tucker clemency. Bush declined.
</P>
<P>
   In the Talk interview, Bush said he did not meet with any of the
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't meet with Larry King either when he came down for
it,'' Bush told the magazine. ``I watched his interview with
(Tucker), though. He asked her real difficult questions, like,
`What would you say to Governor Bush?'''
</P>
<P>
   The Talk reporter asked how she answered.
</P>
<P>
   ```Please,' Bush whimpers, his lips pursed in mock desperation,
`don't kill me,''' according to the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine went on to say no such exchange occurred between
King and Tucker in the interview that aired on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to call yourself a compassionate
conservative, you might want to look up the meaning of
compassion,'' Bauer said at a Des Moines, Iowa, news conference
four days before the Iowa straw poll of Republican presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said Bush's magazine comments were ``inappropriate,
disgusting and profoundly disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Tucker and her lover used a pickax to kill a male
acquaintance and a woman with whom he was in bed. Tucker told
police that she experienced sexual pleasure every time she drove
the ax into her victims.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Karen Hughes said Talk writer Tucker Carlson
``captured the fact that Governor Bush is a warm, down-to-earth and
engaging person, yet in several ways the writer also misread the
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush's decision in the Tucker case was ``difficult
and emotional.'' She said the writer ``must have misread'' Bush's
reaction to his question about Tucker's execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush did not and would not ever make fun of the
serious and difficult responsibility of enforcing the death
penalty,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer also criticized comments Bush made about abortion in the
Talk interview, which was conducted this spring and published this
month. The magazine asked Bush if the number of abortions was up or
down in Texas during his term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ```I don't know,' he shrugs, sounding as though he genuinely
doesn't. `Probably down. Not because of anything we've done,
though. We haven't passed any laws.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, who has vowed to work for the outlawing of abortion if
elected, called Bush's comments ``cavalier,'' adding, ``I do not
believe he is serious about the sanctity of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Since granting the spring interview, Bush has signed legislation
requiring parents to be notified before their minor daughters can
receive an abortion. It takes effect Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Another unusual aspect of the Talk article is that Bush is twice
quoted as using the profanity ``f---'' in answering questions. A
third quote using the word is attributed to Bush, recounting an
exchange between him and former Texas Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, when asked about the governor's language, said: ``That's
between him and his mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said no one who was present for the interviews remembers
Bush using the foul language.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
