 SF CHRON  
 2 Auditors Charged in Fraud Case  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The Securities and Exchange Commission yesterday charged two former
auditors of California Micro Devices with failing to investigate
shady accounting practices by the Milpitas chipmaker.
<P>
   In an administrative action, the SEC said Michael Marrie and
Brian Berry, two auditors from the Phoenix office of the former
Coopers &AMP; Lybrand, ignored obvious irregularities in Cal Micro's
1994 financial statements, such as a write-off of about a third of
the company's accounts receivable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We allege they had red flags in front of them and didn't
respond with appropriate professional skepticism,'' said Helene
Morrison, the SEC's assistant district administrator in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Micro was the target of a series of civil and criminal legal
proceedings charging the company and several of its officers with
falsifying financial results. Last year, Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer Chan Desaigoudar and another executive were
convicted of securities fraud and sentenced to prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC is not accusing the auditors of being parties to the
fraud. Instead, the agency is bringing the case to reinforce the
point that auditors should act vigorously when they find evidence
of accounting irregularities, Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Perlis, a Los Angeles attorney representing Marrie and
Berry, said that the two acted appropriately, but that Cal Micro
provided them false information. ``My clients were victims of a
fraud,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be heard by an SEC administrative law judge. The
two auditors, who no longer work for Coopers' successor company,
PricewaterhouseCoopers, could be censured or barred from practicing
before the SEC if they are found to have violated professional
standards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of SEC11 (92166 ) &QL;
