<SLUG> BC-SALON-SALON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Salon.com Stock Plunges On News of Earnings Loss  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Salon.com, the San Francisco online magazine that went public in
June, saw its stock tumble more than 21 percent yesterday after
reporting a hefty loss in its first-ever quarterly earnings
statement.
<P>
   On a day when Internet and tech shares took a hammering almost
straight across the board, Salon's fall was particularly steep. The
company's stock closed $1.88 lower at $6.88.
</P>
<P>
   This is below Salon's initial price of $10.50 and well off its
high of $15.12.
</P>
<P>
   While the company's revenues doubled in the quarter ended June
30, it announced late Monday that losses before a special one-time
dividend payment more than tripled to $4.6 million from $1.4
million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're growing our infrastructure to be a significant content
player,'' said Todd Hagen, Salon's chief financial officer. ``It's
about us expanding our operations.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to a surge in traffic to the site, which hit 1.3
million visitors in the latest quarter, compared with 567,000 a
year earlier. Page views in the period more than doubled to 47
million.
</P>
<P>
   Salon's bruising in the market yesterday also may stem from a
perception that the company's business model, which relies heavily
on advertising for revenues, may not prove competitive in an
e-commerce-dominated world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great content isn't enough,'' said John Hannon, an analyst
with Security Capital Trading in New York. ``How are you going to
make your money?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very `nichey,' and everyone else is going mass
market,'' said Rob Martin, an analyst at Friedman, Billings, Ramsey
in Arlington, Va. ``It's all about branding, and I don't see that
Salon is branded as the go-to place on the Net for information.''
</P>
<P>
   Hold on there, countered Hagen. Although ads and sponsorship
deals accounted for about 60 percent of $1 million in quarterly
revenues, he noted that e-commerce transactions comprised 20
percent of sales, with the remainder coming from syndication,
subscription fees and book deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the foundation of this wonderful content, but we're
using it as a steppingstone stepping stone  &LR; to other revenue
sources,'' Hagen said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to discuss future earnings projections but noted
that spending will increase on marketing efforts. A TV campaign is
scheduled to debut in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Salon's total quarterly loss, including an IPO-related dividend
payment of $11.52 million ($7.20 a share) reached $16.1 million.
This may have contributed to investors' jittery feelings about the
stock, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as Salon's share price keeps heading south, some
believe the likelihood is increasing that the content-rich site
could be snapped up by a larger media enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought they make an attractive acquisition
target,'' said Friedman's Martin. ``That's still the case.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
