<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINUX-LINUX </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Linux Expo Draws Support from Intel, IBM  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Linux, the upstart free alternative to Microsoft's Windows
operating systems, continues to win endorsements from the giants of
business computing.
<P>
   At LinuxWorld Expo, a trade show and conference that opened
yesterday in San Jose, almost every major player this side of
Redmond, Wash. _ including erstwhile Microsoft allies Intel and IBM
_ pledged new support for Linux. The three-day show is expected to
draw 12,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Chairman Andy Grove put in a surprise appearance during
the conference's opening keynote, delivered by Sean Maloney, a
senior vice president at the chipmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney showed Linux running on a software simulation of Merced,
a powerful new microprocessor Intel is expected to start shipping
next year.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Intel will provide prototype Merced-based machines
so developers can write and test software for the new chip over the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   IBM said its Global Services division will offer a variety of
consulting and support programs for businesses that choose Linux.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company promised to adapt several widely used
network-management programs from its Tivoli Systems subsidiary to
run on Linux. It also said it will work to develop Linux software
with SAP, a German company that is a leading supplier of software
that corporations customize for their own applications.to develop
Linux software. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Corel, the Canadian company best known for its WordPerfect
program, previewed a new version of Linux that it plans to release
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Corel hopes to market its new version, which features easy
installation and a Windows-like user interface, for use on desktop
computers that now typically run Windows 95 or 98. So far, Linux
has succeeded mainly as an alternative to Windows NT or Unix
operating systems on large server computers.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle said it would ship WebDB 2.0 for Linux. The database
publishing program, previously available for other computer
systems, is designed for e-commerce operations and other sites that
display material stored in databases.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola Computer Group, a leader in marketing ``embedded''
computers to drive manufacturing and telecommunications systems,
unveiled a strategy under which it will offer an array of
Linux-based products and services to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Among dozens of other exhibitors, Penguin Computing, a San
Francisco company that sells hardware to run Linux, showed the
first Linux systems based on Advanced Micro Devices' Athlon, a new
high-performance microprocessor released just  &LR; this week. Penguin
demonstrated its systems running ``clustering'' software, a
technology that allows Web sites to combine multiple machines into
one large system that can keep functioning even if one of its
constituent computers fails.
</P>
<P>
   The show, held at the San Jose Convention Center, also had its
lighter notes. Images of penguins, the Linux symbol, were
everywhere, and one company, Magic Software, even showed a live and
clearly disoriented penguin at its booth every hour on the hour.
</P>
<P>
   A new nonprofit called the Linux Fund solicited customers for
its penguin-bedecked credit card, which it said is was  &LR; one of
several ways it aims to raise money to provide scholarships and
other support for open-source developers.
</P>
<P>
   Linux is distributed free online or at low cost by a variety of
companies and organizations under terms known as ``open source,''
where anyone can obtain and modify the underlying code. Last year,
it accounted for 17.2 percent of new licenses of operating software
for servers _ computers that run Web sites or provide data to
corporate networks _ according to preliminary figures from
International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
