<SLUG> BC-IMPACT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPERS FEEL `IMPACT' OF NEW SCHOOL CONSTRUCTION  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By EDYTHE JENSEN  
 and KELLY PEARCE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona cities can make developers pay extra to support
construction of new schools, a judge ruled Tuesday in the first
round of a battle that could change school funding in the state.
</P>
<P>
   An official of Apache Junction, the victor in Tuesday's ruling,
immediately called upon other Arizona cities to start levying their
own school development fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for other cities to join us, to push forward so that
the larger community will benefit,'' City Manager Curtis Shook
said.
</P>
<P>
   But some civic leaders said they prefer to wait for higher court
decisions, and Peoria Mayor John Keegan _ husband of State School
Superintendent Lisa Graham-Keegan _ said it's inappropriate for
cities to levy school impact fees regardless of the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Graham-Keegan rankled school officials last month when she
testified as a witness for the home builders against Apache
Junction.
</P>
<P>
   Her spokeswoman, Laura Penny, said Keegan stands by her
testimony and has nothing more to add following Tuesday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In his 27-page decision, Pinal County Superior Court Judge James
Don wrote that schools are a ``proper public purpose'' under the
Arizona law that allows general impact fees.
</P>
<P>
   Previous legislative attempts to add school fees to state
statues have failed, and home builders argued the existing state
law prohibited them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Public schools are fundamental to a community,'' Don wrote.
``Any shortage of space for schools is ultimately a problem to the
whole community.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Skinner, whose daughter will be a first grader at Gold
Canyon Elementary School in Apache Junction, was savoring the
moment on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, she picketed the home builders outside the
courthouse in Florence. ``I'm glad he (the judge) saw the law this
way. It's refreshing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Don's decision is not the final word. Charles Herf, attorney for
the Home Builders Association of Central Arizona, is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case that is going all the way to the Arizona
Supreme Court,'' Herf said. ``The judge was well aware that the
party who did not prevail will appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   R.L. Brown, a marketing consultant for home builders, said he
was surprised and disappointed by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The developer is not going to lose one nickel out of his
pocket over this. Consumers will pay,'' Brown said. `` They'll
either pay more money for the same house or get less house for the
same money. Either way, they lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Apache Junction Mayor Douglas Coleman said without the fees,
existing residents would have to subsidize growth with higher
taxes, and that's not fair. He and Shook are hopeful the home
builders will tell Herf not to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing is short-sighted and against something
that's beneficial to the communities where they build houses,''
Shook said of the builders.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa resident Don Lux came to the Trend Homes development in
Apache Junction Tuesday to shop for a house in the $130,000 to
140,000 price range. He said the ruling might make him reconsider
Gilbert and Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the city's responsibility to manage their money better,''
Lux said. ``I shouldn't have to be penalized.''
</P>
<P>
   George LaRose, who bought a retirement home last week, said he
shouldn't have had to pay the school fees. ``Why should senior
citizens have to pay for someone else's kids?''
</P>
<P>
   If the home builders prevail, Apache Junction will have to
return the fees to homeowners under city law.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in Gilbert and Queen Creek said they're ready to start
looking at school development fees in light of Tuesday's ruling,
but may want to delay implementing them until the home builders'
appeals are exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert, which has seen its population go from 5,000 in 1980 to
more than 100,000 today, could be a prime candidate for school
fees, Councilwoman Maggie Cathey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of education is definitely affected by growth,''
Cathey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense for us to begin looking at school impact fees
now,'' Queen Creek Councilman Scott Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Because evaluation of fees and required public hearings take
months, Queen Creek should start the process now to be ready to
implement school fees if the high courts rule in Apache Junction's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   William Farrell, attorney representing Apache Junction in the
school fee case, is also Queen Creek's municipal lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale is in the process of writing an ``adequate school
facilities'' law that could give school officials more say in the
number of developments coming into their districts.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale City Manager Marty Vanacour said Don's ruling is likely
to strengthen that city's legal position.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise Mayor Joan Shafer, whose city is in the fast-growing
Dysart School District, said, ``I've always said that if it is
declared legal to do it that we will look into it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dysart School Board publicly supported Apache Junction in
the lawsuit, and filed a ``friend of the court brief'' in Pinal
County.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first victory but we can't celebrate yet because
of strong likelihood that it will be appealed,'' Dysart
superintendent Margo Seck said.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache Junction fees, which took effect in March 1998, add
$1,368 to the cost of a new house, $366 to a new mobile home and
$276 to a new apartment unit. They bring the total city development
fees to $2,374 per house.
</P>
<P>
   That compares to Avondale's $5,495 per house, Gilbert's $4,803,
Chandler's $4,974 and Queen Creek's $7,300 per house. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
