<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILK-MILK </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Milk Ruling May Not Lead to Watered-Down Prices  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Californians shouldn't hold their breaths waiting for milk prices
to drop, despite Monday's ruling that allows less-expensive milk to
be sold here, industry and consumer experts said yesterday.
<P>
   The state Court of Appeals in San Diego ruled Monday that
California must lift its long-standing ban on milk that fails to
meet strict state nutritional standards _ as long as the milk
complies with looser federal standards and is accurately labeled.
</P>
<P>
   California is the only state with higher standards for milk than
those mandated by the federal government. California law requires a
higher percentage of milk solids, which boosts the content of
protein and calcium. But the fortified milk also is pricier.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, if it stands, would allow both California-based and
out-of-state processors to sell cheaper, unenriched milk here, a
change that should lead to lower prices at retail.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision hardly is set in stone. The California
Department of Food and Agriculture, the defendant in the lawsuit,
is weighing an appeal to the California Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   If the high court were to accept an appeal, it easily could take
more than a year for the matter to be resolved. There is no appeal
process beyond the state Supreme Court, said Michael Vergara, the
lawyer for Shamrock Foods Co., the appellant.
</P>
<P>
   Processors are unlikely to rejigger their operations until the
legal maneuvering is completed, which means that current milk
prices and availability could remain in place for quite a while.
</P>
<P>
   But even if no appeal is made and Monday's ruling goes into
effect quickly, there is no certainty that prices will decline.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, California's muscular dairy lobby is expected to
push for legislation that would undo Monday's decision and
explicitly ban the sale of unfortified milk here.
</P>
<P>
   The California Legislature already has watered down two bills
introduced this session that would have facilitated the sale of
unenriched milk. ``We're not going to roll over easy on this one,''
said Bob Feenstra, head lobbyist for the Milk Producers Council,
which represents dairies.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is competition: It is not clear how many
out-of-state dairies are interested in entering California, the
largest milk-producing state.
</P>
<P>
   Shamrock of Phoenix, the biggest processor in Arizona, has been
fighting California regulators and processors for years. Shamrock
did business in California in the early 1990s, before it was kicked
out under an earlier court decision. But Shamrock sold milk mostly
to hotels and restaurants _ not to grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Shamrock isn't certain it could offer large
discounts because its transportation costs would be higher than
those of in-state processors, said Shamrock spokeswoman Ann Puelz
Ocana, the company's director of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers Union, an advocacy group at the forefront of the
milk-price wars, is dubious that Monday's decision will have much
of an impact on prices because milk sales continue to be dominated
by a few large supermarket chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historical and current data show most fluid milk is sold to
consumers in California at prices that are much higher than
competition would dictate,'' said Elisa Odabashian, senior policy
analyst at Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``When farm prices have gone up, retailers have raised it that
much or more. When farm prices go down, they have historically not
passed that along to consumers,'' said Odabashian.
</P>
<P>
   One change consumers can expect, if Monday's ruling remains in
effect, is a choice of both fortified and unfortified milk at
grocery stores _ a situation already enjoyed in the other 49
states.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear whether two tiers of milk would result in
lower prices. ``This opens up the possibility that supermarkets
could start charging even more for the milk we've had all along
because it provides more nutrition than the new stuff,'' said
Odabashian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think consumers are probably not going to have meaningful
gains from this, either financially or nutritionally,'' Odabashian
said. ``But I don't know, on the other hand, if they will be
greatly harmed, other than to be confused'' about the differences
between fortified and unfortified milk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
