r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCENT-LUCENT_SFCHRON     08-10 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-LUCENT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Lucent to Buy Sunnyvale's INS For $3.6 Billion  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Lucent Technologies said yesterday that it has agreed to buy
Sunnyvale's International Networking Services for $3.6 billion in
stock, a move that will bolster Lucent's push into the growing
field of network consulting.
<P>
   INS advises companies on how to design, integrate and run
next-generation networks capable of handling voice, video and data
traffic. Buying INS will allow Lucent to move beyond selling gear
to companies and into helping businesses select, install and use
the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent of New Jersey will pay 0.8473 share, or about $54, for
each share of INS, about a 14 percent premium over Monday's closing
price.
</P>
<P>
   INS said no layoffs were planned for its 2,200 employees, about
700 of whom are in California. In fact, the company said it plans
to hire an additional 1,000 engineers.
</P>
<P>
   INS will become part of Lucent's NetCare division. NetCare,
which currently has 3,300 employees who provide support to Lucent
customers, will be based in Sunnyvale and headed by INS President
and Chief Executive Officer John Drew.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers said the acquisition will help Lucent as it
looks for ways to get a leg up on competitors such as Cisco Systems
and Nortel Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent and its competitors are in a race to provide gear to
companies that want to build state-of-the-art networks. Phone
companies, financial institutions and other businesses are looking
for ways to integrate their voice and data networks so that they
can offer new services and save money by routing traffic more
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Before doing this, however, many businesses look to companies
like INS for help designing, building and maintaining a network.
INS recommends what type of equipment to buy, how to deploy a
network and provides continuing support.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much new technology coming to market, and from the
customer's point of view, it's an incredibly difficult challenge in
being able to assess and identify the right products to give them
the solutions they need,'' said Michael Davies, an analyst with
Punk, Ziegel &AMP; Co. in New York. ``If Lucent's able to provide a
company with a road map, it gives Lucent an advantage over its
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   INS, which has clients ranging from Microsoft to Compaq, also
will give Lucent access to a broad and lucrative customer base. The
network services industry is growing at a fast clip, and sales are
expected to reach $90 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the relationship between INS and Lucent may be a bit tricky
because INS recommends all types of gear to companies, not just
Lucent products.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, INS has had a strong relationship with Cisco, which
owns about 8 percent of INS.
</P>
<P>
   Drew of INS said the company's relationship with Cisco will
change significantly, but he added that the NetCare unit will be
``objective'' when recommending vendors and won't hesitate to
suggest Cisco products if that's the best route.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to continue to recommend the best network,
regardless of who makes the equipment,'' said Drew. ``Lucent
recognizes this and was bold enough to make this move.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew said a deal with Cisco didn't materialize because the San
Jose networking giant doesn't want an internal network support
group. Instead, Cisco farms out its network support to companies
like INS.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cisco said it was investing $1 billion in KPMG, the
accounting firm, to offer more online and networking services to
businesses. Industry watchers said wind of Lucent's pending deal
with INS probably pushed Cisco to make the investment.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Russo, an executive vice president with Lucent, said Lucent
did a deal with INS because of the company's expertise in the
network services area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customer demand for this kind of capability has been
outstripping our ability to provide services,'' Russo said.
``Service and support is a core part of the value that we bring to
our customers, and you can't be a leader ... without a coherent
networking services strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Pyykkonen of CIBC World Markets, said INS, which has
expertise in a technology called Internet Protocol, also will help
Lucent with its recent acquisition of Nexabit Networks. IP is a
standard for moving voice, video and data in packets across
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Nexabit makes high-speed switches that move data traffic on
telecommunications networks. Lucent agreed to pay nearly $900
million in stock for Nexabit last June.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
