<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SGI-SGI </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 SGI to Cut Jobs, Sell Cray Unit  
 By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silicon Graphics Inc., a foundering maker of computer
workstations, said yesterday that it will slash jobs, dramatically
restructure its business, sell off its Cray supercomputer unit and
enter a series of strategic alliances as part of a wide-ranging
recovery plan.
</P>
<P>
   SGI said it will redefine its focus to concentrate on high-end
servers to deliver rich content, such as video, over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   SGI employs about 9,000 workers, one-third of them at its
Mountain View headquarters. The company said it plans to cut
anywhere from 1,000 to 1,500 jobs and reassign an additional 1,500
employees as it spins off large chunks of its business and forms
new joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kelly, a senior vice president at SGI, said the layoffs
largely will come from sales, marketing and administrative areas.
He said SGI plans to cast a smaller geographical net as it focuses
almost exclusively on its 200 biggest customers.
</P>
<P>
   That will mean closing offices around the world and
consolidating the sales force. ``Today, we operate in 30-plus
countries,'' Kelly said. ``We don't need to be in all those
places.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said some SGI Mountain View employees also would be
targeted for downsizing. Restructuring has become a way of life at
SGI, which first began its turnaround efforts more than a year ago.
An industrywide slowdown in the supercomputer and server computer
markets have hampered past initiatives. SGI's stock has fallen
about 49 percent during the past five years, while the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index has almost tripled and the S&AMP;P computer index has
risen sixfold.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its current restructuring plans, SGI will:
</P>
<P>
   _Sell its Cray division, which makes supercomputers that are
used primarily by the scientific community. SGI purchased Cray in
1996 for $740 million, but analysts said the company was unable to
grow the operation.
</P>
<P>
   _Create a new business unit that will focus on making Internet
appliances that can deliver streaming media applications, such as
movies-on-demand, to the consumer market. SGI chief executive Rick
Belluzzo said more than 90 million households now have superfast
connections to the Internet and are waiting for systems that can
deliver complex video and voice files to their personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   _Form a new joint venture to manage SGI's line of lower-end
workstations that run on the Windows NT platform. Analysts said SGI
has failed to penetrate this market and is looking to a partner,
such as Dell Computer Corp., to assume responsibility for the
business and to rustle up new customers.
</P>
<P>
   _Move away from proprietary chips and operating systems for its
computer workstations. Instead of building these features itself,
SGI said future workstations will sport Intel chips and the Linux
operating system. SGI's workstations are famous for their roles in
the creation of such films as ``Jurassic Park,'' ``A Bug's Life''
and the recently released ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut.''
</P>
<P>
   SGI said both software developers and the world at large are
adopting Linux at record rates. By supporting Linux, SGI believes
that its computers will be much more attractive to potential
customers. There are 1 million new Linux users every month,
according to SGI.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are focused on building a strong foundation and putting the
company back on the path of profitability,'' said Belluzzo. After
seven consecutive losing quarters, SGI finally posted a net profit
of $158 million on revenue of $829 million for the fourth quarter
of fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The investment community, however, reacted negatively to the
news. SGI's stock fell 23 percent, to $12.44, in yesterday's
trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed the market reacted the way it did,'' said
SGI's Kelly. ``But that does not put into question the value of
what we are doing. We are not (restructuring) for the short-term
stock pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, analysts believe that SGI might be heading down the
right road. By spinning off Cray and its NT workstation divisions,
as well as phasing out its own chip and operating system
development efforts, the company can concentrate on the more
successful parts of its business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top line is that SGI wanted to be a competitive producer
of everything from supercomputers to high-end server to commodity
Intel workstations, and that didn't serve them well,'' said Matthew
Nordan, an analyst at Forrester Research. ``They've decided to
focus on core competency instead, and I think that will yield them
some long-term gains.''
</P>
<P>
   But some SGI employees worry that the latest round of layoffs
and restructuring may be a case of too little, too little.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the kind of painful decisions that should have been
made two or three years ago,'' said one SGI worker. ``I guess it's
better that it's being done now rather than never. We've really
been spread thin for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
