<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY BETTING ON `RACE UNITY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LORI RODRIGUEZ 
and ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley told
blacks gathered Tuesday in Houston that he is banking his White
House chances on the belief that most Americans yearn to close the
racial divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race unity is not a political position for me, it's who I am
and what I believe,'' the former New Jersey senator told the annual
conference of the National Urban League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm staking this presidential campaign on the conviction that
way over 50 to 60 percent of the American people, including white
Americans, want to move ahead to a brighter day when people are
seen not by the color of their skin or the shape of their eyes but
by who they are; that people yearn for the same racial harmony and
unity that I do.''
</P>
<P>
   In a low-keyed speech laced with personal accounts of his
childhood, Bradley criticized the Clinton administration for
failing to sufficiently move children, minorities and the homeless
out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seven years of a Democratic administration the
percentage of American children living in poverty has barely
blipped down,'' said Bradley, who is Vice President Al Gore's only
competition for their party's presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year after the welfare reform bill, which I voted against,
there was a 29 percent increase of children living in deep poverty.
That's half the poverty level.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a former New York Knicks basketball star and Rhodes
scholar, was warmly introduced by league Executive Director Hugh B.
Price as ``a white guy who can jump and is a straight shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was the third candidate in as many days to troll for
votes among the 4,000 conferees meeting at the George R. Brown
Convention Center in Houston. Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
front-runner for the Republican nomination, welcomed the group
Sunday night; Gore, the Democratic front-runner, addressed a Monday
luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley repeatedly jabbed at the Clinton-Gore
administration, the vice president in his speech deplored the same
litany of social ills, including the high number of uninsured
children, the dire need for better schools and persistent crimes of
hate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did score with warm accounts of his childhood in Crystal
City, Mo., ``a small town of 3,492 people on the banks of the
Mississippi River.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a town that had 96 in my high school graduating class
and one stop light. It was a multiethnic, multiracial factory town;
a town where the Little League was integrated before the schools
were integrated,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a town where as a Little League baseball player in
regional playoffs, we stayed in third-rate motels because the
African-Americans on our team couldn't stay in the first-rate
hotels and the rest of us weren't going to leave our teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, Bradley said, he asked his father, who worked
his way up from a starting position at the small town bank to
majority shareholder of the bank, of what he was most proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the proudest moment was that, throughout the Great
Depression, he never foreclosed on a single home,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other bit of wisdom he conveyed was that you could never
tell by a person's skin color how they were going to repay their
loans; that character was important and was found everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that the future of white Americans is inextricably bound
to the future of the non-white Americans who will constitute a
majority of the work force in the new millennium, Bradley took
another poke at President Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why have our leaders waited just until recently to even use
the word `poverty,' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This I know for sure: Timid leadership and the silence of good
people have caused us to risk losing yet another generation; a
generation that won't participate or benefit from the new economy
that is emerging. ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is morally unacceptable and economically perilous to
continue this course.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bradley campaigned to about 125 Houston Democrats at a
reception in the foyer of the Ensemble Theater near downtown.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is seeking the Democratic nomination ``in a little
different way'' by running a grass-roots operation and knocking on
voters' doors in key primary states such as Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds like a city council race in Houston, doesn't it?'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bradley was escorted to the event by Houston Councilman
Carroll Robinson, one of the first elected officials in the country
to endorse Bradley over Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Answering the audience's questions about policy issues, Bradley
said most of the federal budget surplus should be used to pay down
the federal debt. That would have a bigger impact on the national
economy than the tax cuts being favored by Republicans, he said. If
tax cuts are offered at all, they should go first to the poorest
taxpayers, he continued.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign staff billed the meeting as a conversation
with black preachers and minority leaders. But after the local
Democratic Party invited any and all of its supporters, the meeting
produced a mostly white audience. Several people said they came to
check out Bradley and decide if they will vote for him or Gore in
the March primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's remarks at the Urban League came a few hours after a
gunman opened fire in the lobby of a suburban Los Angeles Jewish
Community Center, wounding five people, including three young boys
attending day camp. That prompted a repeat of his pledge to ban the
sale of cheap guns known as ``Saturday night specials'' if elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time somebody stood up to the National Rifle
Association,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   The 89th annual league, which ends today, will hold a town
meeting this morning called ``The Police and People of Color: Can't
we all just get along?''
</P>
<P>
   Among those scheduled to participate is lawyer Johnnie Cochran,
who defended O.J. Simpson in his murder trial, activist Al Sharpton
and Mayor Lee Brown, a former police chief.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
