<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2797 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-GROW_SFCHRON &LR;      08-10 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Landing VC Cash for A Startup 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I am developing an Internet business and am interested in
getting venture capital financing. But I have neither a startup
track record nor financial contacts. Can you provide some
suggestions?
<P>
   A: There are a number of books and Web sites that dispense
information on venture capital (private equity from institutional
investors) and angel capital (money from wealthy individuals).
Venture Capital Resource Library (www.vfinance.com) has news about
recent deals, links to dozens of venture capital firms and
information about their investments, areas of focus and partners.
</P>
<P>
   Another place to start is www.garage.com, which has practical
information about writing business plans and winning venture
capital as well as links to other sites.
</P>
<P>
   Articles and Web sites typically tout success stories and
virtues of venture capital. What they often don't say is how
incredibly difficult it is to win millions of dollars of venture
capital backing and ultimately graduate to the public markets with
a successful IPO.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mayfield Fund of Menlo Park reviews approximately
4,000 startup ideas each year before funding 20 or 30. That means
only half a percent to three-quarters of 1 percent of applications
get accepted, which is a tougher admissions policy than Stanford or
Harvard. And only about half of those that win financing ever
graduate to the public markets or get acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Located on Sand Hill Road, the Wall Street of private equity
financing, Mayfield and its competitors are bombarded by business
plans. Mayfield General Partner Kevin Fong figures that he and 13
other partners go through 20 pitches a week, about double the
number they received three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He offers these pointers to those seeking VC dollars:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Executive summaries &LR; . Make the executive summary of your business
plan short and compelling, no more than two to 10 pages. Fong says
he and his colleagues take one to 15 minutes to decide whether an
idea makes the first cut. You will need to clearly define your
innovative product and its market potential, your management team,
key risk factors and what you need to do to create a success.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Think big &LR; . Blue-chip venture capital firms are interested in
paradigm shifts, killer apps and liquidity events (such as going
public). They want to stretch their invested time and millions of
dollars into billions. Me-too technology or ideas with limited
commercial potential are destined for the waste basket or delete
key.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in innovation and large opportunities,'' says
Fong. Mayfield, whose investment portfolio includes 3Com, Compaq
and Genentech, recently closed its 10th venture capital fund with
$450 million from institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Connections &LR; . The venture capital community is not an old boys'
club. (There are a lot of young guys, too, and a few women.) But
connections do help. Fong says his firm's comfort level is higher
if entrepreneurs are referred by Mayfield's network of
entrepreneurs, portfolio companies, service firms and friends. More
than 90 percent of companies that win financing from Mayfield go
this route.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Making contact &LR; . Do homework to find out which firms and partners
deal with your product or technology. Write or e-mail your
executive summary, and then let a few days go by before calling to
set up a meeting. If you are smart and lucky, you might get in the
door.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the questions Fong and other VCs will be
asking:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Does the company have a strong management team in place or will
the investors have to do the job themselves while they look for key
managers?
</P>
<P>
   _What kind of business model does the company have? Is it a
known/proven model or one that has not been tried before?
</P>
<P>
   _Is the market the company is going to enter an existing market?
If so, is it growing or shrinking? If it is a new market, does it
have the potential to be large?
</P>
<P>
   _How much technology risk is associated with the success or
failure of the company?
</P>
<P>
   _How would you use the VC? What unique contribution will the VC
provide in terms of strategy, people and a network of possible
partners?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VC FOR WOMEN: Springboard 2000, the first venture capital
conference for women entrepreneurs, is scheduled for Jan. 27, 2000,
at the Oracle Conference Center in Redwood City. Sponsored by the
National Women's Business Council and Forum for Women
Entrepreneurs, the event will let 25 West Coast female
entrepreneurs present their business plans to angel, venture and
corporate investors.
</P>
<P>
   The event seems well timed. Although women are starting
businesses at twice the rate of men, VentureOne says only 4 percent
of the information technology companies that receive VC financing
have a female CEO. For more information on the conference, call
(650) 357-0222 or call up www.springboard2000.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
