<DOCNO> NYT19990810.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2799 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENTURE-VENTURE_SFCHR     08-10 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-VENTURE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Startups Fetch Record Financing  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Kestrel Solutions, a Mountain View company named for an agile
falcon, landed the biggest venture capital investment of any Bay
Area company in the second quarter _ $55.5 million.
<P>
   Meanwhile Pets.com, a San Francisco online retailer of pet food
and other supplies, got its paws on $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The two were among 227 Bay Area companies that attracted more
than $2 billion in venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   Although the public's appetite for anything Internet may be
starting to slow, the financing of startups with a high-tech twist,
and perhaps a catchy name, still continues at a torrid pace.
Venture capital firms poured a record $6.8 billion into emerging
U.S. companies in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That was a whopping 46 percent more than VCs invested in the
first three months of 1999, according to VentureOne, a San
Francisco venture capital research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first six months of 1999, venture capital firms
invested $11.4 billion, or nearly 90 percent of the record $13
billion they invested during all of 1998,'' said Jean Yaremchuk,
vice president of research and technology at Venture One. ``And
last year was a record year.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Bay Area is the center of the venture capital
volcano. In the three months ended June 30, 227 local companies
received nearly double the $1.2 billion that 183 local startups
received in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The average investment jumped to nearly $9.4 million from $6.6
million as Internet and other companies required more capital to
grow quickly and build market share before competitors beat them to
it. Twenty-nine local companies received at least $20 million each
in venture financing, compared with 20 in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hottest Internet area is business-to-business services,''
said Mayfield Fund General Partner Kevin Fong. This includes making
communications connections, conducting financial transactions,
advertising, marketing, maintaining data files and tracking online
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Kestrel Solutions, a Mountain View fiber optic systems
developer, has raised more than $80 million over the past two
years, including $55.5 million during the past quarter from private
investors that included former Secretary of Defense Frank
Carlucci's Carlyle Group and BankAmerica Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Meldon Gafner said Kestrel Solutions' patented
technology allows it to pack 64 signals onto a single strand of
fiber optic cable instead of one. Kestrel's goal is to increase the
capacity of metropolitan communications networks without having to
dig up the streets to lay more cable.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies that raised major amounts of cash in the past
quarter include:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Pets.com  &LR; _ This San Francisco online provider of pet food,
supplies and information received $50 million in June from
Amazon.com, Bowman Capital and Hummer Winblad Venture Partners.
Pets.com CEO Julie Wainwright hopes to make her company the
Amazon.com of online pet supplies and is using the marketing
prowess of the No.1 Internet retailer, including Web page links and
e-mail access to its 10.7 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   Although about 35 percent of its current sales are dog food and
25 percent are cat food, Pets.com picks, packs and ships 12,000
products, ranging from the $5.69 Ferret Spongie Jumper to the $4.99
Repti Cage Carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Competition in the online pet category is heating up. Another
San Francisco startup that is going after the $23 billion-a-year
U.S. pet food and supply business is Petopia.com. The company
received $66 million in July from two strategic partners _ a unit
of France's Moet Hennessey Louis Vuitton and Petco, one of the
largest U.S. pet supply retailers.
</P>
<P>
   To wean customers from their neighborhood pet stores, both
Pets.com and Petopia are striving to establish online communities
where pet owners can chat and find information and free advice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Tavolo.  &LR; Formerly known as Digital Chef and located in St. Helena,
this online retailer of gourmet food and cooking products changed
its name to the Italian word for table last weekAug.4 &LR;  and migrated
to San Rafael. The online company, which was started last year to
provide everything for cooks, raised $35 million in the past
quarter. It stocks 5,000 items online as well as menus and other
information,
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Virtual Vineyards &LR; . This Palo Alto online retailer raised $30
million to establish a network of wholesalers and retailers to ship
wine legally to most U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Google Inc. &LR;  This next-generation Palo Alto Internet search engine
company raised $25 million from blue-chip VC firms that included
Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers and Sequoia Capital. Stanford
computer science graduates Sergey Brin and Larry Page started the
company last year and named it after the giant number ``googol,''
which is 1 followed by 100 zeros.
</P>
<P>
   Most venture capital investors hope to cash out of their
investments eventually when their offspring go public or get
acquired.
</P>
<P>
   According to Deloitte &AMP; Touche, 158 companies went public in the
second quarter of 1999, including a record 90 Internet-related
companies. The average seven-day price increase for these Internet
stocks from their offering price was an incredible 76 percent,
compared with just 18 percent for non-Internet IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   However, the tide seems to have turned, as many of the biggest
Internet stocks have taken major hits in the market since July.
Several recent Internet IPOs have performed poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Some, such as 1-800-Flowers.com, Quotesmith.com and Quokka
Sports, actually started trading below their offering prices. But
several other Internet-connected IPOs, including Chemdex, Packeteer
and Internet Capital Group (which invests in Internet startups),
still soared on their first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield Fund's Fong acknowledges that some Internet stocks may
have shot up simply because they had a ``dot com'' in their name.
But he believes that ``e-commerce is here to stay'' and sees some
market softening as a healthy sign. ``I want the public markets to
be more selective; it's not good if companies go out too early and
disappoint investors.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
