<HEADER>
A2808 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-2000-HNS &LR;      08-10 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE MAKES HER CASE IN IOWA AS WOMAN IN PIONEERING ROLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST DES MOINES, Iowa _ When Elizabeth Dole walked into a
community center Tuesday, the Republican presidential candidate
immediately launched into her well-rehearsed routine.
</P>
<P>
   She talked about sexism at Harvard Law School when she attended
the Ivy League institution in the 1960s. One professor had a
designated ``ladies' day,'' she said, when female students were
grilled in front of their classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Dole then related how several years later she won her first case
against a male prosecutor who was first in her class at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   By offering up these autobiographical tidbits, Dole hoped to
reinforce her credentials as a pioneering woman who has been
successful in her many endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   And campaigning this week in Iowa, Dole is banking on a resume
that includes several Cabinet posts and a stint as head of the
American Red Cross to bolster her chances in the first presidential
test this Saturday in the straw poll in Ames.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have 30 years of service to the public,'' she told the
crowd. ``I am not a seat warmer.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the candidate has denied that her gender alone should
be the deciding factor, the female factor inevitably makes it into
her carefully crafted speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next president, whoever SHE may be ... '' she repeatedly
tells audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the novelty of her effort and her impressive
credentials, Dole's campaign does not appear to be taking off.
Polls indicate she is falling further and further behind
front-runner George W. Bush. She has suffered from lackluster
fund-raising and poor organization.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say she failed to capitalize on the initial burst of
publicity after her resignation from the Red Cross last winter. And
Dole was even undercut by her husband, former Senate Republican
leader and 1996 presidential nominee Bob Dole, who said earlier
this year he might contribute to the campaign of one of his wife's
rivals, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. Dole also has predicted nothing
more encouraging for his wife than that there will be a Republican
president.
</P>
<P>
   While the former senator was back on the campaign trail last
week stumping for his wife, he may not have helped her cause. He
told one group his wife was not present because she was ``getting
her hair fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   While she draws large crowds, political observers are not clear
whether the many women who have come to hear her will participate
in the GOP primary rituals, including the straw poll in Ames this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Dole said she is not terribly concerned about the event's
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   While she dutifully asks her audiences to help her in Ames, she
also played down the significance of the straw poll, arguing that
its importance has been hyped by the media.
</P>
<P>
   Dole also said that her lackluster fund-raising is not a
disadvantage. ``The landscape is strewn with politicians with a lot
of money who didn't cross the finish line.''
</P>
<P>
   While she never mentioned Bush's impressive war chest, she noted
three other Texans who had a lot of money: Phil Gramm, Ross Perot
and John Connally, who never made it to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Dole first captivated the nation with her Oprah-style
performance during the 1996 Republican National Convention. And on
the campaign trail she has perfected a variation of that
much-watched performance. At each event, the perpetually smiling
candidate wanders out among her audience without notes and with a
microphone pinned to her blouse.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to specific issues, the candidate steers clear of
controversy and sticks to mainstream GOP positions, although
earlier in the campaign she staked out unique ground among GOP
candidates in calling for certain gun controls. She tells audience
that taxes need to be cut, wasteful spending eliminated and defense
spending increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pentagon has been reduced to a triangle. We have to build
it back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She called for a crackdown on drugs and for shipping federal
dollars back to the states for education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe you can manage schools by remote control from
Washington,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole shied away from the more controversial social issues that
have divided her party. Only in response to a specific question
does she reply that she opposes abortion except in the case of
rape, incest or if the pregnancy endangers the mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's candidacy clearly appeals to some women who believe that
gender makes a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time we have a woman president,'' said Christine
Holub, 23, who came to hear Dole at the West Des Moines Community
center.
</P>
<P>
   Holub said she was so excited about the candidate that she
dragged her mother to the forum.
</P>
<P>
   But Holub's mother, Pam Nelson, said she was not yet sold on
Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid a woman cannot be elected president,'' said Nelson,
53, who added that she thinks Bush has a more realistic chance of
winning back the White House for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
