<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER OF DISCONTENT FOR TOLEDO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bob Toledo recalls he was 12 years old when he
first cast a covetous eye on a career in coaching. By 17 he was
coaching a Pop Warner team in San Jose. He did it because it was
fun.
</P>
<P>
   Now Toledo is on the stout side of 50, warden of a rambunctious
UCLA football program, dealing with an increasingly complex college
sports world. And insisting the job remains fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always fun,'' he says over a lunch-time pasta. ``I still
have a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   To which one wants to reply: When, sir, did you realize you're a
masochist? Who but a glutton for punishment would consider this a
good time?
</P>
<P>
   Consider what passed for Toledo's summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   It's July and his only headache concerns the planning of his
daughter Alissa's wedding. Then the phone rings at his big new
house on a golf course in Westlake Village. UCLA athletic director
Peter Dalis is calling to say, ``We have this problem...''
</P>
<P>
   So begin weeks of embarrassment and disappointment _ Toledo's
words _ over the revelation that nine UCLA players used
handicapped-parking placards illegally.
</P>
<P>
   The infractions lead to suspensions. So that, as the Bruins
prepare to begin practice this week, Toledo faces opening games
against Boise State Sept. 4 and high-ranked Ohio State Sept. 11
without all three starting linebackers and the team's only two
veteran offensive linemen _ and faces the near-certainty that the
glories of 20 consecutive victories and two Pacific-10
championships in the past two seasons will not be relived anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   To the parking mess, add the shock over
quarterback-of-the-future J.P. Losman's abrupt departure after 10
weeks at UCLA, and Toledo says ``it's probably the worst vacation I
ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   As if the work year wasn't rough enough, the 10-0 start and
national-championship contention having exploded in a hail of Miami
and Wisconsin touchdowns, an end-of-season collapse that was
followed by an FBI points-shaving probe centering on a few Bruins'
apparent association with an undesirable with the a.k.a. Donny
Shacks.
</P>
<P>
   At least, you imagine, people are understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. Before the suspensions were announced in the parking
case, Toledo heard from people who assumed he'd make sure the
players wouldn't miss the Ohio State game. And now, he hears from
people who figure he made sure the players !ital!would!off! miss
the Ohio State game to provide an excuse for losing.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it's an insult to his integrity, precisely the kind
of cynicism Toledo claims to detest.
</P>
<P>
   He prides himself on a (relatively) clean program, and believes
the summer scandal does more damage to UCLA's image than it might
do on a campus with a lesser reputation.
</P>
<P>
   He delivers a long sheet of dos and don'ts to his players each
season, including polite suggestions about whether to avoid bar
fights (do) and whether to park in the blue spaces (don't). He
posts newspaper accounts of other universities' misdeeds on the
locker room bulletin board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to remind them that they're not typical students, they're
high-profile people, and when they do something wrong, it's going
to hit the papers,'' said Toledo, who thinks of himself as a father
with three daughters and 105 sons. ``I constantly remind them not
to do anything to embarrass themselves and the program. It used to
be you could get in a fight and nobody cared. Things have
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   A cynic suggests it's easier to win if you do bend a few rules.
Toledo won't hear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more upset at this than losing the Miami game.
Discipline and these principles mean more to me than winning a
football game,'' he insists. Besides, following the rules ``makes
for an easier atmosphere. It makes the job easier for the coach.
You don't have to go around playing cop and scolding people.''
</P>
<P>
   When Toledo was 17, coaching meant teaching. Today, with the
NCAA limits on practice time and contact with recruits, he feels
more like a corporate CEO than a mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have very little opportunity to coach the players. I coach
the (assistant) coaches,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He appears to be laughing, not complaining, when he says that.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, nobody wants to hear a man making $578,000 in the first
year of a seven-year contract complain. So Toledo talks about how
coaching is ``harder'' nowadays, but he won't admit it's not as
fun.
</P>
<P>
   He'll never convince us. But if he's lucky he'll convince
himself. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
