<HEADLINE>
SOME VICTIMS RETURN HOME AS BOY FIGHTS FOR LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Staff writer Rick Orlov contributed to this story 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The spray of bullets fired by the gunman inside
the Jewish Community Center left a 5-year-old boy fighting for his
life and wounded two other boys, a teen-age camp counselor and a
68-year-old receptionist, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Isabelle Shalometh, the center's receptionist from the North
Hills community in Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley, was the first
person to see the gunman as he walked through the lobby doors and
began firing. Yet she avoided serious injury with bullets grazing
her left arm and back, said her daughter, Lucille Shalometh Goldin.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's front and center, right there. She saw him coming at her
and he just started firing,'' said Shalometh Goldin, of Calabasas
on the western edge of the San Fernando Valley. ``She knew enough
to get down and crawl into the back office.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother was hospitalized in good condition and was released
in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Officials declined to release the names of the other victims.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-year-old boy attending the center's day camp suffered
bullet wounds in the stomach and leg that left him in critical
condition. He underwent more than six hours of surgery in a
``minute-by-minute'' battle for his life and was later listed in
fair condition, said officials at Providence Holy Cross Medical
Center in Mission Hills in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had such extensive injuries. He's been very resilient,''
said Linda Coale, a hospital spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old camp counselor suffered two bullet wounds to her
right leg and was in stable condition at Kaiser Permanente Medical
Center in Woodland Hills, said spokeswoman Lisa Kort.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-year-old boy, flown by helicopter to Children's Hospital Los
Angeles, was in fair condition after doctors removed a bullet from
his left buttock and treated his lower leg for a fracture caused
when a bullet passed through his left calf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he was very lucky,'' said Dr. Calvin Lowe, attending
physician of the hospital's emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   A second 6-year-old boy was shot in the left foot. He was
admitted to Granada Hills Community Hospital, did not require
surgery and went home at 7 p.m. with his mother, said spokeswoman
Lori Kapper.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, who declined to identify herself or her son, said he
was in ``fine condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Physicians said the victims didn't say anything about what
happened, but they did express concern for the others wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbis met with parents and relatives at each of the hospitals
to offer support in response to calls from a regional board of
rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you say? There is no reason for this to have
happened,'' said Rabbi Gilbert Kolin, head of the Los Angeles Board
of Rabbis, who met with the parents at Children's Hospital Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get some madman with a gun who shoots children, and
there's nothing you can do. It just shows this can happen
anywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The North Valley Jewish Community Center has been a popular
family gathering spot for classes, programs and other activites for
decades. Shalometh Goldin recalled spending a lot of time there
when she was growing up and said the center is always packed with
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't go to the Jewish Center and be safe, where can
you go and be safe anymore? There's nowhere,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shalometh Goldin said families were franctically trying to learn
whether family members were wounded in the shooting. She learned of
the shooting when her husband called her at work in Santa Monica.
They went to her mother's house and learned on a recorded telephone
message from the emergency room doctor that she had been shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in good spirits. My mom's a tough lady,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
