<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' HOPES GO RIGHT DOWN WITH HUNDLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley has never struck fear
into pitchers when he batted from the right side, but he was never
as bad as he's been this season.
</P>
<P>
   It's to the point where he has more than four times more
strikeouts than hits, and it's obviously taking an extreme mental
toll on him.
</P>
<P>
   After striking out from the right side in a pivotal
eighth-inning at-bat in the Dodgers' 6-4 loss to Montreal on
Tuesday night, a frustrated Hundley said he may stop hitting from
the right side before the season ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about giving it up, to tell you the truth,''
Hundley said. ``I have to talk to the coaches and (manager) Davey
(Johnson) and see what they say. (The Giants') J.T. Snow did it and
he's swinging the bat well against left-handers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley hit his 17th homer to give the Dodgers a 1-0 lead in the
second inning, and like the previous 16 he's hit, it was from the
left side.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came to a pivotal at-bat with two runners on and one
out in the eighth, Montreal manager Felipe Alou didn't fool around
with right-hander Anthony Telford. He summoned lefty Steve Kline to
turn Hundley around and make the switch-hitter bat right-handed. He
struck out on four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   He's hitting .100 from the right side, just 4 for 40 with no
extra-base hits, two RBI and 18 strikeouts. It's gotten to the
point where it's almost an automatic out when he bats righty, and
what bothers Hundley the most is he knows this.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, the ultimate workhorse, also has power to the opposite
field, and he says that's included in his contemplation. The homer
he hit off Montreal starter Mike Thurman was just inside the
left-field foul pole, like many others this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hit right-handed so you can see the ball coming into
you,'' Hundley said. ``I want the ball away, so I would still get
that facing left-handers. I know I'll at least put the ball in play
from the left side and give it a chance. I've been thinking about
it for a few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson didn't want to talk about Hundley possibly becoming
exclusively a left-handed hitter.
</P>
<P>
   But Hundley's thoughts have merit beyond just this season. Of
his 142 homers, 124 have come as a lefty. In 622 career at-bats
right-handed, he has 125 hits and is hitting .201.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley doesn't tip the average scales from the left side, but
it's not anemic. He's hitting .239 this season and is a .249 career
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when you don't work on it every day,'' Hundley
said. ``You have to work on it and stay on top of it, and I haven't
been able to do that. It's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that, particularly this season, can't be blamed fully on
Hundley. He was coming off the reconstructive right elbow surgery
and spent much of the summer re-learning throwing mechanics and
re-conditioning his body to catch.
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't doing that, he was taking swings in the cage from
the left side because that's why the Dodgers acquired him. They
wanted a left-handed power hitter, and Hundley was that. So the
Dodgers acquired Hundley and since released minor-league pitcher
Arnold Gooch for Charles Johnson and Roger Cedeno.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's hitting from the right side was neglected and it's
remained rusty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a little drop in his hands,'' Dodgers hitting coach
Rick Down said. ``There may be other things, but we're looking at
something because something isn't going right.''
</P>
<P>
   Some baseball personnel say Hundley will never be able to hit
from the right side because of holes in his swing, but there are
others who think otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious before you can control performance, you have to
be able to control yourself, emotionally and mentally,'' Down said.
``He's got to see the ball down and believe he can hit it that
way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
