<HEADLINE>
POWER OF ONE HAUNTS VALDES AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ These moments come every game. It's the at-bat in
which the outcome rides, and too many times this season Dodgers
pitcher Ismael Valdes has finished on the wrong side of the
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   For Valdes to become an ace, those are the at-bats he must win.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched magnificently for 42/3 innings Tuesday in Montreal,
but when the showdown came it was Vladimir Guerrero who hit a
three-run homer to punctuate a four-run inning in the Expos' 6-4
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very frustrating,'' Valdes said. ``Tough luck. I just don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of Guerrero's two homers turned a 3-1 Dodgers lead
into a 4-3 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see... one bad pitch,'' Valdes said. ``That's my goal,
not to make that mistake every time you go out there and pitch.
When you think of that one pitch, that's how the game goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes (8-11) has lost four straight. But a more telling sign of
one pitch, or one at-bat, doing in Valdes is that in 17 of his 25
starts the outcome has been decided by one or two runs. The Dodgers
have lost 13 of those.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Valdes) pitched a good game. Basically, he made the one
mistake,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``He walked (Michael
Barrett) in front of Guerrero, and then threw one down the middle.
(Guerrero's) the best guy in the middle of the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Manicure appointment: Dodgers right-hander Kevin Brown, who left
his Monday start with a blister on his right middle finger, visited
a local manicure establishment to have his cracked fingernail filed
and straightened out. He said he's fine and will make his Friday
start.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who is 3-0 with a 0.85 ERA in his last four starts, has
allowed 25 balls hit out of the infield in that span. Twelve were
hits and 13 were fly ball outs.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching some thoughts: If the Dodgers were in a playoff race _
or if they somehow miraculously find themselves in one later on _
Johnson said he might go with a four-man rotation, given their
problems with fifth starters this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about it,'' Johnson said. ``Brownie, Chan Ho
(Park) could probably do it. Not sure about (Ismael) Valdes, but
again, (Darren) Dreifort is the one who takes two days off before
he throws (in the pen) again. To me, the four-man rotation, I'd use
that if I'm close to winning a pennant, or at this day and time,
even a wild-card spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he may skip the fifth starter's spot when the
Dodgers have a day off to give the four starters more chances to
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably will do that,'' Johnson said. ``I'm also looking at
the big picture, and to make good decisions so it will help us down
the line, give us experience and depth.''
</P>
<P>
   This and that: Right-hander Mike Judd joined the team in
Montreal from Triple-A Albuquerque to ready for his Thursday
start.... Eric Young is still on target to join the Dodgers at
Chavez Ravine when they open a three-game series with Atlanta on
Friday. To make room on the roster for the moves, the Dodgers will
likely ship Jeff Kubenka and Matt Herges back to Albuquerque.
</P>
</TEXT>
